</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-nhl-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yzerman &QL; 
invaluable &QL; 
to Wings
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last season, the Detroit Red Wings' march to the
Stanley Cup championship had a ``win one for Stevie'' undertone.
</P>
<P>
   Center Steve Yzerman, their venerated captain, had suffered
through some down seasons in Detroit before the Red Wings turned
things around this decade. When they won the Stanley Cup for the
first time since 1955 last June, the hockey world exulted in
Yzerman's success.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Yzerman bandwagon picked up the campaign that
despite 15 strong seasons in the NHL, he had never won a major
individual award. Now, that has changed as well, as Yzerman was
voted the unanimous winner of the Conn Smythe Trophy, which goes
annually to the most valuable player to his team in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman finished with 24 points in 21 games, the leading scorer
in the playoffs. He had six goals and 18 assists and scored at
least one point in each of the four games in Detroit's sweep of the
Washington Capitals that was completed with a 4-1 victory Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until last year, I hadn't won anything in my career,'' said
Yzerman. ``This is pretty exciting to have this happen. Right now,
I'm having the greatest time I've ever had in my career. This is
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to have my name on a trophy that has some of the
greatest players in the history of hockey on it. When I came into
the league 15 years ago, I don't think anybody knew how to spell my
name or pronounce it. I'm kind of thrilled that the Yzerman name is
going to be on there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman has been the Red Wings' captain since 1985, when he was
21 years old and Detroit was a struggling team. He adapted to
numerous changes in the organization and is repeatedly cited by
teammates as the glue that holds the team together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Stevie, we wouldn't be where we are right now,'' said
defenseman Nicklas Lidstrom. ``He seems to get better every year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here four years ago, I heard rumors that there was
no leadership in the Detroit dressing room,'' said veteran
defenseman Slava Fetisov. ``In the last four years, I've never seen
a leader like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman believes that winning two straight Stanley Cup titles
and the Conn Smythe this year does not make him any greater or
lesser of a player than he was during the years when the Wings were
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it takes any special ingredient that guys who
have won have and guys that haven't won are lacking,'' said
Yzerman. ``Everybody wants to proclaim that this guy is a winner,
that he knows what it takes to win. I think you play hard and if
you're fortunate, you play on a good team that wins a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fear for all those years was never getting the experience
of knowing what it's like to be on the ice in the Stanley Cup
finals and go through the pressure of winning and the
celebration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
