<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SHUT OUT EXPOS, 2-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ It used to take Al Leiter two and a half hours just
to get to the seventh-inning stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old left-hander would throw down and in on hitters
with fastballs and sliders, which would often evolve into deep
counts and plenty of walks. Leiter averaged more than five walks
per nine innings over the first 11 seasons of his major league
career.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Mike Piazza observed after Leiter had completed an
overpowering five-hit shutout in a 2-0 victory on Tuesday night
over the Montreal Expos in an economic 2 hours 26 minutes: ``I
think he's more of a complete pitcher now. He used to live and die
on cutters and fastballs inside and forget all about the outside
corner to right-handed hitters. What he's doing now is getting more
outs on minimal pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter threw just 105 pitches on Tuesday night, with just one
walk mixed in. ``He went into the ninth inning with less than a
hundred pitches,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``You'll have
to ask him when was the last time he did that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``High school,'' answered Leiter (8-3), who won for the fifth
straight time. ``And those were only seven-inning games.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter added: ``This is the best I've ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an All-Star in my eyes,'' said Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as much as anybody in baseball, he deserves to be on
that team, along with one of his teammates,'' the pitching coach,
Bob Apodaca, said, meaning Rick Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyland, who will manage the National League All-Star team
in Denver three weeks from Tuesday, is using a statistical formula
to help determine who will be on his pitching staff. But no matter
how the numbers crunch, it would be difficult to imagine Leyland
leaving Leiter out.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Leiter, who pitched two seasons for Leyland in
Florida, was simply dominating. He struck out seven batters. Of the
five hits he allowed, four of them were singles. Leiter broke three
different Bradley Fullmer bats. No Expo advanced past second base,
and only two _ F.P. Santangelo in the fourth and Shane Andrews in
the eighth _ even made it past first.
</P>
<P>
   The shutout was Leiter's second this season, both coming in the
last 24 days, with Piazza behind the plate. He had only three
shutouts before this season.
</P>
<P>
   The complete-game performance lowered Leiter's earned run
average to 1.53, the best mark in the majors. In 13 starts, he has
allowed just 15 earned runs in 88 1/3 innings. He has walked just
30 batters, an average of 3.1 every nine innings. In seven of his
starts, Leiter has walked two batters or less.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter is now 4-0 following a loss.
</P>
<P>
   To show just how dominant Leiter has been since the Mets General
Manager Steve Phillips obtained him from Leyland's salary-slashing
Florida Marlins during the off-season, Leiter has yet to allow over
three runs in any of his starts this year.
</P>
<P>
   Five times now, Leiter has not allowed any runs at all.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case much of this season, Leiter was able to win
without much offensive support. Piazza, who was playing for the
first time since he strained his shoulder in Miami last Friday,
scored the only run Leiter would need in the top of the sixth, on a
Butch Huskey run-scoring single off Dustin Hermanson (4-6), who
lost despite surrendering just three singles in his six innings of
work.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza went 2 for 5 in his return and is now 25 for 67 (.373) as
a Met. And the catcher fired a bullet to nail Rondell White on an
attempted seventh-inning steal to end the inning with the Mets
still leading by a solitary run.
</P>
<P>
   They added one more in the top of the eighth on John Olerud's
leadoff double and a two-out Rey Ordonez run-scoring single. Two
runs is not much. But eight times this season now, it has been
plenty for Leiter, who was also helped on Tuesday night by a nice
reaching grab by Luis Lopez in left on a ball hit hard by
Santangelo to the warning track in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really has been better probably than he had been in most of
his past years,'' Valentine said of Leiter, who has incorporated a
changeup and curveball into his repertory this season. ``I remember
him as a thrower. Now, we're seeing a left-handed pitcher who has
real good stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
