A2580 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-WORLDS-HNS &LR;      06-17 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WORLDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NBA players out, 
Rudy T in Worlds
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBA players are out and Rudy Tomjanovich is in as coach for the
U.S. team that will play in the World Championship of Basketball
next month.
</P>
<P>
   The executive committee for USA Basketball, the governing arm
for international play by U.S. teams, met Tuesday and voted to
replace the collection of 12 NBA players who had been selected to
play in the World Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich, meanwhile, reaffirmed his commitment to coach the
national team, which will be made up of players from the
Continental Basketball Association and collegians. Also eligible
will be Americans who have been playing professionally overseas and
retired NBA players who do not have prior commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich will be the first NBA coach ever to lead non-NBA
players into international competition for the United States. He
was chosen by USA Basketball to coach the World Championship team
last year. But because of the NBA's labor unrest, his status as
coach had become clouded.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, however, he said there was no doubt in his mind that
he wanted to coach the U.S. team once it was decided that CBA
players would be used in the tournament July 29 through Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obviously disappointed that I won't be coaching a team
(consisting) of NBA players in the World Championships this
summer,'' he said. ``However, while the makeup of the team will
drastically change, it doesn't change my feelings one bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was selected to coach this team, I stated that I was
extremely honored to be the coach and to represent our country. And
I feel the same way now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tournament, worldwide, is the biggest thing (in
basketball). And it's an extremely big honor for me. I made a
commitment, and I feel I should stick to that commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich will commence the imposing task of fielding a
replacement team for the NBA players who were essentially booted
off the U.S. team Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA Players Association last week informed USA Basketball
that the 12 players, most of whom were chosen before the
just-completed season, would make their intentions known July 2
about participating in the World Championship. NBA owners are
planning to lock out the players and reopen
collective-bargaining-agreement negotiations July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Players originally selected to the team were: Detroit's Grant
Hill, Seattle's Vin Baker and Gary Payton, Minnesota's Kevin
Garnett and Tom Gugliotta, Milwaukee's Terrell Brandon, Charlotte's
Glen Rice, New York's Allan Houston, Atlanta's Christian Laettner,
Sacramento's Chris Webber, San Antonio's Tim Duncan and Miami's Tim
Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``USA Basketball is extremely disappointed in the position the
original 12 players have taken,'' said Warren Brown, executive
director of USA Basketball. ``On June 12, we received from the
Players Association a letter that players as a courtesy would let
us know on July 2 whether the players would participate. Not that
they would. But whether they would, which emphasized even more to
us that, knowing our commitments, we had to move ahead. That
resulted in a call of the executive committee, at which it was
voted that these players would be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts our organization in the position of being held
hostage. There's a great deal of disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Players Association was lobbying Monday
and Tuesday for USA Basketball to submit the 12 original NBA
players selected to FIBA, the world governing body for basketball.
That roster can include 24 names. But submitting all 12 NBA players
would have left only 12 other slots open. And USA Basketball was
not willing to restrict itself if NBA players proceeded with their
boycott of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday, Players Association executive director
G. William Hunter said, ``The players wanted to exhaust every
possible opportunity to participate in the World Championships, but
the decision was clearly taken out of their hands by the actions of
USA Basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Tomjanovich both said the new selection process will
include players from the CBA, colleges and any other player who is
not in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The game plan now is to get a roster of at least 24 players and
bring them to Chicago on July 8, when the U.S. team will begin
training camp. Tomjanovich, incidentally, will be given a large
role in choosing the final 12 players who make the U.S. squad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
