<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ LIKELY TO NEED SURGERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Dodgers right-hander Ramon Martinez will receive two
more opinions in the next two days, but it appears he will need
surgery to repair cartilage and rotator-cuff damage in his pitching
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez will be examined this morning by Angels orthopedist
Lewis Yocum, then fly to Birmingham, Ala., where he will be checked
by renowned shoulder specialist William Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, he has the same problem that Todd Hollandsworth
has, plus damage to the rotator cuff,'' Dodgers manager Bill
Russell said. ``A lot depends on what they see in the next couple
of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez left Sunday's start against Colorado complaining of
stiffness. Monday was the one-year anniversary of Martinez going on
the disabled list with a partial tear of the right rotator cuff
that forced him to miss two months last season.
</P>
<P>
   Head trainer Charlie Strasser said Martinez's injury did not
come on one pitch. In his three previous starts, Martinez walked 16
batters and struggled with his mechanics. The key to his 7-2 start
this season was maintaining a consistent delivery that used more of
his body and less of his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Although Martinez does have a cartilage tear on top of the
shoulder, which is similar to Hollandsworth's problem, the extent
of the injury will be checked in the next two days. Hollandsworth
underwent surgery last Thursday and will miss the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of right now, we are expecting him to make a start in seven
to nine days,'' Dodgers executive vice president Fred Claire said.
</P>
<P>
   Replacement for Martinez: For now, left-hander Dennis Reyes will
take Martinez's spot in the rotation. He will make Saturday's start
in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes has had two disappointing outings recently in relief.
Against Seattle, 10 days ago, Reyes retired the side in order after
taking over for Dave Mlicki, then walked the bases loaded the next
inning. In his previous appearance, Reyes retired the first eight
Cincinnati Reds, then allowed five consecutive hits in the 12th to
lose 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   Randy who? The Dodgers will continue to evaluate their starting
pitching, but Claire said he does not expect the Mariners' Randy
Johnson to be available.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and Seattle spoke for five days about Johnson
earlier in the month but could not reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Mariners have been very clear that Randy Johnson
will not be traded,'' Claire said. ``I haven't talked to them and I
don't think I will. But I always listen to anyone that calls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
