<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2582 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-astroslede-HNS &LR;      06-17 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-astros </SLUG>
 lede-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Schourek walks his way to peril
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Before Tuesday's game, Mark McGwire spent a considerable amount of
time trying to convince anyone who would listen that the St. Louis
Cardinals are more than a one-man team.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates spent the next few hours proving the point.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' much-anticipated batting-practice session began
at about 5:40 p.m. and lasted into the night as they pounded the
Astros 9-4 before a crowd of 34,822 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The fans came to see McGwire and home runs. They saw both, just
not in the same combination. McGwire walked twice, grounded into a
double play, flied out to right field and struck out. Although he
went hitless in the game, he was a big hit at the box office,
helping the Astros draw their largest weekday crowd since opening
day.
</P>
<P>
   The National League's second-most prolific home-run team belted
three against the Astros as part of a 12-hit assault that included
seven extra-base hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy on a baseball team can't dominate like in other
sports,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``We didn't see
McGwire do his thing tonight, but we sure saw it from a lot of
their other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Schourek caught the brunt of the Cardinals' fury, allowing
six runs on five hits and a career-high seven walks in just three
innings. Schourek had allowed two runs, six hits and four walks in
his previous 14 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first couple of pitches, I knew I wasn't going to be
on top of my game,'' Schourek said. ``I thought I could at least
keep us in the game, but I couldn't get ahead (in the count), and I
didn't have much confidence in my stuff. It's hard to win like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-place Astros missed an opportunity to increase their
two-game lead over the Chicago Cubs in the National League Central.
The Cardinals, who were expected to contend for the division title
but find themselves stuck in next-to-last place, moved within 8{
games of the Astros in what is a pivotal three-game series for the
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this is a big series,'' said Dave Clark, who started
in left field for the Astros. ``Any time you play a team in your
division, you don't want to let them beat you up and get new life.
We can't let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was the Astros who appeared a bit lifeless most of
Tuesday night, and probably with good reason. Their team charter
didn't arrive from Cincinnati until 2:30 a.m., and most players
didn't get to bed until at least an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't want to sound like I'm making excuses, but I
was pretty tired from a long day (Monday),'' Schourek said. ``Once
I started throwing in the bullpen (before the game), I was just
beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You usually know what you've got before you go out there, but
I didn't think much of it because I've thrown a lot of good games
after I felt miserable in the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't one of those occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals threatened to make this a laugher, scoring four
times against Schourek in the first inning. Schourek was his own
worst enemy, walking three batters in the inning. Tom Pagnozzi
drove home one of the runs with a sacrifice fly to left, and Gary
Gaetti did the rest of the damage with a three-run homer into the
left-center-field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   Gaetti led the Cardinals with three hits and three RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' hitters gave Schourek a new lease on life by tying
the game with four runs of their own in the bottom of the first.
Jeff Bagwell's two-run double was the biggest blow, while Ricky
Gutierrez and Brad Ausmus chimed in with RBI singles.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek (3-5) threw 42 of his 100 pitches in the first inning,
and Cardinals starter Juan Acevedo (2-1) delivered 31 pitches in
the opening frame.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' offense slowed to a crawl after the first, but the
Cardinals kept walking the walk. Schourek issued three more free
passes in the third, including a bases-loaded walk to Brian Hunter
that gave the Cardinals a 5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete didn't look like he was missing by too much, which
sometimes tells you a guy is trying to be too careful,'' Dierker
said. ``You have to give the Cardinals credit. He made a lot of
close pitches, and they took them. You just can't work around that
many walks.''
</P>
<P>
   After allowing a leadoff double and running the count to 2-0 on
Delino DeShields in the fourth inning, Schourek was hooked in favor
of rookie lefthander Trever Miller, who coaxed a double-play
grounder from McGwire but served up a two-run homer to Brian
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's RBI double off Miller stretched the Cardinals' lead to
8-4 in the fifth inning, and DeShields hit a solo homer in the
eighth off new Astros reliever Reggie Harris to give St. Louis its
final margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros managed just three hits and only five baserunners
after the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like another game after we came right back and tied it
at four in the first inning,'' Clark said. ``We were right back in
the game, but after that, all the air was let out of the balloon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
