<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIEVE SENDS ATHLETICS PAST RANGERS, 9-7
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Ben Grieve had a night to remember in his
first major-league game at The Ballpark in Arlington. The Rangers
hope Matt Perisho can forget his night.
</P>
<P>
   Grieve led the merciless assault on Perisho in his first start
with the Rangers, hitting two home runs as the Oakland Athletics
held on for a 9-7 victory. The Rangers have lost five of their past
six games and were knocked out of first place in the American
League West for the first time in 68 days after the Anaheim Angels
beat the Seattle Mariners, 3-2, late last night.
</P>
<P>
   Perisho moved into the rotation on the same day that Bobby Witt
was cut loose but didn't fare much better, giving up seven runs in
2 1/3 innings. He allowed five hits, three walks and hit one
batter.
</P>
<P>
   Grieve, a graduate of Martin High School, did much of the damage
with a two-run homer in the first and a two-run shot in the second,
his first multi-home run game in the major leagues. The rookie was
called up to Oakland last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any game to hit two home runs is pretty special,'' Grieve
said. ``To do it here in front of people I know is even more so. It
is pretty exciting.'' Grieve's father, Tom, was in the broadcast
booth as the Rangers' television analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates said he thought Perisho's struggles
were the result of being too excited about his promotion to the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the worse I've ever seen him, so I know he's better
than that,'' Oates said. ``I've never seen him give up six runs
total, much less one game. I don't think he gave up six runs all
spring (training). He might have been a little excited trying to
impress everybody. He was jumping a little bit and wasn't hitting
his spots. That's not his style of pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Perisho agreed, saying, ``I like to get the ball and throw it,
but I might have been throwing the ball even before I got back on
the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Perisho's spot comes up again on Sunday, but Oates wouldn't say
if he would get another start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't comment on that until I talk to (general manager) Doug
Melvin and see what his plans are,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were hoping Perisho would give a boost to a starting
rotation that had a 5.72 earned-run average coming into the game,
second-highest in the American League. Instead, he only made the
recent trend even worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very discouraged,'' Perisho said. ``I really wanted to
help these guys when they needed me. I'm very disappointed I didn't
give them a better effort. The offense scores seven runs, and I
give up seven, that's not right. If they're going to score seven, I
need to keep them under seven. That's very frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starters are 1-4 with a 9.20 ERA in their past six games
and have a 6.38 ERA in their past 51 games. Last night marked the
18th time in 69 games a Rangers starter lasted less than five
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't keep going to our bullpen in the fourth and fifth
innings or we're going to be dead by the All-Star break,'' Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, trailing 9-0, battled back with two runs in the
fourth and five in the fifth. They even had the tying run on base
in the fifth after Fernando Tatis' two-run single made it a 9-7
game. But Tom Goodwin, with runners on first and third, struck out
against reliever Buddy Groom to end the rally.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Rangers seemed to expend all their energy just
getting it that close. After Tatis singled, Groom and fellow
relievers T.J. Mathews and Bill Taylor combined to retire 13
consecutive Rangers batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just dug too deep a hole,'' Oates said. ``That seems to
have been the script a number of times. Their bullpen matched our
bullpen, but our starter didn't match their starter. We've got to
get some innings out of our starters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
