<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGHT OF HOPE WITH PERISHO PERISHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Lights. Camera. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Matt Perisho's debut in a Rangers uniform was memorable
for three things _ one of which may still be traveling.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, Perisho was fresh off the Triple-A farm. Admittedly,
he was thrust into a difficult and demanding situation. Admittedly,
I am fresh out of excuses.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, for those who were looking at Perisho as a season's hope
worth clinging to, it was a demoralizing spank in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Seven runs. Two innings. Two home runs by Oakland's Ben Grieve,
one of which might have left vapor trails as it rocketed into the
right-field second deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really trying hard to impress everybody,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates assessed. ``I thought he was jumpy a little
bit, and that's not the way he pitches. He wasn't trying to hit his
spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Perisho barely hit anything. He threw 64 pitches, and 31 of them
were balls. Those that were strikes seemed to whiz back in his
teammates' directions at an alarming speed.
</P>
<P>
   Just turned 23, Perisho faced 16 Athletics batters, and nine of
them reached base.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like batting practice. But around here lately, it's
called Rangers starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   And, egads, it has even infected the drinking water. Blessed
with a nine-run lead, Oakland's Mike Oquist couldn't last through
the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dark day all around. Bobby Witt's pitching merited
yesterday's pink slip, but somber faces in the Rangers' clubhouse
reflected the loss of Witt, the person.
</P>
<P>
   Former club general manager, now broadcaster, Tom Grieve first
saw Witt when Bobby was pitching for the U.S. Olympic team in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen his whole career _ the highs, the lows,'' Grieve
said. ``And I don't think that, with the exception maybe of Steve
Buechele and Geno Petralli, there's ever been a player that I
thought more of than Bobby Witt.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the agate transactions today will be the fact that Witt
was 7-0 at one point just 13 months ago. But Witt's signature in
recent seasons is that he logged a lot of innings. And somewhere
between last year's 7-0 and this season's dreadful 7.66 earned-run
average, Bobby Witt pitched his way out of the Rangers' future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we showed some patience, looking for changes,''
Oates said. ``But I didn't see a whole lot of changes in Bobby.''
</P>
<P>
   If Witt is wise, he will stay home in Colleyville for the rest
of this season and work up a sweat only driving to cash the
Rangers' paychecks. With rest and a vigorous off-season, he could
well be invited to somebody's spring training camp next season.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not getting anybody out now. A hasty change of scenery
might only prompt teams to write him out of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   And so, as one page turned here last night, the attention turned
to Perisho. He earned his long-awaited first start on the modest
wings of a 7-5 record and 4.00 ERA at Triple-A Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   So, what did he do there, anyway, Oates was asked?
</P>
<P>
   The manager formed a pair of imaginary quote marks with his
fingers and answered, ``Pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said, ``He got people out.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had pretty good stuff,'' Perisho said. ``I just
didn't execute.
</P>
<P>
   ``My command just wasn't there. I was so caught up in trying to
get people out, my focus was more on the big picture than one pitch
at a time. Before I knew it, I was down, 7-0.''
</P>
<P>
   With Witt erased, however, Perisho's performance was not so much
a trial as it was a job interview. There are more moves to be made,
probably beginning with the imminent call-up of another Martin High
graduate, pitcher Todd Van Poppel.
</P>
<P>
   The task is simple. The best five arms _ whether some belong to
Perisho, Van Poppel or a rumor named Pete Harnisch _ will pitch
and, somehow, try to halt the current Rangers slide.
</P>
<P>
   They have lost five of their past six in ominously lackluster
fashion. June has been an unkind 7-8.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has been spotty. The hitting has run the gamut from
sporadic to less-than-timely.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the starting pitching that has sucked the juice out of
what was once a robust and promising division lead.
</P>
<P>
   In Darren Oliver and John Burkett, Oates said he has at least
seen signs of improvement. Some of us would demand a peek at that
microscope.
</P>
<P>
   But Perisho was expected to come in, fill a starter's role and,
if nothing else, provide hope.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was another night of summer reruns.
</P>
<P>
   Lights. Camera. Yikes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0010 </DOCNO>
