<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2585 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-REDWINGS-CAPITALS     06-17 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS SWEEP UP SECOND STRAIGHT CUP 
</HEADLINE>
 WINGS-CAPITALS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They were just too much. The Detroit Red Wings were
too talented, too deep, too fast, and too experienced for the
Washington Capitals. And as a result of their 4-1 victory in Game 4
Tuesday night at the MCI Center, they are the Stanley Cup champions
for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings become the first team to repeat as champion since
the 1991 and '92 Pittsburgh Penguins. They are the first team to
earn back-to-back 4-0 sweeps in the finals since the Islanders in
1982 and '83.
</P>
<P>
   Scotty Bowman earned his eighth Cup as a coach, tying him with
the great Toe Blake of Montreal for all-time honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a real good influence on me,'' said Bowman. ``To be
thought of in the same breath is a real honor for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Wings captain Steve Yzerman was awarded the Conn Smythe
Trophy as the most valuable player in the postseason. He was a
unanimous selection.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was especially poignant in light of the presence of
defenseman Vladimir Konstantinov, who was instrumental in the
Wings' run to the Cup last year but whose career was ended when he
was seriously injured in a limousine accident a few days after the
team's victory. Yzerman and his teammates were overwhelmed at the
sight of Konstantinov being wheeled onto the ice to share in the
celebration. After carrying the Cup, Yzerman handed it to
Konstantinov, who, in a wheelchair, was able to hold it with help
from his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very emotional,'' said Yzerman. ``A year ago at this
time, we were told he and (team masseur Sergei Mnatsakonov) might
not live. A year later, for him to be on the ice with us is pretty
significant. Throughout the year, we were aware of his progress. He
was never forgotten on our team, but he was never used as a
motivational ploy. They're two really special guys for different
reasons on our team. Our team has just grown closer throughout the
last year. The only thing we really care about is winning and
playing well together.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome may have been the same as in the first three games,
but the decisive win marked the first game in this series not
decided by a goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings started Tuesday's game the same way they started
the previous three _ by taking the lead. Former Boston College
standout Doug Brown put Detroit up, 1-0, with a power-play goal at
10:30, set up brilliantly by center Sergei Fedorov. Fedorov cycled
around the right side, lulling the Capitals under his spell. Then
Brown came bolting down the left side. Fedorov dished a pass from
the right point underneath the stick of Washington center Adam
Oates to Brown in the left circle. Brown fired a shot that beat
goalie Olaf Kolzig through the pads as Wings left wing Tomas
Holmstrom used the blade of his stick to tie up Kolzig's stick.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit dominated the rest of the period. The Capitals could
barely penetrate the Red Wings' zone, and when they did, they
couldn't forecheck and could barely generate a shot, much less a
scoring chance.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, the Red Wings upped the lead to two goals
when right wing Martin Lapointe scored from long range. Center Igor
Larionov wheeled around the right circle and fed Lapointe just
inside the blue line. Lapointe blasted the puck from the middle of
the point, and it sailed past Kolzig at 2:26. It was Lapointe's
ninth goal of the playoffs, and it appeared the Red Wings were
going to romp to their second straight Cup.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Capitals rallied midway through the period, pulling
within 2-1. Detroit defenseman Jamie Macoun turned over the puck in
the Red Wings' zone, leading to a Brian Bellows goal at 7:49. Oates
assisted, giving him 100 career playoff assists, good for 13th in
NHL history. It was the only shot that beat goalie Chris Osgood,
who had 30 saves.
</P>
<P>
   That woke up the crowd, but less than four minutes later, the
Red Wings regained their two-goal lead. The Detroit power play, 0
for 12 entering Game 4, capitalized for the second time to make it
3-1. Holmstrom, behind the Washington net, dished a pass to
defenseman Larry Murphy in the right circle, and Murphy fired it
over Kolzig's glove at 11:46. Fedorov picked up his second assist.
</P>
<P>
   Brown scored his second of the game at 1:32 of the third,
boosting the lead to an insurmountable 4-1. Slava Kozlov, in the
left circle, threaded a perfect pass to Brown, who was charging the
net. Brown popped in the shot at the right post, the Red Wings'
third power-play goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of what we did,'' said Washington coach Ron Wilson.
``I'm very proud of our team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have kind of an empty feeling right now,'' said Kolzig, who
had a remarkable playoff run. ``But in a few weeks, it will pass
and we'll realize how great a season we had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2591 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-column-HNS &LR;      06-17 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-column </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   Mac attack lesser &QL; 
of Astros' worries
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
EVERYBODY came out to watch the big dog bite. Almost 20,000 people
saw fit to boo and cheer during batting practice as Mark McGwire,
America's latter-day Paul Bunyan, took his Ruthian rips for the
first time as a professional in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rat, Gary Gaetti, had a bigger night. So did several of
the other Redbirds.
</P>
<P>
   Rats.
</P>
<P>
   On both counts.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were 12 hits and 11 runs before the fourth inning
ended, McGwire's contribution to St. Louis' share of same was
mostly passive, albeit hardly negative. He scored twice on a pair
of walks _ the first had preceded Gaetti's three-run home run _
then grounded into a double play right before Brian Jordan socked a
two-run shot.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Schourek's pitch count reached triple digits without him
making it out of the fourth inning. If the Astros ultimately lose
the National League Central, it will be because of games like this
one.
</P>
<P>
   Even Delino DeShields went yard off Reggie Harris, although the
emergency Astro, Mike Hampton's roster replacement, immediately
redeemed himself _ and provided a nice story for his grandchildren
_ by whiffing McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, Gaetti, Jordan and DeShields have 22 homers.
McGwire, of course, has 31. You look at Tuesday's 9-4 final, and
you can't believe the Mack truck went 0-for-3 with only his weak
fly to right, in five plate appearances, leaving the infield in
fair territory.
</P>
<P>
   Downer early
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's inevitable landing on the disabled list had started
what figured to be a festive evening on a downhill run, and the
Astros never recovered. As badly as the Cardinals are heaving
baseballs toward home plate, the Astros found a way to do it worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if Pete was trying to be too fine or what,''
manager Larry Dierker said. ``I don't mind him being careful with
McGwire. But you've got to go after the other guys. It's hard to
pitch around that many walks.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if McGwire, ever a marked man, had been allowed to do
his usual dirty work. Schourek was so knees-knocking careful with
No. 25, whose homer count to date factors out to a season total of
73, he forgot how to throw strikes, period, issuing seven free
passes before he trudged back to the dugout, arm dragging, to more
than a smattering of unrest.
</P>
<P>
   People were miffed, I think, because if the Astros had to take
such a drubbing, they wanted it to be somewhat of McGwire's doing.
Baseball, still a damaged game, its cancer only in remission, can't
have too many heroes who are appreciably larger than life. McGwire
is such a figure, Mighty Casey-esque in both stature and
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Young or old, you hold your breath while he awaits every pitch.
Amazing things can always happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychologically,'' Dierker said, ``it's a little different
facing them because nobody has ever been as hot as McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Going back only to the start of the 1996 season, he has 141 home
runs. Despite his feats of late, though, it's a fact that St. Louis
stands a minus-13 to .500 since his celebrated arrival from Oakland
at the outset of August last season.
</P>
<P>
   The message? Herculean hitting may sell the most tickets, but
those guys on the hill always hold the key to the pearly gates of
postseason happiness.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire can belt 80 dingers between now and the end of
September, each one longer than the previous, and the Cardinals
will still be buried in the nether regions of the division
standings if their earned run average stays where it is today,
pushing 5.00.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen teams lead the league in runs scored and finish
last,'' Dierker said. ``But you will never see a team lead the
league in ERA and finish last.''
</P>
<P>
   Weakened dam
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have remained atop the standings for almost the
entire season because their arms have kept a leg up on
expectations. Unfortunately, with Hampton down for at least his
next two starts after pulling a groin muscle in Cincinnati on
Monday night, the dam is showing signs of giving way.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Ramon Garcia and maybe Chris Holt, who himself went on
the 60-day DL Tuesday. Then there's Doug Henry, who won't pitch
before the weekend because of an ouchy elbow. At the current
attrition rate, Dierker may have to activate himself.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, the Astros signed Lee Smith, who is at least as old as
dirt, didn't they?
</P>
<P>
   The skipper said he could, in a pinch, probably get a man to hit
a grounder to first base, but he doubted he could cover. Afterward,
however, Dierker didn't feel much like being funny.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Hampy's hurting, probably the result of an ill-timed,
50-minute rain delay in Cincy, he knows how tenuous the Astros'
grip on first place is. Mark McGwire is one of his lesser problems,
if not the least of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
