<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-nhl-lede-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Red Wings relive &QL; 
their sweep dream
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ After a 42-year drought for the Detroit Red Wings,
it's raining Stanley Cups on the most dominant team in the National
Hockey League during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings won their second straight championship Tuesday
night, beating Washington 4-1 and sweeping the outmanned Capitals
4-0. The sweep was the second straight for Detroit and the fourth
in a row in the finals, the first time that has happened in league
history.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, Detroit had beaten the Caps in nearly every
aspect except one _ the power play. They took care of that in the
clinching game, breaking an 0-for-12 slide with a 3-for-4
performance with the man advantage. Doug Brown scored the first and
last goal for the Red Wings, with Martin Lapointe and Larry Murphy
adding second-period goals.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Yzerman was held off the board Tuesday, but he finished
with a league-high 24 points in 22 games and was named the winner
of the Conn Smythe Trophy as the MVP of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Scotty Bowman won his eighth Stanley Cup as a coach,
tying Toe Blake for the most by a coach. Blake's final title for
Montreal came in 1968, when the Canadians beat the St. Louis Blues,
who were coached by Bowman in his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional moment on the ice after Thursday's game,
Vladimir Konstantinov, injured last year in an auto accident six
days after the Wings won the Cup, took part in the award
ceremonies. Konstantinov, a rugged defenseman who was a key member
of last year's team, suffered severe head injuries and remains
confined to a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 16th win (in the playoffs) was for No. 16 (Konstantinov's
jersey number,'' said Detroit defenseman Slava Fetisov. ``I know
he's going to be walking soon. I know that. He's a great man.''
</P>
<P>
   After Yzerman, the captain of the Wings, accepted the Cup from
NHL commissioner Gary Bettman, he skated to Konstantinov and handed
him the trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very emotional moment, since we've had him in our
thoughts all year,'' said Yzerman. ``It was the appropriate thing
to do. I mean, a year ago we were told he might not live. To be on
the ice when we won again was pretty significant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings had not won the Stanley Cup since 1955 when they
swept Philadelphia last season. This time, they waited only one
year and nine days to become the first team since Pittsburgh in
1991-92 to repeat as the NHL champion. The Red Wings have been in
the finals three of the last four years, losing in 1995 to New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we won last year, you say `If we never win again, we'll
be happy,''' said Yzerman. ``That's not true. As soon as the
playoffs came around this year, you could tell everybody wanted it
more. In that way, it was very satisfying to win it again.''
</P>
<P>
   A pattern that the Caps couldn't find a way to change doomed
them in the franchise's first-ever appearance in the finals.
Detroit dominated the first period again Tuesday, taking a 1-0 lead
on Brown's first goal at 10:30.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit outshot the Caps 14-6 to run their first-period total in
the series to a remarkable 51-21. Considering that number,
Detroit's 5-0 bulge in first-period goals could have been much
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seemed to beat us in just about every single area,'' said
Washington coach Ron Wilson. ``Not by a large margin, but in a lot
of ways. They came in and knew exactly what to do. Each game, the
first scoring chance they had went in. That just seemed to knock
the wind out of us each time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings carried the play much of the period. After an
excellent offensive shift by Kirk Maltby, Joey Kocur and Kris
Draper, a Red Wings fan seated in the upper reaches of MCI Center
shouted: ``And that's our fourth line.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was frontline player who set up the Wings' first goal.
With Detroit on the power play, Sergei Fedorov executed a spin move
in the corner and made a rink-wide pass that landed on Brown's
stick. Brown beat Washington goaltender Olaf Kolzig, and Detroit
continued its first-period blitzkrieg.
</P>
<P>
   In the four games, the Red Wings scored on their sixth, fifth,
first and fourth shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the story of the series,'' said Washington defenseman
Joe Reekie. ``They scored in the first period, and we played
catch-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second period, Kolzig, whose excellent work in goal
has been a constant throughout the playoffs, was guilty of a rare
stumble. After taking a pass from Igor Larionov, Lapointe sent a
quick but seemingly stoppable shot at Kolzig. The puck, however,
beat Kolzig on the right side along the ice to make it 2-0 at 2:26.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Brown scored a power-play goal at 1:32 of the final
period to make it 4-1, there was no doubt that the Wings would be
just as efficient as the last three Stanley Cup winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed our team had a lot of ways to win,'' said Bowman.
``We were totally focused. We had a tough season, getting over the
accident. Coming in, I wasn't sure if we could win another Cup. But
as time went on, Vladie's recovery was a big influence on our team.
We weren't going to let down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
