<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ, RED SOX SUBDUE WHITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WHITE SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The mystery of Pedro Martinez is no mystery at all.
The more pitches he throws, the better the result. It sounds
strange, but it seems to work for the gifted Red Sox righthander.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night he threw a season-high 140 pitches in just seven
innings to beat the Chicago White Sox, 6-1, at Comiskey Park. But
that's just what he needed, Martinez said _ a gut-wrenching outing
in which he could push himself to the limit without fear that one
bad pitch would send him to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he did give up a monster 418-foot home run to Frank Thomas
in the fifth inning, which cut Boston's lead to 3-1. Martinez also
walked five, which can happen when he's throwing a lively fastball
and a temperamental breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
   But how can you complain when your starter gives up only four
hits and strikes out 11? When he needed to be, Martinez was
dominating. He ended all but one of his seven innings with a
strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I needed to air it out,'' said Martinez (8-2), who had
given up four home runs in each of his last two starts and been
roughed up uncharacteristically in each of his last four. ``Let it
go and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everybody goes through a slump. I'm glad I'm back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His best inning was perhaps his last inning,'' said manager
Jimy Williams. ``He threw quite a few pitches, but maybe he needs
those pitches. I don't necessarily like to do that with pitchers.
But he's a kid who can handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro had very good command and location. The ball was coming
out of his hands very easy. It was alive. He didn't try to muscle
it. He used his arm and his legs.''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 13,483 came to Comiskey Park expecting a pitchers'
duel. Reggie Jefferson changed that forecast in a hurry. After
Jason Bere opened the game by walking Darren Lewis, Jefferson
belted his seventh home run of the year for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that would have been enough cushion for Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``My team tonight is together,'' Martinez said. ``They did well.
I did well. Hopefully, this is the turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the offensive support was excellent as the Red Sox
pounded out 12 hits. Jefferson had three, as did Nomar Garciaparra
and Lou Merloni.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's output, which boosted his average to .300,
included a seventh-inning triple that set up Boston's final run; he
scored on Troy O'Leary's two-out single. Merloni had a two-run
double in the sixth that made it 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``My team deserves the credit,'' said Martinez. ``So do my
manager and my pitching coach. I really appreciate that Joe
(Kerrigan) and Jimy trusted me that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody should thank Jefferson, too. With fellow DH Jim Leyritz
stirring up controversy about players' roles on the team, Jefferson
went out like a professional hitter and did his thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a game plan and an approach to hitting,'' said
Jefferson. ``I knew what I wanted to do out there. The thing that
helps me is a will to go out and put up numbers. I know it's tough
to do when your at-bats are limited. But I still say I've got to do
it or I won't be here. That's what motivates me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
