<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-COURTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STILL TIME TO OVERHAUL THE COURTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 17:
</P>
<P>
   New York's legislature may close down for the season this week,
and slink home after having done virtually nothing but pass
fiscally dangerous tax cuts. However, there is still time to change
things. A breakthrough plan to reorganize the state's inefficient
and complicated court system can be approved if only Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver summons the will to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing makes the virtues of the plan more obvious than Silver's
attempts to avoid responsibility for killing it. So far, his
strategy has been to tie it to a bill providing a permanent funding
source for legal services for the poor. The legal services cause is
important, but it is being used here merely as a poison pill to
make the court reorganization plan unpalatable to Senate
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The state's courts are a mess, impossibly complicated and
inefficient. The reorganization plan is the product of years of
work by Chief Judge Judith Kaye, an appointee of Mario Cuomo. Her
work has been endorsed by virtually every good-government group in
the state, as well as Gov. George Pataki. Republicans in the Senate
seem to be acting in good faith. They prepared a serious bill in
plenty of time for action, and their proposal is close to Kaye's.
Its questionable features could easily be bargained away in
negotiations with the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are afraid court reorganization will take away
patronage, such as attorney's fees for handling estates in
Surrogate Court. They also worry that reorganization might reduce
their control over judicial appointments in New York City. The
Assembly was very slow to produce a bill. The one that emerged
incorporated only part of Kaye's plan, added a big step backward on
merit selection of judges and weighed the whole package down with
the poison pill of legal services funding, which the Democrats
claimed was not negotiable.
</P>
<P>
   Because it involves amending the state's constitution, any court
reorganization bill must be approved by two separately elected
legislatures and by the voters in a statewide election. If Silver
negotiates seriously with the Senate, the plan can pass before a
new legislature is elected this fall and go into effect in January
2000.
</P>
<P>
   If Silver fails to act, or the Assembly passes a meaningless
bill that cannot get Senate approval, the reorganization will at
best be delayed until 2002, and very possibly succumb permanently
to Albany torpor. The state will lose tens of millions of dollars a
year in savings. Citizens will continue to struggle with the most
complicated court system in the nation, which features 11 separate
trial courts, including different venues for divorce and
child-custody cases.
</P>
<P>
   Too often in Albany, politicians spend more time plotting a
posture that will allow them to shift the blame than actually
trying to make progress through compromise. This week, Silver can
take a bold step toward reform, or he can fall back on the
legislature's traditional tactics of evasion. If he fails to do the
right thing, opponents of incumbent Democratic Assembly members
this fall will have a right to blame them for the lost opportunity.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
