<HEADER>
A2614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-BUNKER-NYT &LR;      06-17 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BUNKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE BUNKER IS NOT A LAUGHING MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 17:
</P>
<P>
   Given Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's talent for making enemies _ as in
hot dog vendors, jaywalkers and taxi drivers _ it is hard to resist
poking fun at his latest plan for a $15 million bunker, or ``crisis
center,'' as the mayor's supporters prefer to call it. Despite the
merriment this inspires in the city's journalists and talk-show
hosts, the mayor's proposal makes sense. Crisis experts have said
for some time that New York City desperately needs a modernized
command center to cope with sudden emergencies ranging from
blackouts to floods or riots and even biological or chemical
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's bunker idea was tucked into a back corner of his
capital-budget proposal for this year. The price tag would be $15
million. As now planned, it would occupy space on the 23d floor of
7 World Trade Center in downtown Manhattan, commanding unobstructed
views and proximity to federal agencies whose expertise is often
crucial in emergencies. City officials decided to lease the space
as the most secure and usable of more than 50 buildings surveyed in
the last year and a half. Once constructed, the command hub would
be able to withstand hurricane winds, bullets and some kinds of
bombs. It will have work space for 100 people with back-up
electricity, phone lines and elevators.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if a Hollywood-sized Armageddon hits _ the asteroid
or the tidal wave _ this center would crumble into a pile of rubble
like everything else. In the event of a nuclear attack, let's face
it, we're vapor, including the mayor and his colleagues at command
central. For other disasters, however, the city's trained emergency
managers need the best possible place to work. Some will argue
about the cost. This could be the subject of negotiations, assuming
that the mayor and City Council are still talking. Nevertheless,
New York needs a four-star command post. The mayor's crisis center
deserves to survive the jokes and the politics of City Hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
