<HEADER>
A2618 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     06-17 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE, FALL 10{ BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Bit by bit, the Dodgers season is slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   They found out in Tuesday's 10-6 loss to the San Diego Padres at
QualComm Stadium that Chan Ho Park was not ready step up and
replace injured ace Ramon Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   In any other June, they could have absorbed the pounding Park
took in front of 38,166, but this isn't just any June. The loss
dropped the Dodgers 10{ games back in the National League West,
their biggest deficit in nearly five years.
</P>
<P>
   With Martinez facing surgery on the right shoulder he injured
Sunday, the Dodgers were hoping Park (5-4) could regain the command
that made him the club's top pitcher last season.
</P>
<P>
   They even spotted him a 2-0 lead on home runs by Gary Sheffield
and Raul Mondesi on a rare night when Padres right-hander Kevin
Brown (7-3) did not have his best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Dodgers now have dropped three straight and looked
awful against a team that is threatening to run away with the
division. San Diego won for the eighth straight time and ran its
home record to 25-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who finally appeared to have passed the .500
barrier for good last Friday, are 34-35.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Dodgers held a players-only meeting with
hopes of regaining some of the fire lost in back-to-back losses to
Colorado on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   They were facing a Padres team that moved back into first by
sweeping the San Francisco Giants over the weekend. The Giants won
Tuesday, remaining 3{ back.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers rallied for three runs in the ninth inning against
right-hander Brian Boehringer. Jose Vizcaino singled home two runs
and Sheffield followed with an RBI double. But Trevor Hoffman came
on to get the final out for his 21st save in 21 opportunities, the
only closer in the major who is perfect this season.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Sheffield continued his hot hitting since joining
the club in the big May 15 trade with the Florida Marlins. His
three hits improved his batting average to .352 (35 for 96) since
joining the club.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, however, is Bobby Bonilla, who continues to
struggle since his first weekend with the club. Tuesday, Bonilla
went 0 for 4, including an inning-ending double play in the eighth
after the first two batters reached base.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, who was 2 for 20 on the homestand, has one hit in his
last 24 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Park was coming off his first victory since May 13 when he
allowed just one run in eight innings against Oakland last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But against the streaking Padres, Park had to be that good again
_ and he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   His first mistake was allowing a single to Brown with one out in
the third. Quilvio Veras followed with a base hit to left. After
Steve Finley flied to left, Tony Gwynn lined a two-out, two-run
double to right-center that tied the score 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres took a 3-2 lead in the fourth without barely taking
the bat off their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Joyner walked with one out and went to second on an
infield out. He moved to third on a passed by catcher Charles
Johnson and scored on a wild pitch by Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres took the lead for good in the sixth when Gwynn opened
with a single to left and Ken Caminiti hit a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   For Caminiti, who missed most of May with a strained left thigh,
it was the continuation of a great June.
</P>
<P>
   He has hit safely in the last seven games _ all Padres
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn returned to the Padres lineup for the first time in six
games and acted like he was never gone.
</P>
<P>
   He pinch hit Friday night and his sacrifice fly to the warning
track brought more than 60,000 fans to their feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres appeared to blow open the game in the seventh when
former Dodger Carlos Hernandez lined a three-run double into the
left field corner against Mark Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie allowed a fourth run and all of them were unearned. With
one out, Greg Vaughn grounded to short, but Eric Young did not
touch the bag as he tried to complete a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Second base umpire Jim Quick ruled the base runner, Caminiti,
was safe. When Hernandez doubled it just seemed like piling on. It
turned out to be a critical play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
