<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-REDWINGS-CAPITALS     06-17 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REDWINGS-CAPITALS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS WIN 2ND CONSECUTIVE STANLEY CUP 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs for rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First, his Detroit Red Wings teammates placed the
Stanley Cup _ 35 inches tall, 35 pounds, its base filled with 2,225
names, including his own _on his knee. Then they got behind
Vladimir Konstantinov's wheelchair and gave it a gentle push to
begin a slow parade of triumph across the ice before thousands of
cheering fans.
</P>
<P>
   Every spring, the tournament championship of the National Hockey
League is celebrated with a procession around the rink, but none
has included such poignant joy. There was a wide smile on
Konstantinov's face, a fat cigar in his hand, a team hat on his
head, a red jersey on his chest and tears in many eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Konstantinov, a star of the Red Wings' championship team last
spring, suffered severe brain damage last June, six days after
Detroit won its first cup after a 42-year drought. Also seriously
injured in that limousine accident was Sergei Manatsakanov, a team
masseur. The injuries and the recovery of the two men provided an
undercurrent of an emotional and, ultimately, successful season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, we were told these guys might not live,''
Detroit's captain, Steve Yzerman, said, referring to Konstantinov
and Manatsakanov. Giving Konstantinov the cup first, Yzerman said,
``was the appropriate thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   They won on Tuesday night by 4-1 over the Washington Capitals at
the MCI Center, sweeping the final round of the tournament in four
consecutive games. Last season, they won in four over Philadelphia.
In the last four seasons, all the cup finals have ended with
four-game sweeps. The Wings are the first team since the 1992
Pittsburgh Penguins to win two consecutive post-season
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman didn't get any goals or assists on Tuesday night. Two
goals were scored by Doug Brown, and the others were by Martin
Lapointe and Larry Murphy. Sergei Fedorov had two assists. But
Yzerman, who led the tournament with 24 points, won the Conn Smythe
trophy as most valuable player of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Also taking a bow was Scotty Bowman, the coach, who won his
eighth cup ring as a coach to go with one other earned as a
front-office executive in Pittsburgh. Bowman has tied Toe Blake,
his former mentor in Montreal, with eight championships as a coach.
At the age of 64, Bowman said he was not sure if he would return
next season to try to break the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough decision,'' Bowman said. ``I've got
to leave some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman first coached in the finals 30 years ago, with the St.
Louis Blues, losing in four consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   As most members of the team did, Bowman spoke of Konstantinov.
``Everyone knows what it was for,'' Bowman said. ``That's what we
all wanted to do. We knew he was at the game. We had a tough
season, getting over the accident. Everybody said, we're not going
to let those guys down.'' Konstantinov sat in a private box about
20 rows up from the net that the Wings shot at for the first and
third periods.
</P>
<P>
   During a timeout, early in the third period, he stood up with
help to acknowledge the cheers of the fans, many of whom chanted:
``Vlad-die! Vlad-die! Vlad-die!'' Although it was a road game for
the Wings, the building was filled with thousands of fans clad in
red-and-white clothing. The Wings are a core franchise from the
NHL's ``Old Six'' era, and many of their Michigan-bred fans have
migrated across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   When Konstantinov stood, the players on the Detroit bench took
notice and acknowledged him by tapping their sticks on the ice.
Fedorov, one of the ``Russian Five'' who led Detroit to its
championship last season, spoke of the emotion then and afterward.
``When I saw Vladdie on the ice, I couldn't believe my eyes,''
Fedorov said. ``He was a happy kid.'' Fedorov spoke of the
destruction of Konstantinov's ability to process information and
how he worried if Konstantinov would grow weary quickly. He knelt
down beside him and talked softly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Vladdie, are you a little tired?''' Fedorov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was. I said, `You sure?' He said, `No, I'm not
sure.'''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Fedorov noticed Konstantinov waving his hand,
signaling two fingers for two Stanley Cup championships. Satisfied
that his friend was in fine form, Fedorov left to join other areas
of the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very inspirational to see him in the building,''
Fedorov said. ``Our thoughts are with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman said of Konstantinov, ``He was never forgotten, but
never used as motivational ploy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This was the only game of the series that did not end in a
one-goal decision. Chris Osgood, the Detroit goalie, stopped 30 of
31 shots and said he had no hard feelings to fans or journalists
who have questioned his abilities after giving up remarkably soft
goals in each of the four rounds. ``I don't hold any grudges,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   So did the Capitals, who made their first appearance in the
finals in their 24-year history. They made the game close only
briefly, early in the second period, when Brian Bellows cut the
Detroit lead to 2-1. Ron Wilson, their coach, told why he stayed on
the bench to watch the Red Wings celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fan of hockey,'' he said. ``You want to see the Stanley
Cup up close and dream that next year it's going to be our team
holding it above our heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman spoke of how Konstantinov's Russian teammates _ Fedorov,
Slava Fetisov, Igor Larionov and Slava Kozlov _ kept track of their
comrades' progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a day that went by that they didn't phone,''
Bowman said. ``Those four in particular felt such a part of
them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the Red Wings have five players from Russia and
three from Sweden, Bowman said: ``Our Europeans have really
integrated; that's what makes a team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
