<SLUG> BC-HKN-REDWINGS-YZERMAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRANSFORMATION OF CAPTAIN YZERMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By ED WILLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During the course of the Stanley Cup finals,
Brendan Shanahan said that hockey teams _ like pets with their
owners _ begin to resemble their leader over time.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, then the strange and wonderful relationship
between Steve Yzerman and the Detroit Red Wings came full circle on
Tuesday night. The Red Wings, who were regarded as the classic
can't-win-the-big-one team through the early 1990s, won their
second consecutive Stanley Cup on Tuesday night, finishing a
four-game sweep of the Washington Capitals with a 4-1 victory. And
Yzerman, who was once regarded as the classic great player who
can't win the big one, is now viewed as the National Hockey
League's most respected leader after winning the Conn Smythe trophy
as the playoffs' most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman, who was named captain of the rebuilding Red Wings as a
21-year-old in the 1986-87 season, captured the first major trophy
of his starry 15-season NHL career when he was handed the Smythe
trophy on Tuesday night after a dominating and defining playoff
performance. Yzerman led all playoff scorers with 24 points on 6
goals and 18 assists, finished the post-season at plus 10 and
manufactured key offensive plays in each of the Red Wings' first
three victories over the Caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty exhausted,'' Yzerman said. ``I haven't had time to
sit on the couch and just watch TV for a long time. It's been a
long season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm thrilled to have my name on the trophy with so many
great players. When I came into the league, I don't think anyone
knew how to spell my name or pronounce it. I'm proud the Yzerman
name is going on the trophy. This is very gratifying.''
</P>
<P>
   And well deserved, according to Caps Coach Ron Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He scores points, he kills penalties, and he plays the power
play,'' Wilson said. ``He was their most consistent and important
player. He deserves the award.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman was at his best in Game 2 of the final when the Wings
came back from 3-1 and 4-2 third-period deficits to record a 5-4
overtime victory that changed the complexion of the series. His
two-goal performance also followed some rough treatment at the
hands of Caps center Dale Hunter in the opening game of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took quite a beating,'' said Wings Coach Scotty Bowman.
``He's always geared up, but that got him geared up to beat them
with his stick and skates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give a lot of credit to Steve Yzerman.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always this way with Yzerman, whose career in Detroit
underwent wild fluctuations before he finally settled into his
current role as the team's governing spirit.
</P>
<P>
   In six seasons from 1987 to 1993, Yzerman averaged 122 points a
season and was generally regarded as the game's third-best
offensive center behind Wayne Gretzky and Mario Lemieux. But the
Wings' success, especially in the playoffs, did not equal Yzerman's
individual success.
</P>
<P>
   When Bowman took over the team in 1993-94, the Wings were a
talented, explosive offensive team that was also too soft for the
playoff grind. Bowman eventually changed the makeup of the team,
transforming the Red Wings into a gritty squad capable of playing a
strong two-way game. And critical to that makeover was the
transformation of Yzerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do anything specific,'' Yzerman said when asked about
his leadership style. ``I don't think, `What do I do to lead this
team today?' We just kind of go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   But other members of the Wings see Yzerman's role differently.
Shanahan was asked whether the Wings' second cup and Yzerman's
performance moved the team captain into the special ring occupied
by Gretzky and Mark Messier as the game's greatest leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to compare him to anyone specifically,''
Shanahan said. ``Each player is unique. But I'll just say this.
I'll say he's now one of the great captains of all time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
