<SLUG> BC-HKN-CONN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YZERMAN NAMED PLAYOFF MVP 
</HEADLINE>
 SMYTHE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He has been on the Stanley Cup champions the past
two years, but as far as individual honors go, Red Wings captain
Steve Yzerman had won only the 1988-89 Lester Pearson Award, which
goes to the top NHL performer as selected by his fellow players.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night Yzerman added another award. The 33-year-old
center was unanimously chosen winner of the Conn Smythe Trophy as
playoff MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has had a distinguished 15-year career, Yzerman didn't
achieve a great deal of recognition until last year. Ironically,
that recognition comes as his offensive numbers are diminishing.
After being strictly an offensive gun from 1987-88 through 1992-93
_ when he had more than 100 points each season _ Yzerman has become
a strong, dependable two-way player.
</P>
<P>
   This year he had 69 points in the regular season, 24 of them
goals. In the playoffs, which concluded Tuesday when Detroit
finished its sweep of the Washington Capitals, Yzerman had 6 goals
and 24 points in 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely just as good this year,'' said Yzerman. ``We
were able to relax a little bit more and enjoy the whole ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we won last year, I think we all kind of said to
ourselves, `If we never win again, we'd just be happy.' But as soon
as the playoffs come around, you can tell every guy wanted to win
every bit as much as before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to have my name on a trophy that has some of the
greatest names in hockey. When I came into the league, I don't
think anybody really knew how to spell my name or pronounce it, so
I'm very proud of the fact that the Yzerman name is going on a
trophy that will be a part of hockey for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman, like Bruins captain Ray Bourque, would like to have a
career that spans 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last season, I thought about how much longer I wanted to
play,'' said Yzerman. ``This is my 15th season in the league and I
want to play 20. Right now I'm having the greatest time in hockey
in my life, so I can't possibly think about not playing again. I'm
glad the season is over but I look forward to coming back and
trying again next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman is exhausted after a season that seemed as if it would
never end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been difficult, with the Olympic Games in the middle of
the season,'' he said. ``It seemed like once the season started, it
never stopped. You never got a chance to catch your breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``The playoffs are incredibly draining. I'm looking forward to
taking it easy for a while. It's been a draining year, but
obviously, it's been an enjoyable year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 0216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
