<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2643 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LAD     06-17 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TOOK STEP BACKWARD AGAINST GERMANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Tab Ramos was just one of 22 clueless Americans eight
years ago on an adventure they had no hope to comprehend. Thrown
into the World Cup the United States' first since 1950 the Yanks
arrived in Italy as tourists, as rank amateurs taking on seasoned
pros. They found themselves headed home, humiliated, just two weeks
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just walked on the field with our cameras, really,'' Ramos
remembers. ``Let's be honest, we had a team that didn't belong in
the World Cup. We never thought we'd go to the World Cup. The
United States hadn't been to the World Cup in 40 years, and here
for some reason we qualified, and we were like, `How did we do
this?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's a memory that popped into his head Monday night as he
looked on in disgust as the Americans, now professionals with World
Cup aspirations, were overpowered by Germany in their World Cup
opener. He couldn't abide the hesitation in the United States'
play, the manner with which they backed down to the Germans in the
first 45 minutes of the clash at Parc des Princes.
</P>
<P>
   And it reminded him of the dark ages just eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alexi (Lalas), Marcelo (Balboa) and myself were on the bench
watching the first half,'' he said when it was over. ``It looked
like we'd gone backward, and we looked more our '90 team than our
'94 team, and that's not acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Balboa, too, was part of that team; Lalas was in the stands, his
face painted red, white and blue, his dreams of Cup glory still
four years off. They didn't enjoy what they saw Monday night,
either, but it was Ramos who felt he must speak out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can lose to Germany, 2-0, 10 years from now,'' he said,
``but what's disappointing is that the impression we left is that
we were a team hoping not to have a lot of goals scored against us.
That's not what we came here for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here to win the World Cup, because we know that's
not going to happen. But we want to show we've improved, and we
didn't do a very good job of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons behind that are arguable. Some, Reyna included,
believe Coach Steve Sampson left too many experienced players
Ramos, Balboa and Lalas included on the bench. Others, among them
Sampson, think the Yanks reacted poorly after surrendering an early
goal and couldn't bounce back. Whatever the reason, it wasn't a
pretty sight; aside from the first 15 minutes or so of the second
half, the United States had no business being on the field with
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that it was necessarily the lack of World Cup
experience or taking of an early goal that led us to play with
`timid' play,'' Sampson said. ``It is important against Iran (on
Sunday) that we do inject a little more offense, a little more
experience. It's important we show the physical side of our game
and impose our game on the Iranians. That's essential from the very
first second. Can't afford to make that mistake twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ramos: ``If we don't play any better against Iran, we won't
win.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be the end of the Americans' Cup. A victory over the
Iranians is essential to keeping its second-round hopes alive, and
some sort of positive result a win or a tie; we won't know which
until after Sunday also is necessary against Yugoslavia on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos hopes to make an impact against Iran. Sampson has told him
he'll start in that game, probably in place of Ernie Stewart.
Frankie Hejduk, who nearly pulled the Americans even with a fine
header in the 53rd minute, also will be in the lineup, if one hears
the messages Sampson is sending; he'll step in for Mike Burns, as
he did at halftime on Monday. The other potential change from the
first-game lineup would be Roy Wegerle in place of Eric Wynalda,
but Sampson said Tuesday he has not yet made a determination on a
starting forward.
</P>
<P>
   Might makes right
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the first minute how Germany planned to
neutralize the Americans take midfielder Claudio Reyna out of the
match and their plan worked to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Reyna, whom the Germans were familiar with from his work with
Bundesliga straggler VfL Wolfsburg, received a blow to the kidney
from Jens Jeremies just seconds into Monday's clash, and the 1860
Munich midfielder beat up on Reyna the rest of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our clear tactical intention, because we know he is
the key to their team,'' German forward Juergen Klinsmann said.
``The intention was for Jens to make life difficult for him, and we
felt that tactic worked successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Reyna said he wasn't surprised by the attention he got from
Jeremies, whom he described as ``overly aggressive'' whenever he
plays for 1860 or for the German squad.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest criticism of Reyna, widely considered the greatest
player the United States has produced, is that he doesn't like
physical play. Expect the Iranians and Yugoslavs to treat him in a
similar manner.
</P>
<P>
   Rally, er, shorts?
</P>
<P>
   Winger Frankie Hejduk, the surfer-turned-soccer star who made
the biggest impact for the Americans on Monday, took a page from
baseball superstition and twisted it in an effort to overcome the
Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Since baseball players will often turn their caps backward in an
effort to spur their team in a comeback what's known as ``rally
caps'' former UCLA star Hejduk thought it might be wise to do
something similar. When he learned he'd be coming on for the second
half, he dropped his shorts, turned them around, and made sure they
were on backward before taking the field.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why, he replied, in quintessential Frankiespeak: ``Rally
cap, bro, rally cap.''
</P>
<P>
   He says it has worked several times with the Tampa Bay Mutiny,
but its failure to inspire anything more than one superb chance on
Monday has made Hejduk swear off the ``rally shorts'' idea for the
future,
</P>
<P>
   A bad sign
</P>
<P>
   Eric Wynalda, who didn't manage even a shot in 63 minutes as the
Americans' striker, says he knew things were going wrong almost
from then start.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first couple minutes, I was listening to (German
defenders) Christian (Woerns) and Juergen (Kohler) and Olaf (Thon)
talk to each other,'' he said. ``They were very optimistic. They
were saying, `Go forward, I've got him, I'll stay with him, you
go.' I understand German, so I'm talking back to them, saying,
`Ooh, that's not a good idea, you don't want to leave me here
alone.'
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as they scored, Olaf said to Juergen, `Where are you
going? It's 1-0. You stay here with me.' Suddenly, instead of
having 11/2 guys marking me, I had four. They're not dummies. They
weren't going to take any chances. And they sure as hell weren't
going to let me have space to run. They're up 1-0 eight minutes
into a game. If anybody knows how to go into a defensive shell,
it's the Germans, the most organized team in the world. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``That early goal really put a damper on things. What we really
wanted was to frustrate the Germans into forcing the issue, which
would open things up for me and Claudio and Ernie (Stewart). When
they got ahead early, they were able to seal it up, and they just
kept squeezing it tighter and tighter and tighter as the game went
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 0217EDT &QL; 
