<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3016 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-YEAR2000-INVESTOR     06-17 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-YEAR2000-INVESTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR 2000 COMPUTER GLITCH COULD THREATEN MILLIONS OF INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM   c.1998 Hearst Newspapers   WASHINGTON _ Financial
experts warned Wednesday that the possible Year 2000 computer
glitch could threaten the safety of billions of dollars in the
stock market.
<TEXT>
<P>
   While corporations and government agencies are spending tens of
billions of dollars to solve the problem, investors still do not
know if those organizations are devoting enough time and resources
to fix the potential computer bug before Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors need to know if their stocks will have value,'' Sen.
Robert Bennett, R-Utah, said at a Senate banking subcommittee
hearing on the impact of the Year 2000 problem on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett announced at the hearing that he has introduced
legislation that would require companies to make specific
disclosures about what they have done to solve the problem and what
work they have left to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The millions of people out there putting their money into
these companies have a right to know if they're prepared or not,
and those companies have an obligation to tell them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts warn that many computers originally programmed
to recognize only the last two digits of a year will fail or
malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, when the machines will assume it is
1900.
</P>
<P>
   Under this theory, the impact of the glitch would be felt when
one computer system that thinks the year is 1900 interacts with
another computer system that thinks the year is 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The theory continues: Because computers can't think, neither
system can understand why it is 99 years ahead or behind. Unable to
sort out the problem, the two systems would either stop or give out
wrong information.
</P>
<P>
   Some computers can be reprogrammed through tedious review of
their software code, but many devices have embedded microchips that
must be physically replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, chief economist for the North American division
of the investment firm Deutsche Morgan Grenfell, said the potential
computer failures could prove devastating for many companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things stand, there's a good chance the Year 2000
problem will cause a recession about the size we saw in 1973 and
1974 when the Middle East cut off our oil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett described how the glitch could impact even a company
that had its computers fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens when a company that relies on just-in-time
delivery wakes up and discovers the trains aren't running to bring
them their supplies? Or when their supplier is shut down because of
Year 2000? Or when many of the firms that used to buy the company's
products can't anymore because their factories are shut down?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``That's not even mentioning the problems a company
could have with basic things like using a telephone or trying to
make a financial transaction or even if the water is still running,
all of which could be affected by Year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven L. Hock, president of Triaxsys Research Corp. of
Missoula, Mont., a consulting firm, said that nearly half of the
nation's 250 largest companies have disclosed no information on
their Year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   Of the companies that did provide some disclosure, most of the
information was so sketchy that it gave no clue as to where the
firms were in solving the problem, Hock said.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 10 companies gave specific details on their progress
toward fixing or replacing bad computer systems and predicted
whether they would be ready by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we just don't know which companies are at risk, and
neither do investors,'' Hock said.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that Congress require all companies to answer a
standardized set of specific questions on their plans for fixing
the Year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The questions need to be extremely detailed, so companies
don't have any room to write around the truth,'' Hock said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Stout, a professor of securities law at Georgetown
University, said companies would continue to avoid giving full
information unless they are forced to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, companies are afraid that telling the truth will
scare away investors or tip off their competition, so they don't do
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Bennett's legislation would require a
company to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tell what it is doing to fix the Year 2000 problem;
</P>
<P>
   _ Disclose a summary of all costs already incurred in solving
the potential glitch and how much more money the company expects to
spend;
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide an estimate of expected litigation costs from Year
2000 problems;
</P>
<P>
   _ Report whether the firm is insured for the problem and how
much it is costing;
</P>
<P>
   _ Disclose whether the company has contingency plans to ensure
continued operations in the event of a Year 2000 computer failure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-10-98 1723EDT &QL;
</P>
