 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 390 - JUNE 17, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. MING-NA WEN GIVES 'MULAN' A SPECIAL VOICE Ming Na-Wen made
people cry in ``The Joy Luck Club,'' made them gape in
``Streetfighter'' and made them blush in ``One Night Stand.'' Now
she's making them smile as the voice of the title character in
Disney's ``Mulan,'' which is already heralded as one of the
studio's best. Wen talks about the new film, its personal resonance
to her own life, her struggles to come to terms with her own ethnic
heritage and how her father's death during filming made ``Mulan''
even more meaningful to her. Wan appreciates the fact that
``Mulan'' is the first Disney animated feature to star a largely
Asian cast, and that its story will shatter some stereotypes. By
Jeanne Wolf. 1,400 words + photo. (Not available in England.)
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
IN MEMORIAM : PHIL HARTMAN When the comedian Phil Hartman was
murdered in his sleep by his own wife, who later took her own life
in a tragic murder/suicide on May 28, the world lost more than a
comic star. In a warm personal reminiscence, Andrew Ryan looks back
on four interviews with Hartman and recalls a comedian who was
unusually well-adjusted and at peace with himself. He was,
ironically, at a career peak when his life was tragically cut
short. From Canadian TV Guide. 1,200 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
DONNY OSMOND BOUNCES BACK Donny and Marie are back - big time. Not
only are the 1970's teen idols launching a new ``Donny and Marie
Show'' this September, but Donny Osmond has a major singing role in
Disney's much-touted new animated movie ``Mulan.'' Osmond, now 40
and the father of five sons, talks about the new movie, the
less-than-squeaky-clean reality behind the 1970's Osmond image, how
he has coped with life after teen-scream success and how national
humiliation on ``The Rosie O'Donnell Show'' led to the new talk
show. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
BETTY THOMAS : PUTTING WORDS IN ANIMALS' MOUTHS
</P>
<P>
   WITH 'DR. DOOLITTLE.' Betty Thomas charmed viewers onscreen in
``Hill Street Blues,'' then moved behind the camera with two hits
in a row, ``The Brady Bunch Movie'' and Howard Stern's ``Private
Parts.'' Now there's her most complex film to date, ``Doctor
Dolittle,'' starring Eddie Murphy. Thomas talks about the new
movie, the challenges of combining live animals, computerized
animation and a cast of improvisation-happy comics, why she chose
to remake a 1967 flop and how she coped with Murphy's traumatic
fear of animals of any kind. By Ian Spelling. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
THE X-FILES DUCHOVNY MAKES THE BIG SCREEN LEAP David Duchovny would
seem to have it all. As the paranoid FBI agent Fox Mulder, he is
the star of TV's cult favourite ``The X-Files,'' earning $100,000
an episode. He has become an international sex symbol, but as he
prepares for a major jump to big screen star with the $60 million
movie ``The X-Files,'' he has mixed feelings. ``I'm grateful for
the celebrity it has brought ... but it's taken control of my
life!'' he complains. By Ivor Davis. 1,400 words + photos. (N/A
Great Britain and Australia.)
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
HARRISON FORD LITE You can't spend every summer of your life
keeping the world safe from terrorists and murderers. So after
``Patriot Games,'' ``The Fugitive,'' ``The Devil's Own,'' and ``Air
Force One,'' Harrison Ford lightens up a bit with a mix of romantic
adventure and screwball comedy in ``Six Days, Seven Nights.'' ``I
always think it's time to do something different,'' Ford says. ``I
was tired of seeing that grim and determined look on my face.'' By
Jay Carr. BPI. 1,600 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
WITH 'GLORIA!', ESTEFAN REVISITS THE UPBEAT 70'S 'Disco' is no
longer a dirty word. In fact, disco nostalgia is a growing trend
today in films, clubs and TV ads. Latin star Gloria Estefan adds to
that momentum with a new album, 'Gloria!'. ``It's meant to be
really nostalgic for the days of disco, but with the cutting-edge
sounds of today,'' Estefan says. It's high-energy music with
Estefan playing the role of reborn adolescent. She is good at it -
and makes no apology for it. It will tickle '70s memories even as
it tugs listeners toward the millennium.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
CAROLINE LINK'S STRAIGHT TALK ``Beyond Silence'' is a film about
communication - even though two of its main characters never utter
a word. Much of this exquisite family drama concerns the fragile
line between understanding and misunderstanding, those insidious
places where communication falters and fades between parents and
children, brothers and sisters, and also, in this case, the deaf
and hearing worlds. By Renee Graham. From The Boston Globe. 1,200
words.
</P>
