<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEXTON-MAD-POETS-2TAK     06-17 1582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXTON-MAD-POETS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAD POETS SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (With sidebars Sexton-Plunkett and Sexton-Poems)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the fall of 1968, the poet Anne Sexton received an unexpected
invitation. An administrator at McLean Hospital in Belmont, Mass.
inquired if she might want to teach a weekly seminar for patients
there.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton was intrigued. She was at the height of her powers. She
had won the 1967 Pulitzer Prize for poetry, and had just been named
Phi Beta Kappa poet at Harvard. The media loved her, and hailed the
New England poetry ``renaissance'' starring Sexton, Robert Lowell,
and Sylvia Plath. A tall, striking beauty often mistaken for an
actress or a model, she would never again be confused with the
restless, intellectually curious Wellesley housewife who had
scratched out her first poems just 12 years before.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she was acutely aware of her own fragility.
Sexton, 40, had been in and out of mental hospitals for more than a
decade. In her journeys ``To Bedlam and Beyond,'' as she named her
first poetry collection, she had come to believe that madness was
the wellspring of true creativity. And McLean ``exerted an odd
fascination'' on her, according to Sexton's biographer Diane
Middlebrook, ``as the hospital of choice for Boston's occasionally
mad artists and poets.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexton accepted the invitation. The McLean seminar lasted from
the fall of 1968 until the spring of 1969. Between 15 and 25
patients attended, irregularly, depending on their mental states.
Several hundred of the poems the patients wrote for the seminar are
stored in the Anne Sexton archive at the Ransom Center for the
Humanities at the University of Texas, where Sexton's daughter and
literary executor, Linda Gray Sexton, granted me permission to read
them. And, for the first time, several patients or relatives of
deceased patients have agreed to discuss the seminar and its impact
on their lives.
</P>
<P>
   At McLean, Sexton, the glamorous, seductive, mediagenic poet,
saw visions of her past self _ the helpless, bedraggled mental
patient. As she commented to one of her students: ``I suppose I'm a
person before I'm a poet. As a person, I wanted to tell everyone,
`Look, you're where I was. Come my way, too _ out of it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The call came in September of 1968, in a note from Margaret
Ball, the patients' librarian at McLean:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``Dear Mrs. Sexton, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``During the past two months, I have been directing quite a
small group of McLean patients who write. Some are quite talented;
some of the poems, especially, are fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard you had, at one time, an interest in the writings
of psychiatric patients; the patient who told me this is a great
admirer of yours and suggested I invite you to address the group. I
would like to amplify her suggestion to include a possible series
of workshop or lecture meetings which you would lead. Your visit or
visits would be immensely valuable to motivate as well as instruct
the patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexton did have an interest in the writings of psychiatric
patients. During her first institutionalization, at Westwood Lodge
in 1956, Sexton met a talented young musician who spoke in words
and images Sexton had never encountered before. ``I was thrilled to
get into the Nut House,'' Sexton later told a friend. ``I found
this girl (very crazy of course) (like me I guess) who talked
language.'' By ``language,'' Sexton meant the bold, figurative
language of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   According to Middlebrook, Sexton created her own Genesis myth
after her first nervous breakdown, as a writer ``born again'' from
the trough of despair. There was a vanity of identification. Her
mental instability linked her to the ``mad'' poets of her own
generation, like John Berryman, Lowell, and Plath, as well as to
Baudelaire, Coleridge, and Rimbaud, the French Symbolist who
claimed inspiration from ``a lengthy, immense, and systematic
derangement of the senses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I found I belonged to the poets,'' Sexton said, and with the
encouragement of her psychiatrist, she started writing poetry. Just
as Sexton herself would offer unbounded encouragement to her
students at McLean, Dr. Martin Orne responded generously to her
first baby steps into her incipient profession. ``He said they were
wonderful,'' Sexton recalled. ``I kept writing and writing and
giving them all to him. ... I kept writing because he was
approving.'' Writes Middlebrook: ``In 1957, poetry had saved her
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that Sexton didn't have reservations about
the McLean assignment. ``Anne was quite agitated one day, and
called and said she'd been asked to do a poetry workshop at
McLean,'' says her friend Lois Ames, a poet and therapist who lives
in Sudbury. ``She saw this as an enormous responsibility. `What if
they're suicidal?' she asked. `What if I say something about a poem
that sends them over the edge?''' The pair decided that Ames, an
experienced social worker who was at the time functioning as
biographer, amanuensis, and all-purpose helpmeet for the
anxiety-prone poet, would help her teach the seminars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
McLean as mecca
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That the call came from McLean weighed heavily on Sexton's mind.
Sexton had always wanted to be a patient at McLean, but in her own
view, had never made the grade. McLean, a Harvard teaching
hospital, attracted well-to-do patients from all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   It was also expensive. Although she lived comfortably with her
husband, a textile executive, and daughters in Wellesley, Mass.,
McLean was a luxury Sexton couldn't afford. At the time of her
first breakdown, Dr. Orne had dispatched her to Westwood Lodge,
which was cheaper than McLean. When she collapsed a second time
within the year, Orne sent her to Glenside in Boston's Jamaica
Plain neighborhood, ``a grim institution for mental patients,''
according to Middlebrook. But Glenside was even less costly than
Westwood and would place less of a financial burden on the Sexton
family.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Ames remembers driving with Sexton to the Tuesday night
poetry seminars, and stopping the car on a bluff overlooking the
vast, landscaped McLean campus that looks more like a prosperous
New England boarding school than a mental institution. (Frederick
Law Olmsted, designer of Boston's Emerald Necklace and New York's
Central Park, and himself later a patient there, chose the site.)
``It would be twilight, and the lights would be coming up, and Anne
would say: `If only I could get a scholarship to McLean, I would be
well.' And I answered, `You don't want to go to McLean, they charge
an arm and a leg, and besides, they never let you out.''' At the
time, McLean generally required a three- to six-month stay, and was
charging patients $70 a day.
</P>
<P>
   But for Sexton, McLean was holy ground, the Tintern Abbey of
Boston, where many of the city's famous poets and artists had at
one time or another repaired to recharge their batteries for
renewed forays into the glamorous world of literature. ``We both
recognized that Sylvia Plath and Robert Lowell had been there, and
she wanted to be in that lineage,'' Ames recalls. ``The same way
she wanted to be buried in Mount Auburn cemetery, where her family
was buried. McLean was very much the bastion of those old WASP
families. It was the mental hospital, the place to go if you were
in trouble in those days. It was like going to Shreve, Crump &AMP;
Low.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekly seminars were held in the patients' library, inside
the new Rehabilitation Building. (The room is now a Patient
Resource Center run by the Manic Depressive and Depressive
Association.) Some of Sexton's initial trepidation about her new
charges was confirmed. From week to week, there was no way of
knowing which patients might show up for the seminar. While some
patients were allowed to meander around the hospital grounds or
even take the subway into town, others emerged from
maximum-security wards with aides, dubbed ``angels,'' holding them
gently by the wrist, indicating that their charges were on suicide
watch. Some patients' conditions varied from hour to hour, not to
mention day by day. A patient who wrote an excellent poem might
then disappear for several weeks until his or her condition
improved.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Perkins, an author and documentary filmmaker now living
in Cambridge, was a patient at McLean in 1968. He described the
seminar in his 1994 memoir, ``Talking to Angels:''
</P>
<P>
   ``She would come every two weeks to meet with a small group of
aspiring poets. It was as boring a two hours as any other, although
some of the students were entertaining. These wackos would rise to
their feet and make up their poems right there, often yelling them
out loud. A chorus of nutcakes. Occasionally, Anne Sexton would
speak, but more often she sat there with the rest of us and let
events swirl around her. If people wanted to argue about poetry or
about poems, that was fine with her. Most of us, and I was one,
could barely raise our heads, let alone write poetry or find
anything intelligent to say.''
</P>
<P>
   One former patient, who has redirected her manic energy into a
successful career in broadcasting, has a less rosy memory of the
proceedings: ``Frankly, I couldn't care less about poetry, but she
was famous and I wanted to meet someone who was that well known.''
This woman called the elegant Sexton ``Sexy Annie,'' and even
questioned her motives for teaching the ``loonies:''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
