<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RUSSIA-BOS &LR;      06-17 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S ART AND ARCHITECTURE: A THOUSAND YEARS IN 3 HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Onion domes. Icons. Gogol. Moussorgsky. Saints who have been
mummified, for public veneration. Stalin mummified, for the same
reason. ``The Face of Russia,'' a three-part TV series that airs on
PBS three successive Wednesdays at 10, presents a grand collage of
images and sounds, a millennium's worth. It's all laid out for you
by James H. Billington, the Librarian of Congress and a noted
historian who has been visiting Russia for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Billington fairly drowns in all the material he's given himself
to cover. A thousand years of Russian art, music, literature, film,
drama, poetry, religion, and politics is simply too much to tackle
in three hours, and as a result the shows seem scattered, and
Billington's choices sometimes arbitrary. In 1994, producer Daniel
Wilson and writer-narrator Rod MacLeish devoted the same amount of
time to a three-part television series just on the Hermitage, St.
Petersburg's 1,000 room palace-museum. Time magazine art critic
Robert Hughes had eight hours on TV to give his occasionally
outrageous opinions on 350 years of American art in his ``American
Visions'' series last year _ and Hughes kept his discussion to
visual arts. Billington could have used at least eight hours to
unravel a millennium's worth of Russian culture. As it is, his
series comes off as the couch potato equivalent of the tourist who
breezes through all of Russia in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Billington sometimes manages to go beyond the obligatory
_ the Hermitage, the Kremlin, the larger-than-life rulers from
Catherine the Great to Lenin. He takes us to a tiny, pristine
country church, and to the grandiose Church of the Transfiguration,
with its bouquet of 22 onion domes and its 30,000 hand-hewn wooden
shingles. The Church of the Transfiguration is on a remote island
where it couldn't have been seen by many: It was built for God, not
man.
</P>
<P>
   Enormity and excess are among the themes Billington treats in
this televised tapestry. Take bells. In Christianized Russia, they
conveyed the Lord's message, and because their power only extended
as far as their sound, they got bigger and bigger until Russia had
the biggest bell in the world, which is still ensconced in Moscow's
Kremlin. It has never been rung, because it is too heavy to get off
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Icons were the first art that Russia made her own, and it's with
icons that Billington begins, showing us mournful images of a grave
and tender mother of God cheek-to-cheek with a Christ who is a
miniature adult rather than a child. One of the show's strengths is
the chance it gives us to see icons not as we would in a museum _
static, hung against a white wall, behind glass _ but in use, being
paraded in streets, being prayed to.
</P>
<P>
   The icons that survived Stalin are often in sad shape, covered
in soot from worshippers' candles. While the fall of Communism
meant that icons could be freely exhibited once again, there is
little money to restore them. Skipping through the centuries,
Billington notes how important ancient icons were to such early
20th century giants of Russian art as Kandinsky and Tatlin. And he
shows contemporary icon painters at work, grinding precious lapis
and malachite into rich pigments bound with the yolks of eggs. The
desire of these artists whose lives have seen so much upheaval to
make art that will last a thousand years is a touching contrast
with their peers in the West, many of whom don't mind making art
that is short-lived either by intent or sloppy construction.
</P>
<P>
   Billington begins the second installment of ``The Face of
Russia'' with a classic contrast. In tones fit for a Halloween
creep-out, he describes a terrified visitor approaching the Czar's
inner sanctum, at the end of a maze of dark, cramped chambers in
Moscow's Kremlin. Then he moves to the ``window on the West,'' St.
Petersburg, ``a city designed not so much for people as for
parades,'' he calls it. Just as an icon was part of an icon screen,
so a St. Petersburg palace, however many acres it covered, was
merely part of an even grander design.
</P>
<P>
   The two great women empresses who ruled Russia in the 18th
century, Elizabeth and Catherine the Great, turned the capital into
a glittering stage set. There was misery backstage, though _ all
those millions of people living in poverty and ignorance. The
nightmare of their hopelessness found expression in the writing of
Gogol.
</P>
<P>
   You have to be really crazy about Gogol to forgive Billington's
concentration on this one author at the expense of a parade of
writers including Pushkin, Dostoevsky, Tolstoy, Chekhov, and
Turgenev. Gogol translated into English and then onto TV doesn't
have the force of the footage of Russian icons, architecture, or
opera. This weakest part of the series ends on a promising note,
though, ironically with Gogol's own words: ``Only in music does man
have freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Music and film are Billington's focus for the third and final
episode, Moussorgsky and Eisenstein his stars. While Tchaikovksy
and other composers were looking toward the West, Moussorgsky was
peering deep into the Russian soul. It's perhaps this search for
the most Russian examples of Russian art, especially art linked to
Russian history, that leads Billington to devote precious time to
realist artists like Ilya Repin, painter of impoverished peasants,
and to all but ignore great movements like Constructivism.
</P>
<P>
   In Eisenstein's epic ``October,'' Bolshevik soldiers storm
Rastrelli's great staircase in the Winter Palace to take over the
government. The real takeover, Billington points out, was utterly
lacking in such drama. ``More were injured in filming the
fiction,'' he notes, ``than in the real event.'' Russian film, he
says, is an example of a recurring three-step phenomenon in that
country: the wholesale takeover of an art form from another nation;
its transformation into something wildly inventive and uniquely
Russian; and its breakdown and dissipation. The same thing happened
with classical ballet, an art first borrowed from France, then
brought to its late 19th century zenith in Russia, where it is now
in disarray. In the public mind, ballet is indelibly associated
with Russia. Curiously, it's an art Billington barely mentions.
</P>
<P>
   While he doesn't come out and say that the Russia of today is a
mess, neither does Billington try to construct a happy ending for
his series. Near the end is a particularly dismal image. In front
of the palaces of the Hermitage, one of the world's most glorious
architectural ensembles, is a giant inflatable plastic toy palace,
for people to bounce on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
