<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXTON-POEMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POEMS BY THE `MAD POETS SOCIETY' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Sidebar with Poetry-Sexton)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
(poetry style) 
 
 ``They've got the lights up already''
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Absurd little dots of blatant color
</P>
<P>
   throng the bushes
</P>
<P>
   in front of each stalwart building
</P>
<P>
   on the confounded acres of my home
</P>
<P>
   I'll assume it's winter.
</P>
<P>
   I might even admit it's close to Christmas, but
</P>
<P>
   those reds, greens, blues and yellows
</P>
<P>
   seem so embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to unscrew all those silly
</P>
<P>
   blushing bulbs;
</P>
<P>
   I think I could do without the flourish...
</P>
<P>
   the winking proclamations:
</P>
<P>
   It's holiday time
</P>
<P>
   in the mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   M.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Cats (excerpt)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ... There is no bargaining
</P>
<P>
   with a cat. No deals.
</P>
<P>
   He is as sure as a
</P>
<P>
   Republican. he knows what he wants
</P>
<P>
   and demands it like a car
</P>
<P>
   out of gas. ...
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking like a race
</P>
<P>
   car with radar ears,
</P>
<P>
   cats can kill.
</P>
<P>
   In silence, they creep
</P>
<P>
   like fog. Then wait, patient as death.
</P>
<P>
   They wait for god, and
</P>
<P>
   as quick as thought,
</P>
<P>
   they kill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
S.W.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (Untitled) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I am left alone now,
</P>
<P>
   to face flowers and fiends
</P>
<P>
   whichever come.
</P>
<P>
   Dear God, let the devils be friendly.
</P>
<P>
   What a prayer to pray.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ELEANOR MORRIS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Encounter, Psychiatric Institute
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That awful
</P>
<P>
   Anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   She smiled at me
</P>
<P>
   From her pinned-down, stretch-out position flat
</P>
<P>
   On the tilted stretcher two big men
</P>
<P>
   Were hustling down the stairs. ``And whom have I
</P>
<P>
   To thank for care of me?'' she seemed to say.
</P>
<P>
   She smiled at me. Dark red and bright red were
</P>
<P>
   The colors of her arm. Suddenly I knew she'd done that
</P>
<P>
   shredding.
</P>
<P>
   Dire, innocuous smile!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That anonymity? All people, strange
</P>
<P>
   (Sudden, yet by an awful, slow degree
</P>
<P>
   I knew), could never get a small word in
</P>
<P>
   On her dark room, her razor, finger, arm,
</P>
<P>
   Or her blind soul presiding. ``Hear ye!'' she
</P>
<P>
   Said to the dark room of the world, alone.
</P>
<P>
   And later even, outside, like galaxies
</P>
<P>
   Of rocks _ the stars _ or animals _ the dogs _
</P>
<P>
   All we could ever do was stand and stare.
</P>
<P>
   And there, the arm, bare. Like her own soul, bare
</P>
<P>
   She smiles at me across the ribbons _ flesh _
</P>
<P>
   That say, ``I am alone _ without a sound
</P>
<P>
   You talk, without a recognition see
</P>
<P>
   The star, the animal, the blood of me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EUGENIA PLUNKETT
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A Visit to McLeans
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A sleazy kind of sun sinks slowly to the East.
</P>
<P>
   In Bedlam quiet souls are trooping to the feast
</P>
<P>
   Of burnished meat. After the black mass, the maidens
</P>
<P>
   Sit, combing the sticks out of their jagged hair
</P>
<P>
   My child sits to eat her three year cake ...
</P>
<P>
   Next to us is Hitler's son. You doubt it? Over there
</P>
<P>
   Squirms that famous poet whose course I meant to take.
</P>
<P>
   But he left again. The old man with a rake,
</P>
<P>
   Pushing down the dirty fairway, he's a former head
</P>
<P>
   Of American Psychology. ...
</P>
<P>
   Mother wants to play tennis;
</P>
<P>
   She is crazy, and she pays, so they will let her.
</P>
<P>
   Here comes a friend who tapes his clothes
</P>
<P>
   Tight to the wrist. He left school before Harvard,
</P>
<P>
   Saving his parents the expense by this long way home. ...
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ANONYMOUS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; March 25, 1969
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I will miss you, Anne Sexton
</P>
<P>
   Your keen eyes
</P>
<P>
   Staring into me
</P>
<P>
   Like blue fire,
</P>
<P>
   Daring me to live
</P>
<P>
   To let life matter
</P>
<P>
   To let something good grow
</P>
<P>
   In the fetid soil
</P>
<P>
   Of my heart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELEANOR MORRIS
</P>
