<HEADER>
A3203 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-MILITARY-WASTE-$AD     06-17 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-MILITARY-WASTE-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PUBLIC WORKS PROJECTS KEEP MILITARY SKILLS SHARP _ FOR A PRICE
 &HT;    For release Saturday, June 20.
 &HT;    Photos to illustrate this story are available from the New York
Times News Service.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a maneuver dubbed ``Operation Dino Mite,'' a
military helicopter hovered over a deep ravine, lowered a sling and
pulled up fossils of a 6-foot-tall Thescelasaurus dinosaur for
transport to Montana State University's museum.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, Oregon and towns throughout Missouri, troops have
built athletic fields for schools and communities. And in
``Operation Reefex,''(cq) they have dumped 85 old combat vehicles
and tanks off the New Jersey shore to serve as a reef.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the post-Cold War military and its ``innovative
readiness'' training program. Launched in 1992 under the leadership
of then-Senate Armed Forces Committee Chairman Sam Nunn, D-Ga., it
was born out of concern that the troops might have too much time on
their hands without a Soviet threat to confront.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the U.S. armed forces have been downsized
dramatically and stretched thin as they have been dispatched to
trouble spots around the globe. But the civil-military programs
have continued, despite questions about how carefully they have
been monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Although most projects have been short-range, low-budget items,
a major exception can be found on remote Annette Island in
southwestern Alaska. There, four branches of the armed services are
at work on a five-year project costing at least $20 million to
build 14 miles of gravel road, which the state has promised to pave
later for an estimated $15 million. The road will connect the tiny
Tsimshian Indian village of Metlakatla, population 1,600, to the
landing site for a planned ferry service that would be less than a
mile to the mainland, compared to the 15-mile trip now.
</P>
<P>
   This town on the only Indian reservation in the state had
unsuccessfully lobbied the federal and state governments for
decades to build the road, until they hooked up with the Department
of Defense. There they had a crucial ally in Sen. Ted Stevens, a
Republican who chairs the Senate Appropriations Committee and its
defense subcommittee, making him the most powerful senator when it
comes to deciding how the Pentagon will spend money. Moreover,
Stevens is famous for steering federal dollars in the direction of
his home state.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Stevens denied that the senator had proposed
``Operation Alaskan Road,'' as the project is called, but
acknowledged that his committee role put him in a position to make
sure it would be funded. ``It has been a department initiative, and
we've supported it,'' said John Raffetto, a spokesman for Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   The Alaska road project, costing more than $5 million last year,
consumed nearly one-third of the $16 million annual budget for
civil-military projects for all states. But Raffetto bristled at
the suggestion that the project was pork-barrel spending for a road
that will easily cost $22,000 per island resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you insinuating that $20 million (over five years) is too
expensive for that much training?'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the General Accounting Office, the investigating arm of
Congress, has raised questions about whether the Pentagon is
keeping tabs on its civilian projects, particularly the Alaska road
construction effort. ``The (Office of the Secretary of Defense) has
provided limited and inconsistent oversight,'' the accounting
office concluded in a report issued last March.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the ``training'' benefits were sometimes
questionable. Marines whose mission was to oversee fuel supplies
were detailed to do construction work, and combat engineers were
assigned work that bore little relation to combat-readiness,
including plumbing, masonry, and finished-work carpentry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consequently, it appeared the goal of completing the projects
took priority over the goal of providing valid valid military
training,'' said the accounting office. The study also said that
the Defense Department kept no accurate count of the number of
these projects, estimated at more than 130 nationwide last year,
and that officials had no actual cost total, since the various
services were absorbing expenses from their operations budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Alaska Road has required a major logistics effort,
including building a base camp of 37 buildings to house and feed
300 persons, including the National Guard and reservists from as
far away as Missouri and Massachusetts, who are shuttled in and out
on two-week shifts for their annual training exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Already the undertaking has brought in 850 Marines, who spent 23
days on ships sailing to and from the island from their base in San
Diego. Bringing in heavy equipment, including a rock crusher,
five-ton dump trucks and a bulldozer, required three deliveries by
the military's biggest plane, the C-5 Galaxy. The planes flew in
from a National Guard base in New York at a cost of $12,605 per
flight hour, not counting the expense for the seven-member crew.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department officials described the road construction as
an example of doing for Americans what the U.S. military often does
in foreign countries where troops are stationed. ``This is a great
project,'' said Lt. Col. Kevin Kregcarek, spokesman for the Joint
Services Pacific Command, overseer for the Alaska road work.
</P>
<P>
   As for the questions the General Accounting Office raised about
training, Kregcarek said, ``I didn't see anything off the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more generalists in the military, he added. ``You learn
to adapt and you build on that expertise and you get the job
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon public affairs department, in a faxed response to
questions about the program, said this week that the department has
tightened up procedures for the program and directed all services
to determine whether there is an ``increase in training costs'' in
civilian projects.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also defended the use of the program to deploy
military doctors and nurses to assist in low-income communities
instead of confining their work to the military. ``Training in real
world scenarios builds unit and individual morale, contributes to
recruiting and retention, and provides a 'double bang' for our
military training resource tax dollars,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
