<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnny-Light a well-seated idea
</P>
<P>
   By John Kelso
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Perhaps no one in America has sacrificed as much for
marital relations in America as Bill Bradford II, one of the
inventors of the Johnny-Light.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Bradford, a resident of Burleson near Fort Worth,
gave up a $90,000-a-year job as an electrical engineer to market
the device.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnny-Light warns women in the middle of the night if some
bonehead has left the toilet seat up.
</P>
<P>
   An eerie greenish glow lets those approaching the toilet know
that if they just sit down, they're falling in. Bradford says he
was spurred to come up with the Johnny-Light concept by ``all those
Ann Landers columns coming out about women falling in, in the
middle of the night. Now if a lady sees this soft green light, she
knows not to sit down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Johnny-Light fits between the back of the toilet seat and
the hinge. ``It makes it look like it's part of the toilet,''
Bradford said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford is on a mission. ``What I want to do is replace the tie
as the No. 1 Father's Day gift, and by the grace of God, I'm going
to do it,'' the determined Bradford said. ``But it's also a great
stocking stuffer, and it's cheaper than a marriage counselor for
adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford has a way to go before he reaches the top of the silly
gift heap. So far, it's been rough. In two years, Bradford has sold
only 7,500 Johnny-Lights .
</P>
<P>
   At $10 a pop, that's a far cry from the money he was making
before he quit his day job. To help make ends meet, he umpires Pony
League and high school baseball games. And I imagine it helps that
wife Barbara has a job as a mortgage loan officer.
</P>
<P>
   There have been marketing problems along the way. When a TV show
reported the Johnny-Light's toll-free phone number incorrectly _
it's really 1-888-566-5483, not 1-800-566-5483) _ people found
themselves calling a sex line, Bradford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It said, 'Hi there . . . Are you ready for a good time?' ''
Bradford recalled. ``Actually, it says, `Hi sexy, and thanks for
calling the Pleasure Club Hotline.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bradford remains optimistic that the Johnny-Light will
make him a healthy income one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about how many residential toilets there are in
America,'' said Bradford, who came up with the idea for the
Johnny-Light because he kept waking up Barbara in the middle of the
night by turning on the light to go to the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to do, as our packaging says _ 'Lighting the way to
family harmony.' It's real simple. That's our mission. I guess
that's my commitment statement, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford figures he must be on the right track. He points out
that ever since he and his partners patented the Johnny-Light,
imitators have come along.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we received our patents, all these other people started
coming out with other things for the toilet,'' he said. ``The Beep
Seat _ if the toilet seat's left up for any amount of time, it
starts beeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the His and Hers Light, another competitor. ``What
this is is a red light/green light motion detector that fits on the
back of the toilet lid,'' Bradford explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk up to it, when the toilet seat's down, a red
light comes on. If you walk up to it and the toilet seat's up, a
green light comes on.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds too complicated for me.
</P>
<P>
   So it's getting pretty high tech in the toilet seat warning
contraption development wars.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Bradford says, no one has come up with a
Clapper-type John device that makes the seat flap up and down when
you put your hands together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, though, I tried to visualize that in my mind,
because, believe me, that has been thought about,'' Bradford said.
``But then you're looking at the mechanical, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes a humor column on Mondays, Wednesdays and
Fridays. He can be reached at 445-3606 or at jkelsostatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
