<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTA-CATS-RULING18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commission grants cats right to remain at Bradley's house
 &HT;    By Mary Lou Pickel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Catherine Bradley, the ``cat lady'' of Palm
Beach, can feed wild cats now without pussy-footing around the law.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach County Commission on Tuesday (June 16) approved a
new rule allowing people to care for wild cat colonies as long as
they register with the Animal Care and Control Division and follow
certain requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``God in his mercy has given me my day here,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules also require owners to keep non-sterilized tabbies
indoors or face a yet-to-be-determined fine. The county would only
enforce the rules if neighbors rat out a roaming cat to animal
control officers. First-time offenders can escape the fine if they
sterilize their cat within 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners also modified the qualifications for a hobby
breeder.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, which will go into effect in about three months,
are part of an overhaul of the county's animal care and control
rules, which haven't been changed significantly in nine years.
Officials hope the new rules will cut down on pet overpopulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach to feral cats has basically been to trap them and
kill them,'' Animal Care and Control Director Dennis Moore said.
That hasn't worked well, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who founded the nonprofit Palm Beach Cat Rescue 12
years ago, feeds wild cats on the island and says the new rules are
modeled after her program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know each face of my 300 animals,'' she said. The rules
require Bradley and other caregivers to sterilize and vaccinate
cats, promote adoption of kittens, tag their ears, plant micro-chip
identifiers in their bodies, and, if necessary, euthanize sick
cats. Bradley said donations to her charity will cover the cost.
</P>
<P>
   The rules aim to reduce ``puppy mills'' by tightening the
definition of hobby breeders _ those who breed cats and dogs on a
smaller and higher-quality scale than commercial breeders.
</P>
<P>
   Some breeders, many from the Jupiter-Tequesta Dog Club, balked
at the requirement that they take back dogs that have been abused,
because that requirement might put them over the legal limit of
keeping 10 dogs on their property. They would always take back a
dog that didn't work out, they said, because they are responsible.
</P>
<P>
   County Commission Chairman Burt Aaronson didn't approve of a
``lemon law'' for dogs and voted against the entire ordinance,
which passed 4-1, with Commissioners Ken Foster and Mary McCarty
absent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
