<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Older women would grace the screen
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We live in an enlightened age, right? More women are running
companies, fighting fires, mending bones.
</P>
<P>
   So what's wrong with Hollywood? There women are given the boot
just about the time they develop the grace, wisdom and strength
that truly makes them attractive.
</P>
<P>
   As for the men, well, they're playing opposite co-stars almost
young enough to be their granddaughters, let alone their daughters:
</P>
<P>
   Warren Beatty, 61, and Halle Berry, 29. Michael Douglas, 53, and
Gwyneth Paltrow, 24. Harrison Ford, 55, and Anne Heche, 29. Robert
Redford, 60, and Kristin Scott-Thomas, 37. Jack Nicholson, 61, and
Helen Hunt, 35.
</P>
<P>
   To put all this in perspective, Halle Berry was born one year
after Beatty made Bonnie and Clyde. Hunt was born the year
Nicholson made his ninth film, The Raven. Paltrow was born the year
Douglas starred in the second season of The Streets of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   To put this in another perspective, the scandalous May-December
romance in 1967's The Graduate involved actors Dustin Hoffman, 30,
and Anne Bancroft, 36.
</P>
<P>
   Is Hollywood run by male studio executives, by any chance?
</P>
<P>
   Although we have recently been treated to a glut of movies
starring old leading men/young leading ladies, the phenomenon is
hardly new. In her 20s, Grace Kelly was wooed by everyone from Gary
Cooper to Cary Grant to Bing Crosby, all in their 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-plus years and a women's liberation movement later, the
age gap is widening instead of narrowing. Clint Eastwood, 68,
prevailed against producers who considered Meryl Streep, 48, ``too
old'' to play opposite him in The Bridges of Madison County. (No
doubt they were looking for a 25-year-old frustrated middle-aged
housewife.)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Hollywood will adopt an employment policy for actresses
the airline industry long ago abandoned for stewardesses: No one
over 35 need apply.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's abandonment of over-40 actresses may be cruel, but
it's the kind of discrimination that affects few of us in the job
market. It merely affects us in our souls.
</P>
<P>
   What does it say to us when there are so few screen images of
women over 40 in romantic roles? When we see much younger women
being romanced by men our fathers' age? When Ally McBeal,
metaphorically speaking, boots Murphy Brown and Cybill out of prime
time?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, we're old enough and smart enough not to base any portion
of our self-worth on Hollywood. But in some undeveloped corner of
our psyche, these images are still powerful. And hurtful.
</P>
<P>
   The final straw came last week, when my husband and I rented a
forgettable romantic comedy, Till There Was You. Dylan McDermott
played a scene with his aged, gray-haired mother, who looked as if
she needed a walker to get off the couch.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looks awfully familiar,'' Jim said, hitting rewind. She
was familiar. She was the beautiful Karen Allen of Animal House and
Raiders of the Lost Ark fame .
</P>
<P>
   Allen is 46, McDermott 35. Could be worse. Glenn Close, 51,
played the mother of Mel Gibson, 42 _ her Gertrude to his
Melancholy Dane _ in 1990's Hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic _ and maybe not accidental _ that women's roles in
the movies contract as our roles in the real world expand. We can
be CEOs and doctors, but we can't find the kind of strong-minded,
articulate roles Katharine Hepburn played in her '30s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   Better change my attitude, though, or I'll never make it in
Hollywood. Word has it I'm being considered for a plum role as Jack
Nicholson's maiden aunt.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
