<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently visited Coors Field in Denver and noticed a
striking similarity between it and Turner Field in Atlanta. Were
they designed by the same architect?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, but the look is indeed similar. The Kansas City
architectural firm Hellmuth, Obata and Kassabaum designed Coors
Field, which opened April 26, 1995. The firm Ellerbe Becket of
Minneapolis designed Turner Field, which opened March 29, 1997.
Many people think Turner Field resembles Orioles Park at Camden
Yards in Baltimore, also designed by Hellmuth, Obata and Kassabaum.
Camden Yards opened April 6, 1992, sparking renewed interest in
``retro'' baseball-only stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the group Zero Population Growth do?
</P>
<P>
   A: The organization's goal is obvious from its name: ``to slow
population growth and achieve a sustainable balance of people,
resources and the environment,'' as its mission statement says.
Founded in 1968, Zero Population Growth says its mission is based
on the premise that the finite resources of the world cannot
support an infinite number of people. Based in Washington, it has
more than 55,000 members and 20 chapters nationwide (none in
Georgia).
</P>
<P>
   The organization advocates a variety of measures to reduce
population pressures, including adoption of a national population
policy, access to contraceptives, reproductive choice, school-based
comprehensive sexuality education and health-care services, and
international support for voluntary family planning programs.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Zero Population Growth, 1400 16th St. N.W., Suite
320, Washington, DC 20036 (1-800-767-1956) a scanner are remote,
whether the caller is using digital or analog, said Jeff Battcher
of BellSouth Cellular. Analog is a very secure technology, he said,
but digital is even more secure.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is indeed different. The terminology, however, is
something only an engineer could love. Analog uses a continuously
variable electronic signal that varies in frequency over a radio
channel, Battcher explained. Digital transmission/switching
technologies employ a variety of discrete, distinct pulses to
represent information.
</P>
<P>
   Battcher pointed out that it's against the law _ ``an illegal
invasion of privacy'' _ for anyone to intentionally listen to
wireless telephone conversations. In addition, since 1994 it has
been illegal to sell or import scanners that will pick up wireless
telephone conversations. It also is illegal to modify scanners to
receive those conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Considering the ozone problems in the atmosphere, would it
help if people drove without using their vehicle's air conditioner?
</P>
<P>
   A: That wouldn't do a thing for the atmosphere. All you'll
accomplish is being hot. An air conditioner doesn't put a
significant drain on your vehicle's engine, so ground-level
pollution isn't noticeably increased by turning it on. The only
advantage you'd gain is a slight increase in fuel economy. Although
that means a slight reduction in air pollution, because you're
using less gas, it's not significant. Better, perhaps, to car pool,
take public transportation, ride a bike or walk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently listed Major League players who hit four home
runs in a single game. Didn't Atlanta pitcher Tony Cloninger hit
four grand slams in a game in the late '60s or early '70s?
</P>
<P>
   A: What you're recalling is a pair of grand slams Cloninger hit
July 3, 1966, in a game at San Francisco, giving him 9 RBIs.
Although he didn't hit four home runs in that game, his feat
nevertheless set a National League record for a pitcher, said
Braves publicist Glen Serra. Cloninger also had hit two home runs
in his previous game, but the bases weren't loaded then.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
