international support for voluntary family planning programs.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Zero Population Growth, 1400 16th St. N.W., Suite
320, Washington, DC 20036 (1-800-767-1956). Or on the Internet:
www.zpg.org
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that conversations from a digital phone cannot be
picked up on scanners or other phones, as they can be from regular
cellular phones? If so, what's the difference in technology?
</P>
<P>
   A: The odds of a cellular telephone conversation being picked up
by a scanner are remote, whether the caller is using digital or
analog, said Jeff Battcher of BellSouth Cellular. Analog is a very
secure technology, he said, but digital is even more secure.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is indeed different. The terminology, however, is
something only an engineer could love. Analog uses a continuously
variable electronic signal that varies in frequency over a radio
channel, Battcher explained. Digital transmission/switching
technologies employ a variety of discrete, distinct pulses to
represent information.
</P>
<P>
   Battcher pointed out that it's against the law _ ``an illegal
invasion of privacy'' _ for anyone to intentionally listen to
wireless telephone conversations. In addition, since 1994 it has
been illegal to sell or import scanners that will pick up wireless
telephone conversations. It also is illegal to modify scanners to
receive those conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Considering the ozone problems in the atmosphere, would it
help if people drove without using their vehicle's air conditioner?
</P>
<P>
   A: That wouldn't do a thing for the atmosphere. All you'll
accomplish is being hot. An air conditioner doesn't put a
significant drain on your vehicle's engine, so ground-level
pollution isn't noticeably increased by turning it on. The only
advantage you'd gain is a slight increase in fuel economy. Although
that means a slight reduction in air pollution, because you're
using less gas, it's not significant. Better, perhaps, to car pool,
take public transportation, ride a bike or walk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently listed Major League players who hit four home
runs in a single game. Didn't Atlanta pitcher Tony Cloninger hit
four grand slams in a game in the late '60s or early '70s?
</P>
<P>
   A: What you're recalling is a pair of grand slams Cloninger hit
July 3, 1966, in a game at San Francisco, giving him 9 RBIs.
Although he didn't hit four home runs in that game, his feat
nevertheless set a National League record for a pitcher, said
Braves publicist Glen Serra. Cloninger also had hit two home runs
in his previous game, but the bases weren't loaded then.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
