<HEADER>
A3223 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      06-17 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEIFFER ON CARTOONS; BABY-SITTING HUNTER; WOMAN OF STEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the veritable haberdashery of hats worn with distinction by
Jules Feiffer _ cartoonist, screenwriter, playwright, novelist _ we
can now add one more: editor.
</P>
<P>
   Feiffer presided over the publication of the just-plain-terrific
July issue of  &UR; Civilization &LR; . It's must reading for connoisseurs of
comic strips and cartoons (or ``drawings,'' as the old New Yorker
would haughtily have it), or just anyone who remembers ``the Sunday
funnies'' as a high point of childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Caniff, Walt Kelly, Roy Crane, Will Eisner, Stan Lee,
Harvey Kurtzman, Peter Arno, Winsor McCay, Bill Mauldin: The
immortals are all here, lovingly evoked in essays by a roster of
writers and cartoonists enlisted by guest editor Feiffer. There are
reproductions of such classic strips as McCay's ``Little Nemo in
Slumberland,'' a ``Laffline'' that traces 100 years of comic
milestones, and political cartoons from such contemporary masters
as Pat Oliphant.
</P>
<P>
   One can, of course, argue about the left-outs. I personally
would have loved to see full appraisals of three geniuses who get
short shrift: Garry Trudeau, Charles Schultz, and Matt Groening.
But the issue reflects Feiffer's own view of the most significant
figures in cartooning history (in which number he himself would be
counted), as well as his taste for the surreal and subversive, the
edgily political, the dark and ``underground.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he is without an appreciation for more mainstream fare.
Feiffer's own essay recalls his youth in New York, where the best
comic strips ran in the worst newspapers, fishwraps so bad his
parents wouldn't allow them in their apartment (so he stole the
super's papers). He recaptures the exhilaration he (and many other
youngsters of his and succeeding generations) felt while reading
action strips whose good guys ``broke out of the page to get at the
bad guy, punching through the framed borders of panels, leaping
across the left-hand page, across the gutter, onto the right-hand
page, just to better beat a brush-cut Nazi ...''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of bad guys:  &UR; Cartoon News &LR;  reprints a bunch of
political cartoons published after the Titanic sank in 1912.
British cartoonists tiptoed around the issue of responsbility, but
American cartoonists pulled no punches in assigning blame to the
greed and hubris of the Titanic's owners.
</P>
<P>
   But then cartoons have always been among the best mirrors of the
times. Consider this sketch in Cartoon News that tweaks Clinton
apologists: It shows a man running out of a bank with a gun and a
bag of money. ``Hey! That was Senator Truall!'' cries a man.
Replies his wife serenely: ``Well, what he does in his private life
shouldn't concern us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Della Pietra spent a few months back in 1992 as an
assistant to Hunter S. Thompson and lived to tell the tale in this
month's  &UR; P.O.V. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The godfather of gonzo journalism emerges as just the wild man
you'd expect. As described by Della Pietra, days and nights with
Hunter resembled life on the edge of a volcano; he is depicted as
an eruptive figure fueled by quantities of booze and drugs that
would kill others. ``At this point in his life, he'd probably croak
if he stopped,'' nonchalantly explains Della Pietra, who seems to
have a gonzo streak in her as well.
</P>
<P>
   Her job was to ``have Hunter's hands on the typewriter by 2
(a.m., that is),'' a task she likens to ``caging a wild animal and
slowly cornering it into submission.'' He much preferred to ``jump
in the hot tub with a whole key lime pie, a cell phone, a bottle of
Champagne and `Caligula' on in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   The extremes of Thompson's life eventually wore Della Pietra
out, so she left. But she seems to retain an affectionate regard
for ``this deranged man,'' an affection we can't quite understand
but do believe, somehow, after reading this account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Dawn Steel became pregnant in the mid-1980s, she was pushed
out of her job as president of production at Paramount. But she
fought her way back to become president of Columbia Pictures in
1987, the first woman ever to head both the production and
marketing divisions of a Hollywood movie studio.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Dawn Steel knew a thing or two about swimming with the
sharks. But how much did she know about movies? Producer David
Madden recalls the time Steel, then at Paramount, gestured toward a
pile of videotapes and told him: ``These are movies somebody told
me I should see. Do you think I should see any of these?'' In the
pile were such Cinema 101 classics as ``The Maltese Falcon'' and
``All About Eve.''
</P>
<P>
   Madden's reminiscence is part of an absorbing, shadows-and-light
portrait of Steel, who died six months ago of a brain tumor at age
51, in the current issue of  &UR; Premiere &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In recollections by friends, enemies, and colleagues, it becomes
clear that Steel could be a shark herself, with a habit of berating
producers and other underlings that earned her the sobriquet ``the
Queen of Mean.'' But she also respected those who stood up to her,
and once she'd made it up the greasy pole herself, was willing to
help other women executives looking to make it in an often-hostile
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The old Mount Everest ``because it's there'' attitude toward
grueling expeditions has always struck me as a bit harebrained. I'm
more inclined to the view expressed by a character in Anne Tyler's
``The Accidental Tourist'' to the effect that ``the passage of time
should be adventure enough for anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, I greatly enjoyed Todd Balf's acount in  &UR; Men's
Journal  &LR; of pedaling the new Great Divide Mountain Bike Route, a
2,468-mile off-road bike path. Even though he subjects himself to a
risky ordeal in remote places _ valleys, deserts, dirt roads,
tall-timber country _ Balf offers an engagingly anti-heroic,
self-deprecating take on the enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   After three days during which he does not see a single other
soul, he confesses only half-jokingly, ``I want my blankey.'' To
keep grizzly bears away, he admits, he sings ``John Jacob
Jingleheimer Schmidt'' as he bicycles up and down mountainsides.
</P>
<P>
   Charming as Balf's account is, though, I was still left
wondering: What's the point? Now, if you'll excuse me, I'm going to
make the arduous trek to the company cafeteria, fighting through
any and all obstacles, to get a piece of pie. Why? Because it's
there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
