<HEADER>
A3224 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALAMANDER-POEM18-COX     06-17 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALAMANDER-POEM18-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge sides with cleaning Barton pool
</P>
<P>
   By Laylan Copelin
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks, mixing rhyme and
reason, kept the Barton Springs Pool open by denying attempts to
stop the city from cleaning the spring-fed pool that is habitat to
an endangered salamander and a cool respite for Central Texans.
</P>
<P>
   In a 16-line poem and a 20-page opinion, the judge took literary
and legal swings at the Endangered Species Act, ruling that the
city's cleaning does not harm the 3-inch salamander, which lives
only in the local springs. Sparks denied a temporary injunction to
halt the cleanings. However, the judge also warned of the federal
law's being taken to the extreme:
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore, today, Austin's citizens get away with a rhyme.
But, the truth is, they might not be so lucky next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Kirk Watson praised the decision, saying, ``Sometimes
justice is poetic.''
</P>
<P>
   While the legal victory keeps open what the judge _ an Austin
native and a competitive swimmer in his youth _ called an Austin
shrine, city officials must still get the approval of the U.S. Fish
&AMP; Wildlife Service to resume the cleanings. Officials say the
cleanings are necessary for the pool's safe operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intent is to keep the pool open,'' said David Frederick,
the federal agency's Central Texas supervisor. ``Barton Springs is
a jewel for the city and unique in that thousands of people are
enjoying a habitat with an endangered species.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the agency is negotiating new cleaning methods with
Austin officials, and a decision could be coming within a couple of
days. Both city and federal officials expect the cleaning methods
to prompt changes to the appearance and operation of the pool. For
example, a berm or dam may be built to separate the shallow and
deep ends.
</P>
<P>
   After the judge's decision, the city officials were only
concerned about the buildup of algae in the shallow end of the
pool. It has not been cleaned since May 21, the day before the
lawsuit was filed. In the summer, it is usually cleaned weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The algae are making the shallow end slippery. By this weekend,
city officials may close that section to waders until it can be
cleared. The deep end is expected to stay open because the water
remains clear enough for lifeguards to watch swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the city's legal standing was less clear.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Hamilton and Robert Barnhart, two Central Texans whose
avocation is the study of salamanders, sued the city, claiming the
pool cleanings harmed the amphibian and the city had the wrong
permit to continue the water maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Neither returned phone calls, but their lawyer, Robert Kleeman,
said, ``We're disappointed.'' He insisted the lawsuit was about
saving the salamander and its habitat _ not harassing city
officials and advocates fighting development in the Barton Creek
watershed.
</P>
<P>
   The city had cleaned the pool for decades with methods much
harsher than it is using now, but in May 1997 the salamander was
declared an endangered species. Still, the city continued the
cleanings until January, when a salamander was found stranded after
city workers, in their usual practice, lowered the water to clean
the pool.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted the lawsuit. Under federal law, an endangered
species cannot be harassed, harmed, pursued, hunted, shot, killed,
trapped or captured. The law allows two exceptions: a permit either
for the ``incidental take'' _ or harm _ of the species as part of
the overall management of the pool or a special scientific permit.
</P>
<P>
   The city has applied for the first permit, but it cannot be
granted until this fall after a round of public hearings. In the
interim, the federal officials authorized ``experimental
cleanings'' under a scientific permit. Attorneys for Hamilton and
Barnhart argued that it was the wrong permit and served only as a
convenient stopgap.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks disagreed, saying city and federal officials learned more
about the salamander and its habitat with the carefully watched
cleanings. He agreed that salamanders are sometimes stranded on
land when the pool water is lowered for the cleanings. However,
city and federal biologists scour the exposed pool surface to
return the amphibians to deep water.
</P>
<P>
   The salamander, the judge noted, lives carefree in Barton
springs, ``with millions of dollars and thousands of people
scrambling to assist in their stress-free living and procreation.''
Meanwhile, Sparks wrote that Congress passed the Endangered Species
Act that once blocked the completion of a $100 million dam to save
the habitat of the snail darter, a 3-inch-long perch. ``Therefore,
it is not clear who has the smaller brains.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than lowering the pool water, Sparks said he found no
other parts of the city's cleaning process that affect the
salamander, and he concluded: ``There was simply no evidence
offered at the (June 3) hearing suggesting this is a case where the
'continued existence' of the salamander or the destruction of the
habitat is at issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ruling, the cleaning methods are likely to change
because of what biologists learned from the experimental cleanings.
</P>
<P>
   City and federal officials are considering building a berm or
dam to separate the shallow and deep ends. Because the shallow end
has a limestone bottom, it is not salamander habitat. By separating
the two portions of the pool, the shallow end could be cleaned more
often without dropping the water level of the rest of the pool.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities also are considering digging away more of what
is known as the Beach area. Despite the name, the area is covered
by 3 or 4 feet of water. If the pool is made deeper there,
Frederick said, swimmers would be less likely to step on the
salamanders and the amphibians would not be stranded if the water
level had to be lowered in that portion of the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Kleeman said his clients could support building the berm but not
digging out the Beach area because they consider that a developing
habitat for the salamander. He did not predict what, if anything,
his clients might do as the city continues to seek its final
federal permit to manage the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bunch, a lawyer for the Save Our Springs Alliance, praised
the effect of the judge's decision but was disappointed with his
criticism of the law protecting the species: ``We disagree that the
Act makes no sense. We agree with the judge that the real threat is
development upstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
