A3225 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEASIDE-ARCHITECHTURE     06-17 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEASIDE-ARCHITECHTURE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PICTURE-PERFECT TOWN OFFERS ARCHITECTURE TO INSPIRE AN ARTIST
 &HT;    By CHERYL BLACKERBY
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEASIDE, Fla. _ So what do people do in this Architectural
Digest-perfect town? One would think the Gulf of Mexico would be
the main attraction.
</P>
<P>
   No, indeed. Houses are what draw sightseers, many of whom are
architects and urban planners, who come here to admire and
photograph the real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the town's 300 houses, designed by cutting-edge
architects from around the country, have been featured in
Metropolitan Home and Architectural Digest numerous times, so
numerous that city fathers have stopped keeping track.
</P>
<P>
   The town's signature tin roofs and storybook turrets make a
picture-perfect skyline. Not that every house has Victorian
inspiration. One home has red columns, copies of Greek ruins in
Crete, and others have industrial and modernist influences with
corrugated metal walls.
</P>
<P>
   Colors range from watercolor pastels (near the shore) to cobalt
blue and intense purple (near the woods). Color combinations are
fit for an artist. A house might have a blue door, green shutters
and flamingo pink clapboard walls.
</P>
<P>
   While most visitors end up on the beach, most of the
picture-snapping is done in town.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are so interested in the architecture and designs that
the town's only rental agency has started a ``Seaside Sampler,''
which allows guests to stay in a variety of cottages during a week
or more.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of the ``cottages,'' some of which could house
a party of 12 or more if you included the guest houses in back, are
second homes and are rented out when owners aren't in town. Only
about 30 families live here year-round.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to tell the early houses from new ones. The
first clapboard house went up on 70 acres of wind-swept white sand
covered with palmettos and scrub pines. One by one, design-savvy
and wealthy people bought lots and hired architects, who created
houses that would conform to the town's demanding building codes.
</P>
<P>
   Seaside was the vision of Harvard-educated developer Robert
Davis, who inherited the land from his grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Alabama and didn't want a development of high-rise
condominiums like those that were springing up on other parts of
Florida's Gulf Coast. He imagined a community with ``the simple
genius of a small town.''
</P>
<P>
   He enlisted the help of Miami architects Andres Duany and
Elizabeth Plater-Zyberk. They traveled throughout the South with
cameras, sketch pads and tape measures studying what Davis calls
``Southern vernacular'' architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a coffee shop at Seaside's outdoor market, Davis
laughed at the idea of the Ivy League architects researching what
he calls cracker houses. ``We didn't study that in school.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaside's houses are the result of that research. The houses are
climate-friendly. They are built off the ground so air can
circulate underneath. They have peaked tin roofs, front porches,
side screened porches, and no grass lawns, which would require
fertilizers and pesticides. Landscaping is a jungle of native
plants.
</P>
<P>
   The houses are also people-friendly. They have tiny front yards
so that people on the front porch can chat with neighbors on the
sidewalk. Common greens and swimming pools encourage residents to
socialize. The tallest buildings are only four stories.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is a full-time resident, and his large two-story house is
often a gathering place for neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   You, too, can join the community, at least for a few days. In
Seaside, you can stay in cottages with names like Dreamsicle,
Starry Night and Sunnyside Up. It's a chance to live your fantasy
of a small town _ the one you grew up in, or the one you wish you
had grown up in.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: No one sweats here _ they glow in the perfect
surroundings of Seaside. It's perfect for the over-stressed who
want serious relaxation. There's not much to do that overtaxes _
just biking, walking and swimming in the gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants: There are plenty of cafes for lunch in the outdoor
market by the beach _ gourmet pizza, Greek specialties, hamburgers,
delis. The best restaurant for dinner (also open for lunch) is Bud
and Alley's by the beach. Fresh fish is the main attraction and
reservations are a must. Dress is casual, by way of Calvin Klein.
The elegant dining room at Josephine's French Country Inn is open
Friday and Saturday nights. Shades in the town center is a casual
restaurant that's perfect for kids.
</P>
<P>
   Organized fun: Yoga classes are held in the park; there's a big
fitness center, and several pools. Anyone for croquet? You can
borrow a mallet and try your luck on the green. Wear white.
</P>
<P>
   Cottage reservations: Call the Seaside Cottage Rental Agency,
(800) 277-8696 or www.seasidefl.com
</P>
<P>
   Rates: Get out the American Express gold card. Accommodations
vary quite a bit, but all are expensive. Dreamland Heights and 25
Central Square Penthouses, apartments built above galleries and
shops, range from $240 to $320 per night. Ruskin Place Townhomes in
the Ruskin Place Artist Colony are $425 per night.
</P>
<P>
   Seaside Honeymoon Cottages, beachfront cottages, are $360 per
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Seaside Motor Courts, a nostalgic early 19th-century-era
motel, has rooms for $145 per night.
</P>
<P>
   Seaside Classic Cottages start at $375, and See Forever, (cq) a
spectacular beach house, rents for $850 per night.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer and holidays a three-night minimum stay is
required.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
