<HEADER>
A3227 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMART-CAMPS18-COX     06-17 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMART-CAMPS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Academic camps encourage youths to pursue careers
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi and Pamela Coleman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Amanda Mendez peered into a microscope, hot on the
trail of an elusive paramecium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found some, but they kept swimming off,'' said the
15-year-old, as she adjusted a slide that held a drop of pond water
_ one of many activities at the Operation Achievement GTE Math and
Science Camp at Southwestern University.
</P>
<P>
   Mendez is one of thousands of Central Texas youth spending the
summers honing thinking skills at academic camps.
</P>
<P>
   Forget canoeing and horseback riding. These camps, ranging in
cost from free to about $300 a week, expose kids to everything from
engineering and science to poetry and architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Mendez and about 30 other 11- to-15-year-olds spent last week
boning up on their math and science skills as part of the five-day
camp that ended with a trip to NASA, the Houston space center. The
camp was sponsored by a $30,000 grant from GTE.
</P>
<P>
   One of the camp assignments: collect bacteria samples from door
knobs, drinking fountain spouts and underneath fingernails. The
results surprised some of the students, who didn't expect to find
so much fuzzy gray and white evidence of microbes living among
them. Southwestern professor Vicente Villa said he hopes the camp
inspires the kids to pursue careers in science.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole philosophy is if they can discover this world and
fall in love with it, I can tell them about courses they need to
take to prepare for a career in science,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Texas, campers learned to do everything
from playing the violin to using mechanical engineering to build
cool stuff.
</P>
<P>
   This week, about 32 soon-to-be seventh- and eighth-grade girls
are getting an introduction to mechanical engineering. The weeklong
camp, sponsored by Careers in Engineering for Women at UT, requires
them to build a ball-tossing machine with their newfound know-how.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, during what organizers refer to as ``Tool Time,''
Audrey Fuhrer, 11, leaned over an electric drill press, boring a
hole into a two-by-four _ part of what will eventually be the base
of her ball-tossing machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun, definitely fun,'' said Fuhrer, pushing up her safety
goggles and smiling.
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong camp is free, sponsored by 10 corporations,
including Advanced Micro Devices, 3M and Motorola. Every year,
students apply from schools across Texas. A panel of UT professors
and students selects the most enthusiastic students.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Turner, a teacher from Beckendorf Intermediate School near
Houston who accompanied students to the camp, said the camp
encourages girls to think about engineering for a career and keeps
young minds active.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're learning so much about teamwork and problem-solving _
it's just wonderful,'' said Turner, raising her voice over the
pounding hammers.
</P>
<P>
   In San Marcos, Southwest Texas State University professor Tom
Grimes leads seminars on creative and journal writing as part of
Project Pass, a program geared toward ninth-graders that teaches a
range of subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping that our participation will demystify college for
these kids,'' Grimes said, since the ultimate goal of the project
is that students graduate and go to college.
</P>
<P>
   At Austin Community College's Riverside campus on Grove
Boulevard, BritneyTurner, 12, bounds between buildings, discovering
how to dye T-shirts, weld key chains, make a birdhouse, change oil
and write a screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this camp because it teaches you things,'' said Turner,
who wore a helmet that shielded her eyes while welding. ``Here in
camp, I just made a key chain. It takes a lot of hard work because
you have to listen and pay attention. It's not so easy to do at
first.''
</P>
<P>
   ACC instructors teach the workshops at the Summer Youth Academy,
which is free to its 35 participants, thanks to a $10,000 grant
from AMD. This year's two-week camp ends Saturday with a fair
exhibiting the work of the campers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great opportunity for these kids,'' said Guillermo
Ramirez, an ACC student who works as a group leader for the camp.
``It's a great place for children to get that experience they don't
necessarily get at their schools. It gives them a richer life and a
richer summer experience.''
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writers Pam Coleman, Nicole Monroe and
Rebecca Rodriguez contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
