<HEADER>
A3228 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-MINISTER18-COX     06-17 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-MINISTER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On the streets, God's word is her shield
 &HT;    By Ian Trontz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH _ On a recent evening, police Officer Garry Wilson
again saw the Rev. Lessye Charlow walking with her crucifix down
West 33rd Street, and he cringed a little.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't scorn Christ or Charlow. It's the other
streetcrawlers that worry him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what drives us crazy,'' Wilson said. ``I know what
she's doing is very admirable. It's just a bad element she's
dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, after a prophetic vision, Charlow set out to
drive the drug trade from her street.
</P>
<P>
   A minister for 45 years, she knows only one way how. Several
evenings a week, she wields a second-hand crucifix and a
personalized Bible, with the Red Sea miracle flagged by a yellow
Post-It note, and marches down the middle of West 33rd, filling
dealers and admirers alike with dread.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the weapons that God gave to me,'' she said. ``This
crucifix is my police. This Bible is my police. God anointed me
into the ministry and put all these fallen black men under me and
told me I had to bring 'em up.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlow, a cherubic-looking 78, surrounds herself with redeemed
castoffs. The robe and crucifix came from thrift stores. The ferns
and crotons around her small, prim evangelist church grew from
clippings she found on Singer Island curbs.
</P>
<P>
   Her holly trees are the only ones around with Spanish moss. She
brings the moss home from Cairo, Ga., where she grew up with her
cousin, Jackie Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   She's only 5-foot-3, so the moss doesn't go too high.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, on the corner of Avenue M, the empty lot has
native weeds and forgotten trash and a scraggly pine. The tree
gives enough shade for the young men who sit beneath it on
overturned paint pails and concrete blocks, waiting for cars to
stop.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, Charlow confronted one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him how handsome he was and how he was throwing his
life away,'' she said she told the man.
</P>
<P>
   He answered by pulling a handgun from his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, that's dangerous,'' Charlow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 18 years old,'' he shot back. ``I'm old enough to have a
gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he did what most everyone else does. He walked away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared me a little,'' she admitted. She told her small
congregation about it the following Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `If she was to get shot, she'd wake up in the arms
of Jesus,'''' said Willie Williams, one of her deacons. ``I really
don't want her out there, but I can't stop her. She's going to do
what God says she has to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a mission requires a visionary, and Charlow is a literal
one. Her adolescent dreams were not of wealth, a handsome husband
or even a happy family. Instead, she said, she had bedside glimpses
of herself nailed to a cross, or floating above trees, or standing
above crowds.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to West Palm Beach as a teenage bride, following her
first husband's search for better work. She divorced him, sold
clothes on Clematis Street for a few years, then married a local
school administrator in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, western Riviera Beach had dirt roads and few homes;
urbane West Palm Beach folks called it ``the woods.'' But God had
blueprints, and Charlow said he revealed them one night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to come to Riviera and buy all the land you can
buy, because it will be a great city some day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then another husky voice boomed down on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you come with another dream!'' her husband said.
</P>
<P>
   She was ordained in 1953 and divorced again, childless, in 1954.
Her husband shuddered when she put on her robe; he couldn't accept
her as a minister, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could any of the male-run churches, so she started Faith
Holy Temple Evangelist Church on Tamarind Avenue. In 1959, she
moved the church to West 33rd Street, next door to her house, where
it stands today.
</P>
<P>
   Each Sunday, a congregation of about 20 gives enough money to
pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Charlow said she draws no salary from the church. She supports
herself by babysitting, caring for homebound seniors and cleaning
the offices of a local extermination company.
</P>
<P>
   Then she drives her white 1990 Cadillac back to West 33rd. The
car carries only two items: a golf club she uses to hit balls on a
nearby field for exercise, and a 3-foot-high octagonal sign that
reads, ``STOP The Drugs SAVE The Children.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, 6/11 as on most afternoons, she leaned the sign
against the corner pine tree. A man with a striped polo shirt, whom
she said was a drug dealer, walked away, joining a group of men and
boys across the street.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 minutes, the black-robed Charlow posed like a statue of
sanctity. She glared at the men, with Exodus under one arm and the
18-inch crucifix raised high in the other. Her Christ has a few
more scrapes than He started with. But as far as Charlow's
concerned, it works just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``God's hand is what gives me strength,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She has another guardian too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stresses me out,'' said Officer Wilson, who had spotted
Charlow and parked down the block to keep watch. ``She has no fear,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   The men avoided looking directly at her. After a few minutes,
they scattered like bugs exposed to light. Charlow walked up and
down the street for a few minutes, collected her sign and returned
to her sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   If the drug trade moves just a few blocks away, police Lt. Boone
Darden Jr. said, then Charlow has done something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they relocate, it takes time for their customers to
find them,'' he said. ``If you keep moving 'em, they start losing
sales.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't happened yet. Half an hour after Charlow left the
corner Thursday, the men were back, committing commerce through car
windows.
</P>
<P>
   Charlow has seen a better ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``God told me they're coming to be saved,'' she said. ``I had a
vision that they was coming down the street, in a line. They was
dropping them drugs in a tub and coming in the church to PRAISE
GOD!''
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-16-98 1933E
</P>
