<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3229 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUWANNEE-HOUSEBOAT18-     06-17 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUWANNEE-HOUSEBOAT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A FAMILY MAKES ITS WAY DOWN UPON THE SUWANNEE RIVER
 &HT;    By SHERMAN ZENT
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUWANNEE, Fla. _ My eyes squint against a soft breeze and a
brilliant sun as the houseboat drifts down the River Seine, French
countryside floating idly past on either side. There's a gentle
nudge. Aaaaah, must be my bikini-clad companion with that glass of
chardonnay . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad . . . daddy, can we fish now?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm on the Suwannee, not the Seine, and the nudge is from my
7-year-old son. The houseboat, however, is real and we're cruising
lazily up the river immortalized in Stephen Foster's song Old Folks
at Home, a perfect place to remember old daydreams.
</P>
<P>
   Our cruise begins at Miller's Marina in the town of Suwannee,
where the river empties into the gulf on Florida's West Coast. The
lower area of the river is a national wildlife refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's, started 27 years ago by Bill Miller, is a rustic fish
camp and marina. Three of his six sons help him run the business.
</P>
<P>
   The marina's mechanic explains the boat's operation for us. Turn
the key, push the throttle and you're a captain of the Suwannee. A
generator, separate from the engine, powers the air-conditioning,
heat, lights, microwave and full-sized refrigerator. A propane tank
fuels the oven and three-burner stove top. The boat is spacious,
but not luxurious. There is dark wood paneling and a faint musty
smell.
</P>
<P>
   A full-size bed and another full-size upper and lower bunk make
comfortable sleeping space for six. A hide-a-bed love seat makes
room for two more, but the sagging specimen of furniture does not
look inviting. Eight people on this boat would feel like a crowd
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanic steers us away from the dock, jumps in a skiff, and
we're on our own, a battered aluminum canoe in tow.
</P>
<P>
   My kids quickly find a bell on the bow of the boat, and take
turns clanging until we can't take it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Every little gust of wind, change in current, or wake from
another boat nudges the nose one way or another, and staying on
course takes some concentration. Frequent over-correcting is a
given as you steer the lumbering boat, but the river is wide and
our speed is slow.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, two of our children, ages 3 and 7, and my in-laws (no
really, we're glad they came!) make up our party.
</P>
<P>
   And now we're cruising slowly up the Suwannee. That puts us one
up on Stephen Foster, who never actually saw the river.
</P>
<P>
   I can see well from the helm through sliding glass doors and
large windows. I try steering with my toes, moving them from spoke
to spoke on the wooden wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The banks are lined with untouched cypress and native hardwood
forests.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing on the Suwannee is a big draw, but heavy rains before
our arrival have temporarily changed that.
</P>
<P>
   More disappointing for us, the high water has flooded and closed
Manatee Springs State Park. Easily reached by the second day, most
house boaters anchor in the river, taking rafts and tubes to the
park's crystal clear water.
</P>
<P>
   Since our trip, the park has opened, and fishing is good again.
Bass, brim, and catfish are found in the river's fresh waters,
speckled trout and redfish in the salt waters of the lower river.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least 20 springs along the 80-mile stretch of river
that Miller's Marina allows its houseboats to navigate, a
round-trip that would take five to seven days.
</P>
<P>
   The first evening, we anchor early enough to enjoy the sharp
colors a setting sun pours across the trees on one river bank,
which soften and fade while we make spaghetti and salad.
</P>
<P>
   My wife spies an osprey in a nest. The fish-eating birds are
plentiful, and resemble bald eagles, which also can be seen in the
refuge.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, after a scrambled egg breakfast, we continue up
the river, a series of lazy arcs. We rarely see another boat.
</P>
<P>
   The current is so strong, from all the extra water, that on the
second evening we can only get one of the two anchors to the bottom
of the river.
</P>
<P>
   We grill hamburgers, and play more games around the table.
Everyone's in bed before I realize we have forgotten to look for
stars, and I slip out of the bunk for a peek.
</P>
<P>
   The sky's an explosion of constellations. The brightest are
reflected in the black water's surface, and I'm unexpectedly
surrounded by stars as I walk to the rail _ a houseboat astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   ROLLING ON THE RIVER
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: The only part that is physically demanding is
pulling up anchor, which sometimes gets stuck in the mud. If you
can lift an 80-pound sack of cement, you're OK. Other than that, I
steered the houseboat with my toes. Enough said.
</P>
<P>
   What it cost: Two nights Monday through Thursday is $446;
weekends, $535. Seven nights is $1,070.
</P>
<P>
   Where is it? From West Palm Beach, take Florida's Turnpike north
to I-75. Go north and exit on U.S. 27. Go north, then west on
Alternate U.S. 27. Turn left onto County Road 349 at Old Town. It
dead ends at Suwannee. Trip takes about six hours.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's will send you a package in the mail after making your
reservation, which includes a list of things you may want to bring.
Here are some additional things, however, that youmight want to
consider which are not on their list:
</P>
<P>
   What to bring: Miller sends guests a list, of what to bring, but
here are some other suggestions for what to bring:
</P>
<P>
   _ Food in coolers, or buy it at the full-sized Food Lane
grocery, where you turn onto State Road 349.
</P>
<P>
   _ A cell phone. For emergencies, there is a two-way marine radio
that is monitored by the marina until 5 p.m. After that, if you
have a cell phone, you can dial Miller's home.
</P>
<P>
   _ A good pair of binoculars, so you can scan the banks for
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   _ A canoe or small motor boat to pull along behind your
houseboat. The marina only has a few aging canoes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rafts or tubes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Plastic bags for anything from garbage to dirty laundry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Life vests for young children. Vests provided with the boat
are the standard, bulky orange ones, and may not fit well or be
very comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pots, pans, and cutlery on board were adequate, but we were
short on cups. Bring serving spoons, a spatula, large and small
cooking knives, and a cutting board. Some or all of these may be
provided, but may not necessarily be in the greatest shape.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paper cups and plates, if you want to minimize dish washing.
(And save that hot water for your showers!)
</P>
<P>
   _ Towels. They're not provided.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ear plugs. For heat or air conditioning at night, you must run
the boat's generator. The noise may put some to sleep, but others
might wish they had ear plugs. On a windy night, the surface chop
slapping against the boat's hull might also bother some people.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cards and games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
