<HEADER>
A3230 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YBOR-WALKINGTOUR18-CO     06-17 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YBOR-WALKINGTOUR18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE WALKING TOUR: FIND OUT WHERE TO GET A REAL BEIGNET
 &HT;    By PAUL LOMARTIRE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ Carmen Morales, who grew up in Ybor City, can bring the
past back with anecdotes that make a 1-mile walking tour a lively
excursion.
</P>
<P>
   A volunteer guide, she'll tell you about her history, which is
Ybor's history, too. The nightclubs where she learned to rumba and
jitterbug and stages where she and other immigrant kids put on
talent shows. The clinic where her grandfather died and the shoe
store where Ybor kids got their Sunday shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Morales is also an Ybor City realist. She acknowledges that her
favorite part of Tampa, which she left in 1950, was crumbling into
oblivion before the upscale bars and restaurants turned it into a
profit center.
</P>
<P>
   The tours start at Ybor Square and you quickly find out many of
the nightclubs come with instant history. At Ybor Square, The Jazz
Cellar is located in the cool, dry rooms where Vincente Ybor stored
his tobacco leaves.
</P>
<P>
   The small, white building that was the historic Methodist Church
is now an upscale joint called the Red Star Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   A landmark clothing store that served generations, Fernandez Y
Garcia's, on the corner of 14th Street and Seventh Avenue is now
the all-nude Club Flamingo. A clinic where generations were born
and died is now the Sugar Plum Ballroom featuring Latin and swing
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   On 16th Street across a plaza from the Centro Espanol social
club in the heart of Ybor City is the St. Frances Cafe. It was
opened in 1996 by former nurse Lisa Sizemore in what once was a
central clinic for Ybor immigrants. The cafe won immediate media
attention, including NBC's Today show, because customers are not
given a check for their meal but are asked to pay what they can
afford.
</P>
<P>
   The menu leans toward health food and includes such basics as
pot roast, mashed potatoes and green beans, all made by Sizemore.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Frances, though popular, is to give way to a 20-screen
multiplex-restaurant-shopping center modeled after Miami's CocoWalk
that's expected to open in 1999. Loyal customers including
Sizemore's neighbors are helping to find a new Ybor site for the
St. Frances Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   All along the tour you can see how cash flow is saving the past.
The Circulo Cubano - The Cuban Club - with its ballroom, bar and
theater is being restored. Five other mutual aid society clubs
where Cuban, Italian, German, African and Spanish immigrants went
for everything from medical help to dance lessons are also being
saved through restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Ybor City's original hardware store - on Eighth Avenue near 15th
Street - was owned by the family of current Tampa mayor Dick Greco.
With its high ceilings and open-air front, it now houses Creatures
of Delight, which produces latex dinosaurs and other toys. It
shares the old hardware store with La Mode, a clothing store where
you can buy a neon lime furry bikini among other strange pieces of
clothing. Morales tells you what used to be and that is the value
of her tour.
</P>
<P>
   The walking tour includes the Ybor City State Museum and Gardens
located in the former Ferlita Bakery building. The $2 admission is
a bargain. Included with the museum tour are six renovated cigar
workers' homes that have stood since 1895. One of them, La Casita,
is furnished.
</P>
<P>
   The tour ends near Centennial Park, dedicated to Ybor City's
immigrants. There you'll also find the Alessi Family's Cafe Beignet
where you can get cafe con leche and the best powdered sugar
beignets this side of Cafe Du Monde in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   That stop alone should convince just about anyone that Ybor City
is surviving quite nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Ybor City on the Internet: http.//wwwybor.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
