<HEADER>
A3231 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YBORFLA18-COX     06-17 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YBORFLA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YBOR CITY SPRUCED UP AND SMOKIN'
 &HT;    By PAUL LOMARTIRE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ I strolled and shopped by day and crawled bar to
bar at night.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way to see Tampa's Ybor City.
</P>
<P>
   Ybor City draws huge weekend crowds for its nightlife.
Nightclubs are shoulder-to-shoulder along the main street, Seventh
Avenue, like cheapskates at an open bar.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case about 20 years ago when Ybor was a
crumbling, neglected, dangerous-at-night neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before the city learned to cash in on its lively
history.
</P>
<P>
   A staging area for Teddy Roosevelt and his Rough Riders 100
years ago, Ybor City was created by Cuban, Italian, German, African
and Romanian-Jewish immigrants who built lives around Vincente
Ybor's three-story cigar factory.
</P>
<P>
   Ybor moved his factory from Key West to Tampa in 1886 to escape
labor problems with Cuban workers.
</P>
<P>
   By the '70s, Ybor City's second and third generations had fled
to Tampa suburbs. Surrounded by low-income housing, Ybor became
known for cheap artists' work space and as a trendy/tacky setting
for gay bars. For those nearly down-and-out, an Ybor City apartment
wasn't much but neither was the rent.
</P>
<P>
   Then two things happened.
</P>
<P>
   The Hillsborough County Sheriff's Department moved to Ybor City
in 1978. Two years later, Vincente Ybor's original cigar factory
was renovated into the current three-story Ybor Square antique and
souvenir shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   The cops created a safe place and Vincente Ybor's beautifully
renovated cigar factory showed how to lure tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Events were brought to Ybor City. Every January, it hosts the
Outback Bowl's parade and pep rally. Each February is the annual
Gasparilla Night Parade, a safer, saner version of Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   Today, this area within sight of downtown Tampa is defined by
red-brick streets, black iron lampposts and a variety of Old World
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The dozens of nightclubs offer Latin, swing, reggae, jazz, blues
and rock-till-you-drop. Ybor's eclectic mix of shops won't
disappoint anyone looking for cigars, tattoos, body piercing, art
(from seven galleries), '60s nostalgia, antique clothing, flags,
pottery, just plain weird clothing and gargoyle statues.
</P>
<P>
   Along with coffee cafes, ice cream parlors and bakeries, the
choice of restaurants include traditional Spanish, Cuban and
Italian, not to mention wood-stove pizzas and even a cafe where you
can get a psychic reading with your food.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: You sweat according to how hot and sticky it is _
count on sweating even at midnight. The only work your thighs do
body does is climbing onto bar stools.
</P>
<P>
   Where to find those bar stools: The Green Iguana, Frankie's
Patio, Club Irie, Full Moon Saloon, Fat Tuesdays, The Edge, Spurs,
Irish Pub and Blue's Ship.
</P>
<P>
   What's next in Ybor: A Hilton Hotel (1999), a multiplex
entertainment center resembling Coconut Grove's Coco Walk (1999), a
trolley system (1999) and a 436-unit apartment complex are
scheduled to open in 1999(1999) .
</P>
<P>
   Did you know . . . ? Winston Churchill, Grover Cleveland and
Frederick Remington all stayed at the El Pasaje Hotel, built in
Ybor in 1888 and home to the men-only Cherokee Club. Today, the
Cherokee Club is a men-only club of another kind.
</P>
<P>
   Walking tours: Don't miss a free, 90-minute Ybor City walking
tour sponsored by the Ybor Chamber of Commerce and the Ybor City
Museum Society. For times and tours, call: (813) 248-3712.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
