<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-17 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT HAPPENED TO LOYALTY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On April 5, 1962, President John F. Kennedy gave his special
assistant and longtime friend David Powers a birthday present, a
silver beer mug inscribed: ``There are three things which are real:
God, human folly and laughter. The first two are beyond our
comprehension, so we must do what we can with the third.''
</P>
<P>
   After JFK's death, Tom Wicker of The New York Times wrote an
article for Esquire in which he said the quote's origin was
uncertain. Not so, responded Jack Valenti, who cited ``The
Ramayana,'' by Aubrey Menen, the British novelist and essayist.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti knew his literature and knew his place. He was a special
assistant to Lyndon B. Johnson, Kennedy's successor. Valenti has
since prospered as head of the Motion Picture Assn., but, like Dave
Powers, is a loyalist.
</P>
<P>
   Powers died this year, as did another of JFK's ``band of
brothers,'' Billy Sutton, who entered politics, he said, ``before
it was a crime.'' Both were Charlestown residents who helped out in
JFK's first congressional race in 1946. That era is revived in the
refurbished exhibits of the Kennedy Library, which recreates a
Boston street, a campaign headquarters, and a feeling that laughter
and loyalty were necessary parts of politics, not strangers to it.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the rivalries between the staffs of JFK and LBJ, Powers
would have appreciated Valenti's recent musings on loyalty in The
Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``All presidential assistants, current and former, have a
loosely connected but nonetheless real kinship to each other. Each
of us was lifted to the largest proscenium stage in the world by
one man and there allowed to become `celebrities.' When an
assistant departs the White House he or she usually enters what we
sardonically refer to as `the private sector' to become modestly
wealthy and sometimes more famous. But the fact is, we would not
have been attractive to our new arena without our presidential
patina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the niggling question: What does this band of brothers and
sisters, glistening in the glow of the president's power, owe the
man who gave them opportunities so few are granted?,'' Valenti
asks. ``What causes the question to be asked is the George
Stephanopoulos issue. Stephanopoulos, wearing the new velvet
garments of ABC pundit, was not only the first to publicly mention
the possibility of impeachment, but he continues to be
inferentially critical of his former boss, so soon after departing
the embrace of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti has scaled the heights of Holywood celebritydom, but
insists that, ``I would not be in my present place without my
intimacy with Lyndon Johnson. I owe him. Big time. My modest
judgment is that George Stephanopoulos is in the same debt to
President Clinton. I dare say that no publisher would pay him $2.5
million to write his memoirs, nor would ABC offer him a sizable
compensation to voice his views, if he were still leading a
hermetic existence on Capitol Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   When books are written by the likes of Dick Morris with the
preposterous theme of the hired-hand-as-genius, loyalty is as rare
as laughter. JFK was too Irish to put up with that, having followed
Robert Frost's advice to ``be more Irish than Harvard.''
</P>
<P>
   JFK, in whose White House Pablo Casals played his classical
cello, preferred on his own phonograph rousing Irish songs like
those sung by the Clancy Brothers and Tommy Makem. He identified
with ``The Minstrel Boy,'' gone to the wars, ``his wild harp slung
behind him,'' soon to be found ``in the ranks of death.'' His
loyalists, too, could sing:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though all the world betrays thee,
</P>
<P>
   One sword at least thy right shall guard,
</P>
<P>
   One faithful heart shall praise thee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dave Powers would have been a grand pundit, one of the funniest
talking heads on TV. Celebrity status offers many lures, but for
him, laughter always took second place to loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
