u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-NOTES-BOS &LR;      06-17 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES IN NHL RULES ENDORSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The NHL's general managers are recommending some
key rule changes that will be implemented during the 1998-99 season
if approved at the Board of Governors meeting June 25.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Tuesday, the GMs recommended that:
</P>
<P>
   _The nets and blue lines be moved 2 feet closer to center ice,
making the space between the goal line and the end boards 13 feet
rather than 11. This would reduce the neutral zone from 58 to 54
feet and increase the offensive zones by 2 feet, with the distance
between the blue lines and the goal lines remaining the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``By moving the net out 2 feet, it will be more risky for
goalies to go out and handle the puck,'' said Bruins president/GM
Harry Sinden. ``I was a little unsure whether that wouldn't be too
far. I thought maybe we could get the same job done with 1 foot,
but this will tell us more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is that the power play can operate more
efficiently with that kind of room and therefore increase the
offense. At equal strength, it might be easier to operate
offensively. The defensemen defending with 2 feet extra behind the
net may be able to move the puck out easier.''
</P>
<P>
   _The semicircle of the goal crease be reduced by 2 feet total on
either side of the goalposts, with straight lines to mark the side
edges of the crease.
</P>
<P>
   _The video goal judge be allowed to call down to the referee to
advise whether a player was in the crease at the time a goal was
scored. The referee still would determine whether a player was
pushed into the crease. The current rule allows only the referee to
request such a review.
</P>
<P>
   _A second referee be phased into regular-season games. Sinden
said his understanding was that a two-referee system would be used
in about 20-25 percent of the league's games. NHL director of
hockey operations Brian Burke said this experiment would be
completed by March 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has some plusses,'' said Sinden. ``People are not going to
be able to get away with things behind the play. It may result in
more penalties to begin with, but once players realize two guys are
watching them, I think it will be OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a general feeling the game is faster today. There's a
lot of action behind the play that he can't see. In general, we may
be able to be more proficient and efficient if we have four eyes
instead of two.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it triples the amount of power plays in a game, it's going
to turn me, for one, off and others, too, I imagine. It's going to
be used in some games, enough games so that when the season ended,
we can make a tremendous comparison between two referees vs. one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
On and on
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NHL has come under fire lately for its season lasting so
long and its TV ratings being down. Sinden would like to see the
season wrap up before mid-June. ``I think we can cut it back
some,'' he said. ``We were up against Michael Jordan, and that's
very difficult to overcome. It's more a result of the Olympics than
anything.'' ... Sinden plans to make qualifying offers to most of
the Bruins who are eligible. He declined to name those who won't
receive offers and therefore will become unrestricted free agents
... Sinden said he has talked to the representative for Group 2
free agent Kyle McLaren. ``They made an overture to us and we
responded,'' he said. ``Now we're waiting for a proposal but we
haven't gotten one.'' Sinden also has talked to Mark Witkin, the
agent for Group 2 free agent Ted Donato. ``We had a meeting of the
minds,'' he said, ``but here again, I don't know where it's
going.'' ... Red Wings defenseman Vyacheslav Fetisov has filed a
lawsuit against the limousine company and driver who were involved
in last year's accident that injured him and two colleagues. The
lawsuit was filed Monday in Oakland (Mich.) County Court. It seeks
unspecified damages from John Gambino, Gambino Limousine, and
driver Richard Gnida. Gnida was driving Fetisov, defenseman
Vladimir Konstantinov and team masseur Sergei Mnatsakanov in a
limousine when it crashed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
