<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTAIN HAS YET TO FALL ON STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not over.
</P>
<P>
   A split decision by the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court
does not settle the questions that surround the violent death of 8
1/2-month-old Matthew Eappen.
</P>
<P>
   The issues his death raised in bold relief _ from the options
for child care to the realities of child abuse _ do not magically
resolve themselves with the end of the criminal phase of
Commonwealth v. Louise Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   The same arguments that divided families and friends during
Woodward's criminal trial last fall will be played out again in the
wrongful death lawsuit filed against Woodward Tuesday and in the
negligence suit sure to come against the agency that recruited the
British teenager and placed her as an au pair in Deborah and Sunil
Eappen's Newton home.
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth v. Woodward becomes Eappen v. Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   The civil chapter of this saga will be no less wrenching than
the criminal chapter now concluded with the SJC's 4-3 affirmation
of the trial judge's decision to reduce Woodward's second-degree
murder conviction to manslaughter and to set her free after only
279 days in prison.
</P>
<P>
   One need only substitute the phrase ``vindictive parents'' for
``overzealous prosecutors'' to get an idea of the defense strategy
likely to be used against the Eappens in civil court.
</P>
<P>
   Why put themselves through it? Why invite a public that has made
a cottage industry of second-guessing their motives to chide them
for not ``letting it go,'' for not ``getting on with their lives,''
as if their baby's brutal death at the hands of a trusted au pair
were an accident to be ``gotten over.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the SJC dismissed the image of Woodward as a hapless victim
of circumstance, stating unequivocally that ``we do not view the
judgment against Woodward as a light matter. She stands guilty of
causing an infant's violent death. The outcome of this criminal
trial most assuredly was not an acquittal.''
</P>
<P>
   Not an acquittal, but not justice either. Not if we equate
justice with accountability.
</P>
<P>
   How, the Eappens ask themselves, is a young woman who is
greedily negotiating book contracts and movie deals being held
accountable for shaking their infant son senseless?
</P>
<P>
   How is a young woman who is courting celebrity and dating
tabloid photographers being held accountable for inflicting a 2
1/2-inch fracture in Matty's tiny skull?
</P>
<P>
   In his dissenting opinion, Justice John Greaney unwittingly
provides some insight into the Eappens' need to press forward,
recognizing, as Judge Hiller Zobel did not, that their voices, that
Matty's voice, should have been heard at sentencing. Zobel ``may
have failed properly to consider for purposes of sentencing the
impact of Woodward's crime on Matthew's family,'' Greaney wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears the judge identified himself with Woodward's cause,
compromising the public's confidence in the integrity and
impartiality of our courts.''
</P>
<P>
   By not remanding the case for resentencing to another judge who
might have imposed probationary conditions barring Woodward from
caring for children or profiting from her crime, the high court
Tuesday lost an opportunity to ``engender confidence in the
fairness and impartiality of our judicial system, maintain the
dignity and integrity of our courts, and bring rightful closure to
this difficult case,'' in Greaney's words.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear, even to Deborah and Sunil Eappen, what exactly
would constitute ``rightful closure'' in this case. A successful
prosecution of their claims in civil court could impose an
accountability on Louise now absent; a positive resolution of their
claims against Woodward and, eventually, EF Au Pair, could impose
tougher recruiting and training standards on those who would care
for children; an award of monetary damages for the pain of Matty's
death would fund the Matty Eappen Foundation to educate the public
about shaken baby syndrome and the many other manifestations of
child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Those would not be small victories for a family struggling to
make sense of a senseless loss.
</P>
<P>
   No judicial ruling will bring Matty home from the intensive care
unit of Children's Hospital. No court decision will prevent a
grieving mother from seeing the reflection of her lost son in the
eyes of the 3-week-old son she nurses at her breast. No judgment of
any court will ever deem this case over for Deborah and Sunil
Eappen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
