<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS WINNERS, LOSERS IN THE MARKET SHAKEOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a 10 percent drop in prices is considered a ``correction,''
Massachusetts stocks now officially qualify.
</P>
<P>
   The Bloomberg Massachusetts index is down 10.2 percent from its
high on April 22, the same day broader market indices such as the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 and the Nasdaq Composite also topped out. By
comparison, the technology-heavy Nasdaq is down 8.5 percent while
the S&AMP;P is down 3.8 percent. The much narrower Dow Jones industrial
average is down 5.9 percent since its May 13 high.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the stock market rebounded somewhat following Monday's
207-point rout of the Dow. While the Dow index rose just 37.36
points to close at 8665.29, the Nasdaq soared 37.37, or 2.1
percent. US bonds posted the biggest loss in almost seven weeks as
the dollar declined against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Not many Massachusetts stocks have been able to buck this moody
market. Of the 350 stocks we track on a daily basis, just 75 have
shown gains since the April selloff began. About 75 stocks have
lost 25 percent or more in value in less than two months.
</P>
<P>
   Does what is happening in Asia matter on Boston's Route 128?
Check out the list of big losers.
</P>
<P>
   We took our 350 stocks and screened out companies with a market
value of less than $250 million. Five of the 10 stocks that took
the biggest hits have cited the effects of the slowing Asian
economies on their businesses. Nine of the 10 are tech stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is loaded with companies that make equipment for
the semiconductor business, and virtually all of them have been hit
hard. PRI Automation in Billerica, a favorite target of
short-sellers, is down 41 percent from its high. Analog Devices is
down 40 percent, and Teradyne is down 31 percent. All three stocks
showed gains with Tuesday's tech recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Some very small companies _ with market caps under $250 million
_ have really been crushed. Ergo Science, a Charlestown drug maker
that failed to win government approval for a new drug, is down 77
percent since April 22. Spire in Bedford, which has been pushing
its equipment to make solar panels in Asia, is down 65 percent; the
stock has fallen from 17 1/2 in January to 3 7/8. SystemSoft, a
Natick software company, is also down 65 percent; its stock, which
sold for 35 in 1996, is at 15/16 today.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers are among the few winners. Talbots, a longtime
underperformer, was up 32 percent, and TJX, long an overachiever,
was up 8 percent; both are reporting strong same-store sales.
StrideRite was up 15 percent, reflecting market sentiment that its
flagship Keds brand is finally back on track.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest winner on our list was a technology company,
Pegasystems. Last year stock in the Cambridge customer-service
software maker was hammered when an accounting mix-up forced it to
restate earnings for three quarters. But analysts say the
accounting issues seem to be history, and last month the company
reported better-than-expected earnings. While the market has
wobbled, Pegasystems' stock is up 43 percent since April 22. The
shares closed Tuesday at 28 1/4, up 1 5/8 _ a 75 percent gain from
its January low.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rodney quitting Plymouth Rock
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keith Rodney, the man who founded Plymouth Rock Assurance Corp.
with chairman Jim Stone, is leaving. The company says it has
nothing to do with its angry agents _ but then no one is denying
the agents are hopping mad.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney, president of Plymouth Rock Assurance, says he is leaving
to pursue other interests after 16 years with the Boston automobile
insurer. Rodney, 54, will be succeeded by Hal Belodoff, who runs
Plymouth Rock's agency in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Stone and Rodney go way back. Rodney was the deputy when Stone
first ran the state's insurance division and later the US
Commodities Futures Trading Commission. Given the history it is
unlikely he was pushed _ but there is no denying the change comes
at a difficult time for Plymouth Rock.
</P>
<P>
   From its inception, Plymouth Rock has sold its auto insurance
through agents. But Stone has launched a well-financed venture to
sell insurance directly to consumers nationwide (Massachusetts and
most of the New England states excluded). Plymouth Rock also wants
to sell discounted auto insurance directly to Massachusetts
consumers through an alliance with Savings Bank Life Insurance; the
division of insurance has blocked the proposed discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Both moves have alarmed Plymouth Rock agents, who see the direct
sales as undercutting their own efforts. Frank Mancini, executive
vice president of the Massachusetts Association of Insurance
Agents, says he has heard from a number of Plymouth Rock's 120
agents. ``How many they'll have when this is over, I don't know,''
Mancini says.
</P>
<P>
   Plymouth Rock acknowledges some agents have been moving
business, lured by big upfront commissions from other companies.
One competitor estimated Plymouth Rock has lost 25 percent or more
of its business; Plymouth Rock denies that, and says the losses are
``not material'' to its bottomline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our agents have had concerns, and a lot of our
competitors have gone around to our agents and misstated things and
fueled the fire,'' says Paula Gold, Plymouth Rock's general
counsel. ``We are committed to our agents.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
