<HEADER>
A3246 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOTECH-CANCER-ART-BO     06-17 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-CANCER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH FIRMS IN FOREFRONT OF WAR AGAINST CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A quiet gold rush is on by companies seeking cures for cancer,
America's second biggest killer after heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific breakthroughs in the development of drugs for
treating cancer are becoming common. In May alone, two major
breakthroughs set the medical world abuzz.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, these discoveries are occurring outside the
research labs of America's medical schools _ and inside
pharmaceutical giants and small biotechnology companies.
</P>
<P>
   The National Cancer Institute, which frequently collaborates
with industry on cancer drug development, reported that private
companies paid the agency $13.4 billion last year for assistance in
research and clinical trials _ up from only $115,000 in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America
estimates that large drug companies spent $1.4 billion on cancer
drug research in 1997, often in concert with small biotechnology
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is a hotbed for cancer drug work. Small firms were
responsible for more than half of the 316 cancer medicines in
development last year; about 30 were in development at small
Massachusetts firms. Here is a look at three Cambridge companies
with drugs and vaccines that could become available within five
years:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LeukoSite Inc. &LR; : This company's roots go back to the hallowed
halls of Cambridge University, where two pathology professors, one
American and one British, met while each was pursuing research
there in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The work of the professors, Timothy Springer, &UR;  &LR; on sabbatical
from Harvard Medical School, and Herman Waldmann of Cambridge
University, would years later form the core of the company's most
promising drug, a treatment for chronic lymphocytic leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   The incurable disease afflicts 120,000 adults in the United
States and Europe. The proposed drug being developed by Springer
and Waldmann aims to treat leukemia by zapping only diseased white
blood cells without harming bone marrow. If successful, the drug
would be a vast improvement over chemotherapy, which damages
healthy cells.
</P>
<P>
   With traditional chemotherapy, seriously ill leukemia patients
often relapse and die within six to nine months. But LeukoSite
believes its drug, taken in conjunction with chemotherapy, will
extend lives, &UR;  &LR; said Christopher Mirabelli, LeukoSite's president.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year-old company in April launched an
advanced &UR;  &LR; clinical trial of the proposed drug on 75 patients and
hopes to apply for Food and Drug Administration approval within the
next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   In forming LeukoSite, Springer had intended to develop drugs to
treat rheumatoid arthritis and inflammatory bowel disease. But
opportunity came knocking from England last year. Waldmann had
developed a monoclonal antibody called Campath to &UR;  &LR; treat chronic
lymphocytic leukemia. A UK drug company, Burroughs Wellcome,
licensed the antibody and conducted clinical studies with promising
results on &UR;  &LR; leukemia patients. But when Burroughs Wellcome was
acquired last year by Glaxo, another UK drugmaker, the conglomerate
decided that the potential market for Campath was too
small. &UR;  &LR; LeukoSite snapped up the license.
</P>
<P>
   But tiny LeukoSite, which has 80 employees, needed a bigger
partner to carry out more clinical trials. It forged a 50-50 joint
venture last May with Ilex Oncology Inc. of San Antonio, which
agreed to handle clinical development and commercialization of the
drug. &UR;  &LR; Last August, LeukoSite went public, raising $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts estimate that if LeukoSite's leukemia drug is
approved in the year 2000, the company could generate sales of more
than $6 million the first year, climbing to between $75 million and
$100 million three years later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Therion Biologics Corp.:  &LR; Cancer wasn't on Dennis Panicali's
radar screen originally.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, he founded Therion Biologics to develop a
vaccine for AIDS. When he asked large pharmaceutical companies to
fund his idea, they weren't interested. So, in 1993, he switched to
developing a cancer vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't like that, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hear drug companies and investors say, `When you cure
cancer, come back and see me,''' Panicali recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Cambridge company has 30 employees and has secured
funding from the US government and from a large French
pharmaceutical company. It's now leading an increasingly crowded
field of companies &UR;  &LR; seeking vaccines for a variety of cancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still at the very early stages of cancer vaccines,
trying to figure out why some tumors respond and others don't, and
the research is promising,'' said Dr. Robert Wittes, director of
the division of cancer treatment and diagnosis at the National
Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of therapeutic vaccines is not to prevent cancer but to
prevent a relapse among patients who have been treated with
chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer patients in Therion's clinical trials receive a vaccine
that contains a live but weakened virus that stimulates the body's
immune system into making protective antibodies to fight off cancer
cells.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In the past year, Therion's research breakthroughs have begun
to produce financial results. The company was awarded funds from
the National Cancer Institute to conduct clinical trials of some
vaccines. And in January, Pasteur Merieux Connaught, a leader in
vaccine development, pledged up to $25 million to further test and
develop Therion's vaccines for colon and lung cancer and for
melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preliminary success of some of these small companies and
the recognition that the pharmaceutical industry has worked 30
years looking for new treatments with only minimal success have
prompted everyone to seek out new arenas like vaccines in the
battle against cancer,'' Panicali said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company's next plan is to develop a therapeutic
vaccine for breast and ovarian cancers.
</P>
<P>
   But Panicali is the first to acknowledge that cancer vaccines
are a risky venture for a company that has raised a modest $20
million in venture capital since its formation in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the recent headlines of drugs that work in mice,'' he
said, ``there is still a lot of healthy skepticism, some of which
is justifiable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Vertex Pharmaceuticals Inc.:  &LR; Joshua Boger's holy grail is
creating a kinder, gentler cancer medication that also is more
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are ways of attacking cancer without intensifying the
process,'' said Boger, founder and president of Vertex
Pharmaceuticals Inc.
</P>
<P>
   His company is staking part of its future on Incel, which would
be used with some chemotherapy agents, such as Taxol, to better
target and eliminate cancer cells while reducing the vicious side
effects from chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Vertex is targeting the estimated 500,000 advanced cancer
patients for whom standard anticancer medications just don't work.
</P>
<P>
   Incel is designed to overcome multidrug-resistance _ that's when
cancer patients unsuccessfully try a battery of chemotherapy drugs
or develop an immunity to cancer medications during lengthy
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Some Wall Street analysts have projected the market for
multiresistant drugs at $1 billion a year, if Vertex and its
closest rival, Novartis A.G., the large Swiss-based pharmaceutical
company, obtain FDA approval for their cancer drugs. Last month
Novartis said it would begin a 700-patient advanced clinical trial
for its drug, which is a second generation derivative to
cyclosporine, a drug known for its toxic side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge market,'' said David Stone, biotechnology
analyst with Cowen &AMP; Co. ``If either Novartis or Vertex or both are
successful, one would expect a &UR;  &LR; lot of other companies to jump in
and reignite multidrug-resistance programs. ... Vertex has a chance
to become among the first to gain broad use of its drug in this
part of the cancer market.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Vertex launched four intermediate stage clinical
trials targeting breast cancer, ovarian cancer, soft tissue
sarcoma, and liver cancer. Vertex is also planning to start later
this year two more intermediate trials for patients with prostate
and lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   And although Vertex does not have a US partner to fund Incel's
advanced clinical trials, money is not a problem for the
250-employee company. &UR;  &LR; With significant funding from corporate
partners for four other proposed drugs, plus a secondary offering
that netted $149 million, Vertex had a hefty $266 million in cash
at the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vertex has plenty of options,'' said Stone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
