<SLUG> BC-WOM-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP TEAM GETS SET FOR '99 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ONEONTA, N.Y. _ The spotlight may be on their male
counterparts at the World Cup, but the US women's national soccer
team has hardly been hibernating this year: It is 13-1-1 in matches
around the globe as it prepares for the 1999 Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-team World Cup will be held at seven venues in the United
States, including Foxboro Stadium. Although final rosters are far
from set, several women could feel right at home for their
first-round match June 20.
</P>
<P>
   At least five players in the current 42-member national team
pool from which the World Cup squad likely will be chosen have ties
to New England. The best known _ so far, at least _ are 1996
Olympic gold medalists Kristine Lilly and Brianna Scurry, but
Jennifer Mead, Tracy Ducar, and Sara Whalen are eager for their
turn.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly, a 27-year-old midfielder who grew up in Wilton, Conn.,
became the world's all-time leader _ male or female _ in
international soccer appearances when she played in her 152d
international game May 21. Scurry helped lead the University of
Massachusetts to a 17-3-3 record and the semifinals of the NCAA
Final Four in 1993 before becoming the most capped goalkeeper (each
international game played is a ``cap'') in the history of the US
women's national team.
</P>
<P>
   The other three also played either high school or college soccer
in the region. Actually, when it comes to New England, Mead covers
the whole field: a basketball and soccer star at
Bridgewater-Raynham High before graduating from Providence College
in 1994, the 26-year-old is now girls' soccer coach at Newton North
High as well as goaltender for the Boston Renegades. Mead is 3-0-0
in six games with the national team dating back to 1993, although
she has yet to play in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ducar, meanwhile, is 3-0-0 in four games this year and 10-1-0
with 18 caps since her debut in 1996. Better known in the Bay State
as Tracy Noonan before her marriage in April 1997, she was a
standout keeper for North Andover High, from which she graduated in
1991, before an All-American career at the University of North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Although Scurry still sees most of the action, the 25-year-old
Ducar is patient. ``Every time I get in, it's a chance for me to
show myself,'' said Ducar recently before a game against New
Zealand at the Soccer Hall of Fame here. ``But Bri's a much more
experienced goalkeeper. I can't expect to become the No. 1
goalkeeper overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Ducar got her fifth start of the year in goal that night, but it
came to little: The match was called because of lightning after
only 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When she isn't with the national team, Ducar, who now lives near
Chapel Hill, N.C., plays with the Raleigh Wings of the W-League and
works out with members of the North Carolina-Greensboro men's team,
which she calls ``not good for my ego but good for my
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Whalen, whose first training camp with the national team came in
January 1995 after her freshman year at the University of
Connecticut, has played in 12 games this year, getting her first
goal in a 6-0 victory over Iceland May 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first international goal was important,'' said Whalen. ``It
felt like something was beginning to pay off. It was just amazing:
`I'm scoring a goal for my country!'''
</P>
<P>
   Not that scoring was new to Whalen, who had 21 goals and 22
assists to lead UConn to the 1997 NCAA final. On the way, she
scored both goals in a stunning 2-1 semifinal upset of Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   The day after UConn's 2-0 loss to North Carolina in the final,
Whalen joined the national team in Brazil. But the transition
hasn't been as easy as it was quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating for me sometimes because it's not like UConn,
where I played such a leadership role,'' said Whalen. ``But every
day I just try to learn from the great players, and they've
accepted me really well.''
</P>
<P>
   The months leading up to the final cutdown to the World Cup
roster won't be easy, either. ``It'll be nerve-wracking,'' said
Whalen, 22. ``I know if I play the way I can, I'll be in the top
18. Maybe my time is next year, maybe in a couple of years. Who
knows?''
</P>
</TEXT>
