<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3256 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PICTURETEL-CEO-BOS &LR;      06-17 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICTURETEL-CEO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CEO HELPS PICTURETEL CLEAR ITS FOCUS ON THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The past year can only be described as a disaster for
PictureTel Corp. Everything that could go wrong, did go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of its video conferencing equipment plummeted amid an
industrywide slump, and the undisputed market leader lost money for
the first time since 1990. Its stock fell 75 percent. A shift in
its business strategy wasn't well focused, and senior managers
jumped ship in droves. Meanwhile, the search for a new chief
executive dragged on for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to its woes, the Andover, Mass. company discovered it had
improperly booked $18 million in sales and lease payments dating
back to mid-1996, triggering a spate of shareholder lawsuits. On
top of it all, PictureTel was slapped with a potentially ruinous
patent infringement suit by a Texas company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of like Murphy's Law for PictureTel last year _
one thing piled up on top of another,'' said Jason Ader, a research
analyst at H.C. Wainwright &AMP; Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems that have clouded PictureTel's future for more
than a year are beginning to clear with the arrival of Bruce Bond,
its new chief executive. His challenge is to put the struggling
company's strategy back into focus.
</P>
<P>
   A respected veteran of the telecommunications and Internet
industries, Bond most recently ran America Online Inc.'s networking
subsidiary. His plan is to transform PictureTel from a simple
provider of video conferencing equipment into a full-service video
communications company specializing in helping people collaborate
visually over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role PictureTel should play, as a clear leader and pioneer
in the video industry, is to help carry a light and say, `This is
how you can use this technology,''' Bond says.
</P>
<P>
   The new service-oriented strategy is winning praise from
analysts on Wall Street, including some who had left the company
for dead less than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, PictureTel's stock, which traded at nearly $45 a share
three years ago, is selling for just $8 today, suggesting investors
still aren't convinced a turnaround is under way.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old Bond will make his pitch directly to
shareholders today at the company's annual meeting, the first since
he became PictureTel president and chief executive in March. &UR;  &LR; He
replaced Norman Gaut, 60, who had been chief executive for 12
years. Gaut, who is still chairman of the board, was expected to
step down Wednesday. The board will then name Bond to the
additional post of chairman. Gaut, who wants to cut back his
day-to-day responsibilities, will stay on as a director.
</P>
<P>
   Bond's arrival has inspired new hope for PictureTel, which grew
rapidly in the 1990s through the sale of expensive video systems
for corporate boardrooms but stumbled badly in 1997. The video
systems allowed groups of people in different locations to see and
speak to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some real signs of life that this thing is going to
turn itself around,'' said Ader, one of several investment analysts
who had been critical of the company last fall but have recently
recommended the stock.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a huge threat facing PictureTel disappeared when it
won the patent suit brought by DataPoint Inc. But the primary
reason for Wall Street's new optimism about PictureTel is the
arrival of Bond.
</P>
<P>
   A former football star at Colorado State University, where he
studied psychology and philosophy, Bond earned an MBA from the
University of Dayton and a master's degree from the Sloan School of
Management at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   He was plucked from ANS, the networking unit of America Online,
after it was acquired by WorldCom Inc. last year. After long stints
with AT&AMP;T Corp., US West and British Telecom, Bond said he didn't
want to work again for a giant telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't come cheaply. Terms of his compensation package won't
be disclosed for a year, but his contract reportedly includes a
boatload of low-priced stock options that could be worth millions
if he succeeds in turning PictureTel around.
</P>
<P>
   By reining in costs, Bond has already managed to stop the
bleeding at PictureTel, and he says the company will be profitable
again this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nostrils are close to the water,'' Bond said. ``As soon as
that happens, the whole psychology within the company will be
different,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Bond's leadership is having an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to have PictureTel employees believing again that
their company has what it takes to be the best,'' said Ader.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all its troubles last year, PictureTel didn't lose much
ground to competitors and remains the leading provider of video
communications products and services, with more than 50 percent
market share.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the entire industry ground to a halt in 1997,
amid customer confusion about an array of new products flooding the
market, including desktop systems that allow computer users to
communicate visually. Many buyers decided they'd rather wait than
get stuck with an obsolete system, while others avoided the desktop
systems because the images were poor.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, none of PictureTel's competitors was able to take
advantage of the leader's misssteps and steal market share. The
industry has changed, however, and PictureTel can't just pick up
where it left off.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, competitors have identified a hot new segment
of the videoconferencing market _ small group systems costing less
than $10,000 each _ which could turn videoconferencing into a
mainstream business tool. &UR;  &LR; The emergence of these inexpensive
systems has hurt PictureTel, which specializes in high-end systems
that cost $20,000 to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The most aggressive of these low-end providers is Polycom Inc.
of San Jose, Calif., which, ironically, is run by Bruce Hinman, the
MIT graduate who cofounded PictureTel in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Malloy, the general manager of Polycom's video
conferencing business, says PictureTel is facing the same quandary
that Digital Equipment Corp., the leader in minicomputers, faced
when the PC revolution began.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for companies like that, who are a leader in a
particular generation of technology, to make a smooth transition to
the next technology,'' Malloy said.
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel has responded by introducing its own low-priced
system called SwiftSite, but its challenge is to avoid hurting
sales of its own higher-end systems, which are used by Fortune 500
companies such as Ford Motor Co. and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Bond believes video conferencing systems are becoming
inexpensive commodity items, so his solution is to diversify and
offer companies a broad array of services to help them manage their
video communications needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving away from being just a box provider,'' he said,
adding that PictureTel plans to boost its services revenue to about
50 percent of its sales, up from 14 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   Malloy said that's a typical response for a company that is
caught flat-footed by competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motto is that video conferencing ought to be as easy to
set up and install as a network printer, or a fax machine or a
copier. So you don't need a big services operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond counters that companies expect their video conferencing
systems to do more for them.
</P>
<P>
   Early users of video conferencing systems saw them as an
alternative to travel, he said. This was especially true during the
Persian Gulf War, when executives were afraid to travel because of
the risk of terrorism, and helped fuel PictureTel's growth.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Bond says, companies now want their employees to be
able to collaborate visually over phone lines and the Internet.
With 14 years of experience, PictureTel can help companies achieve
these technological goals, Bond says. Investors hope he is right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
