<HEADLINE>
SOCIETAL, LEGAL CHANGES ARE LEGACIES OF A PUBLIC TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Louise Woodward case was Massachusetts'
contribution to the media phenomenon of the '90s _ the televised
trial as meeting place for public grievances.
</P>
<P>
   What started as a forensic whodunit, dense with dueling medical
experts, became a local equivalent of the O.J. Simpson case, a
prism through which people projected their own anxieties onto those
wrestling with the law. And, like the Simpson case, there is a
civil trial yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   Where the Simpson trial featured spousal abuse, the Woodward
trial featured child abuse. Where Simpson spotlighted race,
Woodward spotlighted class. And when the criminal trial ended, with
a rapid series of legal somersaults, this case _ like Simpson's _
left lingering concerns about whether television, with its
magnifying effect, is distorting the justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ``These events are often a seamless web of spectacle and
tutorial,'' observed Ralph Whitehead, journalism professor at the
University of MassachusettsTuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Show trials can stimulate viewers to reflect on issues that
otherwise rarely enter the public discourse _ in this case, the
difficulties of working parents in securing affordable and reliable
day care.
</P>
<P>
   Television can also blow open the courthouse doors and reveal
uncomfortable truths about the justice system _ in this case, the
vagaries of decision-making by prosecutors, defense lawyers, and
judges, and how they can alter the outcome of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, serious discourse can quickly devolve into
Jerry Springer-like name-calling, stirring up ignorance or even
prejudice in the guise of man-on-the-street opinions _ in this
case, some extreme views on working women's duties to their
children or the irresponsible nature of young women.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's trial rang up the highest ratings of the year on
Court TV in the United States, and it became a prime-time
attraction in Woodward's native England. Playing in 3 million homes
a night, the trial came across to Britons as the railroading of an
innocent girl; one poll revealed that an astonishing 98 percent of
the country believed that Woodward was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The Economist, a British magazine, noted, ``England is the home
of Mary Poppins; Massachusetts is the scene of the Salem
witch-hunts; and so the televised trial of an English au pair in
Massachusetts played on potent stereotypes from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   But what cultural footprints, if any, will be left after this
event? Much grief was aired. Little was settled. There is no
consensus on Woodward's culpability. Nor is there a definitive view
of who was more poorly served by the legal process, Woodward or
Deborah and Sunil Eappen, the parents of the baby who died under
Woodward's care. The British aren't even sure whether to be
appalled by the tawdriness of the US justice system _ or to put
their own trials on TV.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the president of EF Au Pair, the Cambridge company that
arranged Woodward's placement in the Eappens' home, says the case
brought about major changes in the way au pairs are trained. Echoes
of the hubbub surrounding the case can still be heard in Congress,
where tax credits to help parents pay for childcare remains on a
short list of policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   And in the State House, some observers insist that the case's
greatest legacy is in prompting a statewide change of heart on the
death penalty after the murder of 11-year-old Jeffrey Curley stoked
support. Two days before the Woodward verdict, the House voted to
institute capital punishment, overcoming concerns that innocent
people might be found guilty of murder and executed. Then came the
jury's vote to convict Woodward of second-degree murder, even
though millions of trial-watchers insisted she was innocent. The
House reversed itself a week later.
</P>
<P>
   ``People involved in lobbying (against) the death penalty called
here to say they wanted to thank Louise,'' said one of her lawyers,
Harvey Silverglate. Although only one legislator changed his vote
because of Woodward, many others were prepared to do so if
necessary, Silverglate said. ``This case changed more than one
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Execution was never a possibility for Woodward, but her
conviction exposed a fragility in the criminal law that weakened
the argument for harsh, irreversible punishment. After all, if the
system were capable of neatly separating the wrongdoers from the
wrongly accused, how could so many people watch Woodward's trial
and come away with differing views of her guilt?
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people thought she was innocent _ she got a raw deal,''
explained George Katsinis, a waiter at the Sweet Touch restaurant
across from the courthouse on Cambridge Street, which served
throngs of trial watchers. ``But it didn't start out that way _ it
turned about halfway through. Then when she got the light sentence
it turned again. People were upset about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Katsinis could look out the front window of the
Sweet Touch and see streets clogged with TV-news trucks and
sidewalks filled with sign-waving protesters. The crowd outside the
courthouse thickened daily, drawn by outrage _ several types of
outrage. Some people were inflamed by Woodward's alleged offense _
shaking to death a baby who had been in her care. Others, convinced
there was little evidence linking Woodward to the baby's death,
were incensed over Middlesex District Attorney Thomas Reilly's
decision to charge her with murder.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike famous trials of the past _ from Alfred Dreyfus in France
to the Rosenbergs' prosecution for treason in the US _ today's TV
trials aren't simply about judging the accused. TV plays off the
audience. TV trials soak up, like sponges, the vagrant attitudes of
their onlookers. The rendering of justice becomes something more
than an individual denouement: It becomes America's day in court.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those fascinated by the Woodward case had strong
feelings about working mothers, and applied them to Dr. Deborah
Eappen, the baby's mother, an ophthalmologist who saw patients
three days a week. To some who followed the trial at home during
the day _ a group that inevitably included many stay-at-home
mothers and paid nannies _ Deborah Eappen became a symbol for a
generation of women who had, in their view, sacrificed homemaking
for the personal gratification of careers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
