<HEADER>
A3308 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MULAN-FILM-HNS &LR;      06-17 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULAN-FILM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULAN IS A NEW SPIN FOR DISNEY ANIMATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For too long, Disney just didn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   After its animation rebirth via 1989's The Little Mermaid, the
studio lived on film after film about plucky heroines and heroes
seeking true love in musical adventures inevitably spiced with one
big Busby Berkeley-style production number.
</P>
<P>
   Can you spell formulaic? Many filmgoers could, and Disney's
animated fare, while consistently lavish, began getting diminishing
returns.
</P>
<P>
   But while A-team animators in Burbank, Calif., toiled on
Hercules and The Hunchback of Notre Dame _ whose respectable $100
million grosses trailed far behind their predecessors' _ the B-team
at Disney's newer Florida studio launched a lesser project.
</P>
<P>
   Intended as a direct-to-video effort, this project soon evolved
into a major movie _ and a welcome breath of fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   That movie is Mulan, a new spin for Disney animation that opens
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mulan is Disney's first animated feature created primarily by
its Florida artists, who often labor under the humiliating gazes of
tourists in windowed studios at Orlando's Disney-MGM Studio Theme
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Mulan (pronounced moo-lahn) also is Disney's first animated
feature focusing solely on Asian characters. It's the first with
songs from the team of Matthew Wilder and David Zippel, who
maintain the Broadway style of Alan Menken and Howard Ashman but
add a contemporary pop-rock edge _ and sidestep the Busby Berkeley
number.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Mulan contains hardly a hint of romance. Boy meets girl
isn't the essence. History is.
</P>
<P>
   Mulan's title character is a heroine of ancient Chinese
folklore. She disguises herself as a man to take her father's place
in the imperial army when Huns invade their country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see the girl save the guy and not really need
him,'' said Ming-Na Wen, who gives speaking voice to Mulan. (Lea
Salonga of Aladdin provides the singing.) ``He's the one who comes
running to her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy'' isn't Mulan's father but Shang, an army leader who
must whip Mulan and other recruits into shape. Shang is given voice
by B.D. Wong (Father of the Bride), with pop star Donny Osmond
handling the singing.
</P>
<P>
   While he's always taken his sons to see Disney films, Osmond is
heartened by Mulan's new approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my second song was cut, I was so disappointed,'' he said.
``It would have been a romantic duet between Shang and Mulan. But
having seen the film, I'm so glad they cut the love interest and
gave Mulan her independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Composer Wilder previously produced No Doubt's Tragic Kingdom, a
1997 Grammy nominee for best rock album. Lyricist Zippel also wrote
the words for Menken's Go the Distance from Hercules, a 1997 Oscar
nominee for best original song.
</P>
<P>
   Mulan's instrumental score is by veteran Jerry Goldsmith, an
Oscar winner for The Omen.
</P>
<P>
   Wen, who also starred in The Joy Luck Club, was born in Macao, a
Portuguese colony off China's southeastern coast.
</P>
<P>
   Her family moved to America when she was 4, but she grew up
``with very traditional Chinese parents, and my mother used to tell
me about Mulan.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulan's story is as familiar in China as tales of Pocahontas and
Joan of Arc in Western countries.
</P>
<P>
   Wen said Disney ``has made a great deal of effort not to stray
too far from the original story,'' which she called ``part folklore
and part history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Mushu (a small, impish dragon voiced by Eddie Murphy)
and the bug (a good-luck cricket named Cri-Kee) didn't exist, but
that's a Disney thing,'' she said. ``Overall, the story is very
true, and I don't think any Chinese will be offended by the
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulan gained authenticity when Disney dumped its plans to make
it a romance like The Little Mermaid, Beauty and the Beast,
Pocahontas and its other recent films.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first they wanted that relationship,'' Wen said. ``But then
they went back to the original story. It's nice that they realized
this story lasted thousands of years because of its content.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Disney took some license,'' Osmond said. ``But I
believe this is true to the Chinese folklore. Mulan conquers
adversity. That's a great story to show kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Osmond came into the project almost by accident.
</P>
<P>
   He'd auditioned for the title voice of Hercules ``and really,
really wanted that gig, because I'd always wanted to do a Disney
film. But they said my voice was too low for the part. They wanted
someone younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Osmond, 40, got a call months later saying his voice was similar
to Wong's and asking whether he'd like to sing for the male lead of
Mulan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, ``Are you kidding me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Wen isn't bothered by a non-Asian actor's contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just grateful Disney went out of their way to cast as many
Asians as they did,'' she said. ``They didn't have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Actors of Asian ancestry speak in many other roles, including
George Takei of Star Trek fame as the First Ancestor and Pat Morita
of the Karate Kid films as the Emperor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something has a certain ethnic background, I do think you
should cast people with that background,'' Wen said. ``It brings an
innate sensibility to the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if they find voices to better represent a character, you
can't stop them from that creative choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulan also gave Disney a chance to expand its artistic palette.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Disney, chairman of Disney Feature Animation and nephew of
the late Walt Disney, said the Chinese locale provided ``a whole
new set of cultural references and artistic influences in a setting
we had never been to before.''
</P>
<P>
   In preproduction, animation supervisors spent three weeks in
China to study, photograph and sketch the country.
</P>
<P>
   The coming-of-age theme from a female perspective also sparked
Disney's creative team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very exciting challenge for us not to do a love story
but something unique,'' said Peter Schneider, president of Disney
Feature Animation.
</P>
<P>
   Wen said Mulan's ancient tale shows that female liberation isn't
new to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese women are extremely liberated,'' she said. ``China's
history is so full of changes, because it's such a large country.
There was a period of time when women were equal in battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that this 2,000-year-old legend represents such
modern ideals. Maybe the Chinese knew better about what was going
on back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Osmond, who starred for almost six years in a touring production
of Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat, is excited about
Mulan's prospects on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine what they'd do with this on Broadway in a few
years?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he and Wen delight in a film that's emerged as
what Osmond calls ``the silent monster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so proud of this project,'' Wen said. ``It will be one of
those things I can look back on one day and say, `Yes, I was a part
of that' _ and say it with pride.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
