<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASIA (Washington) _ For the first time in his
presidency, Bill Clinton orders the sale of U.S. dollars to support
another currency, hoping the massive purchase of yen will bolster
Japan's economy and prevent a panic-driven currency devaluation by
China. Clinton also dispatches an emergency financial team to Tokyo
for talks. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-GOP (Washington) _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott is
expected to decide whether to allow a vote on tobacco legislation
or use a procedure that would kill it. Earlier, Senate Republicans
emerged from a key meeting with no agreement on how to deal with
the bill. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-SURVEY (Washington) _ A majority of small-business owners
support measures reining in managed care and half would absorb the
cost higher premiums, according to a new survey. The study
challenges claims of small-business lobbyists and insurers that
regulation would force up premiums and make health insurance
unaffordable. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   ONASSIS-AWARDS (Washington) _ Hospice care crusader Rose Crumb
of Port Angeles, Wash., receives the Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis
Award for public service as the founder of the volunteer Hospice of
Clallam County. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-LEADERLESS (Paris) _ already filed _ Western governments
have demanded that Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
initiate sweeping reforms designed to rescue his country's sagging
economy before it drags down the rest of the world. But the problem
is that Hashimoto, like most of his predecessors, lacks the
authority and prestige even to contemplate such a task. By BERNARD
D. KAPLAN.
</P>
