<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FOR PEACE IN FACTIONALIZED LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GLADYS ALAM SAROYAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO, Calif. _ I come from a country where God is the
deciding factor in which neighborhood a newborn baby will first see
the ray of light.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon was not even Jesus' birthplace, or Mohammad's key
geographical point to conquer, nor by any means Buddha's idea of a
serene place. But in that tiny country whose main economy thrived
once on the benevolence of open-handed tourists, religion has taken
the form of a dangerous country club.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Lebanese accuse the Muslims of choosing God above
country, and the Muslim Lebanese, baffled that anyone would not
choose God first and foremost, accuse the Christians of worshipping
France.
</P>
<P>
   France is the nation that formerly colonized Lebanon and taught
its Christians how to flaunt.
</P>
<P>
   Our flag contains the symbol of the cedar, which historically
has helped build a Jewish temple, never mind that the country it
represents is at odds with the Israeli people.
</P>
<P>
   We have no famous mosques or cathedrals whose steeples pierce
the clouds, but on our grounds we still fight the noble cause of
how best to worship God: standing, kneeling or bending.
</P>
<P>
   And then comes Syria, which so believes in love-thy-neighbor
that it managed to roll through our country with tanks filled with
construction workers. Syria, it seems, suffers from a perpetual
unemployment crisis and has found in God-torn Lebanon a perfect
place to build condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, on our southern border, employs Christian Lebanese
youths as their human shields from attacks by Muslim Lebanese
youths whom Iran employs as their human bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Within each religion, of course, is a ruling faction.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese Maronites and the Muslim Shiites love their country
to death, and each feuding side can claim ancestors whose blood was
spilled on that same spot where rivers irrigate olive trees which
are the symbol of peace for both religions.
</P>
<P>
   We, the Lebanese, don't have much to show on Earth for our
religious fighting, but, when we meet our maker, we are hoping for
a special place in our Father's heavenly kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Yup, the time-out place he reserves for naughty children.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gladys Alam Saroyan is a free-lance writer who wrote this
column for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San
Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
