<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COLUMN-HONGKONG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEDOM IS NOT HONG KONG'S WORRY _ IT'S THE ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A year ago, as Britain handed over Hong Kong to China,
the conventional wisdom was that the territory's civic freedom
would be in trouble but its economy unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   That was exactly backward. Today the scorecard on Hong Kong
reads: civic freedom, unaffected; economy, in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong leaders appeared in Seattle this week at a conference
sponsored by the Asia Society and the Washington State China
Relations Council. They answered the predictable (and appropriate)
questions about freedom. The Hong Kong people's freedom to
assemble, publish, vote, worship, transact business and do many
other things depends entirely on the promises of China. In the past
11 months, those promises have been entirely reliable. Amazing,
perhaps _ but there it is.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news has come on the economic side. Hong Kong has caught
the new Asian flu, and not from its mother country. The fever seems
to peak in a different country each month, currently Japan. Anson
Chan, the No. 2 official in the Hong Kong government and the
highest-ranked holdover from the British administration, said
Monday that the plunge in the yen-dollar rate to 146 was
``extremely worrying.'' She told the Post-Intelligencer she expects
no Asian revival ``until and unless the Japanese economy picks
up,'' and added, ``We hope that Japan will show some leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Fung, chairman of the Hong Kong Trade Development Council
(a conference co-sponsor), said Tuesday he was ``really concerned''
about Japan. A hint of leadership from the Bank of Japan pushed the
yen-dollar rate to 142, but Fung was worrying about a pullback by
Japan's banks. ``Japanese banks provide about half of the foreign
loans in Asia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, credit is tightening in Asia, and is virtually
unobtainable in Indonesia. ``If you go to Indonesia and contract
for some garments, the supplier will have a hard time delivering,''
he said in an interview. The fall in Indonesia's currency would
seem to help that garment maker, except that the banks have shut
off dollar credits. The garment maker needs dollar credits to
import fabric.
</P>
<P>
   If the yen-dollar rate passes 150, Fung said, it will put
pressure on the South Korean won. That in turn will pressure the
Taiwan dollar and threaten ``another round of competitive
devaluations in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mudslide of devaluations, China has been the bedrock.
Fung, whose private-sector interests include Hong Kong's big Li &AMP;
Fung trading house with a long interest in China, said, ``Renminbi
(China's currency) will hold.'' Many in Hong Kong worry it won't,
citing warnings by Chinese officials about the slide of the yen.
But Fung says China does not compete directly with Japan in most of
the things it sells, and is undercut less than Korea or Taiwan by a
falling yen.
</P>
<P>
   And Hong Kong? Its dollar has been pegged at 7.8 to the U.S.
dollar since 1983 _ and pegged in stone, with a currency board
backed up by $97 billion in reserves. The Hong Kong dollar will
hold, too, Fung said. (As did Anson Chan. She said her government's
commitment to the peg is ``absolute,'' adding, ``We have the
unequivocal support of the sovereign power.'')
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's pegged currency puts it in the same position as
gold-standard economies of a century ago. ``Rather than adjusting
to the downturn through changes in currency value,'' said Fung to
the conference Tuesday, ``our economy is doing so through
asset-price depreciation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index recently fell below the level of the
Dow Jones industrials for the first time in decades. And the price
of condominiums, where the top half lives, is off 40 percent in the
past year. Prices of standard units in each building are posted in
neighborhood real estate offices like stock quotations, and are
closely followed.
</P>
<P>
   The 40 percent drop, says Fung, ``reflects an economy that's
very efficient. Contrast that with Japan, which has been trying for
eight years to go into a recession in slow motion.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's no-safety-net economy will snap back fast. But it
falls fast, too, and the prospect of another drop is not so
welcome. Last week, condo buyers who owe more on their mortgages
than their flats are worth demanded government subsidies.
Unemployment has risen to 4.2 percent, and some of the laid-off are
demanding unemployment compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's elites do not want to open this Rooseveltian box.
Government at all levels eats up 18 percent to 19 percent of the
economy _ roughly half the level in the United States. Hong Kong
has a Steve Forbes-style flat tax with a top rate of 15 percent,
compared with a middle rate of 28 percent here. ``We intend to keep
government small,'' says Chan.
</P>
<P>
   That resolve will be tested _ by Hong Kong's legislators, who
are tending toward populism, and by Asia's economic storm, which is
not over.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ramsey's column appears Wednesdays. His e-mail address is
bruceramsey(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
