<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL RAGE AGAINST GLOBALIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARCO A. MANGELSDORF  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ What began as a peaceful protest ended with riot police
waging pitched battles with brick-throwing, sledgehammer-wielding
looters. Storefronts were shattered and shops were ransacked as
cars were overturned and demolished.
</P>
<P>
   I saw this scene repeated over several days as rioters perfected
their hit-and-run tactics to elude security forces and volleys of
tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Jakarta? No, Geneva, the heart of normally placid and
heretofore predictably stable Switzerland. Asked why he was
involved, one 32-year-old physical education teacher explained: ``I
need to express myself. I came to support those peoples oppressed
by the power of money. Violence bothers me, but it's the only way I
found to be heard. It's an act of desperation and anger.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this series of demonstrations and subsequent
violence is not dissatisfaction with a corrupt or oppressive
government.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the natives suffering from food shortages or other
economic deprivations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in this exemplar city of global finance and
international organizations, people in the streets were raging
against the principles and practices of the World Trade
Organization and a recent conference here attended by dozens of
world leaders, including President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Smashing windows and battling police on account of the WTO, an
organization dedicated to global free trade? What is going on here
and why should we care?
</P>
<P>
   We should be concerned about this old, yet enduring Emerald
City-like vision of the great benefits and riches coming from
unfettered economic exchange. It is prompting a growing number of
detractors to question, if not oppose, unrestricted trade and the
forces of globalization.
</P>
<P>
   From the left-leaning anti-capitalists in the streets of Geneva
and other European and Canadian cities to the American hodgepodge
of liberal academics, environmentalists and Pat Buchanan nativists,
these differing ideologies share a common suspicion and fear of a
Daimler-Benz-Chrysler, Volkswagen-Rolls Royce,
NationsBank-BankAmerica, United-Delta juggernaut crushing all in
its way.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, free-trade phobics see the unhindered movement of goods,
services and capital across borders as jeopardizing workers'
rights, accelerating consumption of finite natural resources,
threatening small entrepreneurs and shop owners, and promoting
profits over people.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States and Canada, workers fear the loss of their
jobs to the cheap labor markets of Asia and Latin America while
environmentalists worry about big businesses voraciously gobbling
up natural resources and increased pollution in countries with less
strict waste and conservation standards.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, where activists march against American symbols like
McDonald's and Pizza Hut, there is concern that the growing sales
and profits of these and other transnational corporations do
little, if anything, to help the people at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the poverty experienced by the more than 2 billion
souls in the developing world represent a threat to international
stability as people surviving at the edge in region after region
agitate for a better life.
</P>
<P>
   Across national borders, the perception that important decisions
affecting local, regional and even national affairs are being made
in distant boardrooms feeds the belief that what's good for
corporate executives and shareholders is not necessarily good for
the common folk.
</P>
<P>
   Since the days of Adam Smith and David Ricardo, a widely held
vision has endured: An open, competitive market that leads to a
rising tide of material prosperity that lifts all boats.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a unifying, overall strategy of America's role
in the world, which we had during the more black-and-white Cold War
years, Washington has promoted the idea of turning the globe into
one big free-trade zone.
</P>
<P>
   The rumblings of discontent from many quarters show serious
concern over just who stands to gain from all this capital
mobility, increased trade and consumption, and merger mania.
</P>
<P>
   The skeptics _ whether they make their stand on the need to
secure the rights of indigenous labor, safeguard the environment or
do more to eliminate poverty _ are united in their unease.
</P>
<P>
   Going full speed ahead without adequately dealing with these
concerns imperils an intrinsically sound vision that, with some
refinements, could improve peoples' lives from Geneva to Jakarta
and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marco A. Mangelsdorf teaches politics at the University of
California at Santa Cruz.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
