<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING AMONG GOLFERS, DEVELOPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There's not much you can say about taking a cold
and cloudy week's vacation in San Diego (actually, at the in-laws'
place in Escondido), then returning to a hot and sunny San
Francisco overrun by golfers.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino has tipped the West Coast upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The golfers will go away, but Los Angeles power brokers may be
taking over a big new chunk of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   While I was away we found out what Mayor Willie Brown hid behind
the toilet paper curtain on Treasure Island. Pieces of eight,
pieces of eight, pieces of eight. And they just might go to a Los
Angeles supermarket millionaire, a leading Friend of Willie.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months ago Brown blew up and said the San Francisco
Examiner wasn't fit to use as toilet paper after I wrote a column
on restricted access to the island. Obviously, something was up
besides the mayor's blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The other handmade Italian shoe finally dropped. Last week, the
Examiner reported on Treasure Island Enterprises, which was formed
at the beginning of this year and proposes to build a marina,
condos and commercial operations, including a dining, wedding and
special-event destination.
</P>
<P>
   What is this, the Chapel of Love and Canapes?
</P>
<P>
   That would be a special-event destination brought to you by
special people indeed. Access to the island? Well, the old saying
is that political contributions buy access.
</P>
<P>
   Treasure Island Enterprises is run by Brown fund-raiser Darius
Anderson and Los Angeles supermarket magnate Ron Burkle, who has
been one of Brown's law clients and contributed $100,000 toward the
U.S. Mayor's Conference, which was held in San Francisco last year.
Their lobbyist is Billy Rutland, a close friend to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the San Francisco Board of Supervisors could exert
some control over who gets the treasure on Treasure Island if they
vote to enact Proposition K, which was approved by voters two weeks
ago to wrest control of the island from the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. As my wife says, ``Some cities have supermodels. San
Francisco has supervisors.''
</P>
<P>
   This is their chance to be model supervisors and earn their
handsome new salaries passed by the voters.
</P>
<P>
   What else did I miss? So what if Willie Brown has a penchant for
hiring good-looking staffers, and his scheduling secretary has a
Web site featuring sexy photographs of herself?
</P>
<P>
   Brown's policy of hiring the beautiful extends to men (check out
his bodyguards or aide-de-everything Stuart Sunshine). And if
Willie had a Web site, imagine the pictures he'd post of himself.
Of course, the world is Willie's Web, or as he said a couple of
weeks ago, ``I am my own Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, out there in hand-tailored fiberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up megalomania and Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, who has been running off at the mouth himself a lot.
</P>
<P>
   He said that homosexuality is a sin and gays should be assisted
in dealing with it ``just like alcohol ... or sex addiction ... or
kleptomaniacs.''
</P>
<P>
   Kleptomaniacs? Where did he get that one? I guess senators look
down on kleptomaniacs as amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   Is homophobia an existing condition or will your HMO treat it?
And how do we deal with a problem like Trent Lott? Too bad they
haven't invented Brainagra yet.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, R-Miss., seems to have caught something from Pat
Robertson, who went wild a week ago and said God would smite
Orlando, Fla., with terrorist bombs, earthquakes, tornadoes,
hurricanes ``and possibly a meteor'' for flying rainbow flags to
greet gays going to Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Pat, and God will send plagues of bugs, snakes,
alligators, fundamentalists, rednecks, retirees and tourists in bad
shorts, too. How can a meteor hurt a town that develops giant
Porsche-swallowing craters all on its own?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All right, so I came back a little bitter from my cloudy San
Diego vacation and now I'm doing some easy gay-basher-bashing and
Willie-bashing.
</P>
<P>
   You know the West Coast is really upside down when your trip
from the Bay Area to San Diego County was a food pilgrimage. I
caught a 13.2-pound yellowtail. No fish tale. One hunk of it right
out of the Pacific, and that's it for fish in restaurants ever
again.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the pilgrimage part. The pilgrimage was a trip to
Del Mar to find the Chino Ranch. First off, never trust a fruit
stand that plays classical music.
</P>
<P>
   A few pieces of sugar-and-butter corn, two baskets of cherry
tomatoes, some beans, Brussels sprouts, onions and strawberries
from French seeds _ and what does the young woman who looks like a
fine arts major say?
</P>
<P>
   She said: ``That'll be $31, please.''
</P>
<P>
   We'd walked into a foodie trap, and were too embarrassed to ask
for an accounting.
</P>
<P>
   It all was great, though _ the finest corn this side of roadside
stands in New England, and the finest strawberries this side of
France, I guess. Or maybe that's just me having a bad case of
cognoscenti cognitive dissonance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
