<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-MOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT OLYMPIC CLUB, BIG HITTERS TO GIVE DRIVERS A REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Titanium and muscles being what they are in
1998, the 288-yard seventh hole of the Olympic Club's Lake Course
would seem to be but a drive and a putt away from the 156 U.S. Open
contestants.
</P>
<P>
   Caution and patience being what they are in this particular week
of 1998, player after player stepped to the tee during practice
rounds with but an iron in his hand. Instead of charging up the
hill to the green, the world's best tiptoed through the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Darren Clarke, the 6-foot-2-inch, 225-pound Irishman,
brandishing his driver and attacking the hole for a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   A real man he? Nope, just a momentary lapse into foolishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I hit driver onto the green,'' Clarke said. ``But I
probably wouldn't hit it in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is at the U.S. Open this year, where the world's biggest
hitters are leaving their drivers in their golf bags. Clarke says
he'll likely use his no more than three times when the tournament
begins Thursday; Tiger Woods sounds like he's good for maybe only
two, at the first and 17th holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can hit your driver here,'' Woods said. ``You really can.
If you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can if your driver will launch a shot high enough into
the air that it will not run through the Lake Course's meandering
fairways into the clumpy rough. You can if you don't hit your
driver very far. You can if you're inclined toward momentary lapses
into foolishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do, you have got to shape it into the slopes, because
the fairways are running,'' Woods warned.
</P>
<P>
   Woods averages 294.9 yards off the tee, Fred Couples 290;
they're close runners-up to John Daly, holding the lead as ever at
297. And because those are average figures, you know these sweet
swingers are hammering out 300-plus-yard drives about as often as
not.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA is so concerned that this kind of range could render
golf courses and records obsolete, it has been considering putting
a lid on technology. After all, imagine what would happen in
baseball should Mark McGwire be allowed to hit any kind of ball he
wanted with any kind of bat an engineer could dream up.
</P>
<P>
   Though length does not a champion make, even the longest-driving
golfers concede that the USGA has a point of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever they decide, it's all right with me,'' Couples said.
``They're pretty bright, it's not like it's just on a whim and
people are shooting 58s and 59s. Their decision will be well
thought out, and I don't think they're going to all of a sudden say
you can't use a driver, you can't use a 60-degree wedge. They might
do something with the ball, I don't know, and I have no problem
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Here at the Lake Course, particularly this week, the USGA and
Olympic Club superintendent John Fleming have shown that it is
possible to design around the Big Berthas and King Cobras.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to put the driver in their hands as often as
possible,'' said USGA agronomist Tim Moraghan. ``And, yes, I think
there is enough evidence that the players are stronger; equipment
is better and turf conditions obviously are a lot better, which
allow the ball to go farther.
</P>
<P>
   ``But where do you draw the line? Do you have 510-, 515-yard
par-4s? I don't know. ... You have to understand, (the Open) being
open to everybody, not everybody hits it 320 yards. There are
players that hit it 245. You want to have the entire field be able
to have an opportunity to win the national Open.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, the fairways are so narrow that it is hard to keep a
line drive out of the rough. And the rough is so long, it's hard to
put a shot on the green coming out of it. Even the sand is softer,
to preclude its use as a refuge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This golf course demands accuracy off the tee, not necessarily
distance,'' Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Clarke _ or anyone who wants to win the tournament
_ is unlikely to reach for the green from the seventh tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anyone going for 7, because there is really no
point,'' Woods said. ``There is no place to bail out ... it makes
no sense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet the bombers aren't complaining. Mostly, they're raving.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of what it's all about,'' Couples said. ``They
pick the best courses, and the Olympic Club is one of my all-time
favorite _ and they set it up so it's harder than normal but it
really is fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to go out there and play each hole with perfect
shots, you just can't hit it wild _ which I do at times, but I
can't just say I hate the course because I hit it in the rough. I
mean, I hate the course if they make it ridiculous like it's
miniature golf. But they don't do that. What they do is make tight
fairways and high rough and tight greens. And I wish more people
would do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every week, though. The sluggers just have to cut loose once
in a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we did this every week,'' Couples said, ``we would just go
crazy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
