<SLUG> BC-AIDS-DRUG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHER SAYS AIDS DRUGS DON'T LIVE UP TO HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After two years of high hopes for new
AIDS-fighting drugs, a letdown is likely at the upcoming
international AIDS conference, a top expert warns.
</P>
<P>
   The much-ballyhooed AIDS drugs known as protease inhibitors are
not working as well as hoped, said Thomas J. Coates, director of
the AIDS Research Institute at the University of California at San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were oversold,'' said Coates, who charged that the
``scientific establishment is reprehensible'' for having allowed
the drugs to be over-promoted at the last international AIDS
conference held two years ago in Vancouver, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, at the time, said it (the overselling) was public health
malpractice,'' Coates told a news conference Tuesday in advance of
the 12th World AIDS Conference, to be held June 28-July 3 in
Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Volberding, director of the AIDS program at San
Francisco General Hospital, was somewhat more upbeat. He expects
the mood at Geneva ``will still be positive (but) not as ecstatic
as at Vancouver.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates said in a telephone interview that protease inhibitors
``have helped a lot of people. They have extended life and given a
better quality of life to a significant proportion of the
population.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``they're just not the `cure' that some
people were talking about at Vancouver. ... They were oversold at
Vancouver. The talk about cure and eradication was incredibly
premature.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Stanford University Medical Center researchers
reported that for many AIDS patients treated with protease
inhibitors, their bodies have developed resistance to the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Shafer and his Stanford colleagues have genetically
analyzed AIDS viruses from about 200 patients in the San Francisco
area. One-fifth of the viruses were unaffected by the new drugs,
and at least half were partially resistant to the medications.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, AIDS patients who develop resistance to the new
drugs may, through sexual contact, be transmitting their resistance
to others, Coates said.
</P>
<P>
   Even in AIDS patients who do well under drug treatment, ``the
side effects are not trivial, and adherence (to the drug regime) is
not easy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the Geneva conference, AIDS experts will discuss the
lack of easy access to AIDS counseling and treatment in developing
and impoverished nations.
</P>
<P>
   HIV, the human immunodeficiency virus which transmits AIDS, is
``running rampant in the developing world,'' Coates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many life-saving (medical) technologies now, but even
the most simple of those are not available to people in the
developing world.'' He said those technologies include testing
blood supplies to ensure they are not contaminated by HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Coates called the United States' failure to adequately respond
to the international AIDS crisis one of ``the sins of the '90s. ...
If we were willing to spend 1 percent of the military budget, we
could probably stop the virus dead in its tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed 1999 budget for the Defense Department is nearly
$271 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
