<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAST CANCER EXAM NO EASY STOP ON THE ROAD TO PREVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ Deborah Hunt held her breath while the
machine held her breast in a tight clamp for another X-ray. This
time it was a side view, and Hunt tilted her head to make room for
the medical camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``O.K. Debbie, right now I want you to hold your breath. Don't
move,'' said Debbie McClary, a senior mammography technologist at
Ellis Hospital. Seconds later, Hunt sighed and pulled her medical
robe around her shoulders. Around her middle, she wore a lead
apron. Her first mammogram was almost over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't bad,'' said Hunt, a mother of three. ``I expected it
to really hurt. It wasn't painful. It was awkward.''
</P>
<P>
   Most women have heard war stories about this first line of
defense against breast cancer. It's painful. It's embarrassing.
It's a rite of passage to middle age.
</P>
<P>
   For too many women, the mammogram is still the enemy, even
though regular screenings can detect breast cancer in its earliest
stages and improve the chances of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people would rather ignore it than deal with it,'' Hunt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mammograms are recommended every two years for women over 40.
</P>
<P>
   The risks are clear: one in nine American women will develop
breast cancer in her lifetime. Some 43,500 are expected to die this
year.
</P>
<P>
   McClary believes fear keeps women away: ``Some women are fearful
of the exam and some women are fearful of the results.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the examining room, Hunt waited while McClary looked
over the pictures of her breasts.
</P>
<P>
   At 36, Hunt is right on schedule for her first mammogram. Most
doctors recommend that women get a baseline mammogram at 35. Those
pictures serve as a template to compare any future changes or
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't know they encouraged it before 40,'' said
Hunt, who lives in Glenville, N.Y. ``I thought I had a couple of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, McClary returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're beautiful,'' she said of the pictures. ``But I have to
take some more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt looked nervous. ``Why?'' she said. She knew of no breast
cancer in her family nor had she ever felt any lumps during her
self-examinations.
</P>
<P>
   After 22 years as a mammography technician, McClary understands
the anxiety. She lost an aunt to breast cancer and has made it her
career to help other aunts, mothers, sisters and daughters, fight
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breasts are my life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But every breast is different and some are harder to photograph
than others. In this case, she was hoping to get a better view of
Hunt's breast tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the photographer only,'' she said. ``I don't interpret or
diagnose. I try to give as much confidence as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Areta Pidwerbetsky, a radiologist, spends her time
interpreting the results of mammograms and calling patients for
additional exams when she sees a potential problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the callbacks end up being nothing,'' she said. ``It's
the minority that end up being serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt changed back into her clothes. She had no idea that in a
week she'd be one of the women who get that call to schedule
another appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Pidwerbetsky tries to diffuse the fears: one in six women get
called back. Of those, 98 percent learn they don't have breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But a mammogram is the first step to peace of mind. ``If they
find it early, the prognosis is so much better, '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt is a registered nurse and familiar with medical odds.
</P>
<P>
   Most people, she knows from experience, don't expect to be the
one with the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still think stuff like this can't happen to them,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
