<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories in sight at this hour from The N.Y. Times
News Service for Thursday, June 18:
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (212)
556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories from our partners:
Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   INFLATABLE-FURNITURE (New York) _ ``The Inflatable Moment,'' now
on view at the Urban Center, celebrates a time when, if you didn't
have an idea, you just didn't show up. By Herbert Muschamp. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   FARMHOUSE-RESTORE (Balmville, N.Y.) _ Heidi Petelinz Benson's
house is also her hometown. The 19th-century carriage house near
Newburgh, N.Y., where Ms. Benson, a magazine editor, lives with her
husband, Matthew Benson, a photographer, is part of a one-acre
village of ``carpenter Gothic'' out-buildings. For four years, the
Bensons have been renovating _ and reinventing _ with an
imaginative approach toward restoration that only amateurs would
attempt. By William S. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   DAD-SALESMAN-MEMORIES (Racine, Wisc.) _ My father, Allan, was a
furniture salesman. He died 20 years ago this year, on a December
morning when the sky and Lake Michigan were slate-gray. He was 54
years old. He was an ace salesman, ``the king of Milwaukee'' in his
day. But when he died, what he did for a living was still something
of a mystery to my sisters and me. Like many dads of the era,
especially those with daughters, he didn't talk about his work
much. By Patricia Leigh-Brown. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-BANKNOTE-DESIGN (Undated) _ About a month ago, as
preparations began for printing the 10 billion new Euro banknotes
that will replace the familiar currencies of most European nations
by the end of 2001, a French-made anti-counterfeiting hologram
vanished. Officials speculated that it had been stolen by
well-informed thieves who understood the significance of the
device. An alternative theory is that the hologram was snatched by
an unhappy esthete who understands the damage the Euro banknotes
will do to the continent's reputation as a place where the design
of everyday things has a high priority. By Karrie Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-LIGHTS (Undated) _ It's true that everything looks better
by candlelight. Besides, it beats eating in the dark. But there are
hazards: there has been a recall of 30,000 fuel canisters called
Summer Lights by the Conros Corp. of Toronto in cooperation with
the Consumer Product Safety Commission. These plastic canisters for
outdoor bamboo torches can cause the bamboo poles to ignite. There
is a new, safer Tiki light: a 67-inch tall stainless steel model
with a fiberglass wick, which comes with a refillable canister. It
sells at $70 from the Williams Sonoma catalogue. By Marianne
Rohrlich.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ Back in the 1930s, the running joke
among young architects in the office of Richard Neutra, the apostle
of modernism, was: ``What is the best material to build a steel
house of?'' To judge by a new steel-and-glass addition to a
just-restored Neutra house in Santa Monica, it's taken about 60
years for technology to catch up with his vision. By Joseph
Giovannini.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ Files, Part II: How to use them. By
Edward Lipinski. How-to graphic.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Gardening questions and answers. By
Leslie Land.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
