<HEADLINE>
NO MAJOR FLOODING SEEN DESPITE FULL RESERVOIRS, RIVERS IN N.
CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As El Nino relinquishes its cool, clammy grip on
California, it leaves brimming reservoirs and rambunctious rivers
and hints that it is not yet through causing trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Nevada retains 70 percent of an unusually heavy
snowpack, and several days of warm weather have finally produced
the snowmelt that normally comes weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   More water is flowing into the reservoirs than is flowing out:
Some are 96 percent or more full. But no major flooding is
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough space saved to contain possible floods,'' said
Maurice Roos, the state's chief hydrologist.
</P>
<P>
   Some flooding on the state's wild rivers seems inevitable. This
week, the abrupt rise of the Merced River forced the evacuation of
30 Yosemite Valley campers and closed the Yosemite National Park's
main entrance road. The 100-foot washout on Highway 120 has left
the southern entrance, Highway 41, as the only way into the park.
</P>
<P>
   While it appears that 1998 will be a grand year for whitewater
rafters _ high water is expected to last well into October _ some
rivers are simply too dangerous to run now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an amazing year,'' said Chet Bowling, chief of the
U.S. Bureau of Reclamation's water operations division. May storms
turned normal seasons topsy-turvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty cold, and the snowmelt stopped, and in some
places (the snowpack) actually grew,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of California's reservoirs are expected to be full in the
next week or two. Don Pedro on the Tuolumne River, is 89 percent
full. Lake Shasta on the Sacramento River, keystone of the Central
Valley Project, is at 99 percent capacity _ so full that on
Thursday the bureau will open the drum gates near the top of the
dam to flush out debris that has collected on the surface of the
lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're expecting the inflows to drop off pretty soon,''
said Gary Hester, who heads the State Department of Water
Resources' hydrology branch.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Nevada snowpack measured at Echo Summit on May 1 was
67.4 inches, with 34 inches of water content. There have been only
seven deeper, wetter measurements in the past 50 years. During the
last El Nino in 1983, the depth was 144.5 inches, with a water
content of 64.7 inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting the snowmelt now that we usually get in May,''
said Yosemite ranger Al Nash. ``Just another reminder that nature's
in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   El Nino is the name given to the unusual warming of waters in
the Pacific Ocean that affects global wind and temperature
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   A prolonged period of intense heat that would melt the entire
snowpack in a hurry could overwhelm the capacity of the rivers and
cause some flooding.
</P>
<P>
   The most flood-prone area is the San Joaquin Valley south of
Modesto where the Tuolumne, Stanislaus and San Joaquin rivers
converge.
</P>
<P>
   But ``we're not seeing a forecast of really intensely hot
weather,'' Roos said. ``The only (flood prone) areas we'd worry
about are the ones in the high basins of the Sierra from the Merced
to the Kern (rivers).''
</P>
<P>
   State climatologist Bill Mork concurred. El Nino has raised the
ocean temperature, so the weather should be somewhat warmer than in
a non-El Nino year, ``but not as warm as '83,'' he said. ``El Nino
is really dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a flood watch was in effect Wednesday for rivers
and streams in the southern Sierra Nevada. The rapid snowmelt
caused by the warm weather already has caused the Merced to flood
and the Kings River near Cedar Grove to approach flood stage.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service said the flood threat would run
high in the next few days on the San Joaquin, Kaweah, Tule and Kern
rivers.
</P>
</TEXT>
