<SLUG> BC-AIR-BAGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK COURT HOLDS TOYOTA LIABLE IN AIR BAG CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York's highest court has ruled that the
Toyota Motor Corp. can be held liable for injuries that might have
been prevented by an air bag, even though air bags were not
required at the time of a 1991 accident.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision means a Brooklyn woman who was severely hurt
in a low-speed crash can pursue a $10 million lawsuit against the
automobile company. It also means auto manufacturers who adhere to
all government manufacturing standards can still be sued in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decisions like this make manufacturers sit up and listen in
terms of what safety improvements they put in their vehicle,'' said
Manhattan attorney Alan Shapey, who represents the plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Tetherow, spokesman for Toyota Motor Sales USA Inc. in
California, said the ruling was ``contrary to numerous appellate
decisions, both state and federal, throughout the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Court of Appeals rejected Toyota's claim that the
National Traffic and Motor Vehicle Safety Act of 1966, which gave
auto manufacturers the option of installing air bags to meet
restraint requirements, pre-empts state law. Since Toyota could
have installed air bags in its 1991 Tercel vehicles, and chose not
to, the company may be liable for the victim's injuries, regardless
of the federal statute, the court reasoned in a 6-1 opinion.
</P>
<P>
   At the crux of the case is the presumed primacy of federal law
and the independent right of the states to establish standards for
legal actions.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that Caryn Drattel, a certified public accountant
with Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. in New York, was driving her 1991 Tercel
at approximately 25 mph when the vehicle was struck head-on by a
1988 Honda Accord. Drattel, who was wearing a seat belt, suffered a
permanent brain injury and her family sued Toyota, claiming the
Tercel was defectively designed.
</P>
<P>
   Under New York law, plaintiffs in such product liability cases
have to prove not only that a vehicle was defectively designed, but
an alternative design was available that would have made the car
safer. Drattel's lawyer argued that air bags were available at the
time the Tercel was manufactured, and an air bag would have
prevented the then 29-year-old woman's injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota noted that the National Traffic and Motor Vehicle Safety
Act of 1966 gave manufacturers the option of equipping vehicles
with any one of three safety systems _ air bags, passive belt
restraints or manual belt restraints. A trial court justice
dismissed the lawsuit. But an appellate court reinstated the action
in a decision upheld Tuesday by the state's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority, Judge Joseph A. Bellacosa said the
fact that Toyota could have, if it so chose, installed
driver's-side air bags in its 1991 Tercels raises a question of
whether it would have been reasonable and prudent to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This injured plaintiff should not be deprived of the
opportunity to establish ... that Toyota should have included a
driver's-side air bag because, for instance, it possessed the
technology and because it was aware that the inclusion of an air
bag would have been a better alternative safety device given the
specific design of the car,'' Bellacosa wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In dissent, Judge Howard A. Levine said the state Legislature
could not have imposed a regulation requiring air bags _ such a law
would have impermissibly intruded in federal domain _ and said the
court should not, effectively, do what the Legislature cannot.
</P>
<P>
   He said Tuesday's decision would ``inevitably undermine the
regulatory, interest-weighing cost/benefit determination by
Congress ... and by federal regulators.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say the decision has national implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it is important for Caryn Drattel and her family,''
said the plaintiff's appellate counsel, Arthur H. Bryant of
Washington. ``It is also important for others across the country
because of the prominence of the New York court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
