<HEADLINE>
PC EXPO FOCUSES ON CONSUMER DEMAND FOR MINIATURIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Canada, N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In this age of consumer convenience and ease of use,
the name of the game is miniaturization. Both the appeal and some
of the limits of miniaturization were abundantly evident this week
in the cavernous Jacob K. Javits Convention Center in New York,
where PC Expo, the largest computer trade show on the East Coast,
opened on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing more than 600 high-tech companies, including IBM,
Microsoft, Compaq and Gateway, the exposition's floor was crammed
with booths brimming with the wonders of the very small and
reportedly very useful from the latest in flat display screens to
palm-sized DVD movie players and personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The current trend toward miniaturization is more a result of
consumer demand than technological advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like big steaks and small electronics,'' said Fred
Swan, a director of marketing at Logitech in Fremount, Calif. He
said that space in American homes was becoming more limited, and
that if consumers could buy smaller scanners to make more room on
their desks for another framed picture of their children, they
would.
</P>
<P>
   Already, he noted, in home and office space in Japan is so tight
that desktop computers have mostly given way to much smaller
laptops.
</P>
<P>
   Logitech is developing an ergonomically-correct keyboard
codenamed the Huxley that will have full-sized keys but will be at
least two inches smaller overall than most conventional keyboards.
But Swan and other representatives of high-technologies companies
said that the rush to reduce the size of sophisticated, electronic
devices has its own limits, and most of them have less to do with
technology than with the anatomy of consumer's bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keyboards can only be so small,'' said Swan. ``There are a lot
of tiny keyboards on laptops and everything else that are just too
small and too close and are in an arrangement that is unfamiliar
that causes the usability to suffer quite a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucking the trend, Logitech has been making computer-pointing
devices, like mice, joy sticks and track balls, larger and larger
to fit more people's hands more comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   At the Smart Technologies booth at PC Expo, the Canadian-based
company that builds large electronic projection boards, a new
smaller board was featured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer was looking for it,'' said Tabitha Beaton, a
company spokeswoman in the company's home office in Calgary.
``eople said they were working in smaller groups.''
</P>
<P>
   So Smart Technologies created a 38-inch Smart Board that is 20
inches smaller than its standard board. Any smaller, she said with
a chuckle, and the board would not be much better than a
commonplace 17-inch computer monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Many phone service booths at the Expo offered some of the
smallest cellular phones on the market. Two the telephones _ the
Motorola Star Tac and the Ericsson CF 788 _ weigh only a few ounces
and are swallowed up in an average-sized palm.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to mobile communications and cell phones, the
size and weight of these devices for professionals becomes
important,'' said Michael J. Wieser, a commercial banker who
co-founded Cel-Pro Associates, a New York-based cellular phone
business. ``They need something that they can throw into their suit
pockets or into their purse.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding one the tiny telephones to his face, Wieser wondered
aloud how smaller the telephones can get. ``If they get any smaller
the mouth piece is not going to reach your mouth,'' he said. ``The
next thing is going to be the Dick Tracy wristwatch phone.''
Cellular telephone manufacturers said Wieser could not be more
correct.
</P>
<P>
   Sony, a veteran at the miniturization game but a relative
newcomer to the computer industry, unveiled its Vaio 505 series
computer notebooks. Measuring an inch thick when closed and
weighing three pounds, the 505 Superslim is being billed by Sony as
the smallest, fully functional notebook. Its introduction at the PC
Expo was greeted with a chorus of ohhs and ahhs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's first reaction is not to look at all of this great
technology,'' Matthew J. Smith, the senior marketing manager for PC
products marketing for Sony said of first impressions of the
Superslim notebooks which go on sale next month. ``It's just,
`Wow,' a purely emotional response.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
