<HEADER>
A3516 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAD-DAY-LADN     06-17 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAD-DAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS, DAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Like father, like son.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of actor/director James Keach, it's an ongoing
challenge to follow in his father's footsteps. Like his dad, Stacy
Keach Sr., the youngest member of the theatrical Keach clan has
been an actor, director and producer, and now he's pursuing another
aspect of the senior Keach's career: teaching.
</P>
<P>
   While his father was a speech and theater arts professor at
Northwestern, (before directing at the Pasadena Playhouse, signing
with Universal and starting his own production company), James will
make his teaching debut this fall at USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I attended Northwestern and Yale, but since my son, Kalen, is
a USC student, it's an obvious choice,'' he explained during a chat
at the June 9 Father's Day Council Awards at the Beverly Hilton.
Keach, 50; his parents, Mary and Stacy Keach Sr. of Sherman Oaks;
his wife, Jane Seymour (star of ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman''); and
their six children were all at the event, at which James was
honored as a Father of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   With that much family, posing for pictures and conducting
interviews was pandemonium. Two-year-old twins Kristopher and John
were crying, and each of the other four children _ Kalen, 21;
Jenni, 18; Katie, 16; and Sean, 12 _ took turns at entertaining
them.
</P>
<P>
   Once settled down, with pictures out of the way, James continued
talking about his wonderful family. ``Kalen, is not only on the
dean's list but has already written a screenplay. And guess who
he's asked to direct it?''
</P>
<P>
   Of daughter Katie, he said, ``She wrote me a letter, saying I'm
always there for her. And my stepdaughter Jenni handed me a letter
of congratulations. She wrote `Thank you ... It's a comfort to be
around someone so full of love.' And Sean won a sports award at
school and gave me his trophy for my desk.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about Father's Day honors.
</P>
<P>
   According to Katie, ``We usually go out to lunch or brunch on
Father's Day and he orders roast chicken.'' But son Kalen says he
wants to take his dad fly fishing as his Father's Day gift.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing is a Keach family tradition, according to Stacy Sr.
``There were plenty of Father's Day barbecues when James and his
brother, Stacy (star of `Mike Hammer'), were growing up, but we
often went fishing, even if it was only to the fish pond at the
Sportsmen's Lodge in Studio City. I remember the first time I took
James there and he caught a fish. At first he was excited, but then
he cried (because the fish died). But he got over it and turned out
to be a skilled fisherman.''
</P>
<P>
   James recalls those days, too. ``Dad and I would do fun things,
not always on the actual Father's Day. Sometimes he'd let me play
hooky from school and take me fishing or on the set of a film he
was working on. And now I try to do those things with my
children,'' he comments.
</P>
<P>
   For James, Father's Day isn't so much about gifts for Dad as
much as recalling those from Dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important gift my father ever gave me was to focus on
the brighter side of life and never be indifferent or turn your
back on people in need. I try to do that with my kids and teach
them the same values. After all, the bottom line in life is about
what you do for your family, both biological and extended. And
that's what God will be asking ... not about my movie grosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad also taught me to be passionate and to follow your dreams.
When I was little he'd tuck me in at night and say, `Hitch your
wagon to a star.'''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Keach did follow his dreams, and his dad, now 84, is
proud. According to Stacy Sr., ``Dads want love more than anything,
although they treasure all the handmade gifts and cards their
children make when they're small. Love and respect, that's the best
... but the Italian shirt my son gave me this year _ we celebrated
a week early _ is great, too,'' he said with a chuckle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
