<HEADLINE>
BUGS BUNNY DANGLES A CLASSIC CARROT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bugs as Bogey? Daffy as Sam? Tweety as Peter
Lorre?
</P>
<P>
   Nyaaaahh, what's up, Doc?
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Carrotblanca,'' an enjoyable Looney Tunes
reinterpretation of the war-time classic ``Casablanca,'' that will
debut on television Saturday and Sunday as part of the Cartoon
Network's annual Bugs Bunny marathon.
</P>
<P>
   The 8.5-minute ``Carrotblanca'' was created in 1995 and paired
with box-office bust ``The Great Panda Adventure'' in theaters. It
since has been available on home video but never shown on TV, said
Cartoon Network spokesman Paul Siefken.
</P>
<P>
   Like its great 1950s predecessors, the cartoon features several
delightful little in-jokes for the observant, such as a sign
advertising a show by ``Eleanor Roosevelt's All-Girl Revue'' and
Bugs' carrot-juice bender.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, in the fateful airport scene, the intercom
announces the plane's destinations, including ``Cucamonga,'' or
more accurately ``Cuuuuuu-Caaaa-Monn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
