<HEADLINE>
USE OF NEW INGREDIENTS GIVES CLASSIC 1960 COOKBOOK A TIMELY UPDATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a good idea then and an even better idea now.
</P>
<P>
   When ``The Elegant but Easy Cookbook'' by Marian Burros and Lois
Levine was published in 1960, it set the standard for the
time-strapped hostess. But 38 years and 500,000 copies later, the
authors decided that the book needed a face lift _ and a diet.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the loads of cream, butter and good old American
cheese and the grated stuff in a green can, ``The New Elegant but
Easy Cookbook'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster) takes advantage of the plethora
of products now in the supermarkets, from bok choy to fresh oregano
to light sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   Some dishes, although they satisfied our fascination with
foreign food, were often so far from their source that they could
be unrecognizable. The boeuf bourguignon in the original book
includes tapioca, sugar, canned mushrooms, canned potatoes and (!)
water chestnuts. The new version uses low-sodium beef stock, fresh
white cremini or portobello mushrooms, low-sodium canned Italian
tomatoes and burgundy wine.
</P>
<P>
   Some things are gone: Jell-O salads, for instance. Although much
loved in the South, they were deemed passe by the authors. Oh,
well. We'll console ourselves with the greens with pears and
gorgonzola vinaigrette, the chicken and potatoes with bleu cheese
dressing, and the Armenian vegetable salad.
</P>
<P>
   ARMENIAN VEGETABLE SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   1 pound white mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds green beans, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   7 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   4 large red bell peppers, roasted and julienned, see Note
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches green onions, white and most of the green part, finely
sliced
</P>
<P>
   20 large or 30 small Italian, Greek or French olives, pitted
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Note: To roast peppers, preheat broiler. Wash peppers, place on
a cookie sheet and broil about 2-3 inches from the source of heat,
turning with tongs until skins blister and char all over, 15-20
minutes. As each pepper is ready, place in a large plastic bag and
keep bag closed for about 10 minutes; steaming will facilitate
removal of the skin. Remove peppers from bag; the skins should peel
off easily. After peeling, cut peppers in half, remove seeds and
julienne. Refrigerate if not making salad immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Wash and trim mushrooms. Depending on their size, leave whole,
halved or quartered. Steam over hot water for about 5 minutes,
until tender. Set aside. Steam green beans about 7 minutes,
depending on size. Drain and halve or cut into thirds, depending on
size. Cover and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk oil, vinegar and mustard together and pour over mushrooms,
peppers, green onions and olives; cover and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, stir green beans into rest of the salad. Season with
salt and pepper. Don't stir green beans into the dressing more than
30 minutes in advance of serving, because the acid will turn them
gray-green.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 113 calories, 8 grams fat, 11
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 0 milligrams cholesterol, 121
milligrams sodium, 61 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN AND GOLD SQUASH
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound zucchini, coarsely grated
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound yellow summer squash, coarsely grated
</P>
<P>
   1 medium (8 ounces) onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh oregano OR 1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 whole egg
</P>
<P>
   3 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup low-fat or nonfat buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded sharp white Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup whole wheat bread crumbs, optional
</P>
<P>
   Note: This dish can be made a day in advance and refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   Place grated squash in kitchen towel and twist towel to squeeze
out the liquid. You will have to do this in batches.
</P>
<P>
   Saute onion in hot oil in nonstick pan until it is hot and
beginning to brown. In large bowl, combine onion with parsley,
oregano, salt, pepper and squash. Slightly beat egg and whites and
stir in. Stir in buttermilk and cheese, and bread crumbs if using.
Spoon mixture into a buttered 1 1/2-quart casserole, cover and
refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, remove casserole from the refrigerator and let sit at
room temperature about 30 minutes. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
Bake casserole for about 45 minutes, or until mixture is bubbly.
Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 179 calories, 10 grams fat, 13
grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 56 milligrams cholesterol,
214 milligrams sodium, 50 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
