<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON THREATENS TO VETO BILL WITH TAX-FREE EDUCATION ACCOUNTS
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prospects for substantive education reform this
year faded Wednesday as President Clinton and congressional
Republicans hardened their opposition to each other's competing
proposals to fix American education.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton delivered a letter to House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
R-Ga., Wednesday threatening to veto legislation sponsored by Sen.
Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., that would establish tax-free savings
accounts for primary and secondary education. The House is expected
to vote final passage of the measure Thursday, and the Senate is
likely to vote next week.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's legislation would allow parents, guardians and even
corporations and unions to set aside up to $2,000 per year in
tax-free savings accounts. Money from the accounts could be used to
finance public school expenses such as books, computers and tutors,
or private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials estimate that 70 percent of the children
who set up and used the accounts would be in the public school
system. But because parents with children in private schools would
be expected to use them more, half the money set aside in the
accounts would be spent in private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts ``would weaken public education and short-change
our children,'' Clinton said in his letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the House of Representatives passes this bill, the American
people will have the right to say, 'Thanks for nothing,' ``
Education Secretary Richard Riley said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in the House will offer a competing proposal that
would provide tax credits to the purchasers of school construction
bonds, subsidizing about $22 billion in bonds that could be used to
pay for school repairs.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., signaled Wednesday
that Democrats wouldn't seek a compromise involving Coverdell's
legislation and any of the president's education initiatives _ all
of which have been stymied by the Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be happy to compromise, but there is no room for
compromise,'' said Gephardt, blaming Republicans for holding up the
administration's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell said his proposal already includes some Democratic
initiatives, such as making state prepaid tuition programs tax-free
and extending $5,250 worth of tax exemptions for employer sponsored
tuition assistance for employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is as close to a compromise as (Clinton) is going
to see,'' Coverdell said. As for Clinton's school rebuilding
program and his plan to spend $20.8 billion over 10 years to reduce
class sizes to 18 pupils per teacher, Coverdell said, ``he spends
money that isn't here.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the White House on Wednesday, Clinton announced
$40 million in new grants to fund after-school programs at 315
rural and urban schools. The programs are designed to keep the
children of working parents in school between the hours of 3 p.m.
and 6 p.m., when many are inclined to get into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``For millions of Americans, 'Home Alone' is not a funny movie;
it is a serious risk that children and parents undertake every day
all across this country,'' said Clinton, calling on Congress to
expand funding for the grants to reach up to 500,000 more children.
``These grants will give now thousands more children a safe place
to go before and after school and good things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
