<HEADER>
A3554 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-PERSONAL-POLLS-AR     06-17 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PERSONAL-POLLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL POLLS HELP THE NOSEY SATE CURIOSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By PAMELA LI CALZI O'CONNELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cynthia Lewis, it is fair to say, is an extremely curious
person. In the past five months, she has conducted 44 opinion polls
on questions ranging from the political (``Should President Clinton
be impeached?'') to the personal (``Which smell do you prefer in a
lover?'') to the philosophical (``How often do you behave according
to your ideals?''). So far her polls have prompted more than 2,000
responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being able to quench my curiosity about any topic under
the sun,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewis, a senior at Hood College in Maryland, is a regular
participant on a Web site called Survey Central, which lets her
create online polls on any subject she desires
(www.apocalypse.org/bill/survey). The site handles all coding and
tabulation and does things like breaking down answers by sex and
age group. A bulletin-board discussion accompanies each poll.
</P>
<P>
   Survey Central is one of a growing number of sites that allow
Web users to employ some of the tools _ albeit without many of the
statistical methods or the validity of professional polls. Though
it is common to come across personal home pages offering quizzes or
surveys, sites like Survey Central, Open Debate
(www.opendebate.com) and the Internet Voice (www.virtua.com/voice)
seek to centralize and formalize user-created polls.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, they may also give them an aura of legitimacy by
providing greater exposure and snappy interfaces. Visitors remain
anonymous, although these sites typically ask users to register to
insure that they vote only once.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are tired of being part of a mass-media audience, mere
fish in the Nielsen and Arbitron oceans, of seeing public opinion
represented in national polls in which they're never asked to
participate,'' said James Beniger, a professor at the Annenberg
School for Communication at the University of Southern California
and past president of the American Association for Public Opinion
Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the technological capabilities inherent in the Internet
to monitor, store, tabulate and calculate, the idea of every man as
his own pollster could hardly come as a surprise. There's an
empowerment aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Beniger's analysis aptly describes Andy Lee, founder of Open
Debate and a computer science Ph.D. student doing research on
artificial intelligence. Lee said he felt alienated, even betrayed,
by current modes of opinion polling. ``Polls are not conducted in
the public interest,'' he said. ``Many polls are conducted by
political offices, each with its own agenda. To me, the ideal poll
is taken in an open forum after everyone has a chance to discuss
the issue with one another.''
</P>
<P>
   As its name suggests, Open Debate combines discussion and
voting. Lee's idea is to give voters as much information as
possible about the person who framed the poll so they can discern
any bias, and let voters comment at length about the poll itself.
To that end, Open Debate asks users to fill out a profile before
they can vote or create polls. Besides age, sex, location and
occupation, the profile seeks information on a user's religious,
political and philosophical preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Survey Central, which does not seek advertising, nor
Open Debate, which does, censors polls that might be considered
offensive or merely inane. Bill Marrs, creator of Survey Central
and a software developer, said voters tended to give such polls
``the treatment they deserve.'' His site lets users vote on the
quality of individual polls. ``This has turned out to be a highly
effective characteristic of the site,'' Marrs said.
</P>
<P>
   User-created polls cover an enormously wide range of topics,
with an accent on the personal. Ms. Lewis said she especially
enjoyed ``surveys which ask questions people don't normally find
socially appropriate or about topics which people find difficult to
talk about, like suicide or alcoholism. The measure of anonymity
that the Net provides allows users to be more forthright and honest
than they would be if asked the same questions in real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in viewing all the polls Ms. Lewis has created
on Survey Central must register first and then search by her user
name, elijahblue. For the record, voters in her polls preferred
their lovers' ``natural scent'' by a wide margin over ``no odor''
and ``perfume/cologne.'' Most do not think that Clinton should be
impeached, nor do they think that it is easy to live up to one's
ideals, two findings that are perhaps related.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the create-your-own-poll sites have attracted modest
audiences. Open Debate has more than 500 registered users and
Survey Central nearly 250. Anywhere from 20 to 50 new polls are
typically created on each site each week. The founders of these
sites shy away from making grandiose claims about the value of
their polls and from projecting their results onto the larger
population.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gisselbrecht, a research technician studying muscle
development in fruit flies, has created about 15 polls on Survey
Central, including ``How do you feel about animal testing?'' and
``Is there a particular song that gets stuck in your head?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Survey Central is a way to poll a certain well-defined
group,'' Gisselbrecht said. ``This is otherwise a very difficult
thing to do. And as an unexpected fringe benefit, it's quite a nice
little community.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls of self-selected audiences appear to be on the rise, and
not just on the Web. Beniger of the University of Southern
California said that while ``amateur Web polls are completely
unscientific,'' they are ``no worse than the so-called call-in
polls perpetrated by many television and radio stations or the
polls by printed ballots published in many magazines and
newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike these, professional polls select their audiences using
statistics that allow the survey results to be representative of
the larger population.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there may well be something that public-opinion
researchers can learn from sites like Survey Central. For instance,
professional polls of the general population ``rarely if ever ask
users to rate them,'' Beniger said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he was optimistic that such sites might provide a
window into what topics people were really interested in, as
opposed to those topics selected by professionals and their
commercial or political sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, create-your-own poll sites seem to be
functioning as a salve for those, like Gisselbrecht, are
``tormented by curiosity.'' And unlike professional pollsters,
Gisselbrecht said, ``I've never tried to use the results to
convince anyone of anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
