<HEADER>
A3586 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GENEALOGY-2TAKES-     06-17 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GENEALOGY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 CD-ROMs TO ENRICH A FAMILY'S PRESENT WITH ITS PAST  
 (Circuits)  
 (bl)  
 By SHELLY FREIERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service     &HT;    I was at a big family party. Richard, one of my older brothers,
leaned toward me and said quietly, ``OK, the brunette in the red
blouse talking to cousin Harold _ one of Mattie's daughters,
right?'' ``I think so,'' I answered. ``The one with the twins,
right?'' We wanted to ask our mother but could not find her.
 &HT;    So we did the next best thing. We searched our family tree:
three legal-size pages, stapled in one corner and crammed with
eight decades' worth of Levines. First, we found Aunt Sarah and
then Mattie, her four daughters and their eight children. By
process of elimination _ ``See, those are the twins, and they have
one older sister'' _ we settled on Rhona as our mystery cousin. My
mother appeared and confirmed our detective work with a roll of her
eyes.
 &HT;    I made the first family tree in 1984. Harry Levine, my family
patriarch, arrived in New York from what was then Bielsk, Poland,
in 1912, following his two sons, the oldest of 10 children. Four
more children came over before World War I, but their mother,
Pauline, struggled through the war in Europe and did not arrive in
America with the four youngest children until 1920.
 &HT;    When I set about tracing the descendants of Harry and Pauline, I
did it by painstakingly figuring out the spacing on a word
processor. Richard tackled the next one two years ago, this time
using a chart-drawing program on a PC. But now, with several new
children in the sixth generation pushing our family total past 250,
it seems a good time to harness the power of a CD-ROM.
 &HT;    Family tree software is more than a tool to draw family trees.
These programs are supercharged versions of keepsake albums and
family bibles _ a place to record the history of a family, with
births, marriages, deaths and stories. In addition, the CD-ROMs
organize a database for information like occupations, addresses and
medical histories, all of which can be printed in digital albums
along with scanned photographs.
 &HT;    The software also offers lessons in genealogy, historic
databases and links to Internet sites, and some can even
incorporate pieces of audio or video.
 &HT;    You will probably never use all the features on any given
program. All my own extended family needs is a basic family tree
and an updated mailing list. But these CD-ROMs will be useful for
people who are just starting out on a genealogical search.
 &HT;    When I confessed to Mattie (my first cousin once removed) that I
sometimes got her daughters mixed up, she said she could not always
remember my nieces' names. No matter. We chatted about the next
family gathering, and I made a note to add her newest grandchild to
the family tree.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SOME GENEALOGY PROGRAMS
 &HT;    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Serious Tool For Searches
</P>
<P>
   ULTIMATE FAMILY TREE PREMIERE  &QL; 
(Palladium Interactive; $59.95; Windows 3.1 and 95.)
</P>
<P>
   Ultimate Family Tree, like all the family tree programs, begins
with one person, whose name, sex, birth, death and significant
events, like date of marriage, are entered into a template. The
next individual is connected to that person as a spouse, parent,
sibling or child, and they are connected to other relatives, and so
on, until a family tree is built.
</P>
<P>
   For these evaluations, I entered the family of Morris Levine,
Harry and Pauline's third child and my maternal grandfather, into
each program. From Morris, who was born in 1890 and died in 1962,
to Aliya, born in Texas in December 1997 and adopted into our
family in February, there is a thread linking 76 people.
</P>
<P>
   Genealogy forms the underlying structure of all family tree
software. For users who plan to conduct a rigorous genealogical
search for ancestors and lost relatives, Ultimate Family Tree is
the best choice. Its structure, vocabulary and tutorials are
closely aligned with formal genealogy.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it lets users create an extensive database of
records, like all the programs, but also allows them to rate the
facts for historical accuracy, based on the types of sources and
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimate contains tutorials on locating original records and
tracing immigrant ancestors and the ability to include audio and
video files. Like most other family tree programs, it has a Social
Security death index that can be searched for birth and death dates
of relatives and the states in which the numbers were issued. In a
genealogical search, knowing where a relative was born may lead to
other kin.
</P>
<P>
   Once a family database is complete, it can be converted into a
family tree or several kinds of reports. For example, Ultimate will
produce a tree showing the descendants of Morris Levine or all of
my ancestors, or a list of how all of my kin are connected to me.
</P>
<P>
   This CD-ROM also has a very valuable feature for ancestor
hunters looking for family before Ellis Island: a form letter,
addressed to the appropriate authorities in the appropriate foreign
language to request records in non-English-speaking countries like
Germany, France, Sweden and Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimate Family Tree may be set up for detailed genealogy
research, but it is inflexible when it comes to describing
relationships in contemporary extended families. Since genealogy is
defined by direct bloodlines, it is impossible to include some
relatives in a family tree. For example, my nephew Gabriel Pagano
was entered into the database as the son of my sister-in law, but
because he is not a blood relative, he didn't appear on a tree
showing the descendants of Morris Levine. The only way to include
him in the family tree was by cheating: I re-entered him, using his
last name but listing him as my brother's son, a blood relative.
</P>
<P>
   In another quirk of the program, an attempt to list two men or
two women as spouses calls up dialogue boxes that read in part: ``A
female has been linked to the father role.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Flexible System That Is Easy to Use
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY HERITAGE DELUXE
</P>
<P>
   (Mindscape; $19.99; Windows 95 and NT.)
</P>
<P>
   Of the family-tree programs reviewed here, Family Heritage
Deluxe stands out for its uncomplicated interface and ease of use.
The template for entering information about an individual is
designed for simple navigation between a person and his or her
closest relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The names of a person's parents, spouse and children appear on
the screen on tabs around the box that forms the basic record, so
the records of these relatives can be found quickly.
</P>
<P>
   As with other programs, users choose a person as the starting
point for trees or records. The information can be configured in
several forms, starting with the primary individual: as family
trees or reports on descendants by generation or on direct
relationships among individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The trees can be constructed in vertical or horizontal layouts,
and some of the programs offer fan charts that show a primary
individual's ancestors in concentric circles. Like the other
programs, Family Heritage can generate calendars, mailing lists and
albums. Users choose the information to include in a tree, calendar
or report, including pictures and notations.
</P>
<P>
   Other appealing interface features in Family Heritage are the
ability to enter a person's spouse and children in one list. Most
family tree software requires users to return to the parent's basic
record to add another child. This CD-ROM lets users fully integrate
children who are not blood relatives in a family tree: I included
my nephew Gabriel by using an option to link him to my brother.
</P>
<P>
   Entering same-sex spouses does not prompt a dialogue box with
Family Heritage, and the program is more contemporary in its
treatment of spouses. Choices in its records qualify ``spouses'' as
married, partner, common law or friend, and options for the end of
a relationship include separated and estranged. But, strangely,
``dead'' is not a choice, so the user needs to choose ``other'' for
a deceased spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Family Heritage, which was purchased by Mindscape in March, is
scheduled to be released in a new version, Family Tree Creator
Deluxe, in September.
</P>
<P>
   I tried one of its current research accessories, a history of
surnames. I looked up Levine, and the excerpt explains the
derivation of the name and mentions the author Primo Levi, whose
name is one of the many spelling variations of Levine. The name is
also ranked 710th in popularity in the Social Security index.
However, a sort of statistical disclaimer points out that since the
index is sorted by only the first five letters of a name, it may
not be accurate: if the Levins and Levinsons were dropped from the
count, we might plummet in popularity to 823th place.
</P>
<P>
   2 Family-Tree Aids Add Useful Options to Basic Approach &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GENERATIONS DELUXE
</P>
<P>
   (Sierra Home; $49.95; Windows 3.1 and 95.)
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY TREE MAKER DELUXE EDITION 3
</P>
<P>
   (Broderbund; $82; Windows 3.1 and 95; Macintosh Power Mac.)
</P>
<P>
   Generations Deluxe and Family Tree Maker Deluxe Edition 3 are
basic programs with similar templates for entering data and share
most of the features of Family Heritage Deluxe and Ultimate Family
Tree.
</P>
<P>
   Generations has a slightly rigid format: it identifies each
family member as half of a married couple in the basic record
screen. And while it allows a user to customize the events to list
for an individual, that new format for events is then included on
everyone's basic record. So, listing immigration and naturalization
as events for my grandfather Morris locked me into those topics for
his great-grandchildren, too.
</P>
<P>
   The interface in Generations offers users a chance to
illustrate, in different colors, the status of children in a
family. I was able to circle the names of my twin cousins in yellow
so they stood out among their four siblings.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROM also has an ancestor overview feature on the tool bar
that opens a box on the screen showing ancestral relationships for
a given individual: that offers a quick look at a family and an
easy navigation shortcut to a distant great-grandparent.
</P>
<P>
   Generations allows users to pass along the historical data,
family trees and reports they have compiled to other family members
by copying the information to disks. Recipients can see the
information on their computers, with read-only access.
</P>
<P>
   Family Tree Maker also has a straightforward and somewhat rigid
interface, with paired husband-wife records on a family page and
tabs connecting parents and children. Navigation is cumbersome: to
get from one sibling to another, you have to click back up to the
parent level.
</P>
<P>
   Events listings do not include pull-down menus of topics like
baptisms, bar mitzvahs or education, so information other than
addresses and medical or adoption histories is entered in a blank
``facts'' table.
</P>
<P>
   Users can include sound and images in albums they create using
Family Tree Maker Deluxe. Two extensive databases are also
included.
</P>
<P>
   The first, called World Family Tree, is a collection of 27,000
family trees in a set of five CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   The second is an index of 130 million names from various
historical databases, including World Family Tree and Social
Security, and marriage and land records. Sometimes in genealogical
searches, finding an exact date or the name of a missing ancestor
can help fill in a branch of a family.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
