<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3596 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-GAMES-NY     06-17 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPLAYING, OR TWISTING, BATTLE OF GETTYSBURG 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two questions about the past. One is, What happened?
The other is, What could have happened?
</P>
<P>
   History answers the first. Historical simulations answer the
second. If different decisions had been made, if different actors
had been on the stage, would it all have turned out another way? Or
were insurmountable forces guiding the course of events?
</P>
<P>
   Answering these questions is a good game. If you're in academia,
it's called counterfactual history. If you're browsing through an
electronics boutique, it's called Sid Meier's Gettysburg. Meier, a
longtime game designer who created landmark computer simulations
like Civilization and Railroad Baron, has ventured into Ken Burns
territory this time and made one of our national legends into a
scenario machine.
</P>
<P>
   In the game, there are three modes of historical authenticity:
Historical, Mixed and Random. If you play in Historical mode and
make the same decisions as the Civil War commanders, you will
re-enact the Battle of Gettysburg. If you play in Random mode, the
game's interlocking scenarios may diverge radically from the events
of July 1863. They may bear no resemblance to any historical event.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the reshuffling of circumstances generates
new ways to replay history. Do it differently. Do it from the other
side. See what might have happened. Or why things didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come in with an agenda sometimes and say, `This is my
chance to do it the way it should have been done,' '' Meier said.
``And as they play the game, what we're trying to do is show them a
little more about what was really involved _ how battles actually
work. I know in my reading it's hard to imagine being in a
situation where there's so much going on. Decisions have to be made
quickly. You have to react to new information. Some things you can
only appreciate by actually being there and doing them. Being a
commander in a battle is one of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to read about weapons, tactics and terrain. It's
another to call in reinforcements and have them arrive too late, or
to learn that an artillery unit can ``retreat by recoil,'' moving a
few yards back after every round, or that even severely outnumbered
men, if positioned on the crest of a hill or hidden among trees,
can prevail over a larger force.
</P>
<P>
   In the analog world, only war buffs find this stuff interesting.
In a computer game, the footnotes come to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think of the Civil War as a bunch of guys standing
on a battlefield shooting at each other,'' Meier said. ``But there
were really some pretty powerful psychological factors that come
into play if you're a soldier in battle. If you create a formation
where you have your units supporting each other, one next to the
other, that's a powerful formation because psychologically, a
soldier was much more likely to stay on the battlefield if he had
his friends next to him. On the other hand, if you're able to bring
some of your troops on the flank of the enemy where you can shoot
at them and they can't shoot at you, psychologically that's a very
bad situation for the other side. So they will rout and leave the
field, even though they have not taken a lot of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you start to understand in playing the game that it's not
about who can shoot the fastest or things like that. There are some
interesting psychological aspects to battle that you as a commander
can control and affect.''
</P>
<P>
   If you bind all these elements with beautiful graphics and an
easy-to-use interface, you have a great game. The question is, What
is the difference between a historical simulation and history?
</P>
<P>
   In a simulation, historical accuracy is just another parameter,
like volume, brightness and contrast. On one side of the dial is
the kind of truth you find in clocks and motors and chemistry
experiments. On the other is the kind of truth you find in novels.
</P>
<P>
   In between, you have something that looks real, that feels
testable and that seems capable of making predictions. This is the
sort of model that multinational corporations and government
agencies use to predict the future.
</P>
<P>
   If you're an oil company or the Defense Department and you want
to predict the future, it makes sense to build a scenario machine
that generates every possible outcome, because the future is still
in flux. A game is useful in this context because no one knows how
it ends.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens when you start applying those algorithms to the
past? What happens if simulations become our way of understanding
what has already occurred? When educators realize that children
will learn more about Gettysburg from Sid Meier's software than
from a textbook chapter and chalk-and-board lecture, what then?
</P>
<P>
   What happens when history becomes a game?
</P>
<P>
   A book is a tool. A map is a tool. Games can be a tool. But they
are a curious sort of tool because if they're well designed, they
become ends in themselves. They substitute for the things they're
meant to represent. The map becomes the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Because you, the player, are making decisions, the outcome feels
like a consequence of your actions. And it is _ but only within the
confines of the game. All models make assumptions. But because a
computer simulation generates so many solutions, its assumptions
are difficult to discern. You have to play it 40 different ways
before you know what the model makers take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as simple as pointing to a passage in a textbook and
saying, No, that's not right and this is why. In a simulation, the
past may seem more immediate, more meaningful and more clear. But
the history behind it is complex and opaque. History turns into
something like a computerized car _ simple to use and impossible to
fix.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive technicians are listed in the phone book. But who are
you going to call when your history breaks down?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
