<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3598 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-POETRY-ART-NYT &LR;      06-17 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-POETRY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOFING OFF AND CALLING IT POETRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget solitaire. The new Electromagnetic Poetry Kit is a much
better and more creative way to kill time at work, allowing you to
get in touch with your inner E.E. Cummings. It is almost as easy to
install as setting up its analog cousin, which adorns countless
refrigerators with movable magnetic words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an obvious spinoff,'' said Dave Kapell, who invented
the original Poetry Kit, which has become an $8 million enterprise,
in 1993 when he was a songwriter suffering a bout of writer's
block. Back then, he wrote words on slips of paper and laid them
out on a cookie sheet. When a sneeze knocked the words out of
order, inspiration struck.
</P>
<P>
   Two million kits later, Kapell, who is 36 and lives in
Minneapolis, is hoping to dominate what he calls another ``temple
of the household'': the desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   The advantages of the digital version of the kit are clear:
Users can toss in handfuls of words from 30 word lists, allowing
them to merge such disparate interests as golf, legalese,
college-speak and even words in French, Spanish and German.
</P>
<P>
   Digital poets grab the desired word as it floats by at an
adjustable speed, adding a touch of surrealism to the poetic
process. The background can be changed, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in love, you can make a love poem,'' Kapell said.
``Or if you're morose, you can add death words.'' Or you can fuse
the two, and then add the words that have to do with golf.
</P>
<P>
   Another improvement over the kitchen-based version: Poets can
print out their creations or turn them into screen savers.
</P>
<P>
   The Electromagnetic Poetry Kit can be downloaded from the Web
(www.emagoe.com) for $25; there's also a free 30-day trial version
available. The software can also be ordered from (800) 370-7697 for
$29.95.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence that his product stimulates creativity, Kapell
points to a recent discovery by one of his employees, a fan of the
pop singer Madonna, who noticed that the words in one of her new
songs looked awfully familiar. Madonna's publicist denied that she
had used one of the kits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't trying to do anything about it,'' Kapell said. ``We
just wanted to show that the tool was used for its intended
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapell himself has always needed a jump-start when it comes to
free verse. ``Poetry does not come naturally to me,'' he said.
``The boiled-down-to-its-essence kind of writing is something I
need to trick myself into.''
</P>
<P>
   But he finds it easy to come up with words for the kit. ``I'm
always writing down words on the back of my hand, words that are
evocative, that are just fun to say. Sometimes they don't have good
connotations, like melanoma, sausage, bruise.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't worry about causing a decline in work-place
productivity. At the office, poetry is a luxury, Kapell said, but
the kit is a sort of public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``People really do have a need for good, strong, potent
language,'' he said. ``People really want to go deeper _ people
want to write and play with words.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
