<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NEWS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (af)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you missed Tuesday's live birth on the Web, you're not alone.
America's Health Network, a cable television network for medicine
based in Orlando, Fla., said that there were 10 million hits and
that 50,000 people got on to watch. Other estimates put the total
viewers at 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Those who did log on saw the birth from the woman's point of
view. One of the network's regular hosts gave play-by-play
commentary as the woman was injected with a hormone to induce labor
and while she sat on a large plastic birthing ball. The coverage
continued through the delivery of a boy weighing 7 pounds 8 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Live birth on the Web? Shocking? Actually, the surprise is that
it hasn't happened earlier, or more often. In fact, the network's
claim to be the first to broadcast a birth live over the Net has
been disputed. A woman in Colorado says she did much the same thing
in February but restricted her viewers to 150 friends and family
members.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is, after all, an exhibitionist's haven. Voyeurs
around the world can watch people brushing their teeth, watering
their plants, getting married and having sex. Childbirth had to
make it to the Web sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the health network said they were showing the birth
to help educate expectant mothers, but there were doubters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of educational material out there,'' said Dr.
Kimberley Mulvihill, an obstetrician and gynecologist who writes
for Thrive Online, a Web-based health and life style magazine. ``I
think this is more of an attention-getting stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   As educational material for first-time mothers, the birth had
limited value. The health network picked a 40-year-old woman for
her history of easy births. (She would only let her first name be
used, to protect her privacy, of course.) The delivery took just
four hours, and the mother's distress was limited to a few groans.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the lesson first-time mothers are to take away _ have
your baby before lunch and kick back the rest of the day _ then
perhaps the spin doctors at America's Health Network know something
the rest of the childbearing world doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps next, a death, as an instructional aid for first
timers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For months, Microsoft has billed Windows 98 as a move toward
software simplicity and automated technical support, but the
company doesn't seem to believe its own claims. In anticipation of
the operating system's arrival on retailers' shelves next week,
Microsoft has increased its technical support staff by 400, to more
than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has been touting Windows 98 features that help
customers diagnose and fix problems without making support calls.
Nonetheless, said Kim Akers, a Windows 98 product manager, ``we
wanted to ensure that if people did run into problems they couldn't
solve themselves, they'd be able to have those addressed quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Beta versions of the new operating system have been in users'
hands in volume since last December, and tkhow many calls for
technical support have already been received. Ms. Akers said that
compared to Windows 95, the number of calls for help with basic
installation has declined ``dramatically.'' Windows 98, she said,
also appears to cause fewer crashes than Windows 95 did.
</P>
<P>
   Typical calls for Windows 98, said Ms. Akers, have to do with
configuration problems, such as setting up a machine to work with a
network. ``Also, people are calling to say they read about a
feature and can't find it, or can't make it work,'' said Ms. Akers.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it has also improved its Web-based support
area, called Support Online. Windows 98 contains a feature called
WebHelp that connects directly to Support Online.
</P>
<P>
   Technical support calls are free for 90 days after the first
call, and $35 per call thereafter. Support on the Microsoft Web
site is always free, said Ms. Akers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom regarding women and their Internet habits
has them logging on to shop and schmooze. But a paper to be
released by Vanderbilt University's Project 2000, an electronic
commerce program at the Owen Graduate School of Management,
questions those and other assumptions about what women do online.
</P>
<P>
   The report's authors examined a handful of existing studies,
looking for consistent support of several widespread beliefs: Women
go on the Net seeking relationships; women are uncomfortable with
technology; women love to shop, and are drawn to the Web by
cosmetics and clothing, and women don't use online financial
services or products.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found little data in the surveys to support such
stereotypes. ``Although there has been some corroborating research
that indicates that women are interested in relationship aspects of
the online experience,'' wrote the authors, ``there is little in
existing studies to suggest that relationships are as important as
popular belief holds.''
</P>
<P>
   The 24-hour convenience of the Net, on the other hand, appears
to be one of the Internet's main draws for women. ``Women said they
enjoyed shopping but more because of the convenience and lack of
sales pressure than because they like makeup,'' said Emily Lyons, a
recent graduate of Vanderbilt's Owen School of Management and one
of the paper's authors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The paper, titled ``Conventional Wisdoms about Women and
Internet Use: Refuting Traditional Perceptions,'' was written for
iVillage, a commercial site targeted at women and a Project 2000
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   The Vanderbilt research paper also offers recommendations to
online retailers about how best to target women. ``It opens
interesting questions on them,'' said Katie Hawfield, the paper's
other author. ``Perhaps some of the large shopping sites should be
built around a convenience model.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper is one in a series of reports that researchers at
Vanderbilt are doing on the larger issue of diversity on the
Internet. It will be posted Friday on
http://www2000.ogsm.vanderbilt.edu/. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The satellite malfunction that left most of the nation's pagers
useless for more than a day earlier this month inspired a group at
the University of Southern California to examine people's
relationship to a device seldom studied as a social phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which polled people's reactions to being deprived of
their pagers for a day, put numbers to something many have only
suspected: for many people, pagers are far more than a convenience.
They are a vital element of one's day.
</P>
<P>
   The USC study was based on a random telephone survey of 751
households in the Greater Los Angeles area. Of the 250 survey
respondents who reported using pagers, 63 percent said the device
was essential to their work, and 83 percent said that pagers made
their lives easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were suprised by how important a role the pager now plays
in people's lives, both in the household and in the world,'' said
Bill Dutton, a professor at USC's Annenberg School for
Communications. ``Both in the proportion of households that have a
pager, and the number of people who have reorganized their lives
around the pager, so that missing the pager for a day made a big
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutton said his survey clashed with some popular perceptions
about the degree to which a pager is seen as an electronic tether.
``We asked explicitly whether people felt free as a result of not
having their pager for the day. That was true for just 15 to 20
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the respondents said the foul-up had no effect on their
trust in technology. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that the Clinton White House is awash in scandals that
national television networks have ignored, L. Brent Bozell III,
chairman of Media Research Center, a conservative media watchdog
group in Alexandria, Va., this week launched his own news operation
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Bozell said that his Conservative News Service
(www.conservativenews.org) will report news that he believes go
untouched by traditional television news outlets.
</P>
<P>
   According to the press release announcing the formation of new
service, ``The Conservative News Service (CNS) ... will fill the
growing news void left by the establishment media in their chase
for the sensational at the expense of important stories by the
network news media.''
</P>
<P>
   With a staff of four reporters and two editors, the organization
has a three-year budget of $5.46 million, all from private
donations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its own stories, the service carries those by
mainstream media outlets. The Web site also offers visitor bulletin
boards, viewer polls, and links to conservative radio talk show Web
sites around the country. The service is free of charge. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new $49 security system from Securewin for desktop and laptop &QL; 
machines, introduced this week at PC Expo, is an all-in-one
product &QL; 
that restricts access to applications, prevents tampering with
files &QL; 
and blocks children's access to Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   A boot lock feature prevents a stolen computer from being used.
Now all the folks at Securewin need to do is throw a GPS receiver
into the package for tracking it down. &QL; 
 &QL;
