<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-MARTIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN SAGA MAKES ITS WAY INTO THE OLYMPIC CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK FAINARU-WADA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Casey Martin saga is flourishing on the
scared turf of the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Till now, there had been mostly talk from afar: in a courtroom,
then on separate golf tours. But Tuesday, two days before the start
of the 98th U.S. Open, Martin rode the fairways of the Olympic Club
and then addressed the news media about his surprising and
ground-breaking presence.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the game's legends told the very same media, with all due
respect to Martin, that they did not think he should be here as
long as he needed a cart to get around.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a Nike Tour regular, is on the PGA Tour this week for
two reasons. First, because four months ago a court allowed that
the rare circulatory disease in his right leg was cause enough for
him to break tradition and use a golf cart. And second, because he
went out and holed a 25-foot putt to win a five-man playoff in
sectional qualifying for the Open.
</P>
<P>
   These events set up a convergence of Martin and a string of pros
who have questioned whether he and his cart cut into the heart of
the game's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   And so there was Martin, defending his presence and insisting he
has no advantage. Sandwiched around him were the likes of Tom
Watson and Jack Nicklaus, both of whom said, essentially, they like
the kid, hate the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen a few of those players that were outspoken,''
Martin said shortly after playing a practice round with Tiger Woods
and Joel Kribel. ``I'm not going to name names, but they didn't go
out of their way to say hi or anything. At the same time, they
didn't sneer at me either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not going to try to make a big issue out of it and
just try to enjoy the experience. I'm not going to get caught up in
who said what and who is for me and who is against me.''
</P>
<P>
   The general theme from the critics is that they're for Martin,
but against the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tough position the tour has taken, but I think the
tour is right in the sense that the game should be played
walking,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   When Nicklaus was asked about Martin being at the Olympic Club,
he paused for several seconds and then smiled, seemingly somewhat
uncomfortable. Nicklaus was among those who testified against
Martin during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it as it relates to the game of golf,'' Nicklaus
said. ``But I understand the ruling, and from Casey's standpoint I
am delighted for him as an individual. I worry about what its
ramifications are for golf in the future. I mean, you know, is
there somebody else who is injured this week who would like to use
a cart?''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that a regular injury and a disability are two
different animals, Nicklaus said, ``I understand that. But somebody
along the line is going to use (the ruling), I promise you. ...
Someone is going to come in and say, I qualified for the Open but I
sprained my ankle. You are going to have another mess someplace. It
is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, a close friend of Martin, took sort of the middle ground,
saying, ``I don't really like seeing golf carts out there. But he
is one of my good friends and I want to see him out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin tried his best to defuse the whole deal, saying he
respects his critics' opinions, he just doesn't agree with them.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who insist Martin, by virtue of riding rather
than walking, will have a competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I am not at an advantage physically over anybody,''
Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The whole scene hasn't been made any easier by the cart itself.
Martin used a specially-made one-man cart during the qualifying and
had problems, and he had more of the same in practice rounds Monday
and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was finally decided that he would use a basic two-person
cart, which will be allowed only on the fairways. He will stop
about 30 yards short of the greens, at which point a marshal will
take the cart over to the next tee while Martin plays out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am only going to drive on the fairway,'' Martin said. ``I am
not going to be doing curly-cues in the rough to mat it down,
although I'd like to mat it down a bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
