<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOU-DON'T-KNOW-BEANS-     06-17 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOU-DON'T-KNOW-BEANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SIMMERING DISPUTE OVER HOW TO FIX RED BEANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have a friend who courteously disagrees with all this business
of fancy cooking and intricate recipes. ``Why fuss over cooking so
much?'' he asks. ``If you know how to make red beans and corn
bread, that's all you need to know. I could eat them every day.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a point.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to comfort food, red beans are right at the top.
You can cook them soft and creamy, or leave just a little crunch.
They can be spooned over sweet corn bread, or enhanced with fluffy
white rice.
</P>
<P>
   I tend to agree with my friend. A bowl of red beans over corn
bread, with slices of onion and tomato, is a real meal, and if I
had to eat it a couple of times a week, I would survive nicely.
</P>
<P>
   But, do you soak the beans overnight or not? What's the
difference between red beans and pinto beans? If you're fixing red
beans and rice, do you cook the rice in the bean juice, or do you
add the rice later?
</P>
<P>
   And, is it really possible to cook a good bowl of beans without
a ham bone?
</P>
<P>
   There is, it seems, nothing simple about this simple dish.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the answers, it turns out, are purely subjective. There
appears to be no proof that soaking overnight helps the beans cook
up creamier, but don't tell that to the cooks who prefer the
soaking method.
</P>
<P>
   I know soaking isn't supposed to make much difference, but I
still soak mine.
</P>
<P>
   Pinto beans are good, but red beans are really kidney beans, and
they aren't the same. They taste different, and they make a
different gravy. And, just to add to the confusion, there are good
kidney beans, and then there are better kidney beans.
</P>
<P>
   Up at Bayou Boys, a Lewisville food business where Cajun food is
the only commodity, Camellia brand red beans are the only ones the
Cajun cooks use. They've tried other brands, they say, but the
others just don't measure up.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bayou Boys uses Camellia beans in its prepared foods
and sells the dried beans in 1-pound packages. It is the only place
in the Fort Worth-Dallas area I know of that sells Camellia-brand
beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried using other beans, the kind you can get around
here, but they are just not the same quality,'' said Rudy Porche,
chef and co-owner of Porche's Restaurant in Fort Worth. ``We grew
up eating Camellia beans, and you just stay with what you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Porche moved to Fort Worth from Baton Rouge and has been
operating Porche's Creole and Cajun Cafe for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   He soaks his beans overnight and closely watches the amount of
water he uses. ``People do it differently,'' he said. ``Some use a
little water, some use so much it turns out more like red bean
gumbo.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is, he pointed out, not a bad thing, especially if you
have corn bread around to sop it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret to cooking good beans,'' he said, ``is, don't rush
the cooking process. Go real slow. Let them simmer. If you can let
them simmer all day, that's even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana beans and Texas beans came to popularity in different
ways. Dried pinto beans were easy to carry on chuck wagons on the
Texas ranches. They could be stretched by adding peppers and chili
powder, onions and whatever kind of meat you had available.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana red beans gained their popularity in New Orleans,
where they were paired with rice for a customary Monday meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always had them on Mondays,'' Porche said. ``You would
always have a big Sunday dinner, usually ham or something like
that, and you would want to take that ham bone and make something
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to put the ham bone in with the beans and let them
cook all day while the laundry was being done.
</P>
<P>
   Some people believe that red beans cannot be cooked without a
ham bone. They insist that the bone be cracked, so the marrow can
meld with the juices and form a silky gravy.
</P>
<P>
   Others, and I fall into this category, believe that a couple of
good-size smoked hocks and a link or two of spicy smoked sausage
can dress up the beans just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if you are preparing the true New Orleans mixture, fix the
rice and the beans separately. It's a rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Orleans is famous for red beans and rice,'' said Benson
Hayward of L.H. Hayward &AMP; Co., the company that produces Camellia
brand beans. ``New Orleans is where red beans and rice comes from.
It is still a Monday tradition here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayward's company is in Harahan, a suburb of New Orleans. It is
a small, family-owned company with about 20 employees, he said. It
has been in business for 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hayward said the quality of the beans makes them the favorite of
Cajun chefs. ``We look for the upper echelon of quality in the lots
available for purchase. We only buy from certain areas, and we only
buy certain quality. We look for specific moisture content.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Hayward's company does not market its beans
outside southern Louisiana, for the most part. There is one Texas
wholesaler in Sulphur Springs, he said. But Hayward doesn't do
business in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean you can't get good red beans at the local
grocery. You just have to be a little more careful how you cook
them. Camellia-brand beans are good. They cook up faster and
creamier than many other brands, but they can be matched if you
follow Porche's advice.
</P>
<P>
   Cook them slowly. Bring the water to a boil, then back off to a
simmer. Let that simmer continue as long as possible. Two hours is
probably the shortest time; all day is best. Keep them covered with
water, and adjust seasonings to your personal taste.
</P>
<P>
   And, if it makes you feel better, soak them overnight before you
begin cooking.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
