<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-ELS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDING CHAMP ELS HOPES TO GET BACK UP TO PAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It wasn't long before Ernie Els squirmed in his
chair, seeking just the right position where his back could enjoy
some relief.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't look easy and Els had told a news conference he would
probably conclude quickly because of his ailment. He enters this
year's U.S. Open not only as the defending champion, but also as
one of the players trying to overcome a back injury. Sitting
uncomfortably while answering questions, Els couldn't hide the
extent of his problems Tuesday. Nor did he try.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not 100 percent,'' Els said. ``It's not the way you want
to feel playing in a major tournament, but I am defending here this
week. It feels better than it did last Thursday but it's still a
day-to-day thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The last six days couldn't have provided much worse
circumstances for Els. His back started bothering him the evening
before the first day of the Buick Classic in Westchester, N.Y. The
spasms were so bad that he aborted his participation after nine
holes, the first time he ever failed to finish a round. The pain
was most prominent on the left side of his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   One good sign for Els is that the stiffness has subsided a
little more each day since.
</P>
<P>
   But will his back heal quickly enough to allow Els to play his
best golf this week? If it doesn't, Els will focus more on his next
opportunity than his missed one here. If it does, he stands a good
shot of winning his third U.S. Open in the last five years. (He
also won in 1994.)
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we don't play too long of a course, I might be
OK,'' Els said. ``Today, I took my driver out probably four or five
times (during his practice round). I used quite a few 2-irons and
3-irons. You have to put the ball in play and take it from there
and that might work to my advantage. As they say sometimes, beware
of the injured golfers.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no mystery behind Els' injury. The long stretches he
spends standing on golf courses, especially during pro-ams, is one
factor. The bigger one is the 28-year-old South African's constant
globetrotting on the international tour. The endless hours Els
spends on long flights aren't something a chiropractor would
suggest for good health.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays in Australia, Europe, Asia,'' Tiger Woods said.
``That's a huge toll on your body.''
</P>
<P>
   Els said that although he felt some pain during Tuesday's
practice round, his back was not stiffening, as it did Friday. His
doctor has prescribed exercises and stretches to help alleviate the
pain.
</P>
<P>
   And he must limit his hitting. He admits it isn't an easy thing
to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do get frustrated,'' Els said. ``I wanted to go out there
and play and practice and get ready for this tournament, but maybe
all these things happen for a reason. Maybe I should slow down a
bit. There will be more U.S. Opens and British Opens. But it is
frustrating because I've been playing well and I feel that my game
is coming around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
