<SLUG> BC-CIR-BANNED-BOOKS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WEB SITE TO FIGHT CENSORSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Va., Md., Calif.)  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a tribute to the people who have been tortured, burned at the
stake, sent to the Bastille or harassed by J. Edgar Hoover for
exercising their freedom of speech and thought, Banned Books
On-Line offers links to the texts of 30 representative books and
plays, even Scriptures, that have been _ or still are _ kept from
readers by nervous authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The site is a reminder of the irrationality of censorship, the
triumph of ideas and the ultimate irrelevance of thought control
when it can be beaten by the touch of a few buttons.
</P>
<P>
   A reader is soon reminded that Aristophanes' ``Lysistrata,''
Defoe's ``Moll Flanders,'' various editions of ``The Arabian
Nights'' and Chaucer's ``Canterbury Tales'' were all banned from
the U.S. mail for decades under the Comstock Law, an anti-obscenity
statute of 1873. Aristophanes had trouble not only with Victorian
prudes but also with the military dictatorship in Greece, which,
the site notes, censored ``Lysistrata,'' an anti-war play, in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Sanger's 16-page pamphlet ``Family Limitation,'' which
ran afoul of the Comstock Law's ban on birth-control information,
is there with its original pages reproduced, as is Walt Whitman's
``Leaves of Grass.'' Banned Books On-Line contains a link to a site
that chronicles attacks on Mark Twain; ``Huckleberry Finn'' is
still one of the most censored books in American school libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Banned Books On-Line
(www.cs.cmu.edu/People/spok/banned-books.html) was culled from the
indexes of the On-Line Books Page (www.cs.cmu.edu/books.html),
which lists more than 7,000 works. Both sites were created by John
Mark Ockerbloom, 31, who has just received his doctorate in
computer science at Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the links to books from Banned Books On-Line go down.
When that occurs, you can go to the On-Line Books Page, where
alternative sites can usually be found.
</P>
<P>
   Ockerbloom said he had been inspired to set up the banned-books
site in 1994, when Carnegie Mellon removed more than 80 newsgroups
on sexual matters from its Web servers. After student and faculty
complaints, he said, the newsgroups were restored to the
university's computer-science Web servers, but a number of them
remain off the undergraduate system.
</P>
<P>
   Don Hale, vice president for university relations, said
questionable newsgroups had indeed been removed from Web servers
controlled by Carnegie Mellon, but he added that they were still
available to anyone on campus through independent servers.
</P>
<P>
   The Comstock Law's provisions are rarely enforced but have never
been entirely repealed, Ockerbloom said, noting recent efforts to
ban abortion information and ``indecent'' material on the Internet.
Opponents of the Communications Decency Act, Congress' first
attempt to ban pornography on the Internet, argued that it was a
modern-day Comstock Law. The act was struck down by the U.S.
Supreme Court last year.
</P>
<P>
   The banned-books site, which Ockerbloom said got several
thousand visits a week, is linked to a number of other
anti-censorship resources, including the Electronic Frontier
Foundation (www.eff.org/blueribbon.html) and the American Civil
Liberties Union's Freedom Network
(www.aclu.org/issues/cyber/burning.html), in a campaign against
Internet censorship.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ockerbloom, representing Banned Books On-Line, is one of eight
plaintiffs in a suit against Loudoun County, Va., which uses a Web
filter to block his site and others from viewing at the public
library. Other censored plaintiffs represent Web sites that include
the Safer Sex Page and the site of the American Association of
University Women Maryland. Rob Morse, a columnist for The San
Francisco Examiner, is also a plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Ockerbloom's dissertation involved a system to
let Internet users manage large amounts of shared information from
sites that use different formats, without the need to translate
them into a common format.
</P>
<P>
   A Roman Catholic, Ockerbloom also maintains a comprehensive site
called Catholic Resources on the Net
(www.cs.cmu.edu/spok/catholic.html), which is unofficial and not
sponsored by any Catholic organization but has extensive links to
papal doctrine, saints, liturgy, Mary pages, lavish art and much
more.
</P>
<P>
   He occasionally gets angry mail, from ``not just Catholics, but
people in various religions,'' asking him to explain why he runs
sites dedicated to both faith and free thought.
</P>
<P>
   Censorship, Ockerbloom said, endangers democracy by attacking
anything that challenges the status quo. ``It really narrows the
range of discussion in the interest of whoever's in power at the
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own work, he said, ``what I'm hoping the effect will
be is a lot more kids will go out and read `Huckleberry Finn.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
