<HEADLINE>
A PERSONAL COMPUTER IS NOT ALWAYS A PC
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits)  
(ja) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Are all desktop computers considered PCs? Are Apple computers
PCs?
</P>
<P>
   A. A PC, defined in the dictionary as a personal computer, is
designed for an individual to use it to process and store data
electronically, so many devices can be considered PC's. Not
counting the models constructed from hobby kits, PC's have been
around only since 1977, when Apple Computer, Commodore and Radio
Shack began to sell machines that you could buy in stores.
</P>
<P>
   In more technical usage, however, the term PC has come to be
associated with IBM and IBM clones running the DOS or Microsoft
Windows operating systems with an Intel or Intel-compatible
microprocessor. The first PC manufactured by IBM in 1981 was named
the IBM PC, and in the consumer world, PC has also come to mean
``not Macintosh.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer introduced its Macintosh line in 1984. The first
home computer to feature a graphic interface, the Mac runs on its
own microprocessor and operating system. But Mac users can buy
add-in cards or software that will let them run PC programs on
their machines.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to QandA(AT)nytimes.com or postal mail to Questions,
Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y.
10036-3959. This column will answer questions of general
interest.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
