<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3660 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GENDER-NYT &LR;      06-17 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GENDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEX-ROLE TANGLE, A WOMAN'S SEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do women search for information differently from men?
</P>
<P>
   I never thought so myself _ and in fact, found the notion rather
sexist on its face _ until the other day when I stumbled across an
unusual Web search site called Looksmart that is particularly
popular with women.
</P>
<P>
   During the first five months of this year, Looksmart attracted a
higher percentage of women than the other top search sites,
according to statistics compiled by Craig Ruskin, a research
analyst with Relevant Knowledge, which measures Web traffic.
</P>
<P>
   While other sites' audiences tended to reflect the male-centric
face of the Web (only 44 percent of Web users are women), Looksmart
(www.looksmart.com) consistently attracted a higher proportion of
female users, more than half in three of the previous five months.
</P>
<P>
   When Evan Thornley and Tracey Ellery designed the site three
years ago, they were not trying to target women. ``We started out
to target professional families, busy people, a highly educated
group of folks,'' Ms. Ellery said. ``Our vision was to reach a
mainstream audience on the Web. It turned out that a large
proportion of that audience is women.''
</P>
<P>
   That intrigued me because I have been disappointed by most of my
attempts to find useful information on the Web. No matter what
search site I try _ Yahoo, Excite, Infoseek, Lycos, Alta Vista,
Hotbot and the list goes on _ I usually end up frustrated, wading
through screen after screen of long lists of sites unrelated to
what I was searching for, like sites written in German or reams of
personal home pages.
</P>
<P>
   But now I had hope. Perhaps the problem all along was that I was
a woman searching for information in a man's environment. I admit
that it sounded a little odd and even self-serving. But Look-smart
has a higher percentage of women users, so it must be doing
something that appeals to them. I mean, us.
</P>
<P>
   When I went to Looksmart to investigate, I noticed a difference.
Although Looksmart offered the usual opportunity to type in a
keyword to conduct a search, the design of the site nudged me in a
different direction.
</P>
<P>
   Looksmart was clearly encouraging me to browse. Along the left
side of the screen was a prominent list of 12 tempting categories
like Travel and Vacations, Business and Finance, and Shopping and
Services. I could click on any of these to begin broad searches.
</P>
<P>
   Idly, I chose Shopping and Services, and that produced a list
with more specific subcategories. To narrow my search, I clicked
again, delving deeper into such subcategories as Clothes and
Accessories and then Women's Wear. I arrived within seconds at a
list of sites labeled rather inelegantly as Footwear.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical of any site that would use such an unevocative label
for the glorious subcategory of shoes, I clicked on the list. Was I
about to be confronted by page after page of socks? Instead, I
found myself happily examining images of actual pairs of shoes by
companies like Kenneth Cole, Steve Madden and Hush Puppies. The
Hush Puppies site even flashed this message: ``Browse our shoes!''
There are no three sweeter words in the English language.
</P>
<P>
   After about a half-hour of comparing heel heights, prices and
options for summer sandals, I tried to make sense of the
experience. I believed that I had been randomly experimenting with
the search site. But when I phoned Thornley and Ms. Ellery and
described my journey, I learned that the pattern of my search had
been no accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ended up using the site to shop,'' Thornley said. ``This
is not unusual, and it is not unlike what people have observed.
Women on average shop in a more browsing context. Men tend to be
more hunters, searching for a specific item.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean that when women are searching for information,
they're really in effect shopping for facts?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important not to overstate the generalizations,''
Thornley cautioned. ``But what we appear to see is that on average,
women are more disposed toward a category approach to searches.''
Looksmart is certainly more disposed toward that approach. While
most search engines rely primarily on software to sort sites
automatically, Looksmart employs a staff of 30 real people to
review each site, write a brief description of it and categorize
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how we give a much more hands-on approach to sifting
through the information,'' Thornley said. ``Yahoo is the only other
site that really does the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But each has an idiosyncratic way of organizing information in
its database. Yahoo's categories (www.yahoo.com) were very
different from Looksmart's. To arrive at a list of Yahoo's shoe
sites, I had to follow a route that was, to my mind, less
intuitive. I clicked first on Business and Economy, then Companies,
then Apparel, then Footwear, then Women's, then Brand Names.
Although Yahoo's database of sites is more than twice as large as
Looksmart's database of 400,000, I preferred browsing on Looksmart.
</P>
<P>
   Since my opinion of browsing was based on personal taste, I
enlisted the aid of Gary Arlen, who heads Arlen Communications, a
company that has studied online shopping patterns. He readily
agreed to act as a sort of scientific control. He and his wife had
been pricing bedding the day before, and he was willing to do some
comparison shopping.
</P>
<P>
   But Arlen's experience on Looksmart was vastly different from
mine. He narrated his search over the phone in real time: ``I'm
starting at Shopping and Services, then going to Decor and Design,
then searching for bedding, and here's a list for some appropriate
sites. But wait, by the time I get to the sixth or seventh site on
the list, I'm at something called Eco-Baby, and it sells natural
diapers, breast pumps, a whole list of things I'm not interested
in. Oh, wait, _ the last item is bedding.''
</P>
<P>
   Arlen was disappointed that he had been compelled to wade
through stuff he considered extraneous. ``I'm not convinced
browsing is better,'' he said. But then, he is a man.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the real difference in search techniques is based not
on sex but rather on what you need to find. I enjoy browsing as
much as the next, er, person when I am shopping. But when I am
looking for specific information, like the answer to a question my
7-year-old recently posed _ ``How many babies can a horse have at
once?'' _ I can find the answer much faster by searching with the
keywords ``horse'' and ``facts'' on Yahoo than by using Looksmart.
(The answer is usually one foal, but sometimes two.) Believe me:
even after hours of browsing, I can still type as fast as any man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
