<HEADLINE>
ROSE CRUMB OF PORT ANGELES, WASH., HONORED AT SUPREME COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by the New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 The Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hospice care crusader Rose Crumb, winner of the
1998 Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis Award for her public service
achievements, on Wednesday thanked the families of her patients for
showing her ``what a very precious gift life is.''
</P>
<P>
   Crumb, who founded the volunteer Hospice of Clallam County,
Wash., in 1978, said she has learned ``courage, patience and
acceptance'' by working with families to provide their dying
relative with a dignified end.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made me realize what a very precious gift life is, and
that we need to make the most of it every day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Crumb, one of five national winners of the Onassis award, was
selected for the honor from among 42 recipients of the 1998
Jefferson Awards, which recognize community contributions across
the nation. Crumb and the other four recipients were honored
Wednesday at a ceremony at the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony was hosted by Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, who
called the award recipients ``true American heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still true today that the single individual can make a
difference,'' O'Connor said. ``These individuals show that
volunteerism is alive and well in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Crumb, 72, was sponsored for the award by The Seattle
Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   The Jefferson awards, dubbed ``America's Nobel Prizes for Public
Service,'' are presented by the American Institute for Public
Service. The institute was created in 1972 by Onassis, Sen. Robert
Taft Jr., and Sam Beard to honor individuals for public service.
</P>
<P>
   The institute noted that Crumb ``has spent her life dedicated to
hospice care and resolving health care issues for those in need.''
</P>
<P>
   Crumb, a registered nurse who lives in Port Angeles, Wash.,
created the Hospice of Clallam County, a volunteer community
hospital, after overcoming resistance from the health care industry
to ``free health care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Through sheer dedication, force of personality and the support
of client families, she has managed to make believers out of every
skeptic...(and) provides a loving and supportive environment for
patients while saving the government hundreds of thousands of
dollars in health care expenses,'' the institute declared.
</P>
<P>
   Award recipients are selected by a board composed of leaders in
education, business and the public sector. Over the 26-year history
of the institute, 100 Americans have received national awards and
more than 7,000 have received ``grassroots'' awards.
</P>
<P>
   The Jefferson Award certificate includes a quotation from Thomas
Jefferson: ``One man with courage is the majority.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the five Onassis award winners and the 37 other
Jefferson Award winners, the institute also presented four national
awards. The winners were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin ``for providing the political
leadership and entrepreneurial spirit which has led to one of the
strongest economies in U.S. history.''
</P>
<P>
   _ TV personality Oprah Winfrey ``for her philanthropic spirit
and her commitment to promoting decency in daytime television
programming.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Thaddeus S. Lott Sr., of Houston, ``for being a pioneer in
education reform, creating an innovative charter school district,
the first-of-its kind in the country, in inner-city Houston.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bobby Jindal for ``his vibrant leadership on behalf of all
generations _ young and old _ in the national struggle to
strengthen and preserve Medicare in time for the retirement of the
`Baby Boomers.''' He is executive director of the National
Bi-Partisan Commission on the Future of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The other four Onassis winners were:
</P>
<P>
   _ James ``Major'' Adams, of Chicago, for his work with youth
groups.
</P>
<P>
   _ Crystal Davis, of St. Louis, for creating the Community Hope
Center that provides community assistance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pam Marota, of San Francisco, for developing the ``Kimo
Bear,'' a teddy bear used to teach children about cancer and its
effects.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carlos Spaht II, of Shreveport, La., for developing a program
that to encourage young people to stay in school.
</P>
</TEXT>
