<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3716 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REIKEN-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     06-17 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REIKEN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ODD SEA': FIRST NOVEL MAKES MAGIC OF CALAMITY
</HEADLINE>
  (Publication notes at end)  
 (ja)  
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a haunting first novel that takes a horrifying family
calamity and turns it into a form of magic.
</P>
<P>
   You don't know what to think in the opening pages of ``The Odd
Sea,'' by Frederick Reiken, when 16-year-old Ethan Shumway leaves
his rural western Massachusetts home and suddenly disappears. As
his younger brother, Philip, the story's narrator, describes it:
``Ethan had walked down the driveway, the May sun glinting off the
back of his yellow T-shirt. Then he was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the police begin to investigate, you're not certain how
seriously to take this disappearance. Ethan, an outstanding athlete
and guitar player, has spoken of traveling to distant places, so it
may be that he has simply gone off on an adventure. His parents,
described by the narrator with charming humor, seem oddly passive
in their initial response, allowing the remaining four children,
Philip and his three sisters, Amy, Halley and Dana, to continue
their usual outdoor rounds as if there were no real threat there.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Lawrence, even tells his children a story about what
Philip describes as ``a royal family of beavers, and a noble beaver
king who went off to sack the city of Beaverilium, then spent a
decade finding his way back home.'' Philip continues: ``Beavers
sailed ships and fought with weapons and were both helped and
hindered by the crafty beaver-gods of Olympia. I think he managed
to cover everything: absence, distance, longing, hope, return.''
</P>
<P>
   When Halley, the middle daughter, eventually points out the
story's resemblance to Homer's ``Odyssey,'' which she has started
reading in English class, Dana, the youngest, yells out, ``It's
not!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what?'' Amy, the oldest, asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the Odd Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Odyssey.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever!''
</P>
<P>
   Yet soon enough the horror of what may have happened to Ethan
begins to sink in, and each family member reacts in his or her own
peculiar way. Lawrence, a house carpenter by trade, dedicates
himself to learning ``the lost art of timber framing,'' or putting
together houses without using power tools or nails. His wife,
Marilyn, can't sleep, and begins to spend her nights baking,
reading classic novels and standing out ``with the stars,'' which,
she says, on clear nights ``could draw the sadness from her
heart.'' Eventually she grows so depressed she has to be
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Dana works on honing her basketball skills, shooting dozens of
foul shots in the driveway after dark. Philip obsessively searches
the surrounding woods, on the theory that by ``not-finding'' Ethan,
the odds of his survival will be increased, even though Halley, who
is closest to Philip in age, says, ``No offense, but that's
retarded.'' Amy drives to Troy, N.Y., and sorts fruitlessly through
the items left by a serial killer who has been arrested and whose
house and grounds have been found to contain the remains of a dozen
or so tortured children, ages 7 to 17.
</P>
<P>
   So the possibility of disaster grows in the reader's mind, and
with it a sense of the story's looming pain.
</P>
<P>
   The author, who lives in western Massachusetts and is a reporter
and nature writer for The Daily Hampshire Gazette, has skillfully
balanced this pain against the hopefulness of the narrator.
Strongly identifying with his lost brother yet milder mannered and
less talented, Philip eventually picks up a trail that Ethan left
in the weeks and months before his disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   This trail leads him to Ethan's girlfriend, Melissa Moody, the
daughter of a neighboring farmer and a serious painter; to a diary
in which Ethan recorded everything from his thoughts on art to his
sexual activities, and to Victoria Rhone, the director of a local
arts colony who turns out to have been obsessed with Ethan and
played the role of a somewhat ambiguous mentor.
</P>
<P>
   The trail also leads Philip into the surrounding natural world,
which Reiken knits adeptly into his story. ``There is a boundary
where the city light of Pittsfield ends,'' he writes, ``where
suddenly night is deep and dark and stars twinkle beckoning you to
rise, which you do. You start to float out there, beyond things,
without light to obscure the dusty river of the Milky Way. As if
slipping through a doorway, the passage into these hills creates a
sense of being far-flung, lost in some old and still untamed place,
where you could easily disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this the place where Ethan may have gone, Philip wonders,
mixing his romantic temperament with his knowledge of contemporary
physics. Has his brother stepped through some mysterious doorway
into the world of antimatter? Whatever the answer, he uses the
wound of his loss to make of himself the artist who will write
``The Odd Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two years after Ethan's disappearance, one of the
sneakers he was wearing that morning is found in the ivy near the
end of the driveway. And a year or so later the Pittsfield police
arrest a local man for trying to abduct a teen-age girl.
Questioned, the man admits to killing two teen-age boys and burying
them behind his mother's house in the town of Blue Mountain Lake.
</P>
<P>
   I can't say that these developments solve the mystery of Ethan's
disappearance. But they bring you back with a vengeance to more
practical considerations. And the mixture of the grisly and
metaphysical that Reiken works so effectively keeps you spellbound
by ``The Odd Sea'' until its very last page.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   THE ODD SEA
</P>
<P>
   By Frederick Reiken
</P>
<P>
   201 pages. Harcourt Brace &AMP; Co. $22.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
