<HEADER>
A3725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAMMING-COX &UR;  &UR; AOLASKS     06-17 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAMMING-COX </SLUG>
     AOL ASKS CONGRESS FOR RESTRICTIONS ON JUNK
E-MAIL
 &HT;     Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;     By KIMBERLY MARSELAS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An America Online representative urged lawmakers
Wednesday to join its ``war against spam,'' unsolicited bulk e-mail
that has plagued Internet service providers and cost individual
recipients time and money.
</P>
<P>
   Senators and Internet insiders said ``spam'' is worse than
regular junk mail because the addressees and service providers like
AOL, known as ISPs, must pay related costs, while the sender
advertises for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any legislation proposed should give ISPs the ability to
recover the cost of sending this junk e-mail,'' Randall Boe,
associate general counsel for AOL, told the Senate Commerce
subcommittee on communications.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee is considering anti-spam legislation that would
require direct e-mail marketers to provide accurate return
addresses and honor requests to remove private e-mail addresses
from mailing lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simply a question of taking a cloak of secrecy off the
senders,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., the bill's
co-sponsor. The senator said fewer incidents of ``spamming'' would
occur if senders knew they would get replies from angry recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Deirdre Mulligan of the Center for Democracy and Technology
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was enacted, it would lead to a reduction in junk
e-mail,'' she said.~~~ ``But it's unclear whether it will be the
silver bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee heard Wednesday from witnesses with a variety
of concerns about the unwanted e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junk e-mail has the potential to harm our economy in ways
terrorists only dream of,'' said Ray Everett-Church, co-founder of
an ``anti-spam'' coalition. He said ``spam'' has the ability to
crash computer systems of major ISPs. Systems run by AT&AMP;T, Netcom,
Pacific Bell and GTE have already had crashes attributed to
``spam.''
</P>
<P>
   The term ``spam'' is rumored to come from a sketch by the
English comedy group Monty Python, in which restaurant patrons are
offered an abundance of Spam, a processed meat product, according
to attorney David Kramer of Palo Alto, Calif., who specializes in
Internet issues.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said that the proposed requirement that bulk-mail senders
identify themselves could be ``easily circumvented'' by senders who
set up temporary accounts, send hundreds of junk e-mails and then
close the account before they can be traced.
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses accused the senders of making false claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spam has become the fraud artist's calling card on the
Internet,'' said Sheila Anthony, a federal trade commissioner.
Anthony said ``spam'' has been used to promote everything from
pyramid schemes to chain letters.
</P>
<P>
   Spam has also been used to advertise pornographic web sites to
children, said Boe. AOL and other providers have optional parental
safeguards limiting children's access to those sites, but junk
e-mailers ``make a mockery of that process,'' Boe said.
</P>
<P>
   Everett-Church said the problems caused by junk e-mail warrant
its prohibition and said the Senate bill would be inadequate to
stop it. A bill offered in the House last spring by Rep. Chris
Smith, R-N.J., would have made any junk e-mail transmissions
illegal. The bill is pending in the House subcommittee on
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   But the senators at Wednesday's subcommittee hearing said
``spamming'' shouldn't be outlawed because companies deserve a
chance to get their message out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, constitutionally, we probably have to give them
that,'' said Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
