<HEADER>
A3733 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TECH-OVERDOSE-NYT     06-17 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TECH-OVERDOSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL-CLASSES TREND IS ALARMING PROFESSORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)   (bl)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 800 professors at the University of Washington have
signed an open letter to Gov. Gary Locke to say they are worried
about the enthusiasm he and one of his advisers are showing for
instruction via CD-ROMs and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers worry that Washington State will be too quick to
embrace the idea of the virtual, online university to cut costs and
jobs. They say they see some disturbing national trends in that
direction, citing the results of a roundtable of university
professors and presidents brought together by the consulting arm of
the Coopers &AMP; Lybrand financial services company.
</P>
<P>
   A white paper issued after the conference in July said that
``instructional software could easily substitute for campus-based
instruction or at least be a substantial part of the delivery
system'' and that the creation of only 25 online courses could
serve about 80 percent of the undergraduate enrollment in core
courses.
</P>
<P>
   The faculty members' letter, which they plan to deliver next
week, urges Locke to ``support learning as a human and social
practice, an enrichment of soul and mind, the entitlement of all
citizens in a democracy, and not a profit-making commodity to be
offered on the cheapest terms to the highest bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   College professors are facing great upheaval as policymakers
talk about using the Internet to modernize academia. With the
arrival of the World Wide Web, video streaming, multimedia CD-ROMs
and computer-assisted research, students now have easy access to
more facts than scholars a few decades ago ever imagined, and those
changes have made some administrators and taxpayers view a
classroom lecture as an inefficient mode of imparting knowledge
from one brain to many.
</P>
<P>
   A speech by Wallace Loh, the governor's policy director, to the
University of Washington Law School in May worried many professors.
In that speech, Loh said telecommunications would be especially
useful for teaching adults returning to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is likely to be the much more common method of
delivering the learning they need, at home or in the workplace for
them, simply because they're place-bound,'' he said in an
interview. Younger students would be more likely to attend
traditional colleges or universities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The professors do not oppose all Internet instruction. ``Under
certain circumstances, distance learning is a wonderful option for
people who are incapable of getting to a campus,'' said Lauren
Goodlad, an assistant English professor who signed the letter.
``The faculty is just concerned that this would be economically
foolhardy because in point of fact, high-quality teaching, whether
done on a distance-learning basis or on a campus basis, requires
contact.
</P>
<P>
   Many professors did not like what Loh called the ``brave new
world of digital education.'' But others believe that high
technology could free up time for instructors to advise or tutor
students and pursue more research.
</P>
<P>
   Already schools can circulate lectures and video clips of top
professors electronically, and professors can get short-answer
tests graded by computers. One of the main proponents of the letter
acknowledges that technology has helped streamline academic life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to use it and are all using it, but when they
basically want to replace people with computers, that's where we
draw the line,'' said Galya Diment, an associate professor in the
department of Slavic languages and literatures and president of the
University of Washington chapter of the American Association of
University Professors, which helped circulate the letter.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that 95 percent of the signatures on the letter had
been gathered via e-mail. ``We don't want to go back to the caves
or even to typewriters,'' she said. ``What we objected to were the
extreme views, like beaming an image of professors to students and
thinking that would be a satisfactory way of replacing face to face
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Borning, a professor of computer science and engineering,
joined at least 10 other teachers in his department in signing the
letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of education happens through the interaction of faculty
and students in a variety of departments,'' he said. He described
studies in computer graphics at the university that successfully
bring together art, music and computer scholars. ``If you have
people learning from CD-ROMs off in their garage, this sort of
thing is not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Locke, a Democrat, created the 2020
Commission and told it ``to re-think and re-invent higher education
from the ground up.'' Some at the University of Washington have
criticized the selection of commission members _ whom Locke called
``a group of this state's smartest people''_ because the panel
includes many from the business community, but no professors from
any college or university. The commission's recommendations to the
governor are due in September.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
