<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SUMMER, SO LET 'EM EAT COCONUT CAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What looks prettier on a summer buffet table than an elegant
coconut cake? Not much.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Fraser of Mansfield, Texas, saw our request a few weeks
ago and sent in this version from a 1986 issue of ``Southern
Living.''
</P>
<P>
   TOASTED COCONUT CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10-12
</P>
<P>
   18.25-ounce package white cake mix without pudding
</P>
<P>
   3 1/8-ounce package vanilla instant pudding mix
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans or walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Coconut cream cheese frosting, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   Toasted flaked coconut, reserved from coconut cream cheese
frosting recipe
</P>
<P>
   Combine cake mix, pudding mix, water, oil and eggs; beat 4
minutes at medium speed of an electric mixer. Stir in 1 1/3 cups
coconut and nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Pour batter into 3 greased and floured 9-inch round cake pans.
Bake at 350 degrees for 20-25 minutes, or until wooden pick
inserted in center comes out clean. Cool in pans 10 minutes; remove
layers from pans and let cool completely. Spread coconut cream
cheese frosting between layers and on top and sides of cake.
Sprinkle top with 1/2 cup toasted coconut reserved from frosting
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Coconut cream cheese frosting:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter or margarine, softened
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce package cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups sifted powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Melt 2 tablespoons butter in large skillet; stir in coconut.
Cook, stirring constantly, over medium heat until golden brown. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine 2 tablespoons butter and cream cheese, beating until
light and fluffy. Add powdered sugar, milk and vanilla; beat until
smooth. Stir in 2 cups toasted coconut; reserve 1/2 cup toasted
coconut for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate cake several hours or overnight for easier slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 682 calories, 38 grams fat, 82
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 128 milligrams cholesterol,
484 milligrams sodium, 50 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Today's apple: Ida Clarkson of Burleson, Texas, is one of many
readers who sent in a recipe for an apple cake using brown sugar in
the glaze.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 20 slices
</P>
<P>
   4 cups peeled and chopped apples
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon each cinnamon and nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans or walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Mix apples, sugar and oil in large bowl; let stand 1 hour. Sift
dry ingredients together. Add eggs to apple mixture. Blend in dry
ingredients by hand (don't use mixer, as batter will be thick). Add
nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in Pam-sprayed bundt pan for 1 1/2 hours at 350 degrees.
Let cool in pan about 20 minutes; turn out on cooling rack.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle with brown sugar glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Brown sugar glaze:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons white corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   Combine ingredients and boil for 2 minutes. Drizzle over warm
cake.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 314 calories, 16 grams fat, 42
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 21 milligrams cholesterol,
137 milligrams sodium, 45 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Request:
</P>
<P>
   Karen Davis of North Richland Hills, Texas, would like a recipe
for pineapple sherbet using Eagle Brand sweetened condensed milk
and frozen in an ice cream churn.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Barrier of Arlington, Texas, would like a recipe for deep
butter cake and gooey butter cake, which she clipped from the paper
years ago.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
