<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3759 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      06-17 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the e-mail address in the last graf instead of the symbol,
which is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(th) 
 By LESLIE LAND    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARDY SWEET PEAS
</P>
<P>
   Q. I love old-fashioned sweet peas and plant them every year,
but they never seem to do well in my garden. I've heard there is
also a perennial type. Is it easier to grow? If so, would it be
hardy on Long Island?
</P>
<P>
   A. Lathyrus odoratus, the old-fashioned annual sweet pea, would
rather be in England. It needs slightly alkaline soil, plenty of
rain and a long season of cool weather to thrive. And no matter
where they are growing, flowers must be picked constantly. Plants
will stop blooming if they are permitted to form seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Lathyrus latifolius (the most common perennial sweet pea) are an
entirely different story. Unlike their annual cousins, they don't
mind warm weather; flowering usually starts when July does. They
will slack off if the heat gets really brutal, but as long as it
cools off at night they'll keep blooming for months.
</P>
<P>
   These perennial sweet peas are much more drought-tolerant than
the annuals, and far more resistant to pests and diseases. A single
mature plant can cover an area two- or three-feet wide and eight-
or nine-feet tall. They're hardy, too, even in New England.
</P>
<P>
   You may have any color you want _ as long as it's pink or white.
And you will not have perfume. Old-fashioned varieties of odoratus
live up to their name; latifolius is scentless in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Perennial sweet peas aren't popular in the nursery trade,
possibly because they grow deep roots and long vines before
flowering. But they grow easily from seed, and it only takes two or
three years for them to start blooming. Seeds are available from
Park Seed, 1 Parkton Ave., Greenwood, S.C. 29647-0001; (800)
845-3369, and Thompson &AMP; Morgan, P.O. Box 1308, Jackson, N.J.
08527-0308; (800) 274-7333. Both offer free catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   CREATING A RABBIT-FREE ZONE
</P>
<P>
   Q. Every year, I have to replant my flowers at least three times
because the rabbits eat them. They have also devoured my roses,
barberries and perennials. I have tried moth balls, dried blood,
repellants and even fences. They just hop over the fence and have a
buffet. I have seen them standing on their hind legs to reach up
into my bushes. Help!
</P>
<P>
   A. Remain calm, all you have to do is amend your fences. Rabbits
excel at the long jump, not the high hurdles. They can't climb, and
their hearts aren't really in it, when it comes to digging. They
can, however, squeeze through tiny gaps, and they love to do the
limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Help is available at the lumberyard: farmers' rabbit fencing, a
wire grid, three-feet tall, has very close mesh for the bottom
foot. Bury it a couple of inches deep or otherwise secure it to the
ground, so they can't slither underneath. If you are also
conscientious in the matter of tight gates, the fenced area will be
rabbit-free.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the unfenced areas will remain vulnerable until
you get a dog.
</P>
<P>
   READING YELLOW LEAVES
</P>
<P>
   Q. The leaves on some of my tomato and bell pepper plants are
starting to turn yellow. The plants get plenty of sun and water
each day. What am I doing wrong? Is there something I can add to
the soil to help the plants along?
</P>
<P>
   A. Chlorosis, a shortage of chlorophyll that results in
yellowing leaves, is the plant announcing, ``I don't feel well,''
and could be caused by just about anything, including a whole
panoply of diseases. But if it is happening slowly, and there are
no other symptoms (curling, spots, brown edges, wholesale
leaf-drop), it's likely that your plants are either waterlogged or
hungry.
</P>
<P>
   If your soil is heavy clay, frequent watering could be drowning
the roots. If it's sandy, chances are that constant watering is
leaching nutrients from the soil. So the first thing you can do is
cut back on the water a bit; it's OK for the surface soil to dry
out, and the root zone should be moist, not wet.
</P>
<P>
   Then, give your plants a drink of soluble, all-purpose plant
fertilizer, either a widely-available chemical mix like Peters or
Miracle Grow or, even better, a fish and seaweed based organic mix
like Neptune's Harvest, available from Pinetree Garden Seeds, Box
300, New Gloucester, Maine 04260; (207) 926-3400, or Worm's Way,
7850 North Highway 37, Bloomington, Ind. 47404; (800) 274-9676.
Catalogs are free.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
