<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFLATABLE-FURNITURE-     06-17 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFLATABLE-FURNITURE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POINTED HOMAGE TO INFLATABLE DESIGNS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927 .) 
 (ja)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The Inflatable Moment,'' on view at the Urban
Center, 457 Madison Ave., celebrates a time when, if you didn't
have an idea, you just didn't show up. You'd be too embarrassed.
How different from today's climate of fear, when showing up with an
idea could get you fired.
</P>
<P>
   Inflatable architecture, the show's subject, was a terrible
idea, as it happens. As Lloyd Kahn, the architecture editor, wrote
in the Whole Earth Catalog, ``Inflatables are trippy, cheap, light,
imaginative spaces, not architecture at all. They're terrible to
work in. The blazing redundant surfaces disorient; one wallows in
space. When the sun goes behind a cloud you cease cooking and
immediately start freezing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but so what? In those days, a terrible idea was better than
no idea. At times, a bad idea was even better than a good idea.
Architects at that moment were exploring the relationship between
metaphor and material reality. There's nothing like a bad idea for
showing up the difference between them.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Marc Dessauce, an architectural historian who lives
in New York, this big, sloppy, high-spirited show is the
Architectural League's tribute to 1968, the year the counterculture
was officially born amid campus upheavals and street
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Along with anniversary tributes like this show and a weekend
conference last month at the Columbia University Buell Center for
the Study of American Architecture, young designers today are also
offering a small reprise of the inflatable moment. Inflate, a
British design group, has displayed its blow-up bowls and vases at
downtown design stores. The dreadful 1967 Inflatable chair can be
purchased from a Web site. Even Ikea plans to introduce an Air Line
of inflatable footstools and sofas this October.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt it's a perennial dream: to lose gravity, float away on
a cloud, rise above the world and the weight of grown-up
responsibilities. Nitrous oxide is the best way to inhabit that
dream, though the dentist's drill one must put up with to
experience such bliss can be very off-putting. And the impulse to
float away only partly explains the radical work of the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In those years, society at large was exploring the meshing of
metaphor and materiality. In Paris, real cars were torched, real
trees cut down, real bodies carted off to the pokey. Garbage strewn
around the student-occupied Odeon theater gave off a genuine
stench. But as many who were students at the time recall, the May
events served primarily a metaphoric value. The counterculture was
a generalized protest against a diffuse idea of cultural authority.
Since architecture is traditionally an art of the Establishment, it
was not surprising that some of the counterculture's earliest
rumblings emanated from within architecture schools.
</P>
<P>
   The main part of the show focuses on the work of Utopie, a group
of French artists and writers who banded together in 1967 and
devoted much of their energy to designing inflatable structures and
promoting them in publications. The group included the architects
Jean Aubert, Jean-Paul Jungmann and Antoine Stinco and the writers
Jean Baudrillard, Isabelle Auricoste and Hubert Tonka. And the
heart of the show consists of their student work, including diploma
projects for the Ecole des Beaux-Arts.
</P>
<P>
   These presentation drawings depict a variety of pneumatic
building types, including housing, theaters, museums and other
public buildings. Some of these are air-supported structures in
which a pressurized interior supports a thin membrane. In others,
the enclosure is held aloft by air-filled structural ribs. Many of
them are transportable, and thus in theory do not require ownership
of land. Air, so they thought, was free.
</P>
<P>
   Dessauce writes that for members of Utopie, the inflatable
structure occupied a middle ground between conventional practice
and dropping out. The appeal of inflatables was precisely that they
were not architecture at all and therefore were untainted by
establishment associations. Lacking weight, they also lacked
gravitas. Like tents, they were events rather than buildings _
happenings, in the parlance of the time _ and thus made no claim on
endurance, much less on the eternity to which architecture often
aspires.
</P>
<P>
   Utopie's work, while squishy, is not as formless as you might
expect. Jean-Paul Jungmann's Dyodon pneumatic house, for example,
recalls the Buck Rogers designs of the elderly Frank Lloyd Wright,
like his unbuilt plan from the late 1950s for a convention center
on Ellis Island. (Wright's one venture into inflatables, a
windowless rubber igloo designed in 1957, is also included here.)
Most of the projects, though not rigidly structured, are formally
more complex than the geodesic domes of Buckminster Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller, who would routinely ask architects, ``What does your
building weigh?'', was clearly the inspiration for Aubert's 1966
Traveling Theater project, a soft dome of green fabric interlaced
with air-filled structural tubes. But the framework also has the
character of Gothic ribs. In fact, several projects in the show
evoke the fantastic Modernismo Gothicism of Gaudi, and would not
look out of place in the context of present-day Barcelona, with its
brilliant program of innovative public spaces.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at this material now, one thinks, why were these
people so dissatisfied? After all, they were living in Paris! City
of Light! A city where even student cafe food is heaven! What place
in this world or the next could be more Utopian than the Rive
Gauche?
</P>
<P>
   But the Utopie group was living in a time as well as a place. As
architecture students in the '60s, they were cruelly conscious of
the collapse of the utopia that had preceded them _ the modern
movement's dream of the rational, radiant city of towers in a park.
Students in the 1960s were living in the modern movement's future
time frame, but things within that frame had not turned out as
planned. All that propaganda, all that earnestness, and what was
there to show for it? The Tour Montparnasse, a big black shadow on
the Paris skyline. If students in the 1960s displayed an
unwillingness to grow up, who could blame them? Who wanted to grow
up and become a modern architect? Who wanted to be delusional?
</P>
<P>
   This lends considerable poignancy to the second part of the
show, a historical overview in which it can be seen that Utopie's
utopia fared even worse than the modern kind. Based on an
exhibition organized by Utopie in March 1968 at the Museum of
Modern Art in Paris, this show pulls together a hodgepodge of
pneumatic delights, including Quasar Khanh's inflatable lamps and
Andy Warhol's silver Mylar pillows. As a group, these projects have
all the charm of a deflated weather balloon.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is, this stuff actually looked tatty even when
new. Khanh's lamp had a crooked hang. The iconic Blow chair by
Scolari, De Pas, D'Urbino, Lomazzi squeaked when you sat on it, a
sound effect as endearing as nails on a blackboard. The U.S.
Pavilion at the 1970 Osaka World's Fair looked terrific for five
minutes, before leakage problems caused the dome to sag. In fashion
photographs and shop windows, blow-up furnishings looked cool. At
home, they were last night's party favors.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps inflatable buildings were too much like architecture
after all. By 1970, the Utopie group had disbanded. Before long,
the inflatable moment was ripe for satire. In 1972, the
Architectural League presented a project by Marc Balet, a young
Prix de Rome winner, at the Whitney Museum of American Art.
Visitors were invited to toss effervescent tablets into buckets of
water and envision the bubbles as architectural configurations. A
pair of bubbles might be a duplex. Rotated 90 degrees, it became a
ranch house.
</P>
<P>
   Balet later went on toward other forms of inflation, first as
art director of Warhol's Interview magazine, then as director of
the advertising agency Balet &AMP; Albert. But as this show clearly
documents, media hype was an integral part of 1968, and perhaps the
most enduring aspect of the counterculture as a whole. Or to put a
kinder spin on it, work like Utopie's aimed more to influence
consciousness than to rebuild the world.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, it is clear that the conceptual groundwork for
``the inflatable moment'' had actually been laid by the modern
movement. Marcel Breuer had predicted that ``in the end, we will
all sit on a resilient column of air.''
</P>
<P>
   Mies van der Rohe's esthetic ``of almost nothing'' emphasized
void spaces over solid walls. Utopie's reliance on advanced
technology extended Le Corbusier's concept of the house as a
machine for living in. That reliance was the major reason for
Utopie's breakup.
</P>
<P>
   How could utopia be built on the patents of the
military-industrial complex? Even assuming that land could be
borrowed and air pumped in free, what idealistic architect wanted
to stake a vision to the Joint Chiefs of Staff?
</P>
<P>
   And now we have airbags. Also, those little pillows you can buy
at the airport to tuck behind your lower back. The trick is to fill
them only half way, just until they gain a puddly consistency. The
best time I had in the last 10 years was spent floating on a Batman
raft in the blue water off Capri. And what I think about all the
time is shoving off from the shore, drifting down the river on
something light and lazy, while trees pass overhead and all else
waits.
</P>
<P>
   (``The Inflatable Moment'' runs through Aug. 29 at the Urban
Center of the Architectural League of New York, 457 Madison Ave.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
