<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3784 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-BANKNOTE-DESIGN-     06-17 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-BANKNOTE-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE'S NEW BANKNOTES: MORE THAN JUST MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KARRIE JACOBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   About a month ago, as preparations began for printing the 10
billion new Euro banknotes that will replace the familiar
currencies of most European nations by the end of 2001, a
French-made anti-counterfeiting hologram vanished.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance, which could prompt changes in the design of
some of the Euros, occurred on a flight from France to Germany,
where it was to be tested by a printer in Nuremberg. Officials
speculated that it had been stolen by well-informed thieves who
understood the significance of the device.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative theory _ entirely unofficial in nature _ is that
the hologram was snatched by an unhappy esthete who understands the
damage the Euro banknotes will do to the continent's reputation as
a place where the design of everyday things has a high priority.
</P>
<P>
   The seven Euro banknotes created by Robert Kaliena, a designer
for the Austrian Central Bank, were selected in a 1996 competition
in which entrants from all over the continent were asked to depict
the ``ages and styles of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaliena took those instructions to heart and fashioned a
veritable art history lesson with textbook examples of the
Romanesque, the Gothic, the Baroque and the Modern.
</P>
<P>
   The bridges and windows pictured are deliberately detached from
any particular place or building so images of structures that look
very familiar, but that you cannot quite place, are shown on
banknotes that are redolent of the Deutsche mark, the Dutch guilder
or the Swedish krona, but are less . . . well, specific. The Euro
notes depict Europe as you might see it on a
seven-countries-in-seven-days bus tour, a swirl of landmarks devoid
of culture or context.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the aim was to avoid glorifying any nationality or
insulting anyone through omission. Unfortunately, the banknotes, in
striving for the ecumenical look, make Europe seem like a very dull
place, more homogenous, even, than the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In an economic analysis of the Euro, attention is generally
focused on the Germans and the almighty mark or the Italians and
the shrinking lira, but from a graphic design standpoint, the most
significant event in the change-over is the loss of the Dutch
guilder. While the guilder is not among the world's powerhouse
currencies, the Netherlands Bank produces paper money that is so
innovative _ and lovely _ that it should have been the model for
the Euro.
</P>
<P>
   From the mid-1960s to the mid-1980s, a graphic designer named
R.D.E. Oxenaar applied a personal esthetic to his nation's
currency, and in doing so demonstrated that the specific could be
universal. In his designs, Oxenaar used sunflowers, lighthouses and
birds and surrounded them with a kaleidoscopic mix of patterns that
please the eye and protect the money from counterfeiting.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxenaar tradition was carried forward by a designer of
television graphics, Jaap Drupsteen, who created a new series of
guilder notes covered with vivid, eye-catching motifs as hypnotic
as the drawings of M.C. Escher.
</P>
<P>
   Both Oxenaar and Drupsteen were unsuccessful entrants in the
Euro competition. For that reason, Drupsteen is reluctant to give
his opinion on the new notes, but Oxenaar, now retired, readily
offers an assessment: ``Really miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxenaar mentioned that each competitor was sent a package of ``a
safe range of historical'' images chosen by art historians, ``a
kind of European salad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw them all in the dust bin,'' Oxenaar said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Kaliena did not.
</P>
<P>
   It was a ``lost chance to do something interesting in Europe,''
said Lo Breier, a partner in the graphic design and advertising
agency Buero X, based Vienna and Hamburg. Breier, an Austrian,
argues that the competition should have been an opportunity to
reflect on what it means to be European.
</P>
<P>
   Breier was one of a handful of designers invited by the magazine
Der Spiegel to perform an unauthorized redesign of the Euro coins.
The coins show maps of the continent (sans the two non-members
Switzerland and Norway). Each member mints its own Euro coins and
is allowed to place whatever it chooses on the flip side. The
German coins feature the Brandenburg gate and an updated version of
their federal eagle. The editors of Der Spiegel, dismayed by the
predictability, asked Breier and three others for alterations.
</P>
<P>
   Breier recommended drilling two holes in the coins so they could
double as buttons, a way to give the coins practical value in case
they turn out to be worthless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-SURVEY-HNS &LR;      06-17 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-SURVEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY: SMALL BUSINESS SUPPORTS HMO CURBS, EVEN IF COSTS RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A majority of small-business owners said they
support proposals to rein in the managed care industry even if
regulation resulted in higher health insurance premiums, according
to a new survey released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And about half said they would absorb the extra cost, with only
a tiny percentage saying they would drop coverage for employees
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The survey _ produced jointly by the Henry J. Kaiser Family
Foundation of Menlo Park, Calif., and Harvard University _ is the
latest salvo in a growing battle between the managed care industry
and critics who say its cost-conscious methods of providing health
care often deny patients thorough medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care is fast rising as a hot-button political issue,
with many Democrats supporting increased government controls and
many Republicans scrambling to forge other solutions, mindful of
the traditional support they receive from business groups opposed
to government solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is considering at least 10 measures to control managed
care, which now accounts for more than 80 percent of
employer-sponsored health care coverage in the United States. The
proposals would require managed care plans to give consumers more
information on how they operate and open up appeal routes when
patients are denied insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent bill is sponsored by a Republican, Rep.
Charles Norwood of Georgia. It would permit lawsuits against health
insurers when denials of coverage result in deteriorating health or
death. A proposal sponsored by congressional Democrats contains the
same controversial feature.
</P>
<P>
   The survey questioned 800 small-business executives who employee
100 or fewer employees, and 594 said they offer health insurance,
with the remainder saying that high cost prevents them from
providing coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Of those answering a question about proposals to control managed
care, 89 percent said they favor requiring health plans to divulge
more information about coverage; 88 percent favored allowing
employees to appeal managed care decisions; 75 percent would permit
patients to have direct access to specialists instead of having to
go first to a primary-care doctor, and 61 percent would let
patients sue managed care companies.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents were asked whether their support would change if the
measures drove up premium prices. Sixty-nine percent said they
would still support the information requirement; 72 percent would
still support appeals; 59 percent would still support direct access
to specialists, and 51 percent would still support patient
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Among those offering health insurance, 50 percent said they
would absorb the cost if premiums were to rise between $1 and $5 a
month per employee, 33 percent said they would pass on some of the
cost to employees, 9 percent said they would pass on the entire
cost and 1 percent said they would drop coverage entirely. The
remaining 7 percent said they would switch plans or didn't know
what they would do.
</P>
<P>
   If premium costs were to go up $15 to $20 a month for each
employee, 45 percent said they would absorb all costs, 35 percent
said they would pass some of it on to employees, 8 percent said
they would pass on the whole cost, and 3 percent said they'd drop
coverage entirely. The remaining 9 percent said they would switch
plans or had no idea what they would do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support from small employers for consumer protection
regulation ... is surprising,'' said Drew Altman, president of the
Kaiser Family Foundation, which traces its roots to Henry J.
Kaiser, the industrialist who was the moving force behind
Kaiser-Permanente, one of the nation's largest managed care
companies. The foundation and Kaiser-Permanente are not connected.
</P>
<P>
   The prediction ``that many (in the survey) would pass along
costs to workers should serve as another reminder that in health
reform, there is no free lunch,'' Altman said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, support for controls on managed care among small-business
owners runs counter to predictions by the National Federation of
Independent Business that controls would be disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   The 600,000-member NFIB has argued that proposals now before
Congress would drive up premium costs and lead vulnerable
small-business owners to drop coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the people we represent, we get a very different reaction
in terms of their ability to provide coverage,'' said Dan Danner,
chief lobbyist for the NFIB and chairman of the Health Benefits
Coalition, an alliance of business and managed care groups opposing
managed care legislation. ``The smallest of small businesses are
still extremely cost-sensitive, and an increase in cost we believe
without question would have a significant impact on coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Danner pointed to a study last year by the Fairfax, Va.-based
Lewin Group, which said that 400,000 workers would lose health
insurance for each percentage point that premiums rise.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Levitt, director of the Kaiser-Harvard survey, defended
its results, calling them ``an accurate picture of how small
business views these issues in general. Small-business owners
themselves do not view these consumer protect proposals as a
disaster for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
