<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3800 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-17 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETHING UNUSUAL FROM THE PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If President Clinton's speech defending his planned trip to
China was what it appeared to be, it was a speech of great
historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   OK, you're thinking, what was so significant about it?
</P>
<P>
   Well, if the speech was what it seemed _ we are talking about
Clinton, so the operative word is ``if'' _ then it marked a rare
political occurrence: Bill Clinton took a stand on principle.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, it is not a good idea to assume that there is any
meaningful connection between what Clinton seems to be doing and
what he is actually doing. He is a master of illusion in matters of
this sort.
</P>
<P>
   But if Clinton was acting out of some self-serving, ulterior
motive in telling his critics to take a hike, it's difficult to
imagine what that motive might be. The easiest thing in the world
for him to do would have been to call off the upcoming trip to
China, and thereby disarm some of his surliest detractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going because I think it's the right thing to do for our
country,'' the president proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   He'll get plenty of argument on that point, especially from
critics of his policy allowing the transfer of U.S. satellite
technology to China when Chinese interests were allegedly
attempting to influence the American presidential election by
making substantial contributions to Clinton's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have gone so far as to describe Clinton's action as
treasonous, a description that surely falls into the category of
hyperbole. But the timing of the decision, along with other
questions about foreign campaign donations, obviously left the
president open to suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted in his speech that there was nothing unsavory
about the technology transfer, maintaining that he was merely
continuing a policy approved by President Reagan and implemented by
President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional committees are tripping all over one another in
their rush to investigate the policy, so we ought to find out soon
enough if Clinton was leveling with the public or engaging in one
of his patented tap dances around the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he seemed to be standing up to his critics in a
situation where he apparently had little to gain and plenty to
lose. Being a lame duck who must step down at the end of his
current term, Clinton would appear to have no further use for
Chinese campaign contributions _ if he had any use for them in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   And what could Clinton possibly imagine he might gain by
inviting more controversy at a time when he is already up to his
neck in controversy?
</P>
<P>
   True enough, a recent CBS News/''New York Times'' poll found
that 59 percent of those polled believed that Clinton should go
ahead with the China trip. But that would hardly seem to offset the
torrent of criticism that has engulfed Clinton in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech outlined the rationale for his belief that the
United States and the world will be better served by doing business
with China rather than cutting off communication with the most
populous nation on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that ``choosing isolation over engagement
would not make the world safer. It would make it more dangerous.
...
</P>
<P>
   ``It would hinder, not help, the cause of democracy and human
rights in China,'' Clinton added. ``It would set back, not step up,
worldwide efforts to protect the environment. It would cut off, not
open up, one of the world's most important markets.''
</P>
<P>
   America's ability to get along with China, Clinton said, ``will
in large measure help to determine whether the new century is one
of security, peace and prosperity for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton must believe all this stuff, or why would he say it?
What possible political benefit could accrue to an American
president who buddies up to a country that just nine years ago
slaughtered pro-democracy demonstrators in its capital city?
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton is Clinton, and you can't help but wonder if what
he believed yesterday is what he'll believe tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
