<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAD-SALESMAN-MEMORIES     06-17 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAD-SALESMAN-MEMORIES-ART-855&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAUGHTER GATHERS SWATCHES OF MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RACINE, Wis. _ I thought I saw my father at Lathrop's furniture
store the other day. He was standing by the Chiclets dispenser,
looking out over an endless sea of walnut gliders and lampshades
swaddled in crisp plastic wrappers. He was carrying his decrepit
leather sample case under his arm, so bursting with fabric swatches
he could barely keep it together with a piece of string.
</P>
<P>
   My father, Allan, was a furniture salesman. He died 20 years
ago, on a December morning when the sky and Lake Michigan were
slate-gray. He was 54 years old. I was 23. In some ways, it doesn't
seem as if much time has passed since he waited for me at O'Hare
field, arms open, at the bottom of the escalator.
</P>
<P>
   He was an ace salesman, ``the king of Milwaukee'' in his day.
But when he died, what he did for a living was still something of a
mystery to my sisters and me. Like many dads of the era, especially
those with daughters, he didn't talk about his work much. But the
swatches _ some nubby beige, some lustrous turquoise _ were
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Every Monday morning during my childhood, he would leave our
house in suburban Chicago and drive to those distant, exotic places
where the tornadoes were _ places like Davenport and Dubuque, Iowa;
Peoria and Rockford, Ill., and Kenosha, Racine, Milwaukee and
Sheboygan, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   We never knew much about what he sold. But my sister Lori
vividly remembers how proud she felt when a coordinated suite of
International Furniture, my father's line, flashed across the
screen in queenly splendor as a prize on ``The Newlywed Game,'' the
tweed accented with print pillows so it looked ravishing on
television.
</P>
<P>
   I visited Schnadig Corp., my father's old employer, and, in the
company of his former partner, Ivan Kushen, followed a bit of his
trail. I wanted to understand that missing dimension of his life,
the one spent between the yellow stripes and white dashes on the
highway. For a moment, I wanted to be surrounded by people who knew
that side of him, take comfort from them. I suppose I was looking
for swatches.
</P>
<P>
   Like my father, the furniture was snug and dependable, the stuff
that made people, including many suburban newlyweds, feel at home.
He went on the road in 1959, traveling the territory in loops to
visit ``dirty front interiors,'' as he was fond of calling them _
faded, largely family-owned Main Street furniture dealerships that
were his customers and today are vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   Schnadig Corp., founded in 1952, specialized in the kind of
middle-American furniture that long defined Chicago as a furniture
hub. Schnadig had a predilection for carved built-in tables that
would punctuate the ends of sofas and rope-turned feet resembling
threads on a screw. My first and only piece of my father's
furniture was a chocolate-brown velveteen sectional whose pieces
seemed mysteriously to repel each other, like magnetic poles.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest seller was Corona, a Mediterranean-inspired
collection, now campy looking, made glamorous with finials and gold
crushed-velvet seats. To my father, selling Corona was a
no-brainer; it still leaps off the pages of vintage catalogs. With
a mixture of fascination and horror, I received the news from Ivan
that it was probably Corona that put me through college, a
revelation somewhat akin to hauling up a fishing net and
discovering a giant squid.
</P>
<P>
   They call such furniture ``borax'' today. To my father, a born
optimist with rabid enthusiasm for many things _ including his
daughters, the Chicago Bears, the latest gadget and his own
birthday _ furniture was a commodity. We didn't grow up with
International furniture in our house. (My mother preferred modern,
boxy Paul McCobb.) But although it wasn't to his taste, he never
seemed condescending about what he sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't care what it looked like or if he liked it
personally,'' Ivan said as we drove up Highway 41 toward Milwaukee,
the road dipping occasionally beneath concrete viaducts. ``What
your father was really a genius at was selling a dealer what the
dealer could sell.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a furniture matchmaker. He rarely remembered order
numbers, describing pieces by drawing pictures of them in the air.
His sales technique could resemble the scoreboard erupting in
victory at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your father could work up a sweat selling an ottoman,'' Ivan
recalled with palpable affection. ``That's the way he was.''
</P>
<P>
   The qualities that made him a great father served him well in
business. In contrast to what happens today, when goods are
automatically reordered by computer and calling on customers every
60 to 90 days is no longer necessary, furniture dealers bought the
salesman as much as, if not more than, the furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days we used to buy from our friends, whether the
product was good or not,'' recalled Murray Brown, who bought from
my dad at Lathrop's in Racine and now owns Brown's Furnishings and
Design in Boca Raton and Jupiter, Fla. ``That personal touch _
having dinner, meeting the family _ is missing today. It was all
one big friendship. Now you can't find out who owns the company.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAD-SALESMAN-MEMORIES     06-17 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAD-SALESMAN-MEMORIES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 RACINE, Wis.: the company.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   His warmth was like the roads he traveled: uncomplicated,
without curves. He had no visible demons and an almost collegiate
sense of mirth. If he'd been a room, my father would have been a
patio. ``It was a loose, comfortable attitude he had,'' said Sondra
Rosin, who was hired by my dad in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very casual,'' recalled Norman Waxman, who was my
father's sales manager. ``He didn't get shaken up too much. He was
serious about business, but his demeanor wasn't.'' You always knew
how he felt.
</P>
<P>
   The company is alive and well today, even though many of the
small family-owned stores my father sold to no longer exist. The
furniture Ivan Kushen and other Schnadig colleagues sell to stores
like Seaman's, Haverty's and Sears Homelife has gotten far more
sophisticated over the years; those stores now have to compete with
discounters like Value City and chic chains like Pottery Barn.
</P>
<P>
   Tastes have changed for the better. People are ``globally
exposed today,'' in the words of Don Belgrad, the company's
chairman. ``People in Iowa have access to as much information as
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   At former customers of my father's, like Bachman's in Milwaukee
and Ingrassia in Rockford, the sales floors are still filled with
furniture wearing the Schnadig hangtag. It is still clustered in
intimate groupings, tables set with knickknacks and polished
silverware as if company were expected.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure my father would have sold the heck out of them. On one
level, he believed in his furniture, and like most Chicago sports
fans, he had that competitive urge.
</P>
<P>
   When he got sick, he was certain he would win. He would
outmaneuver the cancer as surely as he outmaneuvered traffic on the
Edens Expressway, occasionally driving on the shoulder to do it. He
remained upbeat, going down to the furniture market in High Point,
N.C. _ where he once tried to train a parrot to talk dirty to the
competition _ two months before he died. His last words were ``I'm
going to lick this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   At least a thousand swatches have come and gone since then. And
somehow, being able to drive down those roads, even for a moment,
was to be reconnected again. It turns out that the man whose
laughter and lightness sold who knows how many love seats, whom
people eagerly looked forward to seeing, was the same Dad I knew.
The details remain fuzzy, but the aura is clear.
</P>
<P>
   And I know that no matter how old I am, or even how wise a
parent I become, a small, quiet corner of me will always be a young
girl in Chicago, looking for her father at the bottom of the
escalator.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
