<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: FILES, PART II _ HOW TO USE THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since a file is a relatively simple tool, a piece of hardened
steel with teeth cut across the surface, using it should be fairly
straightforward and easy.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, all one has to do is push the file across the
work surface and drag it back to the starting position. Actually
this procedure can damage the work surface and dull the file.
Learning to file is not difficult, but proper filing depends upon
maintaining the right hand and arm position so that the tool moves
correctly over the workpiece. However, it only takes a little
practice to get it right.
</P>
<P>
   Most files are sold without handles. Never use a file without a
handle because the bare tang, the tapered, handle end, can cause
injury. File handles are sold at most hardware stores and home
centers, and one size handle will usually fit a wide range of
files. Depending on the type of handle, you only need to push or
twist it onto the tang.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the workpiece is especially large, it should be clamped
securely in a vise, ideally at elbow height. Protect the workpiece
by sandwiching it between soft wood blocks and position it low,
close to the jaws of the vise. This will prevent noisy vibrations
that can dull the file.
</P>
<P>
   The are two filing techniques: cross filing and draw filing.
Cross filing is used to remove material and reshape the work. Draw
filing is a finishing technique.
</P>
<P>
   Cross filing has many applications, so master this technique
first. Grasp the file handle with one hand and grip the file tip
with the fingers of the other hand.
</P>
<P>
   Hold the file horizontally and push it across the workpiece at a
sight angle. Exert enough pressure to insure even cutting. Too much
pressure will cause the file to skip and the work to vibrate and
chatter; too little will dull the file teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Do not allow the file to rock as you push or you could round
edges of the workpiece. Instead try to maintain the horizontal
line. The file only cuts on the push stroke, so lift it off on the
return stroke. Dragging the tool back will dull the teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Stop periodically to check the work surface for high spots or
depressions. Test the flatness with a straight edge. If the work is
curved, with the center higher than the edges, you are applying too
much pressure at the beginning and end of the stroke. If the work
is dished, with the center lower than the edges, the starting and
finishing pressure is too light. Changing the file angle slightly
will also help to erase any file tracks, the shallow grooves made
by the file teeth.
</P>
<P>
   After cross filing, the surface of the work is apt to be rough
with file marks. Draw filing will put a smooth finish on the piece
and remove the file marks. Use a single-cut file. Grip the file in
both hands and hold it at right angles to the workpiece. Whether
you push the tool away or pull it toward you depends upon the
position of the file handle. If it is on your right side, the
cutting stroke will be away from you (a push stroke). If the handle
is on your left side, execute a pull stroke. Always lift the file
off the work on the return stroke. After filing, wrap the tool in
emery cloth and draw it back and forth across to polish the work
surface.
</P>
<P>
   During the filing operation, the file teeth may become clogged
with metal or wood particles. These particles must be removed or
they will scratch the work surface. This clogged condition is
called ''pinning.'' It can usually be prevented with ordinary
blackboard chalk. Fill all the gaps between the file teeth by
rubbing the chalk liberally along the file. Always chalk the file
before working on soft metals or draw filing.
</P>
<P>
   Even with chalking, it is necessary to clean the file
periodically with a file card.
</P>
<P>
   The file card is flat brush with short wire bristles. To clean
the file, hold the card so it is parallel to the rows of teeth,
then pull it across the file. To dislodge stubborn metal particles,
use a metal pick (there may be one in a slot in the handle of the
file card) or a sharpened nail.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to store your files is by hanging them in a slotted
rack or placing them in a drawer with wooden partitions. Files
should never be allowed to rest on top of each other. This could
dull or chip their teeth. To keep your files from rusting, store
them away from water and moisture but do not oil them. Oil causes a
file to skip across a work surface.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
