<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-YOUTH-COX </SLUG>
     TALES OF YOUTH DRUG USE SHOW NEED FOR
PREVENTION, ANTIDRUG OFFICIAL SAYS
 &HT;     By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An undercover officer from Dayton, Ohio, told how
he bought LSD from a junior high school student.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-year-old Maryland girl charted her tumble into drug and
alcohol abuse from the age of 9, using ``anything that I could get
my hands on.''
</P>
<P>
   And a pediatrician recalled treating a 7-year-old girl, exposed
to drugs and alcohol before birth, who tried to stab another
second-grader at school with a pencil.
</P>
<P>
   Experiences such as these, related at a Senate Judiciary
Committee hearing Wednesday, show why youth anti-drug campaigns
that have dwindled since the 1980s should be reinstated and the
legalization of marijuana should be shunned, said Barry McCaffrey,
director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a new generation of kids,'' McCaffrey told the panel.
``We have to start over.''
</P>
<P>
   Drugs are becoming more accessible, leading children to
experiment with more dangerous drugs at an earlier age, McCaffrey
said. He said one in four 12th-graders have used an illegal drug in
the past month.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said he was ``astonished'' by the ``slick
misinformation propaganda campaign'' that aims to legalize
marijuana and other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beginning to hold sway in the judgment of people who
should know better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris, the 24-year-old undercover officer who testified behind a
glass shield to protect his identity, said that while assigned to
two high schools in an unidentified upper-middle-class Midwestern
neighborhood, he made multiple purchases of LSD from a junior high
school student.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students in this high school consumed at least 200 hits of
acid every two weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel, the 16-year-old Maryland girl who testified about her
plunge into drug and alcohol abuse, said she experimented with LSD,
cocaine, PCP and other drugs. She said she has been drug-free for
eight months, after several failed attempts to quit that left her
feeling isolated and depressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated myself, and I had no friends that liked me for who I
was,'' Rachel said, who asked that her last name not be publicized.
``They only liked me for the drugs I had.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show a steady growth in drug use, including a rise in
the number of eight-graders who have used marijuana from 10 percent
in 1991 to 23 percent in 1997, McCaffrey reported.
</P>
<P>
   And while marijuana is still the most widely use drug among
young people, the use of heroin and methamphetamine stimulants is
growing, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heroin is now pure and cheap _ as affordable as a ticket to a
movie,'' said Nancy Auer, president of the American College of
Emergency Physicians.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government spends about $16 billion a year on 70
programs in 57 different departments and agencies to fight illegal
drug use.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, emphasizing that prevention is the best way to combat
the drug problem, said a $195 million youth-oriented media campaign
launched in 12 pilot cities last year _ including Atlanta _ is
``already outstripping expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug prevention hot lines whose phone numbers were publicized
received at least twice as many calls than before the campaign,
McCaffrey said. The campaign is to be expanded nationwide next
month.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
