<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former UT coach Penders considered for George Washington job
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Penders, one of two finalists for the head basketball
coaching job at George Washington University, said he does not
consider himself a candidate for the position ``at this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Penders, a former University of Texas coach, and George
Washington assistant Kevin Clark are the frontrunners for the job
at the Atlantic-10 school in Washington D.C. A third finalist,
Delaware head coach and George Washington alum Mike Brey, withdrew
his name late Monday (June 15).
</P>
<P>
   The George Washington job opened when Mike Jarvis accepted the
position at St. John's after eight years with the Colonials.
</P>
<P>
   Sources indicate George Washington Athletic Director Jack
Kvancz, a longtime friend of Penders, wants Penders and Clark to
meet with school president Steven Joel Trachtenberg, as well as the
vice president for student services. The school hopes to name its
coach this week, perhaps as soon as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Penders was in San Diego Tuesday on a working holiday with his
wife and daughter. He said he has a broadcasting audition later
this week with ESPN at its studios in Bristol, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking for any (coaching) jobs,'' said Penders, who
has a clause in his new contract with Host Communications that
allows him to explore other coaching opportunities. ``It would take
a situation where I knew and trusted the athletic director to get
me to even consider it, but right now I'm excited about the TV
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say I'd never do it (return to coaching)
because that might not be truthful, but I don't know,'' added
Penders, 53, who in 10 seasons at Texas became the school's
winningest men's coach with a record of 208-110 before resigning
under pressure on April 2. ``I don't have an urge to get back into
coaching, but if the right situation came along where I knew the
people involved, that would be a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Penders knows several administrators at George Washington,
including Kvancz, a childhood friend who visited Penders for two
days in Austin last week. Both he and Penders said they did not
talk specifically about Penders taking the George Washington job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get to that point,'' Kvancz said late last week.
``He's obviously a quality candidate. But I just wanted to see what
his interest might be and pick his brain a little about other
people out there. We'll have more discussions if that's the way
we're going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Penders said he has not spoken to anyone from George Washington
since Kvancz returned to Washington last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
