<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forget New York, my tiny world has worries enough
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There are currently 7,380,906 people in
New York City, and I know this because I recently visited there and
spent my entire 96 or so hours _ no, no, not seeing ``Les Miz''
(that's what they call it up there) or visiting that much
talked-about Ellis Island. I spent my four days in true midwestern
form:
</P>
<P>
   Worrying about every single person I saw.
</P>
<P>
   All right already. My husband is after me to stop exaggerating,
so I have to confess. A few people up there do seem to be doing OK.
They live in this cool area called, what is it again? Oh yeah, the
Upper East Side, and I know they're fine because they can afford to
pay big rents and buy shoes with real leather uppers. Plus, a few
of them actually looked happy.
</P>
<P>
   There is much awe in my heart for the hardy souls of New York
City who each morning rise and shine. They have bosses and kids and
lunches to pack. They have places to go and people to meet. They
have lives, all 7 million of them. But, good grief, the obstacles
that stand in their way at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Crowded subways. Litter on the street. Gross-looking public
schools. If friends from college ever dare to visit, the
three-night hotel bill looks like a mortgage payment. And the smell
that floats up from those sidewalk grates. Good heavens! Why can't
that Rudy Giuliani guy leave the taxi drivers alone and do
something about that?
</P>
<P>
   Simmer down, says a man I work with, a man who actually _ are
you ready for this? _ grew up in New York City. If I lived up there
I wouldn't notice all this stuff. Yes, yes, he says. It is dirty
and people do seem a little distracted and, of course no one
establishes eye contact or smiles and says hello. That's because _
and he explained this oh-so-well that I wish I could remember it
word for word. It's because the people in New York City have
culture. And, from what I can gather, access to Connecticut on the
weekends doesn't hurt any either.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway shows. Great museums. Good Chinese restaurants. And,
this is my favorite part, you can walk to everything! What that
means, I guess, is that if you want to, you can walk to the Upper
East Side and touch a real tree.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not one to make rash decisions. I'm even trying to give
those men in the Southern Baptist church another chance, although
they'd better damn well hurry up. But I must tell you, I am not
made to survive in a city where everyone looks as though they need
a hug.
</P>
<P>
   We have a joke in our house, which _ as it turns out _ is no
joke at all. It's about the size of My World. My World, you see, is
small. The grocery store is a mile to the south. My kid's school is
2 miles to the east. The video store is right down from the grocery
store. The post office is in between the two. And the newspaper
office is smack in the middle. Every once in a while I do venture 4
or 5 miles outside this world to visit a good friend who has the
gall to reside outside my boundaries. But I like her, and her
children and husband are nice, so it's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Inside this world are just enough worries to keep me going. The
odd homeless woman who wears layers of wool in the summer heat. The
girls around the corner whose mothers let them roam the
neighborhood freely. Why, just six months or so ago my best
friend's car was stolen right out of their driveway!
</P>
<P>
   So, let that Giuliani fellow worry about all those folks up in
New York City, the ones who need a hug and a smile and a weekend in
the country. I've got enough to keep me going right here. And
that's no exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
