<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Area businessmen help Austin hurdler continue her career
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ The group of 50-something businessmen recently gathered
in the north end zone of Royal-Memorial Stadium to watch their
newest project gracefully glide over a series of hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   The men had never seen Tracy Mattes, a transplanted Austinite by
way of Wisconsin and Arizona, run her specialty, the 400-meter
hurdles. Yet they had been giving her about $1,000 a month since
January so she could continue training without having to take more
than one job to pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of mine was telling me about her,'' Ken Wendler said
as he watched Mattes take on the next hurdle. ``He told me about
how she had been a world-class hurdler, how she got malaria in
South Africa and was having a real hard time getting herself going
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a gal working part time but training full time, who
was working her heart out to try and make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattes will run in the U.S. Track and Field Championships this
week in New Orleans. Later this summer, she will fly to Europe to
participate in a series of meets that pays thousands of dollars to
the winners.
</P>
<P>
   The men, whom Mattes calls her ``angels,'' recently upped their
financial support, pooling together enough money to pay for her
plane fare to New Orleans and her expenses during her weeklong
stay. They intend to partially pay for her training until she can
attract sponsors such as Nike, which financially supports a number
of top athletes. Mattes also works as an assistant producer at
KXAN-TV. She trains at Memorial Stadium in the afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsements will come to her if Mattes, 28, can get back to
her pre- malaria form. A month before the 1996 U.S. Olympic Trials,
Mattes was ranked seventh in the world and fifth in the United
States in her event. She finished ninth at the trials and didn't
make the team, but still was able to hang on to her sponsorships
that paid about 75 percent of her living expenses. She got a
part-time job working as a television producer to pick up the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Mattes has been sponsored by Nike, the U.S. Olympic Committee,
Kodak and Bausch &AMP; Lomb. But when she contracted malaria while
competing in South Africa in January 1997, she almost was forced to
give up dream. Her sponsorships, which were based on her on-track
performances, dried up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being in the emergency room in Johannesburg,'' said
Mattes, who moved to Austin to train with University of Texas
assistant Dan Pfaff about a month before her trip to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hospital was horrible, it was a scene out of an old horror
film. I had to take the whole summer off just to get healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattes likely contracted malaria, which still is found in South
and Central America, Africa and Asia, through a bite from an
infected mosquito. The chills and high fever forced her to the
hospital and then out of competition until this spring.
</P>
<P>
   She said she never contemplated retiring to concentrate on a
career in television. She was forced to use her savings to pay
$10,000 in medical bils. By October, when she started training
again, she worked 25 hours a week at KXAN and 30 hours a week as a
clerk at a state agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `This really sucks. I'm 27 and I'm just about
to peak and then this happens,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her supporters, she said, ``came in at just the nick of time. I
didn't know whether I could continue (training and competing) or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   She has run a time of 58.76 seconds in the 400 hurdles, which
equaled the qualifying standard for the U.S. meet. But her group of
financial supporters, who are lawyers, contractors and developers,
will not be there to watch.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's running in the Olympics in Australia, then I'm
there,'' Wendler said. ``I think that would be real neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
