<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZ-OPERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WAGNERIAN MATCH: GRAND OPERA AND GRAND CANYON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Neb.)   (ja) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ Seven thousand feet up and a basso rumble
from the Grand Canyon is not a place where Franz Ehgartner expected
to find himself. A retired pharmacist from Graz, Austria, Ehgartner
had been to the United States only once before, last year, to see
the Wagner ``Ring'' Cycle at the Metropolitan Opera in New York.
But here he was on his 80th birthday at Ardrey Auditorium on the
campus of Northern Arizona University, between Act I and Act II of
``Gotterdammerung,'' the final opera of the ``Ring,'' presented by
the Arizona Opera Company.
</P>
<P>
   It was his 50th ``Ring'' or thereabouts since 1935, Ehgartner
said, in a translation from the German provided by another
operagoer (Heidi Herrmann of Seattle, who was completing her 33rd
``Ring''). ``I would not have come to America if it were not for
the `Ring,''' said Ehgartner, who was wearing a button with the
legend, ``Siegfried for President.'' A Wagnerite of substantial
pedigree, having 112 ``Die Meistersinger's'' under his belt as
well, he added: ``In particular I wanted to see a traditional
`Ring.' And I knew if Glynn Ross was doing it, it would be safe to
come and not see a modern version.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the confounding reputation of Ross, the general director
of the Arizona Opera for the last 15 years and of the Seattle Opera
Company for 20 years before that. He is an impresario openly
disdainful of the recent penchant for trickery like Rhinemaidens on
bungee cords and Valkyries on merry-go-rounds. ``I take my `Ring'
very seriously,'' he said. But he nonetheless was audacious enough
to put a place like Flagstaff on the international ``Ring''
circuit. ``When I talk to people in Germany, they call this `der
Vildenvest,''' said the baritone Edward Crafts, who has known Ross
for 35 years and sings Wotan in Arizona. ``I say, yeah, we're doing
der `Ring' in der Vildenvest.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross is to retire, at 83, at the end of June, having staged four
``Rings'' here and 20 in Seattle, two each June from 1975 through
1984. (The new director, Speight Jenkins, has continued to stage
``Rings,'' though not annually.) ``Seattle is now a `Ring' town,''
Ms. Herrmann said. Even though a year removed from a mild stroke,
Ross is still a man who flashes both the imperious and gregarious
sides that make a showman. He speaks loudly _ his hearing is on the
wane _ and with the assurance that people are listening. He was
born in South Omaha, Neb., and began his opera career in Los
Angeles as an assistant director for a production of ``Faust'' in
1940. But after World War II, during which he was injured in North
Africa and then ran a military hotel in Italy, he assumed he'd be
going into the hotel business as a civilian.
</P>
<P>
   It was on a cross-country drive with his new Italian wife,
Angelamaria Solimene (they've been married 52 years; everyone calls
her Gio), that he made the pivotal decision of his career. They
were visiting the Four Corners, half a day's drive from here across
the painted desert, where Arizona meets New Mexico, Colorado and
Utah. ``We were in the motel, and my wife said to me, `Do you want
to go into hotels or go into opera?''' he said. ``And I said,
`Opera, of course.'''
</P>
<P>
   He is known as a populist promoter of opera in general and
Wagner in particular. In Seattle, long before the Broadway show
``Rent,'' he advertised a production of ``La Boheme'' as a show
about sex and drugs, and promoted a Richard Strauss work with the
phrase ``Get ahead with `Salome,''' using print graphics borrowed
from ``The Rocky Horror Picture Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Such use of humor and irreverence in advertising, he said, ``is
probably my biggest contribution to opera in America.'' For years
he has been comparing the ``Ring'' to sex for reporters who ask
what makes Wagner so special. ``It has to be performed
contiguously,'' he said in an interview, ``within a proper
circumstance and with a proper attitude.'' Excuse me, but hasn't he
said this before? ``I have my script,'' he acknowledged with an
embarrassed grin. ``But I mean sex in the primordial, Darwinian,
survival-of-the-species kind of way, not as an entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been called, in print, ``the most affable megalomaniac in
opera'' and ``the bantam of the opera,'' and occasionally worse, a
reflection of the hoity-toity opera world's occasional
umbrage-taking at the used-car salesmanship with which Ross tends
to put across his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The Flagstaff ``Ring'' was born shortly after Ross came to
Arizona, where the opera company, which performs a regular season
in Tucson and Phoenix, had hired him, among other things, to
blacken $750,000 of red ink. It was on a flight over the Grand
Canyon that he had the idea. ``It seemed like a natural, the `Ring'
at the Grand Canyon, the grandeur of both,'' he said. ``It would
make a good bite for the press. And it so happens there's a Wotan
Mountain here.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did in Seattle, he put on each of the individual operas
during consecutive regular seasons before doing the whole cycle, to
form a company and create the sets. (This is one reason the budget
for the entire ``Ring'' this year is a minuscule $1.3 million;
another is that the singers work for cut-rate salaries. Ross, a
master of penury, has balanced 34 consecutive budgets. ``I think
that's unique,'' he said.)
</P>
<P>
   His marketing of opera is tied to the location. Thus, the
audience for the ``Ring'' is almost entirely separate from the
subscription audience in Tucson and Phoenix, and the visitors to
Flagstaff, like Ehgartner, have spent their off days on organized
tours of the Grand Canyon and attending lectures comparing German
mythology with Hopi mythology. The ``Ring'' they saw was
uncluttered, even spare, the scenery almost entirely consisting of
projections on a screen behind the stage. The action took place on
a bare raised platform, so that the duets, with the characters
stalking each other, often had the feel of a wrestling match.
</P>
<P>
   But the voices _ including George Gray as Siegfried and Karen
Bureau as Brunnhilde _ were powerful. Some of the aficionados,
including Ehgartner, were distressed by some of the unconventional
staging decisions: that both Siegfried and Gunther are onstage
during the deception of Brunnhilde, for instance, and that after
Siegfried's death both Wotan and Siegmund are brought back to view
the body. The director, Lutz Seelig, suffered as a result during
the curtain call. ``He ruined the entire `Ring' for me,'' said
Leigh Metcalf, a high school teacher from Fullerton, Neb., who was
seeing his 21st ``Ring'' and who booed lustily as Seelig appeared
from the wings for a bow.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely anyone held any of this against Ross. Before the
opening curtain of ``Gotterdammerung,'' he appeared onstage to say
that the conductor, Stefan Minde, would be conducting even though
he was ill and might have to be replaced in mid-performance. But
even Minde's curtain call after he lasted through the five-hour
performance did not elicit the response that Ross' appearance
beforehand did. The audience stood and applauded. ``Bravo!'' they
cried. ``Bravo!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
