<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T EAT IT? FORGET IT!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You wouldn't know it to look at me, thank goodness, but my
thighs are pretty good friends, touching just enough so I never
forget that they're there, loving each other.
</P>
<P>
   This generally doesn't bother me until my annual visit to Dr.
Langham's office, when that cute skinny nurse announces, ``Um,
looks like 'bout 145.'' I step off the scale and want to strangle
her. I grumble about the scale being all wrong, and wonder why they
can't get the thing fixed. It's no wonder I don't own one.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, I think I might take my husband up on those
morning walks. Maybe I ought to use that aerobics video my sister
gave me, or the glide-rider I stood in line to buy months ago.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if I'm doomed, if it's true what my sisters say about
turning 40, even though I haven't gained a pound in nearly 10
years. I can't forget that heart disease is a leading killer among
African-American women. I worry that one day my heart will explode,
as my mother's did at age 43.
</P>
<P>
   This lasts, of course, only until the next mealtime.
</P>
<P>
   I reason that I'm a perfect size 8. That even though I eat a
lot, I try to eat healthfully and drink lots of water. That despite
what the scale says, I'm not really overweight. It's like my
7-year-old daughter, Asha, said one morning as we prayed: ``Lord,
thank you for the food, because you know we Staples women love to
eat.''
</P>
<P>
   And, you might say, we look like it. The Texas Rangers have
``Pudge'' Rodriguez. I've got Pudge Asha and Pudge Jamila. And me,
I'm just Fat, they tell me.
</P>
<P>
   We laugh. I walk three days one week and quit. I joined the YMCA
so many times, only to quit, that our personnel department told me
I couldn't do it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   So I don't really exercise. Doesn't near-constant movement
account for something? How about cleaning the house? I can seldom
get that done without breaking a sweat. And what about the grocery
shopping, and the mall shopping, and chauffeuring of my daughters
hither and yon?
</P>
<P>
   Who has time for exercise?
</P>
<P>
   The last time I decided to work off my thighs, my daughters and
I put the video in and proceeded to squat, up and down, up and
down. For days thereafter, I could barely walk. Not only could I
not climb the stairs without excruciating pain, I couldn't come
back down. I thought I might die.
</P>
<P>
   My daughters laughed at me, but exercising for them is just as
sporadic. So they rode their bikes twice after that Christmas
morning long ago. So they run through the house instead of walking.
So they perk up at any mention of an aerobics video deal on
television. So what?
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Jamila, my 9-year-old, handed me a note she had
scribbled in pencil informing me that I could purchase an aerobics
video in ``three easy payments'' of $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hips-buns-thighs,'' it reads. ``1-800-404-9889; if you don't
see results in 30 days, send it back and get a refund.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah. All I need is one more thing to collect dust. Can't eat
it, I'm not buying.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) .MDBR/.MDBR/
</P>
</TEXT>
