<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XFILES-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 WAYS TO HEAR `X-FILES`
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; There are two separate soundtracks to ``The
X-Files'' movie, but there's really nothing mysterious about the
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe that's just what they want you to think.
</P>
<P>
   One disc _ at No. 38 this week in the nation's albums chart _ is
driven by new songs from the likes of Foo Fighters, Filter, Tonic,
Ween, the Dust Brothers, Aswad &AMP; Sting, the Cardigans, the Cure,
Bjork and Soul Coughing.
</P>
<P>
   The other CD features Mark Snow's entire instrumental score to
the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (`X-Files' creator) Chris Carter appreciated our sense
of irony and humor and wanted us to apply that to the theme and put
an ironic twist or some level of comedy to it,'' explained Mike
Simpson of the Dust Brothers, the hip Silver Lake production team
who interpreted the show's theme on the songs compilation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the album's producer, David Was (real name Weiss),
said his wish list began with a hundred names, but ``got cut down
to the point where you hope you can get 11 acts and fill in the
rest with stuff that isn't embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Was, co-founder of the soon-to-reunite '80s dance-rock group Was
(Not Was), added that the process took four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like this _ on Monday, you're a genius, on Tuesday,
you're a loser and on Wednesday, you develop a sense of reality,''
said the Tarzana-based Was, who describes himself as a
``dyed-in-the-wool conspiracy buff.''
</P>
<P>
   Was, a longtime ``X-Files'' fan, said while he would never claim
to be abducted by space aliens himself, ``I wouldn't put anything
past the CIA to create mass delusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a longtime new-music fan, was involved in picking the
tracks and developing the songs project. Two years ago, another
``X-Files'' album offered music inspired by the show from Elvis
Costello, Sheryl Crow and others.
</P>
<P>
   Was said one track that got away was a proposed collaboration
between trip-hopper Tricky and Tom Waits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was unlikely, but it came within an inch of
happening,'' Was explained. ``None of these guys could make it to
the other guy's coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights of the songs album on Elektra is X covering
the Doors' ``The Crystal Ship,'' the Cure doing Roxy Music's ``More
Than This'' and Aswad &AMP; Sting performing a reggae version of the
Police's ``Invisible Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``X-Files'' movie opens Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
