A3868 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-GENESIS-COX     06-17 0326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-GENESIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Genesis set best of 2 worlds
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Box sets typically come in two varieties: Those that showcase an
artist's best work in a way that invites a new assessment of it and
those that offer a handful of unreleased rarities for the rabid
fan. This hefty Genesis collection manages to do both.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking the British progressive-rock outfit's most innovative
and indulgent period, this set covers the group from its mid-'60s
days as an art-school collective to its mid-'70s heyday, when
singer-composer Peter Gabriel was its outlandish driving force.
Most of what's here features Gabriel, Tony Banks, Steve Hackett,
Michael Rutherford and Phil Collins _ a partnership that ended in
1975, when Gabriel went solo.
</P>
<P>
   Two discs compile the band's surrealistic opus, ``The Lamb Lies
Down on Broadway,'' from Gabriel's last tour. This much-bootlegged
live L.A. show has been restored and polished to a high gloss in
the studio, spruced up with new vocals and overdubs. Discs three
and four feature more live material _ including the 27-minute epic
``Supper's Ready'' and works from ``Selling England by the Pound''
_ and a hodgepodge of early demos, rough mixes and other oddities
that provide an intriguing, if not always satisfying, glimpse of a
young band in search of a sound.
</P>
<P>
   This retrospective won't win over new fans or anyone who
preferred the pop appeal of ``Abacab'' to the bat-winged theatrics
of ``Watcher of the Skies.'' But for art-rock enthusiasts, it's a
satisfying and guilty pleasure that captures the essence of one of
rock's most exploratory, if pretentious, offshoots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genesis Archives
</P>
<P>
   Volume 1: 1967-1975''
</P>
<P>
   Genesis. Atlantic. 49 tracks,
</P>
<P>
   4 CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A top-notch retrospective look at one of
progressive rock's pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
