A3877 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAREDO-PROBE-HNS &LR;      06-17 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAREDO-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIMINAL PROBE OF DA'S OFFICE UNDER WAY, U.S. SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Seeking to keep a 73-page document secret,
federal prosecutors have acknowledged that a grand jury is
investigating allegations of criminal activity involving a South
Texas district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors want the document to remain sealed because they
say it contains information about confidential sources, secretly
recorded telephone conversations and names of witnesses who are
cooperating with the government probe, Assistant U.S. Attorney Don
DeGabrielle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a substantial probability that the government's
investigation would be irreparably harmed if the sealed documents
were released,'' DeGabrielle said.
</P>
<P>
   He made the argument in a brief filed Tuesday with U.S. District
Judge John Rainey, who sealed the documents late last month after
issuing search warrants that FBI and Internal Revenue Service
agents used in a series of raids here.
</P>
<P>
   Should the information be made public, prosecutors fear evidence
would be destroyed, people would tailor their testimony and
witnesses would risk being harassed, DeGabrielle told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is substantial concern that disclosure of information
sources will deter future witnesses from coming forward with
information if they fear publicity or being exposed to harassment,
threats, intimidation, or worse by criminal suspects,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sealed document _ a 72-page affidavit for a search warrant _
describes why federal agents believed they would find evidence of
criminal wrongdoing involving Webb County District Attorney Joe
Rubio and others.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not said why the office is under
investigation. No arrests have been made in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit was reviewed by Rainey before he signed a series
of search warrants enabling federal agents to search Rubio's
office, his father's home and several other Laredo locations.
</P>
<P>
   Emilio ``Chito'' Davila, an attorney hired to represent Rubio,
said his client had done nothing wrong and that he hoped
prosecutors would use as much energy to clear Rubio's name as they
have to carry out the probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be the appropriate, right and fair thing to do to
restore confidence,'' Davila said. ``Hopefully, that confidence can
be restored.''
</P>
<P>
   Davila said he suspects the only reason the district attorney
has drawn into case was because he heads that office.
</P>
<P>
   A court document shows that at least 142 people, including
several members of Rubio's staff, are under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department contends all information relating to the
search warrants should remain sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents carted more than 5,000 documents from Rubio's
office, including criminal case files, personal financial
statements and documents showing when and how decisions were made
to drop charges, offer plea bargains or enable first-time
defendants to avoid trial with pre-trial diversion.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those documents were returned Monday as part of an
agreement between federal prosecutors and Rubio's office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
