<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Recent bout of carping not my finest hour
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 21: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My daughter said I have gotten sharp-tongued and nasty and she
wonders what has happened to my erstwhile easy, tolerant
disposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mush-mouthed,'' a friend called it. I don't think I have ever
been what people are prone to call ``sweet,'' a loathsome term, but
I confess to being unreasonably angry and critical the last few
days.
</P>
<P>
   First, a visitor at our beach house annoyed me by trying to take
any task I undertook out of my hands. ``I'll get that for you!''
she cried when I reached for a bag of garbage. ``No!'' I shouted.
``I'm as strong as you are and it's my house and my garbage!''
Crestfallen, she backed away, but she didn't stop getting in my way
when I started to pick up something. And when I lugged a stepladder
upstairs so we could scrub the ceiling fans, she almost broke her
neck trying to climb it ahead of me. ``I climb ladders,'' I said
icily. My daughter intervened. ``Mother, she's younger than we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   My impulse was to say, ``I may be old, but I'm not fat!'' Fat
people should stay off ladders, but in the end, the pleasingly
plump one and I shared the task. I wiped the smoky whiskers off the
fan blades, and she followed with soap and water.
</P>
<P>
   Later, there was a discussion of drivers for our trip home. I
hate being driven, and it was their idea that one of them would
drive my car and I would lounge in the back of my daughter's big
Land Rover, taking my ease and being pampered. I hated it. ``I'm a
good driver,'' I protested, ``and it's my car!''
</P>
<P>
   It was so tactless and rude, even I noticed it, and capitulated
and let the visitor drive my car. But I'll never be really grateful
for her services.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the worst evidence of my bad manners was at my
grandson's graduation. The seniors were beautiful in their caps and
gowns, the service was moving _ except for one thing. A pretty girl
was chewing gum the entire time. She looked like a billy goat
chomping away. So afterward as we met outside, guess who said,
``Honey, you shouldn't chew gum in public!'' She looked stricken,
and my daughter tells me I ruined the day for her. I ask the Lord
to forgive me for that.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's what I did to my kind, always helpful
son-in-law. I asked him where something I needed was and he said,
``I have no idea!'' I have an unreasoning aversion to that answer,
but I could have let it go. Instead, I gave him an uncalled-for
lecture. ``To say, `I have no idea!' instead of `I'm sorry, I don't
know,' suggests that you are glad you don't know,'' I told him in a
tediously teacherlike voice. He smiled and prepared to leave. I
wouldn't let him go. I suggested that his children should be taught
to say, ``I'm sorry, I don't know,'' instead of the arrogant
sounding ``I have no idea.'' He nodded equably and made his
getaway.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter tells me he paid no attention and doesn't remember,
and I'm glad. I mention it to warn anybody who is in danger of
becoming carping and critical that it's no fun. I'm back to being
sugar-mouthed ... if possible.
</P>
<P>
   There may be some dark, sinister reason I'm furious at
well-meaning efforts to take care of me. A lot of people are
grateful when somebody offers to drive them. They don't look on it
as an indictment of their competence. I know women who can sit
still when guests take over their kitchens. As for gum-chewing, who
made me Miss Manners for today's generation? I'm ashamed, and I
confess, hoping there's a lesson here for some other cranky old
broad.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
