<HEADER>
A3891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-VIDEO-MINIREVIEWS     06-17 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-VIDEO-MINIREVIEWS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini Views: Reviews of the latest movies out on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``Spice World'' (PG) _ Keeping its target audience of preteen
girls firmly in mind, this is a bubble-gum movie _ snappy, colorful
and instantly disposable. Based on an ``idea'' by the Spice Girls
(an idea they apparently had while watching ``A Hard Day's
Night''), the movie purports to be a few days in their frenzied
lives. Concert performances, recording sessions, parties, girl
talk, etc. Breezily directed by Bob Spiers (of ``Fawlty Towers''
and ``Absolutely Fabulous''), the movie is what it is _ nothing for
cineastes or music hipsters to bother with, but well-tailored for
its adolescent audience. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Fallen'' (R) _ For his second feature, director Gregory
Hoblit goes from the diabolical human nature of ``Primal Fear'' to
the genuinely demonic. Denzel Washington plays a homicide detective
fresh off the execution of a serial killer. But soon enough,
copycat murders start to plague the city ... or could it be the
same killer? The movie doesn't keep us in suspense for long,
showing that the culprit is a demon that passes from human to human
with the ease of a touch. And that's a problem for the movie: How
do you keep our interest in an invisible, nearly invincible force
of evil? The movie spins its wheels entertainingly enough, as
Washington researches the nature of devils. He's aided by Donald
Sutherland and John Goodman in supporting roles. But the movie
works itself into a corner from which there's only one escape: a
feel-bad, ``surprise'' ending. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Switchback'' (R) _ Obsessed FBI agent Dennis Quaid, affable
retired railroader Danny Glover, and hitchhiking former med student
Jared Leto _ any one of them could be a vicious serial killer.
Alas, after a character-driven unconventional start, this
suspense-thriller from the screenwriter of ``Die Hard'' and ``The
Fugitive'' lapses into an action-driven too-conventional finale.
Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
