A3892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-LATIFAH-COX     06-17 0259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-LATIFAH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Queen reigns without force
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before ``Living Single'' and ``Set It Off,'' Queen
Latifah's music suggested she had versatility. After the
rapper/actress' ``All Hail the Queen'' in 1989 introduced her with
the insistence of ``Ladies First,'' she moved deftly into dance
(``Come Into My House'') and purposeful rap (``U.N.I.T.Y.'').
</P>
<P>
   She's never resided in one genre, and now it seems the Queen,
born Dana Owens, isn't one to adhere to titles either. On ``Order
in the Court'' she begins with the usual believable rap bravado on
``Bananas.'' But after that she turns to some pretty silky R&AMP;B and
barely memorable hooks made better by more singing than rhyming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn You On'' reworks vocalist Cherrelle's hit into a sharper
retort to a man who mistakes kindness as an invitation for romance.
``Parlay'' employs dreamy acid jazz. And ``Paper'' mines Marvin
Gaye's ``I Heard It Through the Grapevine'' for vocal style and
musical structure.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven singles pass between ``Bananas'' and the next
easy-to-recognize rap track, ``Brownsville.'' And though it's
certainly a pleasant musical journey, it's filler. And force is
what you expect from the Queen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Order in the Court''
</P>
<P>
   Queen Latifah. Motown. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: More R&AMP;B with rapper Queen Latifah up front. Her
voice and pen are still strong enough to prop up weak melodies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
