<HEADER>
A3894 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-XFILES-COX     06-17 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-XFILES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A hipper side to `The X-Files'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soundtracks these days frequently are mere marketing tie-ins to
movies, hipper (and more profitable) alternatives to Burger King
commemorative cups. So the soundtrack to ``The X-Files: Fight the
Future,'' which opens Friday, has two songs out of 14 that appear
in the film: a cover of the Doors' ``Crystal Ship'' by the L.A.
post-punk band X and a reworking of the TV theme by the Dust
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The rest is a decent roundup of unreleased songs by the usual
alt-rockers: Tonic, Ween, Bjork, the Cardigans, Noel Gallagher (of
Oasis). Acts contributed songs without having seen the film, but
were trying to capture the series' blend of paranoia and the
paranormal (and mostly succeeding).
</P>
<P>
   The Foo Fighters' melodic ``Walking After You'' has a fittingly
ambiguous chorus line: ``I'm on your back.'' From one cop to
another (``X-Files'' is about FBI agents), this is reassuring; from
one lover to another, it's creepily claustrophobic.
</P>
<P>
   Filter contributes a primal screamin' cover of the Three Dog
Night oldie ``One'' that fits the show's sense of isolation
metaphorically, while Better Than Ezra's ``One More Murder'' works
more literally.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the shows should seek out the hidden spoken track, which
starts 10 minutes and 13 seconds after the last track ends (creator
Chris Carter's Tenthirteen production company is named for his Oct.
13 birthday). For the first time, Carter briefly outlines the
history of the conspiracy underpinning the show.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get confused _ there's also a score to the ``X-Files''
movie, which is instrumental music by Mark Snow and aimed at the
hard-core X-phile, not the 99X listener, as this one is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files: The Album''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Elektra. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Creepy alt-rock accompaniment to the new film.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
