<P>
   FLORDIA-FIRES _ Florida's wildfires, like the record hot weather
in the state, just won't go away. It's so bad that many communities
may cancel July 4 fireworks. A look at the latest hot spot and,
hopefully, comments from folks leaving their homes and firefighting
crews from Georgia and Alabama who are on the front lines waiting
to chase the next flareup. (MWilliams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-WALDO _ WALDO, Fla. _ Hundreds of residents returned to
this small town northeast of Gainesville after an evacuation order
was lifted Wednesday. Wildfires threatened their homes, along with
many others in northeastern Florida, as thousands of acres burned
out of control across the state and dry conditions persisted.
(Date, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEARWASTE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ 14 Mexican delegates are meeting
with Texas state officials today to protest the location of a
proposed nuclear waste site in Sierra Blanca, which apparently is
within 20 miles of the Rio Grande. They are meeting with Sec. of
State Gonzales in the morning before the press conference. (Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-SOUTH _ The Southern Regional Education Board releases
a report, Education and Progress in the South, which looks at
education over the past 60 years. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ A report from Fob James' campaign bus and and an
advance on tonight's gubernatorial debate. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERNECON _ The South's strong economic position in 1998
looks even more phenomenal when contrasted with the impoverished
and backward region described in a 1938 federal report, a 60-year
contrast dramatized in a new report given Wednesday to the U.S.
Department of Education in Washington. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
