<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-TUBETOPS-COX     06-17 0261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-TUBETOPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tubes are tops once again
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 21: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's one summer trend that could very well go bust.
</P>
<P>
   Few looks are viewed as skeptically by women as tube tops.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that most major designers included body-hugging
bandeauxs in their summer collections, or that stores ranging from
Sears to Saks Fifth Avenue are peddling them.
</P>
<P>
   Many women don't think they're fit enough to wear tube tops, and
they look critically at the women who do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Lord,'' said Atlantan Kendra Taylor, 25. ``Those things
should be banned! They're fine if you've got the right body for
them, like that (veejay) Ananda on MTV who wears them a lot.
Unfortunately, most of the women I've seen in them don't seem to
realize that they do make foundation garments you can wear under
those things. Without the proper support, your chest just hangs out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, today's tube tops look less _ um _ cheap than they did
during '70s, thanks to superior stretch fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Allard, design director for the Ellen Tracy label favored
by corporate climbers, had to weigh the pros and cons before making
modest, mature-looking tube tops the basis of her summer
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little daring and not so easy to wear,'' she admitted.
``But so many women today are in such good shape. They think, `If
I've got it, I should flaunt it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1807EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
