<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS-COX     06-17 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio mini reviews: The latest word on current sounds
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault, Doug Hamilton, Al Levine, Miriam Longino, Sonia
Murray, and Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- URBAN
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Dolittle''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Atlantic. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The ``Dr. Dolittle'' soundtrack does a lot to interest R&AMP;B and
rap listeners. If you like your tempo slow, Changing Faces wraps
its fine vocals around a lesser ballad (``Do Little Thing''). The
69 Boyz' party/sports anthem ``Woof Woof'' takes things up to
roof-raising proportions and former En Vogue member Dawn Robinson
takes on, respectfully, Aretha Franklin's ``Rock Steady.'' But what
``Dolittle'' does best is highlight producer-artist Timbaland's
inventive way with a track. He crafts four of the better songs here
and makes the lead single by Aaliyah, ``Are You That Somebody,''
practically irresistible with a sample of a baby's giggle.
</P>
<P>
   -- COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody Love,
</P>
<P>
   Nobody Gets Hurt''
</P>
<P>
   Suzy Bogguss. Capitol. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   How many comebacks does one artist get? Where Suzy Bogguss is
concerned, the answer is: how ever many she wants. She's made only
two original albums since 1993. Motherhood became a priority. But
Bogguss is back, better than ever. She's definitely the queen of
cerebral country, with songs like the title track about a
poor-spelling, would-be robber with a Freudian slip. She rocks
(``From Where I Stand''), she muses (``Train of Thought''), she
dishes out the advice (``Somebody to Love'') and makes you want to
say: Don't stay away so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``How I Feel''
</P>
<P>
   Terri Clark. Mercury. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Terri Clark may have begun with gimmicks in her big
I'm-one-of-the-boys hat and tight jeans, but her third CD proves
more than calculated marketing. Canadian Clark has a country voice
as pure and unaffected as rain on a tin roof and she's kept the
production on this album as simple as a gutter spout. No annoying
electric lounge piano, no pop arrangements. These tunes are draped
in musical cotton: simple acoustic guitar, fiddles, mandolin and
pedal steel. Clark's cover of Kim Richey's ``I'm Alright'' is as
good as the spunky original. The title tune, a cover of a song
originally intended for an R&AMP;B audience, fits Clark's twang with
ease.
</P>
<P>
   -- COUNTRY-ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Blackjack David''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Alvin. Hightone Records.
</P>
<P>
   11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Since the breakup in 1985 of his great roots-rock band, the
Blasters, Dave Alvin has released a string of solo albums that
never quite captured the audience they deserved. While Dwight
Yoakam and X have scored with covers of his songs, Alvin's own
efforts have been ghettoized on low-watt Americana radio stations.
``Blackjack David'' probably won't make him a household name,
either. While chock full of evocative country-folk melodies and
polished playing, it's decidedly unflashy _ a big no-no in this
glitzy era of Shania Twain and Garth Brooks. Guess Alvin will have
to be content with the ability to write near-perfect gems like
``California Snow.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Lynyrd Skynyrd Lyve From Steeltown''
</P>
<P>
   Lynyrd Skynyrd. CMC International.15 tracks (2 CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   This plodding effort is about what you'd expect from the latest
Skynyrd lineup: Another live hits package with new concert versions
of the old tunes that sound a lot like the old versions. No
surprises here. And few sparks. Ten of the 15 tracks were on LS's
two previous, superior live albums: 1976's ``One More From the
Road'' (recorded at the Fox Theatre) and '87's ``Southern by the
Grace of God.'' Even on the new tunes, the good old boys of
Southern rock sound like they've abandoned their Rebel yell style
and are just going through the motions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Premonition''
</P>
<P>
   John Fogerty. Reprise. 18 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Far superior to any previous best-of and live albums, this
live-in-the-studio set is all anyone could ask of John Fogerty,
a.k.a. Creedence Clearwater Revival. It's got fiery guitar work,
rock-solid beats and Fogerty's distinctively strangulated
swamp-rock vocals. All that's wrapped around 18 tracks, including
``Fortunate Son,'' ``Proud Mary'' and other great CCR tunes, along
with ``Centerfield'' and other merely good songs from his solo
career.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
