<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-DOVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bonham Carter flies high in `Dove'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Wings of the Dove'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   After a few too stately Henry James adaptations (``Portrait of a
Lady,'' say), Iain Softley's film dusts off the literary cobwebs
and gets to the driving forces of most any story: power, money,
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Helena Bonham Carter (in an Oscar-nominated performance) plays
Kate Croy, a penniless woman in Edwardian London, who is taken
under the diamond-dripping wings of her aunt (Charlotte Rampling).
The problem is, the man Kate loves _ journalist Merton Densher
(Linus Roache) _ is exactly the sort of low-income fellow her aunt
refuses to let her marry.
</P>
<P>
   So, while Kate vacillates between dull parties for the wealthy
and secret trysts with Merton, she makes a new friend. And hits on
a scheme. The new friend is fabulously wealthy Millie Theale
(Alison Elliott), an American who also happens to be terminally
ill. The scheme? Well, think about it ...
</P>
<P>
   Shot largely in the mournful beauty of Venice, ``Wings'' charts
the unexpected ways the heart can trip up any plan. Elliott is the
weak link of the acting trio; she's not bad, it's just very hard to
pull off an aura of goodness. But Bonham Carter (once little more
than a pretty face, now a real actor) is exquisite to watch her
Kate become not only the agent but the victim of her own scheming.
Grade: A -
</P>
<P>
   -- Other Henry James adaptations: ``The Innocents,'' ``The
Bostonians,'' ``The Portrait of a Lady,'' ``The Heiress,''
``Washington Square.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
