<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, June 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled weather will cover much of the central portion of the
nation Thursday as a strong disturbance in the jet stream passes
through the region. A fast flow of humid air from the south rising
up and over a warm front will cause heavy showers and embedded
thunderstorms from the eastern Dakotas to the upper Mississippi
Valley. A protracted period of heavy rain may result in local
flooding, particularly in Iowa and northern Illinois. Additional
showers will also occur in the western Dakotas as moist air
circulates around low pressure near the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   As the jet stream disturbance intercepts an unusually sultry air
mass, scattered severe thunderstorms will erupt from the Red River
Valley to the middle Mississippi Valley. Winds shifting direction
and increasing with altitude will induce a few of these
thunderstorms to rotate. These rotating storms, known as
supercells, are capable of producing tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and scattered showers will affect northern New England as
low pressure advances northeast through the Saint Lawrence Valley.
Meanwhile, ample sunshine will cover the remainder of the Northeast
and Middle Atlantic states. Farther south, strong high pressure
will promote dry and hot conditions from south Texas to the Florida
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   A pool of unusually cool air will drift south into the Pacific
Northwest, bringing low clouds and chilly conditions to western
sections of Washington and Oregon. Elsewhere, ample sunshine and
seasonable conditions will cover California and the Southwestern
states.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Florida Heat
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the temperature soared to a record 101 degrees at
Daytona Beach, Fla. This marked the 9th day this June that the city
tied or broke a record high temperature and the 7th day this month
that the city reached the century mark. While sultry air is common
in Florida this time of the year, such extreme heat is rare.
Typically, the difference in daytime heating between the peninsula
and nearby Atlantic Ocean induces cooling sea breezes. Circulation
around high pressure over the Gulf of Mexico has caused persistent
winds from the west which have kept cooling sea breezes at bay
along the Florida's northeast coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
