<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: WYETH MUSEUM TO OPEN; CLEARWATER FESTIVAL MOVES;
MARILYN HORNE AT CARAMOOR; `VICTORIAN FAIRY PAINTING' IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1944, the future founders of the Farnsworth Art Museum's
collection in Rockland, Maine, bought four watercolors by an
emerging artist. His name was Andrew Wyeth. On Sunday, in
connection with its 50th anniversary, the museum, with some 4,500
works of art and objects made by the Wyeths, will open the
Farnsworth Center for the Wyeth Family in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Comprising exhibition space and a study center in a new
building, the center is devoted to works created in and about Maine
by three generations of the artistic family: N.C. Wyeth
(1882-1945), his son Andrew Wyeth (born 1917) and Andrew's son
Jamie Wyeth (born 1946). The inaugural exhibition, ``Wondrous
Strange,'' includes more than 100 works and examines the influence
of the illustrator Howard Pyle, N.C. Wyeth's teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Riparian Rites
</P>
<P>
   After a decade inland at the Westchester Community College in
Valhalla, N.Y., the Clearwater Festival is returning to the Hudson
River, where the environmental arts-and-music event will take place
at Marist College in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering, formally Clearwater's Great Hudson River Revival,
will offer more than 50 performers of folk, jazz, blues and other
music between 10 a.m. and dusk.
</P>
<P>
   Among the scheduled entertainers, some of whom will appear only
on one day, are the David Amram Quartet, Judy Collins, Odetta, the
Paul Winter Consort and Pete Seeger, who originated the festival in
1966. Other features will be children's performances, storytelling,
a craft show, jugglers, environmental displays and ethnic foods.
</P>
<P>
   Summer Sounds
</P>
<P>
   The mezzo-soprano Marilyn Horne is to star on Saturday, when the
53rd annual Caramoor International Music Festival in Katonah, N.Y.,
begins with a gala featuring Soovin Kim, winner of the 1996 Nicolo
Paganini International Violin Competition, and the Orchestra of St
Luke's.
</P>
<P>
   This season, running through Aug. 9 under the artistic direction
of the conductor Peter Oundjian, includes a bel canto series led by
Caramoor's opera director, Will Crutchfield; new interpretations of
the classical repertory by the Orchestra of St. Luke's, and the
Caramoor Jazz Festival. Artists in residence are the pianist Mischa
Dichter; Donald Runnicles, music director of the San Francisco
Opera; and the clarinetist Richard Stoltzman.
</P>
<P>
   Taking Wing
</P>
<P>
   ``Victorian Fairy Painting,'' the exhibition that broke
attendance records at the Royal Academy of Arts in London last
winter and more recently at the University of Iowa Museum of Art in
Iowa City, is headed for New York. The show will run from Oct. 13
to Jan. 17, 1999, at the Frick Collection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
