<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3934 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-FITNESS-TEX     06-17 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-FITNESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FITNESS DIVA WANTS BLACK WOMEN TO WORK OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donna Richardson's mother doesn't complain when her dynamic
daughter starts working out at the dinner table, even before the
dishes are done. Her family knows that at any family gathering,
dancing or some other sort of exercise is just about inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always push back the table, put on some music and get people
movin' for 30 minutes. I tell them they can play cards or watch TV
as soon as we finish dancing,'' Richardson says.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson grew up going to Friday-night fish fries at her
grandmother's house and to family picnics, where she looked around
and saw ``walking statistics: heart attacks and strokes waiting to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul food is really unhealthy,'' she says. ``My mother is a
great cook, but her favorite foods are fried fish, macaroni and
cheese, and beans cooked with bacon fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, 35, is determined to help prevent heart disease
through physical fitness and good nutrition _ not only in her own
family, but also among African-American women and the inner-city
kids she meets through her work with the Boys &AMP; Girls clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The heart disease death rate for black females is 222.6 per
100,000 _ 69 percent higher than for white females. For stroke, the
death rate is 39.9 per 100,000 black females, 75.8 percent higher
than for white females, according to the American Heart
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Black women smoke more, have more high blood pressure, more high
cholesterol, more obesity and more diabetes _ and they are less
active.
</P>
<P>
   They are more likely to live in neighborhoods where the majority
of families are headed by women, and their health is consequently
more likely to be compromised by family and social obligations,
according to a study to be released this month in the ``Journal of
Health and Social Behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, a physical fitness celebrity with nine workout
videos and a new book, ``Let's Get Real: Exercise Your Right to a
Healthy Body'' (Pocket Books, $16) was in Fort Worth and Dallas
recently to offer fitness tips and advice as part of a national
celebration of Women's Wellness.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson originally wanted to become an actress and dancer,
and there was a time, she says, when she was concerned that
aerobics would interfere with her career. As it turned out,
aerobics became her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a history of heart disease in my family, and the
turnaround in lifestyles to help control that has taken years,''
she says. ``My dad has had two strokes. My grandmother died of a
heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother, bless her heart, has always been so busy taking
care of everybody else, she didn't take any time for herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother held two jobs and volunteered extensively in her
neighborhood and church. She dieted frequently and often ate late
at night, when she was too exhausted to cook properly. She got very
little exercise. When she retired, she was overweight, had high
blood pressure and was suffering from low self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who was traveling around the world promoting good
health, got her mom back on her old exercise bike, which was
gathering dust. She encouraged her mom to start dancing again (she
had always loved to dance), taught her some new muscle-building
exercises and stretches, and started calling often to encourage
her.
</P>
<P>
   She also recommended eating smaller meals more often throughout
the day; getting more fiber from vegetables and whole-grain foods;
opting for low-fat alternatives to regular salad dressings,
margarine and snack foods; and grilling, broiling or baking instead
of frying.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother lost 35 pounds in nine months and now leads an
exercise class at her church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women tend to focus on others' needs _ their husband's,
children's, parents' _ and they are in denial. They think they
won't get heart disease,'' says Dr. Louis Dickey, senior medical
director for Aetna U.S. Healthcare. ``Wives and mothers defer their
own health-care needs because they are busy caring for their
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is also a problem of heart disease presenting
differently in women. A woman may experience weakness and
dizziness, as opposed to a crushing pressure in her chest. She may
not recognize her symptoms as cardiovascular disease,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women show up later with symptoms, and their risk of dying is
greater. They also get less aggressive care: less heart
catheterization, later surgery, less clot-buster drugs. Women think
they are not at risk, and to some extent, doctors make the same
mistake, especially with younger women.''
</P>
<P>
   Prevention is the key. Richardson and Dickey say everyone has
time to exercise. ``Fitness is hard, because we often don't see an
immediate payoff,'' Dickey says. ``You need to look at it as an
investment in the future _ like your 401(k).''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
