<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta ad man writes book about his dad that everyone can use
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Vincent Staniforth began writing a book about his father,
he didn't pretend to have all the answers. He just had the
questions. What began as therapy for the Atlanta advertising
executive after the death of his father in 1990 became a blueprint
for men and women to learn about their own dads.
</P>
<P>
   ``These questions should have been asked when Dad was alive,''
says Staniforth, whose inspirational book, ``Questions for My
Father'' (Beyond Words, $15), has just been published. ``They
remained unasked for what seemed at the time valid reasons: lack of
time in some cases, lack of courage in others. I knew I was loved.
He knew I loved him. But there was so much more there. All that
time, all I ever had to do was ask the questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions range from ``What's your biggest regret?'' to
``When I was born, what was your dream for me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Answering these questions,'' Staniforth says, ``you might come
to agree with the view that this book is more about self-discovery
than Dad-discovery. And I want to emphasize that these are my
questions. I urge you to develop your own questions. Sit down with
your children and answer the same questions.''
</P>
<P>
   -- SECOND ACT: When your first novel sells 3 million copies
after being featured on Oprah Winfrey's Book Club, what do you do
next?
</P>
<P>
   That was the question facing Jacquelyn Mitchard two years ago
when Winfrey made ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' a best seller and
Michele Pfeiffer bought the movie rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was curious to find out if I could write another novel, even
a bad one,'' says Mitchard, a syndicated newspaper columnist from
Madison, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for ``The Most Wanted'' (Viking, $24.95) came to her in
a dream about a 14-year-old Texas girl who falls in love with a
convict. As she began writing the story, other characters popped
up, including a 40-year-old lawyer named Annie Singer who is in an
empty relationship with a fellow attorney. The teenager finds
friendship and support with Annie, and Annie finds true love with a
young carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   Reviews have been mixed, but Mitchard doesn't care. In a case of
life imitating art, the 45-year-old journalist who lost her husband
to cancer six years ago has remarried. Her husband? Chris
Sornberger, a 32-year-old carpenter and landscaper who came to work
on her house after she had finished the novel. ``He's a lovely,
intuitive, generous man, and I think he's got the right stuff,''
says Mitchard, who has five children, ages 2 to 22. The couple
married in May, a day before Mitchard left on a publicity tour for
her new novel.
</P>
<P>
   -- RICH LIT: John Edgar Wideman has won the $30,000 Rea Award
for the Short Story. Sponsored annually by the Dungannon
Foundation, the annual award is not given for a specific title, but
for originality and influence on the genre. Wideman's story
collections include ``Damballah,'' ``Fever,'' ``The Stories of John
Edgar Wideman'' and ``All Stories Are True.'' Wideman, who lives in
Massachusetts, won the PEN/Faulkner Award in 1984 for ``Sent for
You Yesterday,'' and in 1990 for ``Philadelphia Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   -- FEAR AND LOATHING: Best-selling author R.L. Stine says his
new Fear Street Seniors series, which follows a class of teens
through their senior year in high school, is his scariest. Stine,
whose venture in adult fiction was not as successful as his
children's books, still pens one Goosebumps title each month.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
