<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Moneyline'' expansion part of CNN's block programming
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world, and not just the world of money, will soon be Lou
Dobbs' beat.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs' CNN financial news show ``Moneyline'' will expand to an
hour starting Monday, airing from 6:30-7:30 p.m. EDT, and will be
renamed ``The Moneyline News Hour With Lou Dobbs.'' The extra
half-hour comes out of CNN's ``WorldView'' newscast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more international news added,`` Dobbs said
Wednesday. ``The world's primary issues are fundamentally
economically rooted, and this is our acknowledgment of that fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing is acknowledging a high degree of
interdependency among global economies, governments and important
news developments.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as he put it more simply: ``I can find an economic angle in
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   By way of example, Dobbs said the new expanded ``Moneyline''
might do a story on how the squabbling between independent counsel
Kennth Starr and the White House has affected the political climate
in Washington, D.C., and therefore legislation affecting the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs, who's more than an anchor (he's also president of CNNfn,
the financial news subsidiary cable network), said the expansion
will not mean more features or softer approaches on ``Moneyline,''
although part of the revamp will include a new set and new
graphics, also to be unveiled Monday. The show will also feature
more news on the economics of entertainment and sports, although
``Moneyline's'' traditional what-the-Dow-did-today approach will
not be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion is part of CNN's ongoing attempt to create blocks
of programming that are ``appointment viewing.'' ``Moneyline''
generally gets ratings about 25 percent higher than the general
news block that precedes it, so it's an acknowledgment that viewers
are tuning in specifically for Dobbs' financial reports.
</P>
<P>
   The staff of the program, which originates in New York, has
doubled for the expansion.
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   ``Party Monster very `troubling'
</P>
<P>
   New York City, the club scene, mid-'80s. Weird, man. How weird?
These so-called Club Kids _ young, partying, fame-seeking hedonists
whose only talents were outsized amounts of self-promotion and
self-destruction _ became regulars on``Geraldo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a place for you if you are a freak. If you're a
hunchback, throw a little glitter on it,'' one Kid says of the
scene's attraction in ``Party Monster,'' the rivetingly grotesque
documentary that airs at midnight EDT tonight on Cinemax. The
media, naturally, ate them up; one observer called them ``stars for
no reason.'' Reason enough.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Alig was the biggest no-reason star of all. A gay kid
from smalltown Indiana, Alig fled to New York for his 15 minutes of
fame and wound up serving 10 to 20 for the bizarre murder of his
roommate. ``Party Monster,'' which first made waves at the Sundance
Film Festival, traces with a coolly intimate eye the steady,
drug-happy unwinding of Alig from gory ironist to gory killer.
</P>
<P>
   Alig and his flamboyantly misfit crew were so self-absorbed they
seemed to video tape and record their almost every move, giving
``Party Monster'' an eerie, home-movie air of macabre inevitability
(there's no narrator, and some scenes are recreated with
appropriately dreamlike chaos). So when a fellow Club Kid recounts
the depths of Alig's awfulness and then giggles to an unseen
interviewer, ``Did I just destroy the whole point of your
documentary?'' he doesn't realize that he's only enhanced it. This
is one troubling trip into a glittery heart of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Drew Jubera, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Headline goes here
</P>
<P>
   Looks like Katie Couric is about to get richer. News executives
at ABC, Fox and CBS have confirmed they have spoken with Couric,
whose contract at NBC is up in August. All three competitors also
say, however, that they are not actively seeking to steal her away
from NBC. Couric, who reportedly makes about $2 million a year, is
expected stay at NBC. And she'll reportedly end up with a contract
that could reach $7 million a year.
</P>
