<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRUDENTIAL-RESTRUCTUR     06-17 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRUDENTIAL-RESTRUCTURE-785(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LAWS COULD SHORTCHANGE PRUDENTIAL POLICYHOLDERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Mass.)   (dc) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With billions of dollars at stake and after little debate, New
Jersey lawmakers are poised to adopt legislation governing the
reorganization of Prudential Insurance Co. of America that consumer
advocates say contains troubling loopholes that could shortchange
nearly 11 million policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which was drafted by Prudential in meetings
with state regulators and comes up for a vote Thursday in the state
Assembly, provides a framework for distributing stock to the
policyholders as Prudential shifts from a mutual insurer, nominally
owned by its customers, to a publicly traded company.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer advocates have praised Prudential, based in Newark,
N.J., for deciding to reorganize in a way that compensates
policyholders rather than giving them nothing, as some of the
largest insurers based in New York are proposing. But they are
concerned that Prudential's pledges are not detailed in the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how to determine each policyholder's share of the
company's worth. Traditionally, when insurers have switched to
public ownership they have used their accumulated profits as a
starting point in that calculation. In Prudential's case, that is
$20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential says that it is unclear what dollar amount will be
used as the benchmark but that it is committed to giving
policyholders stock worth the full value of the company, an amount
that will be determined by actuaries. The consumer advocates say,
however, that loopholes and exemptions in the pending measure could
reduce the amount of stock that policyholders receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're saying, `Trust us,''' said Jason Adkins, founder of
the Center for Insurance Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns are misplaced, Prudential executives and state
lawmakers respond, noting that the legislation requires that the
distribution of stock be ``fair and equitable'' and that the entire
plan for the company ultimately be approved by the state insurance
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in fact the concerns of the consumer advocates are
legitimate,'' said Richard Codey, the state Senate's minority
leader and a co-sponsor of the bill, ``then you have the
commissioner of insurance as the safety net.''
</P>
<P>
   The critics say their qualms are justified because of
Prudential's recent troubled past and history of close ties to
state officials.
</P>
<P>
   The company's reputation has taken a pounding for most of the
decade as customers complained of repeated deception in the sale of
securities and insurance policies. Prudential's securities unit
paid $1.5 billion in fines, compensation and legal costs after
customers of risky limited partnerships suffered heavy losses. The
company is also expected to pay up to $2 billion to settle a
class-action suit by customers who said they were misled about the
cost of their life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, New Jersey insurance regulators have been
criticized for showing leniency toward the company, one of the
state's biggest employers. In the life insurance case, Florida and
other states were far more critical of Prudential and negotiated
millions more in penalties and compensation from the company.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Prudential has had a close relationship with the
state's political leadership. Several former governors and other
political leaders have served on the board, including Raymond
Bateman, a longtime legislator and the father of Christopher
Bateman, the current chairman of the state assembly committee on
banking and insurance. Gov. Christie Whitman's husband, John, was a
senior manager for a Prudential subsidiary from 1987 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Randall, the New Jersey commissioner of banking and
insurance, sees no problems with the pending legislation. In a
letter to Christopher Bateman, a co-sponsor of the Prudential
legislation, Ms. Randall said the ``bill appropriately protects and
preserves the interest of policyholders.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which was swiftly endorsed by both assembly and
Senate committees earlier this month, gives broad latitude to
Prudential in determining the company's value and how much each
policyholder should get. It also places no limits on how much stock
could be set aside for executives and other employees, permits
Prudential to keep secret some aspects of the reorganization and
exempts the insurer from a public hearing in which critics could
cross-examine witnesses and demand documents to determine whether
the process is fair.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential and legislative sponsors say none of this should
concern the company's customers. ``This is a terrific bill for
policyholders,'' said Mark Grier, the company's highest-ranking
financial officer and the executive in charge of the
reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, to be voted on in the Senate later this month,
was designed as a guide, Grier said, and not as a detailed plan.
And nothing in it diminishes ``our intention to provide the full
value of the company to our policyholders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives and state legislators have ignored appeals
for more specific consumer protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're committed to doing this fairly, why not put it in
the bill?'' asked one critic, Anthony Wright, who is following the
legislation for New Jersey Citizenaction, the state's largest
consumer watchdog group. ``Why not give policyholders guarantees in
writing?''
</P>
<P>
   Prudential has its headquarters in the district represented by
Codey, the minority leader. ``The company needs a shot in the arm
and obviously this should be it,'' he said. ``And hopefully the
policyholders are taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Prudential is still feeling the effects from its legal problems.
Sales of its signature product, life insurance, have fallen from a
peak of 1 million policies in 1991 to fewer than 300,000 last year.
Profits in 1997 were off 43.3 percent, to $610 million, from the
year before.
</P>
<P>
   Even before publicly announcing plans to reorganize in February,
legislators say, Prudential began lining up bipartisan support in
both houses of the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The company and the legislative sponsors proudly refer to the
bill as one of the most consumer-friendly measures of its type. But
the standard set in other states is not very high.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Prudential legislation would be the first to
require a minimum number of policyholders to approve a
reorganization: at least 1 million, or about 9 percent of
Prudential's total, must vote, with at least two-thirds in favor.
But the number can be less than 1 million if the insurance
commissioner approves.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to determining the value of the company, there is
no mention in the bill of accumulated profits or other financial
assets that historically have been used by mutual insurers in
determining their value and the allocations to policyholders,
leaving Prudential to develop its own criteria.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer advocates say language in the bill that allocates
100 percent of the reorganized company's common stock to
policyholders leaves open the possibility that other kinds of stock
could be created, reducing the amount available to holders. This
ambiguity could be remedied, they say, by specifying that 100
percent of the common stock represents the company's full value.
But Grier said, ``Our interpretation is that this means 100 percent
of the value.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the legislation empowers the insurance commissioner
to authorize the sale of additional stock if Prudential
demonstrates ``a need for additional capital'' or that a sale
``would not significantly dilute'' the value of policyholders'
shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, `What is significant?''' asked Wright of
Citizenaction.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation prohibits any members of Prudential's board,
including Arthur Ryan, the chief executive, from receiving stock
when the reorganization takes place. But stock can be given to
other executives and employees without limit.
</P>
<P>
   Under New Jersey's right-to-know law, Wright said, all the
documents in Prudential's reorganization would have been available
to the public. But the legislation creates an exception that
enables Prudential to keep its business plan, financial projections
and other information secret, including the details of how the
value of the company is to be distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins of the Center for Insurance Research said New Jersey's
Administrative Procedures Act required an adversarial hearing when,
in the course of reorganization, regulated businesses, like
insurance companies, are deciding the disposition of property or
benefits. But the legislation exempts Prudential from that kind of
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential argues that it needs confidentiality to protect trade
secrets. And it says that adversarial-style hearings could be
expensive and time consuming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we create more noise around the process, it takes
value away from the company,'' said Michael Chesman, a senior
lawyer for Prudential. ``Does that do anything for the
policyholder?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
