u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-ART-NYT &LR;      06-17 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S PARLIAMENT APPROVES STIMULUS PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(ja) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ After months of delay, Japan's Parliament completed
passage of a bill Wednesday night that will allow the government to
begin pouring public money into the economy, part of a
fiscal-stimulus package worth roughly $119 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The passage of the supplementary budget, which had been
expected, enables Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's government to
show the world that money for the stimulus package of 16.67
trillion yen will start moving into giant projects throughout the
country in hope of lifting the economy out of recession.
</P>
<P>
   The measure's approval coincided with a concerted move by the
U.S. and Japanese central banks to prop up the exchange value of
the yen by selling dollars and buying yen in the currency markets.
The Japanese currency had fallen to a series of eight-year lows in
the last week on fears that Japan was not doing enough to revive
its economy.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday here, the yen was trading at 142.01 to the
dollar. In New York, the yen rose sharply, settling at 136.37 to
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the government reported its worst annual postwar
economic performance, for the fiscal year that ended on March 31.
Worries spread throughout Asia that a weakening yen could set off
another round of currency devaluations.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the coordinated intervention Wednesday by the Bank
of Japan and the Federal Reserve Bank, along with the impact of
cash flowing into the economy, could give the Japanese government
some breathing room as it sets forth to tackle the challenge of
reducing more than $600 billion in bad bank debt.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's supplementary budget will release 6.1 trillion yen,
or about $4.4 billion, a portion of funds that are part of the
broader package of tax cuts and spending. Economists expect the
impact to be a restoring of some growth to the economy, which will
likely be seen in the October-December quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Ministry officials have said that the funds would be
released almost immediately after passage of the supplementary
budget. And indeed, public works projects have been lined up for
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that the delay in passing Wednesday's budget,
despite foreign pressure to speed up the fiscal stimulants, was
essentially unnecessary, for the governing Liberal Democratic Party
has a majority in the lower house, the more powerful of the two
chambers. The budget had been passed by the lower house on Monday.
And some say the party could easily have pushed the budget through
Parliament more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties tried Wednesday to submit a resolution
censuring Hashimoto, but the resolution was rejected, and this
paved the way for the vote on the budget in the Japanese Senate on
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
