<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-FRANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS WARM UP TO LES BLEUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ Before the World Cup began, the French
seemed uncertain whether to embrace their national team. But after
a 3-0 victory over South Africa in their opener, les Francais are
preparing to jump on the bandwagon with Les Bleus.
</P>
<P>
   France played offensively, took chances, looked stylish. Just
what their fans wanted, especially the Parisians.
</P>
<P>
   Now France has a more difficult task than winning over the
public. It will meet Saudi Arabia at the Stade de France Thursday
night. France could clinch a berth in the second round, but just as
significantly, it could set the stage for the elliptical,
80,000-seat stadium to take on a life after the World Cup concludes
next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Stade de France, inaugurated this year, is a potential $450
million white elephant, with no permanent tenant. Paris St. Germain
plays in Parc des Princes and has no intention of deserting a loyal
fan base.
</P>
<P>
   So Liza, Zizou, and Duga _ the French strike force of Bixente
Lizarazu, Zinedine Zidane, and Christophe Dugarry _ will be
expected to both score goals and capture imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   France has an effective combination of hard-line defenders, led
by the Chelsea-bound, Ghana-born Marcel Desailly, plus domestic
midfielders Didier Deschamps and Emmanuel Petit. Deschamps, the
country's player of the year, was once described as ``a water
carrier'' by former star Eric Cantona. But Cantona added that such
workers are necessary to allow the creators to create.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cantona is the most accomplished and well-known French
player of recent vintage, he and David Ginola were dropped from the
national team after it failed to qualify for USA '94. France had
set up training sites in the US while needing a result at home
against either Israel or Bulgaria in its final two qualifiers. That
failure, combined with a similar failure in 1990, caused a feeling
of letdown among fans. Better not to allow hopes to rise with this
team.
</P>
<P>
   But the new generation of Les Bleus appears capable of erasing
those memories.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia has adopted a Brazilian approach, but the Saudis
have not raised their game to the Brazilian level. Coach Carlos
Alberto Parreira, who guided Brazil to the '94 title, could be
fired if the Saudis fail to at least tie. Parreira, who guided the
MetroStars to the bottom of Major League Soccer's Eastern
Conference last year, will have earned about $1 million for six
months' work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
