<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-ITALY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY OVERWHELMS CAMEROON, 3-0 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELLIER, France _ Fiat magnate Gianni Agnelli, Prime
Minister Romano Prodi, and the many other Italians who wanted
Roberto Baggio and Alessandro Del Piero to play in the same game
gained some satisfaction last night. But the country's two most
creative players did not play together as the Italians took a 3-0
victory over Cameroon to virtually clinch a place in the second
round of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The personnel changes, which included using Luigi DiBiagio and
Francesco Moriero in the starting lineup, and the uninhibited
offensive attitudes of the Italians marked a major change from the
team which had advanced through qualifying with the most
conservative of tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Del Piero, recovering from a leg injury, replaced Baggio in the
second half as Italy displayed much more attacking flair and
defensive composure than when it rallied to tie Chile, 2-2, in its
opener.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no guarantee such aesthetically pleasing ideas will
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Del Piero went in, it was a reminder of the game in the
1970s,'' coach Cesare Maldini said. ``That kind of game was
fashionable 20 years ago, but not now. When a player is tired, he
is substituted.''
</P>
<P>
   Before tiring, Baggio crossed to Luigi DiBiagio for the first
goal in the seventh minute. Del Piero helped set up Christian Vieri
for the last goal in the 90th minute. And Moriero, in only his
fourth international game, set up Vieri for the second goal only
minutes after Del Piero entered.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first goal, we suffered a little bit and felt some
fear of them,'' Maldini said. ``But we comported ourselves very
well. We still have a lot to do. The whole team played perfectly.
We all responded together, and together we won.''
</P>
<P>
   But Italy had to overcome the rough tactics of Cameroon, which
had three players cautioned and Raymond Kalla Nkongo ejected.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians put the pressure on early with Moriero on the right
wing. Vieri had a chip over goalkeeper Jacques Songo'o cleared off
the line by Rigobert Song, then a close drive deflected by Songo'o.
</P>
<P>
   Moriero sped past the Cameroon defense in the seventh minute and
was tripped on the end line by Pierre Nlend Wome. The contact
appeared incidental, but Australian referee Edward Lennie cautioned
Wome.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians converted the free kick into a corner on the other
side. Baggio capitalized on the uncertainty of the defense with a
short corner to Alessandro Nesta, then a sharp cross to DiBiagio,
who headed unmarked past Songo'o.
</P>
<P>
   Cameroon found its rhythm with 18-year-old Salomon Olembe
supplying the touches in midfield. But the Indomitable Lions began
asserting themselves too aggressively. Baggio went down from a
tackle by Pierre Njanka. Alessandro Costacurta was cautioned for
taking down Didier Angibeau. DiBiagio made a sliding tackle on
Kalla, whose cleats went into DiBiagio's thigh.
</P>
<P>
   DiBiagio departed on a stretcher and was booed. Songo'o ran to
the halfway line at halftime to berate DiBiagio, who lifted his
pant leg to reveal his injury.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd began supporting Cameroon, which has several players
performing for French clubs and three naturalized Frenchmen.
</P>
<P>
   Olembe, who was brought to Nantes at 15, supplied the
sophistication and inspiration. He slid a perfect through ball to
Joseph-Desire Job of Lyon, and GianLuca Paglialuca punched the shot
over the goal for a corner in the 13th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Italy appeared content to slow things down and coast into the
second round. But Cameroon forced the action with 10 players, going
all out with substitutes Job, Alphonse Tchami, and 17-year-old
Samuel Eto'o.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the half, Demetrio Albertini, until recently
considered indispensable to the Italian midfield, failed twice to
connect with Paolo Maldini on simple passes and was replaced by
Roberto DiMatteo. Del Piero then replaced Baggio.
</P>
<P>
   Italy wisely waited for the Lions to falter, either through
fatigue or overconfidence. The strategy worked as Olembe became
either too presumptuous or too tired and attempted to dribble
through a defender's legs in the center circle.
</P>
<P>
   Moriero took the play toward the penalty arc and fed Vieri, who
chipped it past Songo'o for a two-goal lead in the 31st minute.
</P>
<P>
   Italy invited the Lions to come forward, then counter.
Cameroon's last good chance occurred in the 28th minute when Joseph
Ndo, son of the country's leading comedian, Oncle Otsama, slipped
past Paolo Maldini for a corner.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lions were not in a humorous mood when Italy began
picking them apart, and Vieri powered past Wome and Songo'o for the
final goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians can advance as Group B's top seed with a tie
against Austria in Saint-Denis Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
