<SLUG> BC-DUNKIN-ROSENBERG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSENBERG TO STEP DOWN AS DUNKIN' DONUTS PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 35 years on the job, Robert M. Rosenberg is doing what
perhaps Michael Jordan should do _ going out on top.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the 60-year-old Rosenberg's duties as president
and chief executive of Dunkin' Donuts will be assumed by his chosen
successor, 26-year company veteran Jack Shafer, 54, who now serves
as chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't anticipate any radical course corrections,'' Shafer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg, who ran doughnut shops during summer breaks from
Harvard Business School, is a son of Bill Rosenberg, who grew the
chain from a string of canteen trucks after World World II.
</P>
<P>
   When Shafer takes over the Randolph, Mass. company, it will mark
the first time the chain is run by someone who isn't a member of
the Rosenberg family.
</P>
<P>
   Since late 1989, Dunkin' Donuts has been owned by Allied Domecq
PLC, a British food-and-beverage conglomerate, whose portfolio of
US quick-service restaurants also includes the Baskin-Robbins ice
cream stores and the Togo's sandwich shops.
</P>
<P>
   Presided over by Rosenberg, the three chains' 6,500 US stores
had about $2.5 billion in sales last year. In 1963, his first year
as president, Dunkin' Donuts had sales of $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Recently remarried and exploring the possibility of teaching at
Babson College, Rosenberg said this was the ideal time to step
down, from both a personal and business standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-five years is a long time,'' he said. The chain's
``momentum is terrific,'' and Dunkin' Donuts is seeing the first
signs of success for its new growth strategy.
</P>
<P>
   With too many restaurants for too few eaters, the fast-food
industry is past its salad days of explosive growth.
</P>
<P>
   But while Boston Market seems to teeter near bankruptcy, and
McDonald's Corp. looks to boost nearly flat US sales, Dunkin'
Donuts has posted double-digit sales gains month after month.
</P>
<P>
   New products such as bagels and ``Coolatta'' drinks have helped
drive sales, said Rosenberg, who added he's redefined Dunkin'
Donuts ``three or four times'' during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   When Rosenberg became company president in 1963, some Dunkin'
Donuts stores still sold cheeseburgers. The menu has continually
undergone deletions and additions.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Dunkin' Donuts has distanced itself a bit from its
doughnut heritage to emphasize coffee, which could account for $720
million of the chain's projected $1.9 billion in sales this fiscal
year. Doughnut sales are projected at $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   One prong of the company's growth strategy is to combine
Allied's three chains under one roof in the hope of luring
customers all day long. Dunkin' Donuts would provide the morning
business. Togo's would draw the lunch crowd, and Baskin-Robbins
would attract ice cream lovers in the afternoon and evening.
</P>
<P>
   While Rosenberg took his company public in 1968 and wooed Allied
as a white knight during the hostile-takeover era, perhaps his
greatest triumph has been adapting to new food trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stick with a menu that was successful in the '60s,
you're in trouble,'' Rosenberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
