<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3995 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXANS-MONEY-HNS &LR;      06-17 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXANS-MONEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, RIVAL HEAD TO WASHINGTON TO HELP FUND TEXAS CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas' gubernatorial candidates, seeking to shore
up support for the fall elections, are cuddling up to special
interests in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. George W. Bush is expected to raise at least
$500,000 on Thursday at a $5,000-per-plate dinner at the Four
Seasons Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Land Commissioner Garry Mauro plans to cash in on his 25-year
friendship with President Clinton at a June 23 reception and
dinner. The Democratic candidate expects the event to raise
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Bush as the front-runner for his party's presidential
nomination in 2000. And that is making the governor's fund-raiser a
hot ticket inside the Washington Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington special-interest groups would only have an interest
in building a relationship with Bush if he is going to run for
president,'' said Paul Hendrie, spokesman for the Center for
Responsive Politics, an advocacy group for overhauling the nation's
campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Mauro, it is a case of the Democrats trying to hit back
at Bush and knock him down the best they can before he becomes a
national player,'' Hendrie said. ``If they can cut into his margin
of victory, it would be viewed as a weakness in his national
standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush downplays the speculation of a presidential bid, saying he
is concentrating solely on a second term as governor of the second
largest state.
</P>
<P>
   ``My head and my heart are in the state of Texas, and I intend
to be the first (Texas) governor elected to back-to-back, four-year
terms. No governor has ever done that, and I intend to win,'' Bush
said earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   A lopsided victory would give Bush leverage over the Legislature
next year, as well as a springboard into a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush is running for president,'' Mauro spokesman Joe
Cutbirth said from Austin. ``Why won't he just say so? It's kind of
goofy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although federal law prohibits Bush from using money raised for
his re-election bid in a future presidential run, Cutbirth accused
the governor of seeking a forum with ``every Gucci-wearing tobacco
and HMO lobbyist in Washington'' who could be tapped for a White
House campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those expected to attend the Bush fund-raiser are
political colleagues of former President George Bush, the
governor's father.
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Tucker, a Bush campaign spokeswoman in Austin, dismissed
suggestions that presidential ambitions underscore the Washington
fund-raising event.
</P>
<P>
   She said the governor attributes the overwhelming interest in
the fund-raiser to ``people who want good leaders, who support good
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has raised roughly $14 million for his re-election race,
far outpacing the $2.2 million the Mauro has received.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will attend a $1,000-per-person reception at the
Sheraton Carlton Hotel on Tuesday for Mauro, and first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton will be featured later at $5,000-per-plate dinner.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Vice President Al Gore will attend a fund-raising
event in El Paso, Texas, on June 25 to help Mauro raise $150,000 in
his uphill battle to defeat Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The three events could raise at least $400,000 for the Mauro
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro also will speak to the National Press Club on Monday to
outline the political differences between him and Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
