<HEADLINE>
MANUFACTURING JOBS RISE IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts manufacturers added 6,900 new jobs during
the first three months of this year, 400 more than during all of
last year, according to an industry report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 456,800 manufacturing jobs counted in March represent the
highest number in the state since 1993, according to the report
done for the Associated Industries of Massachusetts by Standard &AMP;
Poor's DRI of Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But that total is two-thirds what it was in 1984, when the
defense, computer, and aerospace industries all were booming.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday's report cast doubt on whether the latest upturn
can continue for long.
</P>
<P>
   One storm warning, said Sara Johnson, regional economist at
Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, is a decline in exports to Asia since last
fall. Thirty-one percent of Massachusetts exports went to Asia last
year, much of it shipped by Bay State suppliers to the
semiconductor industry. Exports to Canada also have dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Also, layoffs are in store this summer as Compaq Computer Corp.
digests its acquisition of Digital Equipment Corp. _ and they come
in the wake of plant closings by Polaroid Corp. in Norwood,
Lockheed Martin Corp. in Pittsfield, and OSRAM/Sylvania in Danvers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, last winter's job losses were more than offset by
growth in employment at smaller firms that do everything from
supplying cement for Boston's Central Artery project to building
high-speed switches for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really amazes me is the breadth of this activity,''
Johnson said. The growth list included electronics, computers,
printing and publishing, scientific and medical instruments, and
metal fabrication. Fifteen of 19 industrial sectors showed growth,
two were stable, and only the two smallest, footwear and petroleum,
saw year-to-year declines.
</P>
<P>
   The number of new jobs also was bolstered by managerial
decisions to cut back on overtime. ``The state's manufacturers have
been on a hiring spree, choosing to hire new workers rather than
extend overtime hours,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Associated Industries president John Gould attributed some of
the gains to ``the success of policy initiatives,'' including
investment tax credits, lower unemployment insurance costs, and a
reduction in health care costs, ``that have made Massachusetts a
more competitive location for industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
