A3999 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     06-17 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(RESENDING TO ADD BYLINE) 
WITH SON GONE, ALL SHE WANTS IS A PIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. ``JILL'' LABBE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nita Robbins lost her only son in a war that divided this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Now all she wants from her government is a new Gold Star pin,
one in which the deep-blue enamel background isn't chipped and
worn.
</P>
<P>
   First Lt. Russell Robbins was in Vietnam only seven weeks before
a helicopter crash took his life. During his days ``in country,''
he wrote home to his mother seven times.
</P>
<P>
   The mission that deadly day in 1967 was to move six helicopter
loads of soldiers into Viet Cong territory. The troops were short
one door gunner. The 25-year-old Army lieutenant from Fort Worth
volunteered.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they got to the landing zone, the motor failed on the
helicopter,'' Nita Robbins said. ``The pilot got it almost down to
the ground before it hit a concrete dike in a rice paddy. It slung
the plane around and threw Russell out.''
</P>
<P>
   Many men were injured in the crash, but only Robbins died. The
Defense Department sent his mother a Gold Star pin and a letter of
condolence that praised her only son for his service to his
country.
</P>
<P>
   President Wilson started the tradition of sending gold stars to
mothers who lost children in battle, because he believed that the
black armbands worn during World War I were too somber.
</P>
<P>
   Nita Robbins wore her pin constantly, to the point that the
distinctive blue enamel chipped away from between the tiny
five-pointed star and the wreath that surrounds it. She wasn't sure
how to go about getting a replacement, so she turned to a neighbor
for help.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Herman lives next door to Robbins in a west Fort Worth
apartment complex. A veteran of World War II, Herman is the exact
opposite of the genteel Comanche native he is trying to help. A
transplant to Texas from New York, Herman is blunt and high-energy;
Robbins, a former schoolteacher, is soft-spoken and low-key.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Carswell to see if someone out there could help,''
Herman said. ``Some young girl said maybe Mrs. Robbins could buy
one in the BX. Have you ever heard of such a thing?''
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls to local military offices proved fruitless, so
Herman started his letter-writing campaign. His communique to the
Army's adjutant general remains unanswered, but Robbins said she
appreciates his effort.
</P>
<P>
   Herman's contact with Rep. Kay Granger's office resulted in a
call back to Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they are working on it,'' Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   An aide in Granger's district office in Fort Worth confirmed
that she has received a request for assistance from Robbins but
would not discuss specifics. It could take a month or more to get
an answer, depending on the backlog of requests at the Defense
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins said she is surprised at the lengths to which Herman is
going in assisting her, from contacting the representative's office
to calling the local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it was going to go this far,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins counts herself blessed. In good health as she approaches
her 80th birthday in August, she still does all her own housework
and shopping. Her dog, Charlie _ a lovably strange mix of chow,
dachshund and corgi _ has been her companion since her husband died
four years ago of Alzheimer's disease. Two of her four daughters
live in Texas and stay in touch.
</P>
<P>
   But Herman worries about his neighbor, and he believes that a
replacement pin would will bring her the peace of mind that he
feels she is missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like a fair trade,'' Herman said; ``her son for a pin.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
