<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS COMFORTABLE WITH ROLE IN US OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The talk on the eve of the US Open a year ago at
Congressional was about Tiger Woods, the Grand Slam nobody had ever
won in this game, and his date with destiny. He was golf's grandest
story following his record romp in the Masters at age 21, the next
Jack Nicklaus. He had fired the imaginations of the young, and his
presence was shooting the size of purses to highs never envisioned
before he burst on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Woods remains a major player on the global stage, but it was
interesting to note Tuesday that a news conference Wednesdayheld by
his cart-riding former Stanford teammate, Casey Martin, was much
better attended than one an hour later at which Woods talked about
his chances. The Grand Slam? Only Mark O'Meara can pull it off this
year.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Masters blitz, Woods has returned to earth.
He had three double bogeys at Congressional and following an
opening 74 bolted, refusing to talk to the media after finishing
tied for 19th. In the British Open at Royal Troon, he had two
triple bogeys and a quadruple bogey and finished tied for 24th. He
had three doubles in the PGA Championship at Winged Foot and wound
up tied for 29th. At that event, he played 10 holes in plus-24
figures.
</P>
<P>
   There was a stretch this year, starting at Bay Hill, when he
played 11 competitive rounds without shooting in the 60s. That
included the four rounds of the Masters, where he found more
difficult conditions than last year but played well enough to
finish tied for eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Woods's return to the summit, at the BellSouth Classic
in Duluth, Ga., his first victory on the US PGA Tour since the
Western Open last July. This brings Woods to the US Open at the
Olympic Club, and he appears buoyant, confident, and ready to win
his second major championship on a course that, despite the many
rounds he played here during his college days, many say is unsuited
to his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the challenge,'' said Woods. ``I like it when people
say I can't (win at Olympic Club) and it definitely gets me a
little revved up. You also have to understand you've still got to
go out there and play the game no matter what the motivational
factor is. It's all aside once you step on the first tee. You have
to go out there and get your focus and maintain your concentration.
It's patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic isn't an overpowering course in terms of distance; it
will take the driver out of players' hands. The rough, said Woods,
isn't as bad here as it was last year at Congressional, where he
found too much of it. The greens are fairly soft, but everybody has
said they will be firm and slick, and position is the key to
winning on a course where Ben Hogan was beaten in a playoff by Jack
Fleck in the 1955 Open, where Arnold Palmer squandered a seven-shot
lead and lost to Billy Casper in a playoff in 1966, and where Tom
Watson lost by a stroke 11 years ago when Scott Simpson birdied two
of the last four holes.
</P>
<P>
   The US Open hasn't been kind to Woods, but he laughs off the
suggestion that he can't win one. ``I was 21 when you were
speculating (on the Grand Slam) and I'm only 22 now,'' he said. ``I
have a lot of time to play this tournament, and as time goes on I
think I am going to improve and really learn how to play a US Open
golf course. It's different from any other tournament, where
straight and down the middle and making pars wins. Normally you
have got to go 20 under par, and 59s are now becoming regular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf is changing. The way the golf course is set up under USGA
conditions, you have really got to be patient and (realize) par is
really a good score. It's different from the mindset we have
normally. There are players like myself who have struggled with
that in the past. My preparation has really been intense.
Physically, mentally, hitting golf balls and lifting has been
pretty intense. You try to get your game better every day, and
hopefully by the weekend it is on full cylinder.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, whom Woods thinks of as ``a big brother,'' won the
Masters with a dramatic 20-foot putt on the 72d hole to vault past
Fred Couples and David Duval with a birdie/-birdie finish. O'Meara,
who has won five times down the road at Pebble Beach and plays a
lot of golf with Woods, said the experience of a year ago is a plus
for his young friend. ``I'm sure Tiger learned a lot last year at
the last three majors about being patient,'' said O'Meara. ``He's a
very smart kid. He learns from his mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in an informal poll in the press tent, just one reporter
picked Woods to win. The top name was Colin Montgomerie, who saw
the Open slip away last year at Congressional. The next most
popular choices were British Open champion Justin Leonard, David
Duval, and Jim Furyk. Then came Tom Lehman, the only other player
with multiple votes. Ernie Els, the defending champion, received
just a solitary vote.
</P>
<P>
   The back spasms that forced Els to withdraw after nine holes of
last week's Buick Classic in Rye, N.Y., may have raised doubts
among the press and public, but Els remains confident. ``It's
frustrating, especially last week,'' he said. ``I've had such a
nice record at Westchester. I've never played just nine holes and
pulled out of a golf tournament. Maybe all these things happen for
a reason. As long as we're not playing that long a course, I might
be OK. You have to put the ball in play and take it from there. It
might work to my advantage; you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Montgomerie, last year was not the first time he came
close. He lost to Els in a US Open playoff four years ago at
Oakmont. He bogeyed the 71st hole to miss out on a playoff with Els
at Congressional. He lost in a playoff to Steve Elkington in 1995
at Riviera. He's due to win his first major championship. ``It's my
first time here,'' said Montgomerie. ``Last year at Congressional
it was more length and accuracy. Here it is just accuracy. It's
just positioning it. It's a great golf course. I always look
forward to the US Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who after falling short in the Masters seemed almost
relieved to not have to face the media blitz of a year ago, also
has had recent back problems, leading him to withdraw from the
Kemper. He went to Las Vegas, where he spent time with his physical
therapist and his teacher/coach, Butch Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The back's 100 percent,'' Woods said. ``I was playing a lot of
golf at the time and I was doing a lot of running. I went from no
miles to running four, five, six miles every day, and that puts a
little stress on your back. I felt a little twinging, a little
tightening, and a couple of spasms here. I said, `I have to have my
back ready for the US Open,' and I decided to pull out of Kemper. I
basically just stretched it out, warmed it up, and made sure
everything was loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the storied Olympic Club isn't suited for Woods; maybe it
is because of the many times he played it in his two years at
Stanford. ``I wasn't playing as I would have liked to going into
Congressional,'' said Woods. ``I worked hard on the range and just
couldn't find it. My feel was good around the greens, but I just
couldn't drive the ball the way I wanted to. I wasn't comfortable
over my tee shots. This year is different. I feel great about my
swing. I've shot some pretty good numbers lately, and I'm anxious
just to get out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
