<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-HEART-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS KEY TO SPORTS DEATHS IN HEART RHYTHM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Budgeted earlier as BASEBALL-HEART) 
(ps) 
 By PHILIP J. HILTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Matthew Messing was playing hockey in Quincy one
evening in 1995, when an opponent checked him in the chest with a
routine bump. Sixteen-year-old Matthew had taken plenty of checks
before, but after this one, he collapsed on the ice and died
instantly.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, along with nearly 70 others reported in recent
years, had baffled doctors. In each case, they found no injury to
the heart and no previous heart condition in the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Now researchers believe they may have found the explanation for
the rare deaths, which go by the medical name of ``commotio
cordis,'' or ``concussion of the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's edition of the New England Journal of Medicine,
researchers, led by a team from the Tufts-New England Medical
Center in Boston, describe their experiments along with suggestions
for preventing some deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths apparently result from an unusual and chance
conjunction of events. When the heart is beating, there is a
fleeting moment, about a hundredth of a second long, when the
electrical rhythm is resetting, so to speak, in the milliseconds
just before a beat. During that moment, if a moderate blow is
directed to exactly the spot on the chest above the heart, the
electrical rhythm breaks, and the heart quits beating, and instead
``fibrillates'' or quivers uselessly inside the chest.
</P>
<P>
   If the blow is too strong or too weak, or the timing is a few
milliseconds off, the catastrophe does not occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a rare event, so it's important not to scare parents
away from having their children in sports, for example,'' said Dr.
N.A. Mark Estes, director of the cardiac arrhythmia service at
Tufts University School of Medicine. ``There are also some
possibilities for preventing the problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the group tested ``safety baseballs'' that are
sometimes used by children when learning baseball and that weigh
the same but are softer than a regular baseball. They found that
the softest version was much less likely to cause commotio in
experimental animals when it struck the chest in the milliseconds
just before a beat.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, doctors were unsure of what caused commotio, and
experiments in which blows were delivered to the chests of animals
failed to reproduce the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, led by Estes, Mark Link and Paul Wang, also
physicians at Tufts-New England, suggested that earlier experiments
had delivered blows that were too powerful, and not properly timed.
So in their experiment, young pigs were given blows in the chest
with a ball fired by a machine at 30 mph _ an average throw in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 blows delivered during the 15-millisecond ``T-wave''
moment just before a beat, nine caused a young pig to experience
what would have been a fatal heart stop. (The pigs were not
actually killed by the blows, but were quickly revived.) The
potentially fatal reaction in each of the nine cases occurred
immediately on the next heartbeat after impact.
</P>
<P>
   But, in 22 impacts on other pigs that were timed to occur at
other parts of the heartbeat cycle, no potentially fatal heart
failures occurred.
</P>
<P>
   One group of scientists led by Dr. Barry Maron of the
Minneapolis Heart Institute Foundation in Minnesota, has begun to
keep track of commotio instances, and has so far counted 69 that
have been reported in the world over the past few decades.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were usually children, often playing sports,
including a 6-year-old died when a baseball struck him in the
chest; a 14-year-old died when playing lacrosse and the ball hit
him in the chest; a 14-year-old died during a karate match when he
was hit lightly in the chest. In a different sort of incident, an
11-year-old boy died after his father struck him in the chest when
the boy gave the wrong answer to a question as the father was
trying to teach the boy to tell time.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an editorial accompanying the article, journal deputy editor
Dr. Gregory Curfman, noted that 69 is probably an underestimate of
the actual number of cases. He said that safety measures, such as
the safety baseballs now recommended for young baseball players by
the Consumer Product Safety Commission, or chest protectors for use
in hockey, football and other sports, may prevent future commotio
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Shoulder pads now worn by hockey, football and lacrosse players
are inadequate to protect the vulnerable spot on the chest, but
extended pads might.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest value of the article,'' Curfman wrote, ``will be
to raise awareness about commotio cordis, demystify its cause, and
educate us about the recognition and prevention of this tragic
phenomenon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
