<HEADLINE>
STATESMANSHIP GIVEN TOP ODDS IN N.H. SWEEPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, N.H. _ Ok By Me, the defending champion, will have to get
past a top horse in Statesmanship to defend his crown in the
$200,000 New Hampshire Sweepstakes Handicap at Rockingham Park
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A field of eight was drawn Wednesday for the Grade III event, to
be run at 1 1/8 miles on the turf course, with Statesmanship listed
as the 9-5 choice and Ok By Me right behind at 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Ok By Me has not won a race in five starts since capturing last
year's Sweeps in impressive fashion under Joe Bravo. But he has
overcome an ankle problem and run in top company since, most
recently finishing third in the Connaught Cup at Woodbine May 30.
Statesmanship comes to Rock off a nose score as the favorite in the
Red Bank Handicap at Monmouth May 25. As in the Red Bank, he will
be ridden by Jose Santos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bringing Bravo in to ride Ok By Me (Frank Lovato rode
him in Canada), and he fits this horse well,'' said trainer H.
James Bond. ``Our horse likes this course, and I hope we can take
this race again. He worked (a half-mile) in :49 1/5 over the
Saratoga training track (Tuesday morning). He was the only one to
go out there all day over the sloppy going and he worked awful
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statesmanship is a very formidable opponent. He was tough in
Florida all winter. (Trainer) Christophe Clement does a great job
with all those turf horses and he's not bringing Statesmanship up
to Rockingham because he has nothing better to do. He's the horse I
personally fear the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Bomfim, a legitimate speed horse who has won two of his last
three starts on the front end, certainly would set the pace in the
Sweeps, as he did in the Red Bank before finishing third, beaten
just a half-length. But trainer Pat Kelly is not fully committed to
coming and may keep Bomfim in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Bill Mott entered Daylight Savings, who won a $60,000
allowance race at Churchill Downs May 28 under Pat Day. Mott did
not name a jockey and may be looking to use a rider from New York
or a local rider if Daylight Savings does come. And trainer Kiaran
McLaughlin entered Tamhid, who has been competing in allowance
races at Belmont, but did not name a rider. He, too, may just be
kicking the tires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4006 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUCKERS-DATELINE-BOS     06-17 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCKERS-DATELINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUCKERS' CASE AGAINST `DATELINE NBC' OPENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGOR _ Raymond Veilleux, 52, has been a trucker his entire
adult life _ driving them, selling them, and leasing them for
marathon hauls that criss-cross the country.
</P>
<P>
   So, when ``Dateline NBC'' asked if one of his rigs could be
followed from California to Chelsea, Mass., Veilleux allegedly
agreed on the condition that the show portrayed the trucking
industry in a ``positive'' light.
</P>
<P>
   Veilleux and the truck's driver said network employees gave them
that promise _ several times _ in telephone conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the two-part ``Dateline NBC'' show used Veilleux's
truck and its driver as examples of all that is wrong with the
business. The problems: violations of federal rules limiting
driving time, falsified logbooks, alarmingly little sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``American highways are a trucker's killing field,'' the show
declared.
</P>
<P>
   Before the credits had finished rolling across the screen,
Veilleux took a phone call from a customer who told him he had
destroyed not only his own business, but the industry as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a trial that opened Wednesday in federal court here, a jury
will be asked to decide whether ``Dateline NBC'' staff lied to
Veilleux and truck driver Peter Kennedy, defamed them, and caused
them physical and emotional distress. The plaintiffs are asking for
unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for ``Dateline NBC'' said no promises were made to
Veilleux or the driver, and that the report was an accurate,
balanced account of the journey. Bernard Kubetz, the attorney, said
Kennedy even admitted before the trip that he typically broke the
law on long runs.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's lawyer, William Robitzek, said his client has a
longstanding reputation as a safe driver, and that the
coast-to-coast trip complied with federal limits until the last day
of the six-day journey. On that leg, according to Robitzek, Kennedy
exceeded the 10-hour driving limit _ but only to accommodate the
logistical demands of the ``Dateline NBC'' crew.
</P>
<P>
   For Kennedy, who has logged millions of miles on America's
roads, the show's repercussions have included death threats, verbal
abuse from other truckers, ``harassment'' from inspectors, and
constant anxiety that his friends said has turned him into ``a
basket case. And for Veilleux, the program has been the most
devastating event of his small-town life in Oakland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The expectations had been otherwise. Kennedy told Veilleux that
he had enjoyed the NBC crew immensely. He even posed for a picture
with NBC correspondent Fred Francis, arms linked in good
fellowship, to commemorate the trip.
</P>
<P>
   But all that changed on April 19, 1995, when the first segment
of ``Keep on Truckin''' was broadcast. ``What you're about to hear
about the drivers of many of these trucks won't make you feel any
safer,'' a national audience heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 27 years of hard driving, Kennedy says he has racked up
over 3 million miles, sleeping less than he should, and gambling
that his fatal fatigue number doesn't come up,'' the program said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``Dateline NBC'' told viewers, Kennedy ``says he
has to lie to inspectors to stay on the road.... But this
stay-awake-and-on-the-road mentality has led to many accidents and
deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Veilleux was stunned by the show. When the second installment
aired on April 26, Veilleux watched from a hospital bed, a
cardiologist at his side to monitor the chest pains that he was
suffering, Robitzek said.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast was a crippling blow to a business that Veilleux
had built over decades with an excellent safety record, according
to Robitzek.
</P>
<P>
   The experience also destroyed his trust in the news media. ``I
don't believe what I see anymore,'' Veilleux said.
</P>
<P>
   The lengthy allegations of deception, according to the lawsuit,
``must be regarded as atrocious and utterly intolerable in a
civilized community.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubetz, the NBC attorney, said no serious journalist would ever
make the kind of promises that Veilleux alleges he obtained.
Kennedy was told before the trip that anything that happened en
route to Massachusetts, and anything he said or did in transit,
would be fair game, Kubetz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
