<HEADLINE>
L.L. BEAN GIVES MULLEN $20 MILLION AD ACCOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   L.L. Bean Inc., the famed Maine purveyor of outdoor equipment
and apparel, said Wednesday it has awarded its advertising account
to Mullen.
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated annual advertising budget of $20 million to
$25 million, L.L. Bean should be one of Mullen's biggest clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great American brand with virtually 100 percent
awareness,'' said president Joe Grimaldi &UR;  &LR; Mullen, which is in
Wenham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   While other finalists in an ad agency review gave ``excellent
presentations,'' what helped clinch the victory for Mullen was its
``brand experience'' in the outdoor category, said Steve Fuller,
L.L. Bean's director of advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen currently creates advertising for Swiss Army Brands and
Malden Mills, the maker of Polartec climate-control fabric.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Mullen also worked for Timberland Co., a
maker of boots and outdoor apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen's first work for L.L. Bean, of Freeport, Maine, should
break in time for the holidays, Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   For the last five years, Bean's advertising had been handled by
Bronner Slosberg Humphrey of Boston, a direct-marketing firm.
</P>
<P>
   But with sales up only slightly last year to $1.07 billion, L.L.
Bean apparently decided to explore other marketing options in hopes
of regaining its usually robust growth rates.
</P>
<P>
   So L.L. Bean hired Pile and Co. of Boston to conduct an ad
agency review. The review narrowed the search to three finalists:
Mullen, the Richards Group of Dallas, and Carmichael Lynch of
Minneapolis. Earlier this week, Mullen was selected.
</P>
<P>
   A Bronner subsidiary will continue to handle L.L. Bean's
marketing efforts on the World Wide Web, Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   When Mullen became Timberland's ad agency in 1989, the Stratham,
N.H. company was known mostly as a maker of workboots.
</P>
<P>
   With Mullen's help and such slogans as, ``Give racism the
boot,'' Timberland was able to make the transition to a lifestyle
brand known as much for apparel fashion prized by urban hipsters as
for rugged footwear loved by lumberjacks.
</P>
<P>
   Timberland and Mullen parted company in 1995. Between 1989 and
1995, Timberland's annual sales grew from about $156 million to
$655 million.
</P>
<P>
   With the recent sale of Arnold Communications and Hill Holliday
Connors Cosmopulos, Mullen is now the largest independent ad agency
in New England.
</P>
<P>
   By landing L.L. Bean's account, Mullen can claim to be on a
winning streak. Other recent new clients include the Stanley Works,
a tool company; Swiss Army Brands; and Dexter Shoe Co.
</P>
<P>
   Big Mullen clients include Nextel Communications, EMC Corp., and
General Motors Certified Used Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Mullen had billings of $201 million. For 1998, it now
projects billings of about $240 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
