A4014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-TAXES-NYT &LR;      06-17 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO SCRAP TAX SYSTEM AND DEVISE A NEW ONE  
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of rhetoric about the complexities and
inequities in the tax code, the House on Wednesday took a dramatic
though almost wholly symbolic step toward doing something about it.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 219-209 to require that Congress come up with a
new tax system by Independence Day 2002 and to scrap the current
code by the end of that year.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, largely along party lines, was a victory for
Republicans who have spent years expressing and cultivating
unhappiness with the tax laws and the Internal Revenue Service. It
was assailed by President Clinton and Democrats as an election-year
ploy that risked throwing the nation into economic chaos while
avoiding any hard choices about what a new tax system would look
like.
</P>
<P>
   Because the White House has threatened to veto the measure, it
will almost certainly not become law even if it passes the Senate,
where its prospects are unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But the vote gave Republicans a boost in their efforts to build
support for alternatives to the progressive income tax: a
single-rate flat tax, perhaps, or a national sales tax. And during
the congressional election campaign this fall, Republicans are
certain to try to use the vote to paint Democrats as defenders of a
555-million-word set of laws and regulations that gives taxpayers a
headache.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have today is a monstrosity,'' said Speaker Newt
Gingrich, who ticked off statistics about the burdens imposed on
businesses and individuals by the current system, including $200
billion a year spent on accountants, lawyers and other costs of
complying, 8 billion pages a year of forms filed and 5.4 billion
hours spent working on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is a very important step in the right direction,''
Gingrich said as he accepted petitions from the National Federation
of Independent Business, the small business lobbying group,
containing 750,000 signatures calling for an end to the current tax
system.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are generally united in their belief that pushing to
throw out the current code is both good policy and good politics,
and at the heart of the bill passed Wednesday was the notion that
setting a specific deadline is the best way to force action.
</P>
<P>
   It calls for a national dialogue on creating a new, unspecified
system that is ``fairer, less complicated and less burdensome to
working Americans.'' It was watered down somewhat from its original
form, which did not provide for putting any new system in place
before terminating the existing code and called for the current
system to be scrapped at the end of 2001 instead of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But for all their general fervor on the issue, Republicans have
been unable to agree among themselves on a specific replacement.
</P>
<P>
   One camp, led by Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, the majority leader,
and Steve Forbes, who made the issue the centerpiece of his 1996
presidential run, favor a flat tax. They claim their approach would
be simpler and enable almost everyone to pay taxes at a lower rate,
although at the cost of eliminating many popular tax breaks, in
some cases including the mortgage-interest deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Another camp, which includes Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, the
chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, is leaning toward some
kind of national sales or consumption tax system that would
eliminate the income tax altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they supported improving the tax system or
considering a new approach. But they said it was reckless to kill
off the current code without having even begun a serious debate on
the alternatives, much less having worked out the substantial
complexities of managing a transition from one system to another.
</P>
<P>
   Without knowing for sure what tax system will be in place
several years down the road, they said, individuals would have
difficulty planning for decisions like home purchases, companies
would face uncertainty about investment decisions and the entire
economy could suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we will ever live to see a more irresponsible
act,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., who said the bill was
nothing more than a stunt for use against Democrats on the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's pass a law to terminate cancer,'' Rangel said. ``If you
vote against it you support cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was in favor of simplifying the tax system and
had not ruled out any alternatives. But he said passage of the
House bill would be a bad mistake, increasing risks to the economy
at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing in the world we need to do right now is to send
some signal of instability that we've decided to get rid of our
whole tax code without knowing what to replace it with,'' Clinton
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1845EDT &QL; 
