<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WEAPONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSAULT WEAPONS BILL SEEMS HEADED FOR PASSAGE IN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A bill to ban assault weapons in Massachusetts is
expected to be OK'd by lawmakers in the House Thursday, but not
before an expected battle over whether to close some politically
sensitive loopholes in the law.
</P>
<P>
   One amendment that may be approved by the smallest of margins
would prevent current owners of high-capacity guns to resell them.
The other proposed change _ which is more likely to pass _ would
prevent felons from purchasing rifles and shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an extremely tough vote for people to say `No, I'm
going to work for the rights of convicted felons.' That's the kind
of vote that will come back to haunt you time and time again if you
run for any statewide office,'' said state Senator Cheryl A.
Jacques, a Needham Democrat and supporter of an outright ban.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Governor Paul Cellucci _ who, with former governor
William F. Weld, has filed four assault weapons bills over the
years _ Wednesday said he would call legislators and ask them to
support the measure. However, no Republicans voted for the ban when
it passed the Senate last fall and it remains to be seen whether
Cellucci can deliver any GOP votes in the House. Former senator
Jane Swift, a North Adams Republican whom Cellucci chose as his
running mate, was an ardent opponent of a ban. She now favors it.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate bills are similar, except that the House
version allows felons to purchase rifles and shotguns five years
after being released from prison and it would allow current assault
weapon owners to resell them.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci Wednesday indirectly blamed House Speaker Thomas M.
Finneran _ not Republicans _ for the Legislature's failure to pass
an assault weapons ban by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, the assault weapons ban was a victim of
legislative hijinks. We already know there's a difference between
the Senate and House (versions). My hope is that the House and the
Senate, when they have a conference committee, this time around it
will be a real conference committee that will legitimately resolve
the differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci was referring to earlier weapons-ban bills passed in
1996 by the House and Senate that died in conference committee when
then-speaker Charles Flaherty was forced to resign and Finneran was
voted to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the Senate again passed legislation banning
semi-automatic assault weapons and high-capacity ammunition
magazines, which hold more than 10 rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Joint Commmittee on Public Safety released the
bill the House is taking up. That legislation, like the Senate
version, has a child-access-prevention statute requiring safe
storage of guns and increasing penalties for usage of guns in
certain situations.
</P>
<P>
   Currently in Massachusetts, a convicted felon is prohibited for
life from getting a handgun; however, five years after release from
prison, a convicted felon can legally obtain a rifle or shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Also, any assault weapons made before 1994 can still be traded
on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   While the Senate bill closed those loopholes, the House version
does not.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill was stuck in the House Ways and Means Committee
for the past eight months, despite an ongoing effort by proponents
to move the legislation to the House.
</P>
<P>
   But Finneran, feeling political pressure to get it passed,
agreed to have a vote by mid-June. Neither Finneran nor his
spokesman could be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
