<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMSAT-LAWSUIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WINS $4.25 MILLION JUDGMENT AGAINST TELECOM COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A Texas man who worked on telecommunications
deals in Africa has won a $4.25 million judgment against his former
employer, which he said fired him to avoid paying his commission on
a $38.2 million Ivory Coast deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an example of corporate America at its worst,'' said
Lyndell Kirkley, one of several Fort Worth attorneys who
represented Jose Mendoza of Mineral Wells in his suit against
Comsat.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Bethesda, Md., Comsat is an international satellite
corporation that until June 1997 owned two professional sports
teams, the Denver Nuggets of the National Basketball Association
and the Colorado Avalanche of the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza sued Comsat in federal court in Fort Worth. U.S.
District Judge Terry Means entered a final judgment in the case
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-week trial in March, a jury found that Mendoza
was the ``procuring cause'' of the $38.2 million sale, meaning that
the deal resulted from his work but that Comsat hindered completion
of it and then fired him.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded Mendoza $1 million, but Means increased that
amount to about $3 million plus more than $1 million in interest,
because the judge concluded that jurors had calculated damages
incorrectly.
</P>
<P>
   Comsat plans to appeal on several issues, including the judge's
decision to increase the damage award, said Pat Long, a Dallas
attorney for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the jury verdict is going to stand up, the most should be
the $1 million found by the jury,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Long added, ``we don't believe we have any liability.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit also alleges that Comsat engaged in a conspiracy with
two high-powered Washington lawyers, Ivory Coast government
officials and the man hired to replace Mendoza. Jurors did not find
that a conspiracy took place.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence presented during trial indicated that the lawyers, John
P. Sears and Joel Hoppenstein, were behind Mendoza's ouster and
benefited financially from it. Sears served as campaign manager for
Presidents Nixon and Reagan. Hoppenstein worked for Sears' firm.
</P>
<P>
   Trial testimony also indicated that high-placed Ivory Coast
government officials profited _ violating, Mendoza alleged, the
Foreign Corrupt Practices Act.
</P>
<P>
   Comsat acknowledged that the Washington lawyers and foreign
government officials profited, at least indirectly. The company
maintained that there was nothing inappropriate about those
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Comsat hired Mendoza to promote its telecommunications
products and service in several African countries, including the
Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
   In fall 1988, Mendoza appeared close to striking a deal for a
domestic satellite system. The system included ``Earth stations''
to receive and transmit signals, communications systems for police
and the U.S. Embassy, and radio, television and telephone systems.
</P>
<P>
   But before the deal was finalized, Comsat fired Mendoza, who
would have received an 8 percent commission, and hired an Ivorian
named Loum Diagne. Comsat maintained that it dismissed Mendoza
because he couldn't close the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just concluded the deal was dead,'' Long said. ``It took a
change of government and different circumstances in the government
to revive the deal'' more than a year after Mendoza's firing.
</P>
<P>
   The suit _ argued by Kirkley and fellow attorneys Larry Cotten
and David Broiles _ contended that Mendoza was fired to save the
company about half the cost of his commission. The rest was spread
around to the two Washington lawyers, Diagne, and, indirectly,
high-placed Ivorian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Comsat acknowledged that Mendoza was fired and Diagne hired at
the suggestion of Sears and Hoppenstein, who had a business
relationship with Diagne. Diagne and the two lawyers had planned to
construct an office building in the Ivory Coast, but the project
was unsuccessful because Diagne had problems with the title to the
property, the suit states. That left Diagne indebted to Sears and
Hoppenstein.
</P>
<P>
   After Comsat hired Diagne, the company paid the two lawyers
$250,000 and awarded a $729,000 construction contract for the Ivory
Coast project to Diplomatic Security Inc., a firm with which the
lawyers were affiliated, according to trial evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Diagne was also president of a company called La Financiere,
whose investors and shareholders included high-placed Ivorian
government officials. About $611,000 of the $769,000 Comsat paid
Diagne was turned over to La Financiere.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
