<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DAVIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS SAYS HE LOOKS FORWARD TO A BOOST FROM CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ California Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, the Democratic
nominee for governor of the Golden State, said Wednesday he will be
``proud to campaign'' with President Clinton despite controversies
that continue to dog the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from the White House after an Oval Office meeting with
Clinton, Davis told reporters the president ``has literally
transformed peoples' lives in this country.'' At a meeting last
weekend in California the president committed himself to joining
Davis on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, standing with his wife Sharon, brushed aside a reporter's
question about whether Clinton would be an asset, given Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr's Whitewater and Monica Lewinsky probes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Davis replied, ``In California just four years ago,
people were complaining that the equity was declining in their
homes (and that) children were moving back in with them when they
graduated from college because no jobs were available. All that has
changed, and a good share of the credit belongs to this
administration. So I am proud to campaign with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Davis said, he won a commitment from Vice President
Al Gore to make campaign appearances. The dates and locations of
appearances with Clinton and Gore are being worked out, he added.
</P>
<P>
   In the Oval Office, Davis said, he and Clinton discussed the
president's education proposals, including one to spend $12 billion
over seven years to hire an extra 100,000 teachers and another to
allow federal backing for $22 billion in interest-free bonds for
school construction and repairs. He also applauded Clinton's
decision in Monterey, Calif., last weekend to extend until 2012 an
oil-drilling ban off parts of California's coast.
</P>
<P>
   Davis wrapped up a three-day swing through Washington in which
he met with California's 29-member Democratic congressional
delegation, which issued a letter backing him for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Among others he saw here were Gore; Colorado Gov. Roy Romer,
chairman of the Democratic National Committee; Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., and Gerard McEntee, president of the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees.
</P>
<P>
   He said Democratic leaders in Washington are ``pumped'' over his
victory in the June 2 primary over party rivals Rep. Jane Harman
and wealthy businessman Al Checchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has been a constant source of divisive wedge
issues,'' he said, noting that many Democrats and allied interest
groups in Washington have devoted a lot of ``money and personal
attention'' to those issues.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning the name of Republican Pete Wilson, Davis
took a swipe at the current governor for backing such controversial
ballot initiatives as Proposition 187, which in 1994 barred most
social services and education to undocumented immigrants, and
Proposition 209, which in 1996 ended affirmative action in state
hiring, contracting and admissions to public colleges and
universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington interests,'' Davis said, would ``very much welcome
a governor who is positive, inclusive and forward-looking (and who)
will not put on the ballot a series of divisive issues that have
drained the treasuries and occupied the attention (of the Democrats
and allied groups).''
</P>
<P>
   Davis also said he and his Republican opponent, California
Attorney General Dan Lungren, have agreed to five debates _ one
each in July and August and the remaining three after Labor Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
