<SLUG> BC-EXECS-SURVEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSSES AND TOP LIEUTENANTS DIFFER, SURVEY SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chief executives and their top lieutenants need to have a long
talk.
</P>
<P>
   A new survey by the Association of Executive Search Consultants
shows widely divergent views between the two camps on issues like
succession and training for the top job.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, for example, shows 57 percent of senior executives
identified by search firms as ``future CEOs'' think they will have
to go to another company to get the top job. By contrast,
two-thirds of current chief executives believe their successors
will be promoted from within.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem may be what the future chief executives see
as ``successor sabotage'' _ almost half said it was not uncommon
for chief executives, reluctant to step down, to criticize possible
successors within the company to the board, dashing the chances of
internal candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the problem may be different perceptions about
the quality of executive training. More than three-quarters of
current chief executives said they felt they played an active role
in development training, but most senior and human resource
executives disagreed, and said the chief executives needed to be
more involved in training.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a perception on the part of the CEOs that they are
doing an adequate job getting to the next level down,'' said John
Lloyd, chairman of the association and vice chairman of the
Witt/Kieffer executive search firm. ``But there is a disparate view
from young and up-and-coming executives, who want to be more than a
passive bystander.''
</P>
<P>
   The association, which includes 160 executive search firms
nationwide, surveyed three groups of executives in March and April
_ 100 chief executives, 100 ``future CEOs'' and 100 human-resource
executives. They represented a broad range of industries, and on
average the annual sales of their companies were $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   _ At least two-thirds of each group said that the rise of the
``portable CEO,'' who jumps from company to company and industry to
industry, had had a negative impact on loyalty throughout corporate
America. At the same time, the executives said such jumps were not
a stretch for their skills _ about 80 percent over all said that
effective chief executives need not come from within a company's
industry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Higher turnover among chief executives has resulted largely
from increased shareholder pressure for immediate results, most
executives said, adding that such pressure has hampered their
ability to serve others with a stake, such as employees and
communities. Many believe the rate of chief-executive turnover will
increase.
</P>
<P>
   _ A slight majority of all three groups surveyed also said
international experience was not a prerequisite to becoming a chief
executive. But to those who are considering going abroad, the
Asia-Pacific region was cited most frequently as the best training
ground.
</P>
<P>
   _ All the effort required to get to the top spot is not worth it
to some. A clear majority of all three groups said they knew
somebody in an upper management position who had opted out of
corporate America, and that they had considered doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   Most senior and human resource executives believe the phenomenon
of opting out will grow over the next decade. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
