u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-REDWINGS-555&AMP;ADD-     06-17 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REDWINGS-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWMAN AND WINGS KEEP MOTOWN BEAT GOING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two days before the Stanley Cup finals began, coach
Scotty Bowman brought his Detroit Red Wings onto the ice at Joe
Louis Arena in Detroit early on a Sunday morning. Game 1 was still
more than 48 hours away, and it could have been a sloppy, unfocused
practice. Gathering his mostly veteran champions in a circle at
center ice, Bowman began to bark out instructions for a new drill.
Everyone, even in the seats, could hear every word. But in their
totality, the instructions were disjointed and made little sense.
Confused, the players tried the new drill and messed it up.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman quickly brought them back into the circle. He yelled some
more, in a louder voice, while gesturing with his hands and hockey
stick. But it was still difficult to comprehend what he wanted.
After the players bungled the drill again, Bowman blew his whistle
with a shrill blast, brought them together a third time and yelled
even more. Finally, the players began to snarl at one another.
Everyone seemed irked and on edge. Bowman then ordered a different
drill, one of the old drills, one which the players knew well. They
executed it perfectly, with intense focus.
</P>
<P>
   In five quick minutes, Bowman had got everyone's attention and
had charged the practice with sharp, nervous energy.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings won't practice again until September, when they
report to training camp. They guaranteed this Tuesday night at MCI
Center when they defeated the Capitals by 4-1 to complete a
four-game sweep of the Stanley Cup finals. It was Detroit's second
consecutive championship and the fourth season in succession that
the last round of the National Hockey League's postseason
tournament has ended in a sweep. And it was another of Bowman's
many triumphant moments, his eighth Stanley Cup as a coach, tying
him with Toe Blake, his mentor, who won eight with Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman has won five as coach of the Canadiens, one as coach of
Pittsburgh, and two with Detroit. He also won a ring with
Pittsburgh as a front-office executive. This was Bowman's 12th trip
to the finals. His first was 30 years ago, in 1968, when his
expansion St. Louis Blues lost in a four-game sweep to Blake's
Canadiens. Cerebral, demanding, churlish and intuitive, Bowman is
not a charm-school coach. Through generations of athletes, he has
changed some of his tactics while maintaining his inscrutable aura
and air of authority. Igor Larionov, a Detroit veteran who admires
him, calls Bowman ``the conductor of a big orchestra.'' With a
hockey stick as his figurative baton, Bowman has them all on key
and in tempo.
</P>
<P>
   With three trips to the finals in the last four springs, the
late 1990s have swung to a Motown beat. Sergei Fedorov, somewhat
less enamored with Bowman than Larionov, admits the coach ``can
read the game when nobody is certain what is going to happen
next.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we agree,'' Fedorov said. ``Sometimes we disagree.
But it is part of the learning experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Now age 64, it is not certain that Professor Bowman will be back
next season to try for three in a row and to break Blake's record.
He has a year left on his contract, at his option.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough decision not to come back,'' Bowman
said. ``I realize that. But I've got to leave sometime. I want to
make sure I'm leaving at the right time when I do leave.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ken Holland, the Detroit general manager, said earlier this week
that he expects Bowman to return. Without a team to coach, Holland
said, Bowman would be bored by mid-September. Bowman said he would
wait until the emotion calms down to make and announce his
decision. It will take a few weeks for the emotion of Tuesday night
to wear off.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the emotion will still be visible on Thursday, however,
when Detroit _ which calls itself Hockeytown _ will greet the Wings
on their parade down Woodward Avenue to Hart Plaza on the downtown
riverfront. It is possible that the parade will include Vladimir
Konstantinov, the injured defenseman, who attended Tuesday night's
clincher and led the on-ice procession with the silver trophy in
his wheelchair. One of the team's top players last spring,
Konstantinov and the Wings' masseur, Sergei Manatsakanov, suffered
serious brain damage in a crash of their limousine last June 13,
six days after the cup was won.
</P>
<P>
   Before Konstantinov was wheeled onto the ice Tuesday night, he
watched the game from a landing about 20 rows behind one of the
nets. During a timeout, he stood, with help from his wife, to wave
and greet the fans who were cheering him. The Wings players,
standing in front of their bench, heard the noise, saw their
red-clad teammate and responded by tapping their sticks on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole bench came unglued,'' Brendan Shanahan said. ``We
were screaming and yelling. Scotty tried to calm us down because we
still had a period to play. But there was no way. There wasn't a
dry eye on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman smiled and shook his head afterward at the memory. ``It
just went right through the whole bench,'' he said, adding that he
was concerned because the game still had about 16 minutes
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   There are some situations even Bowman can't control. But his
team contained the Capitals with no further scoring. Doug Brown got
two of the goals Tuesday. Steve Yzerman, the captain, won the Conn
Smythe trophy as most valuable player in the postseason. Yzerman,
after accepting the cup, handed it directly to Konstantinov, at the
suggestion of Shanahan. On the ice and in the locker room, the
players kept gathering around Konstantinov. Slava Fetisov said
``Vladdie's spirit'' was with the team all season. Shanahan said
the moment ``transcended sports.''
</P>
<P>
   In a reprise of the team theme song from last season, Larionov
sang softly in Konstantinov's ear ``We are the champions ...'' and
Konstantinov answered `` ... my friend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
