</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WESTBANK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 ISRAELI TEEN-AGERS JAILED AFTER DEATH OF PALESTINIAN FARMER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Two Israeli teen-agers living in a hostel for
troubled youths in a Jewish settlement near Hebron were jailed
Wednesday after a Palestinian farmer was killed on a West Bank
roadside when they hit him with a wooden pole from a passing van.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian, Abdel Majid Abu Turki, 47, a father of 10, was
attacked on Tuesday near the settlement of Beit Haggai, and details
of the incident emerged Wednesday as a Jerusalem court ordered the
16-year-old suspects held for six days pending charges.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers, who appeared in court with their heads hidden by
Jewish prayer shawls, had confessed to the killing earlier and
re-enacted it with police investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The murder is a shocking murder and we can't accept it,''
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told reporters. ``Whoever
committed this terrible act will be prosecuted to the fullest
extent of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad Tibi, an adviser to Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader,
attributed the slaying to ``terrible incitement against the
Palestinians'' by Jewish settlers, and he urged directors of the
hostel to ``examine the education they are giving these youths.''
</P>
<P>
   Tareq Zeid, commander of Palestinian forces in Hebron, called
the killing an example of ``Israeli policies of continuous and
daily attacks'' on Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli police said the teen-agers killed Abu Turki with a
wooden pole they had thrust out of a van as they rode to Beit
Haggai.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Turki's relatives said he had been walking home from his
plot of land with three other men when he was smashed on the back
of the neck from a speeding vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as a murder,'' said Commander Moshe Ariel, the
chief investigating officer for the Israeli Police in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But the director of the hostel, Efraim Hibsh, described the
incident differently. ``This was a prank that ended tragically when
Abu Turki met his death,'' Hibsh said in a radio interview. ``He is
our neighbor, he worked here and we know him. Beit Haggai condemns
the improper phenomenon of harming innocent people, Jews or
Arabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Hibsh noted that the teen-agers were taken to the police by
hostel administrators on Tuesday night after they learned of the
killing from press reports. He rejected accusations by Israeli
peace groups that the teen-agers had drawn inspiration from
anti-Arab views promoted by educators and rabbis in Jewish
settlements. ``We see nothing wrong with the way we are
educating,'' he said. ``We remain faithful to our path.''
</P>
<P>
   The hostel in Beit Haggai provides housing, schooling,
counseling and vocational training for 50 teen-age dropouts and
delinquents. The two suspects were wards of the state, and one had
a police record, said their lawyer, Naftali Wurtzburger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1905EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
