<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4051 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ASIA-HNS &LR;      06-17 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS U.S. INTERVENTION TO BOLSTER JAPANESE ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton abandoned his arms' length
approach to the Asian financial crisis Wednesday and ordered U.S.
intervention in global currency markets in a bid to spark the
Japanese economy _ the second largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. intervention took the form of selling $2 billion in
dollars to buy yen, cutting the value of the dollar against the
yen. Japan also sold $2 billion in dollars to buy yen.
</P>
<P>
   The coordinated maneuver reduced the value of the dollar by 4.8
percent against the yen, thereby bolstering the value of such
yen-based businesses as the Japanese banks that make loans
throughout Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said Clinton ordered the unusual
step because of deepening U.S. concern that Japan's stubborn
recession could drag down teetering Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
   The free falling yen threatened to make Japanese products less
expensive on the world market, thereby undercutting the exports of
other nations, including the United States and Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said Clinton acted because if a major financial crisis
were to develop in Asia, ``then the effects on our nation could be
severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin added: ``It is precisely to avoid that, that the United
States has ... taken action.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also dispatched an emergency team to Tokyo to confer
with Japanese counterparts, including Deputy Treasury Secretary
Larry Summers, William McDonough, president of the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York that handles U.S. government overseas
transactions, in addition to State Department specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it was the first time during the Clinton
presidency that the United States has sold U.S. currency to reduce
its value in order to boost a foreign currency. The Clinton
administration used a related maneuver in August 1995 to prop up
the U.S. dollar by buying dollars in worldwide currency markets and
selling yen in an effort to bolster the value of the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered the action as he prepares for a 10-day visit to
China starting next week. This will be the first visit there by an
American president since the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre of
pro-democracy demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices on the New York Stock Exchange rose in response to
the Clinton administration's actions. The Dow Jones industrial
average closed up 164.17 at 8,829.46 two days after tumbling 207
points due to concern about the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the expansion of the stalled Japanese economy
remains ``very important to keeping our own economic progress
going,'' adding: ``We've got a chance to turn that situation in
Asia around before it gets any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the 10-month Asian financial crisis that began in
Thailand has cost the U.S. economy an estimated $23 billion in lost
exports in the first quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   America's economic expansion, now in its 79th month, is the
third longest peacetime expansion in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered the intervention following a White House meeting
Tuesday with Rubin, national security adviser Samuel ``Sandy''
Berger, national economic adviser Gene Sperling and others.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto in a
15-minute telephone call at 11:30 p.m. EDT Tuesday evening that the
United States would move to bolster the Japanese yen if the
Japanese government took hard-nosed steps to stimulate the Japanese
economy, bail out troubled banks and deregulate the Japanese
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know whether what you do in all these things will
make a large difference,'' Clinton said during a Rose Garden
ceremony. ``But I wanted to send a clear signal to the markets that
the United States supports Japanese reform, believes the Japanese
people can pull out of this economic slump and restore growth and
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin indicated that additional U.S. efforts to boost the
Japanese yen could be undertaken in the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Clinton took the action in part to stem China's
threatened devaluation of the yuan in a bid to make Chinese exports
more competitive with Japanese exports. U.S. officials continued
their appeals for China to resist such a move.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese Finance Minister Xiang Huaicheng warned in an article in
Tuesday's editions of The People's Daily, the Communist party
newspaper, that China could face increased ``pressure'' to cut the
value of the yuan unless Japan showed the ``courage and wisdom'' to
halt the downward spiral of the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has an immense stake in the outcome of the
Asian financial crisis. Two-way U.S. trade with Asia accounts for
28.8 percent of U.S. worldwide commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The two-way U.S.-Japan trade of $187 billion accounts for almost
10 percent of all U.S. trade. Perhaps more importantly, Japan's
multi-billion dollar trade with Asian neighbors supports hundreds
of thousands of jobs across the Pacific Rim, including in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1907EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
