A4058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-COLUMN-500&AMP;ADD-NY     06-17 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLUMN-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TODAY'S GOLFERS FEAR NOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By AL BARKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a rare candid moment some years after the fact, the late Ben
Hogan recalled he had contributed to his own incredible playoff
loss to Jack Fleck in the 1955 U.S. Open, at San Francisco's
Olympic Club, where this year's Open begins Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On the second hole, Hogan had reached the green in regulation,
and was waiting there for Fleck while the obscure municipal course
pro struggled after a poor tee shot, taking considerable time to
play from deep rough and a bunker. When Fleck at last arrived on
the green, he said to Hogan, ``Sorry to keep you waiting.'' Hogan
replied, ``That's OK, we've got nothing else to do today.'' And
with that reply, Hogan reminisced, he gave up his edge, his
intimidation factor. Fleck won, 69-72.
</P>
<P>
   In Hogan's day, a champion player, by virtue of his record and
his manner of being as well, could cow a less-accomplished
opponent. Hogan, with his dour and silent mien, was an intimidator
supreme. Jack Nicklaus was not quite as grim, but his
self-absorption was palpable. Opponents felt he didn't know they
even existed. He did know, though, his effect on them. Nicklaus
once remarked that when in contention coming down the stretch he
had at least a stroke up on the others by simply being Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of thing doesn't prevail anymore, it appears. Today's
leading young players _ Tiger Woods, Justin Leonard, Ernie Els,
David Duval, Lee Westwood, et. al., simply are not afraid of
anything or anyone. They are not terrified by the significance of
an event, or the presence and previous accomplishments of other
players, especially the older, established ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt afraid of anyone out here, in golf,'' said
25-year-old Westwood, the current British hotshot.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? What makes the new generation of golfers so intrepid?
The former PGA champion Bob Tway is one of many who make the point
that today's young professionals experience so much high-quality
competition on high-quality courses as teens and in college that
coming onto the pro circuit is merely an extension of their golf
life. Many of the players have been playing each other for years.
So if intimidation is at least partly the product of dealing with
something new, what's to fear?
</P>
<P>
   Also, a large percentage of today's professional golfers come
from of a middle-class background. Their parents could afford to
provide them with professional instruction, perhaps membership in a
country club, the opportunity to travel, a college education and
the money to play the amateur golf circuit. Previous generations of
pros, in most cases, rose from less-fortunate economic situations.
Kids who come to big-time golf from more comfortable circumstances
simply feel at home, even deserving. Many of their predecessors
often got into golf as caddies, not a bad line of work for a young
person but one decidedly on the servant side of the spectrum. Poor
youngsters are more apt to be awed by the accoutrements of
well-being, at least when first encountered.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Frank Nobilo, the New Zealander playing the American pro
circuit, is among those who feel the amount of money that can be
made in pro golf now is a component of fearlessness. ``You can make
so much now, in only one tournament, that it's leveled the playing
field,'' he said. ``Because you don't have to cut corners, be
overly careful as a player, you can take more chances.'' Nobilo
also points out that pros now ``have all the equipment experts out
here, swing gurus, psychologists, all there for us with the latest
and best information, so we don't have to hang around the old pros,
get their confidence, to get insights on the game and how to play
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Twitty believes today's clubs and balls have to no little
degree taken the artistry out of playing the game. Hence, there is
no call to watch the old timers play cut shots and draws and
knockdowns, and ask them how they do it. ``Technology has made so
much of the game so much easier,'' said Twitty. ``What with how far
the ball goes and how much less it curves in the air, and because
of the perfect grasses we play from, we don't need those finesse
shots anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe there is more to it than equipment technology and
economics. Perhaps there is something in the popular culture that
is putting no fear in the hearts of young athletes. Television, for
example. Past sports heroes were, in a way, mythological figures,
in part because they weren't actually seen that often. But with the
coming of television, and its extensive, not to say
small-screen-intimate coverage, kids can see for themselves that
major leaguers will bobble the easy grounder, strike out swinging
at a bad pitch, miss two free throws in a row, drop a pass in the
end zone, or watch in living color every excruciating moment as
Greg Norman fritters away a huge lead in the final round of the
Masters. Seeing the stars make mistakes has more impact than
reading about it.
</P>
<P>
   Take this a step further. On television, the normally
stone-faced Nick Faldo breaks down in tears upon winning a British
Open. Nothing wrong with grown men crying in emotional times, of
course, even when winning. Quite human, in fact. Which is the
point. It corroborates what Lee Westwood had drilled into him by
his school-teacher father: ``Dad said everyone puts their pants on
one leg at a time,'' Westwood said. ``The best players just make
fewer mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is there to be intimidated by?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
