<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4061 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANGER-CONTROL-KAN &LR;      06-17 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGER-CONTROL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOU'RE SO ANGRY YOU COULD EXPLODE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDWARD M. EVELD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Let's say a guy wearing a ball cap walks into a bar,
plunks down his quarter on the pool table and waits his turn to
play. A second fellow comes in and sets down his quarter _ ahead of
the other.
</P>
<P>
   The guy in the cap starts to boil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Move that quarter,'' he bellows, ``if you don't want your
(expletive) face smashed in.''
</P>
<P>
   A fight breaks out. The cops show up. Luckily, no one pulled a
gun.
</P>
<P>
   These guys would be good candidates for anger-control
counseling. If there were a court case, a judge might require it.
</P>
<P>
   Famous _ and infamous _ names are bringing anger counseling into
the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker Tommy Lee was sentenced to anger counseling after
pleading no contest to beating a photographer. And the parents of
Oregon school shooting suspect Kip Kinkel had enrolled him in anger
control classes but not soon enough: His violent outburst allegedly
killed them and two classmates.
</P>
<P>
   While most of us aren't likely to go that far, every day we get
angry: At bosses, co-workers, employees, other drivers, our
spouses, our children.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors in the 1960s and '70s used to tell people to vent
their anger, and that anger created pressure that needed to be
released, said David Kupfer, a clinical psychologist in Falls
Church, Va., who specializes in anger control. Subsequent research
has shown that people who ``get it off their chest'' vociferously
actually feel worse. Constant complaining or sulking also indulges
anger rather than solves anything, Kupfer pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Now anger-management education helps people alter perceptions
and change behaviors. Often enough, counselors say, our anger stems
from an overblown interpretation of events. Or, we express
justifiable anger in a way that, over time, wrecks relationships
and makes life miserable.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first strategies of anger control is to become aware
of the physiology of anger, said Kirk McClelland, clinical social
worker at CenterPoint Counseling and Recovery in Kansas City. He
just completed a two-year domestic violence program with men.
</P>
<P>
   Once the men learn the physical cues of anger _ tightening of
the jaw and chest, increased heart rate and respiration _ they can
override them cognitively, McClelland said. They can force
themselves to stop, step back and take a time out to cool down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to help them learn that they're doing something that
takes a lot more courage than just moving into the battle,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That simple strategy can keep violence from occurring, said
McClelland, but then clients must work on the roots of their anger.
Many in the program were working-class men who felt inadequate and
unsuccessful and didn't see how to change their situations, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   George Ronan, a clinical psychologist in Mount Pleasant, Mich.,
targets anger in his violence reduction program at Central Michigan
University. Clients often arrive thinking that anger and aggression
are the best options to maintain control of their situations and
other people, Ronan said.
</P>
<P>
   But their anger actually allows others to control them. A person
who loses his cool can be manipulated, Ronan said. Others can push
their buttons _ like the pool player who wanted to have a fun
Friday night but ended up in jail. Similarly, angry spouses, bosses
and workers find their real goals _ a nice weekend, a completed
project _ sidelined by hostility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hostility is our way of saying, `You're not going to get away
with mistreating me this way,' '' said Richard Driscoll, a clinical
psychologist in Knoxville, Tenn., who advises couples on anger
management.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most devastating episodes happen at home, between
husbands and wives. Driscoll spends a lot of time in his practice
teaching partners how to understand and express their anger.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their intimate relationship, spouses can inflict a
lot of damage on each other _ and their marriage. The angry
confrontations say ``straighten up and do me right or suffer my
wrath,'' Driscoll said.
</P>
<P>
   About 12 percent of married couples report ``physical
confrontation'' while angry at each other, including grabbing and
pushing, Driscoll said. About 3 percent say it escalates to serious
violence.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest mistakes partners make is to throw blanket
accusations at each other, he said, such as, ``You never listen to
me,'' or, ``You never want to have sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll said people can manage their anger in several ways: by
changing how they talk about their grievances, by changing their
interpretation of events and by changing their behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of rationally assessing the situation, couples
eventually take to heart their own angry criticisms. Their
relationships become as shallow and empty as the bleak portraits
they've painted, no matter how inaccurate, Driscoll said.
</P>
<P>
   He teaches spouses not to say, ``You never listen to me,''
rather, ``I know you're tired after a long day, but I'm lost right
now and I need your attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Stop and think whether you've interpreted the situation fairly.
Did your spouse really come home late to purposely mess up the
dinner you had planned? Or, if getting home late is a source of
angry confrontations, can you redouble your efforts to leave on
time, or can you change your home schedule to more accurately
reflect work demands?
</P>
<P>
   ``If when you're angry you feel justified, remember you're not
so innocent,'' Driscoll said. ``You're contributing to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Become aware of how much your anger will harm someone you
love. It gives you reason to control it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4063 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MULAN-COMMENT-KAN &LR;      06-17 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULAN-COMMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN MOUTH ROBS `MULAN' OF ITS UNIQUE VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: When ``Mulan'' opens Friday on the nation's screens,
moviegoers will be treated to one of Walt Disney's best animated
films.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it might have been a great film, had its makers had a
little more faith in the subject matter and a lot less reliance on
formula.
</P>
<P>
   The good news: ``Mulan'' is visually spectacular, emotionally
resonant, narratively compelling and filled with cartoon characters
who, strangely enough, seem far more believable than most of the
flesh-and-blood actors populating today's movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our roots are still in the tradition of the Disney animated
classic,'' Mulan's director, Barry Cook, said in a recent telephone
interview. ``But a little at a time, we're getting away from those
elements and finding new ways of telling stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook and crew can be proud of what they've accomplished with
``Mulan,'' which more than any other recent Disney film seems
rooted in a particular time and place. It's based on an ancient
Chinese legend about a girl who disguises herself as a man and
joins the army in place of her aged father. To their credit, the
filmmakers have made a real effort to incorporate Chinese visual
motifs, Asian-American voices, and even elements of traditional
Chinese music.
</P>
<P>
   Cook credits one of the film's writers, Rita Hsiao, and many of
the voice talents for demanding a high degree of respect for a
story that is known all over Asia but which is unfamiliar to most
Americans. Among the voices are those of several prominent Asian
and Asian-American actors, including Ming-Na Wen, Lea Salonga, B.D.
Wong, George Takei, Gedde Watanabe, James Shigata and Pat Morita.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing they emphasized was their love of the tale,''
Cook said. ``The rest of us had never heard of it, but these
Asian-Americans had heard it as children. They had a love for the
character of Mulan coming into the project, and they transferred
that to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The results are, in most respects, spectacular. ``Mulan'' is so
good, in fact, that finding any fault with it puts the critic in
the unenviable position of throwing a wet blanket on everybody's
good time.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``Mulan'' has one problem. In a film that is in
many ways is overwhelmingly Chinese, one character stands out as an
anachronism. The heroine Mulan is accompanied by an inept
pint-sized dragon named Mushu whose voice is provided by ... Eddie
Murphy?
</P>
<P>
   And not a restrained Eddie Murphy, either. No this is Eddie
Murphy in full-blown, African-American street hipster mode. He
cracks wise, spews exclamations and drops references reflecting
contemporary black humor.
</P>
<P>
   That Murphy is often quite funny in the film is not in question.
The problem is his approach is undeniably out of sync with the rest
of the effort, his glib outbursts at odds with the essentially
serious tone of this undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   Mushu doesn't ruin the movie. In fact, he'll probably prove to
be the most popular character with children and as such will sell a
lot of tickets _ and stuffed toys. But Murphy being cast in this
role reflects one of the more irritating elements in Disney's
animation formula.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell it's this: The inhabitants of the Mouse House seem
to have a deathly fear of letting a story find its own voice.
Whatever the elements that attract the filmmakers to a story in the
first place, they eventually will be forced through the Disney
mold, galvanized with the Disney formula to eliminate anything at
odds with the studio's homogeneous world view.
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly a new phenomenon. Even in the studio's first
animated feature, ``Snow White,'' the seven dwarfs were more Three
Stooges than Brothers Grimm. They were basically American stock
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has been reasonably purist when dealing with British
subjects. The studio's ``Peter Pan,'' ``Sleeping Beauty,'' ``The
Great Mouse Detective,'' ``101 Dalmatians'' (the animated version)
and ``Beauty and the Beast'' actually took pleasure in reflecting
British attitudes, characters and humor.
</P>
<P>
   But let the setting get more exotic, and get ready for some
cultural whitewash. ``The Jungle Book'' may have taken place in
India, but the animal characters were so Damon Runyon, the famous
chronicler of Broadway street life, they could have been born
within a block of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was brought home most forcefully in ``The Lion
King.'' The story was set in Africa but, with the exception of the
baboon//shaman character and some African chanting in the opening
number, it was about as Afrocentric as a meeting of the Odd Fellows
lodge in Peculiar.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the attitudes, characters, songs and humor of ``The
Lion King'' reflected the sensibilities of white, middle-class
American suburbanites _ in other words, the people who made the
film as well as its biggest audience.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, when ``The Lion King'' found its way to the Broadway
stage, its visionary director//designer, Julie Taymor, emphasized
its African roots to a degree barely hinted at in the movie. As a
result of this, the stage ``Lion King'' is a real improvement on
the film, an escape into a totally original world.
</P>
<P>
   That ``Mulan'' often actually feels Chinese undoubtedly reflects
a shift in emphasis among Disney animators. But the powers that be
clearly are uncomfortable with following that to its logical
conclusion. After all, if ``Mulan'' were to seem too exotic, too
foreign, audiences might not warm up to it.
</P>
<P>
   So we can think of Eddie Murphy as a sort of box-office
insurance policy. His Mushu speaks in an idiom that American
audiences, especially kids, will immediately recognize.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain irony here: African-American culture has
become such a highly visible force in popular entertainment that
middle-class white kids immediately respond to it. On the one hand,
this represents social progress; on the other, black culture is now
so mainstream that it's considered ripe for co-opting by Disney.
</P>
<P>
   You can understand why the film's producers took this approach.
Robin Williams' manic whirlwind of a genie in ``Aladdin'' forever
changed Disney cartoons. Instead of humor for the ages, he dished
humor for the here and now, imitating Arnold Schwarzenegger, Rodney
Dangerfield, William F. Buckley and other contemporary cultural
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aladdin'' was trendy and topical, a cartoon absolutely aware
of its own cartoonishness and always joking about it.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Mulan,'' like ``Beauty and the Beast,'' is at heart a
serious dramatic story and evokes a much more delicate mood. It
deserves to find its true voice _ a Chinese voice _ undiluted by
Disney's ethnic mix-and-match recipe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
