<P>
   HEASTER-COLUMN (Overland Park, Kan.) _ A job with a chamber of
commerce is just another turn on man's career path. Economics
column by JERRY HEASTER. Story will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   BOMBER-FLEET (Knob Noster, Mo.) _ The B-2 stealth bomber fleet
based in Missouri costs billions more than expected, and a
government report released Tuesday concludes that the aircraft
can't fly as reliably or as secretly as needed. At a cost of $44.3
billion and counting, the 21 stealth bombers still fall short of
Air Force expectations in several ways, Congress' General
Accounting Office said in its report, and the radar-confusing skin
of the aircraft tends to peel apart slightly at the seams. By SCOTT
CANON. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD-OZARKS (Undated) _ U.S. Secretary of Interior Bruce Babbitt
has decided to negotiate a new deal with Doe Run Co. that would
give him authority to block lead mining in the Ozarks. By MICHAEL
MANSUR. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-WINNER (Stilwell, Kan.) _ Rex Gardner returns to Stilwell
with a face flush with victory and burned by the sun and wind, the
winner of the History Channel's Great Race. For finishing first in
the 4,000-mile cross-country endurance contest, he receives
$90,000. By FINN BULLERS. Story will move in ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   TEAM-WORKPLACE (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Most everyone agrees that
teamwork is an essential workplace skill. But ask what being a
``good team player'' means, and the answers vary. Men typically
define a team player as someone who ``follows orders'' or
``supports unquestionably.'' Women usually say a team player
``shares information'' and ``collaborates.'' By DIANE STAFFORD.
Story will move in ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-MICROSOFT (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Microsoft is using a
16-year-old computer geek from Wichita to hawk Windows 98, which
goes on sale next week. By DAVID HAYES. Story will move in ``f''
category.
</P>
<P>
   MULAN-COMMENT (Undated) _ When ``Mulan'' opens Friday on the
nation's screens, moviegoers will be treated to one of Walt
Disney's best animated films. Nevertheless, ``Mulan'' has one
problem. In a film that is in many ways is overwhelmingly Chinese,
one character stands out as an anachronism. The heroine Mulan is
accompanied by an inept pint-sized dragon named Mushu whose voice
is provided by ... Eddie Murphy? By ROBERT W. BUTLER. Story will
move in the ``e'' category.
</P>
<P>
   ANGER-CONTROL (Undated) _ Famous _ and infamous _ names are
bringing anger counseling into the spotlight. Counselors in the
1960s and '70s used to tell people to vent their anger, and that
anger created pressure that needed to be released, said David
Kupfer, a clinical psychologist in Falls Church, Va., who
specializes in anger control. Subsequent research has shown that
people who ``get it off their chest'' vociferously actually feel
worse. Constant complaining or sulking also indulges anger rather
than solves anything, Kupfer pointed out. Now anger-management
education helps people alter perceptions and change behaviors.
Often enough, counselors say, our anger stems from an overblown
interpretation of events. Or, we express justifiable anger in a way
that, over time, wrecks relationships and makes life miserable. By
EDWARD M. EVELD. Story will move in the ``l'' category.
</P>
