<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOB WITH CHAMBER OF COMMERCE IS JUST ANOTHER TURN ON MAN'S CAREER
PATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ Tom Mitchell didn't seem to fit the
profile of a liquor store owner. He appeared a bit on the young
side to be either a business owner or a booze connoisseur.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, his operation always seemed both a thriving
enterprise and a place run with imagination and entrepreneurial
verve. That, at least, was the impression of a veteran observer of
establishments catering to the thirsty set.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Mitchell was indeed a different sort of liquor
store owner. This helps explain why he's now a former liquor store
owner who's made a remarkable career path change. Mitchell recently
sold his growing booze business to join the Overland Park Chamber
of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   As the new retention and expansion manager for the chamber's
Economic Development Council, Mitchell becomes the liaison between
the business community, the chamber and City Hall. His job is to
keep the city's existing businesses happy while working to woo new
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing someone without eco-devo experience represents a
calculated gamble by Mary Birch, the chamber's president, but it
seems a good bet given Mitchell's background and track record.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who grew up in Overland Park, took his undergraduate
degree in communications at Kansas State University in '91 and went
on to get a master's degree in administration from the University
of Missouri-Kansas City in 1994. His quest for a real-life business
challenge led him to the liquor store even though he had no
experience running a business or selling booze.
</P>
<P>
   The store, Mitchell recalled over lunch the other day, seemed an
underperformer and thus a good turnaround challenge. He had no
business background, though, which meant he had no banking
relationship. Some assistance from Mitchell's family helped
overcome the financing problem initially, but as his revitalization
efforts began to pay off, he eventually was able to find the
friendly banker he needed to help grow the business.
</P>
<P>
   The learning curve was steep, Mitchell said. While he's a
typical social drinker, his knowledge of wine and spirits was
minimal. Thus, the challenge was to learn how to run a business
while learning about his wares.
</P>
<P>
   Studying his myriad product mix, enhancing the personal and
business customer base, and putting in 60 to 80 hours a week
minding the store paid off. He took the store from an annual gross
of just under $300,000 in 1994 to some $800,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Birch said she had looked over a dozen or so candidates for the
job before Mitchell came to her attention. She characterizes the
retention and expansion manager's job as a ``chemistry-type
position,'' and she knew almost immediately that Mitchell had the
chemistry it takes to click with business community members.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Birch pointed out, he's a native Overland Parker, he's
been an achiever both professionally and academically, and his
experience gives him a special practical ability to relate to the
needs of small businesses. Birch also said Mitchell's role had a
special importance because the retention and expansion effort is
the fastest-growing part of Overland Park's economic development
effort.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mitchell, he expects to work as hard as he's ever worked
in his life, if not harder, but he still figures the hours can only
get better after those years of marathon days running his own
business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
