<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLLAR FALLS AS U.S. AND JAPAN JOINTLY SUPPORT YEN
</HEADLINE>
   (See also JAPAN-ECON, DOLLAR-YEN) 
(ja) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Intervention by the Federal Reserve and Bank of Japan
Wednesday on behalf of the yen sent the U.S. dollar plunging and
caused the second consecutive sharp selloff in the Treasury market.
The strong gains in many Asian stock markets also stemmed the
flight into Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   The coordinated intervention took the steam out of the dollar's
climb and made dollar-denominated investments like U.S. government
securities less attractive to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin confirmed that the Treasury and
Fed acted in concert with the Japanese central bank, and said the
two nations ``are prepared to continue to cooperate in the exchange
markets, as appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 9/32, to 105 17/32. The bond's
yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose to 5.73 percent,
from 5.65 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Porter, senior economist for Nesbitt Burns Securities,
said, ``On a near-term basis, the dollar could test its downside
technical support, leaving the bond market vulnerable to further
pressure. But if the past two episodes of intervention are any
indication, the dollar's long-term uptrend will re-emerge and we
will see bond yields begin dropping again. The long bond yield
could move back to 5.50 percent by the end of the year and to 5
percent by the end of 1999. That is, assuming the Asian economies
will not have rebounded by then.''
</P>
<P>
   But Porter thinks that it is likely we're only just now seeing
the first phase of an economic downturn in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the Niagara Mohawk Power Corp. issued a record $3.45
billion junk bond offering through Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
Securities. The eight part deal was the largest junk bond offering
in the last 10 years, second only to a $4 billion offering by RJR
Nabisco Holdings in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Yields and spreads over Treasury securities for the Niagara
Mohawk issue ranged from 6.50 percent, or 130 basis points over a
comparable maturity, to 8.539 percent, or 300 basis points higher.
A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury plans next week to sell $23 billion of new two-year
and five-year notes. In when-issued trading the two-year note was
being offered at a price to yield 5.50 percent and the five-year
note 5.52 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
