<SLUG> BC-LEAD-OZARKS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERIOR SECRETARY TO RENEGOTIATE ISSUE OF LEAD PROSPECTING IN MARK
TWAIN NATIONAL FOREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Allowing a lead-mining company to prospect on federal
land in the Missouri Ozarks may be tantamount to allowing the
company to mine, federal attorneys have concluded. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion has led to new negotiations between federal
officials and the company that are aimed at finally ending the
15-year struggle over whether lead prospecting should be occur in
the Ozarks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt has decided to negotiate a new
agreement with Doe Run, the St. Louis company that has applied to
prospect within the Mark Twain National Forest, according to
federal documents released Tuesday by the Sierra Club. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement, the documents stated, should require Doe Run
to relinquish any future mining right that might be implied by its
prospecting permits in exchange for permission to prospect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The documents released Tuesday included an April 16 memorandum
from the Interior Department's solicitor, who has been reviewing
the secretary's legal options for months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Awarding the Doe Run Co. of St. Louis a prospecting permit
``could create an expectation, and perhaps a legal right, in the
permitee to develop minerals that might be found through
exploration,'' the solicitor's memo stated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's more, simply denying the prospecting permit might be a
risky legal move if Babbitt hasn't shown that he has at least
inquired about whether Doe Run would waive its future rights to
prospect, the memo said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Missouri environmental groups and Missouri Attorney
General Jay Nixon criticized Babbitt's decision Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They said they'll settle for nothing less than Babbitt's denial
of any prospecting in the environmentally sensitive Ozarks, just a
few miles from federally protected Ozark streams. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These streams are the jewels of the Ozarks,'' Nixon said
Tuesday. ``We won't get a second chance if these places get
spoiled.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prospecting permits should not be issued until a full
environmental assessment is conducted, Nixon said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon promised he will explore in coming days what his office's
administration and legal options might be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, meanwhile, called for a moratorium on new
mining in the sensitive Ozarks area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We will urge the secretary of the Interior and the secretary
of agriculture to formally withdraw this area from mining
activities,'' said Kathryn Hohmann, the Sierra Club's national
director of environmental quality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We will oppose any efforts to conduct any mining activities of
any type,'' Hohmann added. ``We are in this for the long haul.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hohmann and Ken Midkiff, lobbyist for the Sierra Club in
Missouri, said they met with Interior Department officials last
week in Washington. They were given a copy of the memorandum at
that meeting, Midkiff said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials for the National Park Service, which oversees the
federally protected rivers in the Ozarks, also has opposed the
prospecting permits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doe Run officials on Tuesday confirmed they are negotiating with
the Interior Department, but didn't release details of those
negotiations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not reached any conclusion with them,'' said Jeffrey
Zelms, Doe Run's president and chief operating officer. ``We do
anticipate more discussions.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company has maintained that granting it permission to
prospect would not mean it would be guaranteed a right to mine in
the Ozarks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no entitlement to mine,'' Zelms said. ``We were quite
amazed that some have maintained that we do. We didn't believe we
had such rights.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Interior officials in the solicitor's office could not be
reached for comment on Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
