<SLUG> BC-RACE-WINNER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS MAN WINS THE HISTORY CHANNEL'S 4,400-MILE GREAT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STILWELL, Kan. _ Roaring out of the steep, wooded and curving
hills outside Boston on Saturday night, Rex Gardner of Stilwell
finally had a chance to shake a monkey off his back that had been
perched there for more than a decade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come in fifth and fourth and third and second, but never
first,'' said the 59-year-old marketing manager for CarQuest. ``But
let me tell you, it's much better to win.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Gardner and navigator Gary Kuck of Lincoln,
Neb., won the championship division of the History Channel's Great
Race from Tacoma, Wash., to Haverhill, Mass. The 14-day, 44-city,
4,400-mile endurance race tested vintage-car drivers' abilities to
follow directions and solve problems on the road. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Gardner, driving an open-cockpit 1917 Hudson Indy Speedster,
this was his 12th race and his best finish. The team posted a
28-second score, which means that after more than 58 checkpoints,
rain, sleet, snow, hail and a 34-degree day, they missed a perfect
score by that margin _ 28 seconds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The margin of victory was slim: two seconds better than the No.
2 finisher in the 20-team division. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drivers are judged on how close they come to predetermined times
in stages. Checkpoints are set up along the route to keep track of
each racer, and penalty points are allotted for every second a car
is off the mark. As in golf, the lowest score wins. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come in second three times,'' Gardner said Tuesday after
driving home from Boston with the Hudson in tow. ``By the law of
averages it was bound to be my turn sooner or later.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With entry fee and other expenses, Gardner shelled out $15,000
to $16,000 to be in the race. And after all the prize money is
dished out, he'll come out with $38,000, all of which will go back
into the hobby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is that not many people get to do anything like this
in their lifetime. It's the most intense kind of motor sport that
there is,'' he said. ``I've had a chance to prove myself as we
travel across the country.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
