A4074 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-BILL-HNS &LR;      06-17 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-BILL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY, MCCARTHY INTRODUCE CHILDREN'S GUN VIOLENCE ACT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reacting to a recent spate of school shootings, two
legislators who lost family members to gun violence introduced a
bill Wednesday to hold gun owners, dealers and manufacturers
criminally and civilly responsible for children who gain access to
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Children's Gun Violence Act would impose a prison
sentence of up to six months for the gun owner if a child gets a
loaded firearm and uses it in an act of violence. The owner could
be fined up to $10,000 if the child gains access to the loaded gun
and carries it in public.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bipartisan proposal, gun dealers would have their
licenses revoked automatically if they are found to have willfully
sold a gun to a juvenile. The measure would also increase the
criminal penalties for selling a gun to a minor. In addition,
prospective gun purchasers under age 24 would be required to
present two forms of identification to the dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Within 18 months of the measure's enactment, gun makers would be
required to place child safety locks on new firearms. The
legislation would also require firearm manufacturers to comply with
a trigger-resistance standard to make it more difficult for
children to fire the guns. In addition, the new guns would have to
pass a drop test to prevent accidental discharge if they are
mishandled.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., who lost two brothers to
assassins' bullets in the 1960s, called the proposal ``the least we
can do to stop more schoolyard tragedies and deal more responsibly
with the festering crisis of gun violence involving children.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., whose husband, Dennis, was killed
and her adult son Kevin seriously injured in a Long Island, N.Y.,
commuter-train shooting in 1993, added, ``It's time for us in
Congress to come together and protect our children.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association, however, assailed the proposal
as an infringement on the rights of gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gun-control measures such as one-size-fits-all government
storage mandates, prosecution of grieving parents and waiting
periods all fail to protect children or fight crime,'' said Tanya
Metaksa, NRA's chief Capitol Hill lobbyist. ``When fatal firearms
accidents are at an all-time low and violent crime is on the
decline, it is senseless to propose ineffective laws that will only
restrict the freedoms of law-abiding citizens and the fundamental
right of self defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure's introduction follows a rash of fatal school
shootings in the past few months. One incident involved the
sniper-style shooting of four junior high school students and a
teacher in Jonesboro, Ark. Arrested in the March 24 attack were
11-year-old Andrew Golden and Mitchell Johnson, 13, who allegedly
set off a fire alarm and started shooting when the teachers and
students evacuated the building.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and McCarthy announced the introduction of their
legislation on the grounds of the Capitol, where they were joined
by Suzann Wilson, whose daughter, Brittheny Varner, was killed in
Jonesboro. Wilson said the measure is not about taking rights away
from gun owners but ``giving rights back to our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocate Sarah Brady, whose family name adorns a
federal gun-control law, organized the Capitol Hill event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can no longer accept an epidemic of gun violence,'' said
Brady, whose husband, James, served as President Ronald Reagan's
press secretary and was seriously injured in the attempted
assassination of Reagan by John Hinckley Jr. in March 1981. ``There
are no good reasons for children to have access to guns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
