A4075 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBER-FLEET-KAN &LR;      06-17 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBER-FLEET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL FINANCIAL OFFICE ISSUES REPORT ON SHORTCOMINGS OF B-2
STEALTH BOMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOB NOSTER, Mo. _ The B-2 stealth bomber fleet based in
Missouri can't yet fly as reliably or as secretly as promised,
according to a congressional report released this week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of $44.3 billion and counting, the 21 stealth bombers
still fall short of Air Force expectations in several ways,
Congress' General Accounting Office said Tuesday in its report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The radar-defying skin of the aircraft _ a key to the plane's
stealth qualities and a problem in early models of the bomber _ is
delicate and regularly needs time-consuming taping, painting and
caulking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Systems designed to let pilots know when enemy radar is about to
detect the bomber still do not work right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And the report says that too much time _ days rather than hours
_ passes between B-2 missions because of trouble in planning its
precise flight patterns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Air Force operators at Whiteman Air Force Base told us,'' the
GAO investigators wrote, ``that the (trip-planning system) had so
many failures that they estimated it would take 60 hours to plan a
conventional mission and 192 hours to plan a nuclear mission.'' The
Air Force goal is eight hours. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Whiteman Air Force Base 60 miles southeast of Kansas City,
where the stealth planes are stationed, the people who keep the
bombers flying said the report merely notes the unfinished portions
of a work-in-progress. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give us a chance to mature,'' said Col. Bill
Percival, the commander of the 509th Operations Group. ``We're
going to be able to (fly) this jet as much as we need to, to strike
our targets.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet the picture painted in the GAO report is of a bomber hobbled
by the same technology that makes it so revolutionary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fragile plane,'' said Owen R. Cote Jr., associate
director of the Security Studies Program at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These things can only fly so often.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By military standards, the B-2 is slow and lumbering. By design,
it was never meant to outrun or out-maneuver the opposition. Once
spotted by an enemy, the B-2 is presumed dead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So the problems with its various shrouds could prove critical in
its ability to sneak past another country's air defenses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The layered materials in the plane's skin have proven a constant
headache. They ``frequently fail, requiring high amounts of
maintenance....This reduces the time aircraft are available.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a theme that runs through the report. Although pilots
praise the bomber as surprisingly nimble for something as wide as a
football field, the report said work needed to get the B-2 ready
for takeoff keeps it inside its hangar too much. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hitting a large bird in flight can mean meticulous patching of
that surface. That, in turn, requires some climate control for the
paints and caulks used in the repairs. The GAO report states that
the Air Force may buy portable shelters for the B-2s when they are
stationed away from Whiteman. A series of movable hangars could
cost $15 million to $25 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charting the B-2's precise flight pattern toward a target _
important because the route plays a part in avoiding detection _ is
another trouble spot. What should take eight hours, the GAO report
said, took more than 20 times as long. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Percival said the time for planning conventional flights
already has been trimmed to 25 hours since the GAO investigation.
The Air Force said it expects to meet the eight-hour goal by late
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the B-2 relies on on-board systems to warn its pilots
that they are wandering into enemy radar range. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force spent over $740 million to develop the defensive
system for the B-2A; however, test reports concluded that the
system is unsatisfactory,'' the report stated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the Air Force has decided to cope with the system
and its limitations rather than look for more money and
perfection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It needed to provide total awareness of all electronics
surveillance everywhere,'' Percival said. ``I guess we shouldn't be
surprised if it's fallen a little short.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Col. Bill Hood, commander of the 309th Logistics Group, said a
training mission with two B-2s in Guam in March proved that the
bomber can fly reliably and often, even away from its
climate-controlled hangars in Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is I've got 10 jets here today, ready to go under
any conditions,'' Hood said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, the GAO report suggests the bomber once anticipated to be
built in greater numbers at a cost of $436 million a plane rather
$2.11 billion has significant limitations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The B-2 ended up being too expensive for us to buy in the
numbers you need for it to be effective,'' Cote said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Murphy, assistant director of National Security and
International Affairs Division of GAO, said expectations ``have
been lowered for the whole program... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Where they are today is clearly not where they want to be in
terms of turning the plane around and getting more flights.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
