<HEADLINE>
GENDER SOCIALIZATION INFLUENCES WORKPLACE SKILLS, RESEARCHER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Most everyone agrees that teamwork is an
essential workplace skill. But ask what being a ``good team
player'' means, and the answers vary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Men typically define a team player as someone who ``follows
orders'' or ``supports unquestionably.'' Women usually say a team
player ``shares information'' and ``collaborates.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pat Heim, who holds a doctorate in communication, finds those
differences when she researches gender differences in
organizations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What women see as `helpfulness' often is heard as criticism or
insubordination in the male culture,'' Heim said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heim's findings parallel those of Deborah Tannen, another
specialist in gender-related communication who, like Heim, has
written several books that detail why men and women sometimes
struggle to talk to and understand each other at work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heim has wrapped her research into a one-day seminar she calls
``He Said//She Said: Putting Gender Difference to Work,'' which she
presented recently to members of the Institute for Management
Studies in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said//she said differences are ingrained from birth, Heim
said. It's not just blue vs. pink blankets; it's the way babies are
spoken to and the way they're held. And, despite many gender-blind
efforts, socialization differences continue through childhood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those childhood experiences _ particularly the way boys and
girls play _ left a mark on those who are now adults in the
workplace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys played team sports, war, cops and robbers, cowboys and
Indians. Girls played dolls and house,'' Heim said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys learned competition, conflict, devising strategies to
win, leadership, team play, hierarchies (do what the coach says).
Girls learned relationships, alliances, conflict avoidance,
negotiation and process.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heim said she was looking forward to studying women in their 20s
who are rising in the workplace ranks. They represent the first
crop of post-Title IX girls who, like boys, grew up playing team
sports after federal law required equivalent school athletic
opportunities for boys and girls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting to see if these young women have
brought the rules of team sports to the workplace, too,'' Heim
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she and other gender-difference researchers
find frequent misunderstanding among men and women. Basically, she
said, ``work is played by the rules of team sports,'' using
language that is second-nature to men but foreign to many women. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consider Heim's examples: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the high school coach sends Mack onto the field with the
order to run 10 yards and cut right, Mack, who has been watching
the same play fail, doesn't say, ``I was thinking left would work
instead.'' Mack enters the game, runs 10 yards and cuts right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Mary joins her girlfriends to play dolls, ``What do you
want to do?'' or ``Who do you want to be?'' are common questions.
Mary learns that if she consistently tries to boss others around
she's cut out of playgroups that thrive on consensus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward 20 years into the workplace and see the various
outcomes of those two different socializations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Mack's /{male/} boss says, ``I need the report by 3
o'clock.'' Mack knows he needs more time to do a good job, but he
does the best he can and puts the report on the boss's desk by 3
p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Mack's /{female/} boss says, ``If you can squeeze it in by 3
o'clock, it would be nice to have the report then.'' At 3 p.m.,
when she goes by Mack's desk for the report, Mack looks surprised,
``You said /{if/} I could squeeze it in...'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Mary's /{male/} boss says, ``I need the report by 3
o'clock.'' Mary knows she needs more time to do a good job, so she
starts to negotiate for more time. The boss is upset that she
questions his directive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Mary's /{female/} boss says, ``If you can squeeze it in by 3
o'clock it would be nice to have the report then.'' Mary,
perceiving a collaboration, if not a level playing field, starts
discussing the pros and cons of getting it done by then. The boss
feels stressed when she devotes time to a conversation she didn't
want to have. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Heim warned, it is dangerous to generalize about an
entire sex. There are stereotype busters among both men and women.
But the way boys and girls played while growing up _ and perhaps
even genetic differences in the way male and female brains work _
create communication difficulties in the workplace, she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adult ``play'' continues to highlight the differences. Heim
suggested a comparison between shopping and hunting: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many women like to shop; they see shopping as an enjoyable
process. Many men like to hunt; they may enjoy the process, but are
more focused on reaching the end result _ the kill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The female focus on /{process/} vs. the male focus on /{goals/}
shows up often in the workplace. Women want to talk about a
problem; men just want to fix it and, if forced to talk about it,
want to cut straight to the end result, Heim said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crucial to the workplace success of both genders, she said, is
the ability to build relationships. Just like the definition of
teamwork, though, the definition of ``relationship'' varies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heim said men are more likely to offer friendliness, while women
are more apt to create friendships. There is a subtle difference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Friendliness comes and goes as needed to get something done.
Friendship is a relationship that overrides the project,'' she
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She attributes the difference, once again, to childhood
socializations. Men who are now in the workplace grew up playing on
teams with boys they didn't necessarily like. They learned to pull
together as a team anyway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women in the workplace today grew up with more control over who
their playmates were, Heim said. Liking someone was crucial to
building a relationship. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Heim contended, a man on a workplace team is better able
to ignore ``the slimeball on the team'' and focus on the goal,
while the woman is more likely to be distressed by the slimeball's
presence on her team and fret that she can't establish the
relationship she would like to do the job well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Heim said, men are socialized to accept, if not
enjoy, conflict. They're more likely to shrug off a loss ``when the
game's over,'' while women will carry the loss with them, mourning
damaged interpersonal relationships and dwelling on what they did
wrong. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Curing the communication gap in the workplace requires
understanding how and why each gender talks the way it does, Heim
said. It also requires both genders to adapt a bit, both in how
they talk and in how they hear what the other says. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
