<SLUG> BC-TEEN-MICROSOFT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
16-YEAR-OLD TAKES TIME OUT FROM HIS COMPUTER BUSINESS TO PROMOTE
MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ David Longnecker wasn't even born when a
younger Bill Gates was tapping out the first lines of code for what
later would become the Microsoft Windows operating system for
personal computers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, it's not surprising that the now-goliath software
company run by Gates tagged the aggressive 16-year-old owner of a
Wichita computer company to hawk Microsoft's newest product,
Windows 98. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. will ship Windows 98, an update to the Windows
95 operating system, for sale June 25. Longnecker, who will be a
high school junior this year, is on a three-city publicity tour to
spread the word. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Longnecker was at a Microsoft seminar in May when he met one of
the company's senior systems engineers. He told her about Magic
Technologies, his 2-year-old computer company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``She really thought what I was doing was neat,'' Longnecker
said. Then last week, ``she called up and asked, `Would you do this
little whirlwind tour? You have an hour to decide.' &UR; '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He took the job, but he won't be getting rich. It's an unpaid
gig. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets me out of the house, and it gets my name out there,''
Longnecker said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tour started in St. Louis on Monday, passed through Kansas
City on Tuesday and ended in Nashville, Tenn., on Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They left everything up to me,'' Longnecker said. ``I only
talked to a Microsoft representative once. When I got to St. Louis,
they handed me the (portable) computer and said, `Have fun.' &UR; '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far, fun has meant getting up at 3 or 4 a.m. for early
television interviews followed by more media interviews throughout
the day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Longnecker has been testing early versions of the Microsoft
software for about two years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with it,'' he said. ``Everything I wanted changed
was changed.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the software has been criticized by some industry
analysts as containing relatively minor improvements over the
Windows 95 system, Longnecker said the software is worth the $89
Microsoft will charge for it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more changes than a lot of people can see,'' he
said. ``If I didn't already have it, I'd go out and get it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Computers seem to come naturally to Longnecker. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was big into Nintendo when I was a kid,'' he said. ``I got
my first computer when I was 12. It kind of grew from there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long before natural curiosity took over. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got my computer, I took it apart,'' Longnecker
said. ``What upset my parents was when I took apart the TV.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He managed to rebuild both the computer and television. In 1996,
at age 14, an employee in the Wichita company where his uncle
worked offered to pay Longnecker to build a computer for his
family. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Magic Technologies officially was born in June 1996. Longnecker
is still the company's only employee but has 60 customers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Day-to-day operations are like any small business, Longnecker
said. He handles sales, manufacturing and bookkeeping, all based on
tips he got from employees at his uncle's business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Longnecker said his company netted between $4,000 and $5,000
last year. ``I make more than the average 16-year-old does at
McDonald's,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his other life as high school student, Longnecker said he has
maintained an A average. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His goals? A computer information systems degree from Friends
University in Wichita and a job with Microsoft. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later, they have to hire me,'' Longnecker said.
``I'm doing all this stuff for them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
