</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GIULIANI'S RISING GRANDIOSITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The mayor will probably go one for two. A new stadium
for the Yankees on the West Side of Manhattan will never happen.
But Rudolph Giuliani will probably get his skybox bunker, the
overpriced emergency command center on the 23rd floor of a World
Trade Center building.
</P>
<P>
   A bulletproof bunker in the clouds over Manhattan perfectly
suits the remote, authoritarian, condescending and defensive
personality of Giuliani. Isolated and protected behind a
shatterproof shield, he'll be able to look down at the magnificent
city that he may or may not love, but clearly loves to rule.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mayor's denials, the plans for the bunker were
carried out in secret. New Yorkers found out about it through The
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   So, without benefit of an honest discussion of its merits, the
city is about to make a huge, long-term investment in a high-tech
facility that's in a building it doesn't even control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I question why we would want to make such tremendous
improvements on somebody else's property,'' said Councilwoman
Kathryn Freed, in whose district the command center will be
located. ``The annual rental is a million-four, which impresses me
as being huge. But it's only a 20-year lease. What if they don't
renew the lease?''
</P>
<P>
   A similar command center in Los Angeles is in a sub-basement of
City Hall, four floors below ground level. That type of facility is
far more secure than the 23rd floor of a high-rise, and there is no
landlord to contend with. The annual expenses in Los Angeles are
about $1 million to $1.5 million for maintenance, software
upgrades, equipment improvements and the like. In New York those
kinds of expenses would be in addition to the annual rent of $1.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   The real price of the bunker is not $15 million, as the budget
line would suggest, but more like $70 million over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the many self-aggrandizing features of the bunker is a
teleconferencing system that would allow the mayor to communicate
face-to-face with the president of the United States. Don't count
on that happening. You don't just ring up the president, even in an
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Cutler, the deputy assistant to the president for
intergovernmental affairs, said: ``Any mayor in America can find
any of us through the White House switchboard if anything happens.
There's immediate access.'' But she added: ``It would be hard for
me to make the case for face-to-face communication being necessary.
We have a million issues that happen in communities all over the
country every day.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many potential problems with Giuliani's command
center. When a property is city-owned, the mayor and other
officials can easily control access in emergencies, sharply
limiting those who are authorized to go in and out. That is not the
case in an office building filled with other paying tenants.
</P>
<P>
   And elevators in a high-rise are always a potential problem in
an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Because the bunker was cleverly and successfully concealed as it
made its way through the budget process, the potential problems,
large and small, were not adequately examined. The full range of
possible alternatives was never explored.
</P>
<P>
   That is the way of this mayor. He does not believe in running a
free and open government. He believes he is the government,
answerable to no one. Questions are out of the question. Ask this
mayor what time it is, and he'll tell you to file a freedom of
information request. If a judge grants the request, Giuliani will
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But he cannot silence all of the voices that are being raised in
opposition. Kathryn Freed will continue to point out that while he
is building his bunker and fighting for a West Side stadium, ``The
mayor cut libraries, he cut senior citizens' programs, he cut
after-school programs, he cut parks.''
</P>
<P>
   And Peter Vallone, the mild-mannered speaker of the Council who
has become the target of ferocious attacks by the mayor, will
continue to assert: ``This mayor not only uses his bully pulpit, he
uses his power to bully people. You can only push people around so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic government is a collaborative effort, and while it
may not work efficiently it generally works well. The mayor hopes
to be president someday, but that's unlikely. His instincts are
working against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
