<HEADER>
A4123 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-TAXCODE-BOS &LR;      06-17 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-TAX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO DROP FEDERAL TAX CODE 
</HEADLINE>
 CODE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted Wednesday to eliminate the entire
tax code by the end of 2002, in an election-year gesture meant to
appeal to conservative voters.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, approved by a vote of 219-209, would wipe out the
existing tax code, except Social Security payroll taxes, by Dec.
31, 2002 _ as long as Congress enacts a replacement system by July
4, 2002. The measure provides no alternative tax system, and the
Republican majority is sharply divided between a flat tax and
national sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty Republicans voted against the bill, including the two
from Connecticut, Representatives Christopher Shays and Nancy
Johnson, while 15 Democrats supported the measure. All 10
Massachusetts Democrats opposed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an amateurs' bill,'' said Representative Fortney
``Pete'' Stark, a California Democrat. He called the bill
``foolishness,'' and said the GOP leaders were being ``led around
by the nose.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure caused an unusual split among the GOP's business
constituency. The National Federation of Independent Business
favors repealing the IRS code, but the Chamber of Commerce remained
neutral and business leaders have said the uncertainty created by
eliminating the tax code could wreak havoc with financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, speaking to reporters, strongly opposed the
measure. ``If you voted to get rid of it without saying what the
replacement was, you would put individual Americans and families in
an uncertain position about their investments and health
insurance,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He also referred to the current economic crisis in Asia and
said, ``The last thing in the world we need to do right now is to
send some signal of instability, that we decided to get rid of our
whole tax code without knowing what the replacement would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Steve Largent, an Oklahoma Republican and chief
sponsor of the bill, conceded that the measure probably would not
pass in the Senate. But he said the vote would begin a national
debate on the issue that would be resolved by the 2000 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take more than a majority'' of Congress ``to pass
this,'' said Largent. ``This is lighting a fire under everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The closeness of the vote, however, surprised House leaders who
had made the bill a high priority. After the roll call and an
unscheduled recess, House leaders announced they had dropped a
previously scheduled vote on a new rule for debating the campaign
finance bill. The new rule would have allowed nearly 300 unrelated
amendments to be added to the campaign bill, a strategy Democrats
called ``death by amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   During debate on the tax bill, supporters argued that Congress
needed to change a system that has become complicated and
burdensome to average taxpayers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents said abolishing the existing code with nothing in
its place threatened the stability of the government and the real
estate and construction industries. The existing code provides for
collecting money that funds all government functions, plus it
allows homeowners a mortgage deduction and allows municipalities
and states to float bonds for construction projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4124 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX     06-17 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP STARS INCREASINGLY EARN MONEY FOR NOTHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't listen to Mariah Carey's music that much, don't think
about her a whole lot, don't much care which ballplayer she's
dating.
</P>
<P>
   But when she gave only two days' notice that she would NOT sing
at the recent KISS Party '98 at Starplex, well, that bothered me.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that I had a ticket and had been waiting with bated
breath for la Carey's ``first appearance ever in Texas'' (as we
were repeatedly told.) It wasn't that I didn't understand that this
was a free show and that, now as always, you get what you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, Carey's inability to do at least a short set got my goat
because it was the final proof I needed that pop stars aren't very
good at being pop stars anymore.
</P>
<P>
   There used to be certain basic rules about performing in front
of people. One was that if you say you're going to appear at a
concert, hey, you actually sing something; and no, Mariah, a brief
a cappella version of ``My All'' doesn't count.
</P>
<P>
   Carey's glaring lack of class and common sense, however, is just
the latest in a long series of examples of the larger problem.
</P>
<P>
   A generalization? Yes. But the evidence is pretty irrefutable.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Carey do only one song at the KISS show, but so did
Olivia Newton-John, who has a new CD out and is once again trying
to sell herself as a country singer. You'd think she'd at least
have favored the crowd with one tune from the new CD. But, no.
Guess it's just not important enough to her.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the whole Ginger Spice debacle. Here she is, an
extremely wealthy woman who made her fortune as part of a group
that sold itself as an all-for-one-and-one-for-all unit. And she
backs out of a major U.S. tour (and leaves the group altogether)
just days before the first U.S. show _ and after tickets had been
sold in just about every market.
</P>
<P>
   So much, I guess, for the maxim ``the show must go on'' and
honoring one's commitments, pleasant or not. So much, too, for
really caring about all those little girls supposedly being taught
the value of ``girl power.''
</P>
<P>
   In times gone by, Ginger would have toughed it out until the
tour was over. I think the Spice Girls should go ahead with the
tour and give everyone who shows up a rebate good for one-fifth the
face value of the ticket; seems only fair.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the inability of some musicians to say anything
while onstage. Plenty still do, but a distressing number of
performers don't feel they even owe the fans a ``good evening'' or
a ``hello,'' much less something as simple as introducing the next
song.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't think this is so hard, but it was for Cornershop's
Tjinder Singh, Spiritualized's Jason Pierce and ALL the members of
Dead Can Dance, all of whom said virtually nothing in between songs
at recent shows. Come on, people. You've traveled all the way from
Europe, you're playing before thousands of adoring fans, and you
can't say, ``Thank you''?
</P>
<P>
   But at least those bands tour. So many don't, forgetting that
even in the age of video, the road still breaks bands and
solidifies fan bases. It broke Oasis, it broke Everclear, it broke
Metallica and Dave Matthews and Phish and Sheryl Crow and Jewel and
Paula Cole.
</P>
<P>
   Pulp and Primal Scream, just to name two, have made
good-to-great CDs in the past eight months, and neither has sold
worth a darn, in large part because they either did brief U.S.
tours, or none at all. If you want to stay home and watch soccer
and take it easy, fine; just don't expect to sell in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   If Eric Clapton or bands such as Aerosmith, Metallica and U2 can
still, even with all their wealth, support a CD with several months
of roadwork, so can everyone else. To say nothing of the punishing
schedules still maintained by guys such as B.B. King.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as recently as 15 years ago this sort of stuff was
just common sense. If you really wanted to be a successful
musician, you climbed in a van or a bus and paid your dues. And you
acted happy to be there, because you were one of the fortunate few,
the 1 percent or so of all musicians to make it out of the local
bar-band grind.
</P>
<P>
   For some time now, all that's been reversed; we're supposed to
act as though any appearance by any pop musician is as good as a
vision of the Virgin Mary. It's not; it's just people with some
level of talent playing music. And often, at the level of a Carey
or a Spice Girl, being more than amply rewarded for their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   They're the lucky ones. Not us.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
