<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4129 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-ELTON-BOS &LR;      06-17 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-ELTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELTON PLANS LOW-KEY WELCOME FOR WOODWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PEGGY HERNANDEZ   AND DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELTON, England _ This village promises a low-key homecoming for
native daughter Louise Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Elton say they are embarrassed at the celebratory
image they gave the world months ago when Woodward's conviction was
reduced to manslaughter. Photographs then showed supporters pouring
champagne and singing soccer victory songs.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Brendan Durkan, an Elton elected official and 25-year
resident, said, ``It'll be a homecoming. It won't be a celebration.
A baby is dead. A young girl has been convicted of his
manslaughter, and has to live with that for the rest of her life. I
feel sad for all those involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Elton residents said they have become disillusioned with
Woodward in the wake of developments in the case in the past month,
including accusations that the Woodwards misused money in their
defense fund, and the firing of one Woodward's lawayers, who
allegedly told a Massachusetts state trooper when she was arrested
for drunken driving that she had come to believe Woodward is
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at first a lot of people were behind her because she
is from England, and there was a strong England vs. America
sentiment with this story,'' said Sheena Dunne, 36, a legal
secretary from Cheshire, as she left work Wednesday in downtown
Manchester. ``But after some of these other issues came to light,
it was hard to know what to believe. I don't think she meant to
kill the baby, but she is still guilty, and it has all been rather
bizarre lately.''
</P>
<P>
   This week for the first time, habitually pro-Woodward newspapers
became uncharacteristically restrained, cautioning against making
Woodward a heroine. Wednesday``The death of a child is immensely
sad, and not a matter of popping champagne corks,'' The Daily
Telegraph wrote Wednesday. Several news organizations urged her not
to try to sell her story.
</P>
<P>
   Still, The Rigger Pub promises to be crowded with residents and
reporters. Yellow ribbon is tied to every available post and tree;
police have blocked off the street leading to the Woodwards' home;
and the display window of the local bakery features cream-filled
sponge cakes topped with photos of Woodward and the words,
``Welcome Home, Louise.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward and her father, Gary, are scheduled to arrive in London
early this morning. They will then fly to Manchester Airport, where
the Woodward family will meet with the media at approximately 8
a.m. local time. The family is then expected to travel about 40
miles west to Elton, arriving at about 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward has not been home since the saga began in the first
week of February 1997, when 8-month-old Matthew Eappen lapsed into
a coma and later died.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Woodward's mother, Susan, remained secluded in the
family home, while a lawyer released a statement to quash rumors
that the former au pair had sold her story to a British tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to speculation, (Woodward) will not be going into
hiding at the behest of any national newspaper or media
organization,'' said Paul Barrow, the legal adviser to the Louise
Woodward and Family Trust.
</P>
<P>
   The trust, used to pay Woodward's legal expenses, continues to
receive donations. Wednesday, during a regular meeting of Woodward
supporters at the Elton Community Center, volunteers opened several
handfuls of mail, yielding about $1,600 in checks. Woodward friends
said the trust fund _ which once totalled $450,000 _ is now down to
about $50,000 and will be used to pay for the legal battles to
appeal Woodward's conviction or fight the civil suit filed by the
Eappen family.
</P>
<P>
   It was from this trust that Sue Woodward allegedly skimmed
$15,400 using a forged invoice.
</P>
<P>
   Many here say Woodward, who has said that she wants to go to
college, may have a hard time finding work. They argue that selling
her story may be the only way she can make a living. Others say it
would seriously damage her credibility, even among her supporters
here, to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, even some close family friends were less than
jubilant as they awaited her homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're relieved Louise is coming home, but this is no place for
rejoicing,'' said Steve Collins, who took in Woodward's sister,
Vickie, 19, when her parents were in the United States for the
trial. ``Louise could have come home from America the same way she
went over: free. That hasn't happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
