<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICHARDSON-HOLBROOKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE TO REPLACE RICHARDSON AT THE U.N., OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Story also moved in ``i'' news file.) 
(th) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has decided to name Richard
Holbrooke as the U.S. representative to the United Nations,
replacing Bill Richardson, who will become energy secretary, senior
administration officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will announce the appointments Thursday at a White House
ceremony, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who has decades of foreign policy experience, was the
architect of the Dayton accords that brought a fragile peace to
Bosnia. He is now vice chairman of Credit Suisse First Boston, the
investment bank, and often serves as a special presidential envoy.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is known to have been a strong supporter
of Holbrooke for the U.N. job, which carries Cabinet rank, while
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright initially opposed the
appointment. Sandy Berger, President Clinton's national security
adviser, held his fire, seeing the appointment as inevitable,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright helped to block Holbrooke's appointment to the post at
the beginning of Clinton's second term, but was unable to do so
this time. Albright and Holbrooke were originally rivals for the
job of secretary of state, and when she was picked, she was
reported to have felt that Holbrooke would be too disruptive to a
new team.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke speaks freely with reporters and sometimes tries to
move policy in independent ways. The most recent example came in
May in the Balkans, when Holbrooke secured an agreement from
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to talk to ethnic Albanian
leaders in Kosovo by suspending the implementation of sanctions
that Albright had pressed European allies to approve.
</P>
<P>
   That initiative is now widely regarded as a mistake, since
Milosevic used the suspension to begin a crackdown in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   One official, speaking on condition that he not be named,
described Holbrooke as regularly seeking the spotlight and taking
it away from others. He wondered if Clinton's foreign policy team
would be able to keep the image of unity they had worked so hard to
maintain in the second term.
</P>
<P>
   In his second term, Clinton has been more likely to heed his
vice president's advice on personnel matters. Gore and Holbrooke
originally grew close during Gore's failed presidential candidacy
in 1988. But Clinton and Holbrooke are also said to have
established a good relationship.
</P>
<P>
   It was Albright, as representative to the United Nations in
Clinton's first term, who insisted that the job carry Cabinet rank
and that she participate as a full member of the senior foreign
policy team in the so-called ``Principal's Committee.'' She used
the job to build her own reputation for plain-speaking and
telegenic foreign policy sound bites, which helped her become
secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   In public, the two praise each other highly, and Holbrooke, in
his recent book about his efforts to bring peace to the Balkans,
``To End a War,'' hailed Albright for her own strong views about
the need to exercise force on behalf of diplomacy and moral values.
And Albright has chosen other strong figures, like Thomas
Pickering, undersecretary for political affairs, to work with.
</P>
<P>
   Berger had also opposed the appointment of Holbrooke to the
United Nations at the beginning of Clinton's second term, but did
not raise serious objections to the appointment this time around,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, who is vital to managing the policy differences among
key Cabinet members and maintaining outward unanimity, is said to
regard the new appointment ``as a management exercise,'' an
official said.
</P>
<P>
   But the official acknowledged that the administration is facing
numerous foreign policy challenges, from nuclear proliferation to
economic crises in Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who did not return telephone calls Wednesday, has
told friends that he was stung by criticism that he is not a team
player. He is expected to work hard at dispelling such concerns,
officials said Wednesday. And Holbrooke was praised for his
assiduity, during Bosnia shuttle diplomacy missions, for instance,
at keeping others in the administration aware of what he is up to.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, 57, has been in and out of government since he first
joined the foreign service in 1962 and spent a first tour in
Vietnam. He is best known for his work in Bosnia, when he served as
assistant secretary of state for European affairs. But he also
brings experience in Asia, and also served as assistant secretary
of state for East Asian and Pacific affairs from 1977-81.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke left Washington in 1996 to move to New York and became
vice chairman of Credit Suisse First Boston. He also serves on the
board of Refugees International, a nonprofit organization that
draws attention to the plight of refugees, most recently in Kosovo,
the southern province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson will replace Federico Pena, one of Clinton's
longest-serving Cabinet officers, who announced in April that he
would step down. Pena, a former transportation secretary and mayor
of Denver, said this month that he wants to return to the private
sector, but has not announced specific plans.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was elected to the House of Representatives in 1982
and was re-elected seven times. While still in the House,
Richardson served as a roving diplomatic trouble-shooter for
Clinton, traveling to North Korea, Cuba, Iraq, Nigeria, Afghanistan
and Burma.
</P>
<P>
   While he was loved at the United Nations for his generosity,
bonhomie and political skill, and in particular for his affinity to
the representatives of the developing world, he was sometimes
criticized internally for being lax on policy and for not
commanding respect on the Security Council.
</P>
