A4143 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-17 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ALL AROUND THE TOWN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   T &UR; om Sweeney &LR; , doorman at San Francisco's Sir Francis Drake, saw
a panhandler reading a copy of Golf Digest, apparently trying to
learn who's who at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   _ In keeping with this weekend's Gay, Lesbian, Bi and Trans
Pride celebration _ the name is almost as long as the parade _ New
Mexico artist  &UR; Fred Stern &LR;  will attempt to create two mega-rainbows
over San Francisco. Stern, an internationally recognized artist who
uses fire hoses to make artificial rainbows as long as 2,000 feet,
sees rainbows as a symbol of international unity.
</P>
<P>
   His first local effort will be at 8 a.m. Sunday, with water
sprayed from a San Francisco Fire Department boat near the Bay
Bridge. It will be visible from Treasure Island over San Francisco.
At 6 p.m., a San Francisco fire truck at Market and Hyde will be
used to create a rainbow downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The artist will spend a few days beforehand choosing exact
locations by studying the bay, the streets and the angle of the
sun. The Fire Department is pitching in; Stern's hoping that the
weather does, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ That double-decker Gray Line bus has been missing because _
after 20 years at her station, the corner of Geary and Powell _
she's getting a face-lift. Gray Line's &UR; Darlene Cochran &LR;  says the
$20,000 sprucing-up, including new flooring and a new paint job
inside and out, will take about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Joe Palsa  &LR; was impressed to learn this week that researchers
at the  &UR; Ernest Gallo  &LR; Clinic and Research Center at University of
California at San Francisco have discovered a gene, as reported in
the journal Cell, that makes it easier for fruitflies to get drunk.
Their nickname for this gene is ``cheapdate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Matt Buka &LR;  suggests some cuts for the remaining Beatles'
animal-rights album: ``A Hard Day's Newt,'' ``Eleanor Pigby,''
``The Long and Winding Toad,'' ``Let It Bee,'' ``I Wanna Hold Your
Lamb'' and ``Yelp!''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Andrew Hoffman &LR; ,  &UR; Abbie Hoffman &LR; 's son by his first wife,
 &UR; Sheila &LR; , is throwing a pre-Father's Day party at the Webster Hall
discotheque in New York on Saturday to publicize his availability
to act or consult on two forthcoming movies about his dad. Hoffman,
37, who runs a soup kitchen in Boston, wants to protest the
influence of Hoffman's second wife,  &UR; Anita &LR; , in both projects. One
stars  &UR; Vincent D'Onofrio &LR;  as Hoffman; the other stars  &UR; Ben &LR; 
 &UR; Stiller &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tori Spelling &LR; , actress and daughter of TV producer  &UR; Aaron &LR; ,
told the teen magazine Jump about the time she was a rebel. ``I
went in and told my father that I wanted to be on his show
`Charlie's Angels' as  &UR; Farrah Fawcett &LR; 's little sister. My father
was like, `No way are you going to be in a show with low-cut
dresses.' He said, `You can be on another show.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE JOYS AND THE SORROW OF THE COCKETTES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers  &UR; David Weissman &LR;  and  &UR; Bill Weber &LR;  are just back from
New York, where they were researching their forthcoming documentary
on the Cockettes, the San Francisco troupe that brought a joyous
form of gay and cross-dressing entertainment to local stages in the
early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   The Cockettes, first the toast of the gay community, then the
toast of the whole town, were particularly beloved by local society
figures and seemed destined for bigger things when they headed east
to take their revue to New York. `` &UR; Marlene Dietrich &LR;  places her
limousine and chauffeur at their disposal,'' wrote
 &UR; Sally Quinn  &LR; in the Washington Post, and ``artist  &UR; Robert &LR; 
 &UR; Rauschenberg &LR;  gave them $1,000 to keep them afloat.''  &UR; David &LR; 
 &UR; Rockefeller  &LR; booked tickets for himself and 11 friends. Columnist
 &UR; Rex Reed  &LR; was rhapsodic.
</P>
<P>
   But on opening night, the Cockettes bombed. ``What had been
`gay, light and campy' in San Francisco became boring, tedious,
tasteless, stupid and amateurish in New York, and the audience
began walking out in droves,'' wrote Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   A San Francisco Chronicle story upon the troupe's return home
called its foray ``a bummer.'' Nonetheless, filmmakers Weissman and
Weber claim the Cockettes' ``unique burst of cultural
experimentation ... continues to influence the worlds of theater,
fashion, music, gay politics and spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you that Michael Jackson is unbelievable, isn't he?
He's just unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Vice President Al Gore discussing the Chicago Bulls at a
function in Washington, quoted in the Chicago Tribune, which, on
behalf of Michael Jordan, apparently took it personally.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the restaurant that's named after me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown at opening festivities for
the Black Cat on Broadway.
</P>
