<HEADER>
A4147 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIDE-MAN-THEATER-$ADV     06-17 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIDE-MAN-THEATER-$ADV21-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIFFING ON THE PAST, WITH SURPRISING RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN DRUKMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After toiling for 20 years not exactly anonymously
but far from the bright lights of fame as a freelance journalist,
stand-up comic, playwright, screenwriter and movie director, nobody
is more surprised to see ``Side Man,'' a memory play about jazz
performers, land on Broadway than its author, Warren Leight, 41.
</P>
<P>
   In jazz parlance, sideman refers to a musician who works for
hire on band jobs, who knows the standards by heart and who can
solo dazzlingly but also blend in with an orchestra's sound.
</P>
<P>
   The memories are based on Leight's father, Donald Leight, now
75, a trumpet player who worked with Claude Thornhill, Woody Herman
and other bandleaders through the 1950s. As the author's script
shows, sidemen, who sometimes sabotaged their careers with drugs
and alcohol, gradually became marginalized with the advent of rock
`n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   But the main focus of the play is Leight's own childhood, he
said recently over pastry in a Greenwich Village shop near his
home. Clifford, the author's stand-in (played by Robert Sella),
revisits his past, resuming the peacekeeper role he was forced to
adopt in his parents' crumbling marriage. Ranging between 1953 and
1985, Leight mixes memories of his bitter, often hysterical mother
(Wendy Makkena) and diffident, ineffectual father (Frank Wood) with
a joke-filled celebration of the journeymen musicians he knew as a
child on the Upper West Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my father's friends could remember the horn section from
an obscure gig by such-and-such orchestra,'' Leight said, ``but
would walk right by their own children on the sidewalk and not
recognize them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Side Man,'' directed by Michael Mayer, opens on Thursday at
Stage Right at the Roundabout Theater Company, which is
co-producing it with the Weissberger Theater Group and Peter
Manning. The cast includes Kevin Geer, Michael Mastro, Joseph Lyle
Taylor and Angelica Torn.
</P>
<P>
   In March, when ``Side Man'' had a short run at the CSC theater
Off Broadway, also directed by Mayer, it received excellent
reviews. Shortly after, the screenwriter William Goldman was quoted
in an interview in The New York Times as saying, ``The best play
I've seen in years is Warren Leight's `Side Man.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Leight, who has the genial, sometimes abstracted air of a
professional graduate student, has been cautious. ``So many people
have said to me, `This is the next big thing' about my other
projects _ which usually leads to unemployment and unreturned
calls,'' he said with a rueful grin.
</P>
<P>
   For Leight, his play is also autobiographical because: ``I still
see myself as a sideman in many ways. Coming from a jazz family, I
always felt like I should earn a living. So for the last 20 years
I've been a writer-for-hire, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   This may be why ``Side Man'' seems so charitable in its
rendering of Gene, the title character. Peter Marks wrote in his
review in The New York Times that ``when it's over, you look for
heroes and villains, and discover only people.''
</P>
<P>
   Leight's father, who lives west of the theater district in the
Clinton section of Manhattan, recalled an era: ``Sidemen only got
attention inside the industry. In the '30s, the sidemen were also
`names' _ Gene Krupa, for example, was Benny Goodman's sideman _
but 15 years later, sidemen like that were unknown. Like theater
and film, but more so in music, the leaders and headliners get all
the public acclaim, and no one pays attention to who does the dirty
work. Even in the Philharmonic, people are attracted to name
conductors. But how many people can name four or five musicians in
the orchestra?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Side Man'' began as a staged reading in February 1996 in the
basement of the West Bank Cafe on Theater Row. Leight, a member of
the theater group Naked Angels, had had the play sent to Mayer, who
liked it immediately. ``The world he depicts is so truthful, so
idiosyncratic, it completely charmed me,'' Mayer said. After the
reading he directed it next during development at the New York
Stage and Film Company's annual summer season at Vassar College in
Poughkeepsie, N.Y., where Manning produced it.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer, a recent Tony Award nominee for his direction of ``A View
From the Bridge,'' a Roundabout revival that transferred to
Broadway, said: ``What attracted me to Warren's specific biography
was how universal it is. It's not just a `jazz play' or a
`biographical play.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The response from audiences has been, `That's my story.' And I
ask, `Oh, your father was a jazz musician?' And they say, `No, he
was an accountant, but it's still my story.''
</P>
<P>
   Leight jokes about his difficult childhood. ``I was a poor,
scrawny kid from the Upper West Side _ very 10025,'' he said,
referring to the zip code of his youth. ``At least the 10024 kids
had summer camp. I got drop-kicked to Stanford on a scholarship,
but was out of place in Palo Alto with these Olympic team water
polo players.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1977, he returned to New York, sold an
article on ``something like `Where to Find a Public Bathroom in New
York''' to The Village Voice, and became a career writer. The
articles eventually formed the 1983 collection, ``The I Hate New
York Guidebook'' _ ``my first succes d'estime,'' Leight said,
``that's French for `still living in a walkup.'''
</P>
<P>
   His career has included a stint as the His columnist for
Mademoiselle magazine while also writing for National Lampoon,
providing cabaret material for a revue quartet, the High-Heeled
Women, and performing his own stand-up routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a year that was my 90-job year,'' he said. ``At one
point, I was ghostwriting for a guy who suddenly died. His widow
said, `Hurry up, the publishers will get suspicious if the last
installment takes too long.'''
</P>
<P>
   His ``I Hate New York Guidebook'' was the basis, along with
Mayor Ed Koch's memoir, of the 1985 musical ``Mayor.'' ``It was a
hit at the now-defunct Village Gate,'' Leight remembered, ``and
everyone said I wouldn't have to worry about work again _ which
led, after its closing, to a long jobless streak, of course.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he has found sporadic success in Hollywood, but
has always remained a New Yorker. ``I was looking for an apartment
in Manhattan, and I'd see something I liked. Then I'd hear the rent
and think: `Yeah, I can afford that _ two days a week.'''
</P>
<P>
   The experience prompted the screenplay for the 1993 film ``The
Night We Never Met'' (which he also directed), a story of three
people splitting the rent on an apartment but residing in it on
alternate days, starring Matthew Broderick and Annabella Sciorra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, this one was going to be my big break,'' Leight said.
``But it came out two weeks before `Jurassic Park,' so it became
this lovely sand castle that this enormous tsunami washed away.''
</P>
<P>
   After writing horror films and documentaries, Leight wrote a
screenplay for what would become the movie ``Dear God,'' starring
Greg Kinnear, in 1996. ``This was such a humiliating disaster,'' he
said. ``After six or seven drafts, it was taken from me. Suddenly,
there were 60 speaking parts, a dog in a courtroom scene. I sat in
a screening and thought, `Time to write a play where I make no
compromises.'''
</P>
<P>
   The result was ``Side Man.'' ``Film is good money,'' Leight
said, ``but there's a reason: They pay you to go away. `Side Man'
is filled with my voice because it's my story.''
</P>
<P>
   The author's father saw the play at Vassar. ``I didn't want him
to,'' the younger Leight said, ``but an old musician friend told
him, `Hey, your son wrote a play about you. It's in Poughkeepsie.'
My father told me he was up all night afterward. I assumed it was
the not-so-flattering portrayal, and then he said, `Yeah, I
couldn't figure out who was playing trumpet on ``I Remember
Clifford'' in that scene.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
