<SLUG> BC-IRAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRANIAN DIPLOMAT CRITICIZES `HOSTILE' POLICY OF U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IRAN-ALBRIGHT.) 
(bl) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Iran's most senior diplomat at the United Nations
came to Washington on Wednesday and accused the Clinton
administration of continuing a ``hostile'' policy toward Iran. He
also defended his country's rejection of Washington's offer for an
official dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech sponsored by Middle East Insight, a magazine,
Mohammad Hadi Nejad Hosseinian, Iran's chief representative at the
United Nations, called the United States ``not in tune with the
rest of the world'' for its pursuit of a policy aimed at isolating
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Nejad Hosseinian needed permission from the State Department to
travel outside the New York area for his first trip to Washington
in his new job, and his remarks reflected both a reticence to make
a positive gesture given the tense domestic political situation in
Iran and a desire to reach out to his American audience.
</P>
<P>
   Iran has moved very cautiously on the initiative announced by
President Mohammed Khatami last January for broad cultural
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Iranian journalists and editors were tentatively
scheduled to visit the United States for an interview with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright this month. But they were
forced to cancel their trip apparently because of complaints by
Iranian officials opposed to Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Nejad Hosseinian did not repeat Iran's
longstanding call for U.S. military forces to withdraw from the
Persian Gulf or to unfreeze Iranian assets held in the United
States. He even appeared to approve of American culture, saying,
``Iranians have very good camaraderie with American and Western
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the U.N. envoy also praised the administration for
waiving congressionally-mandated sanctions against foreign
companies that invest heavily in Iran's oil and gas sector, he
complained that the beneficial effect was neutralized by the
administration's continuing opposition to using Iran as the
pipeline route for Caspian Sea oil.
</P>
<P>
   As for Washington's offer to begin a government-to-government
dialogue, Nejad Hosseinian said that there was more continuity than
change in America's attitude, ``so we don't think that this
situation, the government-to-government negotiation, is possible
and useful. It's not.''
</P>
<P>
   With four State Department officials present in the audience,
Nejad Hosseinian also faulted the United States for labeling Iran
an official supporter of terrorism, for financing a radio station
that will beam anti-government propaganda into Iran and for what he
said was its failure to recognize Iran's effort to curb drug
trafficking in the region. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
