<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4152 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARK-MORRIS-DANCE-$AD     06-17 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARK-MORRIS-DANCE-$ADV21-945(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL ON HIS FEET FOR A LAST DANCE AND NEW CREATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
(lb) 
 Robert Greskovic is the author of ``Ballet 101: A Guide to Learning
and Loving the Ballet.''  
 By ROBERT GRESKOVIC   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mark Morris Dance Group was just 8 years old and
performing for the first time at the Brooklyn Academy of Music's
Opera House when the company's general manager, Barry Alterman,
spoke about his vision for Morris in New York: ``I want each of
Mark's appearances in town to be an event.''
</P>
<P>
   In the dozen years since Alterman made that remark in the
opera-house lobby, his wish has been granted repeatedly. Wherever
Morris has taken his iconoclastic choreography in New York, the
occasion has been received as something more than just ``the next
season.''
</P>
<P>
   There were, for instance, ``The Hard Nut,'' Morris' alternative
``Nutcracker'' with its pop 1970s design and comic-book wit, and a
concentration of dances to the music of Lou Harrison, centered on
the expansive, specially commissioned ``Rhymes With Silver.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Morris restricts his eventful
programming to New York. Just before his forthcoming local
appearances, the choreographer and director returned from
California where his company had presented to overwhelming critical
and public acclaim his 1997 staging of Jean-Philippe Rameau's
satirical baroque opera, ``Platee,'' a wildly imagined mix of Greek
gods and swamp creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a Morris double bill at the opera house, Wednesday
through Saturday, with all the makings of still another ``event.''
The run includes Morris' final appearances, sometimes known as
``farewell performances,'' in his danced version of ``Dido and
Aeneas,'' Purcell's 1689 opera.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 staging, previously seen at the academy's Majestic
Theater in 1990, puts Morris and his dancers center stage and
sequesters the opera's singers with the musicians in the pit;
``empitted'' is Morris' word for the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Opening the bill is the New York premiere of Morris' newest
dance, ``Medium,'' a work for six dancers with references to the
untimely death of Franz Schubert. And as a kind of unmentioned
backdrop to the evening are the circumstances under which
``Medium'' came to be.
</P>
<P>
   Morris created the dance on the heels of his quiet and
much-speculated-about departure earlier this year as director of
Paul Simon's ``Capeman,'' the $11 million Broadway show that folded
in March after eight weeks under the weight of overwhelmingly
negative reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as Morris tells it, he immediately made up ``Medium'''
after the demise of ``Capeman,'' as if to dispel any thoughts that
he was in a slump.
</P>
<P>
   Morris likes to refer to his craft as ``making up dances'' and
to the programming of his works as ``shows.'' He prefers the simple
ring of ``show'' or the flourish of ``spectacle,'' as the French
pronounce it, far more than ``program'' or ``bill.''
</P>
<P>
   At 41, Morris continues to cut what has become a familiar
figure, one projecting an unapologetic and unguarded free spirit.
Arriving for an interview in the cafe he had chosen in his midtown
East Side neighborhood, he sailed in with an imperial flair,
dressed in his signature shower thongs, loose Bermuda shorts and
gauzy shirt. His ringleted, shoulder-length dark hair completed the
immediately recognizable Morris picture.
</P>
<P>
   References to his luxuriant locks, once described to Morris'
amusement as ``fecund curls,'' in fact, figured early in his
discussion of ``Dido and Aeneas.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the dance's premiere in Brussels, Belgium, Morris' hair
has been used to great effect in his playing the dual roles of
Dido, the tragic queen of Carthage, and the Sorceress, the
malevolent witch whose machinations lead to the departure of Dido's
lover, Aeneas, and to the queen's death of a broken heart.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only design change for Morris from Dido to Sorceress
is one for his hair. As Dido, his tresses are informally piled on
his head with a chopstick as a hairpin; for the witch, they're all
unfastened and unruly. ``I could do it in a wig or with add-ons,''
he notes, ``but I never have and never wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   But to get to the larger question: Why is he giving up the
roles? ``Mostly I don't want to do it anymore,'' he says. ``It's a
very, very particular part, and I'm old and ugly, and I was less
old and ugly before. Also, a mundane but legit reason is that I
want to get my hair cut.'' He will not say, however, if his
tonsorial transformation will be as severe as Michael Bolton's.
</P>
<P>
   Morris originally planned ``Dido and Aeneas'' as a solo number
in which he would take on all the roles himself, from chorus to
central characters. In the 16-dancer work he ultimately created _
``a very particular ritual of a dance,'' he said _ Christine Van
Loon, the costume designer, dressed the performers uniformly in an
austere black garment that remains part of the production; Morris
calls it a sarong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sarongs have no elastic,'' he said. ``We have to tie them,
and we don't ever leave the stage, not even for a drink of water.''
</P>
<P>
   He speaks hesitantly about the time when he was choreographing
``Dido and Aeneas.'' Without saying so pointedly, it's clear he
doesn't want to freight his dance with specified sentiments about
terminal illness, like those in ``Still/Here,'' the dance with
video and text by Bill T. Jones, or in the subtler ``Not About AIDS
Dance'' by Neil Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   But Morris recalls the time of ``Dido's'' creation as one in
which he felt panicky. ``I had so many sick and dead friends,'' he
said. In his darker moments back then, he felt certain that he,
too, was ``going to die of AIDS, in like an hour,'' and that
``Dido'' might be his last dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very different now,'' he says. ``I've become much less
superstitious.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Medium'' and ``Dido'' will be separated by an intermission.
```Medium' is about medium length,'' Morris notes with a smile,
saying he'd prefer a long intermission between the works,
suggesting ``an hour and a half, like Glyndebourne,'' the English
summer opera festival with intermissions long enough for patrons to
picnic between acts. ``I want them to have no relation to one
another,'' he says of the two halves of the program, ``although
they both deal with death in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   The music for ``Medium,'' by John Harbison, is titled ``Nov. 19,
1828,'' the date of Schubert's death at the age of 31. Morris says
he will never describe a dance to a journalist, but he does suggest
that clues can be found in the composer's notes accompanying
Harbison's recent CD, ``John Harbison,'' which also includes two
string quartets.
</P>
<P>
   There one learns that the 18-minute work includes distorted
musical references to Schubert's works, as they might have haunted
him on his journey to ``the next world,'' and that the title,
``Medium,'' refers to Harbison; in his notes, he portrays himself
as a go-between for the dead composer and today's audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Morris heard the music first in a recording and found it, he
says, ``so beautifully built, so fabulous and mysterious, so
Schubertian.'' The costumes for the piece's six dancers (Morris
does not perform in this dance) are in muted colors and
translucent.
</P>
<P>
   Morris and the designer for the ghostlike costumes of
``Medium,'' Martin Pakledinaz, a frequent collaborator with Morris,
often find themselves talking about Paul Cadmus' transparent
costumes for a ballet by Lew Christiansen called ``Filling
Station.'' ``I love naked,'' Morris admits. ``I'd love to see
everybody naked all the time.'' When pressed on whether he meant
``naked'' or the more art-historical ``nude,'' Morris emphasizes
``naked, just naked, no clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris will talk somewhat nakedly about the failed ``Capeman.''
His thoughts reflect no ill will. ``I didn't hide,'' he says about
attending the opening night and several subsequent performances of
the show that marked his troubled debut on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Officially he remained the director and choreographer of
``Capeman.'' Unofficially his work was revamped by other hands,
notably those of a more seasoned director, Jerry Zaks. Now he is
content to remark on the generosity of his fellow artists.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls being in the dressing room of some ``Capeman''
performers near the time the show closed on March 28. ``Come on,
guys,''' he remembers saying, ``aren't you a little bit blue, or a
little bit suicidal that you're not being appreciated or that the
show isn't happening?
</P>
<P>
   ``And every one of them in some way said, it's an honor and a
thrill to be performing with these people. So I thought: `Note to
self: Wow! This ship is going down and they are not bitter. Is this
New York?'''
</P>
<P>
   He answers himself by ruminating on what makes New York special
to him as an artist and a citizen. He muses about Seattle, where he
was born, and various American and international locales where he
regularly performs. He contrasts places where people are nice but
not necessarily kind, then concludes: ``New Yorkers are not nice
maybe, but they are kind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
