<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4155 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-17 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES ARE MADE OF THIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in April, I promised to tell you about my class reunion.
It's been 10 years since I waltzed across the stage and received
that awesome sheet of paper that told the world I was finally an
official Doctor of Dental Surgery. Boy, was I a happy camper that
day!
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, we all gathered on the plaza with our families to hug
and mug for farewell photos. Finally, my family pinned me down and
tied a string to my foot so I wouldn't float away.
</P>
<P>
   That was in Minneapolis. We moved back to Texas six years ago
and, other than a few Christmas cards, I haven't had much contact
with my colleagues. I didn't even realize that it had been 10 years
until I received the first notice about the reunion. I was thrilled
at the idea of seeing the fellow soldiers who spent four years in
the trenches with me, battling inflexible instructors and
tooth-devouring bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   At the second notice, I went on a diet and started looking for
pictures of my old classmates. My heart sank when I could name only
about 20 of the 85. I knew that most of them would remember me; not
because I was so marvelous, but because I was the only
African-American in the class. During my third year, I was the only
black person in the entire school, but that's another column.
</P>
<P>
   When the big weekend arrived, my family and I flew off to
Minnesota. Once there, we got lost and arrived a little late. When
we walked in, everyone was enjoying social hour. As if on cue,
conversation ceased and every head turned in our direction. My
first thought was, ``They have name tags, thank goodness!''
Everyone smiled and said, ``Hey, Moe!'' transporting me back to the
time when I was with them more than I was at home.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, no Romy and Michelles showed up. Of course, everyone
was at their best, with the trappings of success casually draped
across their bodies. Nevertheless, they looked, you know, human.
One classmate had quit her job to stay home with her children and,
much to her surprise, we were all happy for her. The party animal,
Steve, is now married with children and drives a Suburban. That
really made us happy. All of the skinny people had blossomed,
considerably. That made us real sad. Not.
</P>
<P>
   Last and least was this one insecure fellow who spent the
evening trying to convince everyone that he was the most successful
and important person in the room. He told anyone who would listen
about his great practice, his huge staff, his awesome investments,
his snazzy cars and his incredible home. There's always one, you
know. Eventually, someone told him, ``You win; you're the richest
person here,'' and he finally shut up.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wonderful reunion. Reliving the obstacles I had
overcome helped motivate me for the days ahead. That's what
memories are for, I think; not just reliving, but better living.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
