<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-US-JAPAN-YEN-COX     06-17 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-US-JAPAN-YEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. INTERVENES TO PROP UP JAPANESE YEN ON PROMISES OF
STEPPED-UP REFORMS
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Worried that the plummeting Japanese currency
threatens to cast a troubled global economy deeper into turmoil,
the Clinton administration made a massive purchase of yen on
Wednesday and dispatched a senior finance official on an emergency
mission to Tokyo to try to rescue the coin of the world's
second-largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he authorized the intervention _
estimated by traders at some $2 billion _ after an overnight
telephone call with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, who
pledged to undertake long-promised measures to stimulate Japan's
moribund economy and restructure its adled financial sector.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said some things which made it clear that he was prepared
to take some bold steps to try to move the Japanese economy
forward, restore growth and opportunity. And I believe in that
context we should be supportive,'' Clinton told reporters following
an unrelated White House Rose Garden event. ''I wanted to send a
clear signal to the markets that the United States supports
Japanese reform, believes the Japanese people can pull out of this
economic slump and restore growth and opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's intervention by the Federal Reserve Bank _ its first
such move meant to affect the yen's value since April 1995 _
sparked a rally on Wall Street, which has swooned over the past two
weeks largely on fears that the slumping yen could deepen the
economic crisis across Asia. The closely-watched Dow Jones
Industrial Average jumped 164.17 points to close at 8829.46.
</P>
<P>
   And the target of the intervention, the Japanese currency,
jumped 7 yen against the dollar, closing in New York at 136.5 yen
to the dollar, after opening in morning trading at 143.5.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Wednesday's intervention, the dollar had risen nearly
80 percent against the yen since the Japanese currency touched its
record high three years ago, with nearly a quarter of the increase
having come this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The White House joined private analysts, however, in warning
that the effect of Wednesday's intervention would be short-lived
unless Tokyo follows through on promised stimulus and reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto told Clinton he was accelerating a massive public
works spending program, stepping up planned tax cuts and making the
politically unpopular move of using taxpayer money to help shore up
Japan's troubled banking system, paralyzed by bad loans
conservatively valued at more than $600 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''This intervention is just a finger in the dike,'' said Sung
Won Sohn, chief economist with the Norwest Corp., a bank holding
company in Minneapolis. ''We should not have a mistaken belief that
this has solved the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, ''The absolute key is that
the Japanese government take the necessary actions with respect to
their economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters at a White House briefing, Rubin said,
''The issue isn't our intervention: the issue is what they do. The
only way the problems in Japan will get solved is through what
Japan does.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Rubin sent his deputy, Lawrence Summers, to
Tokyo for a hastily called meeting with his counterparts _ deputy
finance ministers _ from the so-called Group of Seven, or G-7,
industrialized democracies. In addition to the United States and
Japan, the group includes Britain, Canada, France, Germany and
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Summers, the administration's point man on the Asia economic
crisis, left Washington Wednesday afternoon and was to arrive in
Tokyo Thursday evening, Japan time.
</P>
<P>
   Summers and his counterparts are huddling with an eye toward the
dire threat the yen's continuing slide poses to a world economy
already reeling from the collapse of currencies across much of Asia
and the threat of a financial meltdown in Russia that could spread
across Central Europe and further squeeze the countries of Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the yen continues to slide, this thing will become a plague
on Asia,'' said Sohn. ''A global recession, except for the United
States and Western Europe, is a real possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Of particular concern is China, which has resisted devaluing its
own currency, the renminbi, or yuan, over the past year, in the
face of mounting pressure from the falling yen, Korean won,
Indonesian rupiah, Malaysian ringit and Thai baht -- all of which
have plunged by more than 40 percent against the dollar over the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   Those declines have made exports from those countries cheaper,
in dollar terms, than they were a year ago. That's begun cutting
into China's exports, which declined last month for the first time
in two years, slowing economic growth and adding to unemployment
pressures already growing because of Beijing's efforts to wean its
massive worker base from inefficient state-run enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood currency slides have also cut into the crude
oil of China's economic growth, foreign investment, which slid 19
percent in April, as investors from the United States and elsewhere
found that their dollars could go further elsewhere in Asia, where,
in dollar terms, businesses, property and banks have suddenly
become available at fire-sale prices.
</P>
<P>
   All of that has put pressure on China to devalue its own
currency, a step economists insist wuld send other Asian economies
tumbling down another flight of steps toward the cellar.
</P>
<P>
   ''They (the Chinese) are worried about the larger picture in
Asia _ how soon will the recovery begin,'' Nicholas Lardy, senior
fellow at the Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank, told
reporters on Monday. ''As assessments have changed in the region
about how soon that will come about, China is getting more and more
worried about their ability to continue to dodge the bullet, which
is essentially what they've done to date. ''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said he had no indications that Beijing was prepared to
devalue the yuan, which was devalued four years ago in a move some
economists contend helped set the stage for the current Asia
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton preparing for a state visit to Beijing next week,
however, many analysts speculated that Wednesday's intervention on
behalf of the yen was a political gesture aimed at showing
solidarity with the Chinese at least as much, if not more so, than
a market move.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really a political decision by Clinton to help the
Chinese,'' said Joel Kent, an economist with the New York
investment firm, Lehman Brothers Government Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Many currency traders, who have bet heavily against the yen in
recent months as the White House has steadfastly defended a strong
dollar, were caught flatfooted.
</P>
<P>
   ''People were still getting in, eating their breakfast,'' Kent
said, when the Treasury Department made the first of several
traunches of yen purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's move came just two months after the Bank of Japan
dumped a staggering $18 billion worth of dollar-denominated U.S.
Treasury notes in a single day, in a failed attempt to arrest a
slide in the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The yen's weakness reflects continuing difficulties in the
Japanese economy, second in size only to that of the United States.
Japan's economy has grown little in the past eight years and has
contracted for two consecutive quarters, meeting the formal
definition of a recession.
</P>
<P>
   The image of the U.S. Treasury shoveling billions of dollars at
the yen in an effort to prop up the Japanese currency is a striking
contrast to events a decade ago, when politicians here voiced
strident concerns that Japan was using its powerful currency to buy
up landmark properties and businesses across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Japan still holds enormous wealth in this country, the result of
decades of direct investment in property and businesses as well as
portfolio holdings in stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are talking about in the trillions (of dollars), '' said
Sohn. ''We're talking about huge amounts of money here, so Japan is
not going to go to the poor house.''
</P>
<P>
   For use by clients of the New York Times News Service(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
