<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, June 18. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TOBACCO (Washington) _ The Senate jettisons broad
tobacco legislation, the most ambitious and contentious measure
before Congress, and leaves almost no hope it could be revived this
year. By David E. Rosenbaum. (We plan to move the story by 8:30
p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.) The story runs under a 3-column,
3-line hed; with 2-col. photo.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-YEN (Washington) _ The United States takes the currency
markets by surprise and buys yen to stop the precipitous fall of
the Japanese currency, a move that President Clinton says he hopes
will stem the worsening Asian economic crisis. By David E. Sanger.
(Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to JAPAN-MARKETPLACE, inside Business.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-US-SATELLITE (Washington) _ More questions are emerging
about equipment already sold to China, including some of this
country's most sophisticated communications technology. By Jeff
Gerth. (We plan to move this story at 9:30 p.m. in ``w'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ALBRIGHT (New York) _ The secretary of state responds to
overtures from Iran. By Barbara Crossette. (Scheduled to move by
8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-IMMUNE (Undated) _ Scientists have visualized the first
contact made between the probe of the AIDS virus and its two target
sites on the surface of a human cell. The visualization also shows
how cunning and multi-faceted the virus' defenses are against
attack by the body's immune system, confirming many researchers'
views that the AIDS vaccine recently approved for testing is
unlikely to work. By Nicholas Wade. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET
in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   NY-EMERGENCY-PLANS (New York) _ New York City's plans to protect
against germ warfare _ plans that took the form of a bunker last
week _ are moving forward. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RICHARDSON-HOLBROOKE (Washington) _ President Clinton has
decided to name Richard Holbrooke as the U.S. representative to the
United Nations, replacing Bill Richardson, who will become energy
secretary. By Steven Erlanger. (The story has moved in ``w'' and
``i'' news files.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-HEART (Boston) _ It's a rare but fatal danger in the
world of sports: A young athlete receives a sharp but fairly mild
blow on the chest, then collapses and dies. Researchers using pigs
to investigate this phenomenon, commotio cordis, have found that
there is a 15-millisecond period in the normal cardiac cycle where
a baseball thrown at 30 mph hour can cause dangerous ventricular
fibrillation. By Philip J. Hilts. (The story has moved in ``a''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CZAR-BURIAL (Moscow) _ The burial next month of the
often-disturbed remains of Nicholas II, Russia's last czar, and his
family had been planned as an occasion rich in pomp and symbolism,
but with the recent announcements that neither the head of the
Russian Orthodox Church nor President Boris Yeltsin will be there
in attendance, Russia's last royal burial has been downgraded to an
unusually elaborate church service. (The story has moved in ``i''
news file.)
</P>
