<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4164 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MUSEUM-PYTHON-$ADV     06-17 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MUSEUM-PYTHON-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NAUGHTY, SURREAL PLEASURES OF THE `PYTHON' 6
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (bl)  
 By JEFF MacGREGOR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sex! Violence! Gratuitous nudity!
</P>
<P>
   Like all right-thinking American youngsters, I had these things
much on my mind by the time I reached high school in the early
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Back in those ancient, darkling days, however, pre-Springer and
pre-Internet, they were much harder to come by. The shabby
acquisition and shameful consideration of same required a
smuggler's cool, a plausible fake ID and a fistful of bus transfers
to the wrong side of town, where a certain grizzled shopkeeper was
willing to sell us, for a price _ yes _ the comedy albums of Redd
Foxx and Lenny Bruce. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I ran with a slow, if thoughtful, crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Sex! Cannibalism! Gratuitous cross-dressing!
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder then that when ``Monty Python's Flying Circus''
made its stateside television debut a quarter of a century ago on
PBS, my goofball friends and I were galvanized by it.
</P>
<P>
   The smart, naughty silliness of it was unlike anything we'd ever
seen. Hipper and more surreal by far than ``Laugh-In'' or ``The
Smothers Brothers,'' ``Monty Python'' had more in common with the
radio-inflected anarchy of Firesign Theater or the urbane musical
satire of Tom Lehrer.
</P>
<P>
   Better still, it had moving pictures. Best of all, it was
available to us without the plain brown wrapper and could be
studied with relative impunity in the security of one's own rumpus
room. From which plaid-carpeted stronghold every sketch was duly
and painstakingly memorized by us, to be dully and painfully
recited in later performance at our high school talent show. (We
finished a distant and deserving second to a pregnant senior who
sang ``I'm Just a Girl Who Can't Say No.''
</P>
<P>
   Sex! Chartered accountancy! Gratuitous existentialism!
</P>
<P>
   Happily for us all in these more enlightened times, comedy is
off the streets and out of the converted basements and back in the
great museums where it belongs.
</P>
<P>
   The bicoastal Museum of Television and Radio honors the sterling
memory of ``Monty Python's Flying Circus'' beginning Friday with a
three-day marathon presentation of all 45 episodes from the show's
four seasons on the BBC. Then, starting June 30 and running
seriatim through late September in two-week cycles, the museum will
present a dozen composite packages of pre-, post- and
pluperfect-Python material. (The museum's Los Angeles and New York
branches are screening the shows on slightly different schedules.)
</P>
<P>
   These edited shows, bearing titles from the original series like
``Full Frontal Nudity,'' ``Spam'' and ``How to Recognize Different
Trees From Quite a Long Way Away,'' are anchored by classic ``Monty
Python'' episodes but are mostly collaged from cast members' work
before and after the great show itself.
</P>
<P>
   Of greatest interest to comedy archaeologists will be the grainy
black-and-white bits from the mid-'60s. Drawn from earlier shows
and sketches written and performed in various combinations by John
Cleese, Graham Chapman, Eric Idle, Michael Palin, Terry Jones and
Terry Gilliam, they chart the origins and nascent sensibilities of
what eventually became the full ``Monty'' in the fall of 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The first screening package, ``Sex and Violence,'' includes
footage from 1967's ``Frost Over England'' with an alarmingly young
(if precociously smarmy) Sir David. The archival value here is in
seeing Cleese as a supporting player in Frost's repertory comedy
company. Tall as a larch and whippet-thin, his face that of an
angular Anglican choirboy, Cleese mugs and bugs his way through
several near-silent sight gags. In evidence throughout is the weird
British synthesis of slapstick and bone-dry sophistication that
later became ``Monty Python's'' hallmark, the apotheosis of which
here is a sketch wherein a dentist (Cleese) chases a patient
chasing a half-clad dental hygienist across the collapsing reality
of a semi-dreamscape. Benny Hill meets Bertrand Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Last the 1948 Show,'' a comedy-variety show also from 1967
starring Cleese and Chapman, is excerpted next (Britcom fans will
be happy to see Marty Feldman back at work). Sending up tradition
is the leitmotif here, the best moment of which _ and I say this
without fear of contradiction _ is a tabernacle performance of the
Olde Englishe Ballade ``I've Got a Ferret Up My Nose.''
</P>
<P>
   Most appealing though, and perhaps most illustrative of what
Python became, are the clips from 1968's ``Do Not Adjust Your
Set.'' Nominally a children's show, it featured Idle, Palin and
Jones as writer-performers. Gilliam is on hand likewise, providing
the animations. Like all good kiddie shows, it works at about nine
levels at once, most of them well above the little nippers' heads.
From a bowdlerized ``King Lear'' to the reductio ad infinitum of
television watchers watching other watchers watch television, the
show puts the sharpest stuff up on the highest shelf, where the
children won't be hurt by it. Those familiar with the medium will
recognize the influences of Ernie Kovacs and Wizard.
</P>
<P>
   Also seen here are what later became tropes of the Python troop:
Palin as an addled counterman, Jones in a giant diaper and, in
utero, the Commonwealth commonplace that Scotsmen aer bonnie foon,
nae matter what they dee. Uh, do.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the compilation is ``Monthy Python'' No. 1, ``Sex
and Violence,'' shown in its hilarious and groundbreaking entirety.
Weirdly, this was also the first episode I ever saw. To this day
the phrase ``That's a depressing prospect for an ambitious sheep''
takes me back to my performance before an auditorium full of
silent, uncomprehending adults, each of whom was no doubt wondering
just exactly what the school board had spent all their tax money
on.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the question at the very heart of the coming
Museum of Television and Radio retrospective. To wit: Is it worth
seeing?
</P>
<P>
   For ardent fans, certainly. The 45 original episodes remain a
high point in the history of comedy television. There hasn't been
another sketch-driven ensemble series anywhere before or since that
so completely succeeded at what it set out to do. Its slippery
logic and post-modern self-awareness pioneered a style that has
never successfully been imitated. Its joyful and singular
appreciation of both lowbrow antic vaudeville and a high-minded
theater of the absurd is a model of the form.
</P>
<P>
   For those devotees who want to track the creative growth of the
writers and performers, the screening packages are an invaluable
resource. So too are they an excellent lesson to the hardy few who
might aspire to the same kind of work. I would, for example, make
it mandatory viewing for everyone on the staff at ``Saturday Night
Live.''
</P>
<P>
   But deconstructing the ways and means of humor can be a dismal
business (witness that last paragraph), especially for the casual
viewer. For the not-quite-convinced-this-is-funny, then, a night or
two of the marathon should suffice to reach a final opinion. If
nothing else, it wouldn't kill you to get out of the house once in
a while, and the museums are good examples of really expensive
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   For those benighted few who remain firm in rejecting every
British import since the lend-lease days, though, no amount of
sermonizing or high-tech, leather-upholstered, museum-quality
viewing will suffice. The true believers like me can spend this
summer in happy abandon, revisiting a misspent youth of silly walks
and crunchy frogs, of nudging and winking and singing the ``Spam''
song, of dancing the fish-slapping dance and parroting back all the
lines we already know by heart.
</P>
<P>
   And when people ask, ``Now what's all this, then?'' we can smile
our secret smiles, because as ``The Complete and Utter History of
Monty Python'' teaches us: It's sex! It's violence! It's gratuitous
existential cannibal cross-dressing!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
