</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-SHAKEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CLOUDS CONVICTED AU PAIR'S PRIOR INJURY DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A report published by an independent team of scientists casts
doubt on a central premise of Louise Woodward's criminal defense:
that an infant like Matthew Eappen could suffer a skull fracture
that eventually would kill him, then behave for weeks as if nothing
were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence of a prolonged interval of lucidity
between the injury and the onset of symptoms'' in children with
such severe head injuries, said the report in the current New
England Journal of Medicine. ``Thus, an alert, well-appearing child
has not already sustained a devastating acute injury that will
become clinically obvious hours to days later.''
</P>
<P>
   The article, by four physicians at the University of
Pennsylvania School of Medicine, was commissioned by the journal to
respond to the scientific controversy over ``shaken-baby syndrome''
generated by the Woodward case, although the authors did not
specifically address that case. The report, and interviews with its
authors, generally bolster arguments raised by the Woodward
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This article has to answer even the most discerning of
skeptics that the prosecution case of how Matthew died, by
shaking-impact syndrome, is correct,'' said Martha Coakley, one of
the Woodward prosecutors who is now a candidate for district
attorney of Middlesex County in eastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Ayub Ommaya, a Washington neurosurgeon who testified for
the defense, said there are ``holes'' in the journal report that
undermine its conclusions and make clear that ``it is certainly not
the final word.'' While he agreed that ``it is not common'' for an
infant to remain lucid after a severe head injury, Ommaya added
that ``such lucidity has been noted.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the journal article responds to general issues
surrounding ``shaken-baby syndrome,'' which became the center of
focus and confusion during last year's Woodward trial. The authors
say the syndrome is real and responsible for most severe brain
injuries by infants, but they also say a more accurate term is
``shaking-impact syndrome,'' since most damage is done when the
head forcefully strikes a surface.
</P>
<P>
   Can shaking alone cause the severe injuries often lumped as part
of the syndrome? Probably not, the UPenn doctors say, although that
``is still debated'' and severe shaking oftentimes leads to a baby
striking its head against a hard object.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's defense team didn't contest that 8-month-old Matthew
had suffered a severe head injury, but it argued that the injury
that killed him stemmed from a wound as old as three weeks rather
than from anything Woodward did to him before he was hospitalized
and days later died. That issue of whether a baby like Matthew
could die from an earlier severe injury, exacerbated by a
relatively minor later wound, was a key point of contention at the
trial, and was dealt with directly in the article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such rare events have been reported in older children and
adults,'' the UPenn authors said. But, they added, ``there is no
evidence that traumatic acute subdural hematoma, particularly that
leading to death, occurs in otherwise healthy infants in an occult
or subclinical manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence rather suggests that, after a truly severe injury,
there is an ``immediate or rapid onset of neurological symptoms,''
the authors wrote. They based that finding in part on a San Diego
study published last year involving 95 children who died from
accidental head injuries. All but one of those children ``had an
immediate decrease in the level of consciousness.'' The one
exception suffered a different injury than Matthew's and died of
surgical complications.
</P>
<P>
   But Ommaya, the former chief of neurosurgery at the National
Institutes of Health, said a far bigger study is needed to test
whether such delays in symptoms occur. ``You can't make a claim
that you can't have a lucid interval,'' he said. ``There are cases
of lucid intervals.''
</P>
<P>
   The New England Journal authors were less definitive with other
symptoms Matthew suffered, such as retinal bleeding. While
published reports suggest that such hemorrhages are found in ``65
to 95 percent of patients'' with shaken-baby syndrome, the authors
wrote, they are not by themselves proof of the syndrome and it is
tough to tell how long ago the bleeding began.
</P>
<P>
   What about the fact that Matthew did not have severe injuries to
the neck and upper vertebra, or obvious marks on his scalp, which
Woodward's lawyers say proved he was not a victim of shaken-baby
syndrome?
</P>
<P>
   The journal article says that when the surface the baby strikes
is soft, like a couch pillow, ``the force of the impact is widely
dissipated and may not be associated with visible signs of surface
trauma, even though the brain itself decelerates rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   As for neck and vertebra damage, ``it's too ill-defined to say
you have to have a neck injury,'' said Dr. Cindy W. Christian, an
author of the journal article and head of the child abuse program
at Children's Hospital of Philadelphia. ``I don't believe those
things have ever been described as necessary components for this
diagnosis'' of shaken-baby syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Angell, the New England Journal's editor-in-chief, said
she recruited the authors of the article because they were
independent experts who the journal felt could help shed light on a
subject made even more controversial by the Woodward case.
</P>
<P>
   Such a neutral review was called for in the aftermath of the
trial by Harvey Silverglate, one of Woodward's lawyers. But
Wednesday Silverglate said that what he wanted, and still wants, is
a review not of generic shaken-baby issues like the journal
published, but one where independent scientists examine specific
evidence in the Woodward case, none of which the UPenn researchers
saw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
