<SLUG> BC-AIDS-CRYSTALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOS OF HIV MOLECULES RAISE HOPE FOR VACCINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After five years of effort, scientists unveiled the first
detailed pictures of a spiky molecule on the surface of the AIDS
virus that allows it to infect human immune cells _ a great boost,
they say, for designing effective vaccines and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery, considered a technical tour de force, has already
revealed secrets of how this critical part of the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV) docks like a spaceship with
complementary molecules on target cells while defending itself
against immune attack. It also suggests why vaccines against HIV so
far have been disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare tribute to the achievement's importance, the new
pictures of the HIV molecule adorn the covers of both the current
British journal Nature, published Thursday, and its US rival
Science, appearing Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you get the three-dimensional structure of an
important molecule like this, you're many steps ahead,'' said Dr.
Anthony S. Fauci, the federal government's leading AIDS researcher.
``It brings us much closer to things we've had to surmise about.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar feat _ scientists' ability in the late 1980s to grow
three-dimensional crystals of an HIV enzyme called protease _ led
to the development of protease inhibitors. These drugs, used in
combination with others, have drastically cut AIDS deaths rates and
transformed the course of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   To capture pictures of GP120, researchers had to grow it in
crystal form, a challenge for a protein molecule as convoluted and
complex as this one. The molecule measures 1/200-millionth of an
inch across; each AIDS virus bristles with 216 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Fauci and others predicted the most important application will
be in what scientists call ``rational'' vaccine design.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in the top tier of scientific achievements in the
field,'' commented Dr. Robert C. Gallo, director of the University
of Maryland's Institute of Human Virology. ``It will help us induce
antibodies of the right type for vaccine purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   The leading AIDS vaccine candidate, OK'd last month by federal
officials for the first widespread human trials, is based on GP120,
so named because it is a glycoprotein, or sugar-protein complex.
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   However, this experimental vaccine does not contain GP120 in its
natural three-dimensional form, which leads some critics to doubt
it will be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the defenses the virus has built around this molecule are
exactly the same things'' that make a vaccine based on GP120
ineffective, said Joseph Sodroski of Dana-Farber Cancer Institute
in Boston, a leader of the multicenter effort. ``Knowing what those
defenses are will focus our efforts to improve this molecule as a
vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Hendrickson of Columbia University, another member of the
team, said most people infected with HIV make antibodies that
target ``decoys'' on the surface that GP120 presents to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people generate antibodies to parts of GP120 that are
changeable, or parts that are not displayed when the virus is in an
infective state,'' Hendrickson said. The new pictures of GP120
reveal antibody targets that don't change from one HIV strain to
the next and are vital to the virus's ability to get inside human
cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is that these regions will elicit the right kinds of
antibodies that can neutralize the virus,'' Hendrickson said.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing what GP120 looks like in molecular detail also gives
scientists new targets for designer drugs that foil HIV in novel
ways. For instance, the pictures reveal the docking site for a
molecule called CD4 that protrudes from the surface of certain
immune cells.
</P>
<P>
   The site resembles a ball-and-socket joint, suggesting that if a
drug could be designed to fit the socket on GP120 it could block
infection.
</P>
<P>
   The new pictures also reveal how GP120 is sugar-coated with an
``icing'' that prevents antibody recognition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
