<HEADER>
A4169 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS-STEREOTYPES-2TA     06-17 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-STEREOTYPES-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW, IF NOT IMPROVED, USE OF STEREOTYPES IN FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (bl)  
 Karen Durbin is the film critic for Mirabella magazine.  
 By KAREN DURBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to ``Meantime.'' The title of Mike Leigh's scathingly
funny early-'80s assault on Thatcherism might just as well describe
our own age. We live in a time when bullies are in fashion and
creative work that addresses social injustice or the validity of
someone else's suffering is likely to meet with braying accusations
of ``victim art'' and ``political correctness.''
</P>
<P>
   Some filmmakers accommodate themselves to such a climate by
deploying, with a wink and a naughty grin, the sort of stereotypes
that began to disappear from movies 30 years ago and that to some
of us at least, can't be redeemed by any amount of post-modernist
irony or neo-noir chic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, others persist in burrowing beneath cliche, although as
any artist who has made the effort will tell you, confronting
stereotypes has always been a far trickier proposition than
trafficking in them. Stereotypes don't spring full grown from the
foreheads of bigots. They're a kind of estrangement, but they form
around a core of recognizable fact, borrowing fact's credibility
even as they distort its truth. Their presence in a film can seem
positively cutting edge while playing to some of our laziest and
worst assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   Gifted, and disparate, directors such as Quentin Tarantino and
Spike Lee regularly spice up their films and their reputations for
audacity with a touch of bad attitude here, some in-your-face
bigotry there. Sometimes it makes artistic sense; often it doesn't.
A little racism, a touch of misogyny, it's hip, it's bold, it's
real. It's the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But one hipster's cutting edge is another's mortal insult. In
``Jackie Brown,'' Tarantino got a little too real for Lee, who
complained about the number of times Samuel L. Jackson's grouchy
arms dealer used the word ``nigger'' in a single speech (27).
Tarantino could retaliate by pointing out that while the men in
``He Got Game'' are richly developed characters, the women are a
laundry list of types (noble dead black mom, treacherous living
black girlfriend, white hooker with heart of gold, busty white
babes with brains of air). He could, but he won't.
</P>
<P>
   In very different ways, three current films use stereotypes to
give themselves an edge they would otherwise lack. All are bold and
well intentioned, but they vary wildly in the ways they confront
conventional expectations or cater to them.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's new animated feature ``Mulan,'' based on a
fifth-century Chinese poem about a young woman warrior who defeats
an invading Hun army and saves her country, consciously sets out to
turn at least one stereotype on its head; ``Smoke Signals,''
written, directed and starring young American Indians, serves up
its stereotypes with a 400-year-old vengeance, while Warren
Beatty's buoyantly comic political satire ``Bulworth'' ultimately
sinks beneath their unexamined weight.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a recent press screening of ``Mulan,'' a reporter
asked the only child in the room, a boy named Johnny, what he
thought of the movie's eponymous heroine. Mediawise beyond his
eight years, Johnny gave his questioner a patient look and said:
``I liked her OK It didn't bother me that she was a girl.'' Then he
blurted: ``But I really liked the bad guy. He was great!''
</P>
<P>
   Shan-yu, the movie's ruthless villain, certainly is great. He's
a real walk on the wild side, huge and powerful and not unhandsome,
if your tastes run to razor-sharp incisors and fierce yellow eyes.
But the news here is that his unlikely opponent is pretty great,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Stereotypes play to our fears and anxious desires; role models
try to pretend they don't exist. More dutiful than inspired, role
models usually make poor substitutes for good art.
</P>
<P>
   But Mulan came into existence under the watchful, combative eye
of Pam Coats, one of Disney's few female animation producers. And,
like her protector, Mulan is an exception to the rule. An only
child who disguises herself as a man and goes off to war to spare
her aging, battle-scarred father, Mulan is clever, generous,
passionate and determined. But she's a good deal more than that;
she's also vulnerable and funny, showing flashes of irony and
slapstick humor. She's the best animated heroine in Disney's
history not because she's the most politically proper but because
she's the most fully imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is rich with unexpected payoffs. One of the best is a
sequence in which Mulan, trying to be a dutiful daughter, goes to a
marriage broker to be made into a perfect bride. In a conventional
Disney cartoon, this would be the all-important transformation
scene that little girls wait for, the one in which Beauty or
Cinderella or even Belle gets to put on the fabulous dress and the
upswept hairdo and go out there and win the heart of the prince.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, Mulan emerges dressed to the nines, and her
traditionally painted face _ white powder, red rosebud lips and
dramatically shadowed eyes _ looks exquisite.
</P>
<P>
   But love isn't the first concern of the character Mulan (or the
film ``Mulan''), and so the scene subverts the convention. Not only
does it happen way too soon in the story; there's not a prince in
sight, and the marriage broker is no kindly fairy godmother but a
fuming bully who will eventually write Mulan off as insufficiently
demure, in effect setting her free.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Mulan's transformation feels like anything but a
triumph. True, she has been made beautiful, but in the process she
has been obliterated. She has literally disappeared into a generic
feminine ideal, a stereotype of sorts, and it's startling how
sharply one feels the loss of her real face, which isn't generic at
all but distinctively flat and strong and appealingly expressive.
</P>
<P>
   The scene, which plays out with some terrific cartoon slapstick,
resonates with all sorts of disturbing questions about beauty and
identity and female shame. But then, ``Mulan'' itself resonates
with an implicit reproach to a country where women are so
undervalued that orphanages abound with discarded baby girls. And
those are the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   There's a raffish little dragon in ``Mulan,'' something of a
flimflam artist and _ a staple of Disney's contemporary animated
features _ an ethnic joker who supplies the hero with a comic foil
and the movie with lots of raucous humor. In this case, the
ethnicity belongs to Eddie Murphy, whose voice makes Mushu the
dragon very black, very street and very motor mouth.
</P>
<P>
   In a movie devoted to upending cliches, Murphy's Mushu is at
first a disconcerting presence. It seems a very cheap joke that the
only black voice in the movie should be rattling away nervously,
trying to curry favor with a bunch of dignified, disdainful Asians.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Murphy himself is the solution to the problem. He
can't save a bad script, but he can make a good one hilarious; he
individuates Mushu, giving him such a distinctive personality
(sarcastic, exuberant, skeptical, scared, nervy, antic) that it
seems perfectly natural, as well as funny, when the little dragon
salutes one of Mulan's battlefield achievements by squealing, ``You
the man,'' immediately adding, sotto voce, ``Well, sort of.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Bulworth'' could have used Eddie Murphy. But with Murphy
around, Warren Beatty could not have dominated the proceedings as
thoroughly as he does. With some justice, ``Bulworth'' is billing
itself as ``the best-reviewed movie of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also turning out to be one of the most contentious. It has
drawn more boos than raves from black writers, as well as a
fence-straddler by Henry Louis Gates Jr. in The New Yorker. The
most devastating critique was that of essayist Stanley Crouch, whom
no one has ever accused of being politically correct. In a furious
New York Daily News column that took the movie apart, Crouch called
``Bulworth'' ``a Tarzan movie'' that ``pretends to a certain
above-it-all hipness while making sure that there are no Negroes
equal to or superior to the main white character.''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Beatty has put his money, his glamour and his
considerable talent into a film that means to fight the good fight,
attacking the corruption of American politics, highlighting the
racial divide in American life and showcasing the kind of undiluted
liberal passion that Bill Clinton jettisoned well before his hair
turned gray. Furthermore, he has done it with the most effective
weapon, ebullient humor, much of it at the expense of his own
vanity.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sort of. For if the suicidal senator with a sudden mania
for telling the truth is a clownish figure who shows every minute
of Beatty's 61 years, in no time at all his truth-telling turns him
into the great white savior of all the black folk he meets. The
sort of black folk who are front and center in ``Bulworth'' are in
need of saving: drug dealers and the children who work for them;
gangsta rappers and their sexy ladies partying the night away; and
everybody's poor but honest elders, briefly glimpsed being lectured
by Bulworth at church or in their humble, heavily barred homes as
they gather over their ham hocks and greens.
</P>
<P>
   The depths of ego-blinkered condescension in ``Bulworth'' can
hardly be plumbed without a diving tank. Predictably, the silly old
wreck of a senator still gets the girl _ in this case, a beautiful
hip-hop fly girl played by Halle Berry, who is 32 years younger
than Beatty. ``You're my nigger,'' she says fondly, in the line
most likely to remind you that Beatty was a co-writer of the
script.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not enough for Beatty to get the girl; he must get the
guy as well. Witness the presto-chango transformation of the nasty
neighborhood drug dealer (Don Cheadle) into a noble neighborhood
activist, a metamorphosis triggered by (what else?) one of the
senator's lectures.
</P>
<P>
   In the America of ``Bulworth,'' there is barely a black middle
class, no upper middle class and certainly no power elite. No black
executives, black thinkers, black politicians. Most of all, there
are no black saviors. In this well-meaning, racist cartoon, Beatty
not just the man, he the only man.
</P>
<P>
   To understand what Beatty did and did not do, just replace Halle
Berry with Pam Grier (in a sense, Tarantino did this in ``Jackie
Brown'' and created the most resonant female character of his young
career).
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, put them both in the film with the aging white hero
(Ms. Grier could slip right into the plot as a Carol Mosley Braun
figure) and get the sex, race and power issues right out there for
everybody to thrash through instead of trying to sneak past them
with a single, laughably furtive reference (``I'm too old for
you,'' Beatty mutters as he and Ms. Berry ride off into the
narrative sunset).
</P>
<P>
   A political farce that reflected the diversity of black society
is most likely to be made by a black director, and that's at once a
good thing and a bad one. It is crucial for people to be able to
take charge of their own narratives: women describing women's
lives, blacks describing black experience. At the same time, if
that's all that happens, then as a culture we are well lost, to one
another and to ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Alexie wouldn't agree. A member of the Spokane tribe
who, at 31, has published 10 well-received books of poetry, fiction
and essays, Alexie is vocal in his disdain for whites whose work he
sees as simplifying and romanticizing Indian life. He has suggested
that they find their own creation myths and leave American Indians
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie has a point. If the stereotypes that obscure the reality
of African-Americans are belittling or hostile, American Indians
are most likely to find themselves smothered in sentimentality. The
most famous example of this is a prize-winning public service
commercial from the late 1960s that showed a noble Indian shedding
a single artful tear for an environment ruined by whites.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most egregious is Disney's ``Pocahontas,'' released
three years ago, which not only sentimentalized its Indians but
also made a strapping, blond Capt. John Smith its real hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals,'' filmed on the Coeur d'Alene reservation in
Idaho by Chris Eyre and written by Alexie (he was also a
co-producer), is a pungent antidote to all that. The story of two
young men and their strained, competitive search for a lost father,
it shoves every cliche about Indians in your face and propels you
to chew on the implications.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie's fiction, which is partly drawn from his life, has
sparked resentment for its unflattering portraits on the Spokane
reservation where he grew up. ``Smoke Signals'' is unlikely to
change that. It shows us fat Indians, poor Indians, Indians
drinking themselves into a lethal stupor, Indians becalmed in the
middle of the vast, empty nowhere they call ``the rez.'' Its
perspective _ that of the children who view their elders with love,
anguish and rage _ is anything but sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   It is the filmmakers' mordant joke that the characters in
``Smoke Signals'' talk incessantly about what it is to be an
Indian, and when they aren't talking about that, they talk about
white people and what white people think an Indian is. Much of this
is shocking and clever; some of it is slyly hilarious (young
basketball players sitting around after practice suddenly start to
chant, ``General George Custer is guarding me, General George
Custer is guarding me''). And no matter who's watching, some of it
stings. The movie is no easier on white people than it is on
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals,'' which was a double winner at this year's
Sundance festival and will be released by Miramax on Friday,
deserves many of the adjectives lavished on ``Bulworth'' _ words
like ``radical,'' ``driven,'' ``original'' and ``outrageous.'' It
is a genuinely audacious piece of work, summoning up stereotypes in
order to ransack them for their real, complicated meaning. If the
viewer sometimes flinches, the filmmakers don't. The truth can hurt
as much as any lie, and the truth that shapes the world of ``Smoke
Signals'' is the horrific history of white and Indian in America.
Eyre and Alexie have made a funny, inventive and, ultimately, a
fair film about the legacy of that history.
</P>
<P>
   It's a story of lost fathers and of what such fathers might
leave to their sons _ a legacy more valuable than the sons might
allow themselves to imagine but tainted nonetheless. The vanquished
pass on the stigma not only of their defeat but of their failure to
overcome it. For a white audience, ``Smoke Signals'' suggests
something else: so do the victors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
