A4174 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-FARM-BILL-DEMS     06-17 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-FARM-BILL-DEMS-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  DEMOCRATS PUSH FOR CHANGES TO 1996 FARM BILL
</P>
<P>
   By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 17 -- Farmers can blame their dwindling prices
on the Republican Freedom to Farm Act of 1996, according to the
leading Democrats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Farm income has plummeted in more than 30 states since the bill
was signed, said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing crisis in rural America. We believe very
strongly this is a direct result of the Freedom to Farm Act,''
Daschle said. ``There should be no question: the Freedom to Farm
Act was enacted -- prices have fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 law reduced federal subsidies for farmers in the cases
of low crop prices, capped loan programs, and eliminated
restrictions on the quantity farmers could produce.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans contend that now is not the time to debate the
Freedom to Farm Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farm bill should not be opened right now,'' said Jennifer
Cutshall, spokeperson for the Senate Committee on Agriculture,
Nutrition and Forestry. ``These problems are state-specific
situations and should not be addressed by the whole farm bill.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Farm Bureau Federation is also wary of adjusting
the farm bill, as stated in a letter from AFBF President Dean
Kleckner to Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Sen. Richard
Lugar, R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers are better off with the flexibility allowed by the farm
bill, said Kleckner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is working as designed,'' wrote Kleckner. ``It is extremely
important that market forces be allowed to work so that a demand
base can be built. Otherwise, agriculture will not be a growth
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said Democrats from farm states will introduce a package
of legislation that will reinstate a safety net for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The 1996 bill) has thrown (farmers) to the whim of an
unpredictable market, unpredictable weather and unpredictable
conditions overseas,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, ranking
minority member of the Senate Agriculture Committee. ``We need to
change it.''
</P>
<P>
   The package includes eliminating caps on marketing loans for
farmers and creating an indemnity fund for farmers suffering income
losses. The senators had not worked out the details on the
legislative package, including the estimated cost.
</P>
<P>
   The group hopes to push for the legislation before the year is
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a full-court press. We are going to keep
introducing these and we are not going to let up,'' said Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minnesota. ``We are talking about broken dreams and
broken lives. People are losing their farms.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
