<SLUG> BC-IRVINE-MUSEUM-$ADV21-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT A (AS IN ART) IN A CASE FOR CONSERVATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
Eds: Exhibit notes at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID KIRBY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly lost in the sprawling suburbs and high-tech industrial
parks of Orange County, Calif., is the unassuming Irvine Museum.
Tucked away on the 12th floor of a glass office tower between John
Wayne Airport and the San Diego Freeway, it provides an unlikely
setting for the world's largest collection of California
Impressionist paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some of the finest works of this underappreciated genre
have reached New York, bringing their airy palettes and play of
California light to the National Academy Museum in a show titled
``All Things Bright and Beautiful: California Impressionist
Paintings From the Irvine Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Collectively these paintings testify to the energy and passion
of the little-known California Impressionists of 1890 to 1930.
Their work reveals a reverence for the state's landscape, so often
washed in its celebrated white light.
</P>
<P>
   But the paintings tell another story too _ that of an
iron-willed, sometimes combative real estate heiress named Joan
Irvine Smith, whose family once owned the immense ranch upon which
the modern city of Irvine, Calif., is built. Several of the 58
works on view here, selected from Mrs. Smith's 3,000-piece
collection, were painted on the Irvine Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Smith believes that the paintings, inspired by the
unsullied valleys, virgin mountains and deserted coastline of
early-20th-century California, bear witness to much of what the
state has lost forever. She sees the art as an effective tool for
teaching environmental preservation and balanced development. And
she is the first to point out that most of her millions came from
developing parts of the very land that she now hopes these
paintings can help rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conservation must be done in a way that doesn't destroy the
economy,'' said Mrs. Smith, whose mother was a prominent Republican
but who considers herself politically independent. ``A strong
economic base is needed to support environmental preservation, but
you must have a balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The art, she said, ``is a soft sell, a necessity to preserve the
environment, not by hitting people over the head but as a form of
consciousness-raising.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes people think how imperative preservation really is,''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Some native Californians who visit the museum, she said, ``see
the paintings and say, `Ah, this is what it looked like when I grew
up!' Then they compare it to what is going on out there day by
day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Out there'' is visible through the museum's windows: a
sometimes smoggy panorama of housing tracts and clogged freeways
bordered by scarred mountains and, here and there, patches of the
remaining natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always this way. The National Academy exhibition, on
view through July 9 before moving to Chicago, depicts a seemingly
mythical land of milky skies and honey hills. It betrays the
artists' near-religious awe of all they saw around them. And it
shows their mastery at depicting the rare light, shadows and color
of California, especially the coral rays of the setting sun
catching distant peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Artists began arriving in California after the 1849 gold rush,
many settling in San Francisco. Most of them had received formal
training in New York or Chicago, and several had lived and painted
in France _ in Paris and Giverny _ where they were influenced by
Claude Monet.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, artists in Southern California, most notably in Santa
Barbara, Pasadena, San Diego and Laguna Beach (near Irvine), began
experimenting with the Impressionist style. Soon after, Northern
California artists also began to adopt the style, first in San
Francisco and later in artist colonies formed in Monterey, Carmel
and other places outside the city after much of it was destroyed in
the earthquake and fires of 1906.
</P>
<P>
   Like the French Impressionists, the Californians used bold new
pigments, large, contrasting blocks of light and shadow, and broken
brush &UR;  &LR; strokes that sometimes only hinted at objects. And like the
French, they weren't always appreciated by the art establishment.
These artists largely shunned figurative and studio painting,
preferring instead to carry their easels outside in the ``plein
air'' fashion and paint the landscapes and seascapes around them.
</P>
<P>
   The artists ``sought to capture a fleeting moment of specific
natural light,'' said Jean Stern, executive director of the Irvine
Museum. ``The clear and intense light appears often in these
paintings. It defined the landscape. The biblical analogy of light
as the creative instrument is appropriate. Without it, and the
divine energy it represented, the land would not exist.''
</P>
<P>
   A stirring spirituality permeates many of the works and
testifies to the artists' faith not only in God but in the sheer
grandeur of nature. The German-born painter William Wendt is
probably best known for such ``artistic moralism.'' A founding
member of the Laguna Beach Art Association in 1918, he became known
for his depictions of rugged coastal hills, often basking in the
warm glow of sunset. Even his titles, like ``The Silent Summer Sea,
1915'' and ``There Is No Solitude, Even in Nature, 1906,'' reveal a
certain religious poetry.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known, best-loved and probably the best artist of the
school was a native Californian, Guy Rose, who spent eight years at
Giverny, though he probably never painted with Monet. Traveling up
and down California, he perfected the feathery brush strokes of
early Impressionism, incorporating delicate purples, blues and
pinks. Like Monet, he often did serial paintings of the same scene
at different times of day. With six works in the show, he is its
most represented artist. His ``Laguna Eucalyptus, 1916'' and
``Point Lobos, 1918'' are among the exhibition's highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Another notable artist in the show is Granville Redmond, who
could not hear or speak and who suffered bouts of depression. He
preferred the moody, tonalist paintings seen in his dark yet
intensely spiritual ``Nocturne,'' but he knew that wealthy patrons
wanted his sunny trademark panoramas of poppy fields below
snow-covered mountains, exemplified in the mural-like ``California
Landscape With Flowers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
