<HEADER>
A4177 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRVINE-MUSEUM-$ADV21-     06-17 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRVINE-MUSEUM-$ADV21-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: With Flowers.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The show also includes works by the Austrian-born Franz
Bischoff, known for delicate floral paintings and vases as well as
landscapes; the Hungarian-born Maurice Braun, who painted the
burnt-sienna canyons of San Diego; John Gamble, a Santa Barbara
resident who captured the intense purple of the lupines that
covered the valleys, and Anna Hills, Joseph Kleitsch, Joseph
Raphael, Arthur Rider, Elmer Wachtel and his wife, the
watercolorist Marion Kavanagh Wachtel. (The exhibition also
includes a smaller showing of California Impressionist paintings
from the collections of Paul and Kathy Bagley and Thomas and
Barbara Stiles, which closes on July 5.)
</P>
<P>
   Six of the artists were National Academy members, and at least
two paintings in the show _ Paul Dougherty's ``Twisted Ledge'' and
Wendt's haunting ``There Is No Solitude'' _ were exhibited at the
academy early this century. ``It's like a homecoming for these
artists, though most people here have never heard of them,'' said
David Dearinger, the academy's chief curator (the show's guest
curator is William Gerdts). Dearinger said that a ``certain East
Coast snobbism'' may have kept California Impressionism from
gaining a popular foothold in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Smith agreed. ``Easterners don't think we can do anything
out here in California,'' she said by telephone from her home, in
San Juan Capistrano. ``But the East Coast doesn't have the light,
or the geography.'' Still, she credited one group of Easterners,
the 19th-century Hudson River School, with being the first
environmental painters. ``They painted to protest the Industrial
Revolution and destruction of the land,'' she said, ``just like the
Californians after them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Smith is a daughter of perhaps Orange County's most famous
family (along with their friends, the Richard Nixons). In 1957 she
succeeded her mother, Athalie Richardson Irvine Clarke, as a
director of Irvine Co., which was set up to manage and develop the
family's sprawling livestock and produce ranch. For 25 years she
clashed with other directors over the company's future and its
plans to convert the ranch into a city. She pushed for responsible
development of the ranch, insisting on a master plan that included
preservation of natural areas. And she fought to donate 1,000 acres
to build the University of California, Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, after a nine-year lawsuit, Mrs. Smith received $257
million for her interests in the company. She used some of that
money to start her Impressionist collection and the Irvine Museum,
which opened in January 1993; she also owns a gallery in Laguna
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Her influence lingers. Last year, Irvine Co. and the Nature
Conservancy joined to preserve 17,000 acres of endangered coastal
sage scrub. ``Some of these paintings might well have been painted
on that land,'' Mrs. Smith said. ``The artists would be very
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBIT NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ALL THINGS BRIGHT AND BEAUTIFUL: CALIFORNIA IMPRESSIONIST
PAINTING FROM THE IRVINE MUSEUM'
</P>
<P>
   At the National Academy Museum, 1083 5th Ave., at 89th Street,
through July 5. Accompanied by the much smaller `California
Impressionist Paintings From the Collections of Mr. and Mrs. Paul
Bagley and Mr. and Mrs. Thomas Stiles,' which closes on July 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
