<HEADLINE>
HEY, LIZARD BREATH!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA DAVIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Godzilla'' has been universally trashed by critics, so there
must be something wrong with me. I liked it.
</P>
<P>
   I consider myself somewhat of a summer movie connoisseur _ I'm
still very fond of that Steven Seagal movie on the submarine, where
Tommy Lee Jones gets a butcher knife stuck in his head _ and
``Godzilla'' is a darn fine summer movie.
</P>
<P>
   It wastes no time on character development or plot coherence.
But it's so obviously goofing on itself that you don't mind. On the
Summer Movie Scale, ``Godzilla'' is much better than ``Twister''
and more fun than ``Independence Day,'' but not as cool as ``Men in
Black.''
</P>
<P>
   And hey, Godzilla can sink a boat 20 times faster than an
iceberg can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla'' riffs on lots of other movies, besides its
too-obvious similarities to ``Aliens'' and ``Jurassic Park.''
(Let's face it: Godzilla is basically a velociraptor on steroids.)
There are nods to:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Usual Suspects'' (a hospital-bed interview with the sole
survivor of a boat catastrophe);
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaws'' (''We need bigger guns,'' says a soldier after seeing
the big lizard, just as Roy Scheider said, ``We need a bigger
boat,'' after seeing the big shark);
</P>
<P>
   ``Red October'' (an underwater submarine-torpedo chase);
</P>
<P>
   The classic Hitchcock movie ``Foreign Correspondent'' (crowd
scene with black umbrellas);
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Alone'' (can't tell you; would give away too much of the
plot).
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla'' has plenty of other inside jokes. The most obvious
is New York Mayor Ebert _ a portly gray-haired guy in glasses _ who
disagrees constantly with his thin, balding assistant, Gene. Even
funnier: Keep an eye out for ``Barney'' playing on a TV set as that
other giant mutated lizard cruises by in the background.
</P>
<P>
   A BAD SEIN: People are complaining that the final ``Seinfeld''
was a letdown. But should we really be surprised that the grand
finale of a show about nothing would be ... nothing special?
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
