<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4182 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-HOME-BOS &LR;      06-17 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-HOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICTED AU PAIR FLIES TO ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a departure as dramatic as her arrival in the public
realm Louise Woodward left the United States Wednesday for the
first time since her arrest last year, a squad of police officers
guarding every step as she boarded a first-class flight to England.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day a federal judge temporarily barred Woodward
from spending any profits she might earn by selling her story. The
ruling _ the first step in a civil suit against Woodward, convicted
of killing 8-month-old Matthew Eappen _ signaled the continuation
of a legal epic that is scheduled to last at least through the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   But Woodward, 20, was legally free to leave. Her criminal case
complete, a $4,301 one-way plane ticket in hand, Woodward walked
from her temporary home in Marblehead and said goodbye to her
criminal attorneys for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is relieved and pleased to be going home,'' said her
former attorney Andrew Good, as Woodward disappeared into a
first-class lounge inside the British Airways terminal at Logan
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The departure marked the end of several days of chaos for both
Woodward and her former employers, Deborah and Sunil Eappen.
</P>
<P>
   Four months after both sides appealed Woodward's murder
conviction, the state's highest court on Tuesday upheld Judge
Hiller B. Zobel's decision to reduce Woodward's second-degree
murder conviction to manslaughter and free her after 279 days in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by the Supreme Judicial Court, however, sharply
criticized Zobel for several key moves _ including his decision at
trial to remove manslaughter from among the jury's options. A
dissenting opinion also lambasted Zobel for appearing too
sympathetic toward the former au pair and imposing a lenient
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But the SJC opinion let Woodward's criminal conviction stand
without ordering a new sentence. It also allowed her to leave
Massachusetts, where she had remained involuntarily during the
appeals process at the demand of the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was getting ready to go to college when this happened,''
said Harvey Silverglate, another former member of the Woodward
defense team. ``She very much wants to return home.''
</P>
<P>
   The SJC ruling had another important effect: it prompted the
Eappen family to file a civil suit they had prepared in advance
against Woodward in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens _ who supported Middlesex County prosecutors'
decision to appeal the verdict and who urged the court to return
their former babysitter to prison for the murder of their youngest
son _ filed the suit just 78 minutes after the SJC decision was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; They want $75,000 in compensatory damages _ the minimum
required for a civil case filed in federal court _ as well as
unspecified punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also seeks to bar Woodward from ever enjoying profits
she could earn by selling her story of the murder trial. A trial
date inthe civil case has been set for Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in Wednesday's hearing in federal court was an
immediate ban on Woodward's ability to sell her story in the United
States and spend the profits. &UR;  &LR; Judge William G. Young granted the
request, imposing a temporary, 12-day ban that also requires
Woodward to notify the court if she sells her story.
</P>
<P>
   Young said he'll revisit the issue June 29 after he studies a
1995 SJC ruling in the case of Katherine A. Power, a fugitive who
admitted she participated in a bank robbery in September 1970 that
left a Boston police officer dead.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the court ruled, a judge properly banned Power
from selling the story of her crime for profit. The judge made the
ban against Power a condition of her probation.
</P>
<P>
   Young's temporary ban, which lawyers for the Eappens say they
are already seeking to extend, won't block Woodward from writing a
book or selling movie rights; it simply forbids her from spending
the profits. The Eappens say that money should be kept in escrow
should they win their civil suit.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward ``doesn't have a constitutional right to get any money
from that,'' said an attorney for the Eappens, Frederic L. Ellis.
``It would be kind of like O.J. Simpson saying, `I'm going to write
a book and make $10 million, and I'm not going to give any of that
to the Goldmans.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens have already established a foundation to prevent
child abuse in their son's name. They say any judgment against
Woodward will be deposited there, their lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling Wednesday, Judge Young said he believed there was
a ``reasonable likelihood'' that the Eappens can win their first
claim in the civil lawsuit _ that Woodward caused Matthew's death
through ``willful, wanton or reckless conduct.'' Her manslaughter
conviction can be used as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   One of Woodward's attorneys, Anthony Doniger, argued that the
order unfairly infringed on Woodward's free speech rights, since
the attorneys for the Eappens have targeted money she might make by
telling her story.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not seeking to restrain her other assets,'' he said.
``Instead, they're chilling her First Amendment rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, at least, Woodward showed little interest in
exercising her freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   After slipping from the house in Marblehead where she has lived
since late March, Woodward was whisked to the airport in a red
minivan with tinted windows. Police escorts, lights flashing, both
led and trailed her car. A news helicopter hovered overhead.
</P>
<P>
   At Logan, Woodward emerged from the van, her hair down, dressed
in a black pants suit. She kept her eyes trained straight ahead and
ignored questions shouted by reporters and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by seven state troopers, Woodward then swept past
throngs of economy-class passengers waiting in line and heading
straight to the British Airways first-class lounge, complete with a
mini bar. She waited there until boarding her 5:30 p.m. flight.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's one-way ticket was for a first-class seat equipped
with eight movie channels and a VCR, airport officials said. The
special section, sealed off from all but 13 other passengers, also
shielded her from the press.
</P>
<P>
   Under a federal law that prohibits foreigners convicted of
felonies from living in or returning to the United States, Woodward
would have to apply to the government if she wanted to board a
flight back to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Although the US Immigration and Naturalization Service has not
yet determined whether Woodward would fall under the ban,
immigration experts said it would be highly unusual for a
manslaughter convict to be allowed to return.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``The elements of her conviction would be reviewed to see if
it was a crime of violence and if she should be admitted to the
country,'' said William Strassberger, an INS spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Woodward would want to return to the United States,
where she &UR;  &LR; has by turns been a prisoner, a celebrity and a
lightning rod for public opinion, remained in doubt. She did not,
according to her attorney, ``know what the future will hold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's only 20,'' Good said. ``This won't last forever as an
issue in her life. She'll outlive it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4185 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LADN-BUDGET &LR;      06-17 0241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Thursday, June 18 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LA-PLANE-CRASH (Los Angeles) _ Pilots of small planes, including
the one that crashed into a home this week, can take off and land
without anyone checking whether they are qualified, according to
airport and federal officials. No one in control towers asks pilots
for their rating, and the airport doesn't either. By Jesse
Hiestand. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-QUEST (Los Angeles) _ Walt Disney Co., aiming to lure the
elusive teen-age crowd with interactive thrill rides, rolls out its
newest franchise this week with its DisneyQuest indoor theme park
in Florida. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   NORDSTROM-BEANIE (Los Angeles) _ This morning, when employees of
Nordstrom's department store in Woodland Hills arrived at work, 200
people were waiting out front to get a shot at the newest shipment
of beanie babies. According to some employees, people had been
lined up since 2 a.m. because the shipment included four models
that have been ``retired'' by Ty Co., the doll's makers. By Enrique
Rivero. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
