<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-ETHNIC-STUDIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA REGENT TO EXAMINE ETHNIC STUDIES
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By FRANK BRUNI     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The University of California regent who led the
effort to eliminate affirmative action at the state's public
universities expressed serious qualms Wednesday about ethnic
studies programs and suggested that he might try to curtail them.
</P>
<P>
   The regent, Ward Connerly, said that in the next two months he
would review the programs to verify his suspicion that they in
effect promoted ``self-imposed segregation'' on California's
campuses and existed in part to coddle members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, who is black, declined to speculate about what would
happen after his review. But his questions about ethnic studies
seemed certain to stoke the outrage of many faculty members and
students angry about declines this year in admissions of black and
Hispanic students to the University of California's most selective
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly's remarks also illustrated the degree to which many
liberal programs in education, from racial preferences to bilingual
teaching, are coming under fresh scrutiny in California.
</P>
<P>
   Several faculty members at the University of California at
Berkeley said Wednesday that Connerly's review of ethnic studies
represented the latest, but probably not the last, assault on
diversity both at and beyond the state's universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time when the state has come to believe that
immigrants _ particularly Chicanos _ and African-Americans
represent some drain on the body politic,'' William Banks, a
professor in the African-American Studies department at Berkeley,
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Referring specifically to Connerly's challenge of ethnic
studies, Banks added: ``He has concluded that people are happy with
the drop in ethnic enrollments and, hey, while the animal's
bleeding, let's put another stake in its leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Connerly said he was concerned that ethnic studies served as a
divisive force, catering to the members of a given ethnic group and
stressing that group's differences from the rest of society. He
also questioned whether the purpose of the classes was truly
academic, or whether they were exercises in racial and ethnic
pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this something people can learn from their parents, at
home, without the taxpayers paying for it?'' Connerly asked in a
telephone interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know whether they have academic value or whether
they were created largely because of political pressures that came
about in the 1970s and 1980s, when black nationalism was taking
hold,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly was a leader two years ago in the successful campaign
for the statewide initiative that banned affirmative action in
public employment and university admissions.
</P>
<P>
   He first expressed his reservations about ethnic studies, which
include African-American, Hispanic, Asian-American and
Native-American programs, in an interview on Tuesday with the
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   He said Wednesday he did not immediately plan to share his
concerns formally with the other members of the Board of Regents,
which sets policy for the University of California system. But he
said that if his investigation confirmed his qualms and he could
not get faculty members to change the programs on their own, he
would involve the other regents.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly also said that he wanted the regents to investigate the
use of university funds for special racial or ethnic graduation
ceremonies at University of California campuses. Connerly said he
opposed this practice and would ask the regents to discuss it when
they meet on Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these things, I believe, Balkanize my state,'' Connerly
said.
</P>
<P>
   But several professors said that courses offered under the
banner of ethnic studies were no more or less exclusionary or
political than courses in, say, French or Jewish history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are only black studies divisive?'' Troy Duster, a black
professor of sociology at Berkeley, asked. ``That's distorted
political logic.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
