<HEADER>
A4189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECONSCENE-NYT &LR;      06-17 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: REMEDY FOR JAPAN'S ECONOMY IS INFLATION
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Japan slipping into recession and the yen sagging to an
eight-year low, the Clinton administration has finally intervened
to prop up the Japanese currency. No one is saying that the
intervention is more than a palliative. One way or another Japan
must jump-start its long-sputtering economy.
</P>
<P>
   But how? Traditional monetary policy plainly hasn't worked.
Creditworthy Japanese companies can already borrow at a
ridiculously low 1 percent interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   And fiscal policy hasn't done much better. While the stimulus
packages of the last few years have made a difference, consumers
have refused to keep buying after the spigot has been shut off.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krugman, an economist at MIT, argues that the time has come
for Japan to inflate its way out of the problem. He concedes that
asking the Bank of Japan to ``credibly promise to be
irresponsible'' smacks of desperation, but adds that desperate
measures may be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Japan, a pro-inflation stance is no longer unthinkable.
While Japan has been deeply conservative on financial matters, Gary
Saxonhouse, an economist at the University of Michigan, notes that
its newly independent central bank is not averse to radical
thinking. ``At least one widely respected member of their
equivalent of the Fed's Open Market Committee has publicly
supported reflation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese economy is barely bigger than it was in 1990. Its
long period of stagnation has brought myriad problems to the
surface _ notably that most banks would be insolvent if their
holdings of stocks and real estate were valued at market prices.
Given the failure of both easy monetary policy and fiscal stimulus
to make a lasting difference in the economy, conventional wisdom
points to free-market reforms as the key to Japan's recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Few dispute the potential payoff. But, at best, progress will be
slow: cleaning up the clubby banking system, for example, would
take years _ even if the political establishment allowed insolvent
ones to close their doors. And Krugman, who made a splash a few
years ago by comparing Asia's economic miracle to the mixed
blessings of Soviet industrialization, wonders if it is really
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   By his analysis, Japan is caught in a Keynesian ``liquidity
trap,'' not very different from the one that bedeviled America in
the early 1930s. Aging Japanese households are inclined to save
their money. And with the price of everything from washing machines
to office towers falling, earning 1/2 percent interest on savings
accounts still looks like a better route to wealth than buying
housing or autos.
</P>
<P>
   The way out is to convince ordinary Japanese that inflation is
on the horizon, driving them out of cash and into new Toyotas. To
manage this, Krugman wants the central bank to assert that it will
pump whatever amount of money is necessary to generate inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The standard approach under modern monetary policy would be to
increase banks' reserves, and hence the amount they can lend, by
buying government bonds with cash. But nobody in Japan wants to
borrow in the current deflationary climate. ``You can't make a
liquidity trap go away by throwing in more money,'' argued William
Dudley, the chief U.S. economist at Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   What might work, suggests Dudley, is a hybrid of fiscal and
monetary stimulus _ say, a big temporary tax cut, plus a firm
commitment by the Bank of Japan to keep interest rates near zero
even as prices rose. With expectations turned from deflation to
inflation, households would have a new reason to spend.
</P>
<P>
   The catch, says Albert Fishlow, an economist at the Council on
Foreign Relations, is that Japanese households have another way to
protect their assets against inflation. Thanks, ironically, to
pressure from Washington to open their capital markets, the
Japanese are now free to buy dollars or marks. So one plausible
consequence of a shift to expectations of inflation would be a rush
to foreign investments, which would weaken the yen still more.
</P>
<P>
   A weaker yen would make Japan's goods even more competitive in
world markets than they are now _ not necessarily a bad result for
Japan, which has always used export growth to end recessions. But
it would trigger protectionist sentiment in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, it would make goods from China, Indonesia,
Thailand and Indonesia less competitive in the huge Japanese
market, perhaps leading to another round of currency depreciation.
Indeed, much of the global anxiety over the recent fall of the yen
is about its impact on the rest of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   So even if desperate measures work for Japan, they might
backfire for its ailing Asian trade partners. If only as a matter
of prudence, then, counsels Fishlow, ``we ought to be focusing on
how the rest of Asia can make an economic comeback without help
from Japan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
