<HEADER>
A4191 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-ART-     06-17 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO BILL KILLED ON PROCEDURAL VOTES IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With analysis, CONGRESS-TOBACCO-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Wednesday jettisoned broad
legislation intended to curb smoking by teen-agers, the most
ambitious and contentious measure before Congress, and left almost
no hope it could be revived this year.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would have raised the price of cigarettes by
$1.10 a pack, had been debated on the Senate floor for a month. It
was set aside when supporters, mostly Democrats, could not get the
60 votes needed to clear two procedural hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats promised to bring the matter up again at every
opportunity this year, but they conceded that they had little
chance of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that the final vote on this bill occurs on election
day,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Republican opponents of the bill argued that after senators
approved amendments that cut taxes and added anti-drug provisions,
it was not primarily an anti-smoking measure but a tax-and-spend
bill. ``This is a massive tax on low-income Americans, and it is
used to proliferate the bureaucracy of this government,'' declared
Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John McCain, the maverick Republican from Arizona who
was the bill's chief sponsor, had a different view. ``This bill is
not about taxes,'' he told the Senate just before the votes. ``It's
about whether we're going to allow the death march of 418,000
Americans a year who die early from tobacco-related disease and do
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton decried the Senate vote and promised to
continue fighting for passage of comprehensive tobacco legislation.
And he made it clear that he would use the rejection for partisan
purposes in the autumn congressional campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, I am very disappointed that a Republican
minority blocked the legislation from being voted on,'' Clinton
said in an impromptu appearance in the White House briefing room on
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been working for three years now to protect our
children from the dangers of tobacco,'' he added. ``I want the
tobacco lobby and its allies on Capitol Hill to know that from my
point of view, this battle is far from over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader, said the
Senate was so dividedon the tobacco issue that it is impossible to
produce a bill that would command the 60 votes needed to pass it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't figure out a way to get a bill that would be
credible,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   On the crucial vote, 57 senators voted to cut off debate and
move to a final vote, a procedure called cloture. But that was
three votes shy of the 60 votes necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three Democrats and 14 Republicans voted in favor of
cloture. Forty Republicans and two Democrats from tobacco states,
Wendell Ford of Kentucky and Charles Robb of Virginia, voted
against cloture.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Senate dealt the final blow by voting to send the bill
back to the Commerce Committee so that violations of budget rules
could be repaired. It would have required 60 votes to prevent this
from happening, and the supporters fell seven votes short.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in the House of Representatives have been
waiting to see what happened in the Senate before they moved on a
tobacco bill. They are opposed to ambitious legislation like the
Senate bill. However, the feeling in the House on Wednesday night
was that the leaders might still try to pass a less comprehensive
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to raising the price of cigarettes over the next
five years, the Senate measure would have given the government new
authority to regulate tobacco advertising and marketing and imposed
stiff penalties on cigarette makers if the rate of teen-age smoking
did not fall to specified levels.
</P>
<P>
   But amendments added in the Senate in the last few weeks would
have given a tax break to married couples and established new
programs against drug abuse. These measures will die with the
overall bill, though they might be added to other legislation
before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was prompted to consider the tobacco bill by the
settlement signed a year ago this Saturday by the major tobacco
companies and the attorneys general from 40 states. Under the
agreement, the industry would have paid $368.5 billion over the
next 25 years and agreed to restraints on tobacco advertising. In
return, they would have been given immunity from most lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement required congressional action before it could go
into effect. Without a federal law, the states are expected to
press their multibillion-dollar legal claims against the tobacco
companies. Many individuals may also go to court now, especially in
light of the decision of a jury in Florida last week to find the
Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. liable for a smoker's death.
</P>
<P>
   When the bill came out of McCain's committee in April on a
19-to-1 bipartisan vote, its prospects for approval seemed good.
But the tobacco companies rebelled and began a national advertising
campaign against the bill said to cost tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's supporters said that these ads turned the tide, much
as ads by insurance companies were held responsible for defeating
President Clinton's health-care plan in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco companies have made a very wise investment, and
they have won,'' McCain said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
