<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Holy Writings, Sacred Text''
</P>
<P>
   By John Barton
</P>
<P>
   Westminster John Knox Press, $18
</P>
<P>
   The Bible, as some have pointed out, did not fall from a clear
blue sky in a black leather binding and King James English. John
Barton's argument is that even the more scholarly views of why the
Bible includes what it does, and not something else, bear
re-examination.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional view is that various Christian writings
gradually emerged and were accorded authority, and then lines were
drawn: Revelation is in, and the Epistle of Barnabas is not. But
the Oxford University professor argues that what could be called
the core New Testament becomes obvious, and obviously important,
almost immediately _ but how the Christians (and Jews) of ancient
times understood the ideas of ``Scripture'' and ``canon,'' and how
they used the writings in those categories, are different questions
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Barton's views are clearly left of center, although he
says that his conclusions ``do not seem to me to serve either a
conservative or a liberal agenda. ... I nowhere say how Scripture
should be regarded; only how it was in fact regarded at various
points in the past.'' Still, ``Holy Writings, Sacred Text''
contains some fascinating ideas for those interested in a scholarly
study of the topic. _ Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
