u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONFERENCE-AD-COLUMN-     06-17 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFERENCE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: RESHAPING PERCEPTIONS OF ADVERTISING
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Advertising Federation is undertaking what is
intended to be a major multiyear communications initiative to
promote and demonstrate the importance of advertising to marketers
and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the initiative are to be outlined at the federation's
1998 American Advertising Conference in Minneapolis, which begins
Thursday and continues through Sunday. Plans call for the program,
known as ``Advertising: A New Brand of Business,'' to be introduced
in phases; steps would include a survey assessing attitudes about
advertising, a campaign aimed at corporate executives and even a
speakers' bureau to place advertising topics on the agendas of
business conferences.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative comes as agencies are fighting efforts by
management consulting companies to usurp their functions by
offering advertisers brand and marketing strategy services. The
consultants have met with some success in part because they are
perceived as providing more strategic, ``big picture'' advice than
agencies do.
</P>
<P>
   Previous efforts to pitch advertising have been concentrated on
such issues as the value of building brands or sustained spending
on campaigns. This time, however, the federation _ which represents
marketers, agencies and media companies _ wants to focus on
reshaping perceptions about advertising.
</P>
<P>
   If as the old slogan goes, orange juice isn't just for breakfast
anymore, the federation will proclaim that advertising isn't just
clever commercials, amusing animated spokescharacters and punchy
promotions. Rather, the initiative is intended to present
advertising as a fundamental strategic discipline _ echoing what
the management consultants assert _ and agencies as the
professionals that are most expert in that field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've let advertising become too narrowly defined as only the
output,'' said Wally Snyder, president and chief executive of the
federation. ``There's nothing wrong with that, but as a result
we're now viewed by some clients as vendors when we're more than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, who is based in Washington, offered a preview of the
initiative in an interview last week during a visit to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thrust will be to redefine advertising in the minds of
clients at the highest levels,'' Snyder said. ``Our goal is for
them to see advertising as a discipline that is underpinned with
strategic capabilities and broader in terms of the communications
tools at its disposal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we want to let them know that we have an understanding of
the consumer,'' he added, ``and can connect them with consumers in
the most favorable communications environments'' _ particularly in
media like the Internet that enable marketers to better direct
sales messages at specific consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   The federation is forming a steering committee to oversee the
initiative. There will be 27 members, drawn from the ranks of
advertisers, agencies and the media.
</P>
<P>
   Among those members are: Wilder Baker, chairman and chief
executive at Warwick Baker O'Neill; Myer Berlow, senior vice
president for interactive marketing at AOL Networks, a unit of
America Online; Samuel Chisholm, president and chief executive at
Chisholm-Mingo Group; Robert Lachky, vice president for brand
management at Anheuser-Busch Inc.; Arthur Liebler, vice president
for marketing at Chrysler Corp., and David Steward, president and
chief executive at TV Guide magazine, which News Corp. is selling
to United Video Satellite Guide.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the committee will be one of the heaviest
hitters in clientdom: Philip Guarascio, vice president and general
manager for marketing and advertising at the North American
operations of General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks prepared for delivery at the conference, Guarascio
declared, ``We _ the whole advertising profession _ are guilty of
neglecting ourselves and of letting advertising's `brand image' and
identity deteriorate.'' He added, ``And now we are reaping what
we've been sowing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to do, always and unceasingly, is dramatize to
our target audience the value of advertising,'' Guarascio
continued. ``Why should there be any doubt about the power of
advertising to build brands and deliver a return on investment? And
yet there is doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why, Guarascio said, the federation needs its members to
help ``build the new, redefined brand of advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial step will be the survey to gauge attitudes about
advertising, which the research firm of Erdos &AMP; Morgan will conduct
among corporate leaders. Results are to be presented in November.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Snyder said, the steering committee will begin work
on the ad campaign, which will be directed at ``chief executives,
chief financial officers, board members and other `influencers'''
who help determine corporate behavior. The timetable calls for the
campaign to be introduced in 1999, perhaps at the federation's next
American Advertising Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if federation member agencies would be preferred in a
review to select a shop to create the campaign, Snyder smiled and
replied, ``We have a lot of options with our members.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
