<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-CONCUSSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY DETAILS THREAT TO ATHLETES FROM HEART BLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six-year-old Jacob Watt, an Illinois Little Leaguer, became the
latest victim on June 6. Matthew Messing, a 16-year-old hockey
player from Massachusetts died from it in 1995. St. Louis Blues
hockey captain Chris Pronger last month was a near-miss.
</P>
<P>
   Now Boston researchers have nailed down the cause of commotio
cordis, a medical term that means ``concussion of the heart.'' They
also showed that preventive measures, such as softer baseballs for
younger players, do work.
</P>
<P>
   In a report published Thursday, Dr. Mark S. Link of New England
Medical Center and his colleagues demonstrated in anesthetized pigs
that a blow to the chest of only moderate force can stop the heart
cold if it occurs within a tiny window of time _ 15/1,000ths of a
second _ when the heart is suspended between beats, recharging
itself to prepare for the next beat.
</P>
<P>
   The entire cycle of a heartbeat lasts only about one second when
the heart rate is 60 beats per minute. The vulnerable period, Link
noted, only lasts about 1/100th of the entire cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The research resolved a mystery about the cause of death from
commotio cordis. It does not result from physical damage to the
heart, rupture of the muscle, or bleeding, which is why it has been
impossible to document in autopsies. It is caused by disruption of
electrical activity in the heart muscle during the instant before
the tissue is fully recharged and ready to contract again.
</P>
<P>
   Commotio cordis is almost invariably fatal. ``There are six
recorded cases of survival of commotio cordis over the last 10
years,'' Link said. ``Before that, people didn't recognize this as
an entity. And even now it's not that well recognized, so we don't
know how often it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, Dr. Barry J. Maron of Minneapolis Heart
Institute, a collaborator in the new study, has counted 70 cases of
commotio cordis in this country _ 45 of them in the three years
since he published an article in the New England Journal of
Medicine bringing the phenomenon to wider attention. The same
journal published the new study in its current edition.
</P>
<P>
   Commotio cordis almost always involves children and adolescents
under age 17, when the chest wall is thinner and more pliable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be this is more common than we think,'' Link said.
``These are often not reported on.''
</P>
<P>
   A report by the US Product Safety Commission counted 168,000
emergency room visits due to baseball-related injuries in 1996. Of
those, 68 involved deaths, and 38 were caused by baseball blows to
the chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This suggests that commotio cordis is the most common cause of
deaths in baseball,'' said Link, whose five-year-old son and
seven-year-old daughter play Little League. ``But it's still
uncommon, and certainly it's no reason not to play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronger's rare luck in surviving the disorder may have stemmed
from a blow that occurred just slightly outside the 15- millisecond
time frame, Link said, judging from the two animals out of 66 in
the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   If a blow occurs at a different point in the cycle, the
reesarchers found, it can cause a temporary condition called
``complete heart block,'' which is not fatal but can cause a
drastically slowed heart rate and fainting.
</P>
<P>
   In the pig experiments, the team showed that softer ``safety
balls,'' developed to minimize head trauma among Little Leaguers,
sharply reduced the risk of commotio cordis, even when the animals
received the blow during the vulnerable time frame.
</P>
<P>
   Using the softest safety balls, designed for children under age
eight, only two of 26 pigs suffered commotio cordis after being
struck during the vulnerable time window. A regulation baseball
caused the heart to stop eight out of 23 times.
</P>
<P>
   Safety balls of two intermediate degrees of softness, marketed
for children between ages eight and 10 or 11 to 13, seemed somewhat
safer than regulation balls, but the differences were not
statistically significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another approach to prevention is the use of chest
protectors,'' said Dr. Gregory D. Curfman, a New England Journal
editor, in an editorial accompanying the new study. ``The shoulder
pads worn by hockey and lacrosse players are inadequate to protect
the chest, particularly when the arms are raised, and baseball
players generally wear no chest protectors at all while batting.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the journal rarely publishes animal studies, Curfman
said the article's value ``will be to raise awareness about
commodio cordis, demystify its cause, and educate us about the
recognition and prevention of this tragic phenomenon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
