<HEADER>
A4206 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-CHINA-MISSILE-30     06-17 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CHINA-MISSILE-305&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE SUDDENLY IMPROVED ROCKET LAUNCHES, EXPERT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Mo., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A simple, one-page chart presented Wednesday
captured the essence of Congress' inquiry into whether sensitive
U.S. space technology was illicitly slipped to Chinese rocket
scientists.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The chart, offered at a House hearing by Henry Sokolski, who was
the Pentagon's top expert monitoring proliferation during the Bush
administration, showed that between 1990 and 1996, one in four
Chinese rockets carrying commercial satellites blew up. But since
1996, the Chinese have had a perfect record: 10 consecutive
successful launches.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``No failures in the past 10 launches,'' Sokolski mulled aloud.
``Is that a coincidence or is it the result of cumulative
technology transfers?''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and witnesses voiced diverse opinions in response to
Sokolski's rhetorical question, but offered no definitive answers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet the timing of China's new-found success in launching
multimillion-dollar satellites into orbit was striking. It was in
mid-1996 that two U.S. satellite makers _ Loral Space &AMP;
Communications and Hughes Electronics _ helped Chinese engineers
figure out why a satellite launching failed in February 1996. The
Justice Department is conducting a criminal inquiry to determine
whether the two companies breached U.S. national security. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The reliability of Chinese rockets is important because the
missiles that send U.S. communications satellites into orbit are
very similar to the Chinese missiles that carry nuclear warheads.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A rare joint hearing of two committees, International Relations
and National Security, Wednesday opened the House's inquiry into
this issue as well as into whether the Clinton administration's
shift of satellite-licensing authority in 1996 to the Commerce
Department from the State Department loosened controls over
sensitive technology.  &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Partisan overtones hung over the hearing.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration's track record in this regard displays a
single-minded determination to evade sanctions and to ignore or
downplay national security concerns in the interest of exporting
sensitive U.S. technology in the name of `engagement' with China,''
said Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., who heads the National Security
Committee.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ike Skelton of Missouri, the ranking Democrat on the same
panel, responded, ``We need to get the facts first about matters
that affect the national security of this country.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wednesdy's hearing set the stage for what is expected to be a
volatile day Thursday, when senior State, Commerce and Defense
department officials will defend the administration's export
control policies in back-to-back House and Senate hearings.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the House is to vote Thursday to create a special
select committee that will lead the House inquiry into the China
accusations. Democrats grumble that existing House committees,
including the two that held Wednesday's hearing, are capable of
handling the broader inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   A report prepared by the House Democratic Policy Committee,
which will be made public Thursday, accuses House Republicans of
spending $17 million on 50 ``politically motivated'' investigations
since Republicans took control of the House in 1995.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's hearing, Sokolski, citing information on Chinese
rocket reliability obtained from a Singapore-based web site, Dragon
in Space, that tracks Chinese commercial satellite launches, said
he had no doubt that U.S. space technology that helped Beijing's
military arsenal had been transferred to China. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Joan Johnson-Freese, a professor of international security
studies at the Air War College at Maxwell Air Force Base in Alabama
said these assertions were based on ``half-facts that have been
distorted and sensationalized.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers immediately dismissed the professor as
naive. ``The blueprints for all these changes were not left under
their pillow by the tooth fairy,'' said Rep. Dana Rohrabacher,
R-Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
