u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRYARS-MUSIC-REVIEW-N     06-17 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRYARS-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DOCTOR OX': A CONCEPTUAL ARTIST'S OPERA
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ There is a religious group in the Middle East whose
members adhere strictly to their faith by giving the appearance of
following some other practice. A person may go regularly to church
or mosque, and perform all the usual devotions, while having
beliefs that run in another direction. There might be no way of
distinguishing such a person from the host of other worshipers, or
of telling how many, in a particular congregation, are mouthing the
prayers while thinking something else.
</P>
<P>
   Composers are generally more forthcoming about their belief
systems, and it is clear that the British composer Gavin Bryars is
maintaining his firm position as an outsider _ one who cherishes
John Cage, Erik Satie, Ferruccio Busoni and the parlor music of
three or four generations ago _ even though his music is now being
embraced by the mainstream culture. ``Doctor Ox's Experiment,''
which was given its first performance by English National Opera
here Monday night, is Doctor Bryars' Experiment: a conceptual
artist's opera, put together in a spirit of detachment and
disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   It has many of the qualities that a real opera would have.
Indeed, it exaggerates them. It is, for the most part, terribly
slow moving. It swallows its words. It has absurd characters, love
scenes and a war. It has arias, duets and choruses. It has pretty
much everything, and we know only that it is not a proper opera
because it is so boring.
</P>
<P>
   Blake Morrison's libretto, adapted from a novella by Jules
Verne, seems to have been meant for a different sort of piece:
sparky, witty, thoughtful. It offers good cues for musical drama in
its depiction of a sleepy Flemish village awakened when a mad
scientist releases gas into the local atmosphere. Bryars, though,
encases the first act and much of the second in music that does
what most of his music does: slowly glide, perpetually sag.
</P>
<P>
   It may do so rather beautifully, especially when it brings on
its two countertenor young lovers (David James and Ryland Angel)
and their sweethearts, or when one of the latter (Valdine Alderson)
gives the work its final benediction. But the beauty is drained as
far as possible of meaning. It is beauty forever on the point of
cloying.
</P>
<P>
   The production, by the film director Atom Egoyan, is largely in
moonlit slow motion, while allowing Bonaventura Bottone to make
Doctor Ox himself quick, lively and amiable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
