<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-BURNHAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDER TO LEAD RAYTHEON CO. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. Wednesday tapped an amateur rodeo cowboy _ the
first outsider in its history _ to take the reins of the giant
Lexington-based defense and technology firm.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel P. Burnham, 51, a top official at AlliedSignal Inc., will
join Raytheon as president and chief operating officer _ the
company's number two post _ on July 1. He will then be promoted to
chief executive officer on Dec. 1, when Dennis J. Picard steps
down, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Picard, who has worked at Raytheon for 45 years, intends to
remain chairman of the board of directors until sometime in 1999.
He has said he will stay as chairman for no more than another
year &UR;  &LR; after Burnham becomes CEO, but will leave earlier if he
believes the company is in good hands. When Picard, 65, is fully
retired, it is expected that the board will name Burnham as
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   A company steeped in tradition, Raytheon has had only four
leaders in its 76-year history _ all of whom were long-time
employees.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to search outside the company for the next
chief executive is a result of the dramatic changes that Raytheon
has undergone in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Once a mid-tier supplier of missiles and defense electronics,
Raytheon leapt to the elite ranks of the US defense industry last
year with its acquisitions of the defense businesses of Texas
Instruments Inc. and Hughes Electronics Corp..
</P>
<P>
   It is now the nation's No. 3 defense company, behind Boeing Co.
and Lockheed Martin Corp., with annual revenues of about $21
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But in the face of cutbacks in Pentagon spending, Raytheon has
also embarked on a strategy to convert defense technology into
business applications. As a result, it is a major provider of
commercial electronics, such as air traffic control systems and
marine radar. It also makes business jets and provides engineering
and construction services for power plants and other industrial
projects worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham, who is vice chairman of AlliedSignal, has the right mix
of experience to help Raytheon grow all of those businesses, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan is among the very few senior executives who actually
possess proven track records in both commercial and defense
industries, here at home and internationally,'' said Picard in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company hired an executive search firm to identify
candidates to succeed Picard, Raytheon said it approached Burnham
directly because of his reputation in the aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the guy we wanted. We went after him because his
background maps so well with our strategy,'' said Raytheon
spokesman Robert McWade.
</P>
<P>
   At AlliedSignal, a New Jersey conglomerate, Burnham is
responsible for six aerospace-related businesses with $8 billion in
annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of two internal candidates to succeed AlliedSignal
chairman and chief executive Lawrence Bossidy in April 2000, but
analysts said he probably was persuaded to join the larger Raytheon
because he was assured the top job.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham has run the aerospace unit _ AlliedSignal's largest _
since 1992. It supplies engines, avionics and electronic safety
systems to aircraft manufacturers worldwide, including Raytheon
Aircraft Co., Raytheon's Wichita-based subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   When he was promoted to vice chairman of Allied-Signal last
October, he was also tapped as the company's czar of productivity _
responsible for company-wide initiatives to boost efficiency and
root out manufacturing defects. Allied-Signal is considered to be a
global leader in productivity and it's expected that Burnham will
make a similar productivity push at Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham, who was not available for comment Wednesday, is known
for cutting costs. At a January 1991 AlliedSignal meeting, fresh
off a quarter of record earnings, he ordered that a plan be crafted
to cut overhead 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``My speech was `Congratulations. If we keep doing what we are
doing, we'll all be out of work in two years,' '' he said in an
October interview with Defense Week, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   At Raytheon, Burnham's challenge is to oversee the consolidation
of Raytheon's far-flung defense businesses, now that its
acquisition binge is over. He must also get the struggling
engineering business back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon said in January that it would cut more than 8 percent
of its work force, or 9,700 jobs, and shut 20 defense facilities
following the acquisitions. Those cuts, which included 1,000 jobs
from the engineering business, are expected to occur over the next
year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts praised Raytheon's choice, saying Burnham has what the
giant company needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the right person at the right place at the right time,''
said PaineWebber analyst Jack Modzelewski, who raised his rating on
Raytheon to ``buy'' from ``neutral.'' Raytheon's B shares rose 2
3/16 to 54 3/16 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham, who was born in a suburb of Detroit, has strong roots
in New England. His late parents were born and raised in Boston,
and as a child, he spent summers on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Xavier University in Cincinnati, Burnham
received an MBA from the University of New Hampshire. He also lived
in Framingham, Mass. for two years early in his career, when he
worked for RCA's computer systems division.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his four grown children live in the Boston area, so he
and his wife, Meg, are looking forward to relocating here, said an
AlliedSignal spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   His personal interests are wide-ranging. A student of medieval
literature, he is also a fan of modern fiction and auto racing. He
also loves horseback riding, and competes regularly in rodeos.
</P>
<P>
   Described by colleagues as bright and personable, Burnham is
renowned for his stellar vocabulary. ``He'll come up with these
off-the-cuff, $10 words that are unintentional _ they're not meant
to impress anybody,'' said Allied-Signal spokesman Mark Greenberg.
``He has a vocabulary you wouldn't expect to find in a business
executive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from Bloomberg News was used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
