<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERDI-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREENER LAWN AND A NEW SOUND TO VERDI
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``That's an $18 million lawn you are sitting on,''
Henry Stern, the New York City Commissioner of Parks and
Recreation, told the estimated crowd of 15,000 people who turned
out on Tuesday night for this summer's first free performance of
the Met in the Parks series on the Great Lawn in Central Park. ``So
be good to it. Don't step too hard. Don't leave anything on it.''
</P>
<P>
   And, truly, the newly renovated Great Lawn is something for New
Yorkers to treasure. Before the renovation, a heavy rain like that
on Monday night would have left the lawn a mud puddle for days. But
on Tuesday, for the Metropolitan Opera's concert performance of
Verdi's ``Trovatore,'' the thick grass was lush, green and
remarkably dry. Predictions of additional rain may have kept the
attendance down from what was expected. But only once, during Act
III, did a short shower threaten to halt the performance.
</P>
<P>
   Musically speaking, another renovation was unveiled. This year,
courtesy of a $100,000 grant, an improved sound system was tried
out. And with an in-house engineer from the Met controlling
balances, the quality of amplification was about as good as one
could expect at an outdoor classical music event. The sound was
surprisingly clear, warm and present without being overbearing.
</P>
<P>
   And it seemed to make a difference to the audience. Met in the
Parks performances are not occasions for intensely focused
listening. But the audience was noticeably quiet, especially during
the most reflective and subtle sections of Verdi's popular score.
</P>
<P>
   The soprano June Anderson, who scored a success in the role of
Leonora this spring at the Met, gave an affecting and vocally
radiant performance. The Russian mezzo-soprano Larissa Diadkova, so
impressive during the Kirov Opera Festival at the Met this spring,
performed her first Azucena, the Gypsy mother, a chilling,
blazingly sung account of a daunting role.
</P>
<P>
   More news was made by the brothers Armiliato, that is, Fabio,
the tenor and Met regular, and Marco, a conductor making his first
appearance with the company. This was the first time in the Met's
history that two brothers were performing together, said the Met's
general manager, Joseph Volpe, and their proud parents, he added,
had come from Genoa for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Fabio Armiliato gave an impassioned and involving, though not
always controlled, performance as Manrico. Marco Armiliato presided
over a poised, elegant rendition of the score, allowing much leeway
for expressive instrumental solos by the fine Met Orchestra
players. The baritone Haijing Fu as the Count di Luna and the
veteran bass Paul Plishka as Ferrando gave solid performances.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the Met's summer caravan troupe will present ``Il
Trovatore'' at Miller Field on Staten Island. Four performances
follow at parks in Brooklyn, the Bronx and New Jersey through July
3. The other opera the Met is taking to the parks, through July 2,
is Rossini's ``Barbieri di Siviglia,'' including a performance on
the Great Lawn on June 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
