<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: DID RUBIN SET BEAR TRAP FOR CURRENCY TRADERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also DOLLAR-YEN, JAPAN-ECONSCENE, MARKET.)  
(dc) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Thursday, Secretary of the Treasury Robert Rubin made
comments to Congress that currency traders took as a green light to
sell billions more yen, driving the currency down to near an
eight-year low.
</P>
<P>
   The academic but economically correct testimony was interpreted
as a declaration that the United States would not intervene in the
currency markets to support the weakening Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as the dust cleared from an initially successful
surprise intervention to support the yen, traders and analysts were
wondering if they had been set up for a fall by their
interpretation, even if it was wrong, of the treasury secretary's
sell signal. After all, Rubin did make his mark trading on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   His comments, they said, helped get more investors out on a limb
on their bet against the yen. That meant that they scrambled for
safety _ and to cut their losses _ much faster when Rubin
threatened to cut them off. And that panic selling is what helped
push the yen up 5.2 percent in one day against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Currency traders and analysts would not say that Rubin did this
on purpose. But they did agree that his remarks propelled the sharp
fall in the yen last Thursday and Monday and stretched investors,
making the snapback bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect of those remarks were to make the market more
susceptible,'' said John Lipsky, the chief economist at Chase
Manhattan Bank and long-time currency watcher. ``Certainly, there
will be speculation by market participants that they had been set
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Traders and analysts agreed that Wednesday's intervention, the
first to support the yen since 1992 and the first of any kind by
the United States since August 1995, was effective for a day. But
they expect the yen will resume its decline unless there are some
surprising changes of policy in Japan. Even after the rebound, the
yen is still down 16.9 percent against the dollar over the last
year and off 41 percent from its April 1995 high.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Fand, senior foreign exchange strategist at Bank Boston,
said that he saw speculators buying dollars Wednesday on the bet
that the intervention would not support the yen for long.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin agrees that intervention is not effective for long without
changes in policies that, in this case, support the yen. His
emphasis of that point last week led to the additional heavy yen
selling. New policies are necessary because only a change in
Japan's economic outlook _ the economy is now in a recession _ will
make Japan and the yen attractive to investors again.
</P>
<P>
   But taking convincing action immediately will be difficult
because there are elections in July and the Japanese government,
which has announced a long series of disappointing programs to
stimulate the economy, has little credibility in the foreign
exchange market. New promises of action made Wednesday, like
dealing with the mountain of bad bank debt, were generally
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a little worried,'' said Robert White, the treasurer of
Standard Chartered Bank. ``We have taken this step to intervene
with Japanese promises and the Japanese have been known to break
their promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting the lack of any new concrete actions by the Japanese and
Rubin's own distrust of intervention without policy changes, Lipsky
said the whole operation ``leaves the impression of an emergency
measure that would temporarily stave off significant market
instability.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first tests for the yen will come with the results
from this weekend's meeting of Japanese officials in Tokyo with
Lawrence Summers, the deputy treasury secretary, and William
McDonough, the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York,
through which the intervention was done. If there are no positive
surprises, more intervention might be needed to support the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Traders also said that they thought the intervention by the
Clinton administration was motivated by the recent threats from
China that a further decline in the yen would force the Chinese to
devalue their currency, setting off another round of devaluations
in Asia that would further destabilize the region economically.
</P>
<P>
   In timing Wednesday's buying of yen for dollars, it appeared
that the Treasury and the Federal Reserve were able to take
advantage of two tactics of intervention. First, whether
intentionally or not, they let the dollar rally far and fast and
left traders with the impression they would not get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Intervening in this circumstance, which has been called a bear
trap, can catch traders off guard, a key to intervention success.
Some traders said they had seen some speculating hedge funds piling
on their yen selling last week, which meant some faced the sharp
losses needed to force them to sell dollars and buy yen Wednesday.
But most hedge funds had been selling yen for some time so overall
they probably still have profits.
</P>
<P>
   The second tactic is pushing a currency in the direction it is
already going and the Treasury and the Fed were able to do this
because of the sudden rally of the yen Tuesday, as traders wondered
finally if something was up after the Treasury indicated Summers
would go to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Sargen, the global market strategist for J.P. Morgan's
private clients, doubts that Rubin tried to set up the market. ``He
risks losing his own credibility doing that,'' Sargen said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said that his comments last week ``snowballed on
him,'' accelerating the crisis. And Wednesday's move was an effort
to make clear ``that there is not a green light to go out there and
sell yen.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, Rubin proved he learned something else from
his Wall Street career: how to take advantage of mistakes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
