<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4219 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHITECTURE-FIGHT-TE     06-17 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-FIGHT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THIS A MATTER OF RIGHT OR MIGHT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's high noon in Texas. The gunfighters approach one another,
fingers twitching, eyes glinting in the sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   One stands up for all of the state's high-minded designers,
patrons and critics who consider architecture a form of progressive
art.
</P>
<P>
   The other represents entrepreneurs more concerned with popular
opinion, the bottom line and audience comfort level rather than
with critical opinion and artistic ideals.
</P>
<P>
   The first group is responsible for Texas buildings by Frank
Lloyd Wright, I.M. Pei, Louis Kahn, Philip Johnson, Richard Meier,
Tadao Ando, Ricardo Legorreta, Rafael Moneo, Renzo Piano and other
architects approved by a well-intended, international elite. Kahn,
for instance, designed the critically praised Kimbell Art Museum
and Johnson the Amon Carter Museum; Ando is working on a new home
for the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The latter group has brought us a number of buildings and urban
projects _ all, so far, in North Texas _ by David Schwarz. With
offices in Washington, D.C., and Fort Worth, Schwarz has played an
intrinsic role in the Bass family's redevelopment of much of
downtown Fort Worth. His first big, local project, though, was in
the medical district: the castlelike Cook Children's Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   More recent is Schwarz's Bass performance hall in Fort Worth.
Just announced is his winning proposal for a new sports arena for
the Dallas Stars hockey team and Mavericks basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Both the performance hall and the arena proposal declare
Schwarz's signature mix of historic styles with high-tech
infrastructure. The multipurpose Bass performance hall marries a
beaux-arts plan and early modern decorations. The Dallas arena, in
one preliminary sketch, combines elements of the old TWA terminal
in St. Louis with the facade and tower of Will Rogers Memorial
Complex in Fort Worth. (However, that's not necessarily how the
finished product will look; Schwarz will start the design from
scratch.)
</P>
<P>
   The critical response to both projects has ranged from qualified
acceptance to outraged disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   While crediting the performance hall's ``genuine beauties,''
critic Willard Spiegelman adds that `` ... one wonders whether Mr.
Schwarz has nodded too nostalgically to the past or in the
direction of safe charm,'' in his ``Wall Street Journal'' review of
the hall.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... another piece of lick-and-stick architecture,'' writes
``Dallas Morning News'' architecture critic David Dillon in his
response to the arena announcement. He adds that Schwarz's message
to arena executives ``was not `I believe such and such,' but `Tell
me what you like, and I'll give it to you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With such high-profile examples of buildings as high art and
buildings as populist design, it might seem that Texas is sending
mixed signals about how seriously we take architecture. On one
hand, we've got our Pritzker Prize laureates and AIA gold medalists
working on an unprecedented number of Texas museums. On the other,
we have Schwarz fielding commissions to design a number of
important public structures in his trademark mix of retro styles.
</P>
<P>
   Every project sent to Schwarz, critics say, becomes a lost
opportunity to say something meaningful about the prospects of an
architecture for the future. And, they add, in cases where Schwarz
beats out other competitors for a commission, the competition
process becomes a mockery.
</P>
<P>
   OK. I can agree with the latter complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily because _ and, although this is a flawed comparison,
it will have to do _ competitions like those for the Dallas arena
and The Ballpark in Arlington are like pitting Norman Rockwell
against Andy Warhol, Gerhard Richter and Carrie Mae Weems to design
a cover for ``Life'' magazine. It's apples and oranges. You either
want a heartwarming picture or you don't. If you don't, why include
Rockwell? If you do, don't pretend those other people have a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth competition that
Schwarz didn't win often was perceived as less-than-serious,
although not an outright mockery, because Schwarz was included as a
courtesy. As such, he was the apple in a gathering of oranges
comprising Legoretta, Richard Gluckman, Carlos Jimenez, Arata
Isozaki and Ando, to whom the commission was given.
</P>
<P>
   But calling a Schwarz commission a lost opportunity is unfair
and inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   What Schwarz does reflects an important force in our
contemporary world. It's a force that rejects modernist visions of
ongoing artistic and architectural progress, and also ignores the
irony expressed in works by other progressive architectural
thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   It's an unabashedly populist and pragmatic approach _ and not
lacking in innovative solutions. It is every bit as nostalgic as
critics accuse it of being: an architecture of the warm and fuzzy,
if you will.
</P>
<P>
   But is remains an architecture with sufficient validity that it
warrants more serious, unbiased consideration than it has received.
</P>
<P>
   Would I want to see every project take this turn? No way. But
I'd like to see eclectic historicism given its due.
</P>
<P>
   If it were, Schwarz might receive some real competition. And the
quality of this potentially influential parallel to progressive
architecture might overall be raised.
</P>
<P>
   So here's how my script concludes:
</P>
<P>
   The gunfighters fill their hands and fire. But, when the dust
settles, they both still are standing.
</P>
<P>
   The picture fades, the credits roll, the questions linger and a
possibility tantalizes: Perhaps our antagonists decided the
territory is big enough for both of them.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
