u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-FEDERAL-BIAS-BO     06-17 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-FEDERAL-BIAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP SEEKS HALT OF BIAS AT FEDERAL AGENCIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The NAACP is threatening a massive demonstration
here against federal agencies it believes discriminate against
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to picket all of the federal agencies if they
don't get their acts together,'' said Leroy W. Warren, an NAACP
board member, who described the discrimination as ``rampant.''
``These agencies are not following the government's regulations on
employment discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren, who did not say when such picketing would occur, made
his comments at a breakfast with reporters Wednesday, as the
civil-rights group released its report on employment discrimination
in the federal workplace. The report alleges that six agencies
racially and sexually discriminate against their employees and
retaliate against those who file equal employment opportunity
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the agencies Wednesday acknowledged that they faced
problems in dealing with discrimination, and said they were doing
their best to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The report listed hundreds of complaints from employees at the
US Department of Agriculture, the Library of Congress, the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp., the Department of the Interior, the
Internal Revenue Service and the Department of Defense. Warren said
a final study, reviewing additional agencies, will be released this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is appalling that minorities are being retaliated against
for filing complaints about discrimination,'' Warren said. ``They
are being demoted, passed up for promotions, and their lives are
being ruined because they spoke up.''
</P>
<P>
   The equal employment opportunity program is not effectively
protecting federal employees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The EEO is out of control,'' he said. ``A bunch of these EEO
officers ought to be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   But Warren said that some of the blame for the difficulties
within the federal agencies belongs with black personnel directors
who, he said, discriminate against blacks and other minority
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Luther King and too many other people have died for us
to have black people as gatekeepers keeping us out of the jobs we
deserve,'' he said. ``All of you Uncle Toms and Aunt Toms out
there, you aren't going to stop us from picketing. We aren't about
to be sold like some people are.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Helen Thompson, spokesperson for the Department of the
Interior, said the agency is aware it has problems regarding
discrimination against minority employees. Because of this, the
department launched a diversity program about six months ago, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, at all levels of management, are committed to rectifying
this problem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   John Sparks, the Agriculture Department's special assistant to
the secretary for civil rights, said the agency is also aware that
it has diversity and discrimination issues to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be the first to say that we have a long way to go and a
lot to do,'' he said. ``But we understand these issues are
important, and we have been working with minority employee groups
to do whatever we can to resolve problems that exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hubenak, spokesperson for the IRS, said he could not comment
on the report specifically, but he said the IRS does not tolerate
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a policy against all forms of discrimination at the
IRS,'' he said. ``We don't support it nor condone it. We are
committed to doing everything under the law to ensure equal
opportunity and fair treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokespersons for the FDIC and the Library of Congress said they
were not prepared to issue a statement about the report, because
they did not have a chance to fully review it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see this report before it was handed out, and we're
looking at it now, but we have no comment until we've gone over it
fully,'' FDIC spokesperson Phil Battey said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Tom Begines, spokesman for the Defense Department, said
he could not comment on the NAACP report because he did not have
time to fully analyze it. But he referred to a May 16 statement by
Defense Secretary William Cohen that the military ``is one of the
most racially integrated institutions in America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
