<SLUG> BC-GUNS-APPEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD CHILD'S MOTHER URGES CONGRESS TO MAKE GUNS SAFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Suzann Wilson wept Wednesday as she remembered the
last time her 11-year-old daughter skipped out the door and headed
for school. Last March, her daughter Brittheny, three other
children, and a teacher were shot and killed by two schoolmates in
Jonesboro, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson made an emotional appeal to Congress, which has been
hostile toward gun control, to pass legislation that would impose
new child-resistant devices on handguns and make it more difficult
for juveniles to obtain guns.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would require new safety standards on all
handguns, including a child-resistance trigger, a child safety lock
and a magazine disconnect safety for pistols. The bill also would
prohibit the sale of an assault weapon to anyone under 18, raise
the penalties for selling a gun to a juvenile, require two forms of
identification for any gun purchaser under the age of 24, and
impose fines on gun owners if a child gains access to a loaded
firearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``On March 24th, our daughter went to school and walked out the
door and out of our lives,'' Wilson said between sobs.
</P>
<P>
   She described how she warned her little girl to avoid strangers
and come home before dark but never thought to caution the
middle-school student about leaving the school building for a fire
alarm. Two boys, ages 11 and 13, tripped the alarm and shot at
their classmates as they exited the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you know?'' she cried. ``As a parent, I have to be
very supportive of this bill. It's not about taking away any
rights. It's about giving the right to children to have an
education ... This is not an issue that is going to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanya K. Metaksa, lobbyist for the National Rifle Association,
which opposes such legislation, later said a national standard was
``unsound and unsafe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What may be a safe condition for one family can become certain
tragedy for another family faced with violent intruders,'' she said
about the resistant devices. ``One size does not fit all.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference with Wilson were two other women touched
by gun violence: Sarah Brady, the wife of former White House
spokesman Jim Brady who was severely wounded during an
assassination attempt on President Reagan, and Representative
Carolyn McCarthy, a New York Democrat whose husband was killed and
son was severely wounded by a gunman on a Long Island commuter
train.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a society we can no longer accept an epidemic of gun
violence that is killing more children than the polio epidemic at
its height,'' Brady said. She said 14 children die each day in the
United States as a result of guns.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, whose two brothers were shot and
killed, said he will attempt to attach the legislation as an
amendment to the juvenile justice bill that already has passed the
House and is pending in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural fit,'' said Kennedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
