<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-CONVENTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON READIES PLAN TO WOO DEMOCRAT CONVENTION PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Just use your imagination. That's what city officials
plan to tell Democratic National Committee members scouting sites
for their convention in 2000 when they visit here next week.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the Fleet Center without cranes and backhoes surrounding
it. Ignore the hardhat site near the airport and picture a finished
800-room Hilton instead. And the Big Dig? Imagine if it was all
underground.
</P>
<P>
   In the homestretch to land what would be a gigantic prize of
hosting the presidential convention, the Menino administration is
scrambling to spruce up the city and Wednesday released a schedule
for the 50-member delegation that includes a shopping spree in
Filene's Basement, and late-night billiards at Jillian's in Quincy
Marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   And to help them imagine what the city will look like in 2000,
Boston has employed some high-tech visual aids, expensive computer
models and diagrams that replicates the future cityscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they see in two years will be much better,'' said Mayor
Thomas M. Menino, who will lead a 6 a.m. walk through the South End
next Tuesday. ``They have to imagine that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Big Dig is scheduled to be at maximum construction in
2000, it will be underground rather and most of the more disruptive
work going on now on surface streets will be gone, said Howard
Liebowitz, the mayor's point person on the DNC bid.
</P>
<P>
   By August 2000, there will be a large clear space around the
Fleet Center that will be suitable for parking semi-tractor
trailers that TV production crews would bring in, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Democrats will hear that traffic in August is
17 percent lighter than the June car traffic they will see next
week, due to vacations and the absence of college students.
</P>
<P>
   ``August 2000 will be a great time to be at the Fleet Center,''
said Kelley Quinn, a key architect of the city's DNC bid.
</P>
<P>
   Other computer models will depict how the Fleet Center could
accommodate legions of working journalists in the underground
parking garage, which the Secret Service likely would close anyway,
said Quinn. The garage is already air-conditioned and could easily
be outfitted with telecommunications equipment, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fleet Center also offers movable luxury boxes and a TV
production crew that has been hired to do major shows and
tournaments in other venues, she said. The visiting Democrats will
even be flattered at the end of their tour of facility of video
taken of them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is in fact crowing about having more hotels within a
brief subway or bus ride than its top competitors _ Philadelphia
and Los Angeles _ even an improvement over Chicago, where some
delegates had to ride for up to an hour from their hotel to the
United Center, Liebowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel rooms, Menino said ``are a non-issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4228 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABOR-GM-1     06-17 1472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-GM-1,000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLINT STRIKE PUTS SPOTLIGHT ON TRANSFER OF JOBS OVERSEAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: This story is a photo reefer on the Times frontpage) 
(ps) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ The 12-day-old strike against General Motors
began as a little-watched, local dispute at a single metal-shaping
plant here, but the walkout has quickly snowballed into a strike of
national importance.
</P>
<P>
   Now not just one plant, but instead 17 are closed, as parts
shortages created by the strike have shut down most operations at
the world's largest auto maker, a company accounting for 1 percent
of the nation's economic output.
</P>
<P>
   And although the walkout involves a tangle of issues, the strike
has focused increasingly on an issue of paramount concern to
millions of workers across America: the transfer of jobs overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on strike to protect our jobs, and that's an issue
everyone cares about,'' said John Falk, a strapping auto worker who
spent his 40th birthday on the picket line along with his
11-year-old son. ``GM has everyone worried they're going to shut
everything down and move our jobs overseas, but we want to save
some good-paying jobs so kids like 11-year-old Charlie here can
have a good standard of living.''
</P>
<P>
   But GM sees things differently. Ever since 3,400 workers walked
off the job on June 5 at the metal-stamping plant here, GM
officials have insisted that the main issue in the dispute is the
company's need to trim costs further so it can compete better with
Ford, Chrysler and Japanese automakers. To do that, GM is demanding
greater leeway to rely on lower-cost plants, usually nonunion and
often overseas, to supply parts now made at GM plants, a practice
known as outsourcing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The union has accused GM of putting America last,'' said
Harley Shaiken, a professor of industrial relations at the
University of California at Berkeley. ``This dispute is the most
visible example of offshore outsourcing becoming the issue in a
strike with major national implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America began embracing outsourcing in the 1980's, but
the phenomenon has gathered steam in recent years as tariffs and
trade barriers have fallen, making it easier and cheaper for
companies like Caterpillar and New Balance shoes to buy many parts
from abroad instead of making them in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As the practice has spread, unions have fought back, with mixed
success, mostly at the bargaining table and rarely through strikes.
But now, with General Motors aggressively pushing to move more work
to nonunion plants, at home and abroad, the United Automobile
Workers, emboldened by a booming economy and low unemployment, has
decided to strike. The auto workers' tough stand against
outsourcing is being watched closely by unions and other industries
where outsourcing is growing: machinery, apparel, electronics and
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The strike pits the nation's largest manufacturer versus the
nation's most powerful and arguably most respected union _ a union
at the top of labor's firmament, one known for its toughness on the
picket line and shrewdness in delivering at the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   With some analysts predicting that the dispute could become the
biggest auto industry showdown since the 1970 walkout that shut
down GM for three months, the way this strike turns out could cast
a long shadow on labor-management relations nationwide and on how
hard or easy it will be for other companies to turn to outsourcing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The labor movement has to be watching this very closely
because the UAW is standing up for every union that is worried by
the transfer of jobs overseas,'' said David L. Lewis, a professor
of business history at the University of Michigan. ``It's a
life-and-death struggle. General Motors is determined to transfer
many of these jobs out of the country, and the UAW simply can't
have it. If the UAW fails, many unions will find it all the more
difficult to prevent outsourcing. This trend, this outsourcing will
be accelerated.''
</P>
<P>
   The union is triply angry about GM's new push for outsourcing.
The effort could cause additional plant closings, forcing many
workers to relocate and eliminating jobs that well-paid auto
workers hoped might someday go to their children.
</P>
<P>
   GM's effort could also sap the union's power, membership and
treasury by further reducing its numbers. Its membership has
dropped from 1.5 million in the 1970's to 800,000 today as the auto
industry has downsized, in part because of strong Japanese imports.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, union officials say they are especially irked because in
their view, General Motors, in its new outsourcing offensive, is
violating the contract that the Flint local signed last year in
which it accepted numerous steps to increase productivity. The
Flint workers accuse GM of reneging on its commitment to invest
$300 million in the metal-stamping plant so it can build parts for
a new light truck. For its part, GM accuses the union of not
carrying out several promised productivity measures.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for the auto workers for numerous reasons,
symbolic and substantive. With General Motors showing new vigor in
its erratic efforts to cut costs, the UAW wants to send a powerful
message that it will put up costly roadblocks if GM seeks to do
this by downsizing its American plants and work force beyond what
the union has already agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown also carries much symbolic significance because
Flint is the cradle of the United Auto Workers. It is the city
where storied sitdown strikes took place in the 1930s and where
Walter Reuther, the legendary figure who built the union in the
1930s and 1940s, first made his mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the birthplace of the UAW, the home of the
sitdowners,'' said Claudia Perkins, a union representative at GM's
Delphi East parts plant here. ``If they bust the Flinters, they'll
bust the stronghold of the UAW. This is very important.
</P>
<P>
   Many workers suspect that GM has grown weary of Flint and its
labor militancy. Many workers here are convinced that GM will
eventually shut its five remaining plants here, in no small part
because over the last decade it has already closed three plants
here.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At dozens of Flint workers stand in the hot sun waving ``On
Strike'' placards, the strikers are convinced that the public backs
them strongly. Fully one out of two cars driving past honks in
solidarity, while many neighbors and store owners have plied them
with pizzas, donuts and sodas. One barber gave the strikers
discount slips for haircuts.
</P>
<P>
   But, many labor experts say, this show of hometown support masks
the ambivalence that many Americans feel toward the auto workers.
There is widespread envy _ and even resentment _ toward these
members of the blue-collar elite, who have among the best salaries
and benefits of workers anywhere. Before overtime they earn $40,000
a year, and with overtime, often more than $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   The public has certainly not rallied behind the auto workers the
way it rallied behind the teamsters in last August's walkout by
185,000 workers at the United Parcel Service. One reason is
millions of Americans know and like their dependable UPS drivers,
while auto workers toil unseen behind factory walls. Another reason
is the teamsters, unlike the proud, go-it-alone auto workers,
worked assiduously before walking out to line up public support and
from the beginning emphasized an issue that it knew would resonate
with the public: UPS was seeking to create more part-time jobs that
would not pay enough to support a family.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to explain the public's differing reaction to the two
walkouts, Richard Trumka, secretary-treasurer of the AFL-CIO, said
``The GM strike began a local strike. The UPS strike was a national
strike from day one. We're seeing a calculated acceleration of the
GM strike. The issues surrounding the strike _ downsizing,
exporting America jobs _ are issues that workers face across the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This is the ninth time in two years that an auto workers local
has struck General Motors _ a development that industry analysts
say shows that GM's labor relations team is less attuned than
Ford's and Chrysler's. As in the current strike, in many of the
previous walkouts, the showdown was over GM's desperate desire to
downsize, outsource and cut costs and the UAW's demand not only to
prevent layoffs and outsourcing, but to preserve job slots for the
workers of tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue here is not peculiar to General Motors,'' said
Daniel Kruger, professor of labor studies at Michigan State
University. ``It's shared by all large and small employers: how can
we find a balance between corporate efficiency and labor
stability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
