<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MAURO-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LEADS MAURO BY 53 PERCENTAGE POINTS IN TEXAS POLL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Public support for Democrat Garry Mauro has slipped
despite a monthlong television advertising campaign and he now
trails Republican Gov. George W. Bush by 53 percentage points, the
latest Texas Poll found.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 691 likely voters released Wednesday found Bush is
leading in his re-election race over Mauro by 70 percent to 17
percent, with 11 percent undecided and 2 percent wanting neither.
</P>
<P>
   The June 1-12 poll, conducted by Scripps Howard and the Office
of Survey Research at the University of Texas, has a margin of
error of plus or minus 3.7 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's support dropped 4 percentage points from a Texas Poll
done earlier this year, when Bush led Mauro 67 percent to 21
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lead in the current poll is exactly the same lead as he
held over Mauro when the Texas Poll was conducted in the summer of
1997. But that poll was done before Mauro officially announced for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro also ran an estimated $600,000 in television commercials
this past month criticizing Bush for his 1995 veto of a bill that
would have guaranteed patients who belong to health maintenance
organizations the right to choose their own doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is leading overwhelmingly among Republican and independent
voters, and even 37 percent of the Democrats surveyed said they
would vote for Bush over Mauro, now the state's land commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro attacked the credibility of the Texas Poll, calling it
``laughable.'' Mauro said a Democratic poll conducted this week
shows him trailing by just 35 percentage points, with Bush leading
63 percent to 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am right on schedule for the plan I put in place,'' Mauro
said. ``I feel real good about where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   But with less than five months left to the election, no Democrat
has been in worse shape to win the governor's office since federal
troops occupied Texas during Reconstruction more than 150 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have lost governor's races just three times this
century: incumbents Ann Richards and Mark White in 1994 and 1986
respectively, and party nominee John Hill in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Richards was leading in the Texas Poll at this point in her
unsuccessful re-election campaign, while White cut a 14-point poll
deficit in half by the time he was defeated Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Hill held an 11 percentage point lead in a poll for Texas
Monthly magazine just before he lost the 1978 election to Bill
Clements, the first Republican to win the governor's office since
Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Even in her upset victory over Republican Clayton Williams in
1990, Richards trailed just 8 percentage points at this point of
her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the latest Texas Poll results made him happy because
it says Texans are responding favorably to his administration.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the poll found Bush's job approval rating to be 75
percent, the highest since he's been in office and the highest of
any governor polled since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said the poll results also will make him work harder
for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just says I better take nothing for granted,'' Bush said.
``I am concerned about my supporters and workers saying we don't
have to work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The high poll numbers could create a perception that Bush's
actual support had weakened if he were to win by a substantially
smaller margin in a low-turnout election. Such a change in
perception could weaken his potential as a Republican presidential
candidate in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Poll asked voters whether they would be more likely or
less likely to vote for Bush's re-election if he also were running
for president. Twenty-percent said it would make them more likely;
12 percent, less likely; and 65 percent said it would make no
difference in how they voted.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said the Texas Poll was unreliable because its sample was
31 percent Republican, 25 percent Democrat, 26 percent independent
and 18 percent who said other or don't know. Mauro said it is
``absurd'' to believe 18 percent of Texans believe they belong to a
third party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Texas Poll is anything but laughable. It's
amateur hour at its worst,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro also attacked the poll for saying it showed Democrats
losing in the races for lieutenant governor and comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas Poll has John Sharp losing and Paul Hobby (trailing)
at double digits,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller Sharp is running for lieutenant governor.
Former Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby's son, Paul, is running for comptroller.
The Texas Poll results in those races will not be publicly
available until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle Political Writer Alan Bernstein contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
