<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMA-ELECT-NYT &LR;      06-17 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMA RETAINS LEADER DESPITE SUNBEAM FUROR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ore., Texas)  (mk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Delegates to the American Medical Association retained
their current leadership Wednesday, rejecting a presidential
candidate who was critical of a failed deal to allow the commercial
use of the AMA's name.
</P>
<P>
   The 484 delegates of the nation's largest organization of
physicians instead elected as their president Dr. Thomas Reardon, a
64-year-old general practitioner from Portland, Ore., who was
chairman of the AMA at the time of the contract, with the Sunbeam
Corp. Reardon is to begin his one-year term in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA backed out of the deal, and five executives left last
August, after the organization was criticized for endorsing home
health products that it had not tested. Sunbeam has sued the AMA,
seeking $20 million for breach of contract. The association would
have received millions in royalties for putting its logo on
humidifiers, blood-pressure monitors and other devices. The
association plans to approach Sunbeam to try to settle the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Reardon defeated Raymond Scalettar, a Washington rheumatologist
who campaigned against the AMA leadership's handling of the Sunbeam
contract and disputed an AMA committee's conclusion that the board
of trustees had not known of the deal. The medical association
would not release the election tally, but some delegates said they
believed that the vote was close.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the legal costs and loss of top staff members, the
Sunbeam incident damaged the credibility of the 290,000-member
association. For example, an Illinois delegation offered a
resolution saying the AMA was ``shamed by legitimate local and
national criticism of institutional conflicts of interest and
unacceptable commercialism.'' The convention has yet to vote on the
delegation's proposal to open the books on the cost of the Sunbeam
issue, and to open all meetings of the AMA trustees.
</P>
<P>
   After his victory, Reardon told reporters: ``We still have the
litigation to deal with, but I think emotionally we need to kind of
move on past Sunbeam. We have learned that we need to be more _
what is it they say at Nordstrom's? _ more responsive to our
customers, our members.''
</P>
<P>
   The AMA is unlikely to endorse commercial products again, even
though the American Dental Association and similar organizations
have such deals, said the incoming president, Nancy Dickey, a
47-year-old family practitioner from College Station, Texas. ``It's
always possible to say you should have done something different or
better,'' Dickey said. ``I think the delegates generally see that
the money is not worth the difficulty of finding the right deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegates also approved an all-out effort to allow consumers
to choose their health insurance from among competing plans, as
they now choose auto insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians have been unhappy with the current system for a
decade,'' said Dickey, the first woman to be the association's
president. ``Patients have been unhappy for five or six years. Now
even CEOs are unhappy because costs are rising again. If
everybody's unhappy with the existing system, what better time to
change it?''
</P>
<P>
   After watching the Chicago Bulls celebrate their National
Basketball Association championship with victory cigars, the
delegates approved an emergency resolution on Tuesday calling on
professional athletes to avoid the use of cigars and other tobacco
products. After that resolution was approved on Tuesday, some
members of the Detroit Red Wings were seen on television
celebrating their National Hockey League championship with cigars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
