<SLUG> BC-CAJUNN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Race for Cajun Electric Power narrows field to two
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A Southern Co. partnership and Enron Corp. have
emerged as finalists in bidding for Cajun Electric Power
Cooperative, a Louisiana electricity supplier that's been in
bankrupcy for three years.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Louisiana disqualified Louisiana-based
Southwestern Electric Power Co. from the bidding. U.S. District
Judge Frank Polozola has thrown out SWEPCO's $940 million bid and
found the company had tried to buy the support of seven rural
electric cooperatives for its takeover proposal. Polozola ordered
SWEPCO to repay $1 million to the co-ops and recommended a criminal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are planning to appeal,'' SWEPCO spokesman Peter Main said
Wednesday. But for now, the company is disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   Cajun supplies electricity to 12 rural cooperatives that serve
315,000 homes and businesses, about a quarter of Louisiana's
population. The utility was driven into bankrupcy in 1994 by its
failed investment in River Bend nuclear power plant in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-September, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Gerald Schiff is
expected to choose a winning bidder for Cajun's non-nuclear assets
after months of wrangling among the rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Generating, the consortium that includes Atlanta-based
Southern, Northern States Power of Minneapolis and Zeigler Coal
Holding of Fairview Heights, Ill., is bidding $1.18 billion for
Cajun, while Enron is bidding $932.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's down to the two of us,'' said Enron spokesman Mark
Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   Tal Wright, spokesman for Southern, said Louisiana Generating
has submitted ``the best bid'' for Cajun. Palmer, however, said
Enron's proposal is the ``lowest cost offer'' because its rates
would be lower.
</P>
<P>
   Southern and Enron have emerged as prime competitors in electric
power and natural gas markets as the utility industry is
deregulated in the United States and U.S. companies seek footholds
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Southern's interest in Cajun is part of an effort to back up its
power marketing business with generating plants in selected U.S.
markets. The company last month agreed to purchase a network of
power plants in New England for $537 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
