<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mood swings lift market investors
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Stocks soared Wednesday after the U.S. moved to prop
up the Japanese yen, but analysts warned it will be a temporary
rally unless it is followed by more permanent economic reform in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Investors experienced a ``mood swing'' to renewed confidence
about earnings following Monday's pessimism that Asia's crisis
would hurt U.S. profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important point is that there was a reason for the mood to
improve _ namely that the U.S. will not stand aside and let the yen
fall against the dollar,'' said Anthony O'Bryan, a market analyst
with A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, investors will have to be persuaded that
``real, concrete developments'' are in the works to reform Japan's
economy if the rally is to last. Japan's recovery is needed so it
``can help the rest of Asia,'' O'Bryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Harrington, technical analyst at Interstate/Johnson Lane,
said he doubts the new mood will last, given the market's high
share prices relative to earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the correction will resume. I'm inclined to think that
once the end-of-quarter window dressing is over and we get into
July earnings season, we still will have a very turbulent market,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Window dressing'' is the rush of trading late in a quarter by
institutional traders so they can report fully invested portfolios
to their clients.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, however, investors rallied behind the U.S. action
from the opening bell, sending the benchmark Dow Jones industrial
average up as much as 227 points in early trading _ just two days
after the benchmark index suffered its fifth worst one-day point
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Diminished anxiety about world conditions buoyed cyclical, or
growth-related, stocks such as chemicals, paper and heavy
equipment. This boosted the Dow and Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 indexes
1.9 percent and 1.8 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Computer stocks, which have been under selling pressure for
months, continued to rebound, as did smaller-capitalized stocks.
These rallies buoyed the technology-laden Nasdaq composite and
Russell 2000 indexes 1.3 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   In the day's atmosphere, investors paid scant attention to the
Federal Reserve's ``beige book'' report, which showed a
continuation of benign inflation against a backdrop of strong
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. move to prop up the yen may also minimize some of the
market's response to today's April trade report, which is expected
to show a deficit of $13.2 billion. The biggest casualty of
Wednesday's trading was the bond market, where heavy selling had
the effect of lifting 30-year Treasury yields from recent all-time
lows.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
