<SLUG> BC-SAPORTA-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cultural institutions' chiefs compare notes, aspirations
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- How can Atlanta reach the next level in artistic and
cultural offerings?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question directors of Atlanta's major museums and
cultural institutions tried to answer Wednesday at one of their
regular, informal lunches.
</P>
<P>
   Since early 1992, Atlanta's museum directors have been meeting
nearly once a month to exchange ideas, information and support.
Those meetings have helped eliminate any sense of competition or
isolation between and among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably originally met as a therapy group,'' said Terry
Maple, president of Zoo Atlanta. ``We were all struggling mightily
with our institutions that were in growth or rebirth. We found that
when we compared notes, there was a lot of common ground. We even
cross-fertilized by hiring each other's staff.''
</P>
<P>
   The museums and cultural institutions that are part of the group
include the High Museum of Atlanta, Zoo Atlanta, Fernbank Museum of
Natural History, SciTrek, the Children's Museum, the Atlanta
Botanical Garden, the Michael Carlos Museum and the Atlanta History
Center. Ann K. Bergstrom, director of cultural tourism for the
Atlanta Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau, regularly attends to
contribute her perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Atlanta is viewed a place where there's not much to
do. The existing cultural institutions have not become nationally
recognized attractions that draw tourists and conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the museums and institutions, which primarily are
located in the central city, are having trouble even attracting
people from the suburbs. It's a phenomenon Maple describes as
``inertia of the 'burbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's cultural attractions have enjoyed considerable
financial investment in the past decade. Just about every
institution has expanded and established solid financial results by
wiping out their debts and operating in the black.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all agreed that the Olympics has raised the bar,''
said Pat Turner, director of the Children's Museum.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, several institutions have not seen their
attendance grow, with the exception of Fernbank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had record attendance in April and May,'' said Susan
Neugent, Fernbank's president. Fernbank has had quality exhibits
and IMAX movies in previous years, but Neugent said the difference
this year has been strong marketing.
</P>
<P>
   It's a story each institution repeated. They need corporate and
individual partners to keep their museums and attractions fresh
with new exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Crider, SciTrek's director, said her attraction needs
businesses to display cutting-edge technology.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Rifkin, director of the High Museum, said his institution
has enjoyed support from both individuals and corporations. But he
said the Atlanta community still needs to better understand the
economic benefits of having strong arts and cultural institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an investment,'' Rifkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Change at United Way
</P>
<P>
   At its annual meeting Wednesday, the United Way of Metropolitan
Atlanta announced a change in its board structure to better serve
the community's social needs.
</P>
<P>
   W. Thomas Smith Jr., IBM's general manager of small and medium
business for North America, became United Way's new chairman,
succeeding Kent C. ``Oz'' Nelson, retired CEO of United Parcel
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Effective July 1, the United Way board will be streamlined from
62 members to 30. But it will have a 130-member leadership network
to focus on tasks and projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task at hand is to subordinate ourselves to the work to be
done,'' Smith said. Jack Guynn, president of the Atlanta Federal
Reserve Bank, will follow Smith as United Way's chairman next year.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, United Way has redirected its giving and
fund-raising to solving the biggest concerns in the Atlanta
community. United Way surveyed 40,000 Atlanta citizens, who said in
one clear voice they wanted stronger, safer communities. Since
then, United Way has directed most of its giving to four
categories: nurturing children and youth, strengthening families,
encouraging citizen involvement and increasing self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The 130 network members, including county advisory boards, will
focus on various projects. For example, Johnnetta B. Cole, retired
president of Spelman College, is leaving the board but will help
develop the new Johnnetta B. Cole Society, which recognizes those
contributing between $1,000 and $10,000 to United Way annually.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
