<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama's James still a skillful political player
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOOVER, Ala. -- Tuesday's segment of ``Fob James Live'' was
broadcast from an ideal setting for Alabama's athlete-governor: the
announcer's booth at the Hoover Met, the suburban stadium where the
Birmingham Barons play minor league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   As he does weekly, James talked with callers from around the
state, pausing occasionally to describe the scene as the Barons
took batting practice on an emerald field under a clear summer sky.
With the loping efficiency of an outfielder handling routine fly
balls, the governor dealt with questions about unscrupulous bass
tournament organizers, wrongful terminations and child care for
mothers getting off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   But the topic most on the mind of the former Auburn football
great was the radio ad with which his Republican primary opponent,
Montgomery businessman Winton Blount, is now blasting him. In so
many words the ad accuses the governor of lying, perjury and
self-aggrandizement, charges James referred to Tuesday as
``crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's hired some campaign gurus and they've got control
of his mind _ and his money, too,'' James told a caller.
</P>
<P>
   James said later he wasn't talking specifically about Tom Perdue
and Sonny Scott, the Atlanta consultants he hired last year to
streamline the governor's office. But the efficiency experts and
Blount's gurus are the same people. Perdue and Scott were dismissed
after what James characterized as ``a hell of a misunderstanding''
and are now running Blount's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to back up the perjury charge in the ad, Scott cited news
stories in which the foreman of a Montgomery jury said the jury's
first decision was to ``disregard (James') testimony'' in the trial
of a former agency head James had fired for theft.
</P>
<P>
   The self-aggrandizement charge relates to a family-owned
landfill the governor said nets only about $70 profit a month from
business with the state. Scott said the amount involved was
``inconsequential as to whether the governor lied, for lack of a
better word,'' about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The runoff campaign has reached this bitter edge as the two
Republicans prepare for the first of four debates tonight in
Montgomery. James and Blount have pulled out all the stops,
courting black political leaders and winking at possible Democratic
crossovers.
</P>
<P>
   A good turnout by religious conservatives is critical for James.
Ralph Reed, James' campaign manager, told a group of preachers
Monday that Christian conservatives ``could make the difference''
and urged them to exercise their ``godly responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding that he's a millionaire like Blount, James has
also drawn from the Big Jim Folsom-George Wallace playbook to
attack Blount on class lines, calling attention to his family
wealth and endorsement by ``liberal'' newspapers. He characterizes
himself as a ``plain old conservative'' who can be trusted not to
raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   How effective the traditional class appeal will be in a
Republican primary remains to be seen, but an hour's worth of ``Fob
James Live'' is convincing evidence that despite all the bad press
he's received both in and out of state, the governor knows how to
connect with an Alabama audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't want me, if I was a college president, to keep a
football coach that couldn't win games, would you?'' he asked a
caller who criticized his dismissal of another department head.
</P>
<P>
   Not in Alabama you wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
