<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carson Inc. to purchase ethnic-oriented Johnson Products
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Carson Inc. said Wednesday it plans to buy Johnson
Products Co. from Miami-based IVX BioScience in a $70 million cash
deal that will combine two of the nation's major ethnic
personal-care products makers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's brands include Gentle Treatment, Ultra Sheen, Precise
and Afro Sheen. Its cosmetics are sold under the Posner name.
</P>
<P>
   IVX said Carson has agreed to pay an undisclosed amount for
additional cosmetics lines including Flori Roberts, Patti LaBelle
and Imani cosmetics brands and Dermablend. Under the agreement, IVX
has the right to sell these brands to a third party, but that will
not be determined until closing, IVX said.
</P>
<P>
   The Carson deal will allow IVX to focus solely on the
development, manufacturing and marketing of pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make Carson a pure ethnic personal-care
player,'' said Roy Keith, chairman of Savannah-based Carson.
``Johnson has lines that will naturally complement our existing
product line.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes on the heels of a management restructuring at
Carson during which Keith stepped down as CEO. Vincent A. Wasik,
associated with the partnership that is Carson's controlling
shareholder, was named interim CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Carson also said it planned to sell its Cutex nail care
business.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first acquisition in 1998 for Carson, which plans
major expansions in South America and Africa. Carson owns Dark &AMP;
Lovely, Excelle and Magic lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will increase their revenues and it will definitely
increase their market share,'' said Baunita Greer, an analyst with
Cromwell, Miller &AMP; Greer. ``This looks like a very positive
acquisition.''
</P>
<P>
   It also puts Johnson back in the hands of a black-controlled
company. Both Keith and Carson President Joyce Roche are
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Smikle, publisher of Chicago-based Target Market News, which
tracks ethnic markets, said ethnic personal products represent at
least a $2.2 billion market. Johnson, a pioneer in ethnic hair-care
products and once one of the nation's largest black businesses, was
sold to Ivax Corp., now known as IVX, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Carson's stock closed Wednesday at $7.25, down 25 cents. IVX's
stock rose 25 cents to $9.12 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
