<HEADER>
A4238 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-COX     06-17 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chinese native works with Carter Center to bring open elections
to thousands of villages
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- For six years in the 1980s, Yawei Liu worked as a
censor at a publishing house in his native China.
</P>
<P>
   His actual title was editor, not censor, but he had no illusions
about what his job really was. The publishing house looked for
American literature to translate into Chinese. And part of Liu's
task was to delete the passages referring to sex and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were particularly tough to make sure that other people did
not have access to this information,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This Saturday, Liu, now an assistant professor of history at
DeKalb College, departs for China on an entirely different mission:
to bring ideas to China rather than to suppress them.
</P>
<P>
   He's working on importing one concept in particular _ democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Liu is part of a four-man team from the Carter Center working in
concert with the Chinese government to bring fair, open elections
to the villages in which more than three-quarters of that nation's
1.2 billion people live.
</P>
<P>
   Unpublicized elections
</P>
<P>
   The team will be led by Bob Pastor, a Carter Center fellow. Also
making the trip will be Tom Crick, a Carter Center official, and
Qingshan Tan, an associate professor of political science at
Cleveland State University who is, like Liu, a Chinese citizen and
a former student of Pastor's at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Elections have been mandatory in China's 930,000 villages since
1987, and Chinese officials have conducted elections since then,
said former President Jimmy Carter, ``in a totally unpublicized
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Carter added, ``They don't really know what goes on in
those elections in 930,000 villages, which is understandable. So
there they have asked us to help devise a computerized system to
receive reports of the results.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Pastor team observed some village elections, and
also reached a long-term agreement between the Chinese Ministry of
Civil Affairs and the Carter Center to establish a national data
collection system which will allow the ministry to learn the
results of elections quickly, and to determine if the elections
were fair.
</P>
<P>
   The team is making this particular trip to see to it that forms
devised to assess the fairness of elections _ by determining if
there was a secret ballot, if there was competition, and so forth _
have reached the villages and been understood by village officials.
They will also try to make sure that 14 computers and specially
designed software have reached the nine counties, three provincial
capitals and the ministry in Beijing (which gets two computers) so
a pilot project can be conducted. And they will assess how the
forms work, whether data is transmitted accurately to Beijing, and
whether the computerized data collection system, which Liu helped
design, can be used nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Communicating democracy
</P>
<P>
   Liu and Tan are critical to the team, Pastor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason these guys are so indispensable to the project is
their ability to interpret, in the broadest sense of the word,
between two cultures,'' Pastor said. They are adept at
communicating democratic concepts even in cases where Chinese may
not have a precisely equivalent word, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Liu, who is associate director of the Carter Center's China
Village Elections Project, bridges the two cultures as well as
anyone can. He grew up in the city of Xian, in Shaanxi Province in
northwest China, the son of a career Chinese military officer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he lives in Duluth and teaches American history.
</P>
<P>
   Liu, 38, grew up the beneficiary of the liberalization initiated
in China by Deng Xiaoping in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
Whereas Liu at first learned his English from Chinese teachers,
eventually Australian teachers were admitted, and then Americans.
</P>
<P>
   American magazines and movies began to appear. And it dawned on
Liu that, contrary to everything he had been taught, the capitalist
system was not on the verge of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shocking revelation,'' he said. ``Talk about
disillusion.''
</P>
<P>
   When, after six years, he realized he was going nowhere in his
job as an editor/censor, his brother asked, ``Why don't you try
America?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Liu entered the University of Hawaii, where he earned a
master's degree in American history. Then he came to Emory, where,
in 1996, he earned his Ph.D. in American history.
</P>
<P>
   Now he leaves to carry back to China some of what he has learned
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Those involved in the project, from Carter to Pastor to Liu, say
Chinese officials most likely initiated village elections as a
safety valve, to avoid upheaval in the rural areas, whence all
China's revolutions have come.
</P>
<P>
   A duty as well as a right
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motivation, Carter called China's initiation of
village elections ``a legitimate democratic achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it will be extended from the village level to the
county level, and then to the province level and then to the
national level is totally conjectural,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Liu said the task goes beyond teaching Chinese officials, who
have no experience with it, the ins and outs of democracy. He wants
to convince the Chinese people that democracy is a duty as well as
a right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your vote,'' he will emphasize, ``is not only secret but also
sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   Liu felt hostility from some Chinese when he made the trip in
March, as if he were a sellout for working with Americans.
</P>
<P>
   He feels Chinese, though. He will not return there to live right
now, because he fears his 12-year-old daughter (he also has a 3
1/2-year-old girl) would have difficulty catching up with written
Chinese. But he has not sought American citizenship, either,
because that would mean renouncing his Chinese citizenship and
negating, he said, the first quarter-century of his life.
</P>
<P>
   He will continue working for democracy in China, he said, ``no
matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the children are grown, he and his wife will probably
turn their eyes East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking that, when we get old, we probably want to live
in China,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
