<HEADLINE>
SENATE KILLS HISTORIC TOBACCO LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate killed tobacco legislation Wednesday in
the face of a multimillion advertising campaign by cigarette
companies and numerous amendments tacked on by Republican leaders
who declared the bill too pricey and too big.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the legislation came a year after health
advocates, attorneys general from 41 states and cigarette companies
agreed to a more modest settlement to curb smoking among
teen-agers. But that settlement, which needed congressional
approval, was replaced by the much stronger legislation that the
tobacco industry refused to accept.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly four weeks of debate on the bill that would boost
the price of cigarettes, raising at least $516 billion over 25
years, opponents used a two-vote knock-out punch to effectively
shelve the bill.
</P>
<P>
   First, by a vote of 57 to 42, supporters failed to win a motion
for cloture that would have ended debate and forced a vote on the
tobacco legislation. That effort needed 60 votes to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   In a second vote, Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, raised a budgetary
point of order, saying the bill violated spending caps in the
five-year budget plan approved last summer. The Senate voted 53 to
46, falling shy of the 60 votes needed to wave the budget
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, who at first moved to shut
off debate, then declared he would cast his ballot against cloture,
signaling to fellow Republicans to kill the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally had a vote for sanity,'' said Sen. Don Nickles,
R-Okla., a critic of the legislation from the start. ``This bill
was not salvageable.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the tobacco industry's advertising
campaign played a key role in the defeat and added that ``there
should be political consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the American people understand fully what's been going
on, they won't like what they see,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, R-Miss., said earlier that the bill had ``gone far, far,
afield'' from its original goal of curbing smoking among
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who called the Senate bill
``a dead end,'' said Wednesday that House Republicans intend to
pass a simpler bill.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker said his ``highest priority,'' was to pass
``effective legislation that is narrowly focused on anti-teen
smoking, anti-drug efforts. Our goal is to reduce teen smoking, not
increase taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said after the vote that he, too, favored a narrower
version of tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that we can convince Senate Democrats and the White
House to join us in that effort without again resorting to the big
government, big tax, big spending bill that was defeated today,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco industry spokesman Steve Duchesne declared victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the public wins because massive taxes and the black
market were voted down,'' Duchesne said.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry launched a media blitz to persuade
Americans _ and their representatives in Congress _ that the
tobacco bill would unfairly tax tobacco companies and would create
a black market in cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four weeks, Senate Republicans have loaded the
tobacco bill with amendments. The amendments included a measure to
beef up federal anti-drug trafficking efforts and to reduce the
so-called marriage tax penalty, the extra money some married
couples pay beyond what they would if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   The bill _ sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. _ would have
raised the price of a pack of cigarettes by at least $1.10 a pack,
expanded the federal government's ability to regulate tobacco
advertising and marketing and imposed financial penalties on
cigarette makers if they failed to reduce teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., who made an
emotional plea for a vote on the McCain plan, later angrily blamed
Republicans for killing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans chose to kill the bill today,'' Daschle said.
``Their fingerprints are on it ... People will die as a result of
this bill. That is a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   C. Everett Koop, the surgeon general in the Reagan
administration, said he was ``terribly disappointed'' in the Senate
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Senator Lott and his colleagues have done today is public
health malpractice, plain and simple ... I hope that the senators
who derailed the bill today lose sleep every night listening to the
sound of children taking their first puff and the sound of
emphysema and cancer patients gasping for their last breath.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., attributed the defeat to a core
group of people ``who came to the floor determined to kill the
bill'' and then mounted a ``concerted strategy,'' to doom it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had a clear strategy that was in effect from day one, and
today they deliver the coup de gras.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., a longtime crusader against
tobacco companies, decried the ``unholy alliance'' between
Republicans and cigarette makers and pledged to battle to revive
the tobacco bill by repeatedly including it as an amendment to
other measures.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime tobacco foe Sen. Frank R. Lautenberg, D-N.J., said the
tobacco bill was killed by a ``sleight of hand and tricks designed
to fool the American people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
