A4245 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      06-17 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SAYS RUSSIA WAS WARNED OF BALKAN MANEUVERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Top NATO officials formally notified Russia about
Monday's aerial military exercises in the Balkans two days before
they took place, Western officials said Wednesday, although Russian
officials have complained they were left in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian defense minister, Igor Sergeyev, created a political
tempest here on Monday when he publicly rebuked the chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry Shelton, for failing to give
Russia advance word of the exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a soldier and I value honesty in people most of all,''
Sergeyev told Shelton, who was visiting here. ``I do not understand
why they did this to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Western officials said Wednesday that on Saturday NATO twice
informed Russia about the exercises planned over Albania and
Macedonia as a show of power to intimidate the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic. Ethnic Albanians in Kosovo are seeking
independence from Serbia, and Milosevic's forces have been crushing
the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   First, the NATO secretary general, Javier Solana, informed
Russia's ambassador in Brussels, Belgium, Sergei Kislyak.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Naumann, the German general who heads NATO's military
committee, also called Lt. Gen. Victor Zavarzin, Russia's chief
military representative to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be said with absolute clarity that the Russians were
left with no doubt on Saturday that the exercise would take place
on Monday morning,'' Naumann said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials were provided with a detailed account of plans
for the exercise, Naumann noted. They were told when it would begin
and that it would not exceed 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   One view is that Sergeyev was simply posturing. In an effort to
persuade Serbian leaders to stop their crackdown in Kosovo, NATO
planned the air exercise for the eve of meetings in Moscow between
Russian officials and Milosevic. The meetings resulted in a joint
statement by Russia and Serbia in which Milosevic agreed to reopen
talks with Kosovo leaders, but refused to bend on the key demand
that he withdraw his forces from the province.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian defense minister may have been trying to distance
himself from the air exercise and inoculate himself against
criticism that he was cooperating too closely with the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the exercise, Sergeyev expressed concerns about it.
But over the weekend Sergeyev sent a letter to Naumann, protesting
the timing and saying that it was the first step toward NATO
military intervention in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Naumann sent a reply to the Russian Defense Ministry on Sunday
evening. In his response, Naumann denied that the exercise
necessarily presaged military action.
</P>
<P>
   Another interpretation of Sergeyev's response is that he was
genuinely surprised because the Russian officials in Brussels had
failed to pass on the notification quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no problem with NATO-Russia communications,'' said
one diplomat. ``But there may be a problem with Russia-Russia
communications. We have seen some signs that Foreign Ministry
officials do not always pass information on to the Defense
Ministry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
