A4246 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOING-BUGGY-TEX     06-17 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOING-BUGGY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENEFICIAL BUGS BEAT CHEMICAL WARFARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who needs chemical warfare? Many garden centers carry beneficial
bugs that will fight your gardening battles for you.
</P>
<P>
   The most common soldiers are ladybugs, trichogramma wasps, green
lacewings, praying mantises and beneficial nematodes. And
earthworms, which don't eat pests but are good for the soil. Most
places don't keep lacewings and trichogrammas in stock because of
their short shelf life, but the stores will special-order them for
you. Here's a look at what these critters will do for you:
</P>
<P>
   Ladybugs: Ladybugs love to dine on aphids and other little bugs
such as thrips, mealybugs and spider mites. Aphids are those tiny
insects that suck the juices out of the tender new leaves on roses,
photinias, crape myrtles and other shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   Ladybugs come packaged in a mesh bag or a screen-top carton.
Refrigerated, they'll stay alive for several weeks, but you might
not know it, because they stop moving. At room temperature, you'll
see them crawling around in the container. They sell for
approximately $6 to $10 for 1,500 to 2,300 bugs.
</P>
<P>
   To put the ladybugs to work, water the plants where you want
them to linger, so they won't fly away in search of a drink.
Release them at the base of the plants at dusk or in the cool of
the morning. Repeat applications from mid-March through September.
</P>
<P>
   Trichogramma wasps: Don't confuse these garden helpers with
yellow jackets or other stinging wasps. They are gnatlike in size,
and they don't bother people. They do, however, lay their eggs
inside the eggs of such pests as cabbage worms, tomato horn worms
and corn ear worms. When the trichogrammas hatch, they feed on the
pests, killing them.
</P>
<P>
   Trichogramma eggs come on inch-square cards that look like
sandpaper, each holding up to 4,000 eggs. Some garden centers carry
the egg-coated cards; at others, you have to special-order them,
sometimes in multiples of two or three. They sell for approximately
$6 to $8 per square.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cards in the garden or attach them to a nearby tree.
Provide moisture to sustain the wasps.
</P>
<P>
   Green lacewings: These light-green, 3/4-inch insects are valued
for their gray-green larvae, sometimes known as aphid lions for
their voracious appetites for those pests. Mealybugs, spider mites,
thrips and insect eggs are other choice morsels.
</P>
<P>
   The microscopic eggs come in a brown paper sack, looking like
meal that you sprinkle on your plants. They have a short lifespan,
so they are special-ordered and delivered to your home.
</P>
<P>
   Lacewing eggs sell for approximately $13 to $15 per 1,000 or $25
per 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Praying mantises: Not every organic expert recommends these, as
they tend to gobble up every bug in sight _ including your prized
ladybugs and one another. If you don't fear for your other
beneficials, buy a foamy-looking brown cocoon and attach it to a
twig or leaf. A hundred or more praying mantises (up to several
hundred) will emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Praying mantis cocoons sell for approximately $4 to $8 each.
</P>
<P>
   Beneficial nematodes: These microscopic worms prey on the larvae
of such insects as fire ants, flies, fleas and grub worms.
Microscopic is right: A package that covers 8,000 square feet
contains 12 million nematodes. They look like a mealy substance.
Beneficial nematodes sell for approximately $20 to $25 for 7
million to 12 million nematodes.
</P>
<P>
   Soak them in water for 15 or 20 minutes, strain the liquid and
apply it to the yard with a watering can or a hose-end sprayer with
the screen removed. Keep the lawn moist for a month or so as the
creatures work themselves into the topsoil.
</P>
<P>
   Earthworms: The wiggly ones aerate the soil, allowing oxygen and
water to be absorbed by plant roots. They also enrich the soil with
their castings (droppings), adding minerals and nutrients that
plants need.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy either brown-nose manure worms or red wigglers; they
come in a bag, bucket or foam cup, along with some soil or compost.
Earthworms sell for as little as $2 a handful or $14 to $22 per
pound.
</P>
<P>
   Keep them moist until you release them. Some experts recommend
keeping them in the dark. Dig a foot-deep hole in the garden, add a
little compost or worm castings, and cover the worms with soil. Or
release them into your compost _ the outside of the pile, not the
inside, where the heat would bake them.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
