<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-WAR-MEMORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH TOWN CAN'T FORGET WORLD WAR II MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NOSSITER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORADOUR-SUR-GLANE, France _ At first it looks like hundreds of
other small towns lost in the French countryside, with its two
friendly cafes, its flower boxes and its proud little City Hall.
But the streets are straighter and the facades are cleaner, and
many buildings lie in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   All the town's past was taken away one bright June 10 more than
a half-century ago, when the SS came through. As part of a terror
campaign to cow the French Resistance, the SS machine-gunned the
men, herded women and children into the church and set it alight,
then burned the village down.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everybody in Oradour was killed, 642 people in all,
although it was never learned why Oradour had been chosen for the
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   The burned remnants of that story, and of Oradour's history,
have loomed for 45 years over the reconstructed town. Old metal
sewing machines, bicycles, pots and pans, even cars, all
grotesquely twisted from the heat, still lie in fragmentary
buildings that gape at the sky. Charles de Gaulle himself called
Oradour ``the symbol of the country's suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   The state carefully preserved the crumbling walls, and everyone
here knows by heart the meaning of the number 14. That was how many
fellow Frenchmen, from Alsace, were later convicted for taking part
in the massacre, among 21 in all.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Germans forced 13 Alsatians to join the SS
and thus participate in the killings. For years townspeople who had
Alsatian visitors were scorned. The Strasbourg soccer team was
boycotted in nearby Limoges. Visiting Alsatians, if they did not
want their tires slashed, did best to keep a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   Not last week. For the first time in 54 years an Alsatian walked
through the ruins of Oradour openly declaring his origins. The
mayor of Strasbourg, Roland Ries, was invited to take part in the
annual commemorative ceremonies of June 10. He laid a wreath at the
cemetery, spoke to a sister of victims and gave a modest speech at
the City Hall. ``Be assured that I am fully aware of your pain, and
so is everyone else in Alsace,'' Ries said.
</P>
<P>
   Elderly people at the ceremony remembered the smell of burning
flesh when they entered the town, unawares, on June 11, 1944. It
lasted for months, said Camille Bardet, who lost his sister, a
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The ruins themselves are still disturbing 54 years later.
</P>
<P>
   So some in Oradour talked only hesitantly about the ``beginning
of a reconciliation'' with Alsace, the easternmost French region,
like the former assistant mayor and town pharmacist, Henri
Cathalifaud. ``It's still a very sensitive question around here,''
Cathalifaud said. ``It took a long time for this town to come back
to life.''
</P>
<P>
   But others with good reason not to forget acknowledged that the
long passage of years had made old hatreds dusty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, we can't continue the war for 100 years,'' said Marcel
Darthout, who as a 19-year-old survived the massacre, one of six
men to do so, buried under a pile of bodies in a barn. ``It's got
to end. This should have happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Alsatians had asked Ries whether they could accompany him.
But he came virtually alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even a half-century hasn't made the bitterness disappear,''
the mayor of Oradour, Raymond Frugier, said. ``I said it was
important to turn a page, but not to burn one's bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   He was all beaming smiles for Ries, though.
</P>
<P>
   Ries proposed the Oradour visit himself.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview he said, ``I said to myself, 54 years later, the
time had come for reconciliation, and to talk to each other, and
share the grief of the families.'' A woman who lost both her
parents in the massacre put it more frankly, as the Strasbourg
mayor left the ruined church. ``Look, 54 years later we haven't
forgotten anything,'' she said. ``But he seems fairly nice. So why
not?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
