<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO BILL DEATH IN SENATE MAY BURNISH MCCAIN'S IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.) (WIth CONGRESS-TOBACCO, CONGRESS-TOBACCO-ASSESS) 
(af) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The death of tobacco legislation in the Senate
Wednesday was a stinging disappointment for Sen. John S. McCain of
Arizona, yet it may burnish his image as a Republican maverick.
</P>
<P>
   The dictionary, after all, defines a political maverick as one
``who bolts at will and sets an independent course'' from his
party.
</P>
<P>
   That is what McCain did on tobacco, as he did earlier on the
campaign-finance issue, in which he teamed with a Democrat, Russell
D. Feingold of Nebraska, in a futile attempt to change the ways
politicians raise money.
</P>
<P>
   It is what admirers and critics alike expect him to do if, to
the surprise of no one, he runs for president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In an impassioned speech on the Senate floor Wednesday, just
before the final defeat of the tobacco bill he had pushed, he
insisted the vote was not about taxes (some Republican leaders
tarred the bill as an old-fashioned ``tax-and-spend'' package), but
``whether we're going to allow the death march of 418,000 Americans
a year who die early from tobacco-related disease and do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was about ``whether we're going to have the will to
serve the public interest or the special interests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said he had heard a lot of talk about how the
outcome would define the Republican Party. On that theme, he chose
words that could have come from the mouth of a liberal Democrat:
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be something to that. Because maybe we ought to
remember the obligations that we incur when we govern America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We might want to understand that our obligation first of all
is to those who can't care for themselves in this society, and that
includes our children,'' he went on. ``Isn't it our obligation _
shouldn't it define the Republican Party that we should do
everything we can to handle this scourge, this disease that is
rampant throughout young children in America? Doesn't that define
the Republican Party?''
</P>
<P>
   No, Republican leaders said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Their rejection of the tobacco legislation he had shepherded
through the committee that he heads was particularly bitter, given
the overwhelming support the committee gave it only two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has caused the change in attitude since we reported this
bill out by a 19-1 vote through the Senate Commerce Committee?''
McCain asked on the Senate floor as he sensed doom. ``I don't know.
I'll leave that to others.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the legislation, which would have raised the price of a pack
of cigarettes by $1.10 and allowed the government to regulate
tobacco advertising and impose penalties on the industry if smoking
by teen-agers did not decline sharply, goes back to committee
limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, the conservative but hard-to-pigeonhole Arizonan
chuckled during a telephone conversation about Speaker Newt
Gingrich's opposition to the McCain-sponsored tobacco legislation
just voted out of the Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and other Republicans were calling the bill too tough
on the tobacco industry, or too liberal, McCain noted. But some
liberal Democrats, like Rep. Henry A. Waxman of California and Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts, thought it too lenient, McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So maybe we're in the right place,'' the senator said
good-naturedly. Wednesday, that place was outside the party tent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
