<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: KILLING TOBACCO BILL IS POLITICAL GAMBLE FOR GOP
</HEADLINE>
   (With CONGRESS-TOBACCO) 
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was a day of high risks on the volatile issue of
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   In killing anti-smoking legislation on Wednesday, Senate
Republicans took a leap of faith, trusting that the tobacco
industry's $40 million advertising campaign has so changed public
sentiment on the issue that there will be no election-year
ramifications from their vote.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry took a huge gamble as well _ that the
cascade of lawsuits it hoped to curb with the original settlement a
year ago will not bankrupt it. Those risks may be worse now than
they were then. Today, cases brought by individuals can be
buttressed by hundreds of damaging industry documents recently
disclosed as part of the settlement process in lawsuits brought by
states.
</P>
<P>
   The risks were emphasized as Democrats immediately vowed to
paint the Republicans as the tools of Big Tobacco in the fall
campaigns. That debate might again change the public mood on
tobacco and could cost the Republicans seats in the Senate, where
they can spare a few losses and still retain control, and the
House, where they have no room to spare.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton himself provided a preview of the campaign
themes when he made a final appeal to the Senate to ``protect the
children and not the tobacco lobby.'' Asked after the Senate killed
the legislation if there would be a political price to pay, he
said, ``I certainly hope there will be and there should be.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who had been one of the measure's
fiercest opponents insisted that ``the bottom line is the bill
never had any real support from the American people.'' And Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., who drafted the bill, acknowledged that more
and more Republicans had come to believe that the anti-tobacco
issue does not have the broad public support they once feared.
</P>
<P>
   He even said that some of the members of the Commerce Committee
who had sent the measure to the Senate floor on an overwhelming
19-1 vote now opposed the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   It was a turnaround in sentiment reminiscent of Clinton's defeat
in his effort to pass comprehensive health care legislation in
1994. And like the industry battle against health care, it was
partly brought about by a television ad campaign that portrayed the
legislation as a massive tax increase to pay for Big Government.
``When people call in, they parrot the ads,'' said McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year ago the mood was quite different. The prospect of a
comprehensive tobacco settlement seemed something historic that
would change forever the ways cigarettes are marketed in the United
States and alter the nation's public health and regulatory
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal hammered out by the tobacco industry and state
attorneys general, the tobacco industry would pay states $368.5
billion over 25 years for anti-smoking programs and to compensate
for the costs of treating smoking-related illnesses. In return the
companies would have got protection from a wave of court cases
against them.
</P>
<P>
   But that pact turned out to have a Perils of Pauline existence _
in large part because of the impression that after decades of
political dominance, Big Tobacco was on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   By last fall anti-smoking advocates like David Kessler, the
former commissioner of food and drugs, and C. Everett Koop, the
former surgeon general, had seized the public stage to push for
even tougher legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refused to endorse the proposed settlement in its
entirety even though his close adviser Bruce Lindsey had been
intimately involved in the negotiations that produced the proposal.
Instead, he described the basic principles he would like to see in
any tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the president made clear in his budget proposal this year
that he was counting that the settlement would be endorsed by
Congress. He proposed that $65.5 billion in appealing new programs
for child care, education and health be financed by some of the
revenues generated by a tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   When McCain and his Commerce Committee took up the effort to
draft a bill this winter, the political tide seemed to be running
strongly against the tobacco industry and Republicans were also
running scared. They had watched Bob Dole, their presidential
nominee, make the mistake during the 1996 campaign of questioning
whether smoking was addictive as Clinton posed as the defender of
the nation's children. They said they were not going to make that
kind of error in judgment again.
</P>
<P>
   And so after a marathon series of meetings and negotiations, the
committee produced a measure even tougher on tobacco than the
original settlement had been. It would cost the companies $516
billion over 25 years, increase penalties if teen-age smoking did
not drop and provide far fewer of the legal protections that the
industry had counted on.
</P>
<P>
   At that point tobacco walked out and vowed to fight the
legislation. Some predicted the defiance would boomerang and hurt
the industry further.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
