<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NASCAR, THE TRUTH SOMETIMES COMES SLIGHTLY PADDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a weekly basis, no TV series fuels more conspiracy theories
than The X-Files. But recent on-track events suggest that NASCAR's
Winston Cup Series, another TV ratings smash, is creeping up on the
paranormal/paranoia scale.
</P>
<P>
   If the truth is out there, it certainly has been difficult to
discern during the past two Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin's series-leading fourth victory in the Miller Lite
400 on Sunday somewhat was clouded by what kindly has been termed a
``questionable'' caution flag thrown to clear debris from the
Michigan Speedway in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   That caution _ the first of two in the race _ waved on lap 118
after Jeff Gordon had built a lead of nearly 10 seconds over
Martin. Gordon, the reigning Winston Cup champion, had lapped all
but 11 cars in the 43-car field.
</P>
<P>
   First reported as a piece of tailpipe from Sterling Marlin's
Chevrolet, the debris later was classified as a chunk of roll bar
padding that might have been thrown from one of the cars.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a highly paid, professional race-car driver
intentionally toss something onto the track? To artificially create
a yellow flag period, one that would keep himself and everyone else
on the lead lap from going a lap down to Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw people throwing things out the window right before the
caution came out,'' said Gordon, who remained in the lead after
pitting during the ``questionable'' caution and after a four-car
crash on lap 125 prompted the final yellow. But Martin was
relentless, passing Gordon on lap 150 and taking the lead for good
on lap 182.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nelson, NASCAR's Winston Cup director, said that a review
of videotapes and the ``evidence'' was inconclusive, as far as how
the debris got onto the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we consider the situation suspicious, there is no
conclusive evidence as to how it occurred,'' Nelson said.
``NASCAR's view of a caution flag is to warn drivers of potential
hazards. Obviously, roll bar padding is not a hazard, but we don't
know that until we go and pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin declined to pass judgment on NASCAR for the call. But he
noted that he and his driving brethren are ``only human.'' And the
humans driving stock cars have been known to fudge the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-File'' that under Driver Denies Knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the judgment of NASCAR officials openly was
questioned during the closing laps of the Pontiac Excitement 400 at
Richmond (Va.) International Raceway on June 6. The decision was
made to red-flag and stop the nighttime race with seven laps
remaining, rather than clean debris from a messy wreck under
yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Cup star Dale Jarrett, who was leading the race at the stoppage,
felt the decision not to click off laps under yellow ultimately
cost him the victory to Terry Labonte. Jarrett said the call to
red-flag went against NASCAR protocol. Mike Helton, NASCAR's vice
president for competition, said the sanctioning body merely was
trying to give the paying fans as many green flag laps as possible.
</P>
<P>
   A noble gesture, for sure. But the conspiracy theorists pointed
out that maybe this red-flag was not a coincidence. That perhaps
with a prime-time TV audience tuned-in and turned-on _ and a live
Indy Racing League event at Texas Motor Speedway playing on another
network _ that NASCAR stretched its rules for the good of the fans.
</P>
<P>
   And the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   And tough luck, Dale Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the situation suspicious? You can look at it in two
ways.
</P>
<P>
   As Fox Mulder once said, the truth is out there.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Bart Simpson once said, nothing is out there. &QL; 
THE BUZZ &QL; 
NHRA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pro Stock driver Bruce Allen of Arlington is ninth in the
National Hot Rod Association standings with 356 points _ a
remarkable statistic considering he has failed to qualify for four
of 10 events. Allen's latest DNQ was during the Pontiac Excitement
Nationals in Kirkersville, Ohio, on Saturday. Allen stood 16th on
the ladder after Friday's sessions, but he and the Outlaw Fuel
Additives Pontiac Firebird fell victim to tire shake on both
Saturday passes down National Trail Raceway. ``We had to change
some clutch discs Saturday, and it looks like it may have been a
defective batch of discs,'' said David Reher, who is partners in
the car with Allen and Buddy Morrison. ``I think that's what bit
us, because we were fine Friday night.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Pro Stock points leader Warren Johnson reportedly is a few weeks
away from unveiling his latest innovation _ a purpose-built,
clutchless 5-speed transmission. ``We started with a clean sheet of
paper and designed the new transmission from scratch,'' said
Johnson, a three-time champion and the acknowledged Professor of
Pro Stock. ``Most drag-racing gearboxes are basically updates of
30-year-old designs. We've simplified the gear-changing mechanism
and built the transmission to withstand higher torque loads. We've
even added a handle so you can carry the transmission like a
suitcase.'' Reher said he is aware of the project, which is being
engineered by specialist Leonard Long. ``Leonard has made some
refinements to a transmission that began as the Doug Nash
5-speed,'' said Reher, who estimated that perhaps 95 percent of
NHRA Pro Stock teams compete with the clutchless Liberty
transmission built by Craig Liberty. ``I don't think Warren's (new)
transmission will have any effect on his car at all. It may be
handier for changing gear ratios and as far as reliability. But
unless there's something I know nothing about, I don't see any
performance advantage.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Bernstein is on a two-race winning streak in Top Fuel
after having knocked off Bob Vandergriff Jr. at Columbus. It marked
the first time since 1991 that Bernstein, driver of the Budweiser
King Dragster, has posted consecutive victories. &QL; 
NASCAR  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin not only is NASCAR's hottest driver, he also is one
of the sport's top talent scouts. On many occasions, Martin has
said that Roush Racing teammate Jeff Burton is the best current
driver in Winston Cup _ period. Martin holds similar regards for
another protege, and a driver who could be his clone. ``Matt
Kenseth is a superstar in the making,'' Martin said of the driver
who won the pole and the Lycos.com 250 Busch Grand National race at
Pikes Peak International Raceway last weekend. Kenseth, who scored
his second series victory, also moved past Mike McLaughlin into
first place in the BGN championship chase by 73 points. ``Matt has
what it takes. I believed in that for over a year now,'' Martin
said. ``If somebody said to me, `Why don't you create from scratch
the ultimate race-car driver,' he's the one. The sport is hungry
for new talent, and he's it.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Cup team owner Bill Davis said the management of MBNA has
informed him it will not return as primary sponsor of the No. 22
Pontiac Grand Prix driven by Ward Burton next season. ... Circuit
City has announced that it no longer will sponsor the No. 8 Stavola
Brothers Chevrolet this season. The team plans to take a few weeks
off before reportedly returning to the series. ...
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup regular Bobby Hamilton will pull double duty at
Pocono Raceway this weekend. In addition to driving the No. 4 Kodak
Chevy fielded by Morgan-McClure Motorsports, he also will serve as
crew chief on the Automobile Racing Club of America Pontiac Grand
Prix driven by his 20-year-old son, Bobby Jr. &QL; 
IRL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart continues to shatter speed records on the Pep Boys
Indy Racing League tour. Stewart recorded a lap at 183.299 mph
Tuesday during open testing for the Pep Boys 400K at the 1-mile
Dover Downs International Speedway in Delaware. Unofficially, it is
the fastest speed recorded on the concrete oval featuring 24-degree
banked turns _ 27.401 mph faster than the NASCAR Winston Cup record
of 155.898 mph set by Rusty Wallace in May. ``We worked hard on the
chassis to get the car to go through the bumps really well, and
that was the secret,'' said Stewart, who drove the No. 32 Johns
Manville-Menards Special G Force/Aurora normally assigned to
teammate Robbie Buhl. ``I think the key to winning this race will
be who has the best motor, because everybody can run flat-out
here.'' The race is scheduled for July 19. Stewart won the pole for
the True Value 500K at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth with a
record qualifying lap at 224.448 mph, and then cracked off a lap of
228.012 mph during the night race June 6. ... Larry Curry, manager
of Team Menard, is leaning toward the G Force chassis at Dover. The
team competed with Dallara chassis at the Indy 500 and TMS. ``We
won the race at the 1-mile Orlando track with a G Force and
finished second with it at Phoenix, which is also a mile,'' Curry
said. ``We have a lot more data on the G Force at 1-mile tracks.'' &QL; 
FAST LAPS &QL; 
A TRUE HORSEPOWER MAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow marks the 50th anniversary of the first NASCAR
``strictly stock'' race, the forerunner of the series that evolved
into Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Transplanted Texan Jim Roper, the winner of that 200-lap event
at the three-quarter-mile dirt Charlotte (N.C.) Speedway, plans to
reminisce on his horse ranch in Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, not all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work every day,'' said Roper, who raises thoroughbred
horses. ``I'll be 82 in August and I feel as good as I can be for
my age. Hope I'm here for several more years. There's always
something to do here. I haven't been on a horse for 10 or 15 years,
but you have to walk the horses, feed and water and clean up after
'em. You can stay pretty busy. I get great satisfaction out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing a Lincoln he had driven from Kansas, Roper originally
finished second at Charlotte to Glenn Dunnaway. But Dunnaway and
the 1947 Ford he was hired to drive were disqualified when a
post-race inspection found that the car's rear springs had been
modified with a wedge _ a device commonly used in ``whiskey cars''
run by moonshiners of the era.
</P>
<P>
   Roper said that with all due respect to NASCAR founder Bill
France Sr., he scored the race himself from inside the car, using a
counter out of a slot machine. When the race was over, he put the
upholstery back into the car, changed tires and wheels and took it
to an auction _ a clean, one-owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my first stock-car adventure,'' said Roper, who said
he ran in two of eight NASCAR events in '49 before concentrating on
open-wheel cars. ``It's still the best one (victory) I ever had.'' &QL; 
NUTS AND BOLTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eleven events remain on the Championship Auto Racing Teams'
FedEx schedule, and nine are on either natural terrain road-courses
or temporary street circuits.
</P>
<P>
   Team KOOL Green driver Paul Tracy has been placed on probation
by CART chief steward Wally Dallenbach for making contact with
Christian Fittipaldi and causing him to spin during the Detroit
Grand Prix on June 7.
</P>
<P>
   Car owner Andy Petree took Ken Schrader's Skoal Bandit Racing
Chevy to the wind tunnel in Warren, Mich., after the Miller Lite
400. The team was looking for aerodynamic data on their speedway
car.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace's Winston Cup winless streak has reached 43 races.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, Mark Martin and Dale Jarrett _ second through
fourth in Cup points _ are separated by seven points.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Pawuk has cracked the NHRA Pro Stock top 10 with the Summit
Racing Pontiac for the first time this season, at 10th, with 343
points. &QL; 
LAST WORDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a ruthless sport, there's no question about it. Maybe
it's the strong survive-type situation.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Davis, Winston Cup team owner who will lose primary
sponsor MBNA after this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
