<SLUG> BC-BUZZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERMAN FINDS HIS INNER STRENGTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Still Me'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An autobiography by Christopher Reeve &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Random House &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $25 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not a knock on ``Still Me'' to say it was inevitable that
Christopher Reeve would publish an autobiography after the 1995
riding accident that left him a quadriplegic. Before the accident,
Reeve was best known for playing Superman. Now he is another sort
of icon, one whi is real and not pretend.
</P>
<P>
   If Reeve has paid a horrible price for his new style of
celebrity, he is determined to use this notoriety on behalf of
``everyone whose life has been touched by disability,'' to quote
from ``Still Me's'' dedication.
</P>
<P>
   Although his acting was sometimes wooden, Reeve proves with his
book that he is a genuine intellect. Produced without the
assistance of a ghost writer, ``Still Me'' is a moving, honestly
told tale that never descends into self-pity.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve begins his memoir with an idea for a movie he came up with
a few months after his accident. The plot is deceptively simple: a
quadriplegic who once loved to sail gradually loses himself in
shipboard fantasy until he is ready to abandon his waking,
physically challenged life for the dreams he hopes come with death.
At the last minute, he realizes that the love and support of his
family mean more than escape, and he accepts his physical
limitations instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think: This can't be my life, there's been a mistake,''
Reeve writes. ``It took a lot of adjustment. It still does.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Reeve uses about half his book to recount his
pre-accident life and career, ``Still Me's'' real impact comes from
his description of the accident and his life since.
</P>
<P>
   He is brave enough to leave nothing out _ we learn how his
underpants are changed and follow the tortured process he endures
to achieve bowel movements _ and honest enough to admit that the
resulting loss of dignity continues to bother him.
</P>
<P>
   Most poignant are Reeve's descriptions of frustration with his
family _ not out of any lack of love, but with his inability to put
his arms around them and hug back.
</P>
<P>
   His son Will is now 5 1/2, and ``I haven't been able to give
(him) a hug since he was 2 years old.'' To compensate, father and
son romp outside, Will on his bike and Reeve in a special motorized
wheelchair. Will always wins those races, and Dad is a good-sport
loser. Other times, Will plays indoor hockey games, and Dad
pretends that he and his wheelchair are the ice-smoothing Zamboni.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve, of course, has some proselytizing to do. He wants more
government funding for spinal injury research; he has founded the
Christopher Reeve Foundation to support quality-of-life programs
for people with all kinds of disabilities. (The prominently
mentioned address for those who would like to contribute is Box
277, FDR Station, New York, NY 10150-0277.) Reeve also hopes to be
among the first volunteers in scheduled experiments at attempting
nerve regeneration.
</P>
<P>
   We could be trite and conclude that Reeve turned out to be
Superman in real life, but ``Still Me'' engenders enough respect
for the author to eschew flowery tributes.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve crippled his spine, not his heart. ``Still Me'' ought to
be required reading for anyone who feels sorry for himself.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
