<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRES-WALDO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fire forces many to leave home
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALDO, Fla. _ After two weeks of oven-dry heat, it finally
rained Wednesday _ a mist of white and black ash that fell from an
eerily dark midday sky.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Richey ignored it as he narrowed his possessions to
those that would fit in his green-and-tan Ford Explorer: baby
photos of his children, a change of clothes, his homeowners
insurance policy. Like his neighbors in this tiny community
northeast of Gainesville, Richey had to leave home as the state's
monthlong heat wave came to town in the form of an out-of-control
blaze that now burned just a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Fires continued burning around the state Wednesday as they have
for more than a week, but perhaps none burned closer to homes than
the blaze that by afternoon had consumed 3,000 acres just upwind of
Waldo.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters working in the 97-degree heat used bulldozers to
dig their last stand of sorts: a firebreak on the clear cut path
under some high-tension power lines on the western outskirts of
town, just a half-mile from Richey's Line Avenue house.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's on TV, it's interesting. When it happens to you,
it's a different story. It's scary,'' said Richey, a 42-year-old
mailman and former city council member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our house is right in the line of fire,'' said Gertrude Hill,
a neighbor who had stuffed her Jeep full of mementos and was
heading to find a motel for the night.
</P>
<P>
   At least 20 wildfires burned throughout Florida on Wednesday as
another day of temperatures in the 90s and consistent winds made
smoldering embers quick to flare up. Record high temperatures were
recorded around the state, including 96 in tampa, 99 in melbourne,
98 in daytona beach and 99 in orlando
</P>
<P>
   In all, 94 wildfires in 25 counties have burned nearly 43,000
acres since Memorial Day, causing at least 13 injuries and one
death and damaging at least 78 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Some were intentionally set, and Wednesday brought the first
arrest. Police arrested a 12-year-old Putnam County boy on three
counts of unlawful burning of land, a felony.
</P>
<P>
   For Waldo, about as far from an ocean as is possible in Florida,
evacuations had been a rarity. Tornadoes are uncommon. Hurricanes
have typically lost their punch by the time they reached so far
inland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take a hurricane any day,'' grumbled Pete Hermanson, 65,
wearing a paper mask to filter the haze and setting lawn sprinklers
to wet down his roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know what a fire is going to do, really. A
hurricane, you can board up,'' said Hermanson, who moved to Waldo
from Hollywood after a near miss by Hurricane Andrew in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's recommended evacuation was the second in two days,
as the fates of the residents' homes changed, literally, with the
wind. Some 500 residents _ about half the town _ were asked to
leave their homes Tuesday when the fire first threatened. Winds
moved to a more favorable direction, the fire seemed to be
contained, and residents were told to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Then the wind shifted back to the southwest and kicked up
Wednesday, letting the fire jump Tuesday's fire break into new,
unburned territory. Alachua County Sheriff's officials again
advised residents to leave while considering whether to ask Gov.
Lawton Chiles to declare a mandatory evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't look like we're going to get a break with the
weather,'' said sheriff's spokeswoman Linda White as she scanned
the sky from the command post officials had set up on the median of
the road between Waldo and Gainesville. ``It's such an iffy
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's forecast calls for temperatures in the high 90s
throughout the state with a slight chance of thunderstorms in some
areas.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the only cloud of any substance in Waldo was the
pillar of brown and black that billowed upward, giving the sun a
burnt orange cast in the middle of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies patrolled the streets, advising residents to get out
with a simple message: ``This thing is out of control and headed
this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldo Community School Principal Dewitt Lewis meanwhile tried to
round up the latchkey children of parents who work in Gainesville
and to get them to board the city buses waiting in the parking lot
to shuttle those without car to a shelter at the Alachua County
Fairgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have kids that sometimes won't listen to anybody,'' he
said. ``As night falls, the smoke settles and it gets ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Most adults, though, took the evacuation advisory seriously,
packing what they could and driving to friends, relatives or the
shelter. Down the street, Kevin Kelley, 40, finished wetting down
the shingled roofs to his mother's house and tool shed with water
pumped from a well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's worthwhile or not,'' said Kelley,
wrinkling his nose against the thickening wood smoke. ``I don't
know. It's strange. We've never had anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
