<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-FIRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fires imperil Florida homes
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE -- As helicopters hauling huge buckets of water
buzzed flaming patches of trees, worried residents doused their
homes with lawn sprinklers and prayed that winds wouldn't send the
wildfires plaguing Florida any closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put the sprinkler on the roof and wet it down, that's all you
can do _ that and pray,'' said Gary Motley, who lives on this
sprawling city's west side.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen fires flared Wednesday in nine northeastern
Florida counties, most in rural, wooded areas between Jacksonville
and Gainesville. Dozens of people were evacuated from their homes
in several areas.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, one structure was reported damaged by flames
that jumped firefighters' lines in the small town of Waldo.
</P>
<P>
   The fires have also hit Charlton County, Ga., just north of the
Florida state line. About 100 people were being asked to evacuate
their homes in Charlton County late Wednesday, said Lynn McElroy of
the Georgia Division of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 9,000 acres of rural timberland were reported
burned there, with teams of firefighters working to keep the flames
from reaching homes near the town of St. George.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's done a lot of damage, but we're fortunate that it didn't
get our house,'' said Jeanette Bell, a Charlton County resident who
had to evacuate Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   There were also evacuations in Jacksonville's west side and in
Waldo, about 15 miles northeast of Gainesville. Waldo residents had
to evacuate Tuesday and were allowed to return to their homes
Wednesday, only to be told to leave again as the flames rekindled,
fueled by unseasonably hot temperatures and extremely dry
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know in the movies with the twisters and disasters _ last
night that's what it seemed like, everybody running around in a
small town,'' said Chad Ricey, 17, who helped his father, Michael,
carry their possessions to their car.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just take what you can,'' his father added. ``As long as
your family is out, everything else can be replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of injuries Wednesday evening in Waldo or
Jacksonville. But two Jacksonville firefighters were overcome with
smoke and exhaustion, fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The fires have plagued Florida for the past month, burning
43,000 acres in 25 counties stretching from the Panhandle to
Jacksonville and south to the Fort Myers area. The blazes have been
blamed for one death and 13 injuries and damaged 78 structures.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have asked for more firefighters and equipment
from neighboring states that are members of the 13-state
Southeastern Forest Compact. North Carolina sent 36 firefighters
and 10 bulldozers to the Florida fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not used to dealing with this large a situation,'' said
Bruce Hill, a spokesman for the Florida Forestry Division.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a dozen homes near St. Augustine burned, as well as
five homes in Hilliard, a small town north of Jacksonville near the
state line.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke from the fires also prompted the Florida Highway Patrol to
close section of I-10 and I-95 on Tuesday, leading to massive
traffic jams and tempers almost as hot as the blazes. Both roads
were open Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The three-month drought that has set the stage for the fires has
led to a water crisis in Jacksonville, with city officials
restricting lawn sprinkling and urging residents to conserve water.
Their fear is that water supplies will be pushed so low that
firefighters won't have anything to tap should the blazes bear down
on heavily populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Jacksonville Mayor John Delaney also banned
fireworks and canceled the city's upcoming July 4th celebration, as
several other Florida cities are contemplating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Effective immediately, we're banning the use and sale of
fireworks,'' Delaney said. ``The risks are simply too high.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
