<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4267 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERNECON-COX     06-17 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERNECON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South's rise again shown after 60 years
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A famous federal report of 1938 documenting the poor,
malaria-ridden South was revived Wednesday by an advisory board of
Southern governors for its sheer dramatic contrast with the
economic powerhouse the region has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education and Progress in the South,'' a glossy report
unveiled in Washington by the Southern Regional Education Board,
updated by 60 years much of the data originally compiled at the
request of President Franklin D. Roosevelt. Between then and now,
the region's transformation is stunning.
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, the combined endowments of every college and university
in the South could not match those of Harvard and Yale, and the
exodus of its ablest people, including nearly half of the eminent
scientists born in the South, left too many children to be educated
by the poorest and oldest adult population in America.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the combined endowments of the University of Texas, Texas
A&AMP;M, Rice and Emory alone nearly match Harvard and Yale's. More
Southerners have college degrees now _ 21 percent _ than had high
school degrees 60 years ago. Houston is the nerve center of space
exploration, Atlanta is in the consciousness of the entire planet
24 hours a day through CNN and the world's most-recognized
trademark of Coca-Cola, and Research Triangle Park in North
Carolina is the leading example of business-university research
synergy, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any review of today's economic hot spots features a decidedly
Southern drawl _ Atlanta, Austin, the Research Triangle, Nashville,
Houston, Birmingham _ and the list goes on,'' U.S. Secretary of
Education Richard Riley said as he accepted the report.
</P>
<P>
   Many Southerners remember, and some still resent, the picture of
the South drawn by the 1938 report of the National Emergency Board
commissioned by Roosevelt. Roosevelt, who invoked his part-time
residence in Georgia and friendships there as part of his
motivation, said the main reason for the report was his view that
the South, as the last holdout of the Great Depression and ``the
nation's No. 1 economic problem,'' was keeping the country back.
</P>
<P>
   But few today have actually read the 64-page report, said
Kentucky Gov. Paul Patton, SREB chairman. ``The most important
point,'' he said, ``is that President Roosevelt was correct.''In
1938, the average income in the South was 52 percent of that in the
rest of the country. In the 1990s, the per capita income is 92
percent of the national average. Professionals are pouring into the
region, more than half of the country's job growth has been in the
South and two of the top five states in manufacturing growth are in
the South.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike SREB's typical reports filled with data on annual
progress toward various educational goals, the 16-page progress
report is a one-time celebraton of the South's, and SREB's, success
based on a historical coincidence. Mark Musick, president of the
Atlanta-based SREB, said the board felt it was time to take a
longer view of change in the South since this month is not only the
anniversary of the 1938 report, but also the 50th anniversary of
SREB.
</P>
<P>
   The SREB, funded by the governors of 15 Southern states, has
historically embodied the post-World War II agenda of Southern
leaders who believed the region's ticket out of the doldrums was to
invest in educational infrastructure and standards, first in the
colleges and universities, then in the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   This vision, which also is reflected in the 1938 report through
the influence of the likes of former University of North Carolina
President Frank Porter Graham, focused more on regional poverty
than on racial injustice. Graham, at the time, said black and white
Southerners have ``fundamentally a common destiny in building a
nobler civilization, and, if we go up, we go up together.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians cite various factors behind the South's economic
success, from the dismantling of legal segregation to air
conditioning. But the SREB report, in suggesting causes, sticks to
its long-time agenda of investment in education funding and the
raising of academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   This agenda, like the South's economic boom, has spread beyond
the region itself. A 1988 SREB report setting 12 education
benchmarks for the 15 Southern states led to similar education
goals for the entire country. Many of its governor members, such as
Bill Clinton of Arkansas, Lamar Alexander of Tennessee and Riley of
South Carolina, have gone on to shape education policy nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in an inversion of the 1938 statistics, student-teacher
ratios in the South are lower than the U.S. average. Like 60 years
ago, Southern states spend a larger share of their tax dollars on
education, but that share is falling and teacher and faculty
salaries remain below the national average, said former Virginia
Gov. Gerald L. Baliles, chairman of the SREB Commission for
Educational Quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the South is a place of remarkable progress and
momentum,'' Baliles wrote in the introduction. ``It will continue
to be if we recognize that our infrastructure now is as much
intellectual as it is physical.''
</P>
<P>
   But the report notes gaps in the infrastructure. A rural band of
600 counties running across the region's midsection holds 35
percent of the nation's poor and 90 percent of its poor blacks.
Racial inequality, an issue skimmed over by the 1938 report, is
today a continuing challenge to a prosperous South, the new report
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, recalling with a catch in his voice the public schools he
attended in Greenville, S.C., among folks that the 1938 report
compared to the poorest peasants of Europe, said he enjoyed
advantages that too many of his neighbors lacked. ``Southern
elementary, secondary and higher education was segregated,
under-funded, under-utilized and under-appreciated by the people of
an impoverished, agrarian society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
