<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ITALY-NY     06-17 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ITALY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY BEATS CAMEROON 3-0 AND BENEFITS AGAIN FROM IFFY CALL BY
REFEREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELLIER, France, June 17 _ Luigi Di Bagio will remember how
he used his head to score Italy's 100th goal in the World Cup
finals. Alessandro Del Piero will remember how he came off the
bench midway through the second half and helped Christian Vieri
score two late goals and finish a workmanlike 3-0 victory in style.
</P>
<P>
   The Cameroonians will remember how they felt in the 43rd minute.
</P>
<P>
   In the 43rd minute, the Australian referee Lennie Edwards
sprinted across the field to send Raymond Kalla, a Cameroonian
defender, off the field for good with a red card. Kalla had not
tackled from behind, an act that FIFA president Joseph Blatter
wants banned. Kalla was trying to catch up with a ball he had been
dribbling comfortably until his last touch had pushed it too far
ahead. Di Biagio slid aggressively toward the ball and touched it
first. Kalla, a big man, kept coming and, upon arrival, his large
right foot made contact with the ball and his large left foot then
swung forward into the prone Di Biagio's lower body, causing him to
scream in pain.
</P>
<P>
   Cameroon would never get the chance to play with 11 men again,
and for the second time in two matches in this World Cup, a
controversial decision by a referee would work in favor of Italy,
which now leads Group B with 4 points heading into its final
first-round game against Austria on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In its opening match against Chile, Italy was trailing by 2-1 in
the 85th minute when referee Lucien Bouchardeau of Niger awarded
Italy a penalty kick after the Chilean defender Ronaldo Fuentes'
right fist got in the way of a ball kicked by Roberto Baggio.
Fuentes, whose fist was by his side when it touched the ball
meaning it was an unintentional hand ball, was understandably
surprised, and Baggio wasted no time knocking the penalty kick into
the net to salvage a draw and a point.
</P>
<P>
   Edward's decision Wednesday came at a much less crucial moment.
Cameroon already was trailing by 1-0 after Di Bagio's goal in the
seventh minute. But Kalla's red card reduced the young and gifted
Cameroonian players' chances of closing the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned,'' said Kalla, who had not yet committed a foul
in the match. ``I mean the first thing I touched was the ball. I've
never gotten a red card before, not even in a club match. I think
the referee thought that I had fouled somebody earlier. He got me
confused with another player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italians were sometimes in need of protection during this
testy, uneven match. There were several dangerous tackles from
behind by Cameroon players that were not sanctioned at all, and in
the end, four other Indomitable Lions were awarded four yellow
cards to go with Kalla's red. The Italians received two of their
own.
</P>
<P>
   DiBiagio was in the right place, unmarked and unflappable, when
Roberto Baggio found him with a cross in the seventh minute. By
then, all of Italy knew that Coach Cesare Maldini had elected to
ignore Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi's suggestion that he use
Baggio and Del Piero together. Del Piero, one of the world's
premier players, is the man who made Baggio dispensable at his
former club, Juventus. But after Del Piero arrived in France with a
strained leg muscle and Baggio arrived in terrific form, the small
and speedy Del Piero became a substitute.
</P>
<P>
   When he replaced Baggio in the 65th minute Wednesday, Cameroon
was in the process of making the Italians forget their opponents
only had 10 men on the field. Instead of retreating into a
defensive shell, Cameroon had opened the second half aggressively,
and in the 58th minute Joseph-Desire Job, a substitute, had
Cameroon's best chance to score when he slammed a shot toward the
upper-left corner of the Italian goal that Gianluca Pagliuca barely
managed to knock away.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after Del Piero's arrival, the flow of the game
began to take a more logical direction. Vieri, the muscular
Atletico Madrid striker, would capitalize on a lovely pass from
Francesco Moriero to score in the 75th minute and on Del Piero's
penetration and a disoriented Cameroonian defense to score in the
89th. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
