   ``Today, the South is a place of remarkable progress and
momentum,'' Baliles wrote in the introduction. ``It will continue
to be if we recognize that our infrastructure now is as much
intellectual as it is physical.''
</P>
<P>
   But the report notes gaps in the infrastructure. A rural band of
600 counties running across the region's midsection holds 35
percent of the nation's poor and 90 percent of its poor blacks.
Racial inequality, an issue skimmed over by the 1938 report, is
today a continuing challenge to a prosperous South, the new report
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, recalling with a catch in his voice the public schools he
attended in Greenville, S.C., among folks that the 1938 report
compared to the poorest peasants of Europe, said he enjoyed
advantages that too many of his neighbors lacked. ``Southern
elementary, secondary and higher education was segregated,
under-funded, under-utilized and under-appreciated by the people of
an impoverished, agrarian society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
