<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE KILLS TOBACCO BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a victory for the tobacco industry, Senate
Republicans Wednesday buried an anti-smoking measure after almost
four weeks of roller-coaster debate over proposals to sharply raise
cigarette prices and regulate tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by GOP Senate leaders to shelve the most ambitious
legislation to come before Congress this session drew sharp
criticism from President Clinton, who made it clear that he
believed the lawmakers were influenced by tobacco company lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has pumped millions of dollars into a national ad
campaign characterizing the legislation as a big tax, big
government program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the tobacco lobby and its allies on Capitol Hill to
know that from my point of view this battle is far from over,''
Clinton said after a series of parliamentary maneuvers essentially
killed the bill. ``If more members of the Senate would vote like
parents rather than politicians, we could solve this problem and go
on to other business.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Asked if there would be political repercussions for those who
killed the bill, Clinton replied: ``I certainly hope there will be,
and there should be. I think when the American people understand
fully what has been going on they won't like what they see.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said the tobacco
legislation had become too unwieldy. GOP members tacked on a number
of amendments, such as effort to remedy the so-call ``marriage
penalty'' in the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with the bill now is it's lost sight of the
original noble cause of just dealing with teen-age smoking and drug
abuse,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate legislation would have raised cigarette prices by
$1.10 a pack and generated $516 billion over 25 years. It would
have given the federal government broad power to regulate tobacco
products and prohibited tobacco advertising aimed at youths.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the legislation a ``smokescreen,'' Sen. John Ashcroft,
R-Mo., said the measure amounted to ``a massive tax on low-income
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican action was denounced by former Surgeon General C.
Everett Koop, a Reagan appointee, who has led public health
spokesmen advocating anti-tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that the senators who derailed this bill lose sleep
every night listening to the sound of children taking their first
puff and the sound of emphysema and cancer patients gasping for
their last strength,'' said Koop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Republican senators know that they should be protecting
children and not big tobacco, but they just couldn't make
themselves do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   During the lengthy debate, amendments to divert some of the
money generated by price increases for tax cuts and anti-drug
programs and to cap attorney's fees were added to try and woo
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Though a clear majority of senators supported the bill,
conservatives successfully used procedural tactics to shoot it
down.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate Republicans, particularly those from the Northeast, had
been supportive of the measure, and proponents came within three
votes of the 60 needed to end debate and force a straight majority
vote on the bill's merits.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents then challenged the bill on a technicality, and
supporters fell seven votes shy of the 60 required to waive budget
constraints, effectively killing the measure. Texas Republicans
Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison joined those lawmakers voting
to bury the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, in particular, has been an outspoken critic, arguing the
legislation would impose unfair costs on low- and moderate-income
smokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill has no support in America,'' said Gramm after a
meeting where Republicans settled on their floor strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, who voted for the bill in the Commerce Committee,
refused to comment as she left the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor Democrats angrily denounced some Republicans
for demanding that tax cuts and anti-drug programs be added to the
measure and then voting to kill it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this bill goes down today Joe Camel wins and our kids
lose,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, referring to the popular
cartoon advertising icon.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that the ``this is not the end of this issue'' Sen.
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., vowed to tack the tobacco bill onto every
piece of legislation considered by the Senate this year.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, gave one Republican, Sen. John McCain, the
sponsor of the bill, a standing applause after he warned that the
losers in the measure would be the children who started smoking.
</P>
<P>
   While the Arizonan and other moderates have feared that tobacco
could be a potent issue in the next election, an increasing number
of Republicans have to come to believe that voters are
disinterested in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is people are not coming up to members and saying
this is an issue you have to deal with,'' said Sen. Connie Mack,
R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But some Democrats believe they can use the tobacco issue
against Republicans, particularly because GOP lawmakers have been
the primary beneficiary of millions of dollars of tobacco
contributions over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was thrust into the public arena last June when state
attorneys general and tobacco executives reached an unprecedented
agreement that would have required the industry to pay out $368
billion over 25 years to settle lawsuits brought by the states.
</P>
<P>
   That pact, however, was immediately attacked by public health
leaders as not tough enough because it provided some legal
concessions to the industry in the form of immunity from some
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Commerce Committee, chaired by McCain, threw out
most of the legal protections and raised the cost to the industry
to $516 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill passed overwhelmingly in committee, it has
steadily lost support as the tobacco industry stepped up its
advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton held out hope that Congress might still deal with
the tobacco issue this year, there is little chance that the
massive Senate bill will be resurrected.
</P>
<P>
   And in the House, Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., has made it
clear that Republicans will not consider a tobacco bill that
includes major price increases.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
