<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-AOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE ANNOUNCES IT WILL STAY INDEPENDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON and SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cooling off merger discussions with AT&AMP;T Corp., America Online
Inc., the United States' largest cyberspace company, said Wednesday
that it would remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   America Online has been in preliminary talks about a potential
acquisition by AT&AMP;T, the nation's No. 1 long-distance company, for
several weeks, according to people close to the discussions. But on
Wednesday, America Online's top executives said they had no
intention of selling the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to remaining an independent company, as that
is the best course for our customers, shareholders and employees,''
Stephen Case, the company's chairman, and Robert Pittman, its
president, said in an e-mail message to employees. ``We continue to
be eager to establish alliances with a wide range of
telecommunications, media and technology companies.''
</P>
<P>
   One person close to the companies said that while Case appeared
to oppose the idea of a merger, Pittman was willing to consider
such a move. The conversations between the two companies were
described by one person involved in the talks as ``fluid.'' The
person said that several issues needed to be worked out before any
deal could be announced.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the two companies were discussing the fate of
Tel-Save Holdings Inc., a small independent long-distance company
that owns the exclusive right to market long-distance service on
America Online. In acquiring America Online, AT&AMP;T would presumably
want to use the online service to sell long-distance service. But
there remain questions about whether AT&AMP;T would agree to acquire
Tel-Save for a price above its $1.1 billion market value, in
addition to agreeing to acquire America Online.
</P>
<P>
   One indication that the talks had not progressed far enough to
include a concrete offer was that Case did not discuss details of
the merger discussions with America Online's board members until
The Financial Times reported Wednesday that America Online had
rejected an offer from AT&AMP;T, said a person close to America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Still, people close to AT&AMP;T said that Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's
chairman, had meetings with top executives at America Online's
headquarters in Dulles, Va., during the week of May 17.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as telling as the talks themselves is what they reveal
about the direction that Armstrong wants to take AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to jump-start AT&AMP;T's entry into local phone markets,
Armstrong helped engineer AT&AMP;T's $11.3 billion acquisition of
Teleport Communications Group, a leading competitive local phone
provider, in January.
</P>
<P>
   But that deal was mostly speculative; it may be years before
AT&AMP;T offers local phone service to millions of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring America Online would be another bid for the future,
but it would have an immediate impact on AT&AMP;T's growth prospects
and on the structure of the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has built a sizable business providing Internet access to
consumers, serving 1.1 million customers. America Online has about
12 million customers and enjoys a brand that consumers associate
with cyberspace, rather than with monthly long-distance bills.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to the Tel-Save question, any deal between AT&AMP;T
and America Online would face serious hurdles of finance and
corporate politics as well as potential personality clashes.
</P>
<P>
   One problem for AT&AMP;T could be financial, though that does not
seem to have deterred Armstrong. As the most widely held stock in
the nation, AT&AMP;T is mainly valued based on its ability to deliver
steady earnings growth. But America Online's shares trade at almost
10 times the multiple of estimated earnings for this year than do
AT&AMP;T's.
</P>
<P>
   That means that if AT&AMP;T acquired America Online using stock, all
the new shares would heavily dilute AT&AMP;T's future per-share
profits. AT&AMP;T could use cash, but that would require servicing a
huge amount of debt. America Online has a market value of about
$20.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   More personally, Case recently joined the board of Worldcom
Inc., the No. 4 long-distance company, which has agreed to acquire
MCI Communications Corp., AT&AMP;T's archrival.
</P>
<P>
   Case joined Worldcom's board after America Online agreed last
year to sell its data communications network to Worldcom in a
complex three-way transaction in which Worldcom also acquired the
network of Compuserve, another big online service, while America
Online took over Compuserve's customers.
</P>
<P>
   America Online is now one of Worldcom's biggest customers.
Presumably, one of the financial rationales behind AT&AMP;T's seeking
to acquire America Online is that some of America Online's traffic
could be moved to AT&AMP;T's network, saving costs. It is unclear,
however, if the arrangements between America Online and Worldcom
would allow that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
