<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDWATER, GOLDWATER, GOLDWATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Here at ``The Goldwater Arizona Republic,'' with
offices conveniently located on Goldwater Van Buren Street in
downtown Goldwater Phoenix in the state of Goldwater Arizona, we
were awestruck by the City Council's decision to rename the local
metropolitan airport Goldwater Sky Harbor International.
</P>
<P>
   How can we not marvel at the accomplishment?
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to offend as few people as possible by choosing
simply to tack the Goldwater name onto the existing Sky Harbor
name, the Council managed to offend EVERYBODY.
</P>
<P>
   Success on that level won't go unnoticed by other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Any day, now, I expect elected officials with each city, county
and state government entity to spring into action.
</P>
<P>
   None of them can claim to be first, of course. The Goldwater
Phoenix City Council won that race by naming something big for the
former senator before anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   They had to. The Goldwater rush was on.
</P>
<P>
   If they'd waited a few weeks to allow their own citizens to make
a suggestion or two of their own, somebody might have done it
before them.
</P>
<P>
   Any day now you'll be able to take a little stroll into the
Goldwater Grand Canyon, maybe even all the way down to the
Goldwater Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
   You might get there, in part, by driving along historic
Goldwater Route 66.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was the Goldwater Phoenix City Council that struck the
mother lode first, ignoring the stated wishes of thousands of
living citizens and, near as I can tell, one deceased former
senator.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Council took its vote Tuesday, I told an aide of
Mayor Goldwater Skip Rimsza about a newspaper article that appeared
in the Nov. 4, 1990, issue of what was then called ``The Arizona
Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   It begins:
</P>
<P>
   ``Several years ago, Barry Goldwater flatly rejected the
suggestion that Sky Harbor International Airport be renamed for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goldwater turned down the honor, he said, because 'Sky Harbor'
is a name rich in tradition and treasured by thousands of pilots
and countless passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But last year, when then-Phoenix Mayor Terry Goddard proposed
that Sky Harbor's new $280 million terminal be named for Goldwater,
the 81-year-old retired U.S. senator from Arizona relented.
</P>
<P>
   `` 'When they got down to the building, I couldn't raise any
objection to that,' Goldwater said. 'It's a great honor. . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   And it was. And it is.
</P>
<P>
   But, for Goldwater Skip and his gold-digging compadres, it
wasn't enough. Who knows? Maybe the senator changed his mind
sometime before his death. Or even after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater Skip and Goldwater Grant Woods, the state Attorney
General who pushed for the name change, say Goldwater IS Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   And they plan to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater Skip said the airport's name should be changed even if
it was something the senator never asked for.
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, you'll soon be able to stroll over the
Goldwater London Bridge, swim in Goldwater Roosevelt Lake, explore
the ancient mysteries of Goldwater Montezuma Castle and witness a
re-enactment of the gunfight at the Goldwater OK Corral.
</P>
<P>
   Next fall, an adult education course on renaming everything
after Goldwater will be offered at Aqua de Oro Rio Salado Community
College.
</P>
<P>
   And you'll be happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   You will.
</P>
<P>
   Because, as you cruise south on the Goldwater Squaw Peak
Highway, staring at a downtown skyline dominated by the new
baseball stadium, you'll finally be able to smile.
</P>
<P>
   What had been the Bank One Ballpark will have become Goldwater
BOB, which sound's nothing like a financial institution and
everything like the senator's younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   That would please all of us.
</P>
<P>
   And Barry, too. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
