<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-THEATER-WING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES AT THE TOP FOR AMERICAN THEATER WING
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying that she craved more time to expand the
educational programs of the American Theater Wing, Isabelle
Stevenson said Wednesday that she would hand over the day-to-day
running of the organization to Roy Somlyo, who has been involved
with the wing's Tony Awards broadcasts since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stevenson, who has been president of the wing for 33 years,
will become the chairwoman, the first person to hold that post
since the death of Antoinette Perry in 1946. Somlyo will take over
as president.
</P>
<P>
   The wing's board approved the change on Tuesday night, and it
was announced at a monthly meeting of the Tony Administration
Committee on Wednesday afternoon at the offices of the League of
American Producers and Theaters, which presents the Tony with the
wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that I had little time to do so much that I wanted to
do,'' Ms. Stevenson said. ``I had been thinking about this for a
few years, and with the end of the season, and a very strenuous
season at that, it seemed like a logical time to make the change.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides presenting the Tony Awards, the wing sponsors
professional seminars, outreach efforts to introduce students to
the theater, a hospital program and an annual awarding of grants
and scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stevenson said she intended to export the wing's Working in
the Theater seminars to other cities, and also to expand the
Introduction to Broadway program that the wing conducts at public
and parochial schools in the five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isabelle is the greatest asset that the American Theater Wing
has, and we really should exploit that,'' Somlyo said. ``If she
removes herself from day-to-day operations, she can concentrate on
expanding some of the existing programs. She's an established
persona and we ought to be able to capitalize on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Somlyo, who has been managing producer of the Tony
Administration Committee for 12 years, has had a long career as a
Broadway producer and manager. Now, he said, he will devote his
full efforts to the wing. ``I don't anticipate any abrupt
changes,'' he said. ``I think this is more of a natural segue,
really.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Dobie, another veteran manager and producer, will succeed
Somlyo as the managing producer of the Tonys.
</P>
<P>
   The theater wing's earliest incarnation dates back to 1917, but
it became the American Wing of the British War Relief Society in
the 1930s. The wing began awarding Tonys, named for Antoinette
Perry, in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   The wing has never solicited corporate contributions, Somlyo
said, but has accepted them when offered. Now, he said, he intends
to start actively soliciting corporate money to help pay for
service activities, scholarships and grants.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stevenson and Somlyo will assume their new posts on Sept. 1.
Somlyo said he would use the summer for an orderly transition.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
