<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-ASSESS-330     06-17 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-ASSESS-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A NEW ECONOMIC ERA FOR JAPAN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DOLLAR-YEN, JAPAN-ECON, JAPAN-ECONSCENE,
JAPAN-MARKETPLACE, CREDIT, MARKET) 
(bl) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ As currency trading resumed Thursday morning in Asia,
the central question was simply: How much has changed?
</P>
<P>
   Has Japan, in making pledges Wednesday on an economic program to
strengthen its economy, really committed itself to far-reaching
changes? Do its pledges mark a turning point that will lead to a
firmer yen and to greater economic stability for Asia as a whole?
</P>
<P>
   Or are they merely warmed-over promises from yesterday? If so,
will the currency intervention by the United States and Japan be
overwhelmed within a few days by market forces, leading to an
ever-cheaper yen and to greater economic turmoil around the world?
</P>
<P>
   For now there are more questions than answers, but there is
evidence for both propositions.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States emphasized that Japan has agreed to more
specific actions, almost all the elements of the economic program
are already longstanding elements of Japanese policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recognizing that restructuring and revitalization of the
Japanese economy are urgently needed, we will make every effort to
restore its banking system to health, to achieve domestic
demand-led growth, and to open and deregulate its markets,'' Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said in a statement after a conversation
with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But Hashimoto has said the same things many times before.
Indeed, his latest comment was not nearly as strong as his
assertion a couple of years ago that he would restructure Japan
``or else burn up in flames trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Hashimoto pledged this time to abandon the ``convoy
system,'' whereby financial institutions move in tandem and are
hurriedly repaired or given new gas whenever they risk falling
behind. Yet Japanese officials have been saying since last year
that the convoy system has already ended.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe that Japan is likely to tinker with the
system rather than rapidly introduce fundamental changes, as the
markets would like.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``There's this Japanese view that if they just correct the
financial misadjustments, they'll be OK,'' said Ronald Morse, a
professor of economics and business administration at Reitaku
University near Tokyo. Morse said he doubted that any major change
was likely soon.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if Japan has not made any stunning new commitments that
might convince the markets, there are some reasons why Wednesday's
joint intervention may mark a turning point. Above all, there is
timing.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Japan's Parliament passed a supplementary
budget that amounts to the go-ahead for a stimulus package, worth
roughly $119 billion, that is the centerpiece of plans to revive
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials have been saying for months that Americans
should not be too impatient, that the parliamentary process will
take time, but that once passed, the package will revive the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The government has already made all the preparations to spend
the money, simply waiting for the measure's passage to push the
button, and so the funds are now going to trickle through Japan's
economic arteries almost immediately. There is some disagreement
about exactly how to measure the stimulus package and how effective
it will be, but almost everyone agrees that it is a major and
credible effort to stimulate economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Another element of timing is that Hashimoto has long been
expected to introduce new economic measures _ presumably more
far-reaching efforts at restructuring than anything announced so
far _ after elections for the upper house of Parliament on July 12.
So if Washington and Tokyo can prop up the yen with promises and
the odd billion dollars worth of market intervention for just a few
more weeks, then the combination of the stimulus package and the
new measures announced by Japan after the election may in turn
support the yen at a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of precedents for political action creating
turning points in the market. In 1985, the United States engineered
the Plaza Accord to end the strong dollar and bolster the value of
other currencies, and then by April 1995 the yen had soared so high
that Japan organized what has been called a ``reverse Plaza
Accord'' to weaken its currency.
</P>
<P>
   It then took only a little less than 80 yen to buy a dollar, but
Japan managed to turn the trend around and the yen steadily sank
ever since _ reaching an eight-year low of about 146 yen to the
dollar earlier this week. So now the governments are apparently
aiming for a ``reverse-reverse-Plaza Accord'' that would rely on
jawboning, intervention and shrewd timing to send the yen
permanently to higher levels.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are some fundamental reasons to be skeptical about
whether the current coordinated effort can really change the market
environment for the yen. The currency has been tumbling in part
because Japanese capital has been fleeing abroad in search of
higher interest rates, and that is unlikely to change.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even some Japanese government officials worry that
restructuring the economy along market lines _ while advantageous
for the long run _ may in the short term create more anxieties.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto pledged, for example, to ``expeditiously restructure
the financial system.'' It is not clear what that means, but many
analysts believe that Japan has too many banks and that some should
be put out of the public's misery. Thus, a serious restructuring
might lead to more bankruptcies and bank failures, and it is not
clear that in the short run such actions would do much for public
sentiment or the strength of the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the package does for the Japanese economy and the yen,
it presumably will be helpful to Hashimoto and his ruling Liberal
Democratic Party. Hashimoto has been criticized in Japan for not
doing enough to revive the economy, and he can now argue that he is
working in conjunction with President Clinton to tackle the
problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
