<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4298 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-ASSE     06-17 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-ASSESS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: industry further.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the industry went on the attack, with heavy advertising. As
Clinton, mindful of his experience on health care, said, ``Those of
us in politics know that unanswered ads can sometimes be fatal.''
And as the ads ran across eight weeks, Republicans began sounding
the same themes and toughening their stance against McCain's bill.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich branded it a ''very liberal,
big-government'' measure. Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader,
called it a ''big spending bill'' even as he let debate play out on
the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   This week the Republican pollster Linda DiVall and her polling
firm, American Viewpoint, produced a new poll reporting that only
22 percent of those surveyed thought supporters of the tobacco bill
were mainly interested in cutting teen smoking, while 69 percent
said the supporters wanted to get additional tax revenue for the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The firm advised that ''the power of the teen smoking issue can
be completely overwhelmed when recast as a message where the
candidate places a higher priority on cracking down on illegal drug
use and addressing juvenile violence and enforcing the law against
retailers who illegally sell cigarettes to minors.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on Wednesday vowed to keep the tobacco legislation
alive by attaching it again and again to other, unrelated
legislation. ``This bill may be dead. But tobacco legislation is
not dead,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle, the minority leader.``We will
not let this issue die. We will come back. We will keep at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The tactic worked two years ago on a minimum wage increase. But
that was a much simpler, more clearcut issue.
</P>
<P>
   So it is more likely that the battle over tobacco will live on
this year only as an issue in the fall campaign. And despite
Republican confidence, there were signs that the Democrats may very
well still be able to make headway on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Asking different questions from Republican pollsters, the
nonpartisan Pew Research Center recently found wide public support
for government efforts to regulate the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Kohut of Pew said the vote on Wednesday ``is certainly
not risk free but it's not guaranteed as a poison pill either.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Wednesday's outcome risk free for the tobacco industry,
which remains in a legal limbo. Cigarette makers still face
lawsuits from 37 state attorneys general and six of those cases
have been set for trial over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, some talks have begun between industry
officials and lawyers representing those states aimed at reaching
possible settlements. But one industry lawyer said that those
talks, which he described as ``feelers,'' were still at the very
early stage.
</P>
<P>
   One industry official said on Wednesday that tobacco companies
might seek to bring forward a new tobacco bill in the next session
of Congress that is more to their liking. But this hope may ignore
the lessons of recent political history. After all, Clinton's
health care proposal never did recover.
</P>
</TEXT>
