attention on a country that many foreign investors mistakenly
believe is still at war. Already, the state-owned electrical
distribution system has been divided into four regions and sold for
US$586 million to companies from Chile, the United States and
Venezuela. The new private pension system, Central America's first,
has lured heavyweights such as Spain's Banco Bilbao Vizcaya, U.S.
Citibank, Chilean pension funds Provida and AFP Magister and the
International Finance Corporation, a branch of the World Bank.
 &HT;    New opportunities over the next few years will center around
sectors that have been modernized and transferred to private
operators, with growth coming from new investment and the
development of related activities. But the groundwork has been laid
for El Salvador to compete as a regional center for industries
across the board. ``We are convinced that the only way to increase
wealth is to create jobs,'' says Economy Minister Eduardo Zablah.
``For that, we must have investment, and the only way to attract
investors is to reduce operating costs in this country.''
 &HT;    Since the peace accords, the government has been controlled by
the center-right, pro-business Alianza Republicana Nacionalista
(ARENA) party, led first by former President Alfredo Cristiani and
now by President Armando Calderon Sol. Cristiani's administration
focused on fiscal reforms that paid off in a successful monetary
policy that led to a rock-steady exchange rate that has remained on
track for the last four years, with inflation hitting
industrialized-nation levels of just 2 percent last year.
 &HT;    Moody's and Standard &AMP; Poor's, the two main international
ratings agencies, have responded in kind, awarding El Salvador with
some of the strongest investment-grade ratings in the region _ just
below Chile, but on par or above the much larger economies of
Argentina, Colombia, Mexico and Uruguay. The agencies also comment
on the country's ``broad-based support for economic reform'' and
``successful transition to stability and sustained growth.''
 &HT;    The private sector is even more generous. ``Maybe it's the size
of the place, but there's a transparency here you don't find in the
rest of Central America,'' says mining entrepreneur Robert
Johansing. ``Things move faster. People take an idea and put it to
work and you find out quickly whether it will be profitable.'' That
can-do attitude spreads from the factory floor, a la Texas
Instruments, to the highest management levels. Private-sector
leaders seem to understand the reality of free trade and
globalization better than many of their regional counterparts, due
in large part to El Salvador's small market. With the country's
population of only 5.9 million, its companies have looked abroad
for years to expand the market.
 &HT;    Plans for economic growth _ from privatization to industry to
the creation of an international service sector _ hinge on the
country's ability to capitalize on this global vision and to lure
investors and companies that share it. ``We don't consider Central
America an export. That's our local market,'' says Roberto Polomo,
president of Salvadoran shoe manufacturer ADOC. ``There's a lot of
work going on here in preparing for globalization.''
 &HT;    As stabilization was the hallmark of the Cristiani
administration, privatization and deregulation will mark the
presidency of Calderon Sol. Even as national elections loom on the
horizon, the president has succeeded in working with FMLN
opposition in keeping this year's main slate of privatizations on
target. This should boost the country's investment inflow from last
year's disappointing $25 million in registered investment to over
$1 billion in 1998. More important, the reforms leading up to the
sales of state holdings in power and telecommunications set the
stage for free competition once assets are transferred to private
ownership. Add the new private pension funds' ability to generate
local capital sources, and Calderon Sol has staked out his legacy.
``These three privatizations are the concrete achievements ... this
government wants to leave behind,'' says Americo Hidalgo, an
advisor to the Presidential Commission on Modernization.
 &HT;    A strong showing in electrical distribution privatizations has
set the pace. Venezuela's Electricidad de Caracas, Chile's Emel and
AES of the United States bid a total of $586 million against a
strong field to take control of 80 percent of four public
distribution companies. Private generation of power for sale to the
national grid has been allowed for several years, but only one
company, U.S.-based Coastal Corp., operates a plant. Following the
privatizations, all three new distributors are racing to develop
their own generating capability. The prize is the period before
four inefficient state generators are privatized and re-engineered,
a process that could take several years. Meanwhile, the cost of
power will remain regulated and relatively high. The distributors
are betting they can bring new plants on line to operate at half
the cost, and thus return artificially high margins over the short
term. Power development is basically a capital-raising and
cash-flow game, making the proposition attractive to investors,
while plans over the longterm call for supplying electricity to
neighboring countries, an activity already contemplated under the
regulatory code.
 &HT;    State-owned telecommunications company Antel was expected to
bring more than $500 million in late May. Unlike privatizations in
other countries, El Salvador already allows free competition in
fixed-line and cellular operations. Currently, cellular operations,
long distance and other value-added services such as Internet
services and radio communications are offered on the open market,
while two companies have started offering wireline service. New
regulations demand interconnectivity between competing providers;
lower rates set the stage for international consolidation. Main
opportunities exist in creating local networks in rural areas
beyond Antel's reach and focus and making a bid in the
international telecom service industry.
 &HT;    Antel made $600 million last year on sales of $2 billion. Growth
at up to 20 percent a year is forecast, with pent-up demand for
lines topping 1 million, triple current capacity. Demand for
business lines is so tight that a side market in line-expanding
technology _ creating four or eight virtual hookups where only one
exists _ flourishes.
 &HT;    A bigger prize is the ability to compete for the U.S./Salvador
international traffic, the fifth-largest such market in Latin
America. In minutes per capita, Salvadorans connect to the United
States more than any country in the region save the Dominican
Republic. ``This will become the telecom center of Central America,
given the type of laws we have and the interconnection agreements
in place,'' says CTE/Antel president Dr. Juan Jose Daboub. ``Not
only do you get El Salvador's 5 million callers, you get the rest
of Central America and the Caribbean's 35 million people. And El
Salvador and the Dominican Republic have more international traffic
volume than Argentina, Brazil or Mexico.''
 &HT;    Buoyant Salvadorans say capitalizing on this reality will launch
a booming regional telecom industry, with local operators
collecting connection charges to complete calls through the
Americas and budding entrepreneurs building on low rates to create
all manner of international calling centers, telephone help centers
and customer-service support operations for multinationals working
in English and Spanish.
 &HT;    The local banking industry has already created its own regional
network; Salvadoran banks are the biggest, healthiest banks in
Central America. Led by Banco Cuscatlan and Banco Agricola
Comercial de El Salvador, they are now taking ownership in
neighboring countries. Peru's Banco de Credito has also moved in,
buying out Banco Capital to get its toe in the region.
 &HT;    Until last year, Citibank was the only foreign bank in El
Salvador. But since then, investment bankers are arriving in
droves. ``They just keep coming,'' says Citibank vice president
Maria Alicia de Espinoza.
 &HT;    The recent advent of the private pension fund system will add
new fire to an already bubbling pot. In the next five years, the
five authorized funds are expected to generate $500 million in
capital. The funds, which must be invested locally, will radically
relocate the stocks and bonds market, as well as corporate finance.
``You'll see Salvadoran companies start to go public in three
years,'' says Roberto Ulloa, Barclay's chief representative in
Central America. ``There is not much sophistication in terms of
risk right now. That will change.''
 &HT;    Industry will welcome capital sources. While the maquila plants
have flourished under tax preferential treatment, many local
operations are struggling to rebuild plants and make investments to
upgrade machinery following the war. Locally produced products are
suffering mightily against the onslaught of low-duty imports.
However, the maquilas, mainly stitch-and-ship textile plants, are
leading the export sector and are the country's main success story,
with weekly shipments going out to the biggest names in global
fashion.
 &HT;    Many plants are locally owned, a fact that Salvadorans say
shelters them from a normally cutthroat, unpredictable industry.
Indeed, labor is pricier here and the main market, the United
States, is easier served by other countries. However, the
government has plans to extend the almost expired 10-year tax
exemption indefinitely and to redefine the rules to allow other
industries to operate in free zones and sell to other Central
American markets, as well as liberalizing movement in and out of
tax-free zones. But Salvadorans insist that their maquilas are
different. ``We don't sell cheap labor,'' says David Huezo, special
projects director for box and bag exporter Sigma. ``Countries by
the dozen offer that. We offer high labor skill, quality and
confidence.''
 &HT;    Trade pacts are an important factor for the maquilas and the
rest of the regionally focused economy. Central America has its own
free-trade agreements in place, but El Salvador needs more to keep
moving forward. Mexico is the prize closest at hand, with Economy
Minister Zablah predicting that a
Guatemala/Honduras/Salvador/Mexico free-trade agreement will be in
place by year end. Discussions with Caribbean nations are underway,
too, but Salvadorans figure they will be ready for a
hemisphere-wide trade area when it comes, and all the current
effort has that as its goal.
 &HT;    Next year's presidential elections represents a hurdle that is
much closer on the horizon. The FMLN opposition holds a strong
congressional contingent and currently controls the mayorship of
San Salvador, the capital. The coming contest will be a tight race,
but most businesspeople say that while the unknown is always cause
for some worry, they don't see an FMLN president making an economic
about-face. Says one banker, who asked not to be identified, ``It's
not like `the commies' are coming. Those days are over. Before,
there was a lot of political fighting and hardly any dialogue. Now
there is still a lot of fighting, but by the end of the day they
all get together for a drink. That's democracy at its best.''
 &HT;    And perhaps the best indicator that El Salvador will stay on
track toward a new economic future.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
