<HEADLINE>
FORMER COACHES IN CSUN BENEFIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cal State Northridge's football program will get a
hand from former coaches Terry Donahue and John Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-UCLA and ex-USC football coaches are the subjects of
roast benefiting the Matadors. The semi-formal event, which will
also have a silent sports memorabilia auction, is Aug. 7 at the
Warner Center Marriott in Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue, with a school-best 151-74-8 record, coached the Bruins
from 1976-95. His roast will be led by Jerry Long, UCLA's former
assistant athletic director in charge of development. Robinson
posted a 104-36-4 record in 12 seasons at USC. His roast will be
led by Craig Fertig, an ex-USC assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of overwhelmed at the thought that they would come to
a dinner and be honored by us,'' CSUN coach Ron Ponciano said.
``They are both humble and good people who are doing it for
Northridge's cause. It feels good that two coaching legends will
take time out to help the program. It's humbling for me and it
makes me feel good about what we're doing here.''
</P>
<P>
   The event begins at 6 p.m. and the cost is $125 per plate or
$2,500 for a corporate table of up to 10 people. Guests are asked
to RSVP in advance.
</P>
<P>
   For information call (818) 677-2061.
</P>
<P>
   __ Basketball schedule: The highlights of the Matadors' 1998-99
men's basketball season schedule are road games against UCLA and
Tennessee and two tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN, 0-3 overall against the Bruins, plays at Pauley Pavilion
on Dec. 19. Matadors coach Bobby Braswell, a former Oregon
assistant, will face his ex-boss, Volunteers coach Jerry Green, for
the first time at Tennessee on Nov. 17. Northridge is also playing
at Hawaii's Powerbar Tournament on Dec. 3-4 and the BYU Tournament
on Dec. 11-12.
</P>
<P>
   The season opener is Nov. 14 at Long Beach State, the home
opener is Nov. 28 against San Diego and the Big Sky Conference
opener is Jan. 2 against two-time league champion Northern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hectic schedule: Ponciano will rack up some frequent-flyer
miles in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   The first-year coach is in Park City, Utah, on July 19 for the
three-day Big Sky Conference Football Media Kickoff. The next day,
Ponciano has a press conference at 9 a.m. and a flight back to Los
Angeles so he can attend the 11th Annual Matador Football Golf
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   After the tournament at the Porter Valley Country Club, Ponciano
will fly back to Utah for another press conference on July 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all part of the deal,' said Ponciano. ``It is no
different than when I was an assistant during recruiting season
jumping out of cars and planes.''
</P>
<P>
   The golf tourney costs $175 per golfer and is a two-man
scramble. For information, call (818) 677-2061.
</P>
<P>
   __ Matadors honored: Track and field athletes Oswaldo Servin and
Jennifer Overlock were named Northridge's Big Sky Conference male
and female scholar athletes of the year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   To be nominated for the award, the athlete must have at least a
3.2 grade-point average, be a member of the graduating class, have
competed two years and be a letter winner.
</P>
<P>
   Servin holds CSUN's fifth-best time in the 3,000 meters
(8:32.65, 1997) and finished seventh in 1,500 meters in the Big Sky
Outdoor Championship in May. Overland, a graduate of L.A. Baptist
High, earned the school's third-best time in the mile (5:18.35,
altitude adjustment) in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
