<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS WILL STAND PAT ON THIS ROUND OF DRAFT PICKS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By STEVE POPPER     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In recent years, the day of the National Basketball
Association draft has been a vital one for the Nets. With an annual
spot in the lottery, it usually turned out to be the most promising
day of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But in earning their first playoff berth since 1994 this year
with a young and talented roster, the Nets dealt away their picks
in this year's draft and they are not interested in joining in the
fun.
</P>
<P>
   Coach John Calipari will be vacationing with his wife next
Wednesday when the names are called. The Nets will not even send a
representative to Vancouver for the draft. Instead they will hire
on a former assistant coach of the Canadian national team for the
day to fill their seat at the table.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets traded away their first-round selection, No. 15 over
all, to the Orlando Magic in the deal to acquire Rony Seikaly, and
their second-round choice, No. 45 over all, went to the Los Angeles
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets see this year's draft crop as a weak one and they
believe that they have a strong team, so there is no need to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked these guys one thing,'' Calipari said, pointing toward
General Manager John Nash and Dave Pendergraft, the director of
player personnel. ``I said to Dave, `Is there a player in the draft
that can make us better, that if we traded for him, that he would
make us a better team?'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only reason you would do it. Is there someone there
that, not would make us better two years from now, I mean, right
now, who is going to make us better? And it was one or two guys
maybe. There was no definite, `this guy makes us better,' like
Keith Van Horn. We definitely knew he would make us better, so it
was, let's do what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So on Wednesday, Nash will be in the office, watching the phone,
but with little interest in listening.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' plan almost from the start of the season was to tie
the first-round pick in a package to Yinka Dare, trying to entice
someone to take his contract off their hands. Orlando took it and
the Nets have no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our scouts told me yesterday about a player he was
intrigued with, that he thought could possibly make an NBA
roster,'' Nash said. ``My question to him was, `Is he better than
David Vaughn right now?' He said, `No, not right now.' We have a
chance now to be a 50-win team. We're a playoff team and the real
mission is to get home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're picking 15th, you're hoping.''
</P>
<P>
   Calipari listed the players the Nets would have brought in to
consider if they retained that No. 15 pick, including Michael
Doleac, Van Horn's former teammate at the University of Utah,
Georgia Tech's Matt Harpring, Baylor's Brian Skinner, Arizona's
Michael Dickerson, Notre Dame's Pat Garrity, Florida's Jason
Williams, Mississippi's Ansu Sesay, Ball State's Bonzi Wells,
Cincinnati's Ruben Patterson, as well as high school players Al
Harrington and Rashard Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   But Calipari insisted the Nets have no regrets about not adding
youth to their team. The concerns right now are re-signing the free
agents Jayson Williams and Sherman Douglas, seeing the team with
Seikaly healthy, and convincing Michael Cage to put off retirement
for another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our veterans are young,'' Calipari said. ``I think next year
will be a good year to supplement because we will lose a lot of
these guys at this point. Guys will be at the end of contracts and
we can take a stab at that point. That's why we're scouting
European players. If we're playing well and winning, then our draft
picks are going to be worse and worse.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
