<HEADER>
A4324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-COUNCIL-VETOES     06-17 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-COUNCIL-VETOES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE HOUSE THAT ROARED, WITH GUSTO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was more backslapping euphoria in the City
Council chambers on Tuesday than anyone who has slept through its
meetings could remember. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani described the
session as something closer to a party convention than a gathering
of a legislative body, and though he was not actually in the room
to see his budget vetoes overridden, he basically got it right.
</P>
<P>
   As each of the council's 44 Democrats rose to vote against the
mayor, there was enthusiastic cheering from the gallery, and when
each of the seven Republicans voted with him, there was
melodramatic hissing. The way-outnumbered Republicans talked grimly
about the dire consequences of the day. The Democrats, meanwhile,
hailed it as a great moment for the city and an even greater one
for the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I am proud to be a City Council member,'' announced
Priscilla Wooten, D-Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very proud to be a member of the City Council,'' declared
Adolfo Carrion, D-Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, with this override, we are fulfilling the mandate we
have as a legislature,'' asserted Guillermo Linares, D-Manhattan,
his voice rising for dramatic effect.
</P>
<P>
   Even factoring in the natural inclination of politicians to
grandstand, Tuesday's vote to override the vetoes marked a
significant victory for the council _ a victory, to be sure, mostly
over its own fabled pusillanimity.
</P>
<P>
   Since the revised City Charter gave the council substantial new
powers in 1989, its members have been extremely chary of exercising
them. Instead, they have spent more energy complaining that they
needed yet another round of charter revision before they could ever
dream of providing a check on executive authority.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Tuesday's vote demonstrated, the council already
possessed the power to write the city's budget and, thanks to its
huge Democratic majority, was in a position to easily override
Giuliani's vetoes. The mayor can talk tough about countering the
council's ``irresponsible'' action, but it will be difficult and,
in some cases, downright impossible for him to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has broad authority to hold back funds that the
council has approved, but he has no authority to spend money that
the council has not approved. Nor can he, on his own, impose taxes.
Thus the centerpiece of the council's budget _ its elimination of
the personal-income-tax surcharge, worth about $500 million a year
_ will, no matter how much the mayor barks and bites, go into
effect in January.
</P>
<P>
   Both critics and defenders of the council give essentially the
same account of why it has taken so long for it to flex its
charter-given muscles. Every legislative body has its written rules
and then its unspoken traditions. In the case of the council, these
traditions all pointed in the direction of street-naming and
favor-mongering. Not so terribly long ago, the council was compared
unfavorably by one of its very own members with a rubber stamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rubber stamp at least leaves an impression,'' Henry Stern,
who is now the city's parks commissioner, once opined.
</P>
<P>
   For four and a half years, Giuliani has helped keep this craven
tradition alive by treating the City Council with a finely tuned
disdain. The few times the council has dared to differ with him,
the mayor has first heaped scorn on it and then ignored it. On more
than one occasion, he has simply refused to form commissions
established by the council or to seat board members that it had
selected.
</P>
<P>
   But with Tuesday's vote, the mayor's relation to the council has
entered a new phase. Thanks to an unlikely concatenation of events,
which include the battle over Yankee Stadium, this year's huge
budget surplus and council Speaker Peter Vallone's gubernatorial
ambitions, the council members have at last tugged free of the
Slough of Despond. And having tugged free, who knows where they
could end up?
</P>
<P>
   After the vote to override the vetoes, several members insisted
that they had no plans to retreat. ``In the future,'' said
Councilman John Sabini, D-Queens, ``we may be cooperative, but
rolling over _ it ain't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the situation from a slightly different angle, Gene
Russianoff, a senior attorney at the New York Public Interest
Research Group, suggested that the council might not have much
choice in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there is going back,'' he said. ``They won't
be able to say, `We can't do it because the mayor is too powerful.'
People will say, `You can do it; you did do it.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
