<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-U.S.-OPEN-NYT &LR;      06-17 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-U.S.-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POISE AND PATIENCE WILL BE KEYS TO WINNING THE U.S. OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Whenever the U.S. Open has come to the Olympic
Club, something unexpected and memorable has happened.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the elements seem aligned for another unpredictable
tournament. Casey Martin will make history, becoming the first
player in a U.S. Open to compete riding in a golf cart.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els will defend his title with an ailing back, but he
still hopes to become the first player since Curtis Strange in 1989
to repeat as champion.
</P>
<P>
   There will be veteran players enjoying a renaissance, such as
Tom Watson, competing against young players like David Duval, who
are eager to add a major championship to their collection.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the course, picturesque yet challenging. The
5-inch rough, sloping fairways, deceptive wind and small greens
will reward patience, magnify mistakes and make it difficult for
any player to separate himself from the field. Three-under par won
the U.S. Open in 1987, the last time it was held at Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is potential disaster at every hole,'' said Colin
Montgomerie, who has come close to winning the U.S. Open three
times. ``You can make double or triple at any hole, any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Will one of the game's prominent names add the Open to his
resume? Or will another unlikely champion emerge at Olympic,
joining Jack Fleck (1955), who defeated Ben Hogan, Billy Casper
(1966), who overtook Arnold Palmer, or Scott Simpson (1987), who
defeated Tom Watson?
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, when the first threesome tees off at 7 a.m. Pacific
time, four days of golf at its most demanding will begin. Here is a
look at some of the key factors that will determine the victor:
</P>
<P>
   _ PATIENCE. Bogey-free rounds will be almost impossible. You
will see players hacking away in the rough. You will see four-putts
on Olympic's quick greens, which will measure 11 on the Stimpmeter.
You will see frustration. Players who shrug off mistakes quickly
and regroup will have an advantage. This is an area in which Els
has excelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm super cool out there, I get angry just like
anybody else,'' Els said. ``But you have to play the tournament
shot by shot. When you've made a bogey, don't get too hard on
yourself. Par is a good score.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods became impatient during last year's U.S. Open at
Congressional, and it cost him. On several occasions, Woods tried
to overpower shots out of the deep rough, leading to another bad
shot, and a bogey or worse. That has fueled talk that Woods does
not have the game to win another major tournament, talk that he
wants to end this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger has heard that, and believe me, he is motivated for this
tournament,'' said Butch Harmon, Woods' coach. ``Tiger is an
aggressive player, but patience is the key to this tournament for
him. I think you'll see his maturity as a golfer. He realizes how a
few bad holes cost him last year, not only at the United States
Open, but at the British Open. He has worked hard to eliminate
those kinds of holes. To win here, you have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ACCURACY. Length off the tee is not a huge advantage at
Olympic, which only measures 6,797 yards, compared to
Congressional's 7,213 yards last year. The rough, the tree-lined
fairways, doglegs on several holes, and the small greens will force
players to aim at small target areas, from off the tee and on
approach shots. Many people expect Watson, Montgomerie and Tom
Lehman to do well, because they are very accurate from tee to
green.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Montgomerie believes that Olympic's lack of length will
take away some of his advantage, and bring more players into
contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year at Congressional, it was length and accuracy,''
Montgomerie said. ``But here, it's just accuracy. I hit my 3-wood a
long way and straight, so that was an advantage at Congressional.
But here, you can use a lot of 2-irons and 3-irons off the tee to
position yourself in the fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   Players who can hit high tee shots that drop onto the fairway
without rolling far will have an advantage, because Olympic's
slanted fairways will propel shots that are overcooked into the
rough.
</P>
<P>
   _ POISE. Something unexpected always happens at the U.S. Open,
so you have to deal with it. Montgomerie had three great rounds at
Congressional last year, 65-67-69, but a second-round 76 cost him
dearly. He lost concentration during that round when some rowdy
fans annoyed him. Those are the types of things that contenders
have to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday night, barring an 18-hole playoff on Monday, one
player will emerge as the person who avoided the most trouble, who
handled adversity the best, who made the most crucial shots. It
won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time goes on, I look back and say, `Man, how did I ever win
that tournament,''' Simpson said. ``It still kind of validates you
as a player.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
