<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4327 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-nhl-HNS &LR;      06-17 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-nhl-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
2 may be only 
the beginning 
for Red Wings
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ With an unblemished record of eight consecutive
victories in the last two Stanley Cup finals, a 50-22 playoff
record since 1995 and a youthful core of key players locked into
contracts for next season, is it too early to think about a dynasty
for the Detroit Red Wings?
</P>
<P>
   Bowman
</P>
<P>
   Scotty Bowman, who has coached dynasties in Montreal in the
1970s and has coached against teams like the New York Islanders and
Edmonton Oilers in the 1980s, thinks it's premature to speak of the
Red Wings in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult talking about dynasties nowadays in our
sport, the kinds of overpowering teams we used to see go through
the 80-game regular season finishing first overall and then winning
Stanley Cups,'' the Red Wings' coach said. ``I don't think you can
call a team like ours a dynasty. I don't think that's what you're
talking about. I think this is a team with a lot of resiliency.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman might be selling his team short. The Red Wings completed
a sweep of Washington this week to capture their second straight
Stanley Cup. Over the last two years, they are 32-10 in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit is the first team to repeat as champion since the
1991-92 Pittsburgh Penguins and the first to record back-to-back
sweeps since the 1982-83 Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   But will success spoil the Red Wings? General manager Ken
Holland understands that keeping a successful team together these
days is often tougher than building it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a difficult thing these days to keep a team
together,'' Holland said. ``Not only because of trades, free agency
and increasing salaries, but it can be difficult just to keep
everyone happy.''
</P>
<P>
   With one notable exception, the Red Wings demonstrated little
selfishness this season.
</P>
<P>
   They finished third overall in points while playing all year
without their top defenseman (Vladimir Konstantinov, injured in a
car accident after last year's title) and most of the year without
top offensive threat Sergei Fedorov, who was holding out.
</P>
<P>
   Konstantinov's career is over, but Fedorov returned in February
and will remain with the Red Wings for the next three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve Yzerman is 33 but showed no signs of slowing down,
winning the Conn Smythe Trophy as the playoff most valuable player.
Yzerman cites the fact that most of the Red Wings' top players are
still in the prime of their careers as the main reason he doesn't
see a drop-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apart from myself and Igor (Larionov), the majority of our
forwards are 22 or 23 to 29,'' Yzerman said. ``That will keep the
team competitive for a number of years. Our guys are relatively
youthful, so I expect we'll stay together.''
</P>
<P>
   Fedorov (27), Martin Lapointe (24), Slava Kozlov (26), Tomas
Holmstrom (25), Brendan Shanahan (28), Darren McCarty (26), Kirk
Maltby (25), Nicklas Lidstrom (28) and goaltender Chris Osgood (25)
fall into that category.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only Red Wings who are not signed for next season
are veteran defensemen Slava Fetisov (40) and Bob Rouse (34).
</P>
<P>
   In a league that was dominated by a handful of teams for the
last 13 seasons, it could be that Detroit is on the verge of
joining Montreal (1976-79), the Islanders (1980-83) and Edmonton
(four titles between 1984-88) as the next dominant team.
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman, however, cautions against trying to compare the Red
Wings with the Islanders or Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders were led by superstars Mike Bossy, Brian Trottier
and Denis Potvin. The Oilers of the mid-1980s, possibly the best
team ever assembled, had Wayne Gretzky, Mark Messier, Jari Kurri,
Kevin Lowe and Paul Coffey.
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman doesn't believe the Red Wings stack up against those
teams just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be competitive for a number of years, but the Oilers in
the '80s, they could put probably the six best players in the world
on the ice at one time,'' Yzerman said. ``We can't match the number
of superstars they had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we do have is depth. All four of our lines are
solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Another strength is Bowman, who won his record-tying eighth
Stanley Cup as a coach this season.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman, 64, said he has not decided whether he will return. He
says he will wait a few weeks and talk with his family before
making a decision about coaching again. He has hinted he might not
be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing Scotty and his passion for the game and his
unbelievable energy level, I think he'd be bored silly by the
middle of December if he wasn't coaching,'' Holland said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Yzerman: ``Personally, I hope he comes back. He's in charge
of the team, and the players have grown extremely fond of him. He's
the guy who drives the team and puts the fire in the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
