<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BLIND-GOLFERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING GOOD GOLF WITH A REAL HANDICAP
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT KISCO, N.Y. _ David Meador had just run in a five-foot
putt on the second hole at the Mount Kisco Country Club and the
rattling of the ball in the cup prompted Otto Huber to say, ``Music
to my ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Meador smiled at the remark by his playing partner because he
realized that, although neither he nor Huber could see the ball go
into the cup, they could certainly hear it. And sounds, and not
sights, are what count in golf to Meador and Huber.
</P>
<P>
   Not one of the 16 golfers entered in the Ken Venturi Guiding
Eyes Classic _ which raises money for Guiding Eyes for the Blind,
the organization that trains guide dogs for the blind _ saw where
any of their shots went during the one-day tournament last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not stop the winner, Keith Melick, from shooting a
110 over the challenging Mount Kisco course to give him his third
victory this year on the U.S. Blind Golfers Association circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Melick may have benefited from the absence of Pat Browne Jr.,
who had won the tournament the last 17 years in a row, including
last year when he carded a 99. Acknowledged for years as the
world's best blind golfer _ his low score as a blind golfer was a
remarkable 74 at the Mission Hills Country Club in Rancho Mirage,
Calif., in 1982 when he shot in the 70s on four consecutive days _
Browne missed this week's tournament because he is recovering from
rotator cuff surgery.
</P>
<P>
   With Browne on the sideline, Meador was the favorite. A
50-year-old life insurance salesman from Nashville who was a
5-handicap until an auto accident cost him his sight in 1966,
Meador won the U.S. Blind Golfers Association championship in 1977.
But he had finished second behind Browne every year since to earn
the unofficial title of ``second best blind golfer in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not to be his year, either. Meador, despite the
smoothest swing in the tournament, finished third with a 114.
</P>
<P>
   Part of a growing circuit that now includes tournaments in
Canada, Europe, Australia and Japan, the 16 players in the Venturi
Guiding Eyes Classic are among the best blind golfers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the ultimate team game,'' Meador said before starting his
round, during which his coach, Everett Davis, guided him around the
course and lined him up before every shot.
</P>
<P>
   Davis placed the club in Meador's hands, pointed it in the
direction of where he wanted Meador to hit his next shot and then
put the clubface behind the ball. On the green, Davis, like most
other coaches, walked off the distance from the ball to the hole
before setting him up for his putt.
</P>
<P>
   For players on the U.S. Blind Golf Association circuit, coaches
are all-important. ``I sometimes think a coach, like mine, Kevin
Sullivan, can be 90 or 95 percent of your game as a blind golfer,''
Bill McMahon said on Tuesday while hosting his own annual charity
tournament at Shorehaven Golf Club in East Norwalk, Conn., which
has raised more than $100,000 for the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   At Mount Kisco, Bob Andrews held onto the hand of his wife,
Tina, as, in her capacity as his coach, she led him around the
course and drove their golf cart. As the current president of the
association, Andrews _ who lost his sight when a booby-trapped
grenade blew up in his face when he was a 22-year-old Marine
corporal in Vietnam _ publishes the organization's newsletter,
``Midnight Golfer,'' and maintains a data base of all of the
association's members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play the same game, with the same USGA rules, as sighted
players do,'' Andrews said. ``It's all very competitive, but we
have a lot of fun and there's a wonderful camaraderie among the
players.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
