<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. AND JAPAN BUY YEN TO BOLSTER FALLING CURRENCY
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Japan bought yen to stop the precipitous
fall of the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
   The action, which took currency markets by surprise, marks the
first time in six years that the United States has sold dollars and
purchased yen. President Clinton said he approved the move after
speaking by telephone with Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto of
Japan, who committed to specific economic reforms that go beyond
earlier pledges.
</P>
<P>
   As currency trading resumed in Asia, many wondered how committed
Japan was to making far-reaching economic changes. But there are
precedents for a turning point in the direction of the yen.
</P>
<P>
   AOL PLANS TO REMAIN INDEPENDENT
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of merger talks with AT&AMP;T, America Online said it
planned to remain independent. Investors had speculated that the
Internet access provider might be acquired and had pushed shares of
America Online up. The negotiations also indicate that the new
chairman of AT&AMP;T, Michael Armstrong, wants to bolster the
telecommunications company's Internet access and growth prospects.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE JETTISONS TOBACCO BILL
</P>
<P>
   The Senate jettisoned broad tobacco legislation meant to
discourage teen-agers from smoking. The bill, which had been
debated for a month, was set aside when supporters could not get
the 60 votes needed to clear two procedural hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY REMAINS STRONG, FED SAYS
</P>
<P>
   The United States' economy remains strong, with employment high
and inflation low, despite scattered spillover from Asia's economic
ills, the Federal Reserve Board said in its survey of regional
economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S JOBS AT ISSUE IN GM STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   The strike at two General Motors' parts plants seems to be
centering on the transfer of jobs overseas. Striking employees say
they are walking the picket line to protect their jobs. But GM says
it needs to reduce costs further, perhaps by hiring nonunion and
overseas labor at lower-cost plants.
</P>
<P>
   NO UNANIMITY IN THE EXECUTIVE SUITE
</P>
<P>
   Chief executives and their top lieutenants hold widely divergent
views on issues like succession and training for the top job, a
survey by the Association of Executive Search Consultants shows.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE SEEKING A NEW TAX SYSTEM
</P>
<P>
   The House voted to require Congress to come up with a new tax
system by Independence Day 2002.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN AND RUBIN DIFFER ON BILL
</P>
<P>
   Chances of overhauling financial-services legislation this year
dimmed as the Federal Reserve Board chairman, Alan Greenspan, and
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin differed on structure and
regulation at a Senate Banking Committee hearing.
</P>
<P>
   AMA BACKS PRESENT LEADERSHIP
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the American Medical Association stayed with their
current leadership, rejecting a presidential candidate who was
critical of an aborted deal to allow Sunbeam to use the AMA's name
on its products.
</P>
<P>
   30-YEAR TREASURY PRICES DECLINE
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices declined as the dollar plunged against the yen
The 30-year bond's yield rose to 5.73 percent, from 5.65 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
