<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY BASEBALL MANAGERS WEAR UNIFORMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Why do baseball managers wear uniforms? _ W.W., Denton, Tecas
</P>
<P>
   A: It appears that the tradition began because most early
managers of pro teams also were players.
</P>
<P>
   The manager of the first pro team, Harry Wright of the
Cincinnati Red Stockings, was a pitcher and outfielder. More
recently, managers Pete Rose and Frank Robinson played for the
teams they led.
</P>
<P>
   A few managers broke from tradition and wore street clothes, but
that hasn't happened since the 1950s. According to an April 4,
1988, ``Sports Illustrated'' article, the last two were Connie Mack
of the Philadelphia A's and Burt Shotton of the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Grapette soda pop still being bottled? _ J.M., Arlington,
Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Leading Edge Flavors returned the soda to production six
months ago in Temple after purchasing the franchise rights from the
Monarch Co. in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The grape-flavored drink made its debut in 1939 at a Camden,
Ark., bottling plant owned by B.T. Fooks. Monarch acquired the
rights in 1979 and produced it in limited quantities.
</P>
<P>
   Grapette is sold in 20-ounce plastic bottles and will be
available in longneck glass bottles in August, said Eileen Langford
of Leading Edge.
</P>
<P>
   The soda is distributed in Texas, Arkansas, Louisiana and New
Mexico. To find out where, call (800) 335-2353.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have about 50 really old Matchbox toy cars. How do I find
out if they're worth anything? _ J.B., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several collectors' clubs you can start with; one
of the largest is Matchbox USA, with 1,500 members.
</P>
<P>
   Matchbox USA publishes a monthly magazine for collectors and
holds a yearly convention. A one-year membership costs $27 to $34.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, write to Matchbox USA, 62 Saw Mill Road,
Durham, CT 06422, or visit the World Wide Web site
matchbox-usa.com.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
