<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4334 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-TOBACCO-BOS &LR;      06-17 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO BILL DIES IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate abruptly killed comprehensive
antitobacco legislation last night, halting a historic attempt to
crack down on the cigarette industry and creating a powerful issue
in this year's congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   The $516 billion plan, built from a blueprint drawn nearly one
year ago in a landmark settlement between the tobacco industry and
40 state attorneys general, died of procedural causes after
supporters were unable to defeat two parliamentary moves by Senate
Republican leaders to scuttle it.
</P>
<P>
   A motion to force a final vote on the measure fell three votes
short of the 60 that supporters needed, 57-42, even though 15
Republicans broke with GOP leaders who called for killing the bill.
All the Democrats except two from tobacco-growing states voted for
the motion.
</P>
<P>
   The measure expired moments later when supporters failed to
secure the 60 votes needed to waive a Senate rule that would have
permitted the plan to exceed last year's balanced budget agreement.
The vote was 53-46, seven votes shy.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who had called on Congress to use last year's
tobacco settlement as the framework for curbing youth smoking,
immediately cast the setback as an election issue. He blamed the
bill's demise on Republican congressional leaders and ``$40 million
in unanswered advertising by their allies'' in the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was seen by members of both parties as one of the
most iportant issues Congress would take up this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that when the American people understand fully what
has been going on, they won't like what they see,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the 57 votes to keep the bill alive, Clinton said the
number ``clearly shows that a bipartisan majority supports tough
legislation to protect the children of this country from tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill's death was expected to provide fresh momentum for
lawsuits pending against the tobacco industry in 36 states.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain of Arizona, a Republican and the bill's
sponsor, joined Clinton in blaming the tobacco industry's
advertising blitz for turning public opinion against the bill. He
said the campaign caused a number of senators who once supported
the plan to abandon it.
</P>
<P>
   Six Republicans who voted for the measure when it passed the
Senate Commerce Committee 19-1 in April, voted last night to kill
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there has been a change of view by many members,''
McCain said. ``The only conclusion one can draw is that the tobacco
advertising campaign had a significant impact on their
conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign, which cast the antitobacco measure as one of
the most regressive tax-and-spend boondoggles in decades, was seen
as providing crucial support to a small group of Republican foes
who succeeded in killing the bill after four weeks of rancorous
debate.
</P>
<P>
   The ads ``were like cruise missiles equipped with nuclear
bombs,'' said Senator Joseph R. Biden Jr., a Delaware Democrat.
``They work every time in this town.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats vowed to use every parliamentary tool they can
to keep the issue on the legislative agenda, even though House
Speaker Newt Gingrich has said he will not allow the
Republican-controlled House to use the Senate bill as the basis for
a legislative compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans may mug this bill in the Senate, but they
cannot kill it,'' Senator Edward M. Kennedy said moments before the
parliamentary votes. ``We will not let it die.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich is backing much narrower legislation aimed at curbing
youth smoking and drug abuse, a measure that public health
officials have called severely inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to reduce teen smoking, not increase taxes,''
Gingrich said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry, the Democratic point man on the
antitobacco bill, assailed Senate GOP leaders for failing to defy
Gingrich's desire for a less ambitious measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newt Gingrich put out a contract on this bill,'' Kerry said,
``and the Republicans in the Senate are the hit people.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Kennedy's vow to revive the issue, GOP leaders,
including McCain, said the Democratic minority will not be able to
overcome Republican opposition to the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader,
denounced the bill as an unsalvageable ``tax and spend'' plan.
``We've lost sight of the original noble cause of just dealing with
teen-aged smoking and drug abuse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was among the 15 Republicans who broke with Lott and
voted not to kill the bill. Every New England senator voted to keep
the measure alive except for Senator Bob Smith, a New Hampshire
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The only New England senators who opposed the other
parliamentary, balanced-budget maneuver were Smith and Senator Judd
Gregg, also a New Hampshire Republican. That vote effectively
returned the bill to the Senate Commerce Committee, which the
chairman, McCain, said was tantamount to killing it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have required the tobacco industry to pay
billions of dollars over 25 years to help states and the federal
government bear the medical costs of smoking-related illnesses. The
measure also would have raised cigarette taxes by $1.10-a-pack over
five years, expanded the Food and Drug Administration's power to
regulate the tobacco industry and drastically restricted cigarette
advertising and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said the cigarette tax hikes, which the bill
required tobacco companies to pass on to consumers, were an unfair,
economic assault on the 60 percent of smokers who earn less than
$30,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a defining moment for the Republican Party as to
whether or not we are going to have a massive tax increase and
expansion of big government,'' said Senator John Ashcroft, a
Missouri Republican and leading opponent of the bill. ``We should
not become the party of massive taxes on low-income workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican foes succeeded in amending the bill to provide $27
billion in relief for low-income couples who pay a marriage tax
penalty. Several other Republican amendments passed as well,
including a provision that would have used $17 billion on the
tobacco money for antidrug initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Repulicans who pushed for those changes voted
not to allow a final vote on the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the senators who derailed this bill lose sleep every
night listening to the sound of children taking their first puff
and the sound of emphysema and cancer patients gasping for their
last breath,'' said Dr. C. Everett Koop, a former surgeon general.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
