<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4338 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEN-US-BOS &LR;      06-17 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEN-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TRIES TO BOLSTER THE YEN, EASE FEAR OF WIDENING CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States made an unusual foray into the
currency markets Wednesday, selling dollar reserves in an attempt
to prop up the Japanese yen and calm fears that Japan's sinking
economy would prompt a worldwide financial downturn.
</P>
<P>
   The move, the first US effort to raise the yen in six years,
came after the Japanese government promised new measures to revive
its economy, which has slid into recession. Early results suggest
that the US intervention was providing Japan at least some
short-term relief. The yen rose from the eight-year low against the
dollar set earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   US investors cheered the move by bidding the Dow Jones
industrial average up 164 points to close at 8829.46. The Dow had
fallen 207 points on Monday on fears of an expanding Asian
financial crisis, and it had risen only modestly on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And in Japan, the 225-share Nikkei average, the nation's main
stock market barometer, jumped 3.20 percent, or 470.83 points, to
15,186.21 Thursday morning in the first 20 minutes of trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very smart move by the United States,'' said C.
Fred Bergsten, director of the Institute for International
Economics, a research group. ``We were getting to the point where
global financial crisis was really possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The falling yen has cut the price of Japanese steel, computer
chips and electronics on the world market, alarming nations that
sell the same products. Companies that export to Japan are also
finding it difficult to sell their own goods because the purchasing
power of the yen is weak.
</P>
<P>
   From South Korean to Russia and Brazil, countries are under
pressure to devalue their own currencies so that they can compete
with Japan. But cheaper currencies would make it harder for them to
pay off the dollar-denominated foreign debts they have accumulated
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Calls for Japan and the United States to prop up the yen have
been particularly strong in China, where President Clinton is to
visit next week. China has so far resisted devaluing its own
currency in response to the sagging yen.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton said he supported the US
plan to sell yen after Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
promised in a Tuesday evening phone call to make ``aggressive''
economic reforms, including steps to deal with the country's
weakened banks, which are saddled with bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very encouraged by the prime minister's statement that
he intends to pursue aggressive reform of their banking
institutions and intends to do the things that were necessary to
get their economy going again,'' Clinton said, ``and therefore I
thought it was important that we support them.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Treasury and the Federal Reserve hold authority to
trade US reserves, and they made the decision jointly, US officials
said. The Treasury said it acted ``in cooperation with the monetary
authorities of Japan,'' which private currency traders said meant
that the Bank of Japan had also bought yen.
</P>
<P>
   US officials would not discuss the value of dollars that had
been sold by the United States and the Bank of Japan to buy yen,
and estimates from private currency traders ranged from $2 billion
to more than $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hearing that it could be $15 billion, but no one really
knows, because central banks don't discuss these things,'' said
David Warren, a London-based portfolio manager for T. Rowe Price
international funds.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has drawn wide criticism for failing to take steps to end
its eight-year economic stall. The criticism has turned to alarm as
the yen lost about 10 percent of its value against the dollar this
year, suggesting that Japan would be unable to lead Asia out of its
financial crisis by buying products from troubled neighbors like
Indonesia, South Korea and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government has promised to close or merge banks
that have been weakened by bad loans, but few large banks have
actually shut their doors. Hashimoto also has proposed a $115
billion tax cut to spur consumer spending, but some critics say the
amount is not nearly enough and note that the plan remains stuck in
the Japanese parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, some analysts said they had little faith that Japan
was finally ready to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hashimoto didn't say the wrong thing, but he's saying the same
things that have been said before, with no greater specificity,''
said Gary Hufbauer, research director of at the Council on Foreign
Relations in New York. ``There's a lot of market skepticisim that
he will carry through real reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts warned that the US currency intervention by
itself would have little long-term effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a currency intervention work unless the
fundamentals were also in line...and Japan is not taking action to
get them in line,'' said Ronald Reuss, chief economist at Piper
Jaffray Cos., a Minneapolis stock brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Hufbauer said the US currency intervention, and the prospect
that it would buy yen again if necessary, would take pressure off
the Japanese currency for a month or so. ``But if Japan does not
deliver on the tax cuts, skepticism will grow back in, say, late
July or August,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hufbauer echoed many other analysts who believe that Japan's
banking crisis is at the core of its economic downturn. ``They need
to restructure like we did in the 1980s'' with the savings and loan
crisis, said Hufbauer, who speculated that Japanese banks are
carrying $500 billion in bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts have put the bad loans at half that amount, or
equal to 10 percent of Japan's gross domestic product. The US
government spent $153 billion in direct costs to clean up savings
and loan losses, or about 3 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
   The air of alarm over Japan comes as the US economy is booming.
Only last week, Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan told
Congress that the economy was the best he had seen in his 50-year
career.
</P>
<P>
   That stellar performance has come in part because the Asian
crisis is allowing Americans to buy foreign goods at low prices,
keeping US inflation low. However, Greenspan and others have warned
that Asia's woes could become more problematic. US companies could
find it harder to compete with low-priced Asian goods, and the
once-growing Asian economies now have little money to buy US
products.
</P>
<P>
   The US decision to begin selling dollars for yen marked an
abrupt change in government policy. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
had been downplaying the prospects that the US would help the
Japanese economy by propping up the yen.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, the Japanese government reported that the
country's economy had shrunk for the second quarter in a row,
meeting the traditional measure of a recession. Stock markets
around the world reacted this week with sharp downturns,
heightening fears that the Japan's problem would ripple beyond
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's trading of US reserves was handled by the Federal
Reserve Bank of New York, which is the Treasury's agent in the
currency market. One dollar bought 136.75 yen late Wednesday, down
4.4 percent from Tuesday's close of 143.18 yen, and also down from
Monday's mark of nearly 147 yen.
</P>
<P>
   In another apparent boost to the yen, Treasury announced that
Lawrence Summers, its No. 2 official, and New York Fed Bank
President William McDonough will go to Tokyo for a weekend meeting
of finance officials from the Group of Seven industrial nations.
Traders speculated that Summers would press the case that Japan
must follow through on plans to improve the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
