<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4341 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-FLORIDA-NOTEBOOK-C     06-17 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-FLORIDA-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida's hopes rest on arm of Bellisari
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Florida's Steve Bellisari is listed in the
Georgia-Florida High School All-Star
</P>
<P>
   Game program as a free safety. But Florida coach Robby Pruitt
has the final say-so, and he says it isn't so.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't touch the defensive side of the ball,'' Pruitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bellisari will start at quarterback Saturday, and the
6-2, 200-pound left-hander from Boca Raton plans to play that
position at Ohio State this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws the deep ball as good as I've seen,'' Pruitt said.
``He's a whole lot better than we thought. The first time we saw
him, it was like, `My God!'''
</P>
<P>
   Bellisari's passing proficiency has caused Pruitt to rethink his
offensive strategy for Saturday's game. Florida plans to use
Pruitt's specialty offense, the run-oriented wing-T formation, but
he said Wednesday he will also run ``four wideouts and some shotgun
stuff.'' Bellisari's bloodline would seem to dictate athletic
success. His brother, Greg, was an Academic All-American at Ohio
State and plays linebacker for the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs and Gators galore
</P>
<P>
   The University of Georgia will have a noticeable presence in
Saturday's Georgia-Florida All-Star Game. There are 15 future
Bulldogs participating _ 13 from Georgia and two from Florida _ and
14 of them will start on Saturday. The only non-starter in the
group is Charlton County's Terin Smith, and he is backing up three
positions, both defensive end spots and tight end.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Florida has 11 signees in the game _ four from
Georgia _ and eight of them will start.
</P>
<P>
   Two Georgia signees will play very prominent roles. Tim Wansley,
who played quarterback at Buford High, will start ahead of Robert
Cromartie of Douglass at left cornerback and play split end on
offense. Wansley also might return some kicks. Several other
Georgia players will play multiple positions: Washington County's
Terrence Edwards (WR/QB), Brookwood's Ian Knight (TE/DT),
Parkview's Jim May (OL/DL), Wheeler's Lester Norwood (DB/WR),
Washington County's Jessie Miller (LB/DB) and Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like about our team is it's very versatile,''
Georgia coach Rodney Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Special assignment
</P>
<P>
   Being invited to the Georgia-Florida game even as a manager is a
special honor, particularly for Fort Valley's O.J. Barton. Barton,
a rising senior at Peach County High, was a late addition to Team
Georgia at the invitation of Walker. Laoria Barton, O.J.'s mother,
died of a brain aneurysm just three weeks ago. Raised in a
single-parent home, Barton had to move in with his grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed to get his mind off things awhile and be around
people, so I asked him to come along,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Barton's not used to delivering water bottles. He gained 750
yards as a backup tailback for Peach County last fall and will
start this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
