<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burns to carry on RB tradition at Georgia-Florida All-Stars
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Running backs often have stolen the spotlight in the
13-year history of the Georgia-Florida All-Star Football Game.
Garrison Hearst, who later starred at Georgia, and Sammie Smith,
who went to Florida State, won MVP honors in the annual border war
before moving on to rich collegiate and NFL careers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, tailback Jamal Lewis of Douglass High exploded for
137 yards rushing in Georgia's 25-14 win. Shortly thereafter, Lewis
emerged as one of the nation's top freshmen at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Joe Burns of Thomas County Central, who will start
for the Georgia all-stars in Saturday's 6 p.m. contest in the
Georgia Dome, said he's well aware of the game's tradition of
running backs. And if Georgia stays with its ground game, which it
used last year to end Florida's six-year dominance in the series,
Burns is capable of etching his name in the record books as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking at the (game) program and saw what all the other
running backs have done in this game,'' Burns said. ``I just want
to do well enough to get my name in the book and keep it in there
for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns, a 5-foot-9, 190-pounder, certainly left his mark in
Thomasville after a brilliant four-year prep career. Last year's
Journal-Constitution state player of the year, Burns rushed for a
school-record 5,006 career yards and 61 touchdowns, leading the
Yellow Jackets to consecutive Class AAA state titles as a junior
and senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very talented player,'' Georgia all-stars coach Rodney
Walker said. ``He brings great vision to the field. That's the
thing about him that amazes me, how he always seems to find the
holes.'' Burns doesn't have blinding speed, but his durability and
hard-nosed instincts helped earn the interest of several Division I
programs. He committed to Georgia Tech early, after, he said,
several schools backed off because of academic problems. Burns
later earned a qualifying ACT score, then shunned late scholarship
offers from Central Florida and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had made my mind up, but a lot of the colleges stayed away
because they didn't think I'd make it,'' Burns said. ``It made me
work even harder, because I knew what I was capable of doing in the
classroom. My dad was getting on me, because he knew I should have
been doing it all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
