<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    USGA to test clubs' `spring-like' effect
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It might be the first time golfers all over the
world maintained distance and accuracy through a press conference.
Those oversized titanium drivers that golf consumers have grown to
know and love appear to be safe from banishment. Nobody from the
United States Golf Association is going to yank them from their
bags.
</P>
<P>
   Although future standards are expected to be tougher, the USGA
announced Wednesday a relatively conservative plan, considering
recent fears by the equipment companies, who cringed at the thought
of major restrictions on products such as the Callaway Great Big
Bertha and Taylor Made Ti Bubble 2.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA said it is proposing a test to more accurately measure
the ``spring-like'' or ``trampoline'' effect of a golf ball against
a club face, but expects virtually all of the clubs currently
submitted to conform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe that the 'spring-like' effect in clubs that
are presently in use have lessened the skill required to play the
game at championships such as the U.S. Open or at the recreational
level,'' said David Fay, USGA executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Fay said that a standard for ``spring-like'' effect will be
established in the next few months through improved testing and
submitted to manufacturers in advance of a meeting this fall.
Although the official rules of golf have contained a reference to
``spring-like'' effect since 1984, the USGA feels it needed to be
clarified.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is what's around the corner,'' USGA president Buzz
Taylor said. ``It's quite clear that we're concerned with the
future of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   John Daly, who plays Callaway equipment and observed from the
back of the interview room, said, ``I don't believe in slowing down
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what America is all about.'' Early reaction from the
equipment companies was understandably favorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the consumers are not only confused about the
conforming process, but are unsure about the future,'' said Wally
Uihlein, CEO of Titleist/Foot-Joy. ``I think the USGA took a big
step today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of restrictions on other equipment also were exaggerated.
Fay said the USGA has been trying for two years to develop a new
test on golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   And there has been talk, but no decision, he said, on limiting
long putters or changing the club limit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
