A4344 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USOPEN-MARTIN-COX     06-17 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USOPEN-MARTIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin's wheel life
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- There's been so much focus on how Casey Martin
gets to his ball, we overlook how he gets to the hitting area. The
practice range, where everyone is stationary, is the place to watch
the huge, smooth shoulder turn and the powerful downswing.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the slight instance where his right leg bends a
bit on the follow-through, there would be no way to discern the
circulatory disease that makes his career as a professional golfer
a day-to-day, minute-to-minute experience.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson doesn't want carts in pro golf, but like everyone
else, he wants Casey Martin, 26, to do well. One aspect is a matter
of compassion. The other is practicality. But, said Watson, ``I
think that he's got a wonderful golf swing. He's got a powerful
golf swing. It's a shame that he has that affliction.''
</P>
<P>
   The real shame is that because of the fight Martin chose to
undertake, his driving stats usually will be about cornering and
handling, not yardage and fairways hit. Martin hates that the cart
always dominates, but such is the double-edged sword. Without the
publicity and attention his disease (Klippel-Trenaunay-Weber
Syndrome), and the cart generated, he wouldn't be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the nature of the way things are going,'' Martin said, ``I
will always probably be known as the person in the golf cart. But I
can handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, having qualified for a U.S. Open that takes place on
familiar turf from his Stanford days, Martin made headlines when
the USGA-supplied, one-seater cart broke down Monday, forcing
implementation of a traditional golf cart. A day later, he won 30
bucks in a friendly match with Tiger Woods and Joel Kribel, his old
college teammates. For news value, the latter item probably has
more significance.
</P>
<P>
   Even Martin's presence here resulted from a struggle in his
sectional qualifier. He double-bogeyed his final hole in
regulation, then birdied the second hole of a playoff to secure a
spot at Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing how things happen,'' Martin said to an interview
room audience larger than Woods drew. ``I never would have dreamt
it. After going through the ordeal with the PGA Tour (lawsuit), I
didn't have any expectations to play in something like this and
really wasn't going to pursue it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest it be forgotten, Martin is a Nike Tour player. This is his
first event with the regular PGA Tour players, but not his first
opportunity. He refused several sponsor exemptions after the court
case, not wishing to fuel the controversy, but will play in the
Canon Greater Hartford Open in two weeks, largely because Hartford
Insurance is one of his sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't feel I was ready (for a PGA Tour event) and I
didn't want to deal with the media crush right then,'' Martin said
of those hectic days following the trial in Eugene, Ore. ``I wanted
some experience and I wanted to get playing on the Nike Tour
first.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to second-guess the plan. Martin won his first event,
the Nike Lakeland Classic. Two more wins or a finish among the Nike
Tour's top 15 money-winners earns exempt status on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody seems to know Casey Martin already. From the gallery,
kids yell his name. In the Olympic locker room, players greet him
warmly. Even those who were against the cart ruling. Martin is
slowly learning that those who didn't want him riding a cart merely
were concerned about future players who might exploit the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met a lot of the guys, and without exception, everyone
has been just extremely kind to me and about extending me
support,'' he said. ``It's been a great experience. It's hard to
believe it's me sitting there and talking to the great players of
the world, and that they know my name (almost) before I know
theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods doesn't deny it. He's lost all objectivity in the
matter. He is anti-golf carts but as pro-Casey as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really like seeing golf carts out here,'' Woods said,
``but he's one of my good friends, and I want to see him out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Watson, another former Stanford man, ``It is a tough
situation the (PGA) tour has taken, but I think the tour is right
in the sense that the game should be played walking. It is still an
athletic endeavor. People in better condition have an advantage to
people who are not in good condition. ... But the compassion must
go to Casey. It goes from me to Casey.'' Martin will be allowed to
take his cart on the fairway precisely to the ball while a caddie
carries his bag. A USGA official usually moves the cart forward as
much as possible for Martin to find when done putting. Cart or no
cart, Martin still has to walk a lot and his limp is painful for
others to watch. The ticket to ride has reduced the pain, Martin
said. So have responses like Tuesday, when thousands of fans at the
18th green roared for his final approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's stuff I dreamt about 10 years ago,'' he said. ``It's a
dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
