<SLUG> BC-FILM-CANTHARDLY-TEX </SLUG>
 
TEENS `CAN'T HARDLY WAIT' TO PARTY LIKE IT'S 1981 (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cannily scheduled to open when most of its audience is out of
school and most of its stars' TV series are in reruns, ``Can't
Hardly Wait'' is like a bracing game of mud volleyball. It's kinda
stupid, extremely messy, even painful at times; but it's fun, even
if you do feel the need to shower afterward.
</P>
<P>
   It took two writer/directors to make this entertaining piece of
junk about a high school graduation-night party, and the movie is
so erratic that it often feels as if filmmakers Harry Elfont and
Deborah Kaplan were fighting over the camera. The strategy seems to
be: Take every '80s teen-party film you can remember, put 'em in a
blender, load the results into a shotgun and fire it at the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that a soundtrack that appears to be a cross between
hitting the ``scan'' button and going on a blindfolded CD-store
shopping spree, and you have a movie that will set a lot of
people's teeth on edge. But if you can bear with the obnoxious
first half, it might break down your resistance; and it will
probably do it about the time a drunken partygoer does a
spontaneous karaoke riff on Guns N' Roses' ``Paradise City,'' one
of the funniest scenes in any movie this year.
</P>
<P>
   Movies like this give a reviewer pause. On a technical level,
it's not very good: The direction is chaotic, the writing uneven,
the characters familiar. We've all seen variations on the
free-spirited guy with a huge crush on the popular girl who just
got dumped by her jock boyfriend, the nerd who plots revenge and
gets it in a way he never expected, the white kid who wants to be
black and the unconventionally attractive (for movies, anyway),
cynical, independent girl.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cast even resembles '80s-bred actors: Peter
Facinelli, as the jock, looks like a young Tom Cruise; Lauren
Ambrose, as the cynical girl, has a faint Molly Ringwald-ish air
about her. One kid looks like a young Tony Danza. Others bring a
TV-based familiarity, including ``Party of Five's'' Jennifer Love
Hewitt as the dumped popular girl, ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer's''
Seth Green as the want-to-be-black kid, and a couple of other young
actors in unbilled cameos that we won't spoil, even if the previews
did.
</P>
<P>
   So it ain't exactly ``The Breakfast Club'' or ``Say Anything
...'' (although it has elements of each, as well as ``Fast Times at
Ridgemont High'' and even ``Animal House).'' But the '90s have been
too bereft of any sort of teen comedies to justify loud complaining
about ``Can't Hardly Wait,'' which falls firmly into the
guilty-pleasure category. Like the kids at the party, you'll
probably have a good time _ and hate yourself in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't Hardly Wait'' is rated PG-13 for strong language, sexual
situations and alcohol abuse, along with enough loud music to
deafen an elephant.
</P>
<P>
   Movie: ``Can't Hardly Wait''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 1-5
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Harry Elfont and Deborah Kaplan
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Jennifer Love Hewitt, Seth Green, Lauren Ambrose
</P>
<P>
   Length: 96 min.
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
