<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-CHISOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX CONTINUE MOMENTUM AGAINST WHITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The momentum is building, and the Red Sox are really
starting to enjoy themselves. They continue to roll against the
Elite and the Dead Meat. Lately, it doesn't make a difference which
they face.
</P>
<P>
   They had their way Wednesday with the Chicago White Sox in a
12-5 victory that was a lot closer than it might sound.
</P>
<P>
   In danger of squandering a 6-3 lead, the Red Sox flexed their
muscles to the tune of a six-run ninth inning _ all the damage
coming with two outs _ and wound up giving manager Jimy Williams
his 400th career victory and taking two of three at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   That gives Boston six wins in its last seven games, and they've
come against the best (National League power Atlanta) and just
about the worst (American League also-rans Tampa Bay and Chicago).
</P>
<P>
   Tim Wakefield's effort Wednesday typified the grit and
resourcefulness that have this team humming. On a bad day, he gave
the Red Sox six innings and left with a lead _ though, at 6-5, it
was shaky.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox supported him by erasing a 3-1 deficit on Mo
Vaughn's 20th home run, a two-run shot in the third, and scored
three times in the fifth with an ack-ack attack _ five singles and
a sacrifice fly _ to take the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly impressive was the way they broke things open in
the ninth and made Tom Gordon's major league-leading 20th save a
cakewalk. Boston sent nine batters to the plate against three
Chicago pitchers, collecting a walk and four hits _ including a
two-run double by Troy O'Leary and a three-run homer by Damon
Buford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really a throwback kind of team,'' explained Darren
Lewis, a throwback kind of leadoff man who went 3 for 5 and scored
three runs. ``Every day we show up and try to win that game. That's
a sign of maturity and one of the reasons we have so much success.
I'm really enjoying my role. I'm a better hitter than I used to be.
I try to get on base any way I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis had help throughout the order as Boston piled up 13 hits.
Nomar Garciaparra and Vaughn each went 3 for 4 and scored three
runs, Vaughn driving in three and Garciaparra two. O'Leary was 2
for 5 with three RBIs, and Buford knocked in three runs.
</P>
<P>
   It all added up to a most pleasant milestone for Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who won his 400th?'' the manager said with a grin. ``Me? I
didn't know. I'm just trying to win a game. We got some key hits.
Everybody pitched good. The big thing today is we got some big
two-out hits. Mo's homer was with two out. Nomar got a two-out walk
just before it. If you look at the score, you'd think it was a
blowout. But it wasn't. It was a tough game. They were pushing us.
That's the way they play.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield could readily attest to that. Things got tight when
Chicago rallied for two runs in the sixth _ on Magglio Ordonez's
RBI double and the pitcher's wild pickoff throw to second that
allowed Robin Ventura to scurry home from third _ and had the tying
run on third with two out. But Wakefield struck out Greg Norton and
wound up joining Pedro Martinez and Bret Saberhagen to give Boston
three eight-game winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't deserve a win on this,'' he said. ``The offense does.
The whole key for the starter is to keep the team in the ballgame.
I did that until my last inning with two outs when things sort of
got away from me. I let two runs in and was fortunate to get a big
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield also got a pick-me-up from Rich Garces, who is
excelling as the setup man and showed why with 1 1/3 shutout
innings. Gordon went the final 1 2/3, stranding the tying run in
the eighth, and picked up his first save in 18 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our success has to do with the kind of team we got
here,'' said Wakefield. ``The bullpen has been good. Bret, Pedro,
and myself have been on the good side of what's happening, and
that's why we have eight wins apiece. It's nice. Real nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, the de facto team spokesman, provided the last word.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has a very solid approach, plays very hard, and
plays together,'' he said. ``We know they're not going to hold us
down forever. We all know our roles. Sometimes it works and
sometimes it doesn't. We take it day by day. I don't know how many
games we've played. I don't know what our record is. It's best that
way. Just go out there and play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
