<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mexico denounces near-border waste site
 &HT;    By Brad Prendergast
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Tx. _ Haze from raging forest fires in Mexico may be
graying Texas skies, but Mexican delegates in Austin Wednesday said
nuclear waste that the state plans to bury near the border poses a
much greater health threat.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican state and federal lawmakers were at the Capitol to
persuade Texas officials to move a proposed radioactive waste
facility from an underground site near Sierra Blanca, a small town
16 miles from the Rio Grande and 90 miles southeast of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   The officials expressed concern that potential radioactive leaks
could cause problems in Mexico but deflected criticisms that their
request was hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unfortunate that we've had the fires, but I don't
think it (the haze) has much relevance,'' said Mexican senator
Norberto Corella, a member of the delegation from Baja California.
</P>
<P>
   Corella cited a 1983 accord between the United States and
Mexico, known as the La Paz treaty, in which the countries agreed
that no new sources of environmental pollution would be knowingly
introduced within 60 miles of either side of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not honoring the agreement,'' he said, at one point
holding up a sample of the 32,000 signatures on a petition from
Mexicans denouncing the site location. ``It's just not right.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegates also met with Texas' secretary of state, Al
Gonzales, who promised to pass their concerns to Gov. George W.
Bush, according to the secretary's spokeswoman, Jane Dees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's office will continue to study the feasibility
of the site,'' Dees said.
</P>
<P>
   The material that would be stored at the site would come from
nuclear plants, hospitals and research institutes in Texas, Vermont
and Maine if Congress approves a pending compact between the
states. Under the compact, the two New England states would pay
Texas $25 millionapiece to have their low-level radioactive waste
buried at the Sierra Blanca waste site.
</P>
<P>
   The compact has been passed by both houses of Congress, and
arrangements were made Monday night to begin ironing out the
differences between the bills from each house.
</P>
<P>
   Debbi Head, a spokeswoman for Bush, said the governor ``will
support the site only if two things occur: if the compact passes
and if the site is deemed safe.'' Licensing hearings for the site
are ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
