<SLUG> BC-USOPEN-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patience the key at Olympic
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Welcome to a different kind of U.S. Open, where
feats of strength will be required as the first round commences
today, but not as frequently as those dealing with finesse. Where,
for a change, oppressive heat and humidity need not be factored in.
Where, except for a few holes, distance is downplayed and daring is
dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the 98th U.S. Open at The Olympic Club, where the
greens are the size of patios, but not as hard as the United States
Golf Association would like.
</P>
<P>
   Where the rough is deeper than what grows on the lawn of your
laziest neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Where the driver could be the least important club in the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Where the weather for three days has been so spectacular _ blue
skies, temperatures in the mid-70's, no humidity _ that locals are
bracing for either brush fires, quakes, floods or a sourdough
strike at Fisherman's Wharf.
</P>
<P>
   Where par is not only a good score; it might be a winning score.
</P>
<P>
   Where the list of contenders is a mixed one, ranging from the
young and the restless to at least one approaching a tour where
everybody takes a cart.
</P>
<P>
   The shotmaker's choice is Justin Leonard. The
middle-of-the-fairway favorites are Colin Montgomerie and Jim
Furyk. Somewhere in the middle are Fred Couples, Ernie Els and
Davis Love _ provided their backs all remain out of spasm.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the picture are David Duval, Stewart Cink and Tiger
Woods. Surely not to be ignored are experienced players such as Tom
Watson, Mark O'Meara and Tom Lehman, whose competitive fires
haven't dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   ```Possible winner' from `not a chance' is a big upgrade for
me,'' said Colonial winner Watson, 48, who lost by a stroke here to
Scott Simpson in 1987. ``I like being a favorite. I'm very
comfortable with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, 26, who won a British Open last summer and finished
behind Love at the PGA, seems to fit Olympic as well as anyone in
the field. He is among the best in shaping the ball and his
temperament is ideal for a tournament where patience is so crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've enjoyed playing the golf course and I feel real good
about my game right now,'' Leonard said Wednesday after a final
practice round. ``Hopefully, I can hit the ball well enough to give
myself a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   For Woods to contend, he must show more patience with the rough
than he's indicated in U.S. Opens past. He tied for 19th at
Congressional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't playing as I would have liked going into
Congressional,'' Woods said. ``This year is different. I feel great
about my swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, who had great chances to win the last three U.S. Opens,
yielded in 1997 to Els by finding the water at the 71st hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get in that situation again this year,'' Lehman said,
``I'm going to be looking more toward the middle of the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
