A4352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USOPEN-BISHER-COX     06-17 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USOPEN-BISHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Storied Open, site meet today's time
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Welcome, from the leeward side of the cliff
that partitions The Olympic Club from the churning Pacific. First
time I ever saw it was aboard a Honduran freighter headed to Pearl
Harbor, never sure I'd ever make it back. I did, several times, but
not in 1956, year of the incredible defeat of Ben Hogan by a foot
soldier out of the pro shop of a public course in Davenport, Iowa.
The subject of this old club, dramatically clinging to a string of
forested precipes, and the U.S. Open never comes up without
connecting it with the year Jack Fleck beat ``The Hawk.''
</P>
<P>
   In those times, the Open was played in three days, with 36 holes
on Saturday. That Fleck should have tied Hogan in the first place
was shock enough, that he should have beat him in a Sunday playoff
was even more improbable.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to have slipped the minds of golf that after the
playoff, Hogan suddenly announced he was retiring. It deflected a
lot of the attention from Fleck in his grandest hour, of course,
and some looked at it as the deliberate purpose. Of course Hogan
didn't retire. He was still playing in the Open 11 years later, but
as time passed, assumed the cloak of an idol, surely too much above
the level of such pettiness. But it happened and has been quietly
dissolved by time.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Casper humiliated Arnold Palmer here in 1966. Scott Simpson
won the Open here in 1987, unpopular among the slanted media,
sitting poised and eager to write of Tom Watson winning. Watson's
25-foot putt failed to fall on the 18th green, after which Simpson
spoke genuinely of his relationship with God.
</P>
<P>
   Now we are back, and all things have changed. We can't keep our
eyes on golf for the carnival going on around us. Tiger Woods comes
to challenge The Olympic. Try that one on for size. Ernie Els won
the last Open at Congressional, but all the covers out here carry
the likeness of Woods. It is a sort of homecoming. He went to
Stanford, ``The Farm,'' they call it here, but the real uproar
centers around another Cardinal, the young Casey Martin, and the
cart he rode in on.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is the Nike Tour player from Eugene, Ore., with the bad
leg. He won the verdict in his hometown court that allows him to be
the only professional on a regular tour allowed to play from a
cart. ``God provides,'' as he has said.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked the other day if he thought that some day he might
be known for his golf game rather than his wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probaby always be known as the person in the golf cart,''
he said. ``I can handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several of his peers who aren't handling too well,
including his fellow alumnus, Watson. ``I think the Tour is right
in the sense that the game should be played walking,'' he said.
Said Jack Nicklaus, ``I don't like it as it relates to the rules of
golf. I'm just questioning the ultimate, what can happen to the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   He would be merely another player in the field, but for the
cart. He made it dramatically and must feel like the two-headed at
the county fair. This is a championship that each year brings out
the backwoods player, some kid or veteran from up the track getting
his one chance at the brass ring. Lee Trevino got his start in the
U.S. Open. There are names here you may be seeing for the first and
last time _ Robert Deruntz, Garrett Larson, Rene Rengel, Derek
Gilchrist, Grant Clough, Gary March, Vaughn Taylor, an amateur from
Augusta, and Ken Peyreferry. All playing for the U.S. championship,
all even with Woods, Watson, Els, Nicklaus, and yes, Casey Martin,
as the first blow is struck.
</P>
<P>
   If fate should tip a hand to anybody, it ought to be Tom Lehman.
This man has finished second or third in each of the last three
Opens. How many times can he be denied?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
