A4355 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-u.s.open-HNS &LR;      06-17 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-u.s. </SLUG>
 open-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ Tom Watson has faced the rigors of a U.S. Open at
the Olympic Club before and survived. In fact, when the national
championship was played here in 1987, Watson finished second.
</P>
<P>
   But even Watson believes it's a much tougher tract facing the
156 golfers who will tee it up today for the first round of the
1998 Open Championship. And by Sunday, it will be the man who uses
patience, not power, who will be the last one standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rough is the worst rough, most difficult rough, that I
have seen in the U.S. Open ever,'' Watson said. ``This is clingy
rough. You just don't know what it is going to do when you are
trying to hit a shot out of it around the green. So it is going to
put a premium on everything, as it always does in the U.S. Open,
but especially this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the winning score here, I think for four rounds it will
be over par.''
</P>
<P>
   After two full days of practice at the Olympic Club, where one
errant drive means bogey at best, other golfers in the field were
starting to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am waiting for them to go out there and cut the rough a
little bit, but my understanding is that they are not going to,''
David Duval said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Jack Nicklaus: ``The golf course is certainly a formidable
test. And it is certainly a golf course that most of the young kids
today will not have experienced, that type of golf course. That
doesn't mean they can't play it. They just won't have experienced
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But they certainly will this week, in all its glory.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it will have to get to the humiliating point before the
USGA intends to do anything to make the Olympic Club any tamer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can't find your golf ball and we start to slow down
play and it really begins to make fun of the best players in the
universe, that is when I don't think it is quite proper,'' said Tim
Morahan, the USGA representative who set up the course. ``I want it
to be a challenge out there, but I don't want it to embarrass
someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as you all know, the U.S. Open has two things that we
strive for _ tough rough and fast, firm greens.''
</P>
<P>
   The players will get a slight break on the latter. The San
Francisco area has been pounded by rain the last few weeks, and
while it has not rained for several days now, the greens remain
softer and slower than Morahan would like. But otherwise, Olympic
is ready to take on whatever the golfers want to throw at her.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara, the Masters champion who is also the king when it
comes to winning on the West Coast, said the game plan should be a
simple one: patience, perseverance and being able to swallow your
pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the U.S. Open is ever about who makes the most
birdies,'' O'Meara said. ``It is definitely not a birdie feast out
there. It is more about managing your good shots and your bad
shots. So you eliminate the big score and try to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   That has proved true nearly every year. In 1997 at Congressional
Country Club, Tiger Woods made the most birdies during the Open,
yet Woods finished tied for 19th.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the players being tabbed over and over as the
favorites to win this weekend aren't necessarily the most
flamboyant, fire-at-the-flag golfers but the ones who seem to find
success by plodding along patiently, taking their pars and an
occasional birdie and never getting ahead of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Players like Colin Montgomerie, Tom Lehman and Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if you were going to pick a couple of tournaments
for me with my game to play well in, this would be one of them,''
Leonard said. ``Because when I am playing well, I hit a lot of
fairways. I make a few putts and avoid making mistakes. I am a very
patient player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those are the kind of attributes that pay off in this
kind of event where par is a really good score, as I think it will
be this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being one of the youngest golfers in the field, Woods
also has more experience than most at Olympic. He played countless
practice rounds here when he was a member of the golf team at
nearby Stanford University. And he likes nothing more than to hear
that his game is not set up for this course, or this major
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like when people say that,'' Woods said. ``It definitely
gets me a little revved up. But you also have to understand you
still go out there and play the game no matter what the
motivational factor is. That is all aside once you step on the
first tee and you have got to go out there and get your focus on
and maintain your confidence all the way through and your patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preparation has been very intense. Physically, mentally, as
far as hitting balls, lifting and then also the mental part of the
game, it has been pretty intense. I am pretty proud of the way I am
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that will be enough for Woods to win at Olympic Club
will begin to unfold today, where the first round of what is
certain to be a very long tournament begins for the best golfers in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to see the names fluctuate on that leader
board,'' O'Meara said. ``It happens every year. We might see some
prizes. But I would think that coming down the stretch on Sunday,
you are going to see a guy who has either been there before or who
has been playing well as of late. It will be the player who can
understand what he can do and what he can't do with a golf ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
