<SLUG> BC-RUN-SPRINTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINING PARTNERS VIE FOR RECORD IN 100-YARD DASH
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Athens, Ato Boldon won a 100-meter dash Wednesday in 9.86
seconds, missing the world record by two-hundredths of a second.
Only two men have run faster in track and field's glamour race.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, an ocean and two half-continents away, Maurice
Greene heard the result and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of stuck on that time,'' Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   Greene said it proudly and with a smile because Boldon is his
training partner and good friend. One or the other seems about to
break the world record. Or perhaps both.
</P>
<P>
   Greene is a 23-year-old American. Boldon is 24 and runs for his
native Trinidad. They train in Los Angeles under John Smith, a
former Olympian and world record-holder who has become track and
field's sprint guru.
</P>
<P>
   Greene will run the 100 meters and maybe the 200 in the U.S.
outdoor championships, which start Friday and end Sunday in New
Orleans. Because the meet is limited to American citizens, Boldon
went to Athens for the Tsiklitiria international, a lesser
competition, and beat Frank Fredericks of Namibia (timed in 9.93
seconds) by two feet. Later, Boldon won the 200 meters in 19.88
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The only accepted 100-meter times faster than Boldon's Wednesday
were 9.84 seconds by Donovan Bailey of Canada in the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics and 9.85 by Leroy Burrell in 1994. Previous 9.86's had
been run by Carl Lewis, Fredericks, Greene and Boldon, with Boldon
doing it two months ago in Walnut, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   There have been faster 100's that do not count. Ben Johnson of
Canada ran 9.79 in the 1988 Seoul Olympics, only to lose the gold
medal and the world record when he tested positive for illegal
bodybuilding drugs. Obadele Thompson of Barbados ran 9.69 in 1996
in El Paso, aided by a following wind far over the
4.473-miles-an-hour limit for record recognition. Greene has run
9.79 this year, aided by a lesser but still excessive wind.
</P>
<P>
   Greene faces the 100-meter quarterfinals and semifinals Friday
night and the final Saturday night. In separate interviews
Wednesday, Greene and Smith said Greene was ready to break the
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the right conditions,'' Smith said, ``Maurice will do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene said: ``My goal is to break the record and as soon as
possible. I'd like to do it every time I step on the track. If Ato
breaks it, I'll be happy for him, and I've just got to break it the
next day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
