<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PAROLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FLAWED APPROACHES TO PAROLE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 18:
</P>
<P>
   The death of Jenna Grieshaber, allegedly at the hands of a
paroled felon, and the recent killing of a New York City police
officer, Anthony Mosomillo, by a man wanted for a parole violation
have fueled efforts to restrict parole in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, has election-year politics. The state Senate, with Gov.
George Pataki's backing, has passed a bill to end parole for
first-time violent offenders. Not to be outdone, the Assembly last
week also approved a bill to end parole.
</P>
<P>
   Neither bill deals with the broader problems in the state's
sentencing structure, of which parole is only a part. But the
Assembly's measure is somewhat less objectionable, because it makes
some effort to rehabilitate inmates as well as lengthen sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, first-time violent offenders are eligible for
parole after serving half of their sentences. In most cases,
offenders are released after serving two-thirds of their sentences.
Both Senate and Assembly proposals would require offenders to serve
at least 85 percent of their sentences. In most cases this would
mean much longer prison stays for many kinds of crimes, ranging
from murder to second-degree burglary.
</P>
<P>
   There is little evidence that simply increasing sentences
enhances public safety in a cost-effective way. As it is, the
inmate population has nearly tripled over the past 15 years, and
the operating budget for state prisons has more than tripled since
1982. The only fiscally responsible way to pay for longer sentences
for violent offenders is to reform other parts of the sentencing
system.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, that means changing the drug laws enacted under
Gov. Nelson Rockefeller that impose long mandatory sentences on
many low-level, nonviolent drug offenders. The tens of millions
spent keeping small-time drug offenders locked up for 15 years or
more could be better deployed on treatment programs to cut crime
associated with drug addiction. Yet Pataki refuses to consider
drug-law reform.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly bill would allow judges to divert some nonviolent
drug offenders into treatment with reduced prison time. That is one
step in the right direction. The bill would also provide more
in-prison addiction treatment and vocational training.
</P>
<P>
   To the governor, these are unnecessary frills. But nearly all
inmates will be released eventually. If prison fails to provide
some means for rehabilitation, ending parole will increase
incarceration costs without significantly improving public safety
in the long run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
