<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEAMSTERS-HOFFA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY TEAMSTERS LEADER BACKS HOFFA FOR UNION PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The president of a large teamsters' local in New York
City, who two years ago was a running mate of the union's
president, Ron Carey, announced Wednesday that he was endorsing
James P. Hoffa in this summer's campaign for the union's
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement, by Carroll Haynes, president of Teamsters Local
237, which represents 23,000 government employees in New York City
and on Long Island, was a surprise because in 1996 he was elected
vice president of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters when
he ran on Carey's slate.
</P>
<P>
   Carey defeated Hoffa in that race, but federal monitors
overturned that election and ordered a rerun when they found that
Carey campaign aides had improperly siphoned union money into the
Carey campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Carey has been barred from running again.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement endorsing Hoffa, Haynes said: ``It's time for
healing, and time to come together to protect and insure the
survival of our great union. Teamsters need to focus their energies
on electing a leader who can unite our deeply fractured union.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, who is widely considered the favorite, welcomed the
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   He is opposed by Thomas Leedham, director of the union's
warehouse division and a member of the union's Carey wing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2150EDT &QL; 
