<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4361 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CROSSWORLDS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-17 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROSSWORLDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Tech's Glamour Gal   By Carolyn Said  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
She stares confidently from the magazine page, her lips shaping a
wisp of a smile, her body sheathed in a low-cut black dress. She
could be advertising liquor or cigarettes, perfume or cosmetics.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Katrina Garnett is selling ``CrossWorlds United Application
Architecture,'' from CrossWorlds Software of Burlingame. And she's
not a model; she's the president, chief executive and founder of
the company _ a woman who works hard to burnish her reputation as a
technologist and a feminist.
</P>
<P>
   The glamour shot, now appearing in Vanity Fair, Forbes, Fortune,
George and other upscale magazines, illustrates how some high-tech
firms attempt to build their images around charismatic leaders
rather than complicated products.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Customers aren't just buying our software, they're buying a
relationship,'' Garnett said. ``They want to know who is behind
CrossWorlds. I put a face on the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Basing a corporate image on a CEO isn't new. Chrysler, Men's
Wearhouse and Wendy's have all done it.
</P>
<P>
   Like those traditional businesses, Silicon Valley startups
increasingly promote their technology hotshots in ads and articles.
Netscape's Marc Andreessen, Marimba's Kim Polese and Yahoo's Jerry
Yang and David Filo have achieved star status thanks to aggressive
marketing machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``America has always lionized captains of industry,'' said Santa
Cruz author Paulina Borsook, whose book ``Cyberselfish:
Technolibertarians and the True Revenge of the Nerds'' is due out
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The railroad and oil barons appealed to the imagination of the
19th century. Now, technology people are getting that sense about
themselves: `We're sexy; what we do matters and it has high
sheen,''' Borsook said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a celebrity era, whether it's movie stars, athletes
or politicians,'' said Felix Gutierrez, executive director of the
Pacific Coast Center of the Freedom Forum, a foundation focused on
media issues. ``This seems like an assertive attempt to have
customers identify with the creative energy/vision person behind
the technology.''
</P>
<P>
   But some people think that the Crossworlds ad is too assertive
in its use of sex appeal and its close resemblance to an editorial
feature.
</P>
<P>
   Labeled simply ``Trail Blazer'' and photographed by the renowned
Richard Avedon, it blends into magazines like just another glossy
article.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's creating a stir,'' said Laurie Kretchmar, editor in chief
of Women.com, a San Mateo network of Web sites. ``It's a beautiful
ad, but it looks like an editorial photo feature. The twist is that
it's a very attractive female CEO. Her choice of attire was
interesting. Let's face it, sex sells.''
</P>
<P>
   Marleen McDaniel, president and chief executive of Women.com,
said she prefers ads that focus on substance over style. ``I think
this kind of approach misses the point, unless the company is
Victoria's Secret,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some are even more blunt. &UR;  &LR; ``In the valley, people don't care
what you look like, they care what you've accomplished,'' said an
employee at one Internet software company. ``This seems like an
egotistic thing, trading on sex appeal to get attention.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Garnett said the ad isn't about sex, it's about defining a
brand image for CrossWorlds. ``Just because I'm in high tech, I
don't have to look like a nerd,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The ad's copy reads like a Dewar's profile. It states her age as
``Younger than Bill Gates, older than Michael Dell.'' (She's 35.)
It lists Garnett's birthplace, ``Australia's Gold Coast''; favorite
charity, ``Started Garnett Foundation to encourage girls to pursue
technical careers''; and background, ``10 years on the firing line
at Oracle and Sybase.''
</P>
<P>
   It also describes CrossWorlds' investors, ``Raised $45 (million)
from Intel, Compaq, SAP, Manugistics, JD Edwards, Ernst &AMP; Young,''
and ``Bigtime backers: Dave Duffield, Michael Dell, Andy Ludwick.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall message is that Garnett and the company ``take
risks, aim high, believe in what we're doing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   CrossWorlds' software knits together disparate enterprise
applications, such as an inventory system and payroll software. At
$250,000 and up, it's strictly for huge corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett and her husband _ venture capitalist Terence Garnett,
who is on CrossWorlds' board _ have put $5.5 million of their own
money into the company. CrossWorlds does not have an outside ad
agency; the Garnetts conceived the ad and worked with Breeze
Productions of Woodside to execute it.
</P>
<P>
   The ad targets decision-makers at the Fortune 100 companies that
are potential clients, Garnett said.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts were dubious about the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of approach to selling middleware isn't terribly
successful,'' said Ed Acly, director of middleware research at
International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass. ``It would be more
strategic to talk about solving a problem where people are really
hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Chuck Pettis of BrandSolutions in Seattle said the
personality approach is ideal for making a brand name come alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brand is about emotion, status, culture,'' he said. ``I have
to congratulate Katrina Garnett for having the bravery to pose like
that. When she goes to a trade show, they're going to love her.''
</P>
<P>
   Agnieszka Winkler, president of Winkler Advertising in San
Francisco showed the ad to a focus group of both technical and
nontechnical people.
</P>
<P>
   Reactions to the ad's content broke along gender and age lines.
``Younger women felt it was good, showing a woman who is proud to
be a woman and isn't hiding it. Older women had a hard time getting
over the fact that she was in a cocktail dress and not a suit,''
Winkler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men didn't have an emotional response to the ad _ or were
trying to hide their response _ but couldn't understand what it was
about and what the company does,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If grabbing eyeballs is the ultimate purpose of advertising, the
ad is a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``This breaks through the clutter and arrests the viewer,'' said
Andrew Hayman, executive vice president of Publicis, a San
Francisco ad agency. ``Using sex for stopping power doesn't
surprise me. Why not use the same vehicle to sell technology that
we use to sell soap or shampoo?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
