<SLUG> BC-FILM-SIX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``SIX DAYS'' IS LONG ON TIME, SHORT ON CAFFEINE
</HEADLINE>
 DAYS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're wondering how believable Anne Heche is as the romantic
lead in ``Six Days, Seven Nights,'' wonder no more. She has
chemistry to burn, although trailers for the movie don't help; as
Ford fishes a snake out of her shorts, you can hear the announcer
intoning ominously about Heche and her co-star Harrison Ford
exploring remote territory. There's enough subtext there to keep
French critics cranking out Freudian papers for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in her low, smoky voice there's more character than
anything Michael Browning bothered to write for her. Yes, she's the
spoiled, tense editor for ``Dazzle'' a New York fashion magazine.
Heche ends up trapped on a wild adventure with a surly pilot (Ford)
who is so tough he acts like he shaves with broken beer bottles. At
least that would explain why he's so cranky. When we first meet
him, he already has that pinched, Harrison Ford man-of-action
expression on his face, his features tweezed into a point.
Generally, it takes him about half an hour to get to that point. So
when he walks into the movie already cranked up into a full Ford,
you know he's trying to compensate for something.
</P>
<P>
   Arbitrarily chasing into the territory pioneered by ``The
African Queen'' and 40 or 50 other better movies, Ford and Heche
are bound together after a mission to explore a faraway island goes
horribly wrong. He crashes the plane, and the two of them must fend
for themselves against bad guys, the uncharted wilds and the
ravages of the script; they run into everything but Gilligan and
the Skipper. The limp, perfunctory direction by Ivan Reitman makes
this attempt at action comedy seem in desperate need of a cup of
coffee, if not a fistful of Viagra. A movie full of so many obvious
turns should at least be energetic and quick, but ``Six Days, Seven
Nights'' seems to last as long as its title.
</P>
<P>
   As her boyfriend, David Schwimmer has technique to burn, and
maybe that wouldn't be such a bad idea; his confident acting style
borders on bullying. He is playing a character here closer to the
nattering, neurotic Ross from ``Friends,'' which supposedly makes
it easy to see why Heche would turn to Ford. Schwimmer is a pouty
boy, and Ford is a man. A man's man, although it turns out later in
the movie that he knows as much about contemporary fashion as any
of the miniskirted fillies you're likely to see in the halls of
``Vogue'' magazine, or an episode of ``Friends,'' for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention an older man's man. Like poor Gwyneth Paltrow in
``A Perfect Murder,'' or Halle Berry in ``Bulworth'' _ or any 40 or
50 recent pictures you could name _ Heche is paired with a man
literally old enough to be her father. In the poster for ``Six
Days, Seven Nights,'' it almost looks as if Heche is carrying Ford
to safety; and had the movie been smart enough to include a turn
like that, it might have been fun. (At least in ``Bulworth,''
Warren Beatty has the good sense to look embarrassed when Berry
busts him on being 60.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie does look good, and Ford throws himself into the
cliche. Heche rises to the occasion and gives better than she gets,
proving that she's an actress, and a good one, so her sexual
orientation has nothing to do with her onscreen presence. We can
only hope that no one in Hollywood holds this movie against her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' is rated PG-13 for adult language and
cartoon-style violence.
</P>
<P>
   Movie: ``Six days, Seven Nights''
</P>
<P>
   Score: 2 stars on a scale of 1-5
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Harrison Ford, Anne Heche, David Schwimmer
</P>
<P>
   Director: Ivan Reitman
</P>
<P>
   Rating: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
