 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Net Maven Smoking Mad Over `Burn Rate'   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Net entrepreneur Isabel Maxwell is still fuming from the rough
treatment she gets in ``Burn Rate,'' Michael Wolff's story of his
own failed Internet startup.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What bugs her most is Wolff's stated reluctance to negotiate
with Maxwell; her husband, David Hayden; and her sister, Christine
Maxwell, who ran an early '90s Internet search site called
Magellan.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could anyone do business with the Maxwells?'' Wolff wrote,
alluding to the intrigue and scandal surrounding the death of their
father, Robert Maxwell, and the unraveling of his European
publishing empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a gratuitous and inaccurate reference,'' said
Maxwell, taking issue with something that others have noted about
Wolff's work _ his blow-by-blow quotes of supposedly closed-door
meetings, that make the reader feel like a fly on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff told me that none of those quotes were invented, that he
habitually took notes while he, Hayden and the Maxwell sisters were
playing ``let's make a merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell scoffed. ``In any of the meetings where I was present,
he never took notes,'' she said, adding, ``If he wasn't Linda
Tripping it, he was Stephen Glassing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell feels that the market has vindicated her business
acumen. ``We successfully sold our business to Excite,'' she said.
``I can't say as much for Mr. Wolff.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolff will have a chance to confess his sins next Wednesday
night at the Barnes and Noble bookstore on Stevens Creek in San
Jose, where he joins venture capitalists Ann Winblad and Rob Reid,
and journalists Jonathan Weber, Po Bronson and Chip Bayers to
discuss the perils of Internet startups.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Budding enterprises: &LR;  Macromedia Chairman Bud Colligan has
been moonlighting as a venture capitalist with Accel Partners in
Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Colligan's hottest investment is Seattle-based Cybermeals, which
hopes to become the 1-800-Flowers of take-out food on the Web,
creating a nationwide network of restaurants to deliver cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   The company's founding team includes San Francsico investment
banker H. William Jesse, software executive Tim Glass, chief
technologist Bryan Cupps and football legend Fran Tarkenton, who
serves on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Headhunter John Thompson reportedly is looking for a CEO to get
this food fight cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Colligan's other startup, Bright Light Technologies in San
Francisco, will make a business out of stopping spam. Chief
executive Sunil Paul is keeping his plans under wraps but
reportedly intends to sell spam control to Internet service
providers.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Silicon Island? &LR;  A labor-force study is the prime weapon in
Alameda's latest bid to lure tech firms away from the congested
South Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hoppen, an executive with the Harbor Bay Business Park, said
that more than 495,000 people, about 30 percent of whom hold
college degrees, live within a 30-minute drive of Alameda. By
comparison, the Fremont area has a slightly larger labor pool of
540,000 but only 26 percent are college grads.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Famous last words: &LR;  It hardly caused a stir last week when IBM
and Motorola ended their joint ownership of the Texas lab that
designs PowerPC chips for Apple's Macintosh computer.
</P>
<P>
   John Wharton is a semiconductor analyst who followed the
PowerPC's early days, when Apple, IBM and Motorola pledged to take
Intel down a peg. He dug out notes from a 1991 briefing by Apple's
then-Chairman John Sculley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are well aware there is no successful track record of
relationships with IBM, with anybody,'' Sculley said, before
insisting the PowerPC deal would be different.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Narcissus.com? &LR;  Yesterday's column about Webcams prompted
Leander Kahney of San Francisco to point out the Web page of Eric
Ciprian _ an Intel employee who has six cameras peering into his
apartment and office in Oregon ( &LR; cip &LR;   &LR; rian.com/syncity). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ciprian also keeps an online diary for those who want to peer
into his mind, and a discussion group for those who want to talk
about his Truman-like experiment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
