<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Oracle's Services Unit Boosts 4th-Quarter Gain   By Jamie Beckett  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Oracle Corp. reported better-than-expected profits for its fiscal
fourth quarter yesterday, propelled largely by continued growth in
its technology-services business.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The company, the world's largest vendor of database software,
posted earnings of $402.8 million (41 cents a share) in the three
months ended May 31, compared with $360 million (36 cents) in the
year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street had expected the Redwood Shores firm to report a
profit of 38 cents a share, according to IBES International.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue jumped 24 percent to $2.4 billion from $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Like many software-makers, Oracle increasingly is relying on its
computer-services arm for growth. The services business, which
helps customers install and integrate software, was Oracle's
strongest in the quarter, posting a 43 percent gain to $1.17
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Services continue to be the shining star, but we expect
license revenue to pick up in fiscal 1999,'' Gary Abbott, an
analyst at Punk Ziegel &AMP; Co., told Bloomberg Business News.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Oracle database licenses showed continued improvement,
rising 12.6 percent to $873 million. Sales of applications _
prepackaged software that works with the database _ which have been
lagging all year, fell slightly to $215.8 million from $218.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Oracle's applications &UR;  &LR; have lagged the growth rates of rivals
PeopleSoft Inc., Baan Co. and SAP of Germany for the past three
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a disappointing year for applications,'' said Jeff
Henley, Oracle's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Henley said Oracle expects new application software that started
shipping last month to help sales. The company has also revamped
its applications business _ chief executive Larry Ellison took over
the division, and the sales force was reorganized.
</P>
<P>
   Results were released after the market closed. Oracle rose 6
cents to $24.31 on Nasdaq. In after-hours trading, it gained about
$2 more.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, profit rose to $955 million (96 cents) from $845
million (84 cents) in fiscal 1997. Figures for both years exclude
one-time charges related to acquisitions of Treasury Services Corp.
and Navio Communications Inc. in the past year and Datalogix in
fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Annual revenue was up 26 percent to $7.1 billion from $5.7
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
