<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 AOL Up on News It Rejected AT&AMP;T   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Shares of America Online vaulted yesterday on reports that the
world's largest online service recently rebuffed a $19 billion
buyout offer from AT&AMP;T.
<TEXT>
<P>
   AOL stock rose $4.88, to $93.88, in heavy Nasdaq trading on the
heels of a published report in the Financial Times. The British
newspaper, citing unnamed sources close to both companies, said
AT&AMP;T Chairman Michael Armstrong approached AOL several weeks ago
with a takeover offer but was turned down by Chief Executive Steve
Case and Robert Pittman, chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and AOL declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's apparent interest in AOL shows the telephone giant is
willing to pay a steep price for a leading role in the fast-growing
Internet market, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   An acquisition of the Dulles, Va., company would greatly expand
AT&AMP;T's online customer base and help offset its declining
long-distance business. AOL, with 12 million subscribers, dwarfs
AT&AMP;T's sputtering online service, WorldNet, which reaches 1.1
million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T isn't thrilled with its lot in the ISP market,'' said
analyst Brian Adamik, of Yankee Group in Boston. ``This way, they
would gain 12 million customers overnight and they could introduce
voice over the Internet via AOL's instant-messaging technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Case says it is ``conceivable'' that AOL will meld voice
technology into its Internet chat technology, which allows more
than 80 million Net surfers to privately exchange instant messages.
The only hitch is that AOL doesn't have enough network capacity to
provide voice communication _ and AT&AMP;T and other telecommunications
companies do.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, industry insiders splashed cold water on an
AT&AMP;T-AOL merger.
</P>
<P>
   If Case is shopping AOL, he would be more likely to pursue a
deal with WorldCom Inc., where he is a board member, analysts said.
What's more, WorldCom is awaiting federal regulatory approval of a
proposed $37 billion merger with AT&AMP;T rival MCI Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Should AT&AMP;T's bid for AOL fail, it may try to buy MSN,
Microsoft's online service, said PaineWebber analyst Jim Preissler.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T isn't the only company that covets AOL, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of interest in AOL among media powerhouses like
Disney and Time Warner,'' said Preissler, who estimates a
successful takeover bid of AOL could fetch $125 to $150 a share, or
a mind-boggling $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL's site has become prime real estate for banner ads and an
online means to promote movies, books and entertainment,''
Preissler said.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's prime-time audience of 625,000 reaches more viewers than
MTV (502,000).
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T shares improved $1.06 to $63 in trading yesterday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
