<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Levi's New Ads Feature `Hard Jeans'   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Stiff-as-a-board ``hard jeans,'' made from an old style of denim
not prewashed for softness, have the starring role in Levi Strauss
&AMP; Co.'s long-awaited new television advertising campaign.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The six spots, which began airing yesterday, include stiff pairs
of cuffed jeans walking straight-legged, being dipped in a vat of
dark, oily-looking liquid and falling over and hitting the ground
with a clank that sounds like a hammer hitting an anvil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Levi's brand has always been about strength, character and
quality,'' said Mark Hogan, director of consumer marketing for the
Levi's brand. ``This is a way to put it all together and do it in
an in-your-face, cutting-edge way.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a way, Levi's hopes, to completely change the fashion
direction of the blue jeans market, which has been dominated by
soft, prewashed fabric since the early 1980s. ``We think that
creating a desire for this new look is a major opportunity to make
the jeans in peoples' wardrobes obsolete,'' said Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising experts were generally positive about the humorous
and eye-catching new ads, but they were less enthusiastic about the
featured product.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they sacrifice comfort for style and image, they will find
they are pushing the wrong buttons,'' said Erik Olson, managing
director of Greenfield Consulting, a consumer research firm.
``There clearly is a comfort mentality in the U.S. now,'' even
among the 15- to 21-year-old males targeted by the ads, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hogan asserts that stiff denim is a growing trend in
the marketplace. Sales of Levi's vintage jeans, made from the
old-style fabric, have grown noticeably in the past year. Other
companies, such as Diesel, are also selling hard jeans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important look that's happening, and since we've
owned it over time, it's important that we continue to own it,''
Hogan said. Young consumers who buy the jeans will also discover
the characteristic that made them popular in earlier generations _
the jeans become soft and comfortable over time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, created by TBWA Chiat/Day, represents a
significant departure from Levi's last round of TV ads, which were
developed by the company's former ad agency Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding
/San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier spots, which featured gritty, urban characters, a
disjointed story line and obscure cultural references, were
designed to update Levi's brand image. The current spots focus
completely on the product.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan said the two approaches are not mutually exclusive. ``Our
product is the key element of the brand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will run through the end of the year on NBC, Fox,
and cable networks that include MTV and ESPN. Ten to 12 new spots
will be added over the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   TBWA Chiat/Day is also preparing magazine and radio ads, as well
as billboards that will come on top of two other recent billboard
campaigns. The company declined to disclose the cost of the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's good about this campaign is that they're going back to
talking about Levi's,'' said Liz Dunning, a senior vice president
with Addison, a brand-consulting firm. ``Also, this approach gives
Levi's a point of differentiation in a jeans market that has become
very generic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
