<HEADER>
A4369 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-1STL     06-17 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DROPS TOBACCO BILL WITH HOPES FOR REVIVAL DIM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add 12 grafs at end of story and for re-editing
throughout)   (See also CONGRESS-TOBACCO-ASSESS, TOBACCO-MCCAIN, EDIT-TOBACCO) 
(ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Wednesday jettisoned broad
legislation meant to discourage teen-agers from smoking, the most
ambitious and contentious measure before Congress, and left almost
no hope it could be revived this year.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which had been debated on the Senate floor for a
month, was set aside when supporters, mostly Democrats, could not
get the 60 votes needed to clear two procedural hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats promised to bring the matter up again at every
opportunity this year, but they conceded that they had little
chance of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that the final vote on this bill occurs on Election
Day,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Republican opponents of the bill, which would have raised the
price of cigarettes by $1.10 a pack, argued that it was not
primarily an anti-smoking measure but a tax increase to pay for
government programs. ``This is a massive tax on low-income
Americans, and it is used to proliferate the bureaucracy of this
government,'' declared Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John McCain, the maverick Republican from Arizona who
was the bill's chief sponsor, emphasized the importance of stopping
teen-agers from getting hooked on smoking. ``This bill is not about
taxes,'' he told the Senate just before the votes. ``It's about
whether we're going to allow the death march of 418,000 Americans a
year who die early from tobacco-related disease and do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who favors strong anti-smoking legislation,
criticized the Senate, blamed the tobacco companies and their
advertising campaign for the bill's defeat and made it clear that
he would use the issue for partisan purposes in the fall's
congressional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been working for three years now to protect our
children from the dangers of tobacco,'' Clinton said in an
impromptu appearance in the White House briefing room on Wednesday
evening. ``I want the tobacco lobby and its allies on Capitol Hill
to know that from my point of view, the battle is far from over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, the Republican leader, said The Senate was so
divided on the issue that it was impossible to produce a bill that
would command the 60 votes needed in the Senate to pass contentious
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   On the crucial vote, 57 senators voted to cut off debate and
move to a final vote, a procedure called cloture. But that was
three votes shy of 60 votes necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three Democrats and 14 Republicans voted in favor of
cloture. Forty Republicans and two Democrats from tobacco states,
Wendell Ford of Kentucky and Charles Robb of Virginia, voted
against it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Senate dealt the final blow by voting to send the bill
back to the Commerce Committee. It would have required 60 votes to
prevent this, and the supporters fell seven votes short.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in the House of Representatives have been
waiting to see what happened in the Senate before they acted on a
tobacco bill. They are opposed to ambitious legislation like the
Senate bill. The word in the House on Wednesday night was that the
leaders might still try to pass some low-budget alternative.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on Wednesday night, House Speaker Newt Gingrich
said: ``It is our intent to take up and pass effective legislation
that is narrowly focused on anti-teen smoking, anti-drug efforts.
Our goal is to reduce teen smoking, not increase taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to raising the price of cigarettes over the next
five years, the Senate measure would have given the government new
authority to regulate tobacco advertising and marketing and imposed
stiff penalties on cigarette makers if the rate of teen-age smoking
did not fall to specified levels.
</P>
<P>
   But amendments added in the Senate in the last few weeks would
have given a tax break to married couples and established new
programs against drug abuse. These measures will die with the
overall bill, though they might be added to other legislation
before the year is out.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was prompted to take up the tobacco issue by the
settlement signed a year ago this Saturday by the major tobacco
companies and the attorneys general from 40 states. Under the
agreement, the industry would have paid $368.5 billion over the
next 25 years and agreed to restraints on tobacco advertising. In
return, they would have been given immunity from most lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The settlement required congressional action before it could go
into effect. Without a federal law, the states are expected to
press their multibillion-dollar legal claims against the tobacco
companies. Individuals may also be more likely to go to court now,
especially in light of the decision by a jury in Florida last week
to find the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. liable for a smoker's
death.
</P>
<P>
   When the bill came out of McCain's committee in April on a
19-to-1 bipartisan vote, its prospects for approval seemed good.
But the tobacco companies rebelled when they realized that the
Senate was not going to protect them from lawsuits, and began a
national advertising campaign against the bill said to cost tens of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's supporters said that the ads turned the tide, much as
ads by insurance companies were held responsible for defeating
President Clinton's health-care plan in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco companies have made a very wise investment, and
they have won,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Duchesne, a spokesman retained by the tobacco industry,
said that the Senate action on Wednesday was ``evidence the public
came to understand what was in the bill.'' Higher taxes, he said,
would not have solved the youth smoking problem.
</P>
<P>
   From the other side, C. Everett Koop, the former surgeon
general, said: ``I hope that the senators who derailed this bill
today lose sleep every night listening to the sound of children
taking their first puff and the sound of emphysema and cancer
patients gasping for their last breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Koop, who served under Presidents Ronald Reagan and George Bush,
added, ``I hope it keeps the Republican leadership awake, too.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McCain, knowing he was facing defeat and clearly deflated by the
experience, gave a speech unusually critical of his own party. He
noted that some of his colleagues had said that the action on the
tobacco legislation would define the Republican Party, and he
continued:
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Mr. President, there may be something to that.
Because maybe we ought to remember the obligations that we incur
when we govern America. Maybe we ought to remember the principles
of the founder of our party. We might want to understand that our
obligation first of all is to those who can't care for themselves
in this society, and that includes our children. Shouldn't it
define the Republican Party that we should do everything we can to
handle this scourge, this disease that is rampant throughout young
children in America? Doesn't that define the Republican Party?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain then put down his microphone and walked off the Senate
floor. Across the aisle, in an extremely unusual gesture,
Democratic senators stood and applauded. Republicans remained
silent in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's votes came after a day of huddles by leaders from
both parties to count votes. Republicans said that Lott had made
clear that he would allow no votes until he was sure his side would
win.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats left no doubt that they would use the issue in the
congressional election campaigns this fall and portray Republicans
as tools of the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The question before the Senate, said Sen. Kent Conrad of North
Dakota, was ``Do we protect our children's lives or do we protect
the profits of the tobacco industry?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader,
declared: ``This bill may be dead. But tobacco legislation is not
dead. We will not let this issue die. We will come back. We will
keep at it.''
</P>
<P>
   But most Republicans seemed unfazed by such arguments, confident
that the public was more concerned about a tax increase than about
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill breaks the budget,'' said Sen. Don Nickles of
Oklahoma, the assistant Republican leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
