<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Microsoft Sets Its Sites on Home Loans   By Julia Angwin  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Do you trust Bill Gates to pick your mortgage broker?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft is betting you will. The software giant plans to
launch a new Web site this summer to help home buyers find
mortgages and houses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Called Home Advisor, the site will be Microsoft's third
electronic commerce venture. The Redmond, Wash., firm already runs
successful Web sites selling cars and airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to be acting in General Electric style, by having a
top site in each category,'' said Chris Stevens, analyst at the
Aberdeen Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they increase their Internet properties, they have the
ability to cross-reference their listings and find out more about
people,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft announced its intention to get into the $10 billion
online real estate and mortgage market last year and confirmed
yesterday it will launch Home Advisor this summer.
</P>
<P>
   While Microsoft was building its site, dozens of competitors are
already vying to cater to home buyers.
</P>
<P>
   In the online mortgage business, top players include HomeShark
of San Francisco and E-Loan of Palo Alto, which are both
celebrating their one-year anniversaries this month, and Intuit of
Mountain View, which is preparing the third version of its
8-month-old QuickenMortgage Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In the real estate listings business, top sites include the
National Association of Realtors, which has already got 95 percent
of the market covered with its Realtor.Com site, and
Minneapolis-based CyberHomes, which has amassed 75 percent of the
nation's home listings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its late entry, many are betting that Microsoft will
bulldoze its way into a top spot in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time Microsoft comes into an electronic service, it puts
an 800-pound gorilla in the ring,'' said Vernon Keenan, senior
analyst at Zona Research in Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   But most online home-buying services are reluctant to speak
badly of their soon-to-be competitor. Instead, they say they hope
Microsoft's arrival will grow the market for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest competition is not Microsoft, it's simply making
people aware that (buying a mortgage online) is an option,'' said
Ned Hoyt, CEO of HomeShark. ``I'm happy to have Microsoft to spend
the money to do that for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some competitors have begun gearing up for Microsoft's
arrival. E-Loan started blanketing the Seattle area with ads three
weeks ago and is currently raising $10 million for a nationwide ad
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little bit of a trust issue with Microsoft,'' said
E-Loan CEO Chris Larsen. ``We think people will probably wonder,
`Are they going to sell my data?' We would never ever do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Larsen said he hopes to show consumers that they will get a
better deal by buying a mortgage directly through E-Loan rather
than by getting a referral to a loan officer from the Microsoft
site.
</P>
<P>
   That's because E-Loan _ as well as HomeShark and Intuit _ offers
customers a break on the commissions usually charged by loan
brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The online brokers charge about 0.5 percent of the mortgage,
while an ``offline'' loan officer usually charges between 1 and 2
percent commission.
</P>
<P>
   Because Microsoft is referring customers to loan officers rather
than writing loans itself, it cannot offer similar savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't tell customers that you're saving them thousands
of dollars, then why (would they) bother'' buying a loan online,
said Keenan, the Zona analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit realized just that after launching its mortgage site last
fall using the referral model. In March of this year, Intuit
switched to originating loans _ and giving home buyers a price
break _ instead of simply charging mortgage bankers for customer
referrals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've evolved quite a bit,'' said Alison Berkley, senior
product manager for QuickenMortgage.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said she is worried that Microsoft will repeat its
Web browser strategy: Gain market share by giving away products.
</P>
<P>
   ``What concerns us the most is if they destroy the entire
economics of the industry,'' Berkley said. ``Because of their deep
pockets, they have the ability to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft product manager Larry Cohen dismissed the notion the
company would give anything away on its site. He said he doesn't
expect Microsoft to displace any competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not focused on beating HomeShark or beating Intuit,''
Cohen said. ``There's room for multiple players. It's not one
winner takes all.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the area of real estate listings, Microsoft may even have
some catching up to do. Home Advisor is slated to launch with
complete real estate listings for some _ but not all _ metropolitan
areas, while its competitors have amassed sizable portions of the
U.S. market. Microsoft hasn't yet said which locales it will
target.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Realtor.Com has 1.2 million home listings _ out of
the roughly 1.3 million listings in the nation, according to
Michael Keller, vice president of marketing at RealSelect Inc. in
Westlake Village (Los Angeles County), which produces the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you can see how Microsoft will have a challenge gaining a
foothold in an industry where a leader like us is already
established,'' Keller said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
