<SLUG> BC-PROBE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Independent Counsel Online   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Kenneth Starr may be grabbing most of the headlines for his
four-year probe of President Clinton. But he's not the only
independent counsel searching for crimes in the executive branch or
the first to set up his own Internet site to publicize results.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That honor goes to Daniel Smaltz, who since 1994 has been
tracking down alleged abuses of power by former Agriculture
Secretary Mike Espy.
</P>
<P>
   After Starr, Smaltz has garnered the most publicity _ both kudos
and criticism _ for that long-running probe, which has California
connections. Sun-Diamond Growers and one of its former executives
were charged with providing illegal gratuities. And Robert Mondavi
Corp. was questioned last month about its connection with Espy.
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz also recently set up the first Office of Independent
Counsel Web site ( &LR; www.oic.gov &LR; ) to provide an update on
prosecutions as well as legal briefs, press releases and speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the Web site,'' Smaltz said, ``I hope the public will
develop an informed understanding of the role of the Independent
Counsel in investigating allegations of wrongdoing by high-ranking
government officials.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first week of its operation, the Web site attracted
3,330 hits. But traffic quickly tapered off to about one-tenth that
total in later weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Secretary Espy is long gone. He left office under a
cloud in 1994. But the investigation by Smaltz and 10 other
attorneys into Espy's alleged acceptance of more than $35,000 in
illegal gratuities from companies and individuals regulated by his
department, goes on.
</P>
<P>
   The Smaltz team has won 10 guilty verdicts and recovered $10.5
million in criminal fines and civil penalties, said Deputy
Independent Counsel Ted Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Like Starr, Smaltz's investigation has generated plenty of
controversy. And some of his targets, including Espy's brother
Henry, have been acquitted or had convictions against them
overturned on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   California's Sun-Diamond Growers was found guilty and fined $1.5
million for giving illegal gifts worth about $6,000 _ including
luggage and a Waterford crystal bowl filled with nuts _ to the
former agriculture secretary.
</P>
<P>
   But this past March, a three-judge panel reversed that
conviction because the jury was given improper instructions. Smaltz
is asking for a rehearing.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you won't find on the Smaltz Web site is just how much
he has spent on his investigation. After several phone calls,
Greenberg said that the Smaltz probe has cost taxpayers $14,832,985
through last September, including $2.5 million in the most recently
tabulated six-month period.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the investigations by Starr and his predecessor
into Whitewater and other Clinton capers have cost more than $35
million through last September.
</P>
<P>
   You also won't discover online the latest twists and turns in
Smaltz's investigation, such as the recent grilling of Robert
Mondavi Corp. The Napa Valley winemaker confirmed that last month
Smaltz's office asked its government affairs manager Herbert
Schmidt to testify about a 1993 visit by Espy to view vineyard
damage caused by the root louse phylloxera. The tour was hosted by
Mondavi.
</P>
<P>
   Winery spokesman Bob Philipps would only say that the company
and its attorneys ``are cooperating fully with the office of
Independent Counsel and will have no further comment at this
time.'' Smaltz's office declined comment on whether Mondavi is
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz's biggest hit was against Tyson Foods. The big Arkansas
poultry producer pleaded guilty to providing $12,000 in illegal
gratuities to Espy and agreed to pay a whopping $4 million fine and
$2 million more to cover government investigation costs.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Espy paid a $50,000 fine for using money from his
previous congressional campaigns to help pay his more than $300,000
in legal bills stemming from the independent counsel probe.
However, Espy continues to deny he is guilty of accepting illegal
gifts and awaits trial.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Espy suffered a setback when a three-judge panel of
the U.S. Court of Appeals reversed a lower court ruling and
reinstated three charges against him. (The charges are the only
ones in the 39-count indictment that carry a mandatory prison term
of at least one year each.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The charges are predicated on politics,'' said one lawyer who
insisted on anonymity because his corporate client remains a Smaltz
target. ``They start with the premise that a government official
must be guilty of something and then they have unlimited resources
and time to make a case.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Starr, Smaltz also has been criticized for making a big
deal out of seemingly small transgressions. &UR;  &LR; But Deputy Independent
Counsel Greenberg, who last month was anointed Smaltz's media
spokesman, replacing Charles Bakaly who took a similar post under
Starr, strongly disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because the amount is small doesn't make the crime any
less serious,'' he said. ``There has to be confidence in
government. Social interests have to be vindicated and this can't
necessarily be done on a dollar-for-dollar basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz has been speaking out against those who have demonized
the 15 independent counsels appointed over the past 20 years and
labeled them as partisan loonies. Like Starr, Smaltz's team charges
that a major reason for the lengthy investigation and mounting cost
are delay tactics and endless appeals by the targets of the probes.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, if the independent counsels investigating Clinton
and a handful of his former cabinet officers were judged strictly
by return on investment, they might be out of business.
</P>
<P>
   With unlimited budgets and sometimes unfocused objectives,
special investigations into the executive branch of government have
cost taxpayers about $150 million since 1985, including $47 million
spent on the seven-year, Iran-Contra affair during the Reagan-Bush
era.
</P>
<P>
   The first independent counsel law was passed by Congress in 1978
in the wake of Watergate. Since President Clinton signed the
Independent Counsel Reauthorization Act four years ago this month,
the bill run up by the independent counsels is approaching $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ordinary prosecutors who investigate a particular known
crime, independent counsels start when there is information a crime
may have occurred and they have near unlimited latitude and funds
to fish into most anything.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 15 publicly identified independent counsels, six have
brought criminal prosecutions following their investigations. In
the Clinton era, these include David Barrett for ongoing charges
against former Urban Development Secretary Henry Cisneros, Starr
and Smaltz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
