<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BEST-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ACCEPTING FOR `CITIZEN KANE' ... 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 18:
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the American Film Institute's much publicized list
of the 100 best American movies of all time is simply a marketing
device for studios with a lot of old videos to sell. If so, it is a
pretty good one. It was hard to watch the three-hour CBS countdown
of the golden hundred Tuesday evening without making mental notes
of things to rent during the next rainy season. ``Grapes of Wrath''
seems to be aging very well.
</P>
<P>
   Most lists of the best of anything suffer from an overemphasis
on things that happened during the rankers' lifetimes. But the Film
Institute went way overboard, picking only four silent movies,
three of them starring Charlie Chaplin. The only world in which
``Dances With Wolves'' is more important than ``Intolerance'' is
the one that exists at Blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   A list chosen by a committee, whatever its agenda, is probably
never going to be as interesting as selections made by a single
person, where all the quirks of individuality can be given full
rein.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich's all-time favorite movie list,
which he shared with The Times, includes three John Wayne features
as well as ``Being There,'' the Peter Sellers classic about a man
who convinces the world he is a genius by repeating the blandest
possible truisms. After nearly four years of running the Republican
majority in the House, Gingrich seems unclear whether victory
belongs to the brave and the well armed, or simply to those who say
dumb things with conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker also nominated the entire ``Pink Panther'' series, a
choice that suggests an interest in productions that start strong
and gradually degenerate into pointless incoherence.
</P>
<P>
   There is going to be an orgy of list-making leading up to the
year 2000, on every topic from best literature to best snacks. Time
magazine has already weighed in on the most influential comic-strip
character of the century (Bart Simpson). The Washington Post Style
section named Genghis Khan the Man of the Millennium way back in
1995, and a survey of history professors more recently selected
Adolf Hitler as the ``most significant person of the century.''
Unlike the movies, history does not always favor the virtuous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0526 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
