<SLUG> BC-BKC-NAILON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAILON STAYING AT TCU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOEL ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU center Lee Nailon has withdrawn from
consideration for Wednesday's NBA draft and will return for his
senior season.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-9 Nailon, a third-team Associated Press All-American
and the Western Athletic Conference Pacific Division player of the
year, said he decided to return to TCU to improve his skills and
his stock for next year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great deal of basketball ahead of me,'' Nailon said
in a statement. ``I feel by coming back I can improve my game and
can improve my position in next year's NBA draft.''
</P>
<P>
   When he announced in April that he would enter the draft, Nailon
said he would return to TCU if he was not assured by NBA scouts
that he would be among the first 15 players drafted.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts had projected Nailon as a small forward. After several
poor performances at the Pre-Draft NBA Camp this month in Chicago,
Nailon was projected as a late first-round or early second-round
pick.
</P>
<P>
   NBA scouting director Marty Blake had recommended that Nailon
return for his final season of eligibility to improve his strength,
ball-handling skills and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a good, smart player, but he's not ready to go,'' Blake
said. ``At Chicago, he found out that he needed work on his ball
handling. If he goes back to school, it will help him emotionally,
physically and educationally.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU coach Billy Tubbs was pleased with Nailon's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think Lee made a wise decision by taking some
advice from the NBA people,'' Tubbs said. ``I think it's great for
TCU, the team and for our entire program.''
</P>
<P>
   Nailon's decision could cause a logjam for the Horned Frogs.
Tubbs signed nine players to scholarships for next season, in
addition to the six scholarship players currently on the team. NCAA
rules allow Division I men's basketball programs to have 13
athletes on scholarship. However, freshman signees Toshay Harvey, a
6-2 guard from Houston Sharpstown and Justin Lyman, a 6-7 forward
from Fort Bend Elkins, have not made qualifying scores on the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   After transferring from Butler County (Kan.) Community College,
Nailon led the Horned Frogs to a 27-6 season, including a 14-0
record in the WAC, a No. 13 ranking in the AP Top 25 and TCU's
first NCAA Tournament bid since 1987. Nailon finished last season
as the nation's third-leading scorer at 24.9 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to return to TCU and help this team to continue to
build upon the success we enjoyed last year, while continuing my
education,'' Nailon said. ``I have every desire to complete my
degree at TCU.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
