<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEN'S '98 LEGACY WILL BE A ROUGH RIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Of all the golf courses to hold a U.S. Open, few
have been as open to the offbeat occurrence as the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Long after Casey Martin's tire tracks fade from its fairways,
history will remember the 6,797-yard, par-70 layout as the first
Open venue to welcome a golf cart during a competitive round. That
will become Olympic's latest claim to fame when Martin joins 155
fellow competitors in today's opening round.
</P>
<P>
   But it is far from the club's only unique contribution to the
golf world during Open week. It is also the only place where Ben
Hogan, the most prolific winner in Open history, lost an 18-hole
playoff to determine the 1955 title. It was the site of Arnold
Palmer's implosion in 1966, when he blew a seven-stroke lead over
the final nine holes _ the greatest giveaway in Open history _ and
lost to Billy Casper.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday afternoon, MasterCard Colonial champ Tom Watson
predicts that Olympic will be remembered for something else: the
first over-par winning score at a U.S. Open since Jimmy Carter sat
in the Oval Office in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much over par it's going to be, but I think
this year, we are definitely going to see an over-par score win the
tournament,'' said Watson, who based his prediction on fast, dry
conditions during practice rounds and a gnarly, 5-inch blanket of
rough that several players have described as the most punitive they
have seen at an Open venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I say that,'' Watson said, ``is we're due for some
wind. And when it starts blowing, it's going to be difficult to
shoot par around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with pristine conditions, Tom Lehman said, players will
struggle to hit Olympic's tiny greens and sloping fairways. More
so, in Lehman's opinion, than at most Open venues. In his mind,
that helps explain why three underdogs _ Jack Fleck (1955), Casper
(1966) and Scott Simpson (1987) _ won the first three Opens held at
Olympic over more heralded runner-ups Hogan, Palmer and Watson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a little bit more chance involved here. I think that
is the one thing about the course that makes it difficult and a
little unpredictable,'' Lehman said. ``There are about four or five
holes out there where ... you can hit a really good shot and still
be in the rough if you draw the ball instead of hitting a slight
cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, that is a pretty fine line. But that's how fine a
line it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The course's 5-inch blend of bluegrass and poa annua rough makes
chipping from the tall grass a dice roll as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very interesting because playing out of there is
all luck,'' Tiger Woods said. ``This rough is different. It's
clumpy. You can have a ball were you see it on TV and it looks
playable, but there's a huge clump of grass behind the ball and the
guy can't get a club on it. Or you can have what looks like a bad
lie, but you can be behind the clump and it's no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman disagrees. He said he has a standing bet with a fellow
player that no one will be able to reach a par-4 hole in regulation
this week after driving the ball into the rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have dropped balls all over, and I can't hit more than a
sand wedge out,'' Lehman said. ``I just don't think it's possible
unless you get lucky. I mean, you'd be really, really, really lucky
to get the ball to the green from the rough.''
</P>
<P>
   With luck expected to play a major role in deciding the outcome,
Simpson said a larger-than-usual number of starters in the field
could wind up winning on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you would have 50 guys who could win this
tournament,'' Simpson said, listing one-event winners Jeff Maggert
of Houston and David Ogrin of San Antonio as likely contenders.
``People always crack me up when they say there are only five or 10
guys who can win. You've got to be kidding me.''
</P>
<P>
   This, after all, is the Olympic Club. When the PGA Tour brought
its season-ending event, the Tour Championship, to the course in
1993-94, the eventual winners were Jim Gallagher Jr. and Mark
McCumber. Neither player is currently listed in the top 100 of the
world golf rankings or the PGA Tour season money list.
</P>
<P>
   How tolerant is Olympic of the underdog? Martin, a Nike Tour
participant, clipped Woods, the world's top-ranked player, for $30
in a skins competition during their Tuesday practice round.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is assured the notoriety of becoming the first Open
competitor to use a golf cart, Martin said he expects more from his
initial appearance in a PGA Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be really disappointed if I didn't make the cut
here,'' Martin said. ``I think this course sets up well for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it doesn't, Martin will at least leave some historic
tire tracks. And the Olympic Club will make another unique
contribution to Open annals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
