<HEADER>
A4386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FERRARI-PROFILE-AR     06-17 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FERRARI-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITOR IN TOUCH WITH HER INNER TEEN-AGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(af) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It would be so easy to just give in and put Hanson on
the cover. All those feverish letters piling up in her office, a
mini-riot on notebook paper, and what they all want is just one
simple thing, so why not get it over with and just put Hanson on
the cover?
</P>
<P>
   Because it would be wrong, Christina Ferrari says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I just took those letters at face value, I would have
Hanson on my cover,'' said Ms. Ferrari, managing editor of the
highly successful Teen People, Time Inc.'s new young person's guide
to the world of celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But editorially, right now, that isn't where we want to go.
It's a little young for us. Which is not to say I would never put
Hanson on the cover. But right now, we're looking at celebrities
with a slightly older appeal. So it's really, you know, it's not
that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, it seems, is terribly simple in the pitiless arena of
teen magazines, where nuances of cover lines are as carefully
calibrated as precision weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   The Hanson problem is typical: because most of the pop group's
fans are at the younger edge of the spectrum, between 11 and 14,
the group's presence on a magazine cover might send a disastrously
wrong signal to the more desirable readers at the upper end, from
16 to 18, which is Teen People's playground.
</P>
<P>
   As parents and advertising agencies know, the difference in
habits and spending power of those groups is incalculable, and Teen
People is determined not to stumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fine line we walk with teen-agers,'' she said, sighing
philosophically. ``You can't be too young or too old.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Ms. Ferrari and her team have traversed that line quite
proficiently. Teen People began in February, and after just five
issues, Time Inc. announced last week that it was raising the
magazine's rate base _ the circulation figure that it guarantees
advertisers _ to 800,000 copies from 500,000. Several issues have
sold more than one million copies; not close to Seventeen, the
market leader at 2.6 million, but quite impressive for a start-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's had very good growth for a new publication,'' said Bob
Huff, director of planning operations for DDB Needham, the
advertising agency, which has placed several clients in the
magazine. ``But then again, they come from a good family.''
</P>
<P>
   The parent, of course, is the grown-up People Weekly, the
ultimate journal of celebrity, which plenty of teen-agers already
borrowed from their parents to learn about their favorite actors
and rock stars.
</P>
<P>
   Teen People, which borrows heavily from the format and bureau
system of the adult version, is like a training manual for
adolescents not quite ready for a lifetime fascination with
entertainment but eager to take that first step.
</P>
<P>
   Like its parent, it also has a mixture of articles about
subjects like bulimia, interracial dating and fraternity hazing
among the movie stars and the hero profiles. (It avoids the
boy-crazy articles of its competitors, but has just as many fashion
and beauty tips.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The People brand is so familiar and trusted and liked by so
many people,'' Ms. Ferrari said. ``People write in and say, `I
always read my parents' copy of People, and now I have my own and
that's so great, because it focuses just on the people I'm
interested in.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And fortunately for Teen People, Time Inc. found in Ms. Ferrari,
33, who is just as interested in teen-age culture _ the television
shows, the music, the pressures of burgeoning sexuality and style _
as the readers are. Until last year, she was editor in chief of YM,
a monthly for teen-age girls, and has also worked at McCalls,
Redbook and Self.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably would watch those TV shows even if I didn't have
to,'' she said this week in her office in the Time-Life building.
``MTV is like background music for my life. In fact, I joke with my
husband about what I'm going to do when I no longer edit a magazine
for teens, because I'm going to need a new excuse for watching all
of this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferrari, a native of Los Altos, Calif., who graduated from
the University of California at Berkeley, said she was a ``serious
and intense'' teen-ager who is now having the fun that she should
have had more of back then.
</P>
<P>
   She said she admires the enthusiasm and lack of cynicism in
today's generation of teen-agers, although she never tries to dress
or talk like one, and deliberately keeps slang out of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teen-agers want to use slang with each other but they don't
want to see it in their magazine,'' she said. ``They know it's a
bunch of editors in New York trying to talk like teen-agers. I
mean, how fake is that?''
</P>
<P>
   She and her postadolescent staff rely on a cadre of teen-age
scouts and an immensely popular site on America Online to keep them
current, although they frequently have to guess which movies and
stars are going to be popular three months ahead, because of
production deadlines. Most of their choices have been fairly safe,
although the cover of Puff Daddy, the rap star, was unusual in an
industry that rarely showcases black males.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it didn't require genius to put Leonardo DiCaprio on
the cover of the May issue, which sold out in 10 days and went back
for an additional printing of 400,000 copies. But Ms. Ferrari knows
she can't rely forever on a one-person windfall for the teen-age
magazine industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leonardo was huge and wonderful for us, as he was for a lot of
other magazines,'' she said. ``Everybody's getting a piece of him.
But we can't go back to the Leonardo well too many times.''
Especially once the 16-year-olds move on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
