<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBS-PARSLEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRY THESE SAGE USES FOR PARSELY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flat-leaf parsley is a biennial, growing 12 inches or taller. It
is more flavorful than the curly-leaf variety.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions: Grow from seed planted in fall or early
spring; it prefers cool weather. Feed occasionally with fish
emulsion or manure, and mulch with compost, especially in winter
and summer.
</P>
<P>
   Companion plants: Tomatoes, roses.
</P>
<P>
   Food pairings: Meat, poultry, sauces, rice, pasta, dips and
salad dressings made with cream cheese or mayonnaise; blends well
with other spices.
</P>
<P>
   Caveats: Treat parsley worms with ``bacillus thuringiensis,''
spider mites and aphids with insecticidal soap.
</P>
<P>
   ARTICHOKE AND BASIL RAGOUT
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry white wine, such as a white Rhone, riesling or chenin
blanc
</P>
<P>
   1 cup loosely packed fresh flat-leaf parsley, destemmed
</P>
<P>
   8 plump, fresh garlic cloves, peeled and halved
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 firm, ripe tomatoes, cored, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 artichokes OR 8 baby artichokes OR two 9-ounce packages frozen
artichoke hearts, thawed, sliced, see Note
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons fresh basil leaves, destemmed and julienned
</P>
<P>
   In a 3-quart saucepan, bring wine to a boil over high heat. Boil
vigorously until all the alcohol has burned off and there is no
alcohol aroma, about 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With a large chef's knife, finely chop parsley, garlic and salt.
Transfer to a heavy-duty saucepan. Add tomatoes, oil and wine.
Thoroughly drain artichoke slices and add to saucepan. Cover and
bring just to a simmer over moderate heat. Turn heat to low, cover
and simmer very gently for 30 to 45 minutes for fresh artichokes or
10 to 15 minutes for thawed, frozen artichokes, until they offer no
resistance when pierced with a knife. The ragout should not be dry
but should be bathed in a fragrant sauce. Stir in basil. Taste for
seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   To serve as a first course or vegetable side dish, transfer to
warmed shallow soup bowls, spooning sauce over artichokes. Serve
with crusty bread for sopping.
</P>
<P>
   To serve with pasta, toss artichokes with 8 ounces cooked fresh
linguine, using all the liquid as the sauce. The pasta does not
require cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To prepare artichokes, halve a lemon and squeeze juice
into a large bowl of cold water. Add lemon halves to water. With
your hands, break off artichoke stem from base. Bend back tough
outer green leaves, one at a time, and snap them off at base.
Continue snapping off leaves until only central cone of yellow
leaves with pale green tips remain. Lightly trim top cone of leaves
to just below green tips. Trim any dark green areas from base.
Slice artichokes lengthwise, making it easier to remove the choke.
Halve the artichoke lengthwise. With a small spoon or melon baller,
scrape out hairy choke from each half and discard. Cut each
artichoke half into eight even slices. Return each slice to lemon
water. Repeat for remaining artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 209 calories, 19 grams fat, 7
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0 milligrams cholesterol, 37
milligrams sodium, 80 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Patricia Wells at Home in Provence/ by Patricia Wells
(Scribner, $40)
</P>
<P>
   WHITE BEAN AND HAM SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8
</P>
<P>
   1 pound Great Northern OR other dried white beans
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 cups garlic-mustard dressing (see below)
</P>
<P>
   1 medium purple onion, peeled and sliced paper-thin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 pound cooked ham, trimmed and cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup best-quality imported black olives (Kalamata or Alfonso),
for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Rinse and sort through beans, discarding any pebbles, and soak
overnight in water that covers them by at least 3 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Drain beans and transfer to a kettle. Add cold water to cover
beans by at least 1 inch. Set over moderate heat. Bring to a boil,
skimming any scum that may form. Cook until tender, about 40
minutes, salting to taste after 30 minutes. Cooking times will
vary; do not overcook.
</P>
<P>
   Drain beans, transfer immediately to a mixing bowl and pour 1
cup of garlic-mustard dressing over still-hot beans.
</P>
<P>
   Add onion, parsley and ham, season to taste with salt and
pepper, and toss again. Cover and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, bring salad to room temperature. Toss again, correct
seasoning (adding more dressing if you like) and garnish with
olives.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 477 calories, 27 grams fat, 34
grams carbohydrates, 25 grams protein, 42 milligrams cholesterol,
1,091 milligrams sodium, 52 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   GARLIC-MUSTARD DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3 cups
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup prepared Dijon-style mustard
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cups best-quality imported olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Combine egg, mustard and vinegar in the bowl of a food processor
fitted with a steel blade. Season to taste with salt and pepper,
and process for 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   With motor still running, drop garlic cloves through feed tube.
Then begin dribbling in olive oil in a slow, steady stream.
</P>
<P>
   When all oil is incorporated, shut off motor, taste and correct
seasoning. Dressing should be very garlicky.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a storage container and refrigerate until ready to
use.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Raw eggs should not be consumed by the elderly, young
children or anyone with a compromised immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 84 calories, 9 grams fat,
trace carbohydrates, trace protein, 4 milligrams cholesterol, 24
milligrams sodium, 100 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Silver Palate Cookbook/ by Julee Rosso and Sheila Lukins
(Workman, $13.95)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
