<HEADER>
A4406 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALOHA-SHIRT-AZR &LR;      06-17 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALOHA-SHIRT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN CATCHING WAVE OF CASUAL ISLAND LOOK: ALOHA SHIRTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE M. SPITZA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Real men wear floral _ and look darned good doing so.
</P>
<P>
   They have for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis was king, and he wore an Aloha shirt in the 1963 movie
``Blue Hawaii.'' Frank Sinatra sported one in ``From Here to
Eternity,'' set in 1941. During their terms in office, Presidents
Truman and Eisenhower were known for their off-time tropical
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people today are drawn to Aloha shirts because they
suggest another time,'' said Janet Giese, buyer for the Hawaiian
Shop in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young guys like them. Older guys like them. Business guys like
them. They reflect an attitude. The guys who wear them seem pretty
sure of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And macho _ you bet. Vibrant island prints can be very manly.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Jungle Bird'' Hawaiian shirt that hunk actor Tom Selleck
made popular in the television series ``Magnum P.I.'' is an icon of
Americana. It hangs in the Smithsonian Institution, for heaven's
sake.
</P>
<P>
   (If more timely examples are necessary, catch the upcoming
floral-shirted performance of actor Nicolas Cage. He plays a buff
police detective in the flick ``Snake Eyes,'' scheduled for release
later this summer.)
</P>
<P>
   Whether you love 'em or hate 'em, flashy floral Aloha shirts _
and the more contemporary ``motif'' sports shirts _ are back in
fashion for the male of the species this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The look is not isolated to one particular customer,'' said
John Coumbe, owner of John's &AMP; Co., a high-end Phoenix men's shop.
``Ralph Lauren's doing it. Armani's doing it. Everybody's got a
piece of it in their summer line. It's considered to be in good
taste.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, designs with obnoxious touristy prints _ such as those
grounded in Pepto-Bismol pink and sewn of polyester _ are not the
prevailing trend. The eclectic Aloha garb presented in the new
summer movie ``Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas'' is a good example
of what not to wear. (That terry-cloth Aloha shirt worn by actor
Johnny Depp as journalist Raoul Duke is just plain ol' tacky.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys love those wild and flashy prints, and they wear
them all the time,'' Giese said. ``They've been wearing those for
years. But there's also this trend toward classy, tasteful shirts
that have some panache to them _ some pizazz.
</P>
<P>
   It's true. This summer's crop of casual island-inspired fashion
shirts tend toward ``artful sophistication'' and ``retro chic.''
Rayon, Egyptian cotton and textured silk are the fabrics of choice.
Some of the season's best designs are reproductions of patterns
dating to the 1940s _ when Hawaiian shirts were considered
sophisticated sportswear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like neckwear right now,'' Coumbe said. ``There's
no set direction (for Aloha shirts). It's something that just
appeals to you.''
</P>
<P>
   What appeals to today's fashionable gentlemen, Coumbe said, are
patterns that are not too wild. He described the look as ``easy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so flashy. It's low-key,'' he said. ``It could be
orange _ as long as the pattern is simple and not overpowering.''
</P>
<P>
   If worn appropriately, a vibrant island-scene shirt exudes an
aura of confidence. A hibiscus print hanging from broad shoulders
reflects a relaxed approach to life. For that matter, a palm tree
and pineapple print conveys an overall casual outlook.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: These shirts are fun to wear. They are pleasing
to the eye. And they can be great conversation pieces at a poolside
party. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2224EDT &QL; 
