<SLUG> BC-JELLO-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE JELL-O IS ALWAYS RED': SONGS SUIT LETTERS TO A T 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review.)  
(lb) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like a package of Necco wafers, the new revue ``The
Jell-O Is Always Red'' is generous but unexciting.
</P>
<P>
   This grab bag of some 30 lighthearted songs and sketches
rummages its way through the trunk of Clark Gesner, whose credits
include the book, music and lyrics of the popular ``You're a Good
Man, Charlie Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Charles Schulz's comic strip, the three-person ``Jell-O''
show is amiable and eager to amuse. But it is more cute than
captivating, and by its end, some of what was initially enjoyable
has been repeated to the point of worn-out welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Take the tune ``You're the One I'm Four.'' It sounds as if it's
a love ditty, but the joke is that Gesner is singing it to large
onstage numerals. The idea is clever the first time, but when it
turns up again and again, as in ``By the Sea,'' with the letters C
and U and lines like ``Oh, how I'd love to be beside U,'' the fizz
is out of the champagne, and ``Sesame Street'' for grown-ups is
definitely in the air.
</P>
<P>
   In his songs and sketches, directed by James Morgan, Gesner is
joined by Neal Young and Celia Gentry, who displays sufficient
mischief in a variety of guises and accents to suggest that she
might be a lot more fun in different surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   The show's material is not without wit. The title tune, about
the sameness of diner food, packs keen observation. In ``Everything
I Buy Was Made in China,'' Gesner sings ruefully about the
difficulty of finding American-made goods when everything is
imported. And the sketch that introduces Gesner as a huge,
blue-swaddled baby who thinks in Shakespearean language comes as a
welcome relief from lyrics whose rhymes tend to be of the ``noon''
and ``spoon'' variety.
</P>
<P>
   But some routines are frail, talky or predictable, like one
about a cost cutter who wants to charge for public use of the
letter R and another about an executive who is aped by everyone
after he accidentally leaves some peanut butter on his chin.
</P>
<P>
   A little of this ``Jell-O'' goes a long way.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE JELL-O IS ALWAYS RED'
</P>
<P>
   The cabaret songs of Clark Gesner; musical director, Winston
Clark; directed by James Morgan; costumes by John Carver Sullivan;
lighting by Brian Haynsworth; production stage manager, Alan
Bluestone; assistant music director, Norma Curley. Presented by the
York Theater Company, James Morgan, artistic director; Joseph V. De
Michele, managing director. At the Theater at St. Peter's Church,
Lexington Avenue and 54th Street, New York.
</P>
<P>
   With: Celia Gentry, Clark Gesner and Neal Young.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
