<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0552 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4432 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-u.s.open-HNS &LR;      06-17 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-u.s. </SLUG>
 open-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Veterans fully aware that danger abounds
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ They are drawn like so many unsuspecting flies into
the spider's web, brought by a combination of their own confidence
and the come-hither look of the green lady.
</P>
<P>
   That is the danger of the U.S. Open, played on the most
beautifully trimmed courses with the finest of pedigrees. Except
that somewhere out there amid the perfectly mowed grass and the
stately trees and the shimmering water of the blue ponds is a
perilous, bottomless pit, waiting to swallow them up.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the great championships in other sports, the U.S. Open is
not a battle between a pair of great opponents. It has never really
been Nicklaus vs. Palmer or Hogan vs. Snead or Ernie Els vs. Colin
Montgomerie and Loren Roberts in a three-way playoff.
</P>
<P>
   A golf tournament, especially this golf tournament, usually
comes down to a duel with nature. It's the farmer battling the
drought. It's the old man and the sea. It's the scrappy pioneers
trying to make their way across the unforgiving prairies.
</P>
<P>
   If you take your average professional golfer out to the first
tee at the U.S. Open, his first reaction is not likely to be:
``Yikes! I've got to play against Tiger Woods or Justin Leonard.''
</P>
<P>
   What he's probably going to say is something along the lines of:
``Omigod! There's a dogleg to the right, and I have never been able
to fade the ball with consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   What scares these guys during Open week is never the other guys
in their threesome with their hot 3-woods or sizzling putters. It's
that water hazard over here and the bunker over there and the green
that slopes to the back and carries approach shots into the trouble
and the breeze that blows in off the nearby Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Regular folks look at a golf course and see the birds and the
trees and the water, a haven of natural serenity. The golfer looks
at the same piece of land and sees out of bounds on the left,
double bogeys and missed par putts, his own equivalent of metal
crunching from a multiple car wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the U.S. Open can be a pleasant stroll. Like walking
through the streets of the former Yugoslavia. Yes, it can be a
cruise. On a sinking ship with no lifeboats.
</P>
<P>
   Yet year after year, some of them come to the Open fully
convinced they are ready to tame the beast. It is the young ones,
mostly. The ones who look at the yardage cards and sniff at the
mere 6,797 yards offered up by the Olympic Club and wonder why so
many are cringing in fear.
</P>
<P>
   Woods came in from a practice round and declared that if the
winds stayed calm, it would likely take a score of 6 under par,
maybe lower, to win the Open. Els, the defending champion with the
the aching back, offered that it could be in the 4- to 5-under
range. See Leonard with the bounce in his step and Lee Westwood
with the confident smile. Even cart-riding Casey Martin is ready to
hit the accelerator and go.
</P>
<P>
   The kids are practically salivating over the prospect of taking
on a course that is significantly shorter than Congressional
Country Club, site of last year's Open, which measures 7,213 yards.
In one breath, they say all the right things about course
management and shot-making. Then in the next breath, they are
almost hyperventilating at getting a shot at the par-4, 288-yard
No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can hit with a driver on this course,'' Woods said. ``You
really can if you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just it about the Open. What you want to do and what you
think you are capable of doing are often in direct contrast to what
these devilish Open courses will allow. A place like the Olympic
Club opens its gates and asks the guests in for a visit and then
treats them to a weekend of sheer torture.
</P>
<P>
   You can ask any of the veterans, the golfers who have lines on
their faces in part from the sun but mostly from frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson, 48, is already on the record as saying that the
winner will finish over par, which would be the first time that has
happened since 1978 at Cherry Hills in Denver when Andy North shot
1-over for the championship. He points to the Olympic Club's demand
for accuracy and a rough that is tougher to get out of than a Ken
Starr investigation. ``Plus, we're due for some wind, and that's
going to make the greens very hard,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, the rough is longer than it was in 1987,'' said
Scott Simpson, who won the title that year, the last time it was
held at the Olympic Club. ``It's real long, and it's real tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson won that year by beating out Watson with four rounds
that were brilliantly consistent, if not consistently brilliant. He
hit the ball down the middle of the fairways, chipped close and
made a lot of pars and won at 3-under.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what you're supposed to do in any battle with Mother
Nature or the Open, just mind your manners and hope you get out
alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
