<HEADER>
A4439 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LADN     06-17 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS, KARL HAVE HELD `INFORMAL' TALKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Clippers have spoken twice with
George Karl but still appear in the early stages of talks with the
former Seattle SuperSonics coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been some informal bantering back and forth,''
said Bret Adams, who is Karl's agent. ``They have not spoken to me
directly, and I would handle the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl seems to be the Clippers' only serious candidate at the
moment because the Sonics hired Paul Westphal as their coach on
Wednesday. Westphal had talked to the Clippers and was considered
their No.2 choice behind Karl.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Clippers land Karl depends on several factors,
including the status of Chicago Bulls coach Phil Jackson. Karl
would immediately become a candidate for the Bulls job if, as
expected, Jackson is not brought back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really knows for sure what's going to happen in
Chicago,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is how much influence Karl will have with the
Clippers regarding personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I would want to have a lot of control,'' Karl told
the Seattle Times.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not it's with the Clippers, Karl seems ready to get
back into coaching by next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more excited to coach now than in the last five years.
There will be a new team I can get to put together. I'll have a
chance to do some teaching with new talent,'' Karl said.
``Hopefully, it will be a good challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Clippers want to pay Karl big money is another
issue. Karl said he is willing to take less to coach a winning
team; he is believed to be able to command at least $5 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all about money for him,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   There also remains the possibility that Karl would take a year
off from coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to coach next year, but he's not in a big hurry,''
Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Clippers fail to hire Karl, top remaining candidates
include Lakers assistant coach Kurt Rambis and former San Antonio
Spurs coach Bob Hill. Rambis spoke to the Clippers in Chicago last
week during a predraft camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
