<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIFTED-STUDENTS-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAMS FOR GIFTED FAVOR WHITES, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Black and Hispanic parents continue to be less likely
than white parents to be offered classroom tours and meetings with
educators about programs for gifted children, according to a report
released Wednesday by ACORN, an advocacy group based in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   For the survey, modeled after housing discrimination tests,
volunteers posed as parents and visited 26 schools during the last
two months. The report says that little has changed since a similar
survey was conducted two years ago. In that report, released in
April 1996, the group accused the school system of denying black
and Hispanic parents equal access to classes for the gifted by
failing to provide information.
</P>
<P>
   The group filed a complaint with the civil-rights arm of the
U.S. Department of Education. That and other complaints have
prompted a federal civil-rights investigation into the city's
programs for the gifted.
</P>
<P>
   Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew cited his own concerns last year
about the possible exclusion of minority and immigrant children. He
prohibited admission fees and testing fees, which at least two of
the city's 32 community school districts were charging.
</P>
<P>
   He also ordered school-district officials to post information
about their programs in each school and asked district
superintendents to explain in writing what kinds of admission
criteria they used and why they used them.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, in a brief statement, Crew said the latest ACORN
study ``glosses over the substantial efforts'' he has undertaken in
recent years. ``Since becoming chancellor, I have continually
called for greater publicizing of these programs,'' the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   Crew's spokesman, J.D. LaRock, said Wednesday that most
districts have moved away from relying solely on IQ tests and are
looking at examples of students' work and at teacher referrals.
Crew also pointed to the Math/Science Institute, a coaching program
established last year to prepare more black and Hispanic students
for the city's most competitive high schools.
</P>
<P>
   In an agreement with the civil-rights office of the Department
of Education, the school board has promised to post information
about programs for the gifted at every school and district office.
</P>
<P>
   The ACORN report criticized the board for having failed to post
the information. But city and federal education officials
maintained Wednesday that the signs are not required to be posted
until this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for ACORN, formally known as the Association of
Community Organizations for Reform Now, said Wednesday that they
planned to file another complaint with the federal agency.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In their survey, the testers were instructed to try to talk to
teachers and principals about classes for the gifted at each school
and to request class tours.
</P>
<P>
   Only 12 percent of the African-American and Hispanic testers
were able to talk with a teacher or another educator familiar with
the school's gifted programs, compared with 45 percent of the
non-Hispanic white testers, the report said. About 13 percent of
the black and Hispanic testers were allowed to look in on a class,
compared with 40 percent of the whites.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that middle schools in which most of the
students were black and Hispanic failed to provide advanced math
and science classes required for entrance to the city's competitive
high schools. Moreover, the report said that in some federally
financed programs that were intended to integrate schools with
large minority concentrations, white students were overrepresented
in the classes for the gifted.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, at Intermediate School 54 on the Upper West Side,
the report said, white students made up only 13 percent of the
student body but 40 percent of the gifted students, while black and
Hispanic children, more than 80 percent of the student body, made
up roughly 55 percent of the gifted students.
</P>
</TEXT>
