u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NOMINATE-BOS &LR;      06-17 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NOMINATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON NAMES RICHARDSON, HOLBROOKE TO POSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH   AND DAVID MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ President Clinton will name Bill Richardson,
the chief US envoy to the United Nations, as head of the US
Department of Energy today, according to administration officials.
He will be replaced by Richard Holbrooke, the brash diplomatic
trouble-shooter who gained prominence by negotiating an end to the
war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will announce the nominations Thursday at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement signals the departure of one of the
administration's most dashing foreign policy figures and the
arrival of a tough new personality in American foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, long seen as a potential candidate for secretary of
state, will finally get an opportunity to put his imprint on US
foreign policy at the dawn of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear whether Richardson's departure from the UN
was a reward or punishment for his performance. The former New
Mexico Democrat, who raced back to Washington from Rome where he
was addressing a war crimes conference, has openly voiced his
desire to pursue higher office in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Richardson have suggested that he sought the
top energy post to strengthen his domestic political base after
Federico Pena announced he was stepping down in July to spend more
time with his family. In an interview with the Globe last year,
Richardson said he was interested in running for senator or
governor in New Mexico. Some observers have named him as a
potential running mate for Al Gore in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Observers say that Clinton gave him the job as a reward for
distinguishing himself in a series of diplomatic missions from the
Congo to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who served on the House Energy and Commerce
Committee while in Congress, was especially interested in
deregulating the oil and gas industries and promoting alternative
sources of energy.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, 50, resigned his House seat in February 1997 and,
well liked in Congress, won unanimous Senate confirmation to the
ambassadorship.
</P>
<P>
   One official said that Richardson found the United Nations a
frustrating place to work at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved the high diplomacy _ making things happen _ but he
was less enamored of the low diplomacy, which is dealing with the
bureaucracy,'' the official said. ``And there is a lot of
bureacracy at the UN.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But Richardson has also faced some serious foreign policy
setbacks since coming to the United Nations in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When he took on the top job at the UN, Richardson vowed to
persuade Congress to pay more than $1 billion in back dues to the
United Nations. And he pledged to improve the relationship between
US and the United Nations. More than a year later, the US still
owes the money. And Congress remains as hostile to the
international organization as ever.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Holbrooke, 57, a career diplomat who got his start in Vietnam
in the 1960s, has a reputation as a tough negotiator who gets
things done and doesn't mind bragging about his accomplishments.
But President Clinton passed him over in favor of Madeleine K.
Albright for the secretary of state position.
</P>
<P>
   Friends joke that Holbrooke begins every sentence with the word
`I.' In telling about his efforts to bring peace to Bosnia, he has
criticized his superiors, including President Clinton, for acting
too slowly.
</P>
<P>
   But one official who has worked closely with him said the
president does not take the criticism to heart. ``No one doubts
Dick's negotiating ability or his intellect or charisma,'' the
official said last night. ``The president is his biggest fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke shares with Albright a firm belief in an activist
America that leads allies in peacekeeping. In interviews this month
to promote his book about Bosnia, ``To End a War,'' he has called
for more leadership from Washington in preventing bloodshed in the
Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The book, which has been praised by many reviewers, urges
Americans to show more decisive leadership in preventing conflicts
around the world. ``The world's richest nation, one that presumes
to great moral authority, cannot simply make worthy appeals to
conscience and call on others to carry the burden,'' Holbrooke
writes. ``The world will look to Washington for more than rhetoric
the next time we face a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   He brokered the Balkan peace accord that ended the Bosnian
conflict in 1995, which got him nominated for the Nobel Peace
Prize. More recently Holbrooke's efforts to defuse tensions between
Greece and Turkey over the disputed island of Cyprus, and his
efforts to mediate an end to Serbia's bloody crackdown on ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, &UR;  &LR; have gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   As a congressman, Richardson negotiated with hostile governments
in Cuba, Iraq, North Korea and Sudan to help secure the release of
11 hostages.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an open secret at the State Department that
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Richardson often do not
get along. While Richardson's fans have delighted in his
world-trotting problem-solving for years, officials say Albright
has disagreed with him several times.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson has not been dynamic enough in Albright's views,
according to officials who know them both. Albright has a special
interest in the job because she was widely praised for her tough
talk and behind-the-scenes negotiating when she served as the UN
ambassador during Clinton's first term.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who clearly enjoys publicity, has had to clear his
appearances on Sunday morning television talk shows with Albright's
advisers. Often, officials said, the advisers have ordered
Richardson to stay off the shows in order not to obscure Albright's
message.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's appointment to the top energy post has been in the
works for several weeks. But President Clinton had trouble finding
a suitable replacement to fill the UN post.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential candidates included former Senator George
Mitchell, who negotiated an historic peace settlement in northern
Ireland, and Senator Lee Hamilton, a long-time Congressional
defender of the United Nations. Mitchell, according to diplomats,
was not interested in the job.
</P>
<P>
   And an administration official said it was unclear when the two
diplomats would begin their new jobs. Both men will require Senate
approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
