<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARVIS MOVES IN AT ST. JOHN'S 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Jarvis arrived at St. John's Wednesday for real,
six days after the news conference introducing him as the Red
Storm's new head coach. He is still living out of a suitcase and
calling a hotel home. But at least at the school, he has an office,
a campus that he is now a part of, a home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After eight seasons at George Washington University, it took six
days to cut the cord there, to say good-bye to players and friends.
When he walked into his new office, there were letters of
congratulations from coaches he had walked sidelines opposite 20
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The move was an emotional one for Jarvis, whose name has been
raised in almost every high-profile coaching search in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made it kind of interesting at the end of each year,'' said
Jack Kvancz, George Washington's athletic director. ``But the
reality of it was, I knew Mike wasn't going to leave us unless it
was a job he really wanted. He may have messed around with other
jobs, but he told me point-blank, it is not going to happen, that
he was just messing around. Other than make things uncomfortable,
it didn't hurt anything. We didn't lose recruits. But now this is a
job he really wanted.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That made St. John's different from his flings with other
schools. He turned down an offer from Boston College last year and
had his name involved in coaching searches at Virginia and Michigan
this year.
</P>
<P>
   When St. John's began its search, Jarvis called, but not to
lobby for himself. He put in a word for Drexel's Bill Herrion. But
when St. John's invited him into the mix, Jarvis was intoxicated by
the thought of entering the New York market with a team steeped in
tradition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When he got the job, it did not make the parting at George
Washington easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had doubts,'' Jarvis said. ``I believe anybody contemplating
a move as serious as this would feel that way. The biggest fear I
had the last couple of years was getting to a point where I was so
comfortable and so content that I wouldn't think about moving.''
</P>
<P>
   First on the agenda is hiring a staff. His son, Mike Jarvis II,
will follow him from George Washington. And his associate head
coach, Kevin Clark, will probably come, too, now that the Colonials
seem poised to name Tom Penders as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   When Jarvis took over at Boston University and George
Washington, each had a losing record; the St. John's cupboard is
stocked. Before he was dismissed, Fran Fraschilla had led the Red
Storm to its first NCAA tournament berth since 1993. A seven-year
contract worth more than $5 million puts Jarvis in the spotlight he
wanted, but also under the pressure of high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   John Calipari, who left the University of Massachusetts of the
Atlantic 10 Conference for the Nets of the National Basketball
Association, identifies with his former rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was ready for it to come in here,'' Calipari said
of the pressure. ``Well, I wasn't. If Mike wants to know what you
don't do, he can call me because I can tell him. I did it all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
