<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-SUSPENSION-NYT </SLUG>
  
 YANKEE PITCHER STANTON APPEALS SUSPENSION FOR HITTING BATTER  (ja) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Mike Stanton was in his hotel room Wednesday
afternoon when Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, called
to tell the pitcher that the American League had suspended him for
five games, for hitting Baltimore's Eric Davis with a pitch Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're kidding me,'' Stanton replied, and within an hour, he
appealed the ruling. Stanton, who was also fined $1,000, is adamant
that he did not hit Davis on purpose, as Dr. Gene Budig, the league
president, has determined, based on the report filed by the plate
umpire John Hirschbeck.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton will be able to play until his appeal is heard by Budig,
perhaps next Monday, or until he elects to drop the appeal. As of
Wednesday, Stanton intends to fight the ruling vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely unjustified,'' he said. ``I didn't expect any
suspension. I know what was going through my mind, and it
definitely wasn't to hit Eric Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Budig directly tied Stanton's actions to the
perceived intentional throwing incident and ensuing fight between
the Yankees and Orioles on May 19 at Yankee Stadium. That night,
Baltimore's Armando Benitez hit Tino Martinez with a fastball
immediately after allowing a home run to Bernie Williams, sparking
the lengthy brawl.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Stanton hit Davis with a fastball immediately after
allowing a home run to Rafael Palmeiro, although in this instance
no players left the benches or bullpens, and no fighting resulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was appalled by the dangerous act by Mike Stanton,
especially in view of the recent and high profile brawl involving
the Yankees and Orioles,'' Budig said in his statement.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters directly, Budig later added that his
suspension of Stanton reflected the information in the written
report filed by the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, said he respects both
Hirschbeck and Budig, but feels they did not have a true
understanding of what occurred. ``You have to have a feel for the
game,'' Torre said, ``to make an evaluation people are going to
live with.''
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the Yankee owner, went one step further.
``I'm not sure what Dr. Budig's experience is, but I'm not sure
when the last time he wore a jockstrap was,'' Steinbrenner said of
the league president, who came to his baseball post from the
academic world. ``But Dr. Budig did what he felt was right. Budig
has been all over the lot on this thing. Sometimes he comes down
hard, the next time he doesn't come down hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner paused and added, with sarcasm: ``Dr. Budig says he
was `appalled' _ that's kind of funny. He must've been a very great
chancellor in Kansas. He must be a very good educator.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Miller, the Orioles' manager, had been lobbying for an
eight-game suspension, the same given to Benitez. But after reading
Budig's explanation for giving Stanton five games _ Benitez had
provoked the Yankees after hitting Martinez, but Stanton did no
provoking _ Miller accepted the decision without argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say I'm disappointed,'' Miller said, ``but I
understand his reasoning.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said of the penalty to Stanton: ``I'm not the judge, man.
I don't make the rules, I just abide by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Budig's action is severe, in comparison with precedents;
pitchers have been ejected for intentionally throwing at batters in
the past and not been suspended at all.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez was ejected for hitting Martinez in June 1995, when
Martinez played for Seattle, and Benitez was not suspended.
</P>
<P>
   In reacting to the Yankees' fight with Baltimore last month, and
in subsequent action, Budig is clearly trying to establish a new
standard of decorum.
</P>
<P>
   But Stanton, the Yankees and the players association are
maintaining the pitcher is being punished unjustly. Stanton, the
Yankees say, would never target Davis, a well-liked and respected
opponent, and a close friend of the Yankees' Darryl Strawberry. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
