<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0559 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4445 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-CONTROL-FAILURE-B     06-17 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-CONTROL-FAILURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR TRAFFIC RADAR FAILING ALMOST DAILY, CONTROLLERS GROUP SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Air Traffic contollers directing planes flying at high altitudes
over New England and upstate New York have had their radar screens
go blank or freeze on almost a daily basis and they say there are
not enough technicians to keep the system running.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the malfunctions is a computer system installed in
1972 that is failing with increasing frequency. Meanwhile, the
number of technicians certified to repair it have dropped to
dangerously low levels.
</P>
<P>
   While the Federal Aviation Administration acknowledged problems
with the computer system in the Boston Center and at other
facilities around the country, a spokesman said the air traffic
system was safe, and that the agency has no records of failures on
a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   Controllers and the technicians who maintain the equipment,
however, say the system is being stretched to the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is falling apart,'' said William Johannes,
president of the local chapter of the National Air Traffic
Controllers Association, representing controllers at the Boston
Center in Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent example of the erosion of the air traffic system
came on Tuesday, when a controller in New York momentarily lost
track of Air Force Two's speed and altitude as the plane carrying
Vice President Gore approached Newark International Airport. The
DC-9 was 12 minutes from landing late Tuesday afternoon when
crucial data _ the plane's call sign, altitude reading, ground
speed and angle of descent _ disappeared from the controller's
computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   Controllers rely on the computers and radar in their effort to
maintain a safe distance between aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agency has now placed the national airspace system in
jeopardy by allowing staffing in the radar unit to fall well below
recognized norms,'' said Ed Dressell, the Boston Center local
president of the Professional Airways System Specialists, the union
representing the technicians.
</P>
<P>
   FAA spokesman Jim Peters said that safety has not been
compromised by the computer failures. ``Like any piece of
equipment, you will experience problems on an intermitant basis,''
he said, adding that a back-up system has performed whenever the
computer failed.
</P>
<P>
   Peters also said a special team was assigned to the Boston
Center to find the cause of the problems and fix them. An FAA
document obtained by the Boston Globe, however, indicates that that
any fix is at least six months away.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the controller's concerns about technician staffing
levels, Peters said the center has adequate manpower.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, seven certified technicians worked at the Boston
Center to keep the computer system running. Today only three
specialists are assigned to maintain a system that has to run 24
hours a day every day of the year. As a result, in the last month
alone, the three qualified technicians have been ordered to work
more than 60 hours of overtime. One of the technicians is eligible
for retirement and Dressell said ``burnout is becoming an issue,''
as the hours required to service the aging system begin to
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of trained technicians to deal with the computer
outages was caused partly by the retirement of many who were not
replaced in the last decade because the FAA believed a new system
would obviate the need for so many technicians. That new system,
however, is still at least two years away.
</P>
<P>
   On May 29, the technicians' union asked the FAA to declare an
emergency situation at the Boston Center, which would have been
politically embarassing, but given the agency greater flexibility
in staffing levels. Instead, the agency earlier this month called
the repeated failures of the system a ``substantial operational
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The controllers union, meanwhile, say the outages have been
occurring at an ``alarming rate'' Johannes said, and last anywhere
from 12 seconds to 2 and a half hours. In 12 seconds, a plane can
travel more than two miles. When longer outages occur, controllers
use a limited back-up system which requires a more time-consuming
process to ``hand off'' a plane from one controller to another
working a different section of air space.
</P>
<P>
   Controllers also are concerned that the back-up may be down for
occasional routine maintenance when the primary system crashes.
``If that happens, we won't have radar contact with anyone,''
Johannes said.
</P>
<P>
   But, countered the FAA's Peters, even in that unlikely situation
controllers would still have radio contact with the airplanes and
could slow all air traffic down considerably and increase the
separation between planes to ensure there is no mid-air collision.
</P>
<P>
   The computer system that has been failing provides controllers
with all the information on their radar screens. When the system
fails the screens either freeze or go blank, both the radar hit of
the plane and the data block that indicates the plane type, flight
number, airspeed and altitude, disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``When aircraft aren't displayed on radar scopes, controllers
are blind to aircraft and cannot protect the flying public,'' said
Scott Hayden, the local union vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One disappeared twice in recent months from radar
screens of the coast of New Jersey, due to problems with the radar
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air Force One is not the only plane disappaearing from radar
screens,'' said Hayden. ``Unfortunately, these things happen every
day to other aircraft as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
