<HEADLINE>
ON TRACK FOR A TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jerome Davis has never had a lack for motivation.
USC's quarter-miler is reminded of the 28 national titles and the
34 Olympic gold medalists each time he passes through USC's
Heritage Hall.
</P>
<P>
   For Davis, the memory of his older brother, Eddie, who died of
stomach cancer at age 24 in 1995, has been the biggest source of
inspiration. Jerome wears a gold necklace belonging to his brother
with the letter ``E'' as a tribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I step onto the track, I am praying,'' said Davis,
20. ``I wish Eddie could be in the stands watching, but I know he
is with me, helping me deal with all the pain and pressure. I don't
get discouraged because I know he can help me do it. I feel this
comfort. I have no fear. I just know that I am going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie played basketball at Cerro Coso and Butte colleges. Among
his last words to Jerome was encouragement to finish high school
and obtain a college scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we were seven years apart, we would always talk,''
said Jerome, the youngest of three children. ``We were like best
friends. The year he passed away, I was having problems with the
SAT and I thought there was no way I would pass the entrance exam
to USC. Everything seemed to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   On the track, Jerome, who will compete in the 400 meters in the
USA Track &AMP; Field Championships in New Orleans, has also blossomed.
</P>
<P>
   Davis ran a personal-best 45.18 seconds to notch an upset
victory in the NCAA championships in Buffalo two weeks ago. Davis
defeated a field which included 1996 NCAA champion Davian Clark of
Miami _ a 1996 Olympic finalist for Jamaica _ to become the first
USC athlete to win the 400 since Quincy Watts in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Davis tuned up for the NCAA meet by winning his third
consecutive Pacific 10 Conference title, a feat accomplished only
once before in the past two decades. In April, Davis knocked off
1997 World Championship bronze medalist Tyree Washington to win the
400 at the Mt. San Antonio College Relays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at them as favorites,'' Davis said. ``I just look
at them as somebody who has run faster times than I have. The only
way you can get something is to take it from them. I don't really
focus on a person as I do myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The main focus for the 6-foot-2, 183-pound Davis was basketball
despite clocking 46.62 and reaching the state high school 400 final
twice, including a third-place finish as a senior in 1995. Davis
never dreamed of winning an NCAA title in track.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Ron Allice saw something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has something in his chest cavity that it takes to be a
successful quarter-miler,'' Allice said. ``You have to have a good
pain threshold. He handles pressure well. He has an inner strength
that is not always commonplace. He has so many pluses that a NCAA
title is an end result.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has also made his mark on the world scene. Last summer, he
anchored the U.S. 1,600-meter relay team to victory in the World
University Games in Italy. In 1996, Davis was captain of the U.S.
team in the World Junior Championships in Sydney, Australia,
winning gold medals in the 400- and 1,600-meter relays and a silver
in the 400.
</P>
<P>
   Davis credits his steady rise at USC to Allice, a former
440-yard school record-holder at Long Beach State, as well as
guidance from Trojans women's coach Barbara Edmonson, a former
world record-holder at 50, 100 and 200 meters and a 1968 Olympic
gold medalist in the 400 relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing they stress is you have to work hard and want
it,'' Davis said. ``I am glad my progression hasn't been a big
drop. If God let me run any faster, then what is there to come. I
probably wouldn't graduate and would drop out of school. It's been
a slow progression and I can see myself working up the ladder.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, Davis will be looking for a sub-45 clocking and
a berth in the eight-man final. At last year's national
championships, Davis advanced to the semifinals with only a week's
rest after the NCAA championships. This year, he has had an extra
week between the meets and didn't start racing until April in
anticipation for a good showing at the USA championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I have a nice target on my back,'' Davis said. ``A lot of
people are going to be looking at me and say I got lucky at the
NCAA meet. People are going to want to come after me, but you have
to go into a race thinking no one can beat you. Anybody still there
with you in the last 100 meters is in for a fight. They're going to
have to dig deep with some type of heart that they have never used
if they intend to beat you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
