<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HUNDLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY NEARS A NO-TRADE CLAUSE IN PACT
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Early Wednesday, the New York Mets' co-owner Fred
Wilpon had again stressed the organization's desire to keep both
Todd Hundley and Mike Piazza happy. It could soon be a case of one
down, one to go, as it appears General Manager Steve Phillips is
close to an agreement with Hundley on a no-trade clause that could
run up to the All-Star Game break in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Phillips nor Hundley's representative, Seth Levinson,
was available for comment and the Mets had not announced anything
by game-time Wednesday night. But a person familiar with the
negotiations indicated this evening that the Mets were close to
granting Hundley the clause he has been seeking since the Mets
acquired Piazza from the Florida Marlins on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are also discussing a compromise on 12 teams that
Hundley could be traded to after next season's All-Star Game, which
would grant the All-Star catcher some of the job security that he
felt he had lost with the acquisition of Piazza, the Mets' current
All-Star catcher. Hundley hasn't played this season, and he isn't
expected back until mid-July because of elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   That compromise would give Phillips some flexibility down the
road if the Mets come to the conclusion that Hundley _ who now
seems clearly targeted for the Mets' outfield _ is unable to make
the transition to another position. What the Mets had feared was
that they would have no place to play Hundley should that happen.
And Hundley's contract, which will pay him $4.8 million this
season, $5.2 million next season and $6 million in 2000, does not
expire until after the 2000 season, with the Mets holding an option
to either buy out Hundley for $500,000 or keep him for another $6
million in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If the two sides can reach an agreement, the next step for the
Mets is to re-sign Piazza, who becomes a free agent at the end of
the season. He will be seeking a multiyear contract in the $100
million range. Apart from the money, the Mets also need to make
Piazza feel comfortable that he is the Mets' starting catcher and
his status will not be threatened by Hundley's presence. All
indications are that Wilpon and the co-owner Nelson Doubleday have
authorized Phillips to proceed with those negotiations as he sees
fit.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Wilpon had sounded as if he thought Phillips
and Levinson were close to an agreement on the no-trade clause.
``The Mets' organization wants Todd on this team and playing with
this team, which includes Mike Piazza and others,'' Wilpon said.
``Steve is trying to work that out and Nelson and myself are all
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley is also feeling optimistic. He said this weekend that
his gut feeling, in light of the Mets' trade for Piazza and of the
organization's ensuing treatment of Hundley, was that the Mets
would deal him to a noncontending team, which is why he and
Levinson have asked for the no-trade provision that would allow
them to veto trades to certain organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilpon had spoken earlier this week of his special fondness
for the 29-year-old Hundley, both as an individual and for what he
has done for the Mets in his dozen years with the organization.
That may have been one reason Levinson sounded optimistic on
Tuesday night that something could be worked out soon.
</P>
<P>
   There is no timetable set for Hundley's return to the team. But
Hundley has been learning to play the outfield at the Mets' minor
league complex in Port St. Lucie, Fla., and he has begun to take
live batting practice. Hundley will still have to undertake a
rehabilitation assignment in the minors before he is ready to
rejoin the Mets, but it is still possible that he could be back
around the All-Star Game break, July 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   That would enable Hundley to hit behind Piazza in the lineup,
providing an excellent opportunity for just the sort of chemistry
Wilpon believes can help propel the Mets to a post-season berth.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
