<SLUG> BC-NY-CONTRACTOR-BRIBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER GUILTY PLEA, COMPANY CALLS PAYMENTS LEGAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hours after pleading guilty in a major bribery case
Wednesday, Structure Tone Inc., one of the largest construction
companies in Manhattan, seemed to be having second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of five companies that admitted in state Supreme
Court in Manhattan on Wednesday that it had participated in a
scheme to rig the bidding on $2 billion worth of renovation work
for companies like Sony Corp., Credit Suisse First Boston, Morgan
Stanley, Bertelsmann AG and Gleacher &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Under a plea agreement with the Manhattan district attorney,
Robert Morgenthau, Structure Tone agreed to pay $10 million in lieu
of fines and forfeiture of assets.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours later, Howard Rubenstein, a spokesman for Structure
Tone, issued a statement saying the contractor had merely paid
``legitimate sales commissions,'' not bribes, to obtain a $500
million contract at the Sony Building, at 550 Madison Ave. and 56th
Street. Structure Tone, the statement added, was a ``victim'' of
the bid-rigging scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The statement by the company, which has hired several lawyers
and two public relations consultants, brought an angry response
from the district attorney's office and conflicted with Structure
Tone's admissions in court Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the district attorney's office said it did not want to
put the contractors out of business, Structure Tone and the others
who pleaded guilty Wednesday are very concerned that they will be
forever tainted by the scandal. One company at the center of the
scheme, Bennis &AMP; Reissman, has closed, and others have lost work
because of the publicity. Structure Tone is the only one to issue a
news release or grant an interview, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Structure Tone press statement is flatly contradicted by
the guilty plea they entered in open court,'' said Daniel
Castleman, chief of investigations for the district attorney. ``In
pleading guilty, Structure Tone admitted that it paid a bribe to
Bennis &AMP; Reissman, albeit through a middleman, to get the Sony
contract. The fact that Structure Tone pleaded guilty to commercial
bribery and has agreed to pay $10 million speaks for itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
