<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-ISSUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR ISSUES UNRESOLVED AS ALBANY SESSION DRAWS TO CLOSE
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As one of the most sluggish legislative sessions
in memory drew toward a close Wednesday, lawmakers remained deeply
divided on a host of major issues, from changing parole rules to
creating charter schools to expanding health care for poor
children.
</P>
<P>
   With the state legislature pressing to complete its business by
Thursday, Gov. George Pataki and the leaders of the Democrat-led
Assembly and the Republican-controlled State Senate said they could
not agree on the legislation to end parole for all violent
offenders, one of the governor's major election-year initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects also looked dim for about a dozen other issues,
including a bill to provide health care for poor children up to age
18 and a plan to create charter schools that are publicly financed
but operate independently of local school boards.
</P>
<P>
   The session-ending malaise comes two months after the
legislature broke with its tradition of having extraordinarily late
budgets and passed a record $71.6 billion budget that included
generous spending on schools and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the last few weeks have been bogged down in
election-year politics and the animosity between the Republican
governor and the Democratic Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver. The
gridlock is such that Pataki had scheduled a trip to Buffalo
Wednesday to sign copies of his recently released autobiography.
But he decided to cancel the trip to be on hand in the State
Capitol just in case there might be a breakthrough on any of the
legislative fronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to meet through the afternoon and into the
evening until we close on some of the issues or recognize that we
can't,'' Joseph Bruno, the Senate majority leader, told reporters
on Wednesday morning after emerging from a meeting with Pataki and
Silver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we agree on,'' he said, ``is that we will be
closed by tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and legislative leaders directed their staffs to work
through the night to try to seal some deals.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders have managed to reach agreement in a few areas. The
most significant is a bill that would provide the largest increase
ever in pension benefits for the more than 300,000 current and
retired state employees. It now goes to the governor, who has said
he would be open to a ``reasonable'' pension bill.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, retired employees would get pension
increases ranging from 1.44 to 10.30 percent based on when they
retired. The larger increases would go to the people who have been
retired the longest because the value of their pensions has been
eroded by inflation. Current employees, upon retirement, would have
their pensions set on a new formula that provides increases to
account for current inflation rates.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation did not establish a permanent system of
cost-of-living increases as the public employee unions had wanted.
But union leaders said it helped fix a basic inequity in the
pension system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased with this agreement,'' said Denyce Duncan Lacy,
a spokeswoman for the State Public Employees Federation. ``But
we'll be back again next year lobbying for a permanent solution to
the pension.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislature also agreed on a bill that would extend for
another two and a half years a landmark program that required the
state to begin closing its expensive and outdated psychiatric
hospitals and to use the savings to expand a wide range of
community mental health programs. The program, which was set to
expire in 10 months, was intended to revolutionize care for the
mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is expected to be passed by both houses on
Thursday and to be sent to the governor for approval. Zenia Mucha,
a spokeswoman for Pataki, said the administration was unaware of
the legislation but would be open to considering it.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday evening, the leaders of the Assembly said they
would pass legislation that begins the process of legalizing casino
gambling in New York. But it was not clear if the Assembly proposal
would be accepted by the Senate, where a similar measure was
defeated. The legislation would allow casinos in the Niagara
Falls-Buffalo area, in the Catskills and in Warren County in
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and the legislative leaders remained far apart on
Wednesday on other major issues, though their differences could be
resolved in the flurry of legislative horse-trading that has
historically dominated the end of session.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs that legislative leaders, particularly Silver,
would be willing to compromise on issues dear to the administration
in return for Pataki's agreement to restore some of the $1.6
billion he cut from the budget that the legislature sent to him in
April.
</P>
<P>
   One area for potential compromise is the governor's proposal to
create independently run charter schools that would be an
alternative to public schools. Silver has blocked the proposal but
has left open the possibility that he would support it if the
governor agreed to restore money for teacher salaries, school
construction and repairs and other areas in the budget, according
to people with knowledge of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Another major piece of legislation still being negotiated
involves ending discretionary parole for all violent felons. Pataki
and his allies in the Senate have been pushing hard to get the bill
enacted. But the Democrats in the Assembly have said that they will
only agree to such a bill if it includes a provision allowing some
low-level offenders to attend drug treatment programs instead of
going to prison. So far, Republicans have rejected that provision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
