<SLUG> BC-NJ-RAPIST-ATTACKED-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF PROSECUTOR CALLS FOR GREATER EFFORT TO EXPLAIN `MEGAN'S LAW'
</HEADLINE>
   (ja)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ A day after shots were fired at the house
where a paroled rapist lives, New Jersey's chief law enforcement
officer told prosecutors on Wednesday to combat vigilantism by
doing more to educate the public about ``Megan's Law.''
</P>
<P>
   In a directive to the state's 21 county prosecutors, Attorney
General Peter Verniero said that better community education was the
best way to reduce the confusion, misinformation, anger and fear
surrounding the law, which permits warnings about sex offenders
deemed potentially dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incumbent on us to redouble our efforts in light of
yesterday's incident,'' he said in the directive.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, most county prosecutors have focused on explaining
the law and all its requirements to municipal police chiefs and
school superintendents and principals.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero said in an interview that he was not trying ``to
suggest the offices are not doing their job.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I want them to increase their efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Verniero issued the order as detectives tried to find out who
fired five bullets early Tuesday into a house in Linden that
included the basement apartment of a paroled rapist. The bullets
pierced the windows and walls of a first-floor apartment while its
resident, Joan Bazydlo, watched television. Neither she nor the
parolee, Frank Penna, 55, were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred 10 days after Linden police gave neighbors
fliers telling them of Penna's presence and including his name,
address, description and photograph. Penna was convicted of
kidnapping and raping two teen-agers in 1976 and was paroled in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero called the shooting the first case of vigilantism since
the state won a long court fight over ``Megan's Law'' this year and
resumed issuing public notices about paroled offenders that
prosecutors have classified as posing moderate or high risks of
committing new sex crimes.
</P>
<P>
   On July 9, a federal appeals court in Philadelphia is to hold a
hearing on another constitutional challenge that the New Jersey
public defender's office has filed against the law. This challenge
deals with sex offenders convicted and sentenced after passage of
the law in 1994. The earlier case, which ended in February when the
U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear it, dealt with those sentenced
before passage.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Buncher, a deputy public defender who helped prepare the
case, said the gunfire at the house where Penna lived could be
relevant to his office's contention that the notifications violated
the privacy rights of parolees. But Buncher said his office had not
decided whether to include the Linden gunfire case in its arguments
to the court.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have expressed fears that public acts of
violence against parolees could jeopardize the law in the courts.
Verniero said Wednesday that he was not worried about one isolated
incident. ``If we saw repeated, constant vigilantism, that would
give me more concern,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his directive, Verniero said his office and the county
prosecutors, who oversee both the risk classification system and
the notification campaign, ``must be equally resolute'' in
expanding community education to prevent vigilantism.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the public, he said, believe incorrectly that
they will be told about every paroled sex offender in their
neighborhood. ``Others question the efficacy of the law,'' he
wrote. ``By explaining the law to them, answering their questions
and detailing how local law enforcement officials are handling the
situation, the sense of frustration that often leads to rash or
criminal behavior is reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Verniero said he wants prosecutors to stress that the state will
not tolerate vigilantism. He said the prosecutors could spread that
message and other details about the law to parent-teacher
associations, civic and religious groups, neighborhood watch
programs and other community groups.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero said the prosecutors have enough staff members in their
``Megan's Law'' units for increased public appearances. He also
said that deputies in his office's speakers bureau will discuss the
law more often in their engagements and that he will talk about it
more in his speeches.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lawyers who have denounced the law since its passage in late
1994 said the notification system guarantees violence, threats and
harassment against paroled sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Martone, executive director of the New Jersey branch of
the American Civil Liberties Union, said, ``There will always be
one or two people in the hundreds you've told who, despite
admonitions, will say, `I don't want that time bomb next to me.'''
</P>
<P>
   John Furlong, a lawyer who assists paroled offenders in
challenging risk classifications, said the public despises sex
offenders more than murderers. Public notifications, he said,
create scare-mongering and harassment. ``I don't expect a rational
response from a politicized public,'' Furlong said. ``The law
appeals to the basest instinct in all of us to cast the demons out
of our midst.''
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation of Tuesday's shooting continued, the Union
County Crimestoppers Organization, a group of law enforcement
officials and business executives, offered a reward of as much as
$5,000 for information leading to the arrest and indictment of
anyone responsible for the shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
