<SLUG> BC-NY-VENDORS-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI GIVES SIDEWALK VENDORS A REPRIEVE
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sidewalk vendors, who had faced banishment from many
of their most lucrative corners, won a reprieve Wednesday when
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani took the rare step of backing off a major
crusade in his quality-of-life campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani administration officials, who dominate the city panel
that determines where vending is allowed, voted to rescind the
144-block ban on vending that was to take effect next month and to
reconsider later this summer after seeking additional testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan's financial district, some customers toasted the
decision with bottles of Snapple bought from their favorite
vendors' carts. But few peddlers joined in the celebration, saying
that they believed they had won just a temporary reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Deputy Mayor Rudy Washington said the administration
planned to pursue the regulation of vendors. He said the panel, the
Street Vendor Review Panel, was re-examining its votes of May 20 on
the advice of lawyers and in response to public outcry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that as soon as we close one block, we're off to
court,'' Washington said. ``It doesn't hurt anything to take a
second, back up and take in more evidence. We'll have a more
bulletproof case, and at the same time do the right thing that
strikes the right balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ester Fuchs, a professor of political science at Barnard College
and a persistent Giuliani critic, said that the mayor would have
risked permanent damage to his reputation if he had pursued plans
to put strong limits on vending.
</P>
<P>
   ``His targets since the last election have been the
disenfranchised, or people who have little political power,'' she
said. ``The piece of this puzzle which the mayor forgot was that
the patrons of the street vendors are generally working people who
probably voted for Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the mayor's top advisers, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Giuliani had no intention of abandoning his
crackdown on vendors since he still felt that street peddlers
undermined civility by causing congestion and sanitation problems.
But one of these advisers said the mayor realized he had
``articulated badly'' his reasons for the crackdown. The other said
the mayor was concerned about being perceived as ``governing by
fiat.''
</P>
<P>
   At his daily news conference Wednesday, Giuliani said that he
and his panel were trying to ``strike the right balance'' between
street vendors and restaurants, which lose money to the carts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they wanted to do was to listen to more businesses and
more vendors to make sure that the plan they put into effect is a
sensitive one and a good one and accomplishes the purpose of
allowing people to remain in business, and doesn't have a
deleterious effect on the businesses that presently exist,''
Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he had not yet decided what changes the review
panel _ made up of three Giuliani appointees and one member named
by the City Council _ should make.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Cicio, president of the largest trade group, the Big
Apple Food Vendors Association, laughed when he was told about the
panel's action. ``This is a just a smoke screen,'' he said. ``They
got a lot of bad press, and they realized they made a mistake. It
got a little too hot in the kitchen, so they shut off the burners.
But this mayor is not giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   Cicio said he was pinning his hopes on the City Council, which
is considering at least three bills to disband the Street Vendor
Review Panel and regulate the carts another way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
