<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRONX-INDICTMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER STATE SENATOR FROM BRONX IS INDICTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pedro Espada Jr., a former state senator who built a
health clinic in the Bronx into a powerful political empire, was
arraigned Wednesday along with two of his employees on charges that
they illegally diverted $221,000 in Medicaid funds to the failed
1996 re-election campaigns of Espada and his son, Pedro Gautier
Espada, then an assemblyman.
</P>
<P>
   Espada immediately denounced the indictment as a political
vendetta backed by the leadership of the Bronx Democratic Party,
with whom he and his family have been embroiled in a long and
bitter feud.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment followed a two-year investigation by the Bronx
district attorney, Robert Johnson, that began when a state appeals
court cited rampant fraud in the collection of the Espadas' ballot
petition signatures and barred the candidates from the 1996
Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Bronx assistant district attorney, Eric Hirsch,
the investigation revealed that the elder Espada and the two
employees, Sandra Love and John Connors, had directed to the
campaign coffers payments ranging from $18,000 to $85,000 from a
health-maintenance organization for Medicaid-eligible patients that
Espada had formed in the Soundview section of the Bronx in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money didn't go to pay health care providers for treating
needy patients,'' Hirsch said. Instead, the money was used to pay
for campaign expenses, including radio and television
advertisements, mailings, posters and photographers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch said Espada and the two employees concealed the
disbursements by falsely listing them as prepaid marketing expenses
on an annual report to the State Department of Health by Universal
Health Plan. The plan is a health maintenance organization
affiliated with Our Lady of Mercy Hospital in the Bronx and that
falls under the umbrella of Espada's Comprehensive Community
Development Corp., a web of health and social service agencies
based at Soundview Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Love, a longtime aide to Espada, is the senior vice
president of Soundview Health Center and a board member of
Universal Health Plan. Connors is executive director of the health
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Espada, Ms. Love and Connors all pleaded not guilty to three
counts of second-degree grand larceny, as well as one count each of
second-degree grand larceny, falsifying business records and
offering a false instrument for filing. Each was released on
$25,000 bail. If convicted of second-degree grand larceny, each
faces a maximum sentence of 15 years in prison. Espada's son, who
is now a city councilman, was not charged.
</P>
<P>
   Administrative Judge Burton Roberts presided over the
arraignment. The case was assigned to Justice Daniel Fitzgerald of
state Supreme Court in the Bronx, who was chosen at random from a
list of seven ``judges who have no political roots in the Bronx,''
Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   In an elaborate rally on the steps of the Bronx County Building
after his arraignment, Espada described the criminal charges as the
culmination of a bitter, longstanding feud between his family and
the Bronx Democratic organization.
</P>
<P>
   Standing behind eight boys and girls who sang a few lines of the
pop song ``I Believe I Can Fly,'' Espada accused the district
attorney and Democratic leaders of conspiring in a political witch
hunt against him and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidence of their criminality is available,'' Espada said,
alluding to a videotape his son had secretly recorded of a
conversation on May 23 between his son and state Sen. David Rosado,
who holds Espada's old seat. ``Their conspiracy cannot go
unpunished.''
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, Espada's son said, Rosado boasted of the Democratic
Party's ability to influence the district attorney to call off the
investigation if Espada pledged not to run for state Senate. Rosado
said Johnson had passed information about the Espada investigation
to the party through the Bronx borough president, Fernando Ferrer,
the younger Espada said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosado has said that he was lying at the time to serve his own
political purpose, eliminating Espada as a potential opponent. And
Wednesday, Johnson denied conveying information about the Espada
investigation to any elected official. He characterized Espada's
allegations as a diversionary tactic. ``I know what I've done, I
know why I've done it, and I know it's not political,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Espada, who announced his candidacy for his old Senate seat last
week, demanded the ousters of Johnson, Ferrer and the Bronx
Democratic leader, Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his own race, Espada said, his brother, Jose
Espada, is planning to run for the Assembly seat now held by Ruben
Diaz Jr., and his son, the councilman, will run for Democratic
district leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
