r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BRAWLS-MAJORS-AZR     06-17 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAWLS-MAJORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSIC CHIN MUSIC  
 OLD PRACTICE OF RETALIATION DRAWS SCRUTINY AFTER BRAWLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roland Hemond recalls the time Charlie Grimm, the former Cubs
first baseman and manager, went to home plate and lay down in the
batter's box after a teammate blasted a home run.
</P>
<P>
   A puzzled umpire asked, ``What are you doing, Grimm?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure,'' Grimm answered, ``I'm going to be down here in a
few seconds, anyway. I might as well start from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemond, the Diamondbacks' vice president of baseball operations,
has dozens of stories about the ``beanball.'' It is the game played
inside the game _ pitchers taking aim at hitters for a variety of
real or perceived indiscretions _ and it has been around since
baseball's inception. Hitters and pitchers. Dogs and cats. Same
deal. Each wants to own the plate. The ball is often a mediator
that only pours fuel on the fire.
</P>
<P>
   But in today's game, instead of accepting or making light of the
expected knockdown pitch as Grimm did, the hitter goes to the plate
with malice aforethought and designs to storm the mound.
</P>
<P>
   And the altercation, should it erupt into a bench-clearing
brawl, would be the lead-in on ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' for a week,
instead of being the one-day story it was in daily newspapers years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The game hasn't changed. Baseball has always had its own
on-field code of self-policing. The times and attitudes have
changed, and modern electronics brings brawls _ disturbing to most
_ into our living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been this way in baseball,'' Hall of Famer Rod
Carew said. ``You can tell when someone is throwing at someone
intentionally, and you can tell when a pitch just gets away. I
believe in retaliating, but there are ways to do it without getting
anyone hurt. You can throw at their butt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was worse when I was playing, but hitters never dove out
across the plate like they do now. You never showed up pitchers the
way they do now. These things have been going on since they started
playing baseball. It's not going to change, and I don't want it to
change. But it should be handled in a more professional manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemond agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, players would run out and nobody would throw
any punches,'' Hemond said. ``Nowadays, it seems more instigated,
and punches are thrown. I don't know if it's the change in society
or what, but we have to find a way to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of frightening bench-clearing brawls between the
Yankees and Orioles, and the Royals and Angels this year,
baseball's acting commissioner, Bud Selig, is taking steps in that
direction.
</P>
<P>
   He has instructed Paul Beeston, chief operating officer of Major
League Baseball; American League President Gene Budig; and National
League President Leonard Coleman to devise solutions to prevent
brawls.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said he wants to protect the image and integrity of the
game. As an owner, he also wants to protect the health of players.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks learned the point, painfully. The future of
minor league pitching prospect Ynocencio de la Cruz is in question
after he underwent surgery to repair a separation in his throwing
shoulder. It was the result of a beanball-induced brawl May 28
while he was pitching for South Bend in the Class A Midwest League.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an outstanding prospect, but it's difficult for a pitcher
to come back from an injury like that,'' Diamondbacks Manager Buck
Showalter said. ``I saw the same thing with Brien Taylor (No. 1
draft pick of the Yankees, who had shoulder surgery after an
off-field fight). He is really struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   So what changes can we to look for from the group studying ways
to eliminate such incidents?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to focus on everything,'' Selig said. ``Violence
has always been part of the game, but it's now at a point it has to
stop. I want them to explore all areas of the game. I have strong
feelings on this.''
</P>
<P>
   If Selig &AMP; Co. can get the players' union to agree, the result
will likely produce a system of heavier fines and more painful
suspensions for players who leave their bench or position to make a
melee.
</P>
<P>
   In the NHL and NBA, players leaving the bench to join a fight
are subject to five-figure fines (up to $25,000 in the NBA) and
suspension with loss of pay. Additionally, NBA teams are fined a
minimum of $5,000 if a player leaves the bench to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, baseball suspends. But with today's salary structure, the
fines of $500 and $1,000 are chicken feed. Plus, players are still
paid while serving suspensions. Tender justice.
</P>
<P>
   Budig drew praise for his eight-game suspension of Anaheim
Manager Terry Collins and his Kansas City counterpart, Tony Muser,
for failing to control their players. But what did he accomplish?
Anaheim has been on a tear, and Kansas City, which had been
struggling, has played .500 ball.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter isn't sure of the value of punishing managers in that
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, I've never been suspended . . . but the year is
young,'' he said. ``I've never been in that position. I imagine
it's different for each manager. Some guys are more hands-on, and
others delegate more authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter says, considering that teams play 162 regular-season
games, instances of violence are far fewer in baseball than other
sports, although he quickly adds it's nothing to be proud about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say something contradicting Bud or Gene because
they've done more research and have more time to analyze what's
going on,'' Showalter said. ``But it's part of the game. Any time
you have competitive people doing something that means a lot to
them, they're going to go about it passionately and protect their
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (baseball officials) step in when they feel the sport
isn't controlling itself within the lines. Baseball polices itself
from within. You can't make a second baseman sit for three innings
in a penalty box. You can't call a technical foul and give somebody
a run. For the most part, the game has done a good job of policing
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Brenly, the Diamondbacks' television analyst, served a
14-day suspension a few years ago for joining a melee when he was
San Francisco's bullpen coach. He said it had little effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could still throw batting practice and warm up the pitcher,
as long as I was off the field and out of the clubhouse by game
time,'' he said. ``In fact, it helped in a way. I did radio work
for three days during it, and it helped lead to what I'm doing
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be stiffer fines for leaving the bench. A $500
fine today is nothing _ it's like losing meal money. Something is
needed like hockey's third-man-in rule. What happens is you get
players milling around and somebody throws a cheap shot from the
outside. If they weren't there, it wouldn't happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
