<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLFERS SIGH WITH RELIEF OVER RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Amateur golfers, as well as the professionals
who are playing in this week's U.S. Open, breathed a collective
sigh of relief Thursday when the U.S. Golf Association announced
that it will not ban oversize titanium drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But this is as far as those products can go, the USGA indicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is what is around the corner,'' said Buzz Taylor,
the USGA president. ``We are perfectly satisfied with what is out
there now, but our concern is for the future of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation for weeks that the USGA would move to
ban the high-tech clubs because they are sending the ball too far,
making courses obsolete. The media hyped it, and the leading club
manufacturers took out full-page advertisements in several national
publications that warned the USGA that any such ban would be met
with litigation.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the USGA's news conference centered on a new
test that will measure objectively the ``spring-like effect'' in
clubheads. The test, which has yet to defined, will be based on the
rebound velocity of a golf ball off a clubface, the USGA said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1984, the Rules of Golf have stated that ``the material
and construction of the club shall not have the effect at impact of
a spring (Rule 4-1e).''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the literal sense, all clubs have some spring-like effect
because all clubs deform at impact,'' said David Fay, executive
director of the USGA.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the USGA plans a test. Particulars will be released
to club manufacturers within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent ``Golf Digest'' survey of 509 of the nation's 26.5
million golfers, it was determined that 71 percent used oversize
drivers. Of those polled, 89 percent opposed a ban, while 8 percent
were in favor of it. The survey also revealed that 54 percent said
they would stop using the driver if it were banned; 39 percent said
they would ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the USGA's announcement was greeted as a victory
for companies such as PING, Callaway, TaylorMade and Titleist,
which are considered the big four club manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big relief that they didn't draw the line,'' said John
Solheim, president of Phoenix-based Karsten Manufacturing, makers
of PINGs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel there's a cloud about the future because they
haven't defined what they're going to do (with the test).''
</P>
<P>
   But Solheim said it is clear that his company's new PING TiSI
driver, which has not yet been approved by the USGA, is considered
legal.
</P>
<P>
   Fay said the PING TiSI is legal, but he couldn't give a
timetable for the club being approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that strict sense, if someone were to win the U.S. Open
with that club, there is not going to be an asterisk applied to
it,'' Fay said.
</P>
<P>
   Ely Callaway, president of the company that makes the popular
Big Bertha drivers, also is relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased that the USGA has agreed with us that there is
nothing wrong with the state of the game,'' said Callaway, who went
as far as hiring antitrust lawyer Leonard Decof to litigate a
possible USGA ban.
</P>
<P>
   It was Decof who successfully fought the PGA Tour and USGA when
those organizations tried to ban PING's square-grooved irons from
1989-93. That lawsuit ended with the tour and the USGA having to
pay PING's reported $10 million in legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the USGA wanted no part of another possible lawsuit.
But Fay downplayed that fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``With respect to litigation, we have faced this matter before
and that doesn't influence how we go about doing our business,''
Fay said.
</P>
<P>
   There had been other speculation that the golf ball and the
length of the shaft might come under some kind of scrutiny. Fay
said that the USGA is looking at those products, but ``we have
nothing planned on those at this time.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2325EDT &QL; 
