<HEADLINE>
SOSA LEARNS PATIENCE AT PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probably the biggest reason the Chicago Cubs are enjoying their
finest season since 1989 is the play of right fielder  &UR; Sammy Sosa,
who hit 16 home runs in a 17-game span that included three on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, consistently among the league leaders in strikeouts, still
is there this season but is showing amazing patience at the plate,
possibly for the first time in his career. He's also hitting the
ball to right field with more consistency.
</P>
<P>
   All these factors have helped Sosa's batting average climb
higher than ever. He still has the home runs and RBIs he normally
has and soon will have to be considered a serious MVP candidate,
especially if the Cubs continue to surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I try to pull the ball, I just go out of control,'' Sosa
said. ``In batting practice, I'm trying to go to right or
right-center.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa used his new hitting philosophy to recently hit home runs
in five consecutive games, tying a franchise record shared by  &UR; Hack
Wilson and  &UR; Ryne Sandberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something for me to be very proud of, being together
with those two guys,'' Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie sensation  &UR; Kerry Wood may have instilled much-needed
juice into the pitching staff, but Sosa still makes this club tick.
His big bat in the middle of the lineup remains one of the most
feared in the league. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Always a first &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tampa Bay third baseman  &UR; Wade Boggs, a 17-year veteran, was tossed
from his first game last week after arguing a called third strike
with umpire  &UR; Earl Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I got so upset,'' said Boggs, who went face-to-face
with Cooper for about 90 seconds after the ejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the fine line a player crosses to get ejected, and I
didn't come close to approaching it. I've never even had an umpire
tell me, `One more word and you're gone.' I know umpires have tough
jobs and I've always respected that. I didn't get over 1,300 walks
without knowing the strike zone.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
On solid ground? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Seattle dropped into last place in the American League West last
week, and almost immediately talk started to make the rounds in the
Northwest over the job security of  &UR; Lou Piniella, the only manager
to guide the Mariners into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as soon as the talk started to gain momentum, the biggest
star on the Mariners came to Piniella's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we are is flat,''  &UR; Ken Griffey Jr. said.
``Lou's fine, nobody should even have to consider that. We have
spirit. There's energy on the bench. Everyone is pulling hard for
one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella is not the problem with the Mariners' swoon; a lack of
relief pitching is. Of course, acquiring necessary help hasn't been
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see what's going on with the club, and we aren't
satisfied,'' assistant general manager  &UR; Lee Pelekoudas said.
``We're making calls trying to get some things done, but it isn't
easy. Just because you feel a certain player may help you doesn't
mean you can get him.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The rain man &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Tim Raines quietly became only the fourth player in history to have
800 stolen bases in this century when he stole second base last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Raines, 38, stole his 800th base during a Yankees game in
Montreal, where Raines played 12 years. The only other players with
800 stolen bases are  &UR; Rickey Henderson, Lou Brock and  &UR; Ty Cobb. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Todd Van Remember Me? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pitcher  &UR; Todd Van Poppel finally is putting up the kind of numbers
everyone always thought he was capable of. The celebrated former
first-round pick from the 1990 draft is 5-2 with a 2.65 ERA in his
past 10 starts at Triple-A Oklahoma, a Rangers farm club.
</P>
<P>
   Van Poppel is making a push to return to the major leagues,
where he was supposed to win several Cy Young Awards by now. Van
Poppel, 26, is itching to get back and show he is the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real happy with the way I'm throwing the ball,'' Van
Poppel said. ``I know I've still got some things to work on, but
I'm confident right now I could do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers apparently will call up Van Poppel if the need
arises, which may have occurred with  &UR; Bobby Witt being designated
for assignment. In addition to the formidable record and ERA, Van
Poppel has 66 strikeouts in 82 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, pitchers don't develop until they're 25 or
26,'' Rangers General Manager  &UR; Doug Melvin said. ``You hear scouts
talk about him. They say he's pitching a lot better than they had
seen him previously.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
