<HEADLINE>
ATHLETE IS ONLY OVER-50 WOMAN POLE VAULT COMPETI TOR IN ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Kathy Jager knows what it means to jump for joy.
</P>
<P>
   Jager, who in the last four years has become one of the elite
recreational athletes in the Southwest, recently took on a new
challenge, the pole vault. And as far as anyone can determine,
she's the only woman over age 50 who's competing in the event in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Jager, who will turn 55 on June 26, will try to beat her best
mark of 7 feet, 6 inches this weekend in the Grand Canyon State
Games _ a competition designed to give the recreational athlete a
forum to shine.
</P>
<P>
   And Jager will have many opportunities. In addition to the pole
vault, Jager will participate in nine other events during the
three-day competition.
</P>
<P>
   Why so many, when the majority of weekend warriors would be
content with one or two?
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people aren't as crazy as I am,'' said Jager, who is a
home health care nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Opening ceremonies for the sixth annual games begin at 7 p.m.
today at America West Arena, highlighted by the Olympic-style
procession of athletes. Gymnast Kerri Strug and swimmer Gary Hall
Jr., both Olympic gold medalists, will participate in the
festivities, which include music and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight is relaxation time. Friday will be another story for the
athletes, who are expected to number a record 11,000 in 29 events
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jager, used to running herself ragged at meets, is ready. In
previous competitions, she has done as many as six events in one
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part is wondering what shoes I should put on
when,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pole vaulting is a relatively new sport for women, so there was
no way to go but up. And Jager got in on the bottom floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream as a youth was to do something a little more
athletic, but I never got the opportunity,'' she said. ``So when I
was 50, I decided to make this dream happen. I think the second
half of my life is the best part, the chance to live out my dreams.
This is one way of achieving what I have the potential to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you're getting older doesn't mean you can't
achieve your goals and dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   She will be pole-vaulting Friday as the lone female competitor
in her division when the games get under way at Arizona State
University. Jager also will compete in the long jump, high jump,
shot put, discus, javelin, 100-meter run and 200-meter run _ then
she'll hop in pool for the 50-meter breaststroke and 50-meter
freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Jager is used to variety. Raised by her grandparents in St.
Peter, Minn., and influenced by her athletic uncles, she was a
tomboy, living on a farm and climbing trees. In her 30s, she began
playing soccer.
</P>
<P>
   But she wanted a lot more, both professionally and athletically.
She took care of the job first, going from social work into nursing
14 years ago. When she decided to take the plunge at the Grand
Canyon games five years ago, she was an immediate hit in a number
of events.
</P>
<P>
   But the pole vault represented a unique challenge, and Jager
sees it at more than just jumping.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is not to beat everybody in the pole vault or the
other events,'' she said. ``It's an opportunity to improve and
inspire people to say, `I can do this.'
</P>
<P>
   I've had people come up to me after an event and say that after
watching me they wanted to get back into athletics. You don't have
to just sit and do nothing. You make a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Her current pole vault coach is Todd Lehman, a former vaulter at
Phoenix's North High School and at the University of Southern
California who works out of the Kiss The Sky Track Club at the
Phoenix Swim Club. He has helped her improve by 18 inches in a
matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never discourage anyone from vaulting,'' Lehman said. ``It
doesn't matter what age they are. She has fallen on her head a few
times, and as I've told her, no one is immune from ridicule.''
</P>
<P>
   Jager said she almost quit the event, but when she recorded the
7-6 effort, things began to fall into place. Lehman thinks she can
get to 9 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a wall, maybe because I had unrealistic expectations,''
she said. ``I had mental blocks. Todd has helped me put things in
perspective regarding the peaks and valleys.''
</P>
<P>
   A family friend, Bob Bergfeld, who competes in the master
division, got her interested in the pole vault, and he taught her
the basics. She also credits Ed Hedges, track coach at Central High
School in Phoenix, with helping her in the shot put and discus, and
Irwin Jones, coach of the Phoenix Bobcats Track Club, with giving
her tips that has helped cut up to a second off her sprint times.
</P>
<P>
   Since she began competing seriously, she has won a number of
gold medals in state and national competitions in running and
jumping events, and she will participate in a Masters division
national meet in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Jager says she has the full support of her husband, Carl, and
their two children as she balances a work schedule with her five-
to six-day-a-week training regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep a balance,'' she said. ``And I let my husband
carry my bags.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2328EDT &QL; 
