<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING OF AGE  
 DON'T OVERLOOK MIDDLE MEN AT OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Five years ago, most of the attention at major
championships centered on foreign players. Guys such as Nick Faldo,
Nick Price, Greg Norman, Bernhard Langer and Jose Maria Olazabal
dominated golf's biggest shows.
</P>
<P>
   That trend, however, shifted dramatically in the past few years
with the emergence of Tiger Woods, Ernie Els, Justin Leonard, David
Duval and Phil Mickelson. Generation X seemingly had arrived, and
the game would never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Well, guess what? Another notable group of favorites has popped
up this week on the eve of the 98th U.S. Open _ middle-age former
champs. It's as if the game at the professional level has gone back
to the future.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara started it by winning The Masters at age 41. Fred
Couples, 38, recently won his second tournament of the season and
sits on top of the money list with $1,477,017. Even Tom Watson, who
is nearing senior status at age 48, broke through with a victory at
the Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   Others in this age group also are playing well. Tom Lehman (39)
always comes to mind, especially at the U.S. Open, where he has
been in contention to win the past three years. Same with Mark
Calcavecchia (38), John Cook (40), Scott Hoch (42) and Scott
Simpson (42), who captured the Open in 1987, the last time it was
played here at the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf ball doesn't know what age you are, which is one of
the great things about this game,'' said O'Meara, whose dramatic
birdie on the final hole at Augusta National earlier this year
edged Couples and Duval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, there are so many great players in the world
right now. A lot has been said about these young guys bursting on
the scene, so it's nice that some of rest of us are getting some
recognition, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It's more than just a fad, O'Meara insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I've played some of my best golf in the past three
years,'' he added. ``And it's great to see a guy like Tom Watson
regain his putting touch. There are others who also seem to be back
into the chase.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, for one, simply smiled when asked about the so-called
resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things go in cycles,'' the Scottsdale pro explained. ``Great
players are great players, period, no matter how old you are. I
think it's just one of those things that happened last year _
Justin, Tiger, Davis and Ernie winning the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now this year, if O'Meara, Freddy, myself and Greg Norman win
majors, then suddenly the old guys are back. Well, the old guys
never went anywhere. The young guys just played a little better
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   If age and experience have anything to do with this week's Open,
and there is a strong indication that they might, considering the
conditions at the notoriously tough Olympic Club, one of those
middle-age players just might be holding up the U.S. Open trophy
come Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even Watson, who chuckled after being introduced at his
news conference as a ``possible winner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, `possible winner' from `not a chance' is a big upgrade
for me,'' said Watson, who was the runner-up by a stroke to Simpson
in the '87 Open. ``It helps to win a tournament at my age, and
gives you thoughts of, `Why can't I do this every week?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Watson, whose 33 victories include the 1982 U.S. Open, said that
course management will be at a premium this week because of the
severe rough, which runs as deep as 5 to 7 inches in spots. And he
said that those who have experienced Olympic's subtle, sloping
greens and who keep the ball below the cup, also will have an
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Is he talking about himself?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I like being a favorite,'' he said, laughing at the
thought. ``I am very comfortable with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, view Watson and the rest of the middle-age gang
in a much more serious vein. One of those is Leonard, who seems to
be on everyone's list of favorites, possibly even more so because
of the back problems that recently have plagued Woods and Els, the
defending champ.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at anybody as a young guy or an old guy,'' said
Leonard, whose accuracy off the tee fits Olympic virtually to a
``T.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf is a sport where, once you're a pro on the PGA Tour, age
is not going to matter. If a player is 40 years old and he's won
out here, has the experience, that's a tremendous advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do believe that age is not as big a deal as some
people make it out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus, who at age 58 will be competing in his 41st
straight Open, concurs. Of more importance, the winner of five
national championships said, is how the sponsoring U.S. Golf
Association sets up the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tom (Watson) will play very well here, just like he
did in '87,'' Nicklaus said. ``He's not too old, that's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``And considering the nature of the course, I think that anyone
who has played here before on these tight fairways and hills will
definitely have a tremendous advantage over those who have not.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that list include the Golden Bear? Can he still compete
with the likes of Els, Woods, Leonard, Duval and Mickelson?
</P>
<P>
   ``They better play well,'' he said with a wink before bursting
out in laughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
