<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-ARENA-ORLANDO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT IN PREDATORS PAYS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Will Meris' office in Scottsdale is decorated with
Orlando Predators memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a second. This is Arizona. The Rattlers play here. Nobody
is seen wearing a Predators shirt in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're the owner.
</P>
<P>
   Meris is not only the youngest owner in football at age 32, but
one of the most unusual. While his team works out about 2,100 miles
away, Meris runs an investment fund in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Some in sports probably wished their owner kept that kind of
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not as much a hands-on owner as a lot of guys in this
league, which is kind of good,'' first-year Predators Coach Jay
Gruden said. ``He lets us handle the football side of it. He lets
people in the front office do their things. But if he sees changes
need to be made, he'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meris, a 1984 Scottsdale Chaparral High School graduate who
spent most of his time on a tennis court, always is on the lookout
for new challenges. The former stockbroker found one in 1992 when
he attended the Rattlers' first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea what Arena football was,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meris, sitting in the front row with a friend, caught a
misguided player in his lap. Five years later, he owned a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept thinking Arena football has so much excitement, I
wanted to get involved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see something in the local market that is working, you
go for it. That is what I saw in the Rattlers. No one in the
country knows what Arena football is where there is not an Arena
football team. Where there is Arena football, everyone loves it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Predators didn't fall into Meris' lap as easily as an Arena
football player. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Meris said he had heard that the Predators, whom he watched on
TV lose to the Rattlers in the 1994 title game, were for sale at
the end of the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   He said the hard part was getting a meeting with the owner, Don
Dizney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to meet with the previous owner's attorneys for two
hours to make sure I was for real, to see if they would let me meet
with him,'' Meris said.
</P>
<P>
   He got the meeting and, 24 hours later, a deal was hammered out,
with Meris paying $2.3 million for the team that originally was
bought at $120,000. At the time, Meris was laughed at for paying
such a high price. It was the most ever spent on an Arena team.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Meris is laughing. Last year, the asking price for an Arena
team was $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   In December '96, Meris sold 40 percent of the club to the
public, making it the only publicly traded Arena football team.
Orlando Predators Entertainment Inc. is listed on the Nasdaq market
under the ticker symbol PRED.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, it's done well with them,'' said Jerry
Trice, vice president of football operations for the Arena Football
League. ``They seem to be satisfied. We have other owners watching
it closely to see if that's something they might want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Meris didn't stop there. With money from the public offering and
raising more on his own, he invested in Gridiron, which is the
Arena patent, for future returns from the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exciting,'' Meris said. ``This is the reason why I got
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this league gets the big revenue and the NFL comes in like
they're talking about, the Predators will get triple shares
compared to the other teams. All national revenues get divided
between the 16 teams. We'd get three times. We paid through the
league an undisclosed amount of money for that right.''
</P>
<P>
   Meris, who rents a house in Orlando, joins the team for every
game. He won't have to go far this week. The Predators (4-3) play
the Rattlers (6-1) at America West Arena on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Meris said he has used the Rattlers as a marketing model and
still roots for them _ but only when they're not playing the
Predators.
</P>
<P>
   The Predators are at the top of the league in attendance with
the Rattlers. Meris also knows where the money is made in the
league: concessions. When the Predators signed a new lease with
Orlando Arena this year, he made sure that they got 20 percent of
the concessions. Arena fans in Orlando love beer, Meris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's high risk,'' Meris said of his investment. ``I was aware
I was spending money that could be risky. All the research I did,
though, I felt this league would continue to grow.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
