<HEADLINE>
WESTPHAL'S PATIENCE PAYS OFF IN PLUM JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When Danny Ainge was introduced as the future coach of
the Suns a couple of years ago, he said he probably would resemble
Paul Westphal more than any of his coaches.
</P>
<P>
   That caused more than a few jaws to drop, considering the Suns
had just fired Westphal the season before.
</P>
<P>
   But Ainge says he saw patience, integrity and perspective from
Westphal during the three seasons he played for him. And of those
virtues, apparently patience was the most valuable.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two years out of the NBA, Westphal was named
Wednesday to replace George Karl as coach of the Seattle
SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for Paul,'' Ainge said. ``It's obviously a great
coaching opportunity. His patience paid off, and he's getting a
chance to coach a team that's been winning 60 games a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's equal to the situation he came into the first time around
(when the Suns won 62 games in Westphal's first year).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a great nucleus in Gary Payton, Vin Baker and Detlef
Schrempf. That's a pretty impressive nucleus, and they're young,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal's name has surfaced in coaching searches over the past
two seasons, but in each instance he was not hired or turned the
jobs down. The Suns paid Westphal for two years after he was fired,
which gave him the luxury of waiting.
</P>
<P>
   But there also were accusations, specifically from Houston's
Charles Barkley who played for the Suns when Westphal was fired,
that Westphal had been blackballed.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge believes Westphal was simply biding his time for the right
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't trying to go for just any job, like some coaches out
there,'' Ainge said. ``It worked out well for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Suns General Manager Bryan Colangelo said the Suns organization
was queried about Westphal by other teams on previous occasions,
and during the SuperSonics' coaching search. He said the club was
never anything but honest and supportive about Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, let's address Charles for a moment,'' Colangelo
said of Barkley. ``Charles will say whatever is to his benefit at
the time, so take that with a grain of salt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we were asked, we gave supportive and candid answers
as it relates to Paul's abilities as a coach. I know that several
people in this organization were questioned by Seattle. The same
answers were given to Seattle that were given to others who
inquired during the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an organization, we're pleased for Paul. And as an
individual, I'm very happy for him _ not only because he's back,
but because he's got a terrific opportunity in Seattle. That's a
well-respected organization that has enough talent to be a title
contender.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
