<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-KEALY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU'S KEALY CLEARED FOR SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Ryan Kealy has received complete clearance from
his doctors and will be at full strength when Arizona State begins
preseason drills in August, the quarterback said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy is ahead of his rehabilitation schedule. He underwent
surgery in December after suffering a torn anterior cruciate
ligament in his right knee during ASU's regular-season finale
against Arizona. The initial concern was that he might not be ready
for the start of Camp Tontozona on Aug. 12, but Sun Devils Coach
Bruce Snyder said Kealy's rehabilitation ``went perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm full speed and fully recovered at this point,'' Kealy
said. ``The only thing that needs to be done is just to get out and
do some of the things I couldn't this spring, rollling out, stuff
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy said he has been running and lifting weights and is up to
200 pounds, 10 more than last season. He hopes to add another 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get bigger, just to sustain some of those hits,'' he
said. ``I was a little bit beat up at the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy set ASU freshman records for completions, attempts, yards
and touchdowns in 1997 and led the Sun Devils to a 9-3 record. In
his last six regular-season games, he completed 94 of 169 passes
for 1,264 yards and 11 touchdowns with only three interceptions. He
passed for 2,137 yards overall.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Mary's High School standout suffered a torn ACL in his
left knee after his prep career ended and rehabilitated it during
the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (rehabilitation) wasn't so bad, I guess because I've gone
through it before,'' he said. ``The strengthening process wasn't
new to me and it really helped out this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said Kealy is ``good to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's stronger. He has confidence in the knee and he's throwing
the ball well.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy's successful freshman season is one reason the Sun Devils
are ranked in the top 10 in several preseason polls. This season's
national championship game will be played at the Fiesta Bowl.
Coincidentally, Kealy is interning in the Fiesta Bowl's Tempe
headquarters for the second straight summer.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy said he's trying not to get caught up in the hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think rankings really matter to us at this point,'' he
said. ``It's flattering, but we can't take it for anything that
it's not. We've got to go out there, do the hard work and earn our
position.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
