<SLUG> BC-CLIMBER18-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMPUTEE FELT RELIEF AND EXHAUSTION AT EVEREST SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Tom Whittaker dragged his exhausted body and his
artificial foot the last few feet to the summit of Mt. Everest.
Then he flopped over onto the Tibetan side of the world's highest
peak, out of the wind.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:30 a.m. on May 27, the Prescott College professor became
the first amputee to climb Everest, but he was too spent to
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling was definitely one of relief,'' Whittaker, 49,
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And of continuing danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're also very cognizant of where you are,'' he said, ``and
that you're out on a limb.''
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker knew the math: For every 3.5 people who reach the
summit of Everest, one dies. And sometimes they die on the descent.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker and his group _ CBS cameraman Jeff Rhoads and four
Sherpa guides _ made the descent in good order, but the extreme
toll that the climb made on their bodies made it possible to enjoy
the feat only in retrospect.
</P>
<P>
   Normally after a climb like this, Whittaker said, he would be
thin and wasted. But after bulking up to 205 pounds before the
ascent, he's dropped to 185 pounds on his 6-foot-3 frame, just five
pounds under his normal weight. Whittaker said he was aided by
supplements supplied by Inter-Cal Corp. of Prescott, sponsor of the
expedition.
</P>
<P>
   He also credited the lightness and utility of his artificial
foot, developed by Flex-Foot, which cut the weight of the prothesis
from 7 pounds to 2.5 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker said the artificial right foot had both disadvantages
and advantages over a real foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you're driving a tin foot, you're putting out more
energy,'' Whittaker said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the foot can't be manipulated at angles, which
makes descents more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   However, Whittaker said, the artificial foot is a plus for
traversing ice because the climber can dig in the front points of
his crampon and lean into the foot without putting strain on the
Achilles tendon and calf muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker became a professor of adventure education at Prescott
College in 1995, teaching such activities as climbing, kayaking and
river-rafting.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, he had been living with his disability for more
than 15 years. He lost most of his right foot and his right kneecap
in 1979 in a car crash, shortly after he completed a master's
degree at Idaho State University.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his disability, Whittaker set a goal of climbing
Everest. He failed in 1989 after he lost an artificial foot in a
violent storm on the mountain that blew away most of his gear. He
tried again in 1995, but storms again frustrated him.
</P>
<P>
   His successful expedition was also plagued with danger. Just a
week before he made the summit, he extricated from a crevasse a
climber who had broken several ribs in a 250-foot fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of that exhausting rescue, he developed pulmonary
edema _ swelling of the heart _ and was forced to go partway back
down Everest to seek medical help.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Whittaker was modest about his success and eager
to cite the triumphs of others such as Rhoads, who reached the
summit twice in a week, the first non-Sherpa to complete the climb
twice in a single season.
</P>
<P>
   Before Whittaker made the climb, he was determined to show other
disabled people what someone with a damaged body could accomplish.
On Wednesday, however, he said he didn't mean to preach to disabled
people about what they should or should not do; he just wanted to
see them live their lives in a positive way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we let other people define who we (disabled people) are as
a population,'' Whittaker said, ``we'll always live under a
shadow.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
