<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE EXTINGUISHES SNUFFS SEN. JOHN MCCAIN'S ANTI-SMOKING BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Senate snuffed out Sen. John McCain's sweeping anti-smoking
bill Wednesday, giving Big Tobacco a major victory in its epic
battle with the Arizona lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's $40 million national advertising campaign against
McCain and his tough-on-tobacco legislation proved to be a ``very
wise investment,'' the senator said, because ``they won.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The losers are the children of America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, though, predicted that, ``when the American
people understand fully what is going on, they won't like what they
see.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This battle is far from over,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   After four weeks of intense haggling, the Republican-controlled
Senate on Wednesday shot down two attempts by McCain and his allies
to gain the 60 votes needed to keep the measure alive. Arizona's
other senator, Republican Jon Kyl, split with McCain, effectively
voting to kill the measure.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Kyl said McCain's bill would have
resulted in a ``huge regressive tax increase'' that ``would have
created a huge black market for cigarettes.``
</P>
<P>
   Democrats vowed to bring the bill back to the Senate floor and
attacked their Republican colleagues as servants of Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this bill goes down today, Joe Camel wins and our kids
lose,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi countered for
Republicans who argued that the measure had become a big-government
``tax and spend'' bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost sight of the original noble cause of just dealing
with teenage smoking and drug abuse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Sen. Phil Gramm said the public saw through McCain's bill
and concluded it was a massive tax increase on blue-collar workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Washington, it looked like everyone in the world was for
this bill . . . but yet when you got outside Washington, back in
America, the public either was totally (uninterested) in this issue
or they were against,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So in the end, the American people knew more than we knew. And
as a result, for the good of the nation, this bill is going to
die.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., said he would try to revive
some form of tobacco legislation, a bill ``that is narrowly focused
on teen smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to reduce teen smoking, not increase taxes,''
Gingrich said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also reminded reporters the ``issue is not gone'' because
the state attorneys general, including Arizona's Grant Woods, are
pursuing the tobacco companies in court.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said that as a result of Wednesday's Senate vote, ``We'll
have to take a serious look at going our own way, state by state,
on this, if that's what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you the attorneys general across this country are
committed to the issue and will continue to fight the tobacco
industries in the courtroom,'' Woods told ``The Republic.''
Arizona's lawsuit against the industry is scheduled to go to trial
in March.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wednesday's vote represented a big victory for the
tobacco industry, which had spent millions on radio and TV
commercials and full-page ads in major newspapers, including ``The
Republic,'' attacking McCain's bill.
</P>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco chief Steven Goldstone even flew to Phoenix in late
May to blast McCain's bill in a speech to a local Kiwanis club. The
move personalized the industry's crusade against the senator.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco vendors across the state also mobilized against McCain,
flooding the senator's office with letters and postcards provided
by the Philip Morris Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Samuelson, manager of a Phoenix Cigarettes Cheaper! store,
said one of her customers relayed the news of the bill's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dead in the water!'' Samuelson exclaimed. ``We put too
much pressure on them.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain conceded the advertising blitz had a significant effect
on the debate. Before the tobacco industry's ad campaign began, he
said, the Senate Commerce Committee had approved the bill 19-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's clearly been a change,'' McCain said. ``The
only conclusion one can draw is, the tobacco companies' advertising
campaign has had a significant effect on their constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain predicted the vote could come back to haunt those
senators who voted against the bill in November.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl is not up for re-election until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I would not like to go into this next election
having been responsible for killing a way to address the fact that
3,000 kids start smoking every day and 1,000 of them will die
early,'' McCain told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   As drafted, the measure would raise the price of a pack of
cigarettes by $1.10 a pack over five years. The money would go to
help states pay their smoking-related health care costs, finance an
anti-smoking advertising campaign and pay for health research.
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of Republicans, the measure also was expanded
to include an election-year tax cut for couples making less than
$50,000, a series of anti-drug provisions and a cap on fees for
lawyers who participated in lawsuits against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the Democrats, backed by public-health groups,
sought to frame the debate as a question of choosing children over
cigarettemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to teenage messengers who customarily sit at the foot
of the Senate rostrum, Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., said their peer
group would be targets for tobacco marketing. The industry, he said
would ``consciously attempt to addict them to nicotine.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the truth was different, that they, too, favor
cracking down on teen smoking, but that the bill had gotten out of
hand. &QL; 
Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-8546 or at
michael.murphy(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
