<HEADLINE>
ALOHA SHIRT HAD MODEST START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE M. SPITZA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hawaiian shirt came into being after island missionaries
encouraged the natives to cover their nakedness, H. Thomas Steele
writes in the book ``The Hawaiian Shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, Hawaiians utilized traditional Polynesian
designs and native tapa _ or bark cloth _ for their shirts. Designs
and motifs were hand-painted or stenciled from hand-carved wood
cuts. Shirts were often one of a kind.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the patterns were more geometric and less floral,
Steele writes. By the 1920s, small island tailor shops were making
custom prints for Hawaiian families for special occasions, such as
weddings.
</P>
<P>
   When tourism came to Hawaii in the late 1920s, the Hawaiian
shirt literally became a blank canvas for local artists. Designs
depicting everything from romantic beaches and erupting volcanoes
to tropical flowers and local legend began to appear.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1936 that a shirtmaker named Ellery J. Chun
coined the term ``Aloha'' shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The expression stuck. Today, Aloha shirts are considered
American folk art. The older shirts are collector's items. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0581 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RACIAL-BEATING-TRI     06-17 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RACIAL-BEATING-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER FOR DEFENDANT IN RACIAL BEATING CASE STILL UNCHOSEN
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RIVERHEAD, N.Y _ ``The prosecution is doing everything it can to
keep me from having a fair retrial,'' Austin Offen said Wednesday
after a court hearing that left still undecided the question of who
would represent him at his retrial on attempted murder charges.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the legal risks of acting as his own lawyer, Offen
continued to insist on defending himself if necessary, and the
court delayed its plan of naming a new lawyer from the Legal Aid
Society of Suffolk County after a society representative raised the
possibility of a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Offen, whose first trial in the beating of a young black man
during a 1996 brawl outside a Westhampton Beach nightclub ended in
a hung jury on April 8, said during a telephone interview from the
Suffolk County jail, ``It's my right to pick my own lawyer, but the
district attorney's office is forcing the judge to pick someone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first trial ended, his lawyer, Bruce Barket, told the
court that Offen was broke, owed him more than $73,000 in legal
fees and had no way to pay him. However, Barket told the court, he
could continue to represent Offen if the judge would dismiss him as
his private lawyer, then reappoint him as a Legal Aid lawyer, paid
with state funds set aside for indigent defendants.
</P>
<P>
   As a Legal Aid lawyer, Barket would receive a standard fee of
$40 an hour during court time; his regular fee is $225 an hour in
court, plus the cost of investigators and expert witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Joel Lefkowitz of Suffolk County Criminal Court,
dismissed Barket but refused to reassign him. Instead, he turned
the matter over to the Legal Aid Society of Suffolk County and
suggested that it appoint another lawyer, Steven Wilutis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've refused to meet with anyone from Legal Aid because I want
Barket,'' Offen said during the telephone interview. ``He's been
with me for two years and now the judge and the D.A. want to get
rid of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution has charged that Offen, 27, who is white,
attacked Shane Daniels, 23, who is black, with a metal club during
a racially motivated brawl outside a nightclub on May 26, 1996.
Offen has denied the charges. Daniels' severe head injuries have
left him with no memory of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   During a hearing before Lefkowitz, Offen was permitted to speak
briefly on the selection of a lawyer, but only after the judge
cautioned him against representing himself.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Stephen O'Brien, who has opposed reappointing
Barket, said it was the view of the district attorney's office that
if a defendant could not pay for a lawyer, it was up to the judge
to appoint one. ``If taxpayers are paying the bill, then the
defendant no longer has the right to pick and choose,'' O'Brien
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilutis, who was in the courtroom, said afterward that he had
not met or spoken with Offen.
</P>
<P>
   James Miller, a lawyer representing the Legal Aid Society, told
the judge that since Legal Aid lawyers had represented three of the
witnesses in Offen's first trial, conflict of interest might
prevent naming a new Legal Aid lawyer for the retrial. That
objection would not prevent reappointing Barket as a Legal Aid
lawyer, though.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
