<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-STONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN STONE, 83, RADIO PIONEER AND PRODUCER OF `HOWDY DOODY'
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin Stone, a longtime broadcasting executive and
entertainment lawyer who was the producer of ``Howdy Doody'' and
the founder of a suburban radio network, died on June 7 in
Washington, where he was attending the graduation of a grandchild.
He was 83 and lived in Pound Ridge, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone owned WVIP in Mount Kisco, N.Y., which he founded in 1957.
He was forced to close the station last year, however, after a fire
gutted the seashell-shaped building that housed it.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s and early 50s, Stone produced ``Howdy Doody''
at NBC and ``Author Meets the Critics,'' a book-discussion program
that ran for six years variously on NBC, ABC and the old Dumont
network.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, he helped establish a group of suburban AM
and FM stations in New York under the Herald Tribune Radio Network,
said William O'Shaughnessy, president of Whitney Radio in New
Rochelle, N.Y. The group included WVIP, WVOX in New Rochelle, WFYI
on Long Island and WGHQ in Kingston, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Under Stone's leadership, suburban radio stations began to offer
more variety, from local news to big-band music, from local
political debates to announcements of school closings. ``He was a
pioneer in radio and TV,'' O'Shaughnessy said. ``He taught us that
radio could aspire to be more than a jukebox, that it achieves its
highest calling when it is a platform for many different
viewpoints.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer by training, Stone worked in the 1940s on the
Lend-Lease Act, under which Britain was permitted to use American
armaments during World War II, and the G.I. Bill of Rights. In
later years, he worked as an entertainment lawyer, whose clients
included Jackie Robinson, Howard Cosell, Merv Griffin and the actor
Gabby Hayes, O'Shaughnessy said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, Stone was an unofficial adviser to President Harry S.
Truman, who was reviewing his post-presidential employment
possibilities. Stone produced three television appearances Truman
made for the Ford Foundation soon after he left office.
</P>
<P>
   Stone was the head of the industrial division of the 1964
World's Fair in New York. In recent years, he was a director of the
New 42d Street Development Corp., a nonprofit organization involved
in the revitalization of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Stone was born in Brooklyn and attended Bard College and Yale
Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Stone's first wife, Lyndel, a painter, died in 1967. He is
survived by his wife, Antje Schwecke; a son, Richard, of Rhinebeck,
N.Y.; a daughter, Judith Ain of Washington; a brother, Allan, of
Great Neck, N.Y.; and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
