<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0584 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4632 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-dale-HNS &LR;      06-17 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-dale-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   Astros receive &QL; 
new lease on life
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AT one point during Wednesday's news conference to announce the
almost-in-blood commitment by the Astros to spend the next 30 years
occupying the (advertise here) Ballpark at Union Station, a series
of loud roars wafted in from the Astrodome playing field. For what
was a very sweet moment, it seemed a fitting response but also a
tad ironic.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the crowd was saluting the visiting Hercules, not one
of the local heroes. And later, when Mark McGwire jacked home run
No. 32 over the left-field scoreboard in the third inning, he
received a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, though. Applause is applause. Noise is noise.
Baseball is coming alive in Houston again, and if Mark McGwire can
contribute, then hooray for him.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, now 43-27 after a most memorable ninth-inning rally,
are having a stellar year on the field, and it's beginning to be
aptly mirrored at the turnstiles. That hole in the ground downtown
holds grand promise of better times to come, even a new era of
profitability for a franchise that two years ago had Virginia on
its mind.
</P>
<P>
   If team sources are to be believed _ the venerable Tal Smith
being one of them _ the losses incurred by Drayton McLane Jr. since
he bought the team six summers ago are closing in on $100 million.
The new park, while ahead of its construction schedule because of
the favorable dry weather, is still a season and a half from
completion, meaning the bleeding must continue for the near term.
</P>
<P>
   Red ink will flow for a while
</P>
<P>
   Smith said there's nothing the Astros can do this year, winning
the World Series included, to finish in the black. But the deal
they have cut _ finally _ with the Houston Sports Authority, those
civic-minded gents assigned to protect the city's and the county's
interests, affords McLane a fighting chance to operate a more
economically viable enterprise in the future.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a free ride. Although McLane won't have to put any
money into erecting the structure, as was originally the plan, he
will have to pay $7.1 million per year in rent, royalties and
maintenance. That sounds high, but in return he can use the stadium
as he sees fit while pocketing every dollar squeezable from the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The only expressly excluded enterprises are those defined as
being industrial, toxic or sexually oriented. Regarding the last, I
assume that means his ushers, male and female, will have to remain
fully clothed while on duty.
</P>
<P>
   Drayton gets the luxury-box income. He gets the concessions. He
gets the naming rights, too. He can also cover the outfield fence
with signs, as he has done at the Dome, and make a little extra
jingle there. While the Astros will never be a cash cow, they'll do
OK as long as baseball itself can fight off further suicidal
tendencies. Eventually, he'll make up his losses and perhaps one
day conclude that having taken the plunge into professional sports
was an absolutely smashing idea.
</P>
<P>
   McLane's lone out regarding the lease, which covers three
decades with options for an extra one in two five-year increments,
appears to be a successful bankruptcy petition. And he can't go
bankrupt playing at the ballpark. No chance. Downtown ball is a
happenin' thing these days. Why should Houston be any different?
</P>
<P>
   De facto dignitary on hand
</P>
<P>
   Smith called the stadium ``absolutely essential'' to the
survival of the Astros in Houston. He called Wednesday one of most
significant days in franchise history, much of which he has been
personally a part of. It was a big enough day for baseball's
permanent acting commissioner, Bud Selig, to come down from
Milwaukee and lend his support, to both the project and Houston's
place in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Selig is a stadium buff himself. The Brewers are getting a new
one, too, you know.
</P>
<P>
   During the proceedings, which culminated in a formal
lease-signing at home plate made all the more special by the 6-5
victory that fell from the sky three hours hence, lots of folks
accepted kudos for helping make Drayton's dream a reality. Granted,
a smattering of them were the same people who once fought the
project vigorously, but I won't name names.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is it got done, and it's going to get finished
on time and on budget. As Sports Authority chairman Jack Rains
noted, there's no ``wiggle room'' _ other than the $10 million
that's already built into the price.
</P>
<P>
   Which, Rains said, is ``$229 million, down from $278 million.''
The two numbers are apples and oranges, however, seeing as how the
latter included architectural fees and the like, whereas the former
is only the steel, bricks and mortar. The real, all-inclusive sum
is $243 million, still quite the bargain compared to what most
publicly subsidized playpens go for in the late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   So those early cheers were perfectly timed, even if they were
for one of the bad guys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
