<DOCNO> NYT19980617.0585 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4633 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-U.S.-HNS     06-17 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-U.S.-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S. left looking 
for new direction
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ The steps were small, and the wait was long, but when
the United States arrived at the 1998 World Cup, it finally brought
a team that looked worldly and seemed refined, with proven
professional players wise to the ways of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks later, the Americans' adventure to France is
beginning to look like National Lampoon's European Vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Which way to the Louvre? Where's McDonald's? Are we on the right
train?
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are looking lost and panicked, all but decked out
in Bermuda shorts, Hawaiian shirts and knee-high black socks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tourists'' is how veteran midfielder Tab Ramos put this
gone-askew expedition.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a 2-0 undressing by Germany, the U.S. team suddenly
seems out of its element, with coach Steve Sampson thrown into the
role of the bumbling leader telling everyone that things will be
all right but having a hard time sounding convincing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may as well pack our bags right now if we don't change
things quickly,'' U.S. forward Eric Wynalda said. ``We'll lose to
Iran, and that will be it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pivotal game with Iran on Sunday fast approaches, U.S.
players are roundly questioning Sampson's strategies and
techniques, particularly his starting lineup for Monday's
opening-game loss to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to believe when you looked down our bench (against
Germany) and there was Marcelo Balboa, Alexi Lalas and all the
experience just sitting there,'' said Ramos, a well-decorated
veteran who has been among Sampson's most vocal critics and also
sat on the bench Monday. ``It's the coach's decision. You don't
have to agree with him. And I don't. We should have had more
experience out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the 2-0 loss, Sampson's strategies and motivation
techniques had seemed to work wonders for this U.S. team. They
seemed to keep players happy, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson was being called creative and ingenious. Players
applauded his efforts, publicly embracing his midfielder-heavy
philosophy, which promoted speed and counterattacks but left little
room for veterans such as Lalas.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sampson's controversial move to cut veteran captain John
Harkes from the squad weeks before the tournament caused only a few
ripples within the team, as the quarterbacking reins were handed
over to talented 24-year-old Claudio Reyna.
</P>
<P>
   And when Sampson introduced one of his more unique motivational
drills during training camp, instructing players to stand in a
circle on the soccer field and hold hands while telling their
teammates a ``word of the day,'' everyone participated.
</P>
<P>
   Then once in France, Sampson tried to keep the family atmosphere
going by isolating the team at a luxurious chateau in the French
countryside and limiting exposure to the bright lights and buzz of
Paris and the World Cup as the tournament began.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after the sluggish loss to the powerful and veteran
German team against which Sampson surprised many by benching Lalas,
Balboa, Roy Wegerle and especially Ramos, U.S. players are shaking
their heads in discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were isolated in the middle of France, then plopped down in
Paris where it's like a circus,'' said Lalas. ``The (young players)
didn't know what to think. They didn't have the experience to deal
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany started seven players in Monday's game who had
participated in at least two World Cup tournaments. Three German
players had been in at least three Cup tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   The United States started seven players taking part in their
first World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, who before the game had been called dinosaurs in
the German press, started only three players younger than 31. For
the United States, all but one starter _ defender Thomas Dooley _
were younger than 30.
</P>
<P>
   The drastic gap in experience was clear from the opening kick,
with 33-year-old German star Juergen Klinsmann perfectly executing
an assist to 31-year-old Andy Moller for Germany's first goal.
Then, it was Klinsmann, a veteran of four World Cup tournaments,
icing the victory with a marvelous quick catch and goal midway
through the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went out there with the wrong attitude. We went out there
timid, which is to be expected from guys who haven't been there
before,'' said Wynalda, the starting forward who did not get a
single shot on goal in the Germany game.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Wynalda's problem was he never got the ball and the
German defense squeezed the inexperienced outside midfielders.
</P>
<P>
   Reyna played a solid game in the middle for the United States,
but few opportunities could develop against the German defense and
Reyna fell victim to one of the more physical poundings he ever has
taken.
</P>
<P>
   The German scouting report clearly said to take the ball away
from Reyna by any means possible, and that's what happened. Reyna
had bumps and scrapes all over his body after the final whistle.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on the U.S. bench as the poor outing was unfolding were
Lalas, Balboa, Ramos, Wegerle and Jeff Agoos, who have participated
in more than 400 international matches combined over the years and
have handled physical international play for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to prepare people for the World Cup,'' Ramos
said. ``You have to live through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos is one U.S. player who has done just that.
</P>
<P>
   He was around at Italia '90, when a young and overmatched
American team managed to qualify for the World Cup for the first
time in 40 years. Ramos also was around four years ago for USA '94.
</P>
<P>
   Balboa also played for the U.S. World Cup teams in 1990 and
1994. And Lalas and Wegerle played in every game four years ago at
the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But all four watched from the bench Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys played really hard and did some good things, but it
looked like we'd gone backward,'' Ramos said. ``We looked more like
our '90 team than our '94 team. That's not acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Reyna even admitted that he was surprised at Sampson's decision
to leave such experience on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   And Sampson, who already has said that Ramos will start in
Sunday's game against Iran, also hinted at injecting more
experience into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have had a psychological problem more than a physical
problem against Germany,'' Sampson said. ``We have to find a way to
get some more experience onto the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Ramos, Sampson also may start Balboa against Iran,
while getting Lalas and quick-striking veteran Preki Radosavljevic
some time on the field.
</P>
<P>
   He also likely will sub in Wegerle. And considering the
impressive outing by Frankie Hejduk, a youngster at 23 who nearly
headed in a goal for the United States, he should get the start in
front of Mike Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to put a team on the field that will go forward
against Iran, something we didn't do a very good job of against
Germany,'' Reyna said. ``We have to get more chances. We need to
pretty much do everything better against Iran than we did against
Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of advancing to the next round, a victory against Iran
on Sunday is vital.
</P>
<P>
   The final U.S. opponent in the Group F round-robin stage of the
tournament is a tough Yugoslavian team. If the Americans could
defeat Iran, earning three points, they could go into the final
game with a clear shot at advancing with either a tie or a win
against Yugoslavia, depending on what happens in Sunday's
Germany-Yugoslavia game.
</P>
<P>
   But if the same confusing lineups and performances lead to a
U.S. loss against Iran in Lyon on Sunday, then all hopes of
advancing would be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 1990, we were tourists, basically,'' Ramos said. ``We
knew we were lucky just to be in Italy. But we're much better than
that now. We need to show people that we are. We have to play
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Or else this European vacation will be over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-98 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
