<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-ITALY-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Italy finds `A' game in Group B victory
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vieri scores twice in shutout of Cameroon
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ It might not have been quite the overwhelming show put
on display one night earlier by their traditional World Cup rival
and 1994 final opponent, Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Vieri, Vieri close.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's Christian Vieri, a 24-year-old star in the making with a
game as flowing as his thick locks of hair, hammered home two goals
in Montpellier as the Azzurri came back from a mediocre opener to
defeat Cameroon 3-0 Wednesday and take control of the Cup's Group
B.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone performed well, they worked hard, and the attackers
did extremely well,'' Italy coach Cesare Maldini said. ``We had a
lot of chances and converted many of those chances that came our
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The win was the first victory by any team in Group B, after
Italy had to feel lucky escaping with a last-minute 2-2 tie against
Chile in a sluggish Cup-opening game last week. Also in the group,
Cameroon and Austria tied last week, while earlier Wednesday
Austria pulled out a last-second tie with Chile.
</P>
<P>
   What the victory means for Italy, then, is that it is all but
guaranteed a spot in the second round, although Italy likely hopes
to finish first in the group so it can avoid Brazil in the round of
16.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from Italy's opener last week, when a controversial call
and Roberto Baggio's late penalty kick were the only reasons Italy
pulled out the tie, winning the group might have seemed unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, with Baggio again playing a critical role in
setting up Luigi Di Biagio's eighth-minute goal with a beautiful
assist and Vieri scoring his Cup-leading third goal of the
tournament, Italy looked like its old self.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get going in our first game; yes, we were a bit
lucky,'' Maldini said. ``But when we got the early goal today, we
relaxed and played good soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italians finished strong on nearly every possession,
peppering Cameroon goalkeeper Jacques Song'o with an array of near
misses after Di Biagio's first goal.
</P>
<P>
   Italy then was helped considerably when Cameroon's Kalla Nkongo
was red-carded for a cleats-first tackle from behind on Di Biagio
just before halftime, meaning he was ejected from the game and
Cameroon had to play 10 against 11 the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, that was like setting up target practice for the
Italian forwards, specifically Baggio, Alessandro Del Pierro (who
entered in the second half) and Vieri.
</P>
<P>
   Vieri's first goal of the night came in the 75th minute, only
moments after Del Pierro fired a strong shot that Song'o barely
knocked over the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   Vieri took a pass near the right-front corner of the box,
chipped the ball to his right and fired a loft shot over the head
of Song'o. Vieri's second goal came from close range after he
dribbled his way clear of trouble in the box, then side-kicked it
past Song'o.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great scoring goals; I love scoring goals,'' Vieri said.
``Tonight was a great night to get two, but the important thing is
our team is looking good for moving on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
