<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFTY DOES IN ROJAS AND METS, 5-4, AGAINST EXPOS
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The rule of thumb in baseball is that right-handed
hitters have more trouble with right-handed pitching than they do
with lefties on the mound. Which is why there are so many questions
surrounding Mel Rojas' seasonlong inability to get right-handed
hitters out.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his split-finger fastball, Rojas, who is a
right-hander, said he has always had more success against
left-handed hitters. But the hard-throwing Mets reliever is at a
loss to explain why righties are currently batting .391 against
him, as opposed to the lefties' .192 average.
</P>
<P>
   It was a left-handed hitter who finally did Rojas (3-1) and the
Mets in Wednesday evening. Bradley Fullmer's two-out bases-loaded
single, which a diving Brian McRae could not quite come up with in
short center field, proved to be the difference in Montreal's 5-4
victory. It came on Rojas' first pitch to the left-handed hitting
first baseman, moments after Bob Apodaca, the pitching coach, had
visited the mound with the left-hander Brian Bohanon warming up in
the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the right-handed hitters, who picked up three more
hits in five official at-bats against Rojas in his one and
two-thirds innings (including a Shane Andrews leadoff double in the
bottom of the ninth), who really caused Rojas to lose this game.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's game-winning rally came after McRae had tied the
score at 4-4 in the top of the ninth with a leadoff homer off
Ugueth Urbina. That home run spared Rojas _ who had allowed a
go-ahead run in the bottom of the eighth _ only momentarily.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in the last five games on this trip that
the Mets had lost in the bottom of the ninth. The Mets have now
lost five times since sending reliever Greg McMichael to Los
Angeles on June 4 in part of the Hideo Nomo deal. The bullpen has
been charged with four of those losses.
</P>
<P>
   After breezing through four relatively quick scoreless innings,
the teams were tied at 3-3 after six.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored first on a two-out, fifth-inning single over
short from Bobby Jones off Carl Pavano, the promising rookie the
Expos acquired from Boston as the main ingredient in the Pedro
Martinez trade. A pitcher driving in a run is rare, but it was
Jones' second r.b.i. of the season, and his second in as many
starts. The Met right-hander, who is 5 for 22 (.227) from the plate
this year, is 3 for his last 5.
</P>
<P>
   But the Expos roared back with a pair of runs in the bottom of
the fifth, the first on Rondell White's leadoff home run to center
field. The second scored on Shane Andrews' groundout, after Mark
Grudzielanek had singled following White's home run and Chris
Widger had doubled Grudzielanek to third.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, after Mike Piazza had reached first by grounding a
single off a diving Grudzielanek's glove at short, John Olerud
delivered a stand-up triple to tie the score. No slide was
necessary after White, the Montreal center fielder, and right
fielder Vladimir Guerrero collided in right-center field, seconds
after White had dropped Olerud's long drive to the fence.
</P>
<P>
   To make things worse for Guerrero, he dropped a Carlos Baerga
liner on the very next pitch trying to grab the ball, jai alai
style. Olerud scored easily from third, Baerga stayed at first and
the Mets had a short-lived 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero began to make amends for his mistakes almost
immediately. He robbed the next batter, Butch Huskey, of extra
bases with a fine catch at the wall in right, then turned and
doubled Baerga off to end the inning. Baerga had figured hit all
the way, and was nearly home when Guerrero's throw completed the
double play.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the sixth, Guerrero reached first on a one-out
infield single. Rey Ordonez made a sensational diving play at short
to prevent the ball from going into the outfield, before deciding
he had no chance on a throw to first. Bradley Fullmer followed with
a hit-and-run single to right, sending Guerrero to third. Then,
with White up, Fullmer and Guerrero executed a successful double
steal to tie the score at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   Fullmer broke first, just before Jones's pitch bounced in front
of Piazza. The catcher threw to Baerga at second, and Guerrero
broke for home. Baerga one-hopped the relay, however, and Guerrero
scored. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
