<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO, RANGERS CAN'T LOOK TO RYAN FOR HELP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The best pitcher at The Ballpark in Arlington
last night watched from a luxury suite, frowned at the idea, and
said he'll pass, thanks all the same.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he knows that the Rangers are ``undecided'' on their
Saturday starter and are desperate for help in their starting
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. Been there, done that, got the T-shirt to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   No, he won't be pulling his uniform _ the only one ever retired
by the Rangers _ out of the showcase in The Legends of the Game
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan is 51 _ my how the years have flown by _ and hasn't
thrown a pitch in a real game since the one that blew out the ulnar
nerve in his right elbow in Seattle on Sept. 22, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   I'd still put my money on him over some of the forgettable
performances we've seen on the mound here lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I can still crank it up over 90,'' Ryan said. ``The arm's
just fine. It's the rest of the body that's worn out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin resisted the temptation of
making a personal plea for the future Hall of Famer to reconsider,
which is good. Watching a grown man on his knees, crying and
begging, always makes me a little queasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think I haven't thought about it,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   It has gotten to that point for Melvin and the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   So how bad is it? Glad you asked.
</P>
<P>
   So bad that on Tuesday Melvin was ``thisclose'' to pulling off a
deal with Toronto for 41-year-old right-hander Dave Stieb, who also
retired after the 1993 season after his release by the White Sox.
Instead, the Blue Jays elected to call Stieb up themselves after he
put together a string of quality starts at Triple-A Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   A clause in Stieb's contract gave the Blue Jays 48 hours to call
him up or lose him after any club contacted his agent and expressed
its intent to bring him to the big leagues. At least two teams,
including the Rangers, were ready to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   This, friends, is what pitching in the big leagues has come to:
In the same week, Stieb is back in the majors after not pitching
for four years, and Anaheim knuckleballer Steve Sparks, who hadn't
pitched for a major-league team since 1996, shuts the Rangers down
despite an 0-8 record and 6-plus earned-run average in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody call 911. Immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Every day Melvin walks into a conference room adjacent to his
office, where he keeps an array of marker boards listing the
starting rotations and pitching depth of every team in the major
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually spend an hour in there a day,'' Melvin said, ``just
staring at the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not a restful 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly you see that you're not as bad off as you think,''
Melvin said. ``Almost everyone has the same problems. Between
expansion and all the guys who are on the disabled list _ and there
are a ton of them _ that's what makes it tough. If all those guys
were healthy, teams might have some extra pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe then they could afford to trade someone _ anyone _ to the
Rangers, who remain unsure who'll start Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're signed to a player contract, you've got a heartbeat
and there's a `P' behind your name, you're a candidate,'' manager
Johnny Oates said, ``unless your name is Wetteland.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering what he has seen the past few weeks, Oates might
even drop the heartbeat qualification.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a trade, which Melvin deems unlikely, the Rangers will
have little choice but to summon Todd Van Poppel from Oklahoma, a
move the Rangers' GM would much rather not make.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to see him stay and pitch a full year someplace,''
Melvin said. ``He's never done that. But we may not have any choice
but to bring him up to pitch Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   It is particularly disquieting to Melvin that Van Poppel is out
of options, which means the Rangers will have to keep him on the
big-league roster or risk losing him if they try to send him back
down. That already happened earlier this season when they lost
Julio Santana to Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always nervous about calling somebody up when they're out
of options,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, unless Ryan has a change of heart, the Rangers
are out of options, too.
</P>
<P>
   The one ray of hope is that Melvin plans to spend the weekend at
his boyhood home in Canada, helping his parents celebrate their
50th wedding anniversary. The last two major trades he has pulled
off for pitching help _ John Burkett in '96 and Rick Helling last
year _ came while he was at home in Chatham, Ontario, visiting with
his family.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin needs the same good luck charm to work again.
</P>
<P>
   It's that or go back to Ryan and grovel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
